r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-30 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELECTIVE DISCLOSURE CAN HELP THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Securities regulators, investors and corporate executives have
learned yet again, in the harshest way possible, that they have
much greater problems than what's known in the trade as selective
disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the Securities and Exchange Commission
approved a rule barring companies from sharing important tidbits
with favored analysts and investors before making public disclosure
of the information. The idea is to prevent heavy hitters from
profiting at the expense of the little guys as the stock market
increasingly becomes the province of small investors.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of worker capitalism, online trading and
lightning-fast dissemination of fact and rumor on the Internet has
made regulators more sensitive to the need to protect the investing
public. It's a notion that sounds good in theory, although in
reality it's arguable whether the little guys should be playing the
same game as the big guys.
</P>
<P>
   The investors the SEC is mostly trying to protect are for the
most part those who shouldn't be trading, but rather buying and
holding stock in companies with promising prospects. Or, perhaps
even better, they should be buying and holding mutual funds with
solid records of investment performance.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, however, the potential for Internet abuse
transcends the issue of traditional give-and-take of material
information. A brutal reminder of this fact of life came Friday
when a bogus news release concerning Emulex Corp. was posted online
on an obscure business news wire. It falsely warned of an impending
earnings restatement from profit to heavy loss.
</P>
<P>
   The story was picked up by the major financial newswires, and
Emulex's stock fell 60 percent, wiping out nearly $2.5 billion of
the company's market value before the hoax was revealed. The stock
did manage to recover most of its loss, closing 6.5 percent lower
for the day.
</P>
<P>
   When a stock can be clobbered this badly by a fraudulent news
release, it would seem that selective disclosure may not be as
threatening as regulators perceive. In fact, it might even serve as
a useful filter for financial intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, the system allowed early briefings for a
favored few, a fraudulent press release might be recognized as such
more quickly. In a world in which the analyst community has early
access to information, revelations create a buzz about companies
experiencing untoward developments. Thus, if word of an untoward
event appears without warning on the Net, it might be viewed as
suspect in the absence of any Wall Street buzz about the company.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, one of the big debates among Wall Streeters
concerned the so-called efficient markets hypothesis. According to
the theory, stock prices always reflect the knowledge and
expectations of all market players. Thus, nobody has an edge and
it's impossible to beat the market by finding undervalued stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Internet's ability to communicate info-garbage as well
as straight poop, too much efficiency may prove a dangerous thing.
The best way to counter this threat will no doubt be a subject of
intense debate. Meanwhile, it's possible that too democratic an
information marketplace may work against the little guys rather
than for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
