A5945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CENSUS-WHITES-LADN     08-30 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-WHITES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    WHITES NOW MINORITY IN STATE
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Under a wave of immigration from Latin America and
Asia, the population of non-Latino whites in California fell below
50 &UR;  &LR; percent in 1999 for the first time since the Gold Rush, the
U.S. Census Bureau reported today.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide numbers showing minorities had become the majority
last year reflects what already occurred in Los Angeles County and
the rest of Southern California where the non-Latino white
population continued its decline last year. Statewide, whites were
49.8 &UR;  &LR; percent of the population in 1999, down from 57 &UR;  &LR; percent in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's report, based on 1990 census data and estimates
compiled as of July 1, 1999, attributed the demographic shifts to a
massive influx of legal and illegal immigrants and the relocation
of many white Californians to Nevada and other Western states.
</P>
<P>
   The new study estimated that Los Angeles County had a net gain
of 454,672 residents in the 1990s, a 5 &UR;  &LR; percent increase. That
included net gains of 724,089 Latinos, or 23 &UR;  &LR; percent, and 248,626
Asian-Pacific Islanders, or 25 &UR;  &LR; percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the county lost 521,473 white residents, or
14 &UR;  &LR; percent. African-Americans posted a gain of 4,153, or
0.4 &UR;  &LR; percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, whites account for 33.1 &UR;  &LR; percent of the county
population, Latinos 41.6 &UR;  &LR; percent, Asians 13.4 &UR;  &LR; percent and
African-Americans 11.2 &UR;  &LR; percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``California gets 40 &UR;  &LR; percent of all the immigrants in the
U.S.,'' said Larry Sink, a Census Bureau statistician who compiled
the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there has also been a tremendous migration out of the
state. Californians are fueling the boom we see in Nevada, Arizona,
Colorado, Washington and Oregon.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest census estimates provide a preview of the results of
the 2000 census, which will be released in late December. Since the
1990 census, the bureau has compiled yearly estimated updates,
based on birth and death rates and other factors, for use by
government agencies, businesses and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In the six-county Los Angeles region, only Riverside and San
Bernardino counties -- which drew many newcomers in search of
afforda recorded net gains of white residents during the 1990s.
White declines were also reported for Orange, Santa Barbara and
Ventura counties.
</P>
<P>
   Every county in the region reported sizable increases of Latinos
and Asian-Pacific Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern California trends were mirrored statewide.
California gained nearly 3.2 million residents, or nearly 11
percent, while the state's white population fell by 563,000, or 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   There were 16.5 million whites in 1999 among the overall
population of 33.1 million, a 10.6 percent increase in the decade,
while the Latino population reached 31.5 percent and the Asian 12
percent. The population of African-Americans and American Indians
increased slightly, with African-Americans accounting for 7.5
percent of the state's people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a trend that has been building for years,'' said
Reynaldo Baca, a University of Southern California sociologist who
specializes in Mexican immigration and immigrant education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has great implications for California. These are the people
who will be our future tax base, work force and the student bodies
of our universities. We need to invest in that future now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize that this is not the America that many people
envisioned. And there has often been a nativist response to
newcomers. But I see great hope. These newcomers will relay the
pillars of our civilization because they believe in the future and
in hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau's latest findings tracked with a March report
by the agency, which studied domestic migration to and from
California and other states between 1990 to 1999. It estimated a
net 7.3 percent loss for the state due to migration to other
states. During the same period, the study estimated that California
experienced a net 7.6 percent gain in residents born outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic migration out of California, which peaked during the
height of the post-Cold War recession in 1993-94, was more
pronounced in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County's estimated 1999 population of 9.3 million is
larger than some nations, including Sweden with 8.9 million and the
Dominican Republic with 8.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the county were a nation, it would rank 82nd on the Census
Bureau's population list of 227 world nations. And, if the
six-county Southern California region were a country, its total
estimated population of 15 million would place it 62nd on the
bureau's list.
</P>
<P>
   Sink noted that tracking race data will become much more
complicated for the bureau under new rules enacted for the 2000
census. For the first time, persons of mixed-race heritage were
allowed to list that information on their census forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 32 possible combinations for race,'' said Sink. ``We
are still trying to determine how we'll compile and report that
information.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
