<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FATAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY DIES AS CAR PLOWS INTO BANK
</HEADLINE>

 &HT;    (Corrects driver's age to 91 years.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News writers Lisa Van Proyen and Beth Barrett contributed to
this story.) 
By JORDAN SMITH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A 1-year-old boy was killed and four other people
injured Tuesday when a 91-year-old motorist accidentally hit the
accelerator instead of the brake and smashed into a Bank of America
branch in Sylmar, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Val Conrad, who renewed his license just six days
ago, was backing out of a handicapped space at the bank about 11
a.m. when he sent his station wagon plowing through the plate glass
doors and across the bank, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby was sitting with two men and a woman on a couch
inside the bank when the car hit them,'' said Capt. Greg Meyer of
the Los Angeles Police Department's Valley Traffic Division. ``It's
a real tragedy here.''
</P>
<P>
   The child was identified as Nathaniel Escodero, according to the
Los Angeles County Coroner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Three other bank patrons, along with Conrad, were treated for
minor injuries at area hospitals, Meyer said. Their identities were
not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost control for reasons we have yet to determine,'' he
said. ``He came out of the parking spot at a high rate of speed and
through to the other side of the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy was in the bank with his grandmother and 8-year-old
brother, but neither of them was injured, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons in the bank said the lobby was busy with lunchtime
customers when the crash occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly glass was flying everywhere and people were
screaming, running and crying,'' said 24-year-old Sylmar resident
Ray Moreno who was inside the bank making a deposit during his
lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw people get hit and thrown out of the way. Then I heard
the grandmother screaming for her kid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno said he found the child unconscious, wedged beneath the
rear of Conrad's car and the couch he'd been sitting on. Moreno
also said Conrad looked confused by what had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pretty much didn't know what was going on, he just asked
what happened,'' he said. ``I even saw him backing out of the
parking spot. Next thing you know he didn't stop -- he just didn't
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash remains under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the detectives feel there's a chargeable offense, they'll
recommend that,'' said Los Angeles police Sgt. John Amott. ``But
ultimately that is up to the city attorney or the District
Attorney's Office.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad has no crashes or tickets on his record, according to DMV
records.
</P>
<P>
   The Sylmar man was driving with a valid California license
issued Thursday, according to the Department of Motor Vehicles. His
license was restricted to driving only between sunrise and sunset,
with no freeway driving allowed, the technician said.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle Conrad, Conrad's wife of 46 years, said her husband had
been told in the past that he shouldn't drive because of his
health, specifically because of his diabetes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going out to get a haircut and do some shopping
today,'' she said. ``I was worried. They told him he isn't supposed
to drive. But he's a pretty good driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said his investigators will ask the DMV to review Conrad's
driving license.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger issue here is that as we get older, I think it's
well-established that our motor skills deteriorate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult because people don't want to give up their
independence, but the reality is they've got to make a mature
decision and realize their driving abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Coincidently, the Legislature sent Gov. Gray Davis a bill that
would require the DMV to toughen rules for licensing certain
California drivers. The Brandi Joy Mitock Safe Drivers Act -- SB
335 -- would force the DMV to give road, written and vision tests
to motorists determined unsafe by police, doctors or family
members.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored by state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los
Angeles, was sparked by the 1998 hit-and-run death of 15-year-old
Woodland Hills resident Brandi Joy Mitock by a 96-year-old driver
who had been suffering strokes for four years prior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is a reaffirmation of the Legislature's desire to
establish safer driving measures for all Californians,'' said
Brandi Joy's father, Mark Mitock. ``Had our bill been in place a
few years ago, who knows who we might have saved.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
