<HEADER>
A5949 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SATS-SCORES-LADN     08-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATS-SCORES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    VALLEY SAT SCORES CLIMB
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Daily News writers Jennifer Hamm, Amy Raisin and Bhavna Mistry
contributed to this story.(  
 
  
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Unified students improved on the SAT
college entrance exam, with Van Nuys High School and School
claiming the district's top scores, according to results released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Districtwide, average math scores rose 10 points to 457 and
verbal scores rose six points to 439 over last year, but both were
still far below state and national averages. For the second time in
three years, Van Nuys had the highest average scores for both math
and verbal, with a combined 1,095 out of 1,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fantastic,'' said Herm Clay, principal of Van Nuys,
which averaged 536 on the verbal SAT and 559 on the math SAT.
``We've always been a high-performing school on SATs and it's very
gratifying to continue to have the best scores in the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater San Fernando Valley Area suburban schools in Ventura
County, Las Virgenes, Santa Clarita and Glendale districts
continued to beat the state and national averages although Glendale
scores fell this schools had mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Of seven schools in Los Angeles Unified that scored above the
national average in math, six were in the Valley. Besides Van Nuys,
they were El Camino Real (556), Sherman Oaks Center for Enriched
Studies (514), Chatsworth (515), Taft (516) and Granada Hills
(527).
</P>
<P>
   The scores released Tuesday by the New York-based College Board,
which administers the test, pleased Los Angeles Unified officials,
who have been struggling to overcome classroom and teacher
shortages wh academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the average verbal score was 497, unchanged from the
previous two years. The state's math average increased four points
to 518. Nationwide, verbal scores stayed steady at 505 while math
scores rose three points to 514.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've improved at a faster rate than either the state or the
nation,'' said Gordon Wohlers, associate superintendent of
planning, assessment and research.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed the increases, which followed incremental changes
during the past several years, to ``a strong focus on academic
performance that started five or six years ago'' under
then-Superintendent Sid Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having said that, we've got a long way to go to catch up to
the mean (scores) on both the state and the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers said the fact that the district has been coping with
worsening teacher and classroom shortages underscores the
significance of the improved scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that we're rising above some of the hurdles,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, scores continued to rise for districts outside Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County schools scored above the state and national
averages for the sixth year in a row, and scores for Las Virgenes
Unified were its highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   In the Las Virgenes district, students at Agoura High earned a
combined average of 1,144 while those at Calabasas High posted
1,149 -- the best ever, said assistant superintendent of education
Jim Christianson.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Clarita, average SAT scores posted by local high school
students fell slightly, but still surpassed state and national
averages, according to results released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the William S. Hart Union School District, the average score
was 551 in math, down by three points from last year, and 526 in
the verbal portion, down by two points.
</P>
<P>
   In Burbank and Glendale, nearly all schools saw declines in
verbal and math scores.
</P>
<P>
   In the Glendale Unified School District, Blue Ribbon award
winner Crescenta Valley High School showed the greatest drop. The
school's verbal score slid 23 points to 516, while its math scores
plummeted 18 points to 571. Glendale High School posted the only
gains, improving seven points to achieve 534 on the math section.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale Unified School District officials attributed the poor
performance to greater numbers of students taking the exam. This
year, 1,007 students took the exam compared with 895 students last
year. At Crescenta Valley, 11 percent more students took the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy that the number of students tested is up but we
did drop a little in the performance area,'' said Donald Empey,
Glendale Unified's assistant superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   At John Burroughs High School in Burbank, verbal scores dropped
by 10 points to 487 while marks in math went up seven points to
504. Though more students took the test, the group made up a
smaller percentage than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That concerns me,'' said Caroline Brumm, coordinator of
Burbank Unified's student and program evaluation. ``Our (scores)
are pretty stable but I'd like to see them increase.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
