<SLUG> BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PITCHES HIS HEALTH CARE PLAN FOR UNINSURED CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to insert `access to' in lede, and to change `to' to
`for.')  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Vice President Al Gore kept his campaign
focused on health care Tuesday by emphasizing his plan for
providing access to coverage for the country's 11 million uninsured
children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan, for insuring all children by 2005, relies primarily
on an expansion of the Children's Health Insurance Program, or
CHIP, an initiative that has provided coverage, with modest
premiums, for about 2 million children since its enactment in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The program now covers children in families with incomes up to
200 percent of the poverty level, and Gore would raise that ceiling
to 250 percent, or to about $41,000 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to cover every single child within this next
presidential term,'' Gore said, addressing a group of parents and
health care workers that had been gathered by his campaign in a
park here.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico is a swing state that was carried by President
Clinton in 1992 and 1996. Before then it had voted for the
Republican nominee in six consecutive presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Access to health insurance is a serious problem in the state,
where 14 percent of poor children are uninsured, the sixth-highest
proportion of any state, according to the Census Bureau. The
problem is particularly severe among Latinos and American Indians,
and Gore laced his comments Tuesday with Spanish phrases.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominee had little to say about his Republican
rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. But, in what has become a
regular feature of his policy discussions, he closed his remarks by
challenging Bush to issue a detailed plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presently he has not presented any plan to address this
problem,'' Gore said of children's health coverage, ``but there is
still time, even before Labor Day, to offer these specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for Bush, called Gore's claim
``inaccurate,'' and said Gore should explain why the number of
uninsured children had increased by more than 2 million during the
Clinton-Gore years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Bartlett said, has put forth a plan to provide a tax
credit of up to $2,000 for premiums on health insurance policies
bought by families with incomes of $30,000 or less. Families
earning $30,000 to $60,000 would qualify for a smaller credit.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Bianchi, a Gore policy adviser, said the Bush credit would
not be large enough to help many families buy insurance in the
private market.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals, which would increase access for both poor
children and their parents, would cost an estimated $95 billion
over 10 years. The CHIP program relies on states to sign up
eligible children. The state and federal governments share the
cost, with the federal government paying most of it.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to raise the income ceiling for CHIP coverage is
the centerpiece of Gore's plans to move incrementally toward a
system of universal health coverage. That incremental approach, he
has said, reflects the lessons learned from Clinton's failed
efforts to insure all Americans in one vast restructuring of the
American health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it clear that the proposals that I'm announcing
here do not represent a complete solution to every problem in
health care,'' Gore said. ``The approach that I'm recommending is
the step-by-step approach, paso a paso, so that we move toward
universal health insurance for all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic primaries, Gore's opponent, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, criticized his reliance on the CHIP program, because it
has had difficulty enrolling all eligible children. Currently an
estimated 7 million children eligible for CHIP are not enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged that shortcoming Tuesday, but placed blame for
it on states that, he said, ``put up barriers to participation''
because they ``don't really want to put their own money into the
program, and so they make it difficult for families to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some governors, noted Bartlett, the Bush spokesman, have
attributed the problem to a lack of flexibility in federal
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has outlined a series of measures intended to lower what he
called the ``cultural barriers'' to enrolling in CHIP. Those
measures include simplifying applications for coverage, eliminating
asset tests that sometimes intimidate eligible families, requiring
states to change their minimum eligibility periods to a year from
six months, and allowing families to apply by mail instead of in
person.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president would also allow families with incomes above
the higher CHIP ceiling that he proposes to buy insurance for their
children, through either CHIP or Medicaid. Those families would
have to pay a full premium, but the financial burden would be
reduced somewhat if they applied for Gore's proposed 25 percent tax
credit on health insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gore proposal would extend CHIP coverage to the 7
million uninsured parents of children who are eligible for either
CHIP or Medicaid. Some 85 percent of the parents of eligible
children are not insured, according to Gore aides.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's plan, states could set their own eligibility levels
but would receive federal matching funds for those parents they
enroll. If health coverage for parents is provided, Gore reasons,
families will be more likely to seek coverage for their children as
well.
</P>
</TEXT>
