<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATIONS BEGIN INTO ALLEGED VIOLATION AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NCAA and Pacific-10 Conference have launched
separate investigations into allegations that a USC assistant
basketball coach offered money to a junior college coach to secure
a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are investigating this issue with the cooperation of USC
and the NCAA has also begun an investigation,'' said Pac-10
assistant commissioner Jim Muldoon. ``It appears the NCAA
investigation has already started.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 assistant commissioner for enforcement Dan Coonan was out
of his office Tuesday, interviewing some of those involved in the
case. It's customary for the Pac-10 to enlist the assistance of a
member school when conducting an investigations. The findings would
then be forwarded to the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Southern Idaho coach Derek Zeck said USC assistant
Dave Miller offered him money during a summer camp at Cal State
Northridge to land 6-foot-7 forward Jerry Dupree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I'll write you a check to donate to your booster
club to recruit and get Jerry,'`` Zeck said. ``I said `I don't do
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Henry Bibby said the allegations were ``totally
false,'' and added ``neither I nor anyone on my staff offered any
money to Mr. Zeck while we were recruiting Mr. Dupree.''
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, USC and Southern Idaho coaches have had an
antagonistic relationship for some time, stemming from problems
obtaining Dupree's transcripts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
