<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-WARS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTERIES, BOXES AND LOWER PHONE BILLS  &HT;     BY TODD WALLACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Is phone service any different via cable lines? The answer: Not
much.
<P>
   ``Basically it works,'' said Robert Lee, a Fremont resident and
quality assurance agent for the Internal Revenue Service, who uses
AT&AMP;T cable lines for his local phone service.
</P>
<P>
   One subtle wrinkle is that AT&AMP;T gives customers shoe-box-size
batteries, normally placed in the garage, with enough juice to
power the phones for eight hours during a blackout. Telephone
service, by contrast, normally has backup batteries and generators
hooked to the network.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T spokesman Andrew Johnson said the company is building
power supplies into the network in future towns, just like
traditional phone service. ``The battery made customers question
whether they should make the change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also installs boxes on the side of homes to connect the
cable wires to customers' internal telephone wiring. That way
customers can plug their handset into the usual phone jack.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there have been bugs:
</P>
<P>
   _Billing errors. Howard Underwood, a Fremont attorney, said AT&AMP;T
routinely bills him for free local calls at local toll rates of 5
cents a minute. Underwood said the problem occurred during three of
the last four months.
</P>
<P>
   _Voice mail. About 600 customers in the San Ramon area lost
voice mail access for three days earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   _Occasional outages. One customer noticed the phone service
recently went dead for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson said the company has ironed out most of the glitches
and, to be fair, Pacific Bell has also been fraught with its own
problems. And just to reassure customers, AT&AMP;T has promised to give
customers a mobile phone in case of an outage. (AT&AMP;T said it has
stashed away enough phones to handle any routine glitch, though not
a major disaster _ like an earthquake _ that shuts down the entire
network.)
</P>
<P>
   Several customers also reported good luck with the customer
service. ``The call times were short and they solved the problem on
the first call three out of four times,'' Lee said. The fourth
time, he said, AT&AMP;T called him back twice to answer his question.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has also offered customers strong incentives in the past to
sign up. Lee said the company gave him a month's free service and
knocked $50 off his cable bill. Underwood got $150 to try it for
three months.
</P>
<P>
   But both said they stuck with AT&AMP;T because of the lower monthly
bills. Lee said AT&AMP;T's service includes a wider calling area for
free calls; he now pays $20 per month for AT&AMP;T versus $30 for Pac
Bell. Also, AT&AMP;T service is cheaper for multiple lines.
</P>
<P>
   Neither reported installation problems, though Johnson said Pac
Bell still takes longer than AT&AMP;T would prefer to transfer
customer's phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said AT&AMP;T can install a phone line with a new number in
three days, but the process takes seven to 10 days to transfer
existing Pac Bell customers who want to keep their number. Johnson
also said the company wishes it could complete installations on
Sunday, but Pac Bell technicians do not handle orders that day.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman Bill Mashek, however, insists it takes three
business days to switch over a phone number. He said Pac Bell can't
move faster because of industry rules.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, some local customers said they are benefiting so far
from the battle. Dan Calic, best known as the founder of a Fremont
AtHome users group, which tracks AT&AMP;T's cable Internet service,
estimates he saved $90 on installation and other fees by signing up
for AT&AMP;T's phone service for two lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped at the opportunity,'' Calic said. ``I haven't had any
glitches and the quality of the reception has been fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
