<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPT-SPRINT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK LOSSES FOR SPRINT EXECUTIVES HAVE BEEN HUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Eds. please note: This is a sidebar to SPRINT-FUTURE.)
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Another day, another 10 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   That is the average Sprint Corp. Chief Executive William T.
Esrey has lost on the value of his Sprint securities every day
since July 13, when Sprint and WorldCom Inc. called off their
proposed merger in the face of opposition from regulators in the
United States and in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Sprint and WorldCom gave up on their $129 billion
merger, Sprint's stock ticked up slightly. The next day it started
a decline that has seen it drop to levels it had not seen in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Shares and options Esrey received that were worth more than $700
million at the merger price, even after accounting for the average
price Esrey had to pay for the shares, were worth about $244
million at Tuesday's stock close of $32.56 for Sprint FON shares
and $48.06 for Sprint PCS shares, a loss of more than $472 million.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey is not alone, of course. Most Sprint employees have stock,
and then there are the rest of the shareholders. The company's
capitalization, the value of all Sprint FON shares and PCS shares,
dropped to $73.5 billion, compared with the $115 billion WorldCom
was going to pay, not counting the $14 billion in debt it would
have assumed.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's tracking stock for PCS traded Tuesday at 28 percent off
its 52-week high of $66.94 on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not much to say. The disappointment of the failed
merger lingers,'' said Tom Burnett of Merger Insight, a research
firm for institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's broadband and Internet assets are strong, and its local
telephone service is solid, but until the market decides what
Sprint can earn independently, its stock will suffer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to guess, I would say it is within 10 percent of a
tradable bottom,'' Burnett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5959 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-FUTURE-2NDTAKE     08-30 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-FUTURE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT'S PRESIDENT LOOKS AT THE COMPANY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...double hit to Sprint's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts still like Sprint. They say it is innovative and
has a motivated work force and some strong assets, particularly its
wireless and local phone services. But they say that several
factors tied to the failed merger raise questions about Sprint's
ability to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   One is the loss of more than half a dozen top executives. A
provision of the Sprint stock option program allowed options that
otherwise would take years to earn to become available when
shareholders approved the merger, even if the deal was not
finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts even question whether William T. Esrey, the chief
executive who built Sprint into a force to be reckoned with, is the
person to lead it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Esrey and his top people said Sprint could succeed alone and
then they went into the WorldCom deal,'' said Steve Koppman, senior
analyst with Dataquest, a division of the Gartner Group of
information technology consultants. ``Now, when he says they can go
on their own, it doesn't sound credible to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMay called that assessment ``hogwash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill said very clearly...at the time that we decided to merge
with WorldCom, that going alone was still a viable strategy. To
suggest that we had concluded that we couldn't make it on our own,
there wasn't a strategy we couldn't employ going forward, it
absolute hogwash,'' LeMay said. ``People are engaged in revisionist
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street wants Sprint to clearly articulate a strategy and
present people who can carry out that strategy, and Sprint is
working to do that, LeMay said. ``That's the issue, not Bill
Esrey.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will present its plans and introduce the new
management to investors and analysts in presentations before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans include Sprint's place in the explosive growth
expected in data transmission. Though Sprint does not have the
world's largest Internet backbone, it is often acknowledged as one
the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Internet backbone business is about a billion dollars now
and is growing at about 75 percent a year,'' LeMay said. ``We think
we can accelerate that growth next year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sprint has its Integrated On-Demand Network,
or ION technology, which allows customers to use multiple fax,
phones or Internet hookups through a single line into the home or
business. Though Sprint has some difficulties with that technology,
LeMay said it was the technology customers wanted, a single line to
provide all their voice and data needs.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of 2002, LeMay predicted, Sprint also will be
able to offer ION services through its wireless network, greatly
expanding its market potential. That means the company will be able
to offer the service without having to work through a local
telephone provider. And it will be able to serve customers who live
too far away from special equipment to get high-speed Internet
connections by land lines.
</P>
<P>
   The tremendous growth of data movement over wire lines will
happen with wireless service as well, LeMay said: ``People are
going to find uses for that technology that we simply cannot
comprehend now. It is a major part of our growth opportunity. It is
just a matter of timing.''
</P>
<P>
   But in any transforming market, timing can be everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole industry is going through a major shift. All
companies, including Sprint, face uncertainty,'' Kagan said. ``But
Sprint also is facing these challenges after they lost a lot of
senior talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Esrey's time to become a bold visionary leader or step
aside. It can't be business as usual. Sprint is at a very important
transition point. We will just have to wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
