<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWBURY HAD BIG DAY WHILE DOING THE SPLITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC kicker David Newbury had never made three
field goals in a game before Sunday's victory over Penn State, a
fact made more surprising because Newbury did it with a shoe that
split open during pregame warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had started to split the last couple of days at Irvine, and
we glued it back together,'' Newbury said. ``But by the end of
pregame warm-ups, it split back open.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury did not want to break in a new pair of cleats right
before kickoff, so he had the shoe glued again before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about wearing new shoes,'' he said. ``If I can
make three field goals with a split shoe, I'm pretty happy.''
</P>
<P>
   After making only 11 of 20 field goals last season, Newbury's
3-for-3 performance against Penn State has surprised more people
than even he expected.
</P>
<P>
   During a communications class Tuesday, Newbury said the
professor, unaware that Newbury was a student, told his class that
he had watched the game and couldn't believe the kicker had
performed so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Last year, Newbury couldn't hit anything.' We were
all smiling,'' Newbury said.
</P>
<P>
   But after the class, Newbury made a point to introduce himself
to the professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed it off,'' Newbury said.
</P>
<P>
   FAN ARRESTED: A Penn State student was arrested during the
Kickoff Classic for attempting to steal a USC helmet that was on
the team bench. The fan snuck on to the field with the Penn State
band but was apprehended by Giants Stadium security before he could
leave the field with the helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYZING CARSON: USC quarterback Carson Palmer's subpar
performance was still a heavy topic of conversation Tuesday, and
Hackett said Palmer was ``short-arming'' throws and never got ``in
a rhythm or a flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said wide receiver Kareem Kelly, who caught just two
passes, also never was allowed to get into a flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look back at that,'' Hackett said. ``Neither guy
had a chance to get into a rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW ATTITUDE: Hackett said the biggest difference in the 29-5
victory over the Nittany Lions was how the Trojans reacted to Penn
State formations for which they had not prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys adjusted,'' he said. ``Our guys played with a
confidence I hadn't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (Penn State) would be more physically dominant
against our defense. Was it us or was their offense disjointed? I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   KNIGHT RETURNS: Linebacker Darryl Knight did an about-face and
decided to rejoin the football team. Knight contacted Nevada-Las
Vegas and informed the Rebels he intended to transfer but changed
his mind after a meeting with USC coach Paul Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just frustrated. It was something we talked and got
resolved,'' Knight said. ``I want to be a Trojan.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight quit the team last week after being kicked off the
practice field by defensive coordinator Bill Young during a
walk-through. He had been demoted to the scout team prior to the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   He could challenge for a starting linebacker spot next season
because he plays weakside linebacker, where senior Markus Steele is
the current starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been reinstated. The Knight family has too much history
here,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Center Carlos Acosta of Moorpark College, who left the team last
month after becoming homesick, also returned Tuesday and will
redshirt this season.
</P>
<P>
   MACKENZIE OUT: Tailback Malaefou MacKenzie will not practice
this week to rest his strained hamstring. Hackett said MacKenzie
should be ready for the Colorado game the following week.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Ryan Nielsen (shoulder) and tailback Petros
Papadakis (foot) will only practice once to rest nagging injuries
but are also fine for the game.
</P>
<P>
   GOAL FOR WEEK: Hackett said the Trojans have not played well in
games following a victory and a bye, and it's something he wants to
correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our history the last two years is we play questionable after a
bye,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   USC is 2-1 in those situations. They lost to UCLA 34-17 in 1998
but also defeated San Diego State 35-6. Last year, the Trojans
defeated San Diego State 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY OF PLANE: Lightning forced the team plane to sit on the
runway for more than two hours after the game, and USC did not
return from New York until 2:30 a.m. PDT Monday morning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
