<HEADLINE>
SPRINT'S PRESIDENT LOOKS AT THE COMPANY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Since Sprint Corp. and WorldCom Inc. gave up
on their $129 billion merger, Wall Street has kicked the breath out
of Sprint's main stock.
</P>
<P>
   The shares, known by their FON trading symbol, closed Tuesday at
$32.56, less than half the $76 in stock that WorldCom was going to
pay. Sprint's separate PCS stock, which tracks the operation of its
wireless business, traded Tuesday at $48.06, 20 percent off its
price July 13 when the deal was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the stock price slide has sickened Ronald T. LeMay,
Sprint's president and chief operating officer. But during a recent
interview, LeMay outlined Sprint's plan to address Wall Street's
uncertainties about how the telecommunications company will move
forward independently.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, which employs roughly 20,000 people in the Kansas City
area, will shift from being known primarily as a national
long-distance provider to a mover of voice and data by both land
lines and wireless technology, LeMay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not happy at all where the stock price is. I am a big
shareholder too. I can empathize because I am feeling it,'' said
LeMay, whose value of Sprint and Sprint PCS securities has fallen
by about $223.7 million, to about $127.6 million, since the merger
was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The company will focus on markets worldwide where it is
currently building out networks of its Internet backbone _ which
connects Internet service providers to the Internet _ and its
wireless broadband technology.
</P>
<P>
   Its wireless broadband, the ability to provide Internet service
with wireless technology, has the potential to reach roughly a
third of the U.S. market to serve both consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, LeMay said Sprint would work its way out of the
stand-alone consumer long-distance market, packaging its
long-distance with such services as PCS wireless and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not going to be the same uniform national market people
have gotten accustomed to when people look at long-distance
carriers,'' LeMay predicted. ``It is going to be much more a
locally oriented market with long-distance and other things as
components.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question there are fundamental changes occurring in
the market. The question, analysts said, is whether nine months of
merger negotiations sapped Sprint of some of the talent, drive and
agility to master the rearranged steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying the right things, that the market is changing
and they are changing to meet that challenge,'' said Jeff Kagan, a
telecommunications industry analyst based in Atlanta. ``Recognizing
the problem and admitting you have a problem is half the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have to deal with the reality, that they are
without the same bench strengths they had a year ago. The company
has to either go it alone and fill in all of their weak spots or be
acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of what has happened to Sprint's share price is tied to
the annulment of the merger, analysts say. Investors are
disenchanted with the telecommunications category generally, and
the shares of AT&AMP;T, WorldCom and many others are trading well off
prices of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for long-distance service continue to drop, putting
pressure on company earnings at the same time many companies are
investing tens of millions of dollars in the data and wireless
networks essential to be competitive. That revaluing of the
telecommunications industry was already under way at the time that
Sprint's merger with WorldCom was canceled, giving a double hit to
Sprint's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts still MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
