<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MISTAKES WERE MADE ...   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the lovely and talented Leah Garchik's
meticulously researched and edited column Tuesday in this very
newspaper, there was a tiny mistake.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reference to actor Jack Larson, ``who played
photographer Jimmy Olsen on the TV series `Superman.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As a former kid whose lower jaw hung like a busted drawbridge
for 30 minutes every week during ``Superman,'' I know that Jimmy
was not a photographer, but a cub reporter for the Daily Planet
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   I blanched at the tiny mistake because:
</P>
<P>
   1. Now Leah can't have a perfect year '00.
</P>
<P>
   2. Now Leah will get e-mail from every Boomer still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The largest volume of response I've received to any one item
came after I mixed up two ``Leave It to Beaver'' characters, Larry
Mondelo and Lumpy Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, of course, was the Beaver's African American pal. Just
kidding! As anyone who watched TV in the late '50s knows, blacks
had not yet been invented.
</P>
<P>
   Nor had homosexuals. Leah's item was interesting in that it
revealed that Jack Larson was (is?) gay. So mild-mannered Clark
Kent wasn't the only person on that TV show who was ducking in and
out of closets to keep a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ANYWAY, my point is that mistakes happen and we need to be
forgiving. In Monday's column, for instance, I wrote that San
Francisco's Ingleside Terraces neighborhood is located in the
city's southeast corner, when in reality it is quite clearly in the
southwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   This might explain why, on a Boy Scout hike, I took a wrong turn
and wound up being raised by wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   ONE PROBLEM is that there are no orientation songs about San
Francisco, like there are about, say, New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York, New York, it's a helluva town/The Bronx is up and
the Battery's down.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm working on one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That old S.F., it's a columnist's feast/Ingleside's west and
the Bayview is east.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fog's from the left, so it's never too hot/North Beach is
North and Soma's south of the Slot.''
</P>
<P>
   I could go on. That might be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   EVEN JERRY Brown makes mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's New Age, free-range mayor hosts yoga and
consciousness-raising sessions in his own home, as do most of us.
</P>
<P>
   In a Chronicle story on the sessions, Brown is quoted thusly:
``Aristotle says the unexamined life is not worth living.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp-eyed Barbara Loeb points out: Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Brown should get his philosophers straight,'' Loeb says,
and she's right, because what's worse than a crooked philosopher?
</P>
<P>
   Loeb notes that the famous quote (``The life which is unexamined
is not worth living'') is from Plato. The quote is from Plato's
``Apology,'' in which Plato wrote down not his own words and
thoughts, but the orations of, and the dialogues involving,
Socrates.
</P>
<P>
   Aristotle? He was that ancient Greek shipping magnate who
married Jackie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   AND SAY, maybe Mayor Brown can invite Al Gore in for a few of
those yoga sessions, loosen Al up a bit, free his head.
</P>
<P>
   What a scene: It would take six burly Secret Service agents
armed with Liquid Wrench to help Gore achieve a lotus position.
</P>
<P>
   But as Yogi Berra, the great yoga master and George W. Bush
speechwriter, once said, ``When you come to the fork in the road _
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR JERRY, by the way, just might be the most relentlessly
idealistic person in American folklore since Jimmy Olsen. (Gunther
Toody is close, but a little too ditzy.)
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy was just so full of enthusiasm and energy. Even when he
and Lois Lane were tossed into a dark mine shaft by the bad guys,
Jimmy always knew that Superman would rescue them.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jerry Brown, saving Oakland might be the craziest and
most ambitious political stunt in decades. And undertaken with a
seeming lack of ulterior motive, except maybe that of collecting
frequent-flier cosmic karma points.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco used to have a fascinating, in his own way, mayor.
Whatever happened to that Willie Brown guy? Somebody should check
the bottom of the old mine shaft. Which, by the way, is being
converted to a live-work shaft loft.
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING TO the theme of mistakes and Greeks, the Greek
community in Sydney, Australia, is in an uproar, and you hate it
when that happens.
</P>
<P>
   In designing the medals that will be awarded to Olympic
medalists, the artist was instructed to salute the ancient Olympics
of Greece, but rendered an arena that is distinctly ancient Roman
in style.
</P>
<P>
   Which is like designing a travel poster of San Francisco that
features Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, I'm told that if you look closely at the medal, the
athlete is wearing horn-rim glasses and has a plastic
pocket-protector on his toga. The artist explained, ``Oh. I thought
you said you wanted me to honor the ancient  &UR; geeks. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   FULL CIRCLE back to my own mistakes: I noted in Monday's column
that Urbano Drive is the only street in the city where you can go
around and around forever.
</P>
<P>
   Readers such as Ernie Lubbe point out that I am way wrong. There
are many many circular streets in San Francisco. There is even a
circular street, Country Club Drive, that circles inside another
circular street, Lakeshore Drive.
</P>
<P>
   However, notes Lubbe, Circular Ave. is not circular.
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is, if I spent all my time checking old facts, I
wouldn't have time to make up new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Jimmy Olsen used to say, ``Jeepers!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
