<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW--BUSINESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITE EASES SALE OF BUSINESSES  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
If you want to buy a small business or have one you want to sell,
there are a number of useful Web sites to learn how to do it and
find listings.
<P>
   One of the best, especially if you live in California, is San
Ramon's Business Exchange Network and its California Businesses for
Sale site ( &LR; www.allcalifbiz.com &LR; ). Former small business consultant
and business broker Peter Siegel started the Web site seven years
ago for two main reasons _ to track the number of businesses sold
in California and to create a central clearinghouse for business
buyers, owner/sellers and agents and brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knew what was on the market so I started both a monthly
newspaper and a Web site,'' said Siegel. The site has about 2,100
California business listings at any one time and more than 50,000
visitors a week. Businesses can be perused by county and region or
by sector, such as manufacturing, services, restaurants, hotels,
liquor stores, gas stations and million-dollar businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel, who operated a catering company and traffic schools
while getting his undergraduate and MBA degrees at UCLA, also
offers plenty of free information and advice on his site. Articles
cover dozens of subjects, including negotiating the sale of your
business, putting a value on goodwill, the escrow process and
presale tuneups. California Businesses for Sale also sponsors
workshops.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Web sites also help connect business sellers and
buyers. They include  &LR; www.bizquest.com &LR; ,  &LR; www.biztrader.com &LR; ,
 &LR; www.businessesforsale.com &LR; ,  &LR; www.mergernetwork.com &LR;  and
 &LR; www.nationlist.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses sell for between 2.5 and 6 times their annual
adjusted gross income, according to Siegel. Fifteen years ago, when
he operated eight traffic schools catering to Los Angeles college
students like himself, Siegel did even better than that. He figures
he made close to $300 on every $450 of revenues. Thirty people
would pay $15 each to attend the class and he paid the instructor
about $85 and rented a room from the YMCA for about $40.
</P>
<P>
   Operating your own business can still be a good deal. But in
this era of plenty of jobs and low unemployment, Siegel said it has
been getting harder for some sellers to find buyers. In fact,
California business sales are down from a year ago. Through Aug.
19, California Businesses for Sale tracked 11,875 sales compared to
12,710 in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel offers these 10 tips to business sellers to avoid
wrecking a deal:
</P>
<P>
   _ Place a reasonable price on your business. Because an inflated
figure either turns buyers off or slows down potential buyers, rely
on a consultant to help you arrive at the best ``win-win'' price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carry on ``business as usual.'' Don't become so obsessed with
the transaction that your attention wavers from day-to-day demands,
affecting sales, costs and profits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hire experts to ensure confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   _Prepare for the sale well in advance. Be sure your records are
complete for at least several years back and do all pertinent legal
or accounting ``housecleaning'' and literally spruce up the plant
or store.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anticipate information the buyer may request. To obtain
financing, the buyer will need appraisals on assets such as real
estate, as well as information to satisfy environmental
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure your marketing and advertising are going full tilt
to keep potential buyers competing against one another.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be flexible. Don't insist on all-cash at the closing or
dismiss any contingent payments. Depend on the advice of your
consultant, CPA or attorney and their knowledge of financing and
tax implications.
</P>
<P>
   _ Negotiate; don't ``dominate.'' Decide ahead of time when ``to
hold'' and when ``to fold.''
</P>
<P>
   _Keep time from dragging down the deal. Stay on a schedule.
</P>
<P>
   _Be willing to stay involved for a time to help the buyer
through a transition period.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
