<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CABLE--LINES-SFCHRON &LR;      08-30 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE--LINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES SEEK A CLEAR LINE AROUND PAC BELL 
 &HT;     BY TODD WALLACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; By all accounts, AT&AMP;T's efforts to sell local phone service in
California three years ago was a disaster.
<P>
   Thousands of residential customers had to wait weeks to be
switched over from Pacific Bell, partly because of glitches in Pac
Bell's order system. Others lost their dial tone for several days.
And AT&AMP;T said it was forced to pay so much to Pac Bell, which
controls the local phone lines, that it had little hope of ever
turning a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in late 1998, AT&AMP;T offered to pay its 50,000 customers
to switch back to Pacific Bell, and reported it lost $4 million on
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   But Ma Bell isn't giving up on the local market. During the past
two years, the telecommunications giant has quietly signed up many
more than 10,000 local phone customers in the Bay Area through its
cable television lines _ doing a partial end run around Pac Bell.
In a handful of cities in the East Bay, including Fremont, AT&AMP;T has
signed up nearly 20 percent of homes eligible for the service. The
company now serves more than two dozen towns, mostly in the East
Bay and Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   Now, AT&AMP;T is preparing to fire a cannon shot across Pac Bell's
bow on Friday, offering potential customers five free months of
local phone service to switch. AT&AMP;T insists there are no
installation fees, long-term contracts or other catches. If
consumers decide to switch back to Pac Bell after five months, they
can do so without paying AT&AMP;T a penny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable,'' said one financial analyst who
follows AT&AMP;T. Added Yankee Group analyst Fritz McCormick: ``It
shows they are very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The promotion also demonstrates that local phone competition is
starting to become a reality in some neighborhoods _ but in a
different form than originally envisioned. Instead of using Pac
Bell's telephone wires, rivals are increasingly offering phone
service to consumers over coaxial cable TV lines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to AT&AMP;T, two cable upstarts are also rolling out
phone service: RCN Communications, which just struck an agreement
to lay wires in San Francisco, is initially offering phone service
in Daly City, South San Francisco and San Mateo. And Seren
Innovations has initiated local telephone service under the
``Astound'' brand name in Concord with plans to expand into nearby
Walnut Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is already translating into lower prices. RCN is
offering basic dial tone for just $5 _ half the $10.69 Pac Bell
charges. And AT&AMP;T is charging just $5 for a second or third line;
Pac Bell, by contrast, charges another $10.69 per month plus a $33
setup fee.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, both RCN and Seren, a division of Northern States
Power Co. in Minneapolis, are bundling phone service with cable TV
service and superfast Internet access, promising customers a
discount for the entire package. Seren, for instance, is knocking
10 percent off the total price. AT&AMP;T says it plans to follow suit
next year.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates are underwhelmed with the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Costa, a telecommunications analyst with The Utility
Reform Network in San Francisco, said cable coverage is too spotty.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T doesn't offer any phone service in San Francisco, San Jose
or Oakland, for instance, because the equipment is outdated. AT&AMP;T
said it must retrofit most of its 2.6 million cable lines in the
Bay Area during the next couple years to offer the service. And
even in cities it serves, AT&AMP;T hasn't upgraded the equipment in
some apartment buildings or blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wishful thinking that cable is going to be a viable
competitor for phones for anything but a handful of customers,''
Costa said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, though, Pac Bell could benefit if AT&AMP;T and RCN steal
a significant slice of its customers. The phone company needs to
convince state regulators that the local phone market is open to
competition in order to win permission to enter the long-distance
market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a handful of companies are using Pac Bell's wires
to offer local phone service, but it is extremely limited.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications, for instance, is test marketing a
package in San Francisco that includes local and long-distance
service for $34. But Verizon doesn't market local phone service by
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Other major players, including WorldCom and Sprint, also tried
marketing local phone service through phone wires in 1997 and 1998,
but pulled out along with AT&AMP;T. They both blamed foul-ups with Pac
Bell's order system and said Pacific Bell charges too much to tap
into its wires to a home. (Companies typically must pay about
$14.50 per line, Pac Bell spokesman Bill Mashek said, or they can
buy Pac Bell's services at a 17 percent discount.) Pac Bell says
that it ironed out most of the bugs, and that none of the players
made a ``whole-hearted'' effort to compete through local phone
wires.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, AT&AMP;T is making a huge bet that it can gain a leg up
on Pac Bell by using its own wiring. The telecommunications giant
spent roughly $125 billion buying companies like TCI, the cable
company that serves 90 percent of the Bay Area, and Media One, a
Colorado cable giant. To make the deal pay off, AT&AMP;T has told Wall
Street it hopes to sign up millions of local phone customers during
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the company has had trouble meeting its target
of signing up 400,000 local phone customers nationwide by year end
(not including Media One). As of June, AT&AMP;T sold roughly 101,000
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not necessarily going to hit those goals,'' said
McCormick, the Yankee Group analyst. Although McCormick said that
AT&AMP;T has been reasonably successful, the firm may have set the bar
too high.
</P>
<P>
   Given the situation, some analysts weren't sure whether AT&AMP;T's
five-month promotion is an aggressive marketing tactic or a
desperate move to meet its subscriber goals.
</P>
<P>
   ABN AMRO analyst Kevin Roe said the move could be logical in a
``highly penetrated market'' like some parts of San Francisco. But
if AT&AMP;T starts using the promotion in ``virgin markets,'' he said
it could be a troublesome sign. Another analyst, who asked not to
be named, said the promotion shows that AT&AMP;T ``will do anything''
to meet its goals.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokesman Andrew Johnson, however, said the company is
doing well without the promotion. Since it started service in
Petaluma in May, for instance, AT&AMP;T said it has grabbed 2.5 percent
of the market in just three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time that we're ready to make a big splash,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T plans to back up the promotion with newspaper ads, radio
spots and television commercials on both broadcast stations and
cable. (Until now, AT&AMP;T has mostly used direct marketing tactics,
even going door to door, in a handful of towns.) In addition to the
Bay Area, AT&AMP;T plans to start the five-month promotion in eight
other cities around the country, such as Seattle and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
