<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWRENCE-HOT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE LETS GO OF RECORD HIGHS AS STUDENTS MONITOR AN `ARCTIC'
96 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Outside, temperature readings again flirted
with 100 on Tuesday. Inside the University of Kansas Storm
Prediction Center, three student meteorologists wrote down the
readings, printed them out and dutifully recorded them on
clipboards filled with thick stacks of other numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But these KU students don't have to read the thermometer to know
it's hot outside. Before Tuesday's comparatively arctic 96 on
Tuesday, Lawrence endured back-to-back highs of 109 degrees,
national highs for each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony of all this,'' said KU senior Keith Weber, 21, ``is
that we're at the hottest spot in the nation and the weather lab
has no air conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last week, the air-conditioning unit on the sixth floor of
KU's Malott Hall has refused to do its job.
</P>
<P>
   But the students monitoring the lab's numbers are still there,
albeit wearing shorts and sweat-drenched T-shirts, trying to
capture readings as furnacelike drafts from four fans surround
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do get kinda used to it after a while,'' said Matt Makens,
a 20-year-old junior. ``We're still laughing about it, though. And
if it does get cooler, we'll be the first to know.''
</P>
<P>
   If?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, it will get cooler; we just don't know when,'' Makens
said.
</P>
<P>
   The KU weather lab is an unofficial National Weather Service
monitoring station. It houses $30,000 worth of computers and
monitoring equipment that help examine the science of Lawrence's
weather from ground level to the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Not a cloud was in sight Tuesday from an office window facing
some residence halls on the KU campus. Just endless blue. On the
roof of Malott Hall is a weather monitor that records wind speeds
and humidity and temperature readings at the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night at midnight, it was 89 degrees,'' Makens said.
``We're right on the boundary of wet weather...but the southern
winds are sucking up all the warm Texas air and just blowing it on
us. If it could just shift a little, we'd have rain.''
</P>
<P>
   He used a computer model to demonstrate. ``Only thing is, the
computers are out to lunch too, because of the heat,'' he said.
``They base their prediction models on what it should be from
previously recorded weather averages. The computers don't even know
about these extreme temperatures. One model told us it would be in
the high 80s today.''
</P>
<P>
   The three students shook their heads.
</P>
<P>
   In weather like this, human beings _ and their knowledge of
fluid mechanics and weather systems _ beat out a computer guess any
day, the students said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the professors are always telling us, `don't marry
the models,' '' said senior Brian Koochel, 23.
</P>
<P>
   David Braaten, an associate professor of atmospheric science,
explained that the weather temperatures are only as accurate as the
monitoring stations that record them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Lawrence, our weather data is recorded out at the municipal
airport,'' he said. ``If we only beat the Texas record by two or
three degrees, well, that can always be chalked up to the
calibration of the instruments or the site location of the
sensors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Automated Surface Observing System sits off to the side of
the main runway at Lawrence Municipal Airport, a few miles from
Interstate 70.
</P>
<P>
   The machine is actually eight modules mounted on poles. Each
module analyzes one aspect of the weather and reports the
information to computers in Lawrence and Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   But inside one dome-shaped unit, a fan whirrs continuously. Here
is where the thermometer sits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most people don't know,'' said Braaten, ``is that every
temperature printed in the newspaper or broadcast over television
or radio is really a shade temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   The unit, he explained, always records the temperature inside
the housing cooled by the fan, because scientists want to know the
temperature of the air, not the solar temperatures on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're standing out in the sun, it's safe to say that you
can easily add 30 more degrees and you'd be pretty accurate on the
actual temperature,'' he said. ``But that probably won't make
anyone feel any better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
