<HEADER>
A5968 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NET--WORTH-SFCHRON &LR;      08-30 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET--WORTH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO'S STOCK GETS CLAWED ON WALL STREET  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
There's a tug-of-war breaking out on Wall Street over Yahoo.
<P>
   On Monday, Lehman Bros. stock analyst Holly Becker questioned
Yahoo's growth prospects and sky-high valuation in light of the
slowdown in Internet advertising. Her report sent Yahoo shares
plummeting $12.19 _ about 9 percent _ to $122.06.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Yahoo bulls _ including Henry Blodget of Merrill Lynch
_ rushed to the company's aid with positive comments about its
long-term prospects, but they failed to breathe much life into the
stock. It closed yesterday at $121.
</P>
<P>
   This chain of events was eerily similar to what happened to
Amazon.com earlier this summer, and shows how susceptible even the
leading Internet companies have become to the slightest shift in
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   On June 22, another Lehman analyst _ Ravi Suria _ issued a
scathing report on Amazon.com's convertible bonds. Amazon's stock
fell from $46.06 the day before the report to $33.88 the day after.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's backers, again including Blodget, reiterated their
bullish opinions, but there was no immediate improvement in the
stock. It has since regained about half that loss, closing
yesterday at $39.63.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when Suria initiated his missile attack on Amazon's
bonds, his co-worker Becker had a buy rating on Amazon stock. Since
then, Becker has lowered her opinion on Amazon to ``neutral,'' the
same opinion she ``reiterated'' on Yahoo this week.
</P>
<P>
   Becker didn't respond to requests for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   When I called Yahoo for a response, a Yahoo spokeswoman pulled
out her ``Holly Becker'' file and read me the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``At this juncture we see no material change to the past
statements we have made about our business. As we identified in
discussing the June quarter, we are not immune to changes in the
dot-com world and are working a little harder in this quarter than
in past ones given the tightness in dot-com advertising budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   The beating Yahoo stock took is a bit puzzling. Becker's report
didn't break a lot of ground, and she's not the first analyst to
raise such warnings. As Yahoo's statement indicates, Internet
advertising has been a concern for most of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In case you were glued to ``Survivor'' instead of ``The Nightly
Business Report,'' here's a recap:
</P>
<P>
   A lot of dot-coms are running out of money. Since dot-coms are
the biggest Web advertisers, this is bad news for Internet
companies that rely on advertising. Analysts estimate that
advertising accounts for 70 to 80 percent of Yahoo's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, Yahoo reported a blowout second quarter, and its
stock jumped from $105 to $124 in one day. The stock kept going up,
hitting $139 last week, until Becker weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   In her report, she explains that ``in the second quarter, the
dot-com environment remained healthy until June, leaving Yahoo with
only one difficult month. In 3Q, Yahoo will be facing a full
quarter of belt tightening by dot-com companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further, Yahoo's 2Q also benefited from unexpected upside in
e-commerce,'' Becker writes. In addition to advertising dollars,
Yahoo gets a cut of certain sales that go through its site. But,
``with a lion's share of its merchants already paying a royalty and
flattish transaction growth, we believe it is unlikely that 3Q will
see as great of an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker says she's looking for signs that traditional advertisers
are moving online, ``but we are receiving little comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked at Yahoo's top 200 advertisers for July and found
that ``dot-com advertisers continued to make up the majority of
advertisers, 61 percent in July compared to 63 percent in May. ...
Traditional companies were down to 23 from 24 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts _ even the bulls _ agree that Yahoo is unlikely to
have an exceptional third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first full quarter of the dot-com shakedown. And it's
a weak seasonal advertising quarter,'' says Blodget.
</P>
<P>
   He says things will pick up for Yahoo during the fourth quarter,
because advertisers won't cut back on marketing during the
pre-holiday season. But others envision a longer slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see any near-term catalyst that's big enough to
really drive this stock to the next plateau,'' says Derek Brown of
WR Hambrecht &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst John Corcoran of CIBC World Markets agrees.``Over the
next two quarters, investors need to be cautious in terms of their
upside expectations,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Yahoo will replace dot-com advertisers with Fortune
500 companies. ``But when you sell to a Fortune 500 player, it's a
much longer selling cycle. It takes six to nine months to get in
the door,'' he says. ``They're also more sophisticated and
conservative media buyers than the dot-com players. They start off
with smaller ad buys.'' And, needless to say, they will drive a
harder bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Corcoran reduced his 12-month price target on Yahoo
to $215 from $250, but maintained his ``strong buy'' rating.
</P>
<P>
   Like most analysts, he says Yahoo ultimately will benefit from
dot-com consolidation. Weaker competitors will disappear and
Fortune 500 companies will concentrate their spending on the top
two or three sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe that the Internet is a mass medium which is
rapidly acquiring real estate across a variety of new technology
platforms, there are two or three players defining and establishing
brands that are truly global platforms. One is Yahoo,'' says
analyst Chris Dixon of PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're also one of the few that has figured out how to
integrate (Web) hosting and business services with advertising and
e-commerce,'' he adds. ``Most importantly, they have a business
model that is almost the best I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where Yahoo differs from Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo is a very clean Internet play,'' Corcoran says. ``They
understand that the marginal cost of distribution over the Internet
approaches zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon uses the Internet to great advantage on the front end,
but it still has to ship and warehouse books, a capital-intensive
business subject to intense price competition.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: Yahoo is profitable; Amazon is not.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Yahoo's market capitalization is $66 billion,
Amazon's is $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even with this week's $7 billion decline in Yahoo's market cap,
Brown warns, ``there's little room for a shortfall.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at penderk(AT)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
