<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5969 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HEART--OFGOLD-SFCHRON     08-30 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART--OFGOLD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA TOWN FINDS BANK WITH HEART 
 &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; The little eastern Sierra town of Bridgeport won't lose its only
bank next month after all.
<P>
   When Bank of America leaves Bridgeport at the end of September,
its place will be taken by Oak Valley Community Bank, a tiny
independent based in the San Joaquin Valley town of Oakdale.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport, the center of a tourist region that draws tens of
thousands of vacationers to its mountains, lakes and streams every
summer, is one of the most isolated communities in California.
Mammoth Lakes, the nearest town with a bank, is nearly 60 miles
south.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's announcement two months ago that it planned to close its
Bridgeport branch meant the town's 700 residents would have had to
drive 120 miles round trip to do their banking.
</P>
<P>
   Area merchants said the bank's departure would disrupt their
businesses and leave them vulnerable to robbery as they took their
cash on the highway. Bridgeport's plight was the subject of stories
in The Chronicle and other news media.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Valley decided to take over BofA's Bridgeport office after
local residents carried out a three-week whirlwind courtship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled,`` said resort owner Kellie Annett, who
spearheaded the campaign to keep a bank in Bridgeport. Annett said
she telephoned the chief executives of every bank within 100 miles
to find a replacement for BofA.
</P>
<P>
   Most bankers said BofA's Bridgeport branch didn't do enough
business to make money. But Oak Valley Chief Executive Officer Ron
Martin said he was won over by the prospect of gaining a new group
of loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' said Martin. ``We met a lot of nice people in
Bridgeport.`'
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he hopes to make a go of it by winning more business
from area residents and taking over the accounts of the Mono County
government, whose seat is in Bridgeport. ``In the scheme of things,
it will be profitable,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Valley will purchase for an undisclosed sum the office BofA
built 40 years ago when it first came to town, plus some equipment.
The bank isn't buying accounts, but BofA said it will make it easy
for customers to make the switch.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakdale bank is asking state and federal regulators to speed
the process of approving the branch sale so it can take possession
on Sept. 29, the date BofA is scheduled to leave. BofA has pledged
to keep the branch open if the red tape isn't completed by that
date, officials of the two banks said.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Valley's arrival takes the heat off BofA for a move many
local residents saw as a case of an unfeeling corporation putting
profits before community service. That rap was unfair, BofA
officials said, because they had been trying to sell the Bridgeport
branch for years before deciding to close it.
</P>
<P>
   Making sure that Bridgeport had a bank ``was something we placed
a high value on,'' said Larry Knutson, the BofA executive in
Bakersfield who supervises the branch. ``In this case we were very
fortunate.``
</P>
<P>
   The deal pairs the nation's biggest bank with one of
California's smallest. North Carolina's BofA has $680 billion in
assets and more than 4,400 branches in 21 states. Oak Valley has
$120 million in assets and four offices in the San Joaquin Valley
and Sierra foothills.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
