r a BC-HEAT-KAN &LR;      08-30 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE SLIGHT BREAK IN HEAT, MAN DIES IN KANSAS CITY HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR and DONNA McGUIRE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After more than a week of 100-degree
temperatures, the relentless heat wave has claimed its first
victim.
</P>
<P>
   A family member found the body of a 68-year-old man late Monday
in his uncooled Northeast area home. A fan buzzed inside, but it
probably just increased the elderly man's body temperature by
circulating hot air, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For eight days now, temperatures in parts of the metropolitan
area have hit at least 100 degrees. A weak weather front brought
some relief Tuesday to Kansas City's north side.
</P>
<P>
   That brought a divergence in temperatures from north to south _
a disparity that reached its greatest difference at 2:30 p.m., when
the temperature at Kansas City International Airport was 87 while
at New Century AirCenter in southwest Johnson County, Kan., it was
100.
</P>
<P>
   The official high at KCI on Tuesday was 91, which was a break
from a 105-degree Monday. New Century AirCenter's high Tuesday was
100. Kansas City's record high for a Tuesday, set in 1984, was 110.
Today the high may reach 102 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Across the metropolitan area, social service agencies,
utilities, cities and school districts were reallocating resources
to combat the effects of the heat. The area remains under a heat
advisory today, and Health Department officials urge people,
particularly the elderly, to take precautions and stay cool.
</P>
<P>
   Many schools were letting students out early.
</P>
<P>
   The weather also kept the Kansas City area under an orange alert
for ozone, a warning that air pollution may rise to unhealthy
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Local utilities _ both electric and water _ reported record
consumption on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the heat wave's human toll that concerned most on
Tuesday. This week's heat-related death brings the year's total to
six, but health officials worry that the number could quickly rise
if the intense heat lingers. The forecast calls for temperatures in
the 100s and high 90s through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Last year 21 died in the summer heat. Those concerns had social
service agencies scrambling Tuesday to establish cooling shelters
and provide air conditioners, fans and information about how to
stay cool.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite Williams, 94, had no air conditioner in her Northeast
area home on Monday, and she regretted having to close her front
door at sunset. It meant she would be stuck inside her steamy home,
without a breeze, all night.
</P>
<P>
   Before relief came her way, she stretched out on the living room
couch, near the front door where the breeze once flowed. And she
turned off a large floor fan borrowed from a neighbor. It was
blowing only hot air, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was afraid to look at the thermostat. She didn't want to
know how hot it really was. Finally, she got the idea to soak bath
towels with water and drape them across her body. She also wet a
wash cloth and periodically brushed it across her cat, Blackie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those wet towels sure saved me,'' she said Tuesday afternoon,
a few hours after two men from Bishop Sullivan Center installed a
new window air conditioner for her.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Woods, chairwoman of the Kansas City Health Department's
heat task force, cautioned that when temperatures are around 100,
fans do little more than circulate the hot air. They may even raise
the body temperature of someone trapped in that heat, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can be helpful, she added, if people spray their bodies
with water or use wet towels, as Williams did.
</P>
<P>
   In response to last year's heat wave, Bishop Sullivan Center has
provided about 300 free air conditioners this year to low-income
elderly and disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think this program has helped,'' said Executive
Director Tom Turner, who purchased an air conditioner for Williams
on Tuesday after hearing of her situation.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, which quickly gave away the five air conditioners it
had available Tuesday, expects to receive about 30 more today. That
likely won't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   By 1 p.m. Tuesday, more than 150 people had called seeking help.
A few others dropped by the agency's office on Truman Road. One man
looked downcast when a staff member said about 100 people were
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Nena Sudan, who lives a few blocks from the agency, was among
many turned away in recent days because her home already had one
window air conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that,'' Sudan said Tuesday in her rented
Northeast area home. ``But I'm just suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   One window air conditioner cools her living room and a small
downstairs bedroom, where her husband, Sabir Sudan, sleeps in a
hospital bed. The 51-year-old Vietnam veteran has kidney cancer and
arthritis in his spine.
</P>
<P>
   Nena Sudan, 57, avoids sleeping on the cooled couch downstairs
because it hurts her arthritic hips too much. Her upstairs bedroom
gets so hot, she can't sleep there until 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday afternoon at 4:30 p.m., it was 104 degrees up here
with the fans going,'' she said, huffing from climbing 12 wooden
stairs from the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes someone else will donate a window unit for her.
</P>
<P>
   The Sullivan Center and United Services Community Action Agency
are seeking money to buy more air conditioners. United Services
provided 360 units to Missouri residents before running out earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   An officer from the Kansas City Police Department's East Patrol
Division called to check on elderly people Monday and Tuesday as
part of the patrol's senior watch program.
</P>
<P>
   One 95-year-old woman reported dizziness, heat problems and
possible dehydration Monday but refused to seek medical attention.
She had an air conditioner but refused to run it regularly because
of the electric costs.
</P>
<P>
   A worried officer, Donna Rollo-Leap, went to the woman's home
with paramedics. The woman still refused a hospital visit, but
Rollo-Leap finally persuaded her to stay at her granddaughter's
home for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't think (people) understand is there is help for
their utility bills,'' Rollo-Leap said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the metropolitan area, hospitals reported people seeking
treatment for heat-related problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
