<HEADER>
A5971 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INSIDER--TRADING-SFCH     08-30 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDER--TRADING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI CHARGES TECH WORKER IN INSIDER TRADING CASE  &HT;     BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
A former engineer at Santa Clara's Nvidia Corp. was arrested
Tuesday on insider trading charges after allegedly earning almost
$450,000 on the company's shares prior to the announcement of a
major partnership with Microsoft Corp.
<P>
   Manu Shrivastava, 31, an Indian citizen residing in San Jose,
was released later in the day on $500,000 bail. His next court
appearance is scheduled for Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Nvidia, a maker of computer-game technology, fired Shrivastava
several weeks ago after learning of his alleged stock trades from
securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious thing for this company,'' said Dan Vivoli,
Nvidia's senior vice president of marketing. ``As soon as we
realized what happened, we took action against this employee.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission,
Shrivastava purchased nearly $31,000 worth of Nvidia call options
in early March.
</P>
<P>
   Call options allow a buyer to purchase shares at a fixed price.
Typically, an investor hopes the value of a stock rises before the
actual purchase is made, thus allowing the shares to be sold at a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said Shrivastava began purchasing Nvidia call options
using an online brokerage account after learning through an
internal company e-mail that Nvidia had won a lucrative contract to
develop components for Microsoft's new X-Box game machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xbox deal is closed!'' the SEC quoted Nvidia's chief
executive, Jen-Hsun Huang, as saying in one of the messages. ``If
Xbox becomes as big as Sony Playstation, we generate about $2B in
sales over 5 years.''
</P>
<P>
   This message was followed the next day by a separate e-mail from
Vivoli reminding the company's 500 employees that the Microsoft
contract remained confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a word to anyone outside of our walls,'' it said. ``Let
the news roll out in a controlled way.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft unveiled its X-Box several days later, including word
of the collaboration of Nvidia in developing graphics components.
</P>
<P>
   But rumors of the deal leaked out in advance of the unveiling,
driving Nvidia's share price up more than 70 percent. After the
announcement, Nvidia's stock price jumped another 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shrivastava's total earnings from his stock deals during the
period came to $446,724, the SEC said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mitchell, an SEC spokesman, said the Nasdaq Stock Market,
on which Nvidia's shares change hands, routinely investigates
trades that take place prior to major price movements. This led
securities regulators to Shrivastava, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Caldwell, who heads the securities fraud section of the
San Francisco office of the U.S. attorney's office, said
Shrivastava was arrested by FBI agents at his home yesterday
morning on charges of wire fraud and insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Shrivastava nor his lawyer could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   While Nvidia has not been charged with wrongdoing, the SEC's
Mitchell said the case raises questions about how a company should
share confidential information with hundreds of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it appropriate for a company to be sharing this information
without reminding them of the legality of trading on this
information?'' he asked. ``That's the question this case clearly
flags.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell at the U.S. attorney's office agreed. ``The company
might want to think about how widely it wants to publicize
impending announcements that could affect the stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nvidia's Vivoli insisted that the company had acted
responsibly. He noted that all company employees sign an agreement
never to trade in stock options, and that they also agree never to
buy or sell the company's shares during self-imposed ``blackout
periods.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a blackout period had been declared shortly after the
first message went out telling Nvidia workers that the deal had
been closed with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Vivoli also observed that nearly all of the company's employees
were involved with the X-Box project ``in one way or another,'' and
thus it would have been difficult keeping a lid on such news.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's X-Box is slated to hit store shelves by late 2001.
It is the software giant's first stab at competing with the likes
of Nintendo Co., Sony Corp. and Sega Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Since Shrivastava's firing, Vivoli said the company's
stock-trading policy has been reiterated to workers in an e-mail
message and through team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   He said Shrivastava had been working for Nvidia as a software
engineer for only about a year. ``He was one of several engineers
in the company,'' Vivoli said. ``He didn't stand out one way or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty of insider trading, Shrivastava would forfeit
all his stock-market winnings to the U.S. government. He also faces
imprisonment for up to 10 years and fines of up to three times his
alleged profits.
</P>
<P>
   Nvidia's share price slipped 19 cents yesterday to close at
$77.81.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
