<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5973 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MINORITY-GROWTH-SFCHR     08-30 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-GROWTH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES INCREASE THEIR NUMBERS SUBSTANTIALLY, CENSUS FIGURES 
 SHOW
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The 1990s was a period of explosive growth for some minority groups
nationwide, and in California such increases put the total minority
population squarely in the majority, according to new figures
released Wednesday by the U.S. Census Bureau.
<P>
   It is a trend that experts say is likely to continue through the
next decade and one that will have enormous political and economic
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Asians and Pacific Islander populations across America grew by a
staggering 43 percent, while Latinos also made significant gains,
with a 39.7 increase in population.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the growth has been fueled in part by immigration of
high-tech workers, births to young immigrants and the arrival of
spouses and children of new citizens in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is substantial growth in two populations that were
already fairly large. To grow that fast really shows how strong the
migration has been over the last decade,'' said Barry Edmonston,
director of the Population Research Center at Portland State
University.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is riding on the data, said Amy Smith, a census
statistician demographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal dollars are allocated based on these numbers, things
like Head Start programs and Children in Poverty programs,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The census figures _ annual estimates based on births, deaths
and net migration for 1990-1999 _ show California's population
becoming increasingly diverse as it grew from 29.8 million to 33.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   During the decade, California had the largest numeric increase
in both Latino and Asian populations, with Los Angles County
showing unequaled growth from both groups.
</P>
<P>
   The population of Latinos in Los Angeles grew by 790,079 to
4,141,317, and the population of Asians increased by 259,665 to
1,253,291.
</P>
<P>
   California's Latino population rose from 7.7 million to 10.5
million from 1990 to 1999, a 36.4 percent increase. The Asian and
Pacific Islander population grew by nearly 36 percent, from 2.95
million to 4 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the state's non-Latino white population
declined from 17.9 million in 1990 to 16.5 million in 1999.
Non-Latino whites were 49.8 percent of the total state population
last year, while in 1990 they were 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other California minorities showed increases, but far smaller
than Asians and Latinos. American Indian and Alaska Native
populations grew by 9.4 percent, while African American populations
increased by 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the population grew from 249.5 million to 272.7
million. The Latino population rose from 22.4 million to 31.3
million, and Asian and Pacific Islanders went from 7.4 million to
10.8 million. The white population grew by 9.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonston said the decade's change has been influenced heavily
by immigration. One part of that is from foreign high-tech workers
being recruited to areas where the industry is booming, such as
Silicon Valley and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bulk of it is from Asian and Mexican immigrants who
were legalized in 1986 and became citizens in the 1990s, he said.
They then brought their spouses and children to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonston said NAFTA also affected population, bringing in
foreign workers and their families for a few years. Even though
they are in the nation temporarily, they are included in the count.
</P>
<P>
   The latest national figures reflect a change from the 1990
Census, when Latinos had to choose between white, black and
``other'' categories. There were also Asian and American Indian
options, but none for Latinos or Hispanics, who had traditionally
been counted among the white population.
</P>
<P>
   According to the new data, Nevada was the fastest-growing state
in the nation, ballooning about 50 percent from 1.2 million to 1.8
million, largely because a dramatic increase in the Latino and
Asian populations.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada saw a 144.6 percent increase in Latinos and a 123.7
percent increase in Asians _ the biggest growth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas topped the nation for growth in Latino population, with
a 170.3 percent rise from 19,876 to 53,729.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are indicative of how diversity has spread across
the nation. Margaret Leal-Sotelo, former national director of
census education programs for the Mexican American Legal Defense
and Education Fund in Los Angeles, said the figures also validate
the belief among Latino advocates that Latinos have been
undercounted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when you could go to parts of the country and
not see Latinos, and now we are seeing Latinos in Arkansas, in
Atlanta and in parts of the Carolinas. And I think that is very
telling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Effect on Elections
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Census Bureau released additional figures Tuesday
showing that the number of Latinos and Asian Americans who vote
jumped sharply, even as the overall number of voters nationwide
dropped by 2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500,000 additional Latinos voted in the congressional
elections of 1998 than voted in 1994, and the number of Asian
Americans and Pacific Islanders voting increased by 366,000 in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Magpantay of the Asian American Legal Defense and
Education Fund in New York said the new population figures raise
the prospect that increasing numbers of Asian American voters could
have an effect on the November election.
</P>
<P>
   He said many Asian Americans registered to vote after
Republicans cut safety nets and benefits for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asian Americans are voting their preferences. They are voting
for who they think will represent their interests,'' Magpantay
said. ``Asian Americans are going to have a much bigger impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
