<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-PHILIPPINES-KIDNAP-SF     08-30 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-KIDNAP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA MAN KIDNAPPED BY PHILIPPINE REBELS  &HT;     By BENJAMIN PIMENTEL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Oakland, Calif., man became the first American taken hostage
in the latest campaign of terror waged by Philippine rebels, who
have threatened to kill him if their demands are not met.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Schilling, 24, a recent graduate of the University of
California at Berkeley, was abducted Monday by the Abu Sayyaf,
which is fighting for an Islamic state in the southern Philippines.
Since April, the group has kidnapped three dozen people, including
European tourists from a Malaysian resort.
</P>
<P>
   Shilling's mother said Tuesday that hearing the news was like
plunging into ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to figure out how to pray, how to wait,'' Carol
Schilling, 51, of Oakland, said. Her son had been living in the
southern Philippine city of Zamboanga with his Filipino wife, who
reportedly is related to a rebel spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio interview in the Philippines, the rebel spokesman,
Abu Sabaya, accused Schilling of being a CIA agent and threatened
to execute him unless the United States agrees to release militants
jailed for the bombing of the World Trade Center in New York in
1993. That attack killed six people and injured more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling's abduction came after the rebels released six other
captives, all Westerners, from a guerrilla camp this week _
reportedly in exchange for $6 million. The captors continue to hold
French journalists and Filipino Christian evangelists who came to
their hideout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had followed news of those hostages and was feeling relieved
that they were being released, even though (Jeffrey) wasn't part of
that,'' said Carol Schilling. ``Now, my son is a hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. State Department official said the American Embassy in
Manila was working with the Philippine government to negotiate
Schilling's freedom. But the U.S. government will not pay ransom,
release prisoners or change policies, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing so only encourages additional terrorism and endangers
other people,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how Schilling, who moved to Zamboanga in March,
was abducted. An envoy to Philippine government hostage negotiator
Robert Aventajado confirmed seeing Schilling in an Abu Sayyaf camp,
a U.S. State Department representative said.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling's wife, Ivi Osani, said the rebels accompanied her and
Schilling to a rebel camp on Jolo island. She said the rebel
spokesman, Sabaya, is related to her mother and had been urging the
couple to visit the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   In a tearful interview with a radio journalist in the
Philippines, Osani pleaded with the rebel group to release her
husband. She said Schilling had told her to return alone to
Zamboanga, and she learned of his kidnap when she arrived there
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Father Jun Mercado, a Mindanao-based Catholic priest who has
followed the conflict on the island, said the Abu Sayyaf may have
decided to use Schilling as a shield in anticipation of a major
military offensive by the Philippine army after the release of the
other hostages this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sabaya, the Abu Sayyaf spokesman, said in the radio interview
that his group had been looking for an opportunity to kidnap an
American. He also suggested that they may demand even more money
for Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans may think we are afraid of them, but we are
really determined to get an American,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Schilling denied that her son is a CIA agent, calling him
a ``passionate, very idealistic'' young man.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, who graduated from UC Berkeley last year with a
degree in Near Eastern Studies, converted to Islam six years ago
and had befriended Filipino Muslims in the Bay Area before moving
to Zamboanga, his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to the Philippines because he had sympathy for the
Muslim people, their poverty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling eventually fell in love with Osani, a Filipino Muslim
student from Zamboanga. In April, he sent his mother an e-mail that
said: ``Met the girl of my dreams.'' The couple were married two
months ago. When the rebel group kidnapped the group of tourists in
Malaysia on April 23, Carol Schilling urged her son to come home
and even sent him a plane ticket, she said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was just too in love with Ivi to leave,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, her son told her that he was getting worried about the
Abu Sayyaf's threat to behead Americans. The group had beheaded two
Filipino captives earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, the Philippine military waged an all-out
offensive against a bigger rebel group, the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front, on the island of Mindanao, creating more tension in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Schilling said her son had tried to keep a low profile in
Zamboanga, remaining mostly indoors in the past months. He also
tried to get a job in Zamboanga, but he didn't have the proper
visa.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she said, he e-mailed her to say that he was coming
home on Sunday. His future plans with his new wife were unclear,
she said, but he planned to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed to start working for his wife and the kids they
planned to have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Schilling said that despite her son's abduction, she
harbors no ill will toward Muslim Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a distinction between the Muslim Filipinos and
the Abu Sayyaf,'' she said. ``They're extremists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
