<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-MARIJUANA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT RULING KEEPS CALIFORNIA POT CLUB FROM DISTRIBUTING 
 ITS WARES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HENRY K. LEE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Responding to an urgent request from the Clinton
administration, the U.S. Supreme Court issued an emergency order
Tuesday temporarily preventing an Oakland, Calif., medicinal
marijuana club from distributing its goods.
<P>
   The justices agreed by a 7-to-1 vote to stay enforcement of a
federal judge's ruling in San Francisco that would have allowed the
Oakland Cannabis Buyers' Cooperative to dispense marijuana to
seriously ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the Oakland club said they were not surprised
by the ruling, and they voiced confidence that they will prevail
when the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco _ which ruled in
their favor last year _ again hears their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This to me is a little bump in the road,'' said Jeff Jones,
executive director of the Oakland club. ``The Ninth Circuit could
lift the power of the stay and change the direction this case is
going again, kind of like a tennis match.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Uelmen, a Santa Clara University law professor and an
attorney for the club, agreed, saying the Supreme Court ruling only
``preserves the situation'' for now. ``Stay tuned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Michael, a spokeswoman for the Department of Justice,
had no immediate comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals could decide as early as next month whether
it will schedule oral arguments to review a decision made in July
by U.S. District Judge Charles Breyer in San Francisco that allowed
the dispensing of medicinal marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Oakland club has a new incarnation as the Co-op
Stop on Broadway in Oakland, selling hemp products and providing
identification cards for medicinal marijuana patients.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer's decision was based on a ruling last year by the appeals
court that said he should have considered the needs of patients who
could ``suffer imminent harm`' without marijuana and had no legal
alternative. In doing so, Breyer essentially modified his own 1998
order that shut down the Oakland club and five others in Northern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruling is the latest in a protracted legal
battle that has pitted the wishes of California voters and
advocates of medicinal marijuana against federal drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passage in 1996 of Proposition 215, the
voter-approved measure that allows marijuana to be provided for
medicinal use, enforcement of the initiative has been tangled up in
the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has not budged from its stand that
marijuana is an outlawed substance under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Laws similar to Proposition 215 have been passed in Alaska,
Arizona, Hawaii, Maine, Nevada, Oregon and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did medicinal marijuana clubs open for business than
then-state Attorney General Dan Lungren, joined by federal and
local law enforcement agencies, moved to shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Breyer ordered the shutdown of a number of pot
clubs, including those in San Francisco, Oakland and Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer's brother, Stephen Breyer, sits on the Supreme Court and
recused himself from the case Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Harriet Chiang contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
