<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES OVER COWBOYS? WE'LL FIND OUT SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dave Campo admitted Tuesday that he is ``nervous ...
excited ... scared of everybody'' just five days before his first
game as head coach at any level.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added that he could not have handpicked a better
opponent for his Dallas Cowboys to open the season against than
Philadelphia, at 3:05 p.m. Sunday at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles haven't had a winning season since 1996, but they've
become a sexier preseason pick than the Cowboys in some national
publications, and have been tabbed to make the playoffs for what
would be the first time in four years for long-suffering Philly
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Illustrated'' picked Philadelphia to finish second in
the NFC East behind Washington and predicted Dallas will finish
fourth in the division, ahead of only Arizona. (''SI'' has the
Washington Redskins, Eagles, New York Giants and Cowboys all making
the playoffs, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter who we play, but I think it is a
little bit of added incentive that some publications are picking
Philadelphia,'' Campo said before the annual Kickoff Luncheon and
Happy Hill Farm fund-raiser at the Intercontinental Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like (opening against the Eagles), personally,'' Campo
added. ``Starting out in your division adds a little significance
to what you do in preparation in training camp. Philadelphia is
probably just as excited about the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' first three games, over a span of 22 days, will be
played against divisional rivals Philadelphia, Arizona and
Washington. The latter two are night games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Facing divisional opponents early provides a ``barometer'' _
Campo's word _ for where the Cowboys are likely to fit into the NFC
East picture this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious the Eagles are a better football team than they
were a year ago,'' said Campo, citing the development of
second-year quarterback Donovan McNabb, the dogged running style of
Duce Staley and a revamped offensive line as just three reasons for
their improvement offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Eagles led the NFL last season with 46 takeways
(28 interceptions, 18 fumble recoveries).
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot have turnovers and win,'' Campo said. ``They're a
pressure defense. That's good for them and good for us. It's a good
news/bad news story. If you guess right, you make some big plays;
if you guess, you give up some big plays.
</P>
<P>
   If the Eagles ``blitz up the middle, and you happen to be
running an off-tackle play. ... I like Emmitt's chances of getting
the ball downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt is Emmitt Smith, who missed all five preseason losses
with two injuries, a toe sprain then a calf strain. The last time
Smith missed an entire preseason (1993), he rushed for 1,486 yards
in 13 starts and the Cowboys won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Campo couldn't say it clear enough: ``Emmitt is 100 percent.
He's ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither owner Jerry Jones nor Campo could be dragged into
making a prediction about where the Cowboys will finish in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the things that has hurt this team in the past
is maybe we worried too much about where we were going to end up,''
Campo said. ``Remember, we didn't win the division last year. The
Redskins won the division.''
</P>
<P>
   The preseason consensus among national publications is for
Washington to win the NFC East again. The debate is over the depth
of the division, and which team among the Cowboys, Eagles and
Giants will be second-best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the division is much improved. Every team made some
strides in the off-season,'' Campo said. ``The tougher the
division, the better chance that a team coming out of that division
has of going all the way. I'd rather have it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo waited 30 years to get to Sunday's game. He becomes a
first-time head coach when the scoreboard actually matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared of everybody ... whether it's their first string or
their second string ... because somebody has made a big play
somewhere to get here,'' said Campo. ``So, I'm nervous going into
this game; it's very simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The game is still four days away. But Campo already knows he'll
never forget it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
