<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LIEBERMAN-RELIGION-SF     08-30 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-RELIGION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN DEFENDS HIS MENTION OF RELIGION WHILE CAMPAIGNING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Refusing to bow to criticism from the
Anti-Defamation League that he has overemphasized religion in his
vice presidential campaign, Democrat Joseph Lieberman said Tuesday
that he will continue to discuss ``the constructive role that faith
has traditionally played in American life, and what it can play in
our future.''
<P>
   ``The ADL has a job to do, and I respect them. In this case, I
respectfully disagree,'' Lieberman said in an interview with The
Chronicle during a campaign stop in San Diego. ``Faith is a source
of unity, I believe, and it has also been a source of good works.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was quick to add that he is ``a fervent believer in
the First Amendment and the separation of church and state.'' But
the Connecticut senator added: ``I'm not talking about programs
here. I'm talking about a tone of respect _ for the place that
faith plays in people's lives and the lives of the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments by the first Orthodox Jew to be part of a
presidential ticket came in response to sharp criticism this week
from ADL director Abraham Foxman, who charged that Lieberman
appeared to be almost ``hawking religion'' in his most recent
campaign stops, in which he discussed the importance of religious
beliefs in American life.
</P>
<P>
   Foxman seemed to expand his criticism in comments to the Reuters
news service Tuesday, saying the message of both presidential
campaigns appears to be: ``Vote for me because I believe in God.''
</P>
<P>
   The mix of religion and politics threatened to overshadow
attempts in recent days by both Lieberman and Vice President Al
Gore to define differences between Democrats and Republicans on key
campaign issues like prescription drug benefits, health care and
helping working class families benefit from the ``new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has emphasized religion and morality throughout his
political career. He was one of the first Democrats to criticize
President Clinton over the Monica Lewinsky affair, and in the last
year, he has called for the Federal Communications Commission to
consider the content of TV programs when renewing broadcasters'
lucrative licenses.
</P>
<P>
   He has said that if it were up to him, such shows as ``Friends''
would be shown only in movie theaters or late at night so children
couldn't watch, and he once stated that Hollywood ``doesn't
understand piety.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Lieberman responded to comments by
screenwriter Joe Eszterhas, who took out a full page ad in
entertainment industry publications urging Hollywood to give ``not
a penny more'' to the Gore-Lieberman team until the senator could
``clarify`' his comments on the creative freedom of the
entertainment industry. Eszterhas, author of ``Basic Instinct'' and
``Showgirls'' is in the midst of a marketing campaign for his
latest book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever want to be at a point where government tells
Hollywood what movie to make as a matter of law,'' Lieberman said.
``Most of what we'd tried to do ... is to appeal to the industry to
draw its own line and acknowledge that we have a culture that's too
violent and too vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the violence and vulgarity in the movies is one of the
contributors to that,'' Lieberman said, adding, `I don't ever say
that it creates  &UR; all  &LR; the problems. It doesn't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With just two months to go before the general election,
Lieberman's first solo trip to California since the Democratic
National Convention provided a glimpse of the Democrats'
presidential strategy for securing victory in the nation's most
populous state.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman plunged into GOP strongholds in Southern California,
beginning the day with a spur-of-the-moment stop at an Anaheim
coffee shop, where he slid into booths with diners, asked about
their lives, then asked them: ``Anything you want to say about this
campaign?''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Lieberman received a rousing reception at a
speech to 2,500 members of the Communications Workers of America in
Anaheim, where he was repeatedly interrupted by standing ovations,
rhythmic applause and chants of ``Go, Joe, go!''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that focused on high-tech issues, Lieberman won
applause when he said that ``America cannot afford to have a
president in the 21st century who doesn't know the terrain of the
new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   And, outlining the differences between Democratic and Republican
tax plans, Lieberman argued, ``There's nothing wrong with being
rich. In America, we all want to be rich. But we shouldn't help
those who need it least at the expense of those who need it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at Children's Hospital in San Diego, Lieberman toured
oncology wards and held a round-table discussion with health
workers and parents of critically ill children to stress the
Gore-Lieberman health care proposals _ and what he charged is a
Republican lack of planning on health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has a role to play here,'' he told Sherri Buys,
a mother from El Cajon, after she described her family's health
care problems. ``Our opponents are good people. We never say
anything about them personally. ... But our opponents, as far as I
can tell, don't have any program to deal with health insurance for
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman himself, without ever specifically mentioning
religion, raised moral and cultural issues in his speech before the
CWA.
</P>
<P>
   Praising Al and Tipper Gore for leading what he called ``a
crusade about the moral future of America,'' Lieberman said, ``They
know that many Americans have a swelling sense that our standards
of decency and civility are being eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is too much violence and vulgarity in our culture, and
it's affecting our children and our safety,'' Lieberman said. The
Democratic ticket, he promised, will ``stand up and fight for
American families so you can give kids the values and faith that
you want to give them.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one voter who heard Lieberman speak Tuesday said the
candidate had earned himself points. ``I don't care what religion
you are,'' said Buys, a Mormon and mother of five. ``As long as you
have something to believe in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
