<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' AIKMAN POURS EFFORTS, FUNDS INTO HELPING CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDISON, Texas _ Although it was hard to tell, Brooke Elliott
was excited. Brooke, 10, had just met her hero, Troy Aikman. Aikman
shook her hand and asked her name, causing her to blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cool,'' said Brooke, a resident of Happy Hill Farm
Academy/Home.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was all dressed up with somewhere important to go Tuesday
on the Cowboys' first off day of the 2000 regular season. The Troy
Aikman Foundation was one of the sponsors for the Dallas Cowboys
Kickoff Luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   The annual event, which drew the entire Cowboys team to the
Hotel Intercontinental benefits The Courage House _ an abused
children's center _ located at Happy Hill Farm near Granbury.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could have been golfing, running errands or resting
on their only off day of the week. Instead, they gave of their
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a responsibility that we have,'' Aikman said. ``It's a
big part of what we do with the foundation. That takes up a
considerable amount of our time, but I think it's something that's
worthwhile, and it's making a difference. It's not so much about
what's fun. Even though it's enjoyable, it's about being given an
opportunity to make a difference and trying to take advantage of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical off day for Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   The Troy Aikman Foundation is busy building interactive
playrooms in children's hospitals across the country. Three ``End
Zones'' are open already, including one at Cook Children's Medical
Center in Fort Worth, and a similar project is opening soon at St.
Anthony's in Oklahoma City, where Aikman's sister, Tammy Powell, is
program director. Others are planned for Houston, Indianapolis and
the UCLA Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he formed the foundation, it was because he had done a
lot of charity work, golf tournaments and whatever, and even though
he knew a lot of money was raised, he never knew where it went,''
said Aikman's mother, Charlyn Aikman, who runs The Troy Aikman
Foundation. ``You never saw a face with where the money was going.
When he formed his foundation, it was with the idea that we would
help individual children one-on-one, but we were raising more money
than what people were applying for.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the board members had the idea of building an
interactive, high-tech playroom in a children's hospital, so the
children could go in there and have a place just to get away from
their rooms and do something interesting. We did the one in Dallas
and thought that would be it. Well, now we've got hospitals calling
us and saying, `Can we have one?' That is now 100 percent of our
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman shows up for the grand openings of his ``End Zones,'' and
then occasionally makes unannounced visits to spend time with the
hospitalized children. Tuesday, he spent his day with the children
of Happy Hill Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy's profile is very high,'' said Ed Shipman, the founder of
Happy Hill Farm. ``He has been very good to me. He came down to the
farm a couple of years ago and toured the campus with the kids.
They know Troy, and they know a lot of the Cowboys on a first-name
basis. In terms of role models, he's the kind of guy who is right
out there in front, and we're very grateful for that
relationship.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
