<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARSEATS-LAW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LAWMAKERS APPROVE STRICTER CAR SEAT MEASURE  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ In a move to reduce the number of children killed
or maimed in car crashes, lawmakers approved a bill Tuesday
requiring car safety seats or booster seats for kids younger than 6
years and lighter than 60 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the seats are required for children under age 4 or
less than 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at all uncommon for children over age 4 ... to slip
out of the belt, get thrown from the car and suffer severe brain or
spinal injuries,'' said state Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Hillsborough,
the bill's author. ``This bill is probably not as far as we should
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Speier's bill, the $100 fine for child seat violations
would rise to $250 for subsequent offenses. Violations also would
cost one point on a driver's record, which could lead to more
expensive auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration recommends
that all states require seats for children weighing between 40 and
80 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-one percent of deaths and 66 percent of injuries in car
accidents would be eliminated if children were properly restrained
in safety seats, booster seats or seatbelts, according to the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis is expected to sign the bill. Last year, he
objected to a tougher car safety bill carried by Speier.
</P>
<P>
   The new age and weight requirements would take effect January 1,
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Car accidents are the leading cause of death for California
children ages 5 through 7. In 1998, 697 children under age 6 died
in car crashes. Nearly 100,000 were injured, according to
government data.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, the state has required children younger than 4 or
less than 40 pounds to ride in car safety seats. Speier's bill,
although aimed at ensuring that larger children use booster seats,
is slightly different. It would exempt kids over 6 or over 60
pounds, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   Safety seats are designed for infants and small children and
have a protective case and their own seat belts. Booster seats
allow shoulder and lap seatbelts, which are designed to fit a
168-pound adult rider, to cross a child in the correct places _
over the chest and below the pelvis. Many child safety seats are
designed to convert to boosters as the child gets bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``As parents we all sort of thought its safe to put bigger kids
in adult seat belts. It's not,'' Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups including the American Pediatric Association
recommend booster seats be used until a child weighs 80 pounds and
is at least 4 feet 10 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   That would generally mean children under age 10 sit on boosters.
</P>
<P>
   Speier's bill initially required children up to age 7 to use
safety or booster seats but contained no weight limits.
</P>
<P>
   It would have made California the first state to have such a
law, she said. Since then, Washington has enacted a similar law.
</P>
<P>
   Davis objected to the lack of a weight ceiling in Speier's
original bill. Speier scaled back the measure to win his signature.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-member Senate sent the bill to Davis by a vote of 24 to
9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
