<HEADLINE>
EYES SEEM TO BELIE COWBOYS' VIEWPOINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who are you going to believe, me or your lying eyes?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question that comes to mind when assessing the Dallas
Cowboys' less-than-stellar preseason play, and then listening to
them go on about how good they're going to be this season.
</P>
<P>
   It makes one feel like a naive lover who catches his partner
with someone else, yet believes her when she says, ``It wasn't
me.'' You know what you saw, but you know what you want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   What you know is that quarterback Troy Aikman, he of the three
Super Bowl rings and superb accuracy, is in his favorite offense
again.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith, the third-ranked rusher in NFL history and owner
of four rushing titles to go along with three Super Bowl rings, is
still the running back.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers Joey Galloway and Raghib Ismail are the fastest combo
in the league, which in turn should mean the most explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Harris, a former All-Pro, is expected to be the best
inside target the Cowboys have had at tight end since Jay Novacek
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in extremely capable backups in quarterback Randall
Cunningham and running back Chris Warren, and more speed at
receiver in Jason Tucker, James McKnight and Wane McGarity, and
it's hard find a team other than the Super Bowl champion St. Louis
Rams with more weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, no team in the NFC East compares to the Cowboys'
offense, not even the favored Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   But let's consider a few other things:
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will be hard-pressed to be hitting on all cylinders
when the season opens, considering they are running a new offense.
Only Smith, Aikman, center Mark Stepnoski, guard Larry Allen and
tackle Erik Williams were around when they used the system from
1992-1997.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way the six other members of the offense will be as
comfortable against the Eagles on Sunday as they will be in
December, which is good considering that's the toughest part of the
Cowboys' schedule. Three of their final four games are against
Tampa Bay, Washington and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   However, it also means that the Cowboys need to get off to a
good start, so the season won't hinge on those final games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 6-19 on the road the past three years combined,
including a 1-12 mark against nondivision opponents. The Cowboys'
four nondivision road opponents _ Tennessee, Tampa Bay, Baltimore
and Carolina _ are playoff and Super Bowl contenders. Having talent
on paper is one thing, but the Cowboys must prove they have the
character to take care of business away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Campo promised that the Cowboys, who led the league
in penalties last season, would be more disciplined in 2000. While
winning exhibition games doesn't matter, you can assess a team's
ability to execute and eliminate mental miscues. The Cowboys didn't
show they've overcome their penalty problems in the preseason.
Sure, the Cowboys have weapons, but how do we know they won't shoot
themselves in the foot?
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the defense is considered the team's weak link. Most
experts say the Cowboys will have to outscore opponents to win,
citing the uncertainty in the secondary and their inability to rush
the passer and stop the run in the preseason. Signing former Giants
cornerback Phillippi Sparks helps the secondary, but Sparks is
weeks away from being in optimum shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys must prove there is life without middle linebacker
Randall Godfrey (Tennessee) against the run, and Deion Sanders
(Washington) in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Sanders was hurt for much of last season, but opponents
didn't target his side of the field on a regular basis. The Cowboys
like the combo of Sparks and Ryan McNeil at cornerback. Neither,
however, strikes fear in opposing quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what you saw in the preseason, Cowboys defensive
coordinator Mike Zimmer guarantees that they will be able to rush
the passer with defensive ends Greg Ellis and Ebenezer Ekuban and
tackles Leon Lett and Alonzo Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will get the passer unless we just grossly over-evaluated
our players,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis' 1999 performance, Lett's Pro Bowl past and Spellman's
dominance in practices gives credence to Zimmer's promises.
</P>
<P>
   But it smacks of an unfaithful lover saying ``trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who are you going to believe, your eyes or the Cowboys?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
