<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATUS OF LUCKY, SPARKS NEVER SEEMED THIS ELITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm wondering. Do you figure Mike Lucky ever knew he was this
important? And what about Phillippi Sparks? He had actually retired
from the game. As it turned out, Sparky undersold his ability by a
mere $2 million, maybe more.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Dallas Cowboys scurried around this week to fill
talent gaps (that's a tad worrisome, don't you think? Mere days
before the regular season opens, and the local team has to still
``scurry''?), the addition of a third-string tight end and a
nondescript journeyman cornerback caused jubilation at Valley
Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I read it in the paper, so it must be true. Jerry has gone
sleepless this week because of a continuing case of the giggles.
And Camps is wearing a smile wider than the grill on a '57
Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   All this joy resulted because of O.J. Santiago, a tight end no
longer wanted in Atlanta (speaking of worrisome _ the Falcons don't
want you?), and Mr. Sparks, a cornerback who told the Giants he was
retiring after last season and the Giants replying, ``What took you
so long?''
</P>
<P>
   But as a businessman, there is no doubting Phillippi. He turned
retirement into a financial bonanza, after he had spent the summer
turning down the Jerry Jones offer of a minimal NFL contract valued
at $444,000. Then cornerback desperation took over for the Cowboys,
once it became obvious that Kareem Larrimore wasn't yet prepared to
take over.
</P>
<P>
   Phillippi, the shrewd one, will pocket $2 million, bonus
included, for 2000, and can make another million if he's still
around next season. The Cowboys hope he won't be, but that depends.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the last time Jones paid out this kind of big dollars to
talk a guy out of retirement, he ended up with coach Gunsmoke.
Hopefully, that won't be a reflection on Phillippi.
</P>
<P>
   But while Sparks has earned All-Pro honors for business smarts
in the jock kingdom, his summer still pales in comparison with Mike
Lucky's. From almost total football obscurity, Lucky is now an NFL
legend. Yes, legend.
</P>
<P>
   When misfortune struck Lucky early in training camp, he ended up
on crutches with a blown-out knee, his second NFL season over and
done with. But to be harsh about it, the Cowboys' year didn't
exactly hinge on the absence of a third-string tight end. Or did
it?
</P>
<P>
   Seven tight ends came to Wichita Falls trying unsuccessfully to
replace Lucky. Seven of 'em. All released.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth turned up this week in Santiago, who does have some
proven NFL ability, and the Cowboys were thrilled to surrender a
fourth-round draft pick next year, and a seventh-rounder the year
after.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me this: What other player in NFL history went down with an
injury and it took eight guys to replace him? Like I said, Mike
Lucky, the legend.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, it was mentioned to a Cowboys' staffer how shocking it
was to only now realize the value of Lucky, while not realizing
what his July injury had meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to tell you,'' came the answer. And yes, they did.
But obviously, I didn't have the proper appreciation for
third-string tight ends, or an understanding yet of the Jack Reilly
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about intrigue. Forget Joey and Rocket, what the heck does
Reilly have planned for his three-headed tight end monster of
Harris-LaFleur-Santiago? We all wait in eager anticipation, which
is also the case for young Philadelphia quarterback Donovan McNabb,
except for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who provide the opening-game competition for the
Cowboys on Sunday at Texas Stadium, have installed a bombing-raid
kind of passing attack to fit the immense talents of McNabb. Don't
you know Donovan's game face had to light up Monday when he took a
film-look at the Cowboys' defensive misfortunes of the exhibition
season.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, of course, was hardly the lone problem, but as a
rookie corner, he became the focus. And with Sparks in questionable
physical condition, Kareem could still be seeing plenty of action
against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Snideness and jokes aside, the signing of Sparks was a
necessity. You might say Jones was forced to wisely buy 2 million
bucks worth of time for Larrimore to relax and not feel the
pressure. The kid seemed to be doing OK until two weeks ago in the
exhibition game at Denver. The Broncos chewed on him badly that
night and, as was feared, that experience appeared to spook Kareem.
His confidence suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore was basically handed the starting left corner spot
after fellow rookie Mario Edwards was injured. So, of course, was
the second-round rookie pick, Dwayne Goodrich, but Goodrich's
injury came after he had fallen far behind the other rooks in the
immediate cornerback pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   Do not buy into Valley Ranch current excuses that Larrimore was
only listed No. 1 because of the pending retirement of Kevin Smith.
It was known after the Valley Ranch minicamps in June that Kevin's
on-going physical problems were beyond repair. Actually, Charlie
Williams was the probable stop-gap solution at left corner, until
the rookies matured, but he also has been shut down with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys were banking on Larrimore being the immediate
answer, and if not him, Edwards. That's why Sparks stayed on hold
until now. But it's not a disgrace for Larrimore to need seasoning.
This is normal for most corners. Even Kevin Smith, as great as he
once was, didn't start until the 11th game of his rookie season.
Old-time fans will remember Ike Holt, ordinary at best, holding the
job until Kevin was declared ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Valley Ranch glowed this week with the smiles of Jerry and Dave
Campo. The rest of us start finding out on Sunday just how
permanent those smiles will be.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
