<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5987 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-COPPER-RIVER-SFCHRON &LR;      08-30 2638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPPER-RIVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BATTLE LINES DRAWN IN LAST ALASKAN WILDERNESS  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE COPPER RIVER, South Central Alaska _ Brown bears are not
seen particularly often in this region, but they are omnipresent _
both in the bush and inside your head.
</P>
<P>
   They leave their tracks along the beach at every camp, sometimes
right by your tent. They are the sovereigns of this green and rainy
realm; you are the vulnerable interloper.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these 1,500-pound predators are not particularly interested
in the few rafters who manage to negotiate the Copper River's
serpentine length to its delta on Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   At this time of year, the bruins are here for the salmon _ for
the 400,000 sockeyes, 50,000 kings and 50,000 coho that dodge the
offshore commercial fleet and swim up the Copper's turbid waters to
spawn in its hundreds of clear tributary creeks.
</P>
<P>
   Stay out of the bears' right of way, don't surprise them in the
bush, avoid getting between a sow and her cubs and you'll be OK.
Usually.
</P>
<P>
   The bears and the salmon are firm evidence of the Copper's wild,
even primeval, state. By any measure, this is one of the last great
wilderness complexes left in the world. The 350-mile river drains
an area the size of West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But the 21st century is encroaching on the river, engendering a
fierce conflict in the process.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is the Eyak Corp., a consortium of Alaskan Native
Americans that claims its tribal members need dividends from
resource-extraction projects to prosper. The corporation wants to
develop the region, to open it to logging, road building and
mining.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the fight against the consortium are Dune Lankard and
Pamela Smith, traditionalist brother-and-sister Eyaks who say
development of the river's delta would doom both its rich fisheries
and native culture. Lankard and Smith have recently been joined in
their fight by Julia Butterfly Hill, the California activist who
spent two years in a Humboldt County redwood tree to protest
logging plans by the Pacific Lumber Co.
</P>
<P>
   Their confederation points to something even larger than the
issues swirling around the Copper: A growing association of
environmentalists and traditionalist natives who hope to combine
their individual skirmishes into a coordinated effort to restore
the once-contiguous coastal rain forest that stretched from Big Sur
to Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska has been much tamed in recent decades, but the mighty
Copper River and its main tributaries and branches _ the Chitina,
the Tazlina, the Bremner _ are still remote, unpeopled and wholly
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Though the river _ named for a rich copper ore body in its upper
reaches _ is relatively short, it transports a huge amount of water
due to runoff from the great glaciers that crowd its innumerable
tributary valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The only sign of human activity during a typical eight-day raft
trip is the occasional bush plane. No people live here, though a
derelict cabin can sometimes be discerned through the thick scrub
of alders and cottonwoods.
</P>
<P>
   But the wildlife is extravagantly abundant. Bald eagles seem as
common as crows, perching on snags as they scan the shallows for
fish. Moose browse in the willow thickets, and mountain goats
forage on the crags that loom over the river.
</P>
<P>
   The sandbars are thick with tracks: not just brown bear, but
black bear, wolf, coyote, lynx, wolverine, marten and river otter.
</P>
<P>
   The Copper's 750,000-acre delta constitutes the biggest wetland
on the Pacific North American coast, a vast maze of tidal flats,
sloughs and channels that supports millions of shorebirds and
waterfowl.
</P>
<P>
   Copper River king and sockeye salmon are reckoned the best in
the world by many top chefs, and the season's first commercial
catches bring rarefied prices in Seattle and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the transcendent biological richness of the Copper River
system hangs in a delicate balance _ one, say its advocates, that
could be catastrophically upset by the developments now planned.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among these is a road that would traverse the delta to
a huge coal deposit, incidentally opening vast portions of country
to logging, mining and recreational development.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other threats: another proposed road east of the
river to a body of gold ore, and a planned 60-mile biking and
hiking path along the Copper from a trailhead south of the river
hamlet of Chitina to the fishing town of Cordova. Critics maintain
that the trail is simply a precursor to a full-fledged state
highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more access, the fewer fish, the less wildlife,'' said
Lankard, an Eyak/Aleut native and commercial fisherman who helped
lead a recent raft trip down the Copper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system may look infinitely rich, but in reality it's
limited and very sensitive,'' said Lankard. ``The salmon run is
already reduced from what it was several years ago. We have more
subsistence dip netters (anglers fishing for home use) each year.
There's a jet boat working the lower river. It all adds up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lankard is trying to impose a vastly ambitious vision on the
river and the delta, one that is without precedent: A cultural
easement.
</P>
<P>
   Like the commonly employed conservation easement, it would
protect natural resources by paying landowners to relinquish
development rights.
</P>
<P>
   But Lankard's plan goes a step further: It would formally
empower the Eyaks _ who have inhabited the Copper River region for
about 3,500 years _ as part of the conservation plan, allowing them
subsistence hunting, fishing and gathering rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Eyaks, said Lankard, are as much a part of the Copper River
ecosystem as the bears and the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming through the Copper's gorges and delta, fishing for kings
and sockeyes, hunting the seals that swim 80 miles upriver in
pursuit of the salmon, picking the abundant berries, mushrooms and
fiddlehads _ these are all activities integral to Eyak culture,
Lankard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Eyak tradition, people, fish and wildlife are all fellow
beings inhabiting the same sacred place,'' said Lankard. ``The
river and delta are our mother _ and you don't sell mom.''
</P>
<P>
   The salmon is an especially sacred emblem for the Eyak,
pervading diet, social life and religion. When Lankard fishes the
dangerous waters off the delta, he always prays to &UR; Wilghtnee, &LR;  the
Eyak salmon goddess.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she's always brought me home safely,'' he said, `'though
once I had to change a starter when my boat was drifting (without
engines) into the breakers, and another time I had to be airlifted
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lankard wants to use federal conservation funds to establish an
easement on the Copper River system, preserving its fisheries,
wildlife and forests in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   He also favors buying out the development rights from native
corporations and private investors for the coalfields east of the
delta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner of the fields has indicated he'd be willing to
establish an easement for $10 (million) to $15 million,'' Lankard
said. ``He knows development will involve a lot of delay and
expensive litigation, and he seems agreeable to a smaller profit in
the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Lankard is finding some powerful allies in the environmental
community. The National Wildlife Federation, the Wilderness
Society, the Sierra Club and the Audubon Society have all joined
his cause, as has the tree-sitting activist Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hill accompanied Lankard on his recent trip down the Copper. She
acknowledged her support for native subsistence hunting and fishing
rights may draw fire from some environmental and animal-rights
advocates who have supported her in the past, but she was
unperturbed by the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always gone with my heart, not by what's popular,'' she
said. ``Fishing and hunting for food is basic to Eyak culture. The
Eyaks have a profound respect for the fish and wildlife they take,
and they consume it reverently. I have a far greater problem with
factory farming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill is also joining forces with Lankard and other coastal
activists to promote the idea of protecting the Pacific rain forest
as one entity, a single forest that runs from Big Sur to south
central Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are redwoods in the south and spruce in the north, but
it was originally one forest, and it should be restored as one
forest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lankard is also facing formidable resistance _ including
from many of his 325 fellow shareholders in the Eyak Corp., which
controls about 100,000 acres of forestland around the river and
Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   After oil was discovered on Alaska's North Slope in the late
1960s, federal legislation was passed that deeded vast amounts of
land to state tribal corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal members thus became shareholders in their corporations _
and dividends depended on the exploitation of tribal lands through
logging, mining and development.
</P>
<P>
   Lankard believes such development undermines the very essence of
being native. And besides, he said, the tribal corporations have
been abysmally inept at providing fat dividends through the
liquidation of natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   The Eyak Corp. was founded in 1971. By 2002, it will have paid a
total of $102,000 to each shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   More money can be made for the Eyaks, Lankard believes, by
selling conservation easements for tribal forests and by promoting
environmentally sound activities such as regulated commercial
fishing and ecotourism.
</P>
<P>
   Lankard points to some success in this regard. He worked long
and hard to stop logging on 3,000 tribal acres near Cordova on
Nelson Bay, and the corporation ultimately negotiated a $3.6
million easement deal with a trustee council formed to disburse
settlement money after the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the corporation sold easements on an additional
77,000 acres to the federal government for $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   But while those actions have basically put the tribe out of the
logging business, Eyak Corp. managers still view some resource
development as essential to the well-being of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support all forms of resource development, but I do
believe in balance,'' said Brian Lettich, general manager for the
Eyak Corp. ``I don't think we should lock everything up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lettich said fishing and tourism are not enough to support
Cordova, where most of the region's residents _ including Eyaks _
live.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fishing has been fairly bad in recent years, and even when
it's good a lot of the money leaves town each winter because
fishermen are transient _ they live in Anchorage, Seattle or
Bellingham,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lettich says only the development of natural resources can
support and improve the region's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been that way up here,'' he said. ``Resource
development pays taxes for roads, water systems, sewers and city
services. If it wasn't for the roads and airstrips that exist in
Cordova and Chitina, Dune and his folks couldn't raft the Copper.
They wouldn't have access.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Lettich supports the proposed road to the
coalfields east of the delta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eyak Corp. wouldn't benefit from the road that much _ most
of the land is controlled by the Chugach (native) Corp.,'' said
Lettich. ``But it would really improve Cordova's economic base.''
</P>
<P>
   That position rankles David Grimes, who was also on the recent
raft trip down the Copper with Lankard.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes, a commercial fisherman, raft guide and co-founder of the
Coastal Coalition, which was formed after the Exxon Valdez oil
spill to lobby for the protection of Prince William Sound and its
surrounding forests, said the last thing the Copper needs is more
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already developed,'' he said. ``We have the finest
biological development in the world, and we already have a superb
access corridor _ the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes is particularly concerned about the proposed bike trail
down the Copper, a project enthusiastically supported by Alaska
Gov. Tony Knowles.
</P>
<P>
   He explained his fears as he adroitly rowed around and through
the Copper's heaving boils, whirlpools and eddy lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's promoted as a bike path, but it will be built with heavy
equipment and helicopters,'' Grimes said. ``It will involve
spanning dozens of creeks, rivers and gorges with trestles, it will
allow passage for three-wheel all-terrain vehicles, and it will
cost tens of millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes pointed to a sign that had been recently tacked to a
shoreline cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That marks an access easement through native lands to U.S.
Forest Service lands and the Richardson Highway,'' he said. ``What
you basically have here is (a stalking horse) for a river highway.
The ultimate goal is a road.''
</P>
<P>
   At Abercrombie Rapids, the Copper _ which in some places is a
mile wide _ narrows to about 250 yards. Brown bears congregate here
to catch salmon, and harbor seals ply the surge of the main
channel, having followed the fish up from the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes rowed hard for the north bank at the rapids, beaching the
raft on a small sandbar. The group cautiously disembarked.
</P>
<P>
   Bear scat and prints were everywhere. Across the river, five
brown bears _ including a sow and two cubs _ paced the banks,
gazing hungrily into the silty water.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly, a bear walked out of the alders and intensely regarded
the group from a distance of 75 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avoid eye contact and walk slowly back to the raft,'' Grimes
said. As the group inched backward, the bear ambled back to the
river for more fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state wants to build a bear-viewing platform here,'' said
Grimes as he rowed out of the eddy to the main current. ``You don't
think that will change the character of this place? The bears will
be constantly distracted from their fishing by hikers and mountain
bikers, and sooner or later you'll have (an attack). Then what?''
</P>
<P>
   Like Hill and Lankard, Grimes supports the idea of conserving
the Pacific rain forest as a single ecosystem. He said the key to
restoring and protecting it is to make sure wild salmon have the
conditions they need to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the forests from Alaska to California originally supported
wild salmon,'' he said. ``Salmon are basically forest creatures, so
if the runs are healthy, the forests are healthy. That means the
watersheds are stable, you have good cover from old-growth trees,
you have good biodiversity. Wild salmon are the prime indicators
for forest health along the Pacific Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   To Smith, Lankard's sister, the Copper River system and the
creatures that inhabit it are essential for resuscitating Eyak
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a member of a group of Eyak traditionalists that is
trying to preserve tribal identity _ partly through lobbying to
establish conservation easements on Eyak lands, partly through the
revival of local ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   She was instrumental in organizing the first potlatch _ a
traditional gathering focused on feasting and gift-giving _ to be
hosted by the Eyaks in almost a century.
</P>
<P>
   At a proper potlatch, the Eyaks believe, everyone and everything
shows up _ not just human guests, but the spirits of ancestors and
wildlife, and the very essence of the natural elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held it at midsummer, when we figured the weather would be
best,'' Smith recalled. ``But the worst summer storm in years hit
as it got under way.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrants moved into a large warehouse, said Smith. There
was no power, it was cold and dark, and the storm raged outside
with unrestrained ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had the people, our food and the (ceremonial) drums,''
she said. ``So I apologized about the weather to one of the elders
who was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's voice caught at the memory, and she paused before
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Don't you understand? You invited everyone _ and
they  &UR; all  &LR; came.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
