<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-INDIANS-T     08-30 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS OWNER SAYS HE WILL INCREASE PAYROLL TO HELP CLUB WIN IN
2001
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers owner Tom Hicks said Tuesday he
is ready to do what it takes this off-season to get his struggling
baseball team turned around. Hicks said that includes increasing
the Rangers' $68 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to spend money just for the sake of spending
money,'' Hicks said. ``But we're going to spend money to get the
right player or players to help our ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, speaking Tuesday before the Rangers' 12-1 loss to the
Cleveland Indians at The Ballpark, said he doesn't know exactly how
much the payroll will increase. He said it will depend on who the
Rangers can acquire, either by trade or through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing magic,'' Hicks said. ``We'll take it position by
position and pitcher by pitcher. We'll spend what we need to
spend.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks was at The Ballpark on Tuesday night to help honor former
club president Tom Schieffer. He'll be back again Wednesday for his
monthly meeting with general manager Doug Melvin and manager Johnny
Oates. They have much to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated like everybody else,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said he does not see next year as being a choice between
staying with younger players or spending a lot of money on veteran
players to fill the many holes on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about following the White Sox's model,'' Hicks
said. ``I don't see us following the White Sox's model, the
Yankees' model or the Orioles' model. Well, I know we're not going
to be like the Orioles. We're going to continue to follow the
Rangers' model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with Doug Melvin's philosophy. You need to have a
strong core of good players, some young players pushing them from
below and then you add through free agency what you need to round
out the team. We've got good young players and we've got the
flexibility to add free agents. It doesn't have to be one way or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   It has to be some way or his manager may go nuts, if he hasn't
already. He watched the Cleveland Indians pummel starter Ryan Glynn
for five runs in five innings, add five more off reliever Francisco
Cordero and cruise the rest of the way behind starter Steve
Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he spent most of the game on the bench thinking and,
``I'm totally wiped out between the ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Oates: What do I think? How do I act?' Everyone is
frustrated, discouraged. We're all soul-searching and spellbound.
In 33 years, I've never experienced anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn was making his first start since fainting in the dugout
Aug. 11, and Oates said: ``I think he was trying to overthrow a
little bit. Stuff-wise he had good stuff, but he didn't locate it
very well. He got a little hyper, which is understandable since
it's been a while since he's been out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Glynn will be fine. He said his team will be fine. He
just doesn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballclub won't lose every game the rest of the season,
even though it looks that way,'' Oates said. ``We'll get it turned
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is determined that it will happen next year. He also
remains determined that Oates will be there to see it happen. Hicks
repeated again Tuesday that Melvin and Oates won't be held
responsible for the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team won three division titles in the past five years,''
Hicks said. ``We're going to go through this project together. If I
ever lose confidence in them, it will be for reasons that haven't
happened yet.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
