<HEADER>
A5989 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     08-30 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORA GETS THE DODGERS THINKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Alex Cora has proven to the Dodgers he can be
effective at the plate along with providing stellar defense, and in
the process it should refocus the Dodgers' offseason efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez is the marquee free agent in the upcoming class,
but the Dodgers won't be ultra-active in courting him because of
Cora's play at shortstop this season and the Dodgers' need to
upgrade its starting pitching, baseball sources said.
</P>
<P>
   As late as May, the Dodgers had questions about whether Cora
could handle himself at the plate. He had batted .143 with three
RBI in parts of 1998 and 1999, and the memory of him getting
overpowered against San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman in '98 has
faded.
</P>
<P>
   Cora's played well defensively, and though he's been streaky
offensively, he's handled the bat well. Cora went 2 for 4 Tuesday
against Milwaukee and is batting .265 with three homers and 23 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said Cora's established
himself as an everyday major-league shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident with him,'' Malone said. ``I think he's a
potential Gold Glove defender. He's definitely shown he can handle
himself offensively. I'm excited about his future. I think he's a
winning player. He does a lot of things to help you win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers won't turn a deaf ear when it comes to Rodriguez,
but they no longer believe they have to make an all-out run to
acquire him because of Cora's development, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   GOIN' WITH FIVE: If the Dodgers get back in the playoff race and
make a run during the last few weeks of the season, they'll go down
the stretch with a five-man rotation. Because of Darren Dreifort's
right arm troubles, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he wouldn't
go to a four-man rotation late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen,'' Johnson said. ``That won't happen.
He usually has a hard time throwing on the second day (after a
start).''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has used discretion and given Dreifort an extra day or
two to rest whenever possible. That was again the plan this time
through the rotation until lefty Carlos Perez pitched in relief
Sunday. Therefore, Dreifort, who's 10-7 with a 4.48 ERA, was moved
to today. It marks the 14th time in 26 starts he's pitched on a
``normal'' four days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break, Dreifort's started four times on four
days' rest. He's 3-0 with a 2.74 ERA in those starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some time you have to go to the whip,'' Malone said. ``I
personally don't feel it's an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   COURT TALK: It's unlikely any of the 21 members of the Dodgers
organization subpoenaed will actually have to appear in court, said
Mike Abernathy, the Chicago-based lawyer representing the Dodgers
in the criminal proceedings stemming from the May 16 brawl at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think 19 Dodgers or 21 Dodgers are going to be
traipsing into the courtroom for this,'' Abernathy said. ``This is
a misdemeanor, and videotapes are usually enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Abernathy said defense lawyers were denied access to Major
League Baseball's files on the incident pertaining to the Dodgers
and Chicago Cubs. The hearings were for the disorderly conduct
cases against James Maness and Ronald Camacho. The trial won't be
until November, Abernathy said.
</P>
<P>
   The disorderly conduct case of George Carlin is set for Sept.
18, but Abernathy said he would file motions to strike the
subpoenas to a group that includes manager Davey Johnson and
general manager Kevin Malone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
