<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK TOSSES ONE-HITTER IN DODGERS' WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ If a borderline 3-1 pitch in the sixth inning wasn't
called a strike, Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park may have been
celebrating more than just an overpowering outing.
</P>
<P>
   Park, along with his teammates, could have celebrated a
no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, James Mouton homered on the next pitch for Milwaukee's
only hit as Park struck out a career-high 14 in a 7-2 victory that
was the most commanding performance of his career Tuesday at County
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Mouton's homer end Park's no-hit bid at 52/3
innings, but the Brewers didn't come close to another hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can say,'' Brewers hitting coach Rod Carew
said. ``He just dominated us. That's the best I've ever seen him
throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek tied a career high with four
RBI on three hits, but he was certainly overshadowed. Park (14-8)
walked three and hit a batter, but the first Milwaukee runner to
reach base came after first baseman Eric Karros' fielding error
with one out in the fourth inning. Mouton's homer came after a
two-out walk to pinch hitter Mark Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was a no-hitter,'' said Park, who has won 21
of his last 30 decisions. ``After the home run, I was mad about
(it) because it was a ball. After that, I was looking at the people
get excited and I checked the scoreboard and it was one hit. That's
how I knew, and I said, `OK, forget about everything.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (70-62) have won eight of their last nine and have
tied a season high by going eight games over .500 for the fourth
time.
</P>
<P>
   However, the most amazing part of going 8-1 without left fielder
Gary Sheffield (he remains in Los Angeles with a viral infection)
is the ground the Dodgers have made up. They were nine games behind
first-place San Francisco in the National League West after losing
to Montreal last Monday, but after this road win _ their NL-leading
38th _ the Dodgers are five games behind the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spring training, they told me (Park) was uncomfortable
throwing certain pitches in certain counts, and I said that was
going to change,'' Dodgers catcher Chad Kreuter said. ``I want him
to be able to throw any pitch at any time, and to be successful in
the big leagues you need to have that confidence. That has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Park (14-8) is one win shy of tying his career high of 15, which
he established in 1997, but he's throwing as well now as he has at
any juncture of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Brewers, just like he's done for the past two
months, he's mixed his slider, curve, changeup and fastball. But
the key has been his ability to throw any pitch during any count
for quality strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Park has allowed two earned runs or less in his last seven
starts, and he hasn't allowed more than three earned runs since
July 4. He's also won his last three starts and had a career-high
string of 20 scoreless innings snapped on the Mouton homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You (saw) him change the hitter's eyesight so many times,''
pitching coach Claude Osteen said. ``He's got the hard breaking
stuff down, the changeup is down and now, boom, here's a 95 mph
fastball letter high. That's going to get a lot of people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's 14 strikeouts, the last of which came against Mark
Loretta to end the eighth, was the most by a Dodgers pitcher since
Hideo Nomo struck out 17 Florida Marlins on April 13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for this last year, and I've seen it now on a
regular basis,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He's
focused, relaxed, making a lot of quality pitches. He still fools
around a little bit, throwing a couple flop curves up there, maybe
trying to get an easy out. But when he got serious he got 'em. All
his pitches are sharp and crisp and he's not overthrowing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
