u f BC-CNN-CHANGES-1STLD-WRI     08-30 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-CHANGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NEWS CHIEF AT CNN EXPECTED TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite and expand by 250 words.)  
 By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Kaplan, who has been the president of CNN's U.S.
news-gathering operation since 1997, is expected to announce
Wednesday that he is leaving the network, executives close to the
situation said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives are also planning to announce a major
reorganization of its management, reflecting dissatisfaction with
the channel's inability to turn around its weak ratings in the
absence of breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's resignation comes at a particularly difficult time for
CNN, a unit of Time Warner Inc., leaving its leadership unclear
during a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's ratings have been sliding precipitously recently, and its
parent company is about to complete its merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   News of Kaplan's departure began circulating through CNN late
Tuesday afternoon and took many on his staff by surprise. There
were conflicting reports as to whether he was leaving on his own
accord or had been asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   But CNN executives made it clear Tuesday night that although
they regarded Kaplan as a talented producer, they had been unhappy
with his management of budgets and his occasionally explosive
temper.
</P>
<P>
   His duties will be divided among a number of executives. Tom
Johnson, the chairman of CNN, will continue in his position, with
Eason Jordan, formerly of CNN International, taking over as the
chief news executive. Phil Kent of Turner Broadcasting
International will become the chief operating officer. Jim Walton,
the president of the sports division, will head the network group
for the United States. Chris Cramer, a former BBC news executive,
will take over the international group.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are being instituted by Terence F. McGuirk, the
chief executive of the Turner Broadcasting System and a longtime
and trusted lieutenant to Ted Turner, the founder of CNN. Amid
lagging CNN ratings, McGuirk, aided by Steven Heyer, the president
of TBS and former head of Booz Allen's media group, had instituted
a sweeping evaluation of the network. They are devising a plan to
start a major marketing and advertising campaign to try to counter
its lagging ratings, which have fallen during slow news days, and
because of additional competition from networks like the Fox News
Channel and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Executives Tuesday night did not offer details of their
findings. Kaplan did not return phone calls. McGuirk, who is also
close to Johnson, was said to be unhappy with what one executive
called ``Mr. Kaplan's my-way-or-the highway approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, his tenure at the network has been rocky.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan joined CNN after a 17-year career as a producer at ABC
News, where he won 34 Emmy Awards serving as executive producer of
that network's leading news programs, ``Nightline'' and ``World
News Tonight.'' He also became the first executive producer of the
ABC news magazine program ``Prime Time Live.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his hiring, CNN executives had said they expected
Kaplan to help them combat their traditional lull in ratings during
slow news cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences tune to CNN when important news breaks but do not
commit to a regular schedule of programs. When Kaplan took over
CNN, he promised an antidote to that problem, instituting what
executives called ``appointment viewing'' _ network-news-style
programming that people would watch regularly.
</P>
<P>
   But his time at CNN had been marked by a series of
confrontations over news and personnel decisions. The main program
that Kaplan created, ``CNN NewsStand,'' was embroiled in a fiasco
in 1998 when its very first program, called ``Tailwind,'' a report
contending that U.S. forces had used nerve gas in Vietnam, was
found to be full of errors and had to be retracted, complete with
an on-the-air apology. Two producers were fired, and one executive
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's job was considered in jeopardy at the time, but he was
absolved of the final responsibility for the broadcast by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the highly popular Lou Dobbs, the anchor of the
network's most profitable program, ``Moneyline,'' quit after
fighting with Kaplan over news coverage that interrupted Dobbs'
program. ``Moneyline'' has since dropped in both ratings and
profits, and Dobbs has been publicly wooed by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last year, CNN's founder, Turner, expressed
interest in bringing Dobbs back to CNN, a move that Kaplan strongly
opposed. Dobbs did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Many at CNN had expected that Kaplan would leave the network
after the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that he was offered various other
opportunities with Turner Broadcasting, but that he declined them.
His departure will be effective at once.
</P>
<P>
   The executives believe they are in good hands with the new team
of Jordan and Kent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eason Jordan may be the strongest young television executive
in the world,'' one senior Turner executive said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
