u a BC-PERU-BERENSON-PARENTS     08-30 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-BERENSON-PARENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PRISONER'S PARENTS, A POLITICAL EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wheeling a suitcase behind them, Rhoda and Mark L.
Berenson looked like any retired couple off for a vacation as they
waited in an American Airlines ticket line at La Guardia Airport
Tuesday afternoon. But the man in front of them in line knew
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they going to release your daughter?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Although she had appeared on every news report the night before,
Mrs. Berenson was startled. ``We're so known,'' she murmured.
</P>
<P>
   But then she realized that the man was not exactly a stranger.
He was Brad Blakeman, a lawyer who works for the George W. Bush
campaign and is one of the many critical contacts she and her
husband have made over their four years of writing letters,
visiting lawmakers and talking to anyone who would listen about the
plight of their daughter, Lori Helene Berenson, 30.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, Ms. Berenson, 30, was convicted by a masked
military tribunal of conspiring to attack the Peruvian Congress,
and she has been imprisoned high in the Peruvian mountains on a
life sentence ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Berenson, a lifelong Democrat, started in on Blakeman,
rattling off the names of Republicans who support his efforts to
free his daughter. After the encounter, Mr. Berenson said, ``We
desperately need a way to get to George W.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been just over 24 hours since the U.S. Embassy had called
to tell the Berensons that their daughter was to be given a new
civil trial. Since then, Mr. Berenson said, they had answered 100
e-mail messages, held a news conference outside their apartment
near Gramercy Park, planned another news conference with Jesse
Jackson, and packed their bags for Tuesday's flight to Chicago to
appear on Oprah Winfrey's television show. The show's segment,
``The Fight of Your Life,'' had been scheduled before the big news.
</P>
<P>
   Since their daughter's arrest, the Berensons have gone from
professors to crusaders. They retired from their jobs _ he taught
statistics and she taught physics, both at the college level _ to
devote themselves, and a considerable amount of cash, to the
Committee to Free Lori Berenson. And they have steadfastly
maintained her innocence, despite skepticism from U.S. officials
and some human rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   They have learned to talk Peruvian politics, and they have
learned that letters to their daughter, which have to be in Spanish
so the censors can read them, should say ``translated by a
computer'' at the top in case there is some incendiary mistake.
They have learned where to buy knitting yarn in Arequipa, where
they stay when they go to Peru to visit their daughter, taking
turns every few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Their experience has taught them, too, that the announcement of
a new trial may not be the breakthrough many have taken it to be.
The Berensons have welcomed the news, but cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   They have already had their hopes raised and dashed countless
times, said Mrs. Berenson, 57. There was the time in June 1998 when
Peru's new prime minister said Ms. Berenson should be pardoned and
sent home, only to be immediately contradicted by the country's
real power, President Alberto K. Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was December 1998, when the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary
Movement, a guerrilla group, took over the residence of Japan's
ambassador to Peru. The incident seemed so similar to the one Ms.
Berenson had been accused of devising with the same group that it
jeopardized attempts to secure her a new trial. More recently,
prison guards said Ms. Berenson was drawing an escape plan, but it
was actually just a knitting diagram for a cat pattern that her
mother admired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to be an individual human being depending
on a large government for your life, because they're just not
geared to focus on individuals,'' Mrs. Berenson said. ``It's like
what that one congressman said: Lori is like a little shrimp caught
between two giant whales.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman James Talent, a Republican from Missouri,'' Mr.
Berenson supplied.
</P>
<P>
   The Berensons would much rather talk about their daughter than
their own work to free her. That, they say with a shrug, is just
what any parents would do. Indeed, they often seem to be nothing
more than regular parents.
</P>
<P>
   But events have cast them into the unexpected. Mrs. Berenson is
now an expert on prisons, and Mr. Berenson, 58, wants to continue
working for human rights. ``I have the idea that Lori will be
working with me,'' he said. Then, he was back to sounding like a
normal parent: ``Of course, no one wants to work with their father
all of the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
