<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ ONE-HITS DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ In a Red Sox spectacle for the ages,
Pedro Martinez Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night lost a no-hitter to the first batter
in the ninth inning but won an extraordinary showdown marked by a
bench-clearing melee, the ejection of eight Devil Rays, and a Carl
Everett slugging explosion.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre evening ended with an 8-0 Red Sox victory and two
Boston players in the hospital: third baseman Lou Merloni for
overnight observation after a concussion, and first baseman Brian
Daubach for X-rays on his left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Both were injured in a brawl that erupted after Martinez hit the
first batter he faced, Gerald Williams, on the left hand, prompting
Williams to charge the mound and whack Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other Tampa Bay batter reached base. And that was 24
outs later, on the fifth pitch of the ninth inning, a
95-mile-an-hour fastball that former Sox catcher John Flaherty
drove to right-center for a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted the no-hitter so bad for Pedro that I wished I had a
long, rubber arm that could have reached out and grabbed it,'' said
Everett, who hit two homers, a triple, and a double, driving in six
runs.
</P>
<P>
   But Flaherty's hit dropped for a clean single, and Martinez
gracefully accepted the outcome. He has yet to pitch a no-hitter,
though he pitched nine perfect innings for Montreal in 1995, only
to give up a hit in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed at all,'' said Martinez. ``I have
achieved enough excitement in my career. A no-hitter is not what is
going to dictate what kind of pitcher I am. I think my career is
more interesting than just one game.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was as unforgettable as any. A game that began with a
crowd of 17,450 jeering Martinez for hitting Williams ended with
virtually every patron cheering every pitch as Martinez approached
the first Boston no-hitter since Dave Morehead's in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The brawl broke out when Martinez plunked Williams on a 1-and-2
count. Williams paused for a moment as if to assess his injury,
then raced toward Martinez as both benches and bullpens cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised,'' Martinez said. ``I had no intention
whatsoever of hitting him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has 27 walks and 14 hit batsmen,'' said manager Larry
Rothschild. ``I gotta wonder about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez leads the league in hit batsmen _ three ahead of
Detroit's Jeff Weaver and Tampa Bay's Esteban Yan _ and he is
perennially among the major league leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez stood his ground with his hands down, Williams
shoved him, swung wildly, and hit him in the arm. When Martinez
swung back, Merloni tackled Williams and settled at the bottom of a
pile as more than a dozen players flung themselves into the fray.
Catcher Jason Varitek also landed on top of Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was down there, too,
</P>
<P>
   ``I escaped all right,'' he said. ``Gerald seemed to be
complaining a lot and crying for people to get them off him. He was
scared down there; I wasn't. He was crying a lot, saying, `Just get
them off me, get them off me.' If you're going to charge the mound,
you better be responsible for the things that happened down
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni stayed in the game until the third inning, when Manny
Alexander hit for him. He suffered worsening headaches as the night
went on, manager Jimy Williams said, and he was taken to nearby
Bayfront Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams was ejected for charging the mound, and
Rothschild was tossed while arguing Martinez should also have gone.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach was also among the first to reach the melee. And
something he did in the scrum not only injured his left elbow but
earned him the wrath of the Devil Rays. A group of them pulled him
out and screamed at him, and as Daubach tried to walk away,
clutching his elbow in pain, Tampa Bay's 6-foot-4-inch, 250-pound
closer Roberto Hernandez gave him a hard, two-handed shove in the
back.
</P>
<P>
   As if that were not enough, Tampa Bay then waged a bizarre war
for much of the game against Daubach: Three pitchers were tossed
for hitting him or throwing at him. Two coaches, acting as interim
managers, were ejected along with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly had an invisible bull's-eye on his back,'' Jimy
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild said the Rays believed Daubach was throwing ``cheap
shots'' in the pile.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, asked what Daubach might have done to incite Tampa's
wrath, said, ``I think Gerald, by charging the mound, got hit a
little, because he was bleeding. But if I saw something, I'm going
to keep it inside of me. I'm not going to tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when the number of Devil Rays ejected (eight)
exceeded the number of balls they hit out of the infield (six).
</P>
<P>
   Other than Flaherty's hit, only one other ball threatened to
drop. Left fielder Troy O'Leary made a leaping catch at the wall to
catch that one, a shot by Steve Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra also prevented a hit in the first inning,
snaring a grounder by Miguel Cairo and making an acrobatic throw to
first to nail him.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing a fastball that reached 97 miles an hour and a jarring
changeup that all but paralyzed every Devil Ray he faced, Martinez
struck out 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the best fastball he's had all year,'' Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Jimy Williams said, Martinez maintained his
composure after the brawl and throughout the night, which included
a series of Tampa Bay eruptions, including a Daubach plunking that
cleared both benches in the seventh after the Red Sox began to move
en masse toward the field, led by Alexander. There was more
posturing than fighting, though, before order was restored.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so crazy that even Everett wanted peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, I'm the one who's hyped up,'' Everett said. ``But I
wanted to tell everybody to calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who was suspended for five games in May for hitting
Cleveland's Roberto Alomar, said he considered retaliating as the
Rays continually attacked Daubach. And he was advised against it by
Everett, who was suspended for 10 games for bumping umpire Ron
Kulpa. ``Don't even do it,'' Everett told him.
</P>
<P>
   And Martinez concurred, earning his manager's great admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot afford to retaliate and be thrown out and act
stupid,'' said Martinez. ``I need to help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Everett helped the team Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night. Martinez had
told him before the game, ``Just give me three (runs).''
</P>
<P>
   After knocking in his first three, Everett said he told him,
``There's your three.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he went to work,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   Did he ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
