u s BC-BBA-DEVILRAYS-BOS &LR;      08-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DEVIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ'S STYLE GETS DEVIL RAYS HOT 
</HEADLINE>
 RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ They call him Ice.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerald Williams was afire Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night after Pedro
Martinez hit him in the left wrist with his fourth pitch of the
game, which would turn into a dazzling one-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Seems Williams and his Devil Ray mates had some issues with
Martinez. ``It started when Jose Guillen got hit there (by Martinez
in Boston Aug. 14),'' said Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild.
``Pedro made an issue of it being his arm and all that. We didn't
do anything that night, and right away tonight with two strikes it
starts up.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, did it start up. Williams, apparently acting on behalf of
the team, carried his fury to the mound, flailed at Martinez, and
wound up at the bottom of a massive pile.
</P>
<P>
   Was Martinez throwing at Williams? ``Obviously, we felt that he
was,'' said Rothschild, who was ejected along with Williams. ``The
guy has 27 walks and 14 hit batsmen. I gotta wonder about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had to be restrained repeatedly from taking
another run at Martinez after order was restored, had little to say
afterward. ``I think it should speak for itself,'' he said of
Pedro's pitching style. ``I just want to remain a professional.
Sometimes it becomes increasingly difficult, given a guy's
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added, ``I had a better chance preserving my health
fighting than I did taking the ball 95 miles an hour on a small
bone in my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rays, like many of Martinez's foes, believe he gets away
with more than he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems there are some guys who can do whatever they want to
do and it's all right,'' said Greg Vaughn, who was ejected for
arguing a called third strike. ``And that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene only got uglier as the night went on.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Rays starter Dave Eiland also was ejected,
after he hit consecutive batters, Brian Daubach and Nomar
Garciaparra. Acting manager Bill Russell also was tossed.
</P>
<P>
   Then Eiland's replacement, Cory Lidle, was thrown out of the
game for sailing a pitch behind Daubach in the seventh. And out
went another acting manager, Jose Cardenal.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Lidle's relief, Tony Fiore, brushed back Daubach
with one pitch and hit him with the next. That earned Fiore an
ejection.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild said the Rays targeted Daubach because they believed
he ``was throwing cheap shots in the pile.''
</P>
<P>
   Said the manager, ``You've got to protect your players. The only
problem is that our pitchers kept missing the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's news to Daubach, who got hit twice and was forced to
dance away from several other pitches before Sox manager Jimy
Williams spared him any further anguish by replacing him in the
seventh with Rico Brogna.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Daubach threw cheap shots, Eiland said, ``Damn right he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the mayhem, there was a baseball game, a fact that
appeared lost on many players in Tampa Bay uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a crazy game,'' Guillen said, ``that people forgot
it was a no-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Others wished they had been somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proud to stand here and say I was part of that game,''
said former Sox catcher John Flaherty, whose leadoff single in the
ninth broke up the no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez said it had a positive effect on the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought out the best in us,'' he said. ``Maybe we needed
something to wake us up and get reunited again and play as hard as
we could. Today was a good sign they better not wake us up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
