<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5999 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-30 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAD, MAD WHIRL FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most famous, and bizarre, no-hitter in Red Sox history began
this way:
</P>
<P>
   A 21-year-old lefthanded pitcher with a nasty fastball and an
unbridled temper named Babe Ruth walked the first batter, Ray
Morgan of the Washington Senators.
</P>
<P>
   When umpire Clarence ``Brick'' Owens called ball four, Ruth
charged the plate, and the following exchange is reported to have
ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get back to the mound or you're out of the ballgame,'' Owens
yelled at Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you chase me, I'll punch your face,'' Ruth replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're out now,'' said Owens, whereupon Ruth delivered on his
end of the bargain, throwing a left at Owens's head.
</P>
<P>
   After Ruth's ejection (he later was fined 100 bucks and
suspended 10 days), his onetime roommate, Ernie Shore, replaced
him. Morgan was caught stealing, and Shore retired all 26 batters
he faced for a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   That was 83 years ago. Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night in St. Petersburg, Fla.,
the Florida retirement haven with inhabitants old enough to
remember Shore's masterpiece, Pedro Martinez came within three outs
of trumping it in both brilliance and weirdness.
</P>
<P>
   Four pitches into the game, Martinez hit leadoff batter Gerald
Williams in the left hand. Williams was guilty of nothing other
than being the first man of the night in a Tampa Bay uniform to
face Pedro, who had lost three straight decisions to the Devil Rays
and had been roughed up by them in his last outing.
</P>
<P>
   By now, we are all aware (aren't we, Einar Diaz and Matt
Lawton?) that when Martinez takes offense for any slight _ real or
imagined _ someone pays the price. In this case, it was Williams,
who didn't appreciate the terms of the transaction and charged the
mound, knocking Pedro down and undoubtedly causing John
Harrington's forehead to leak perspiration as he watched his $75
million investment manhandled.
</P>
<P>
   The benches cleared, and the tone for a night of madness had
been set. And given that the game was being played in a domed
ballpark, Sox manager Jimy Williams couldn't blame either of his
usual suspects: a full moon or, as he said Sunday in Kansas City, a
full sun.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the vortex stood Martinez, who inning after
inning seemed unaffected by the chaos swirling about. Twenty-four
up, 24 down, not so much as a sniff at a base hit until catcher
John Flaherty, the onetime Red Sox benchwarmer, lined an outside
fastball to right-center field for a single to open the bottom of
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez would finish with his third career one-hitter. Once
again, a Red Sox pitcher would fall short of the feat last
accomplished Sept. 16, 1965, by Dave Morehead, who in a near-empty
Fenway Park no-hit the Cleveland Indians, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, Tom Yawkey called me up and gave me a $1,000
check,'' Morehead was quoted as saying in Peter Golenbock's oral
history of the Sox, ``Fenway.'' ``He even paid the taxes on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Morehead threw his no-no days after his 22d birthday. The
following April, on a wet and cold Patriots Day, he hurt his elbow
and was never the same.
</P>
<P>
   But no pitcher, it is safe to conclude, ever has flirted with
perfection under stranger circumstances _ hit batsmen,
bench-clearing brawls, and ejections _ unless it is Martinez
himself.
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, 1994, when he was just 22 and pitching for the
Montreal Expos, Martinez took a perfect game into the eighth inning
against Cincinnati before hitting Reggie Sanders with an 0-and-2
fastball. Sanders, apparently oblivious to the reasoning that only
a fool would throw at a batter with a perfecto in progress, took
exception and charged the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez lost his no-hitter, and the lead, in the next inning.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, on June 3, 1995, in San Diego, Martinez was
perfect for nine innings, then gave up a leadoff double to Bip
Roberts to open the 10th and was taken out of the game. The Expos
held on to win, 1-0, and Martinez should have gone into the record
books with a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Four years earlier, a committee charged with holding up
the statistical purity of the game had ruled that a pitcher
couldn't be called perfect, or be given credit for a no-hitter,
unless he pitched a complete game. Nine innings of perfection
wasn't enough, so Martinez joined Harvey Haddix of the Pirates (12
perfect innings in 1959) in a netherworld as strange as the one
occupied by Roger Maris when commissioner Ford Frick wouldn't
recognize him in the record book as the sole holder of the home run
record, previously set by that man again, Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, here's what Shore gave manager Wild Bill Carrigan as
the reason he had to stop rooming with the Babe, according to
Golenbock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't live with that man Ruth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? I thought you and Ruth were friends,'' Carrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right, we are,'' Shore said. ``But there's a place
where friendship stops. I told him he was using my toothbrush and
he said, `That's all right, I'm not particular.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But that isn't all, Mr. Carrigan. A man wants some privacy in
the bathroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 0227EDT &QL; 
