<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, August 30.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ A look at the possible legal
conflicts between action on a limited national missile defense and
the requirements of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-QUIZ-SHOW (Bombay, India) _ In a country where hundreds of
millions live in grinding poverty, the Indian version of ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' has suddenly become the most popular TV
show. Some poor people are using up what little money they have on
phone calls to try to get on the show. We watch it with viewers in
a Bombay slum. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-POLICE-SUIT (Los Angeles) _ A federal judge has ruled that
the Los Angeles Police Department can be sued as a racketeering
enterprise by people who claim their civil rights were violated by
LAPD officers. The ruling creates the possibility that the
department could be the first in the nation to face trial under the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law. It also could
dramatically increase the city's liability. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-DEPORT (Undated) _ Like phantoms barreling down from a
hazy, distant past, ancient crimes and misdemeanors, sometimes
decades old, have been dredged up by Immigration and Naturalization
Service investigators to condemn tens of thousands of immigrants to
hasty and usually irrevocable deportation proceedings. The
magnitude of the crime is irrelevant. If it is considered an
aggravated felony _ shoplifting can be an aggravated felony _ the
immigrants must go. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-EDUCATION (Washington) _ A look at education issues in
the presidential campaign: Five years after the Republican Congress
shut down the government in part because of the money President
Clinton wanted to spend on education, four years after Bob Dole
embraced a Republican platform that advocated abolishing the
Department of Education, George W. Bush has made an expanded
federal role in education a central issue of his campaign. Vice
President Al Gore has responded in kind on an issue that has been
an especially strong one for Democrats. By David E. Rosenbaum. The
first in a series on the issues of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-VOICES (Pittsburgh, Pa.) _ Conversations with dozens of
voters in a variety of neighborhoods about their attitudes toward
the presidential candidates, and how and why those attitudes may
have recently changed. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
