   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOBBYISTS-RESTAURANT (Undated) _ This week, the Caucus Room, a
steakhouse, opens in downtown Washington under 65 partners whose
rosters of political connections, high-tech interests and, in some
cases, both, are longer than a Manhattan wine list. By Marian
Burros.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KIDNAP-TAXES (Undated) _ An IRS legal memo says that if your
child is kidnapped you can take a deduction for the child only for
the year of the kidnapping and not for subsequent years, even if
you maintain a room for the child and spend money _ apparently
because the law makes the kidnappers (assuming the child is kept
alive) eligible to deduct the cost of caring for the child. By
David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   MOMS-BACK-AT-WORK (Undated) _ Not so long ago, housewives with
resume gaps spanning several years faced tough slogging in the job
market. No more. In today's full-employment economy, employers are
actively wooing women who held jobs once upon a time and are
finding in them a rich new source of talent. By Melinda Ligos.
</P>
<P>
   MASTERCARD-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ How do you reach people in the
fastest-growing segment of the American population? Simple. Speak
their language. Mastercard, the latest mainstream company to
acknowledge the buying power of Latinos, has decided to speak
directly to them, in Spanish. By Courtney Kane.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BUSINESS-SCHOOL (Boston) _ In 1974, two Harvard Business
School professors fed up with a male business culture created the
first all-woman business school. Today, the Simmons Graduate School
of Management is still the only all-woman business school, but its
raison d'etre appears to have disappeared. Women now account for 30
percent of all business school students, up from 5 percent a
quarter century ago. Yet enrollment at Simmons continues to grow.
Women say they come for the same things they seek in a workplace:
supportive colleagues, flexible scheduling and a chance to be
themselves. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
