<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NY     08-30 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BEAT YANKEES, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Like Boston's Pedro Martinez, Andy Pettitte flirted
with a no-hitter Tuesday night. But unlike Martinez, Pettitte did
not engage in any brawls, there were no ejections _ and after
Pettitte's no-hitter was broken up in the sixth, he suffered the
loss when the Seattle Mariners came back for five runs in the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez hammered a grand slam off reliever Jeff Nelson
with two outs in the eighth, giving Seattle a shocking 5-3 lead
over the Yankees. The Mariners had lost 13 of their last 15 games,
and the Yankees had won three in a row. Pettitte (16-7) had won
seven straight games.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-3 loss marked the third time in their last 11 games that
the Yankees blew a three-run lead and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Guillen broke up Pettitte's no-hitter with a bloop single
with two outs in the sixth, but Pettitte was in command, leading by
3-0. He retired the first batter in the eighth, but allowed three
consecutive singles to load the bases. Stan Javier then hit a
sinking line drive in the direction of Luis Polonia, the left
fielder broke late and just missed a sliding catch; one run scored.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre summoned Nelson to relieve Pettitte,
and Nelson struck out shortstop Alex Rodriguez for the second out.
Nelson fell behind Martinez, two balls and no strikes, fired a
fastball and Martinez drove it to the opposite field, about three
rows into the right-field stands, thrilling the Safeco Field fans.
It was the second home run surrendered by Nelson this season.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez was three outs from completing a no-hitter
against Tampa Bay when the Yankees began their game here Tuesday
night. It may be that as Pettitte changed T-shirts in the clubhouse
or got a cup of water or had a last look at the Seattle scouting
reports, he might have seen the last few outs of that game, the hit
by Devil Rays catcher John Flaherty that broke up Martinez's
no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte might have had no-hitter on the brain when he took the
mound, but there was no way he would expect to throw one himself,
for he is not well suited to do so. Unlike Martinez or Randy
Johnson, Pettitte does not overpower hitters and compiles few
strikeouts. To the contrary, Pettitte is reliant on his sinkerball,
his objective to get batters to beat this pitch into the dirt and
get lots of ground-ball outs. Going into Tuesday night's game,
Pettitte had allowed more than a hit an inning, 172 hits in 161
innings, with just 96 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte was particularly sharp Tuesday night, throwing
harder than usual; on an average day, his fastball will be clocked
at 88 mph to 89 mph, and Tuesday night, the radar gun readings were
91 mph to 92 mph. All three types of his fastball were moving well:
the sinker down and away, the cutter darting inside, the fastball
boring down on batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners could not merely wait for a fastball, either, for
Pettitte mixed in a curveball at about 73 mph to 75 mph and a
changeup of 82 mph to 83 mph, the change of speeds confounding.
Pettitte retired the first nine hitters he faced on four ground
balls, two strikeouts and three fly balls _ and he seemed appeared
annoyed, nonetheless, griping to catcher Chris Turner as he walked
off the mound at the end of third.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte walked Rickey Henderson on four pitches leading off the
fourth, but Javier grounded to short to start a double play, and
Scott Brosius gloved Rodriguez's hot smash to close the inning.
Pettitte retired the Mariners in order in the fifth, the last out
coming when Chris Widger flailed at a breaking ball. Pettitte had a
3-0 lead, he had great stuff and he was facing a team in the midst
of a deep, depressing, debilitating slump; the possibility of a
no-hitter appeared real.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Oliver popped a foul ball near the stands, and Jorge Posada
_ playing first base _ reached over the hands of some fans to make
a leaning catch. Eleven outs to go. David Bell popped to second; 10
outs.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte's preponderance for creating contact finally
manifested itself, in the form of a fluke hit. The
right-handed-hitting Guillen swung hard and looped a pop fly into
short right field, far out of the reach of the three fielders who
pursued it, and the Seattle fans _ suffering through the team's
drought _ stood and cheered, their enthusiasm tinged with sarcasm.
Pettitte's expression never changed; it was impossible to tell,
from his body language, whether he realized he was throwing a
no-hitter, if he was vested in the idea of creating history.
</P>
<P>
   No, he just got the ball back and concentrated on facing the
next hitter. Henderson slapped a double into the right-field
corner, but with Javier representing the potential tying run at the
plate, Pettitte rebounded, enticing Javier to chase a cut fastball
in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored all their runs early, rewarded for their
patience against the Seattle left-hander Jamie Moyer. Bernie
Williams singled with two outs in the first, and designated hitter
Jose Canseco waited through a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Roger Clemens remarked how difficult it is for
opposing pitchers to get through this part of the Yankees' lineup
now, knowing that a mistake could kill them. It wears on a pitcher,
Clemens explained, and eventually, the increased tension causes a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco has 444 career home runs, David Justice has 34 homers,
Glenallen Hill is averaging a home run for every seven at-bats
since he joined the Yankees, and Posada is on a pace to hit 30
homers. With their revamped lineup, the Yankees have 45 homers this
month, most in the league.
</P>
<P>
   So Moyer got himself into trouble with the Canseco walk, and
suffered the consequences. Justice ripped a single to drive home
Williams, and after Hill got ahead in the count, three balls and
one strike, before lining a single to left. Yankees 2, Seattle 0.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added a run in the second, collecting three more
walks; Moyer would allow seven in all, a career high, and last six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 46 games, the Yankees have knocked out opposing
starters 12 times before the end of the fifth inning; only 13
pitchers have survived the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Tomko (7-4) gave up two hits in two innings to earn the
triumph after replacing Moyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
