<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BAIL OUT KARL, BEAT BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The best thing about Scott Karl's performance
Tuesday night in his first start for the Angels: He kept the ball
in the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be saying a lot, but it was critical, as it turned
out.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't dig that big of a hole, and the Angels, once they got
their big bats cranking, were able to overcome Karl's shortcomings
for their 32nd come-from-behind win, 9-4 over the Toronto Blue Jays
in front of 17,773 fans at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus slugged a three-run home run in the fourth inning to
get the Angels close. It was his 38th homer, leaving him just one
shy of Reggie Jackson's franchise-record 39 set in 1982. And Mo
Vaughn walloped his 32nd in the fifth inning to tie the score 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels then batted around in the sixth, scoring four times _
on a run-scoring double by Adam Kennedy to break the tie, a
run-scoring single by Bengie Molina and a two-run single by Darin
Erstad, who reached the 200-hit plateau with three singles.
</P>
<P>
   It was a notable milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad got his 200th hit in the Angels' 132nd game. The last
time anyone got there faster was in 1935, when Joe Medwick of the
St. Louis Cardinals got to 200 in 131 games. Erstad got there
faster than any AL player in 75 years, since the Philadelphia A's
Al Simmons got his 200th hit in his 125th game. Erstad is now just
two hits shy of Alex Johnson's club-record 202 in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is incredible,'' said Angels manager Mike Scioscia,
who once more mounted the soapbox in support of Erstad as the AL
Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he brings to this club ... he plays every game one way,
the right way, whether it's a spring training game or the seventh
game of the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Series, of course, is something the Angels only talk
about _ they haven't been there _ but it was with that in mind that
they sought to add to their pitching with the acquisition of Karl,
a 28-year-old left-hander who had struggled mightily at Colorado
(1-3, 7.40 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was everything ... nervousness, rustiness, excited ... they
hit good pitches, they hit bad pitches,'' Karl said, assessing his
2 2/3 innings in which he was clubbed for four runs on nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   Once Karl departed, the bullpen took charge. Lou Pote bailed
Karl out of a jam in the third, Mike Holtz got Pote out of a mess
in the sixth, then Al Levine, Shigetoshi Hasegawa and Troy Percival
combined to retire the final nine Blue Jays in order.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the five Angels relievers shut out Toronto on two hits
over the final 6 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The win kept the Angels four games behind first-place Seattle in
the American League West and three games back of Cleveland in the
AL wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Carlos Delgado had two of the nine hits off Karl,
including his club-record 88th extra-base hit. And Dave Martinez
had two singles to stretch his career-best hitting streak to 19
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a potent offense, but the key to this game was
Pote,'' Scioscia said, noting his reliever's 3 1/3 scoreless
innings. ``Their guy (starter Chris Carpenter) shut us down the
first time through the lineup, but the second time around we got
some balls to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels hit 'em, too, led by Erstad's three singles, hits
No.198-200.
</P>
<P>
   Someone wondered the fastest Scioscia ever got to 200 hits,
knowing, of course, the former catcher topped out one year with the
Dodgers at 127.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia didn't have to think too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
