<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ JARS YANKEES WITH LATE GRAND SLAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Any one of the Mariners would have walked through fire
to get a hit like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a little singed is nothing compared to the hellish last
two weeks Mariners had just been through.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez brought fire back into the Mariners offense
Tuesday night with an eighth-inning grand slam that produced a 5-3
victory over New York. The comeback easily stands as the Mariners'
biggest win of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed this one more than we needed oxygen,'' shortstop
Alex Rodriguez said of Martinez's fourth grand slam of 2000. ``It
was the biggest hit of our season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were five outs away from losing, down 3-0 to
Yankees lefty Andy Pettitte, who was so on top of his game that it
took Seattle all of six innings just to get a hit. With a trail of
tears that included 13 losses in their previous 15 games, the
Mariners' night looked like simply more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte carried a three-hitter into the eighth. The way recent
history had played out, the Mariners could have mailed this one in.
Instead, the results of a late night of talking baseball kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Mariners remained in the clubhouse long after
Monday's 9-1 loss to the Yankees. They talked over the ins and outs
of the bad spell. They talked about having fun, about putting all
those yesterdays behind them. They talked about playing baseball
more and about worrying about the pennant race less.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe at the time it sounded dumb and hit jaded ears like just
another sound bite. But one out into the eighth inning, the words
rang true.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell singled to right. Carlos Guillen singled to right.
The crowd started to get into it.
</P>
<P>
   And then a freaky thing happened. The Mariners caught a break.
Jorge Posada was still playing first base for the Yankees. He's a
catcher by trade, and just fills in at first. He didnt have the
experience to cope with Rickey Hendersons tortured fly ball behind
first base. Posada never came close to catching the ball. Henderson
had a hit and the Mariners had the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   And then another freaky thing happened. The Mariners caught
another break. Luis Polonia tried to make a sliding catch of Stan
Javiers sinking line drive in left. Polonia had a bead on the ball,
but he missed it. Javier got a single and the Mariners got a run.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks, the breaks had gone against Seattle. All of a
sudden, the clouds had parted. With Jeff Nelson coming in out of
the New York bullpen, Pettitte was out of the game and light was
beginning to shine. The light dimmed some when Rodriguez struck
out, but up stepped Martinez, a man made for hitting with the game
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez came into the at-bat with just one hit in his previous
18 at-bats, but he's such a good hitter pitchers have to fear him
more in a slump than they do most hitters on their best day.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson missed with one pitch. Then another. Nelson didnt miss
with his third pitch, catching the strike zone. It also caught
Martinezs bat. Right fielder Clay Bellinger gave ground, then gave
more ground, trying to will the ball into his glove. What he found
was that there was more room on Martinez's fly ball than there was
in the ballpark. Bellinger had his body pressed vainly up against
the right field wall while Martinezs home run settled into the
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd talked about how much we'd been overswinging,'' said
Martinez, who'd been one of the culprits. ``This time, I didn't
overswing. I didn't try to hit a home run. I just tried to hit the
ball hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It just so happened he hit it high, too. High enough for a grand
slam. High enough to finally let the dogs out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy,'' Mike Cameron, the next hitter, said of the
emotion let loose in the Mariners' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   How crazy?
</P>
<P>
   ``So crazy I didn't even see the first two pitches that (Nelson)
threw me,'' Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one we've been looking for,'' said reliever Arthur
Rhodes, who was warming up in the bullpen at the time of the home
run. ``No one had his head down. We were behind, but we felt
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down three runs in the eighth and come back with a
big inning like that, it's huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella said the win ``has to be our biggest one of
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate residual of the victory was an increase in
Seattle's AL West lead to 2{ games over Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a special win for us,'' Piniella said. ``This is the
type of win that can maybe turn things around for us. We got
pitching, defense and timely hitting. This was the type of game we
have been waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the glow of Martinezs accomplishment was that of
starting pitcher Jamie Moyer. The lefty gave up three runs in the
first two innings and was on the verge of being blown out in the
fourth inning when he intentionally walked Bernie Williams to load
the bases with one out and Jose Canseco at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer fell behind 2-0 and 3-1, then came back to strike out
Canseco. David Justice then lined out, and for the first time in
just short of forever, the Mariners avoided a big inning. That kept
the Mariners within striking range. Ultimately, they would strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, that was the turning point of the game,'' Javier said.
``It was a tough situation, and Moyer pitched out of it. Getting
Canseco was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the last Mariners pitcher to get Canseco with the game
on the line. Once the Mariners took the lead, Kazuhiro Sasaki had
to pitch through the middle of the Yankees lineup to finally put
New York away.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams lined out hard to first base, where John Olerud,
just brought into the game as a defensive change, made a nice
catch. Canseco struck out. Polonia popped out.
</P>
<P>
   End of game. End of slump?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of win that can turn things around for us,''
Rodriguez said. ``We've got to build on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
