<HEADLINE>
RANGERS, JAYS CONSIDER OPENING 2001 SEASON IN PUERTO RICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers could open the regular
season next year in San Juan, Puerto Rico, against the Toronto Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Blue Jays are close to finalizing an
agreement to play their season opener on April 1 in San Juan. The
game would be televised by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a possibility,'' Rangers vice president John Blake said.
``It's under discussion but nothing has been decided. Major League
Baseball has made us a proposal, and we're going through that
proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball would be opening the season outside the
continental United States for the third consecutive year. The first
game of 1999 was played in Mexico, and this year it was held in
Japan. TEAM MEETING
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates held a team meeting Tuesday, trying
to keep his team focused for the final month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed a few things,'' Oates said. ``Mainly, just to
stick with it. The effort has been there, but maybe the focus or
the concentration might wander. I have no problem with the effort
or the concentration. When have you seen a guy not run out a ground
ball? They've played hard to a man.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro said: ``I think sometimes you lose
focus when you go through a bad time. We need to refocus, and this
was to give us a jump-start.'' LAMB FRUSTRATED
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Mike Lamb was at The Ballpark in Arlington early
Tuesday, working on defense with infield coach Bucky Dent. But he's
out of the lineup both Tuesday night and Wednesday night as manager
Johnny Oates wants to give him a couple days off to clear his head.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb committed his league-leading 26th error Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new experience for me,'' Lamb said. ``For me, it's been
hard, but that which won't kill me will only make me better. But
it's tough. I have high expectations, and it's difficult when you
don't meet those expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he expects Lamb to return the lineup Thursday night.
HICKS WON'T SHY FROM TOP PICK
</P>
<P>
   The the Rangers could have the top pick in next year's June
amateur draft, which could be an expensive proposition. In fact,
some teams with the top pick often shy away from taking the best
player because they're not sure they can afford them.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Tom Hicks said that won't happen with the Rangers if
they're in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to draft based on the who's the best player, not
on signability,'' Hicks said. ``To me that's money well-spent.''
ROSTER MOVE
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers optioned reliever Darwin Cubillan to Class-A Pulaski
on Tuesday to make room for pitcher Ryan Glynn, who was activated
off the disabled list. Cubillan was optioned to Pulaski because the
Appalachian League season ends Saturday and he can be added to the
big-league roster immediately afterward. He will remain with the
Rangers but can't be in uniform for games. CRABTREE SUPPORTS
EXTENSION
</P>
<P>
   Tim Crabtree, the Rangers' player representative, said his
teammates were 100 percent in support of extending the current
bargaining agreement through next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the game right now is in good shape,'' Crabtree said.
``We've got some teams that aren't spending a lot of money in the
middle of the pennant race. There are a lot of good things going on
if somehow in the next contract we can figure out how to increase
revenue sharing.'' MINOR-LEAGUE FLASHES
</P>
<P>
   _ Class-A Port Charlotte outfielder Kevin Mench was named the
Florida State League MVP on Tuesday. In 125 games, Mench is hitting
.331 with 111 runs, 26 home runs and 116 runs batted in. First
baseman Travis Hafner and pitcher Aaron Harang are on the
postseason All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Gulf Coast Rangers defeated the Yankees, 8-4, Tuesday in
the first game of their best-of-three playoff. Game 2 is Wednesday
in Tampa, Fla. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
