<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIC AGREEMENT EXTENDED, BUT STRIKE HASN'T BEEN AVERTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ There was a great deal of irony Tuesday night
during Tom Schieffer's much deserved tribute for his tenure as
president of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer was lauded for his role in building The Ballpark in
Arlington, the club's palatial home. He was presented with a
Rangers jersey with the number 94, emblematic of the year the
stadium opened.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is the number also is a reminder of the low point of
Schieffer's time at the helm: the players' strike that wiped out
the '94 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question in my mind that the most difficult period
to be involved with the franchise was during the strike,''
Schieffer said. ``That was just awful, and it took all the fun out
of it for everybody. Hopefully, because it was so bad last time, it
scared the beejeebies out of everybody, and they won't bring us
close to that again.''
</P>
<P>
   All anyone can do at this point is hope.
</P>
<P>
   The union announced Monday that it is picking up its option on
the Basic Agreement for 2001. But the action is merely the
continuation of the cease fire in the labor wars, not the end of
hostilities. The issues that led to the most damaging strike in
baseball history still exist.
</P>
<P>
   The owners wanted a device that would slow down salaries. They
sought a salary cap but settled for a luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work. From 1996, the first year of the current
agreement, until Opening Day this year, the average salary rose
from $1,119,981 to $1,988,034.
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap would trigger more revenue sharing, leveling the
playing field between the large- and small-market clubs.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. The gap between the clubs with the largest and
the smallest payrolls is larger than ever. Teams that spend a lot
of money dominate in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer knows the issues. He once was a member of commissioner
Bud Selig's blue-ribbon panel charged with finding ways to solve
the economic-disparity issue.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended that teams share 40 to 50 percent of all
local revenues, that a 50 percent competitive-balance tax be
assessed on payrolls that top $84 million and that money be
available for low-revenue clubs to meet a minimum payroll of $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened with the blue-ribbon committee was you had some
very thoughtful people get together and examine the game in a
somewhat dispassionate way and make some recommendations that I
think people ought to look at very hard,'' Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   They ought to, but will they?
</P>
<P>
   It's assumed the committee's recommendations will form the basis
of the owners' negotiating strategy, but first Selig has to sell it
to the owners. It won't be easy to get the large-market clubs to
sign off on a plan that would cost them that much revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams that produce more revenue and cash flow are more
valuable than teams that don't,'' Schieffer said. ``When you go
into revenue sharing that reduces their income and their cash flow,
that reduces the value of their franchise. How do you compensate
the larger franchises for a reduction in their overall value? You
have to figure out how to solve that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   If the owners figure it out, they still have to sell it to a
union that not only remains opposed to anything that might slow the
growth of salaries, but will have its own issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always trying to make it as good as possible to be a
big-league player, whether it's pension or minimum salaries going
up,'' said Rangers pitcher Rick Helling, a member of the union's
executive board. ``I'm sure there'll be things we want to discuss.
It's give and take on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Helling is cautiously optimistic because, so far, there
has been little of the bitter rhetoric that led up to the '94
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've heard one player or one owner say we're
headed for a work stoppage,'' he said. ``It's always been media, or
in a couple of cases maybe an agent saying this doesn't look good.
As far as I understand, I've never seen a player or an owner say
that, and that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer is cautiously optimistic because few dispute the
financial problems facing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a much broader consensus now that you have to look at
this as an industry problem and not just an individual club
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains much work to be done if the number 02 isn't
going to be as foreboding in a few years as 94 is now. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
