<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-QBS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TEXAS, CHOOSING BETWEEN SIMMS AND APPLEWHITE ISN'T A SNAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the ongoing and oft-analyzed competition to
land the starting-quarterback job at Texas, this much is a given:
Chris Simms is No. 1 on the Longhorns' roster.
</P>
<P>
   That became a fact during the off-season, when coaches granted
Simms' request to switch numerals on his game jersey; he wore No. 8
last season. Whether the new digit coincides with the sophomore's
status on the Texas depth chart at the conclusion of fall drills
remains to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Simms is locked in a battle for playing time with Major
Applewhite, the 1999 Big 12 Offensive Player of the Year, who
underwent reconstructive knee surgery in January. Texas coaches
have pointed to a series of fall scrimmages as the primary platform
for quarterbacks to stake their claim to the starting job for the
Longhorns' Sept. 9 opener against Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Wednesday's final preseason scrimmage at
Royal-Memorial Stadium, neither quarterback has made significant
headway. Simms, in the first two scrimmages, has completed 12 of 26
passes for 206 yards and three touchdowns. He has thrown one
interception. Applewhite is 13-of-30 for 216 yards and one
touchdown. He has thrown one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Their near-identical statistics do not surprise Texas offensive
coordinator Greg Davis, who stressed that both quarterbacks will
play, at least during the early stages of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect much separation,'' Davis said. ``They're both
extremely talented and very accurate passers. One of them is not
likely to come out here and go 0-for-14 to help make things real
clear-cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the most clear-cut message has come from coach Mack
Brown. Although Applewhite has not experienced swelling in his knee
during fall drills, Brown said he will have reservations about
Applewhite's health until he plays in a game with full contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major's not competing for a job or with Chris,'' Brown said.
``He's competing with his knee. The important thing for him is just
being healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Longhorns' quarterbacks will not be exposed to
contact until the season opener, Applewhite can't convince coaches
he is fully recovered until the Louisiana-Lafayette game. Davis
said both quarterbacks will play in that contest. When and how much
is yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty, said Davis, is there will be no preordained
appearance schedule. If a quarterback leads scoring drives on
consecutive possessions to open a game, said Davis, that player is
staying in as long as he has the hot hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are telling them we plan on playing both, but we're not
going to script anything that we can't follow through on,'' Davis
said. ``How that works itself out will be determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Both quarterbacks expressed satisfaction with a shared-duty
situation for the short term. But both players predicted coaches
would settle on an established starter by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see two guys starting off the season. But, eventually, I
think there will probably be one person,'' Applewhite said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected coaches to settle on a single starter
before Big 12 play begins Sept. 30 against Oklahoma State, Simms
said: ``I would think so. Coach Brown has got a great sense for the
aura of the team and the right timing for everything. I trust him
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Brown said the timing hasn't been right to settle the
No. 1 issue on the minds of Longhorns' fans. But there is a new No.
1 on the Texas roster, a switch Simms made because he thought the
digit looked better on his 6-foot-5, 222-pound frame than the No. 8
he wore last season.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Texas fans will learn if Simms emerges as No. 1 on the
depth chart as well.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
