<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-30 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODEL FIRST LADY WITH `INFINITE HEART' 

</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listening to the candidates' wives in Philadelphia and Los
Angeles go on about their husbands put Allida Black in mind of
Eleanor Roosevelt's appearance in Chicago in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Historian and author Black, who's tailored a career around the
person she calls ER, tells how Eleanor Roosevelt stopped a nasty
fight on the floor of the Democratic convention that year. FDR, who
stayed home, was about to be nominated for his third term, but
there was hot disagreement over his vice presidential choice, Henry
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   No first lady had ever addressed a national political
convention, but FDR asked his wife to go make peace. She took her
regal straight-backed self to the podium and without notes
addressed the scrapping delegates, telling them this was no time
for a president to not have a solid right-hand man. She pacified
the crowd, Wallace got the necessary votes and her speech became
another part of the ER legend.
</P>
<P>
   During FDR's days, Republicans complained that it wasn't right
for a president to cash in on his wife's popularity. Now everyone
loves the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Black spoke at a recent Women's Equality Day lunch in Santa
Rosa, Calif., one of the few places in the country that annually
celebrates the 19th amendment. She thinks Laura Bush, Lynne Cheney,
Tipper Gore and Hadassah Lieberman all made political points for
their husbands, but doesn't see any of them carrying what she calls
the ``Eleanor gene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that they're wimps, but there's no one there who has the
vision of Eleanor Roosevelt,'' said Dr. Black, who teaches history
at George Washington University and is director and editor of the
Eleanor Roosevelt Papers.
</P>
<P>
   She credits Tipper Gore for having ``good knowledge of politics
and policy, knowing how to use her influence and understanding the
need to sometimes cross the aisle and build bipartisan support,''
as she did for her warning label project and mental health
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   The one with the Eleanor gene is Hillary Clinton, says Black,
who knows the first lady and who, in fact, regularly sent her ER
quotes for three years by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Think back to the early Hillary-bashing days and remember Bob
Woodward making sport of the first lady for saying that she had
imaginary conversations with Eleanor Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the stupidest thing,'' says Black, pointing out that
anyone tuned into history who has a particular champion always
wonders how that person might respond in a given situation.
</P>
<P>
   Black, who has worked with the first lady on assembling a
collection of ER papers at the university, is accustomed to making
Eleanor-Hillary comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In her heart ER was committed to her beliefs. It wasn't an
act. But Eleanor was also a pol, a real political warhorse. Same
with Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   Another comparison is that both married men were comfortable
around strong women but took flak from their advisors when their
wives grabbed the spotlight. A popular line during Eleanor's time
was, ``Please, God, make Eleanor tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding what kind of first-lady influence they actually
wielded, Black says, ``Eleanor lied. Hillary told the truth and got
in trouble for telling the truth. Eleanor went to her grave saying
she had no power.''
</P>
<P>
   Black got interested in Eleanor Roosevelt while studying FDR.
``I realized that so many things I associated with what he did,
Eleanor had a hand in.''
</P>
<P>
   She admired her faith in human nature. ``Her heart was infinite.
She saw the worst that democracy had to offer and she still kept
going. She saw people starving and she saw people being mean and
selfish, but she said you either believe that people are inherently
good or inherently bad. And she thought they were good. Not that
they were perfect but they had possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor, she said, believed that women's role was to be involved
in social change in matters of health care, schools, civil rights,
housing, immigration and the like, ``some of those things that are
now part of the platform for both political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   As to ER's appeal to women, she continues to enthrall. ``Women
admire the way she spoke out. She struggled to find her voice and
then she used it masterfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Who doesn't have a favorite ER quote pinned to their bulletin
board or their brain? Such as:
</P>
<P>
   ``You must do the thing you think you can not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``No one can make you feel inferior without your consent.''
</P>
<P>
   Black's favorite is, ``Staying aloof is not a solution. It is a
cowardly evasion.''
</P>
<P>
   If your spouse were running for president or you were running
for the U.S. Senate, it might be, ``A woman in politics must have a
hide as thick as a rhinoceros.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
