<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSING-HOMES-0903-CO     08-30 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    NURSING HOME BANKRUPTCIES PROMPT CALLS FOR AID, QUESTIONS ABOUT
COLLAPSE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For release on or after Sunday, Sept. 3 
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's ailing nursing home industry is
pressing for a new infusion of federal funds as Congress returns to
the capital next week.
</P>
<P>
   And with one of every ten facilities now in bankruptcy
proceedings, Congress is widely expected to deliver $2 billion in
higher Medicare payments _ the second boost in as many years _ to
help the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, calls for more funds have prompted renewed questions
about why the industry, whose nearly 17,000 facilities run chiefly
on government money, soared on huge profits during the 1990s and
then crashed last year. Eight of the major chains have sought
bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled companies blame budget-cutting by the federal
government, which three years ago turned down the spigot on
Medicare reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home industry, led by the American Health Care
Association, has run a $1 million public relations campaign, to
make its case that that Medicare spending for skilled nursing
facilities has been dropping lower _ by $15.8 billion over seven
years _ than Congress intended in its own budgets.
</P>
<P>
   However, critics of the industry fault the big chains for
creating their own crisis by over-extending themselves and
over-charging the government, even as they kept staffing so low
that, according to a federal study, 54 percent of the homes fail to
offer adequate care.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these conflicting views will be laid out Tuesday when
Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, holds a hearing in his Senate
Special Committee on Aging to examine the cause of the nursing home
collapses.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the problem go back to the mid-1990s, when loose
rules for Medicare reimbursements allowed costs to soar 30 percent
a year to a high of $13.6 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, warned in 1995 of ``widespread examples of overcharges''
by nursing homes. The GAO cited a speech therapist whose pay was
only $12-25 an hour but whose company billed Medicare for $600 or
more per session.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home chains also have been investigated for billing the
government for blood tests that were unnecessary, for
double-billing, and for seeking payment for services that were
never delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is now seeking $1.3 billion in repayment
for alleged fraud by Louisville-based Vencor Inc., a major nursing
home operator that is currently in bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest chain, the Arkansas-based Beverly
Enterprises, Inc., has agreed to pay $175 million and sell 10
facilities to resolve federal charges that it defrauded Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Congress clamped down on the Medicare overpayments and the
abuses by setting flat rates per resident as part of the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997. As a result, nursing chains that had reaped
huge profits under the old system saw their future suddenly darken.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies that have gone bankrupt are the ones that were
very aggressive with their expansion plans throughout the mid
1990s,'' said Andrew Gitkin, a nursing home analyst with
PaineWebber. ``Their balance sheets got very bloated. That put them
in a vulnerable position.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he argued that Medicare payments dropped too low and
should be raised. ``If the industry is going to recover, that's a
critical component,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the industry are hard-pressed to reject the plea for
more funds. ``We don't want these facilities to close because it
would be a nightmare to move these residents,'' said Joshua Wiener,
an expert on long-term care with the Urban Institute, a Washington
research group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically hold older people hostage because they're
living in the facility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Wilkes, whose Tampa, Fla., law firm has filed some 1,000
lawsuits against nursing homes for shoddy care, offers a harsher
assessment of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've created their own crisis, and they're now playing on
fears'' by pressuring Congress for more aid, he said. ``So far, the
blackmail's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry backers plan a rally next Tuesday of nursing home
workers on the steps of the U.S. Capitol to portray support for
Medicare increases as support for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the group's confidence, the AHCA has halted an
earlier ad campaign to rally support for a new round of Medicare
increases for nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is now running ads in the home states of key
senators, including Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-SD, and
Senate Finance Chairman William Roth, R-Del., to thank them for
their help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caring for seniors,'' says the narrator in one of the TV
spots. ``That's our senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   Nursing home industry supporters: www.keepthepromise.com
</P>
<P>
   National Citizens' Coalition for Nursing Home Reform :
www.nccnhr.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
