<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peeved neighbor rousts roosters
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An indication of how much Austin has become
infected with a bad case of infectious yuppititis can be seen on El
Paso Street.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody contacted the city to complain about Jesse Strzelecki's
three pet roosters roaming freely in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Kelley, senior sanitarian with the city health department,
won't say who lodged the complaint. But there has been some talk
that the person who turned Jesse in must be a newcomer who doesn't
understand the Austin tradition of decorating with farm animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being attacked by the new, newly nouveau riche of
dot-com people,'' said Diana Claitor, who is pro-rooster ``and
damned proud of it.'' She's a book editor who lives near Jesse.
</P>
<P>
   After the complaint, a city health inspector called Jesse and
told him he had to confine the roosters to his property. Now the
birds are in a pen in Jesse's yard.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't have free-range roosters in Austin, where can you
have free-range roosters?
</P>
<P>
   ``A large pain in my (butt) is what it is,'' said Jesse, a
carpenter who has two boats in his front yard, an enormous
Rottweiler-husky mix named Roger on a chain, a ``Ski Boat 4 Sale''
sign nailed to a tree and, all of a sudden, a wire pen with
roosters inside.
</P>
<P>
   It is trendy in Austin to have livestock in the neighborhoods.
We used to have a 400-pound hog named Wallstreet in my
neighborhood. I have seen a goat in a yard near Fran's Hamburgers
on South Congress Avenue. But as the town becomes more gentrified,
expect the herd to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse says his rooster collection began two years ago when a
rooster _ he named him The Old Man _ showed up in his yard. ``I
started throwing food out to it, and it decided to stay,'' Jesse
said. He kept The Old Man, then went to a flea market and bought
two more roosters _ Red and Raven _ to keep The Old Man company.
</P>
<P>
   They're pets, and Jesse says most of the neighbors like having
them visiting their yards. ``Hey, at least I ain't fightin' 'em,''
Jesse said.
</P>
<P>
   He says The Old Man and the Rottweiler mix are buddies. ``The
Old Man, he'll sleep underneath the boat with my dog,'' Jesse said.
Now that The Old Man is doing time in bird jail, however, those
days of wine and roses are over.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Carlin, Jesse's next-door neighbor who moved here from
Seattle in November, is glad the birds are in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scare my cats to death, and they poop in my yard,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, lady, free fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Linda said the birds keep her up all night with their crowing.
``I've had lots of friends make jokes about making chicken soup,''
she said. But she said she's not the one who got the birds busted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several times when they start crowing at 4 in the morning, the
dog will chime in,'' she said. ``Then the guy starts up his truck.
Vroom vroom. At all hours. It's just bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds normal to me.
</P>
<P>
   Linda likes the idea of the roosters being in a pen with a tarp
thrown over the top. ``I noticed this morning they were quieter,''
she said. ``They were still crowing, but it was like a muffled
crow.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the street's longtime residents see it otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they might as well run loose,'' said Mary McFarland,
who has lived in the same house for 47 years. ``They might as well
run loose as the dogs. If the dogs can run loose, I think the
chickens should run loose, too. At least they don't destroy the
yard. And the city sure don't keep up with their leash law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the whole neighborhood's going to hell,'' Diana
said, speaking of the growth. She's got a point. Nobody in Austin
is free when the roosters aren't.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 512-445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
