<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Months of therapy paying off for determined police officer
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Tuesday morning, Mary Beall went home to her
family.
</P>
<P>
   It was 107 days after she was critically wounded in the line of
duty during what the Dayton police officer describes as ``the one
minute and 48 seconds that changed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Declaring ``I feel good,'' Beall said she couldn't wait to sleep
under the same roof with her family, to be there when children
Vanessa, 16, Ian, 13, and Maddie, 7, come home from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means almost everything to me,'' Beall said as her
husband, John, wheeled her out of the rehabilitation unit at Miami
Valley Hospital. ``It's what I've worked so hard for.''
</P>
<P>
   Beall spent the morning exchanging hugs and sometimes tearful
goodbyes with a staff that had come to regard her as family.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Boehmer, 21, a patient care technician, was one of many
wiping away tears after Beall's departure. ``I love her to death,''
she said. ``She's one strong lady. She just refused to be bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnessing Beall's ``depth of character'' from day to day was a
life-changing experience for Boehmer: ``I always wanted to be a
nurse. Now I want to be a spinal cord nurse.''
</P>
<P>
   Certified rehabilitation nurse Donna Bova vacillated between joy
and sorrow. ``She's ready,'' Bova said. ``I'm only worried that
she'll try to do too much too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot of support from her family and community,'' said
RN Gail November. ``She and John are very strong. They're going to
make it through the hard spots. She's going to come through and
shine like I know she can.''
</P>
<P>
   Paralyzed since the May 15 shooting, Beall has been undergoing
intensive therapy since being transferred from Good Samaritan
Hospital in mid-June. The suspect, Raham Twitty, 21, has been
indicted on nine felony counts, including three counts of felonious
assault.
</P>
<P>
   John Beall, also a Dayton police officer, said he expects his
wife to recover even more rapidly now that she is home.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's home now, and that in itself is a huge accomplishment,''
concurred Beall's doctor, David Shuster, medical director of the
spinal cord injury team at Miami Valley Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Since coming to Miami Valley Hospital, Beall has resumed normal
speech and has undergone daily therapy to regain daily living
skills such as feeding herself and even applying makeup. She is
able to move her shoulder and to bend her arm at the shoulder and
at the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary and her family; they have the right stuff,'' Shuster
said. ``Now will be the time to put that to use so that she can
function optimally.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look at this homecoming as an ending, but I
see it only as a beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the hospital Beall said that community support
has boosted her morale. ``I want to say thank you to everybody who
supported me and sent letters and cards, and thought about me all
the time in the hospital,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beall's return home was the high point of what promised to be an
upbeat two days for the family. Tuesday was Mary Beall Get Well
Night at the Dayton Dragons minor league baseball game, and John,
flanked by Vanessa and Ian, threw out the first pitch. Proceeds
from items raffled at the game will be donated to the Mary Beall
Get Well Fund, managed by National City Bank. Some of the items
include a baseball signed by Dragons' part owner Earvin ``Magic''
Johnson and the honor of throwing out the first pitch at one of
this year's Dragons playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at $135,000, the fund will finance the building of a more
accessible home for the Beall family. Groundbreaking on the new
home is scheduled to take place this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It is hoped that the family will be able to move in before the
end of the year. But Tuesday morning, Mary Beall had a more
immediate goal: ``I just want to go home now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Escorted by family, friends and partner, Dayton police officer
Shawn Smiley, Mary Beall left Miami Valley Hospital on Tuesday
morning _ and entered a new life.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Boehmer and her co-workers went back to the unit and had
a good cry. ``She means a lot to me,'' Boehmer said. ``She is so
ready to dive back in and resume her role as mother, wife,
daughter, sister. All these things in her life have changed. But
she's still Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Mary McCarty by e-mail at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
