<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Keeping the state out of religious affairs in
everyone's best interest
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We feel very strongly, and we hope you would agree, that
appealing along religious lines, or belief in God, is contrary to
the American ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment requires that government neither support
one religion over another, nor the religious over the
non-religious.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words could have been directed at the ``No Pray, No Play''
advocates urging ``spontaneous prayer'' at football games of the
Santa Fe, Texas, high school where student-led prayers over
loudspeakers were ruled unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe is a town of about 8,500 about 30 miles southeast of
Houston. Santa Fe's minority of Jewish, Mormon and Catholic
residents report they feel surrounded by hostile forces in a
religious war.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christian fundamentalists feel the U.S. Supreme Court has
repeatedly demonstrated it does not understand the U.S.
Constitution's ``establishment clause'' that says, ``Congress shall
make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting
the free exercise thereof. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   People who want to mingle government and religion argue that the
words ``separation of church and state'' do not appear in the
Constitution. They're right. But neither do the words ``interstate
commerce,'' ``separation of powers'' or ``right to privacy.'' They
are, however, fundamental constitutional principles.
</P>
<P>
   It was President Thomas Jefferson who first used the expression
``a wall of separation between church and state'' in an 1802 letter
explaining the First Amendment's establishment clause to the
Danbury Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   Many religious fundamentalists work tirelessly trying to force
the government to turn the United States into a Christian nation,
or at least take a supporting role in religion.
</P>
<P>
   The Founding Fathers understood the threat government-sponsored
religion posed for their new nation. That's why they restrained the
government from taking sides in religious matters while giving
rights to citizens to believe or not believe in religion.
</P>
<P>
   President George Washington's administration signed a treaty
with Tripoli in 1797 that declared ``the government of the United
States is not, in any sense, founded on the Christian religion.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the citizens in Santa Fe appear to want to
impose their religious beliefs on citizens who hold minority
beliefs by reciting the Lord's Prayer following the National
Anthem. A similar recitation of the Lord's Prayer took place in
Hattiesburg, Miss., last week without the use of a loudspeaker or
an official leader.
</P>
<P>
   Christian fundamentalists have started a movement to
spontaneously pray at high school football games by reciting the
principal Christian prayer taught by Jesus to his disciples. They
do not care about the feelings of non-Christians, non-believers or
Christians who believe that religious expressions should be
private.
</P>
<P>
   If these public prayers really are spontaneous, and if school
officials really have no role in this spontaneous expression of
personal religious observance, then they might be considered
constitutionally protected free speech.
</P>
<P>
   They also can be considered rude and disrespectful of the
beliefs of others who came only to enjoy a state-sponsored event.
</P>
<P>
   The words at the beginning of this column were not directed to
the ``No Pray, No Play'' fundamentalists. They were sent to Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice-presidential candidate who is
an Orthodox Jew. Lieberman often fills his campaign talks with
``overt expressions'' of his religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The words came from the Anti-Defamation League (ADL), the
world's leading organization fighting anti-Semitism through efforts
that counteract hatred, prejudice and bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
