<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS31-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Kursk tragedy reminds me of a similar incident involving
a U.S. submarine in the '60s. Can you elaborate on that?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're probably remembering the Thresher, a nuclear sub lost
after making a deep dive on April 10, 1963, some 220 miles east of
Cape Cod, Mass. It had 129 men aboard. A Navy court of inquiry
reported in December 1963 that the sinking ``most likely'' was due
to a piping system failure that allowed flooding of the engine
room.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. nuclear-powered sub, the Scorpion, with 99 men
aboard, was lost on May 27, 1968, 400 miles southwest of the
Azores. Officials said in December 1968 that the Scorpion probably
had suffered an implosion (caving in), caused by exceeding crush
depth.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all the fires in our western states, I'm curious: Have
there been fires in the Canadian west as well?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but they haven't been as widespread as in the United
States. ``We really haven't had much of a fire season in Canada,''
said Tom Johnston of the Canadian Interagency Forest Fire Center in
Winnipeg, Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, fires have burned areas in Manitoba, British
Columbia, Ontario, Northwest Territories and northern Saskatchewan.
Most recently, a fierce lightning storm sparked more than 350
forest fires in southeast British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported about two weeks ago that Albert Gore III was
ticketed in North Carolina for speeding 97 miles per hour in a
55-mph zone. What became of that? Has his father commented on this
publicly?
</P>
<P>
   A: The incident occurred Aug. 12. A magistrate released Gore,
17, on $100 bail and ordered a hearing for Sept. 13. Punishment
could be a steep fine and loss of driving privileges in North
Carolina. The only statement came from Camille Johnston,
spokeswoman for Tipper Gore, who said the Gores are dealing with
this ``as a family matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The newspaper reported that ABC is not going to show Monday
Night Football this year in high definition. I bought a high
definition television set a year ago mainly to watch Monday Night
Football, and the picture was absolutely stunning. This seems like
a step backward. What are ABC's plans for this?
</P>
<P>
   A: The network would not tell why it decided not to broadcast
this year's Monday night games in high definition. ``Those are
business reasons we keep to ourselves,'' said Mark Mandel,
spokesman for ABC Sports. ``Next year, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the network had to broadcast the games through two
signals: one in high definition and one for regular TV viewers.
Mandel pointed out that this was expensive, and not enough
consumers yet have high definition sets to make the cost
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We visited the Biltmore Estate in Asheville, N.C., recently
and have two questions. During our tour, one of the rooms was shut
off for the filming of a scene for the sequel to ``Silence of the
Lambs.'' How many movies have been shot at the Biltmore Estate?
Also, while driving around the property, we saw several homes
marked ``Private Residence.'' Who lives there?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both the library and the tapestry room at Biltmore Estate
