<HEADER>
A6105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     08-30 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Wednesday, Aug. 30, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL-MARIJUANA (San Francisco) _ Despite the U.S. Supreme
Court's ruling barring distribution of medicinal marijuana in
California to people whose doctors prescribe it, local cannabis
supporters are optimistic they will win the fight in the long run.
Supporters say they are not quite willing to give up the court
battle. But they concede that the quest to legalize the medical use
of marijuana will most likely be resolved in Congress and the White
House rather than in court. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA and ULYSSESS
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SATS (San Antonio) _ The SAT math scores for Texas high
school students were static though the nationwide scores hit a
30-year high. Educators and business leaders in the state said the
scores show that Texas' education reforms now must move to the high
school level. By EDMUND S. TIJE
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ She calls herself a ``New Democrat,''
standing in the middle of the political road on social and fiscal
issues. He rides his ``Mainstream Express'' tour bus along the
Senate campaign trail, touting himself as a moderate Republican
lawmaker. But the ideological paths of First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and four-term Rep. Rick Lazio in New York's historic Senate
race rarely converge. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCES (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-TRADER (San Francisco) _ A San Jose, Calif., man is free
on bond after being arrested on criminal securities fraud charges
for alleged insider trading. The defendant allegedly netted nearly
$447,000 by buying options on his company's stock after learning it
had won a lucrative contract to work on Microsoft's new video game
console. By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If you want to understand why
relying too much on job interviews is an idiotic way to hire
people, think about one of the all-time favorite interview
questions and how conventional wisdom says you should answer it.
``What's your biggest weakness?''If you ask this and let the
applicant give a pat answer, you're wasting your time. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-APPLE (San Francisco) _ The release of Apple Computer Inc.'s
next-generation Mac OS X is on schedule with its first public test
set for Sept. 13, according to Apple Chief Executive Steve Jobs.
The new operating system, which Jobs called the ``future of the
Macintosh,'' will be released in beta form at Apple Expo in Paris.
The company is on track to release the product to the general
public in early 2001. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-CADILLAC-CATERA (Undated) _ General Motors' luxury-car
brand has never been popular with baby boomers or Generation Xers,
who haven't bought into the gratuitous luxury trappings of
traditional Cadillacs. Which is why GM chose to bring its high-end
midsize sedan, the Catera, to Cadillac showrooms. By G. CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-CADILLAC-ROADSTER (Undated) _ Cadillac's new, as yet
unnamed roadster will be just an extension of the critically
acclaimed Corvette C5 platform that debuted in 1997. But it will be
trimmed in Cadillac regalia and priced to compete against the likes
of the Mercedes-Benz SL 500, Jaguar XK8, BMW's new Z8, and the
forthcoming Lexus SC 430 _ all of which are limited-production
luxury roadsters. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-VOLV0-S60 (Undated) _ Volvo's all-new S60 sedan, set to go
on sale in the United States in November, is a high-end model of
the Toyota Camry or Honda Accord costing $27,075. You can load up
an Accord or Camry to that kind of sticker price, but the Volvo has
a lot more going for it than a mass-produced car like a Camry or
Accord. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-NISSAN-PATHFINDER (Undated) _ Nissan's 2001 Pathfinder
sport-utility vehicle might not exactly qualify as a hot rod. After
all, it is a truck. But with its all-new 240-horsepower V-6 engine,
the midsize Pathfinder has the most powerful standard engine in the
class _ one that has even more power than some V-8s in this
segment. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COWBOY-TOURISM (Bandera, Texas) _ It doesn't take a rope and a
whip to get foreigners to visit Texas, but they sure help. The
traditional tools of cowboys are public relations devices in the
gifted hands of Kevin Fitzpatrick, a trick roper who serves as an
international ambassador for the Lone Star State. By ZEKE
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CRENSHAW (Undated) _ Marshall Crenshaw's legacy might be
as an artist able to give a musical face to everyone except
himself. He's mimicked Buddy Holly, played John Lennon in
Beatlemania, written a documentary score on Yogi Berra and scored a
hit for the Gin Blossoms. Ask most people to name one of his own
songs, however, and they'd be speechless. Crenshaw talks about the
jazzy bend of his latest album, ``No. 447,'' and a reissue of past
works that he hopes will change that. By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (San Francisco) _ The constant emphasis on the San
Francisco 49ers' passing game by the news media and the 49ers
themselves misses the point. The 49ers are a run team. That's what
they do best and that's where the focus of their offense should
lie. If the team wants to eke out every inch of success they can
muster this year, they'll do it by running. By KEVIN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ An Asian-American political
action committee called 80/20 made headlines last weekend when it
endorsed the presidential candidacy of Democrat Al Gore. Even some
Republicans in the nonpartisan group voted to support Gore over
Republican nominee George W. Bush. But before anyone concludes that
Asian Americans lean Democratic, let's examine the endorsement in
political context. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
</TEXT>
