<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV20-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV20  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: CHINESE PORK TENDERLOIN WITH ORZO 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, Sept. 20, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
becoming a client of 20MINUTE-MENUS, contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)  
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Generally a dish of Chinese Pork Tenderloin would be served with
an appropriate Chinese side dish like rice.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the wonderful things about American cooking is that
it can put dishes from any cuisine together if they taste good.
What appeals to me about this combination is the play of the salty,
spicy tenderloin against the creaminess of the Italian dish, pasta
with ricotta, garlic and basil.
</P>
<P>
   These dishes are opposites and they complement each other in
ways Chinese dishes cannot.
</P>
<P>
   The ricotta mellows the Chinese ingredients; the Chinese
ingredients enliven the Italian.
</P>
<P>
   The combination has one drawback: it provides a brown plate. So
I suggest a dish of cherry tomatoes on the side. They will provide
some acidity and lots of color.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE PORK TENDERLOIN
</P>
<P>
   8 dried mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces pork tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   Enough fresh or frozen ginger for 1 tablespoon grated ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon reduced-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoon dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4-cup no-salt-added beef stock
</P>
<P>
   Enough cilantro to yield 1 tablespoon chopped
</P>
<P>
   1. Cover mushrooms with hot water and allow to soften.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut the pork into half-inch thick pieces.
</P>
<P>
   3. Grate the ginger and mix with the soy, vinegar and sherry,
and marinate the pork in that mixture until time to cook.
</P>
<P>
   4. Heat the oil in a nonstick pan large enough to hold all the
ingredients. Reduce heat to medium high and brown the pork on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   5. Drain the mushrooms; coarsely chop and add to the pork.
</P>
<P>
   6. Add the beef stock and the marinade and continue cooking over
low heat until pork is cooked through. If there is too much liquid,
remove pork and boil the sauce until it begins to thicken.
</P>
<P>
   7. Meanwhile wash and chop cilantro and use to decorate the
plate. Serve with ricotta noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ORZO WITH RICOTTA
</P>
<P>
   1 cup orzo
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   Basil to yield 1 tablespoon chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons reduced fat-ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring water to boil in covered pot. Chop garlic. Heat oil in
small skillet and cook garlic for 30 seconds. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash and chop basil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook pasta according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   4. Drain pasta and stir in garlic, basil and ricotta. Season
with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Reduced sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   No-salt-added beef stock
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   Package dried mushrooms (preferably Chinese)
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces pork tenderloin
</P>
<P>
   Bunch cilantro (1 tablespoon)
</P>
<P>
   Box orzo
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (1 tablespoon)
</P>
<P>
   Reduced-fat ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 843 calories, 24 grams fat, 5
grams saturated fat, 110 milligrams cholesterol, 568 milligrams
sodium, 90 grams carbohydrate, 4.1 grams fiber, 58.5 grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
