<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON AND LAZIO SPEAK, BUT DON'T ACT, LIKE CENTRISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LARA JAKES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ She calls herself a ``New Democrat,'' standing in
the middle of the political road on social and fiscal issues. He
rides his ``Mainstream Express'' tour bus along the U.S. Senate
campaign trail in New York, touting himself as a moderate
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But the ideological paths of First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and four-term Rep. Rick Lazio rarely converge.
</P>
<P>
   For all their attempts to claim the political center, Clinton
and Lazio far more represent their respective parties' extremes
than either would likely admit.
</P>
<P>
   On issue after issue _ from abortion rights and health care to
crime and federal spending _ there are stark differences between
the two candidates where political analysts and pundits once
suggested there were none.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, there are differences,'' said Barbara Bartoletti,
state legislative director of the League of Women Voters, a
nonpartisan advocacy group. ``You can look at several issues and
see their differences, whether it's a tax plan or abortion or the
issue of responsible gun legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began running for the Senate in July 1999, while Lazio
entered the race only in May, replacing New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who dropped out amid health and marital woes. The
candidates are vying in a historic race to replace retiring
Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lazio do share common ground in a few areas. Both
ardently favor environmental protection and the death penalty. Both
agree on increasing federal aid to hire more teachers and build new
classrooms, although Lazio only this summer reversed his
long-standing voting record to make way for those education plans.
</P>
<P>
   The most succinct example of their differences is in how Clinton
and Lazio would apportion federal aid. Each has called for at least
modest tax cuts and neither supports dipping into the $2.3 trillion
Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, Clinton generally favors using federal tax
dollars for social programs: expanding health care coverage,
stabilizing low rent for public housing tenants and supplying
economic assistance to needy foreign nations. Lazio, meanwhile,
generally favors distributing federal aid in the form of deep tax
cuts and tax credits. He also supports giving more spending
discretion and control back to states and localities _ a main plank
of the GOP's ``Contract With America'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with fiscal restraint, Lazio reserves judgment on the
$3.8 billion Transportation Bond Act New York voters will face on
November's ballot, fearing it could exacerbate state debt. Clinton
supports the referendum, which will repair crumbling roads and
bridges upstate and pump money into New York City's mass transit
system.
</P>
<P>
   On the matters that party extremists care most about, Clinton
and Lazio do not disappoint their respective ideologues:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lazio disavows flag-burning; Clinton would not vote for a
constitutional amendment to ban it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lazio would hold U.S. senators and representatives to 12 years
of service; Clinton opposes such term limits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lazio has voted against federally funded health insurance for
homosexual and other domestic couples; Clinton supports such
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Only after Lazio entered the race did he openly favor making
attacks on homosexuals a federal crime, legislation that Clinton
has backed for years. And on abortion rights _ perhaps the most
inflammatory campaign topic of all _ Lazio's support is far
scaled-back compared with Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, too, Clinton's proposals to limit firearm sales
go well beyond Lazio's. But gun control is one of the only criminal
justice matters Clinton is willing to discuss, even when pressed.
Lazio's voting record is chock full of purported crime-curbing
measures _ well in line with the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Because New York voters generally favor strong abortion rights
and increased spending on social programs like health care and
education, Clinton appears to have an edge on the issues, political
scientists have said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton has so far failed to break through the 50 percent
ceiling in public opinion polls, suggesting that voters may care
more about the personalities in the race than their stands on
issues.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is one point on which Clinton and Lazio steadfastly
converge, it is in pledging to stick to the issues while bashing
each other personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a citizen's responsibility to go beyond the rhetoric and
get to those differences on where these two stand on the issues,''
Bartoletti agreed. ``There are ideological differences here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
