<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-CADILLAC-ROADSTE     08-30 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CADILLAC-ROADSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CADILLAC ROLLING OUT A BEEFIER SISTER TO THE CORVETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Corvette is about to go upscale. Way upscale.
</P>
<P>
   It will have a new name as well as a new look and a new
(translate: much higher) price. And to justify that higher price,
it will be badged as a Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   But not to fear, Corvette fans; the Chevrolet version won't be
affected, and the Corvette as we know it will continue to exist and
evolve as before.
</P>
<P>
   The new roadster, as yet unnamed, will be just an extension of
the critically acclaimed Corvette C5 platform that debuted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be trimmed in Cadillac regalia and priced to compete
against the likes of the Mercedes-Benz SL 500, Jaguar XK8, BMW's
new Z8, and the forthcoming Lexus SC 430 _ all of which are
limited-production luxury roadsters.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac announced plans for the new roadster at the recent
Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance car show in California, and said
that it would carry over many of the styling cues of the Cadillac
Evoq concept roadster that was unveiled in January 1999 at the
North American International Auto Show in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Evoq concept dramatically demonstrated the promise of
Cadillac's `art and science' vision, and the production version
delivers on that promise,'' Cadillac General Manager Michael J.
O'Malley said. ``As we expand Cadillac's global portfolio, this
expressive roadster will be developed to attract customers in all
important luxury markets, including North America, Europe, Japan
and the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said that it would expand the Corvette factory in
Bowling Green, Ky., to build the new Cadillac roadster alongside
the 'Vette, beginning in August 2002. It will go on sale that fall
as a 2003 model.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hill, chief engineer for the current Corvette generation,
will lead the team developing the Cadillac, which he promises will
be quite different from the 'Vette.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new luxury roadster will be a Cadillac through and
through, blending the very best elements of dynamic styling,
advanced technology and robust performance,'' said Hill, who has 27
years experience with Cadillac even though he has been closely
connected with the Corvette program for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath, the car will ride on the same front engine/rear
transaxle vehicle platform as the current Corvette, but its
exterior, engine and transmission will be completely different.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury roadster will feature several exclusive Cadillac
technologies, GM said, including the 4.6-liter Northstar V-8 in its
first production rear-wheel-drive configuration, mated to an
electronic five-speed automatic transmission with manual mode in a
transaxle configuration like that of the C5.
</P>
<P>
   It will have other elements of the Northstar System, now used in
cars such as the Cadillac DeVille and Seville, including MagneRide
active suspension damping and the StabiliTrak yaw-control system.
The roadster also will have Michelin's revolutionary run-flat PAX
tire system and night vision, a Cadillac technological first
available this year only on the DeVille.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Evoq name (pronounced ``evoke''), though; GM has
endured a lot of good-natured ribbing about the name of the concept
car (a lot of people have redubbed it the ``Ewok''), and has
decided that the production car will be called something else. We
don't know what, yet, however.
</P>
<P>
   Although an exact price hasn't been announced, the vehicles that
the new Cadillac will compete against cost from the low $80,000s
up. Expect the new roadster to be priced somewhere between $75,000
and $85,000, GM officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The big question, of course _ the one that underscores what a
gamble this vehicle will be for General Motors _ is whether enough
consumers will want to ante up 80 grand or more for a car bearing
the Cadillac name.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Cadillac's first attempt at marketing a high-priced,
two-seat roadster. There was the Allante, on the market from 1987
to 1992, a $70,000 two-seater whose body was designed and built by
Pininfarina in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Allante bodies were airlifted aboard Boeing 747 freighters to
Detroit, where final assembly of the vehicles took place.
</P>
<P>
   It also was intended to compete against the Mercedes roadster of
the day, the 560SL. Although the body was beautiful, the car fell
short of its mark in lots of other ways, including performance.
</P>
<P>
   Like all other Cadillac products since 1985, the Allante came
with front-wheel drive, which isn't what consumers expected in such
an expensive car that is supposed to have outstanding performance.
Competing vehicles all had rear drive, the preferred system for
high-end luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   The new Cadillac roadster will have rear-wheel drive, of course,
because it is to be built on the Corvette chassis. But it also
signals the beginning of a switch back to rear-wheel drive for
Cadillac, whose only rear-drive product now is the German
Opel-built Catera midsize sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it isn't a huge sales success, the new roadster is
expected to pave the way for a new, reinvented Cadillac brand
designed to appeal to consumers much younger than the median age of
67 for current Caddy buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of these things that for internal and external
reasons, Cadillac has to go ahead with,'' said Rex Parker, vice
president of AutoPacific Inc., a leading auto-industry consultant
group based in Santa Ana, Calif. ``If BMW is going to do their Z8
roadster and Mercedes is continuing to do its SL, then Cadillac has
no choice if it wants to be a world-class luxury brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether people buy it or not doesn't matter,'' Parker said.
``A manufacturer with pretensions of selling against the BMWs,
Mercedes, Audis and Lincolns of the world is forced into these
things. It's the ultimate rite of passage for Cadillac as it
prepares for its next generation of buyers. They have to do
something, no matter how expensive it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting the new roadster on the Corvette platform is a stroke of
genius, and will mean that the car will be much better executed
than the Allante, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have to be better conceived than the Allante simply
because the Corvette platform is so good,'' he said. ``And why not
build it? GM already has this great platform and a plant that is
way under-utilized.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
