<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-NISSAN-PATHFINDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     2001 NISSAN PATHFINDER COMES WITH MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nissan's 2001 Pathfinder sport-utility vehicle might not exactly
qualify as a hot rod, seeing as though it is, after all, a truck.
</P>
<P>
   But with its all-new 240-horsepower V-6 engine, the midsize
Pathfinder has the most powerful standard engine in the class _ one
that has even more power than some V-8s in this segment.
</P>
<P>
   To get more power than what comes with the Pathfinder, in a
similarly priced vehicle, you would have to choose the biggest V-8
available in the Dodge Durango, and then you still would have just
245 horsepower. You could still top that with a Pathfinder if you
chose a manual transmission, because with the manual, the
Pathfinder's engine cranks out 250 hp.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you could spend $43,000 or more for a V-8 model of the
Mercedes-Benz M-class or $50,000-plus for a BMW X5 and have more
power, but then you'd have to worry about making the mortgage
payment on the house.
</P>
<P>
   For just over $28,000, you can get a two-wheel-drive Pathfinder
with all of this zip, like our test vehicle, the 2001 Pathfinder
SE. Those of you who have older Pathfinders will find this extra
power quite exhilarating, seeing as how the new engine replaces one
that turned out just 170 horsepower. Torque has improved
dramatically, too, now up to 265 foot-pounds from 200.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan says the new Pathfinder will go from zero to 60 mph in
just 8.8 seconds, up from 10.9 seconds in last year's model.
</P>
<P>
   The new V-6 is based on the Nissan VQ 3.0-liter engine used in
the 2000 Maxima, Nissan's flagship sedan. But it has been enlarged
to 3.5 liters for the Pathfinder, and it was designed specifically
for sport-utility applications, with emphasis on higher torque at
the lower end of the power spectrum for off-road and trailer-towing
duties.
</P>
<P>
   With its aluminum block (35 pounds lighter than the cast-iron
block in the previous 3.3-liter V-6) and other improvements, Nissan
has been able to improve the efficiency and therefore the fuel
economy of this engine so that even with all of the extra power,
the EPA fuel-economy ratings are the same as last year's _ 16 miles
per gallon in the city and 19 on the highway (with automatic
transmission).
</P>
<P>
   Many of the engine improvements were designed to reduce noise,
vibration and harshness _ NVH in auto-engineering language. That
has helped to make the Pathfinder one of the most refined SUVs in
this class.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the 1999 model year, the Pathfinder got a
refreshed exterior, but the vehicle's styling remains much like it
was when the current generation was introduced in 1996. The
exterior continues unchanged this year. The changes that came in
the mid-99 models brought a bolder, more aggressive appearance to
the vehicle, with a higher hood, multi-parabola headlights, special
grille designs and a muscular front fascia.
</P>
<P>
   There are some improvements inside for 2001, including a
restyled instrument panel and new center console.
</P>
<P>
   Even the four-speed automatic transmission is new, featuring
Nissan's ``Duette'' electronic control system for seamless
shifting. The automatic is standard on entry-level XE and uplevel
LE models, while it is optional on the midlevel, sportier SE model.
For performance addicts, the SE comes with a five-speed manual
gearbox, which can be a lot of fun with all of the extra
horsepower. (Remember than the Ford Mustang GT has only 260
horsepower with its V-8 engine. Of course, it weighs less than the
Pathfinder, so it has a bit more zip.)
</P>
<P>
   All Pathfinder models are available with shift-on-the-fly
four-wheel drive, which can be engaged at speeds up to 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Ride comfort is outstanding in the Pathfinder, due in large part
to its monoframe construction. Like such vehicles as the Jeep Grand
Cherokee and Lexus RX 300, this arrangement combines body, floor
and frame into one piece, like a car. Most other SUVs are pure
trucks, with body-on-frame designs.
</P>
<P>
   For everyday family use and highway trips, the Pathfinder is
hard to beat. Roadhandling is fairly decent for a sport-utility,
again due in large part to the monoframe construction.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-inch aluminum-alloy wheels with unique designs for each
model are standard on the 2001 Pathfinder, along with mud- and
snow-rated steel-belted radial tires. Antilock brakes are standard
throughout the model lineup, along with power rack-and-pinion
steering.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's Infiniti luxury-car division sells its own version of
the Pathfinder called the QX4, but even the Pathfinder has a full
complement of premium equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Ours came with the automatic transmission, a fantastic
six-speaker Bose audio system with six-disc in-dash CD changer
(including steering-wheel controls), air-conditioning, halogen fog
lights, rear wind deflector, power windows/mirrors/door locks (with
remote control), cruise control, heated sideview mirrors,
titanium-tinted gauges, padded center armrest with dual-level
storage, retractable cargo cover to help keep your luggage secure,
leather-wrapped tilt steering wheel, 12-volt power outlets up
front, in the center console and in the rear, reclining 60/40 split
rear seat, variable windshield wipers, electric rear defroster and
wiper, and a flip-out rear liftgate glass.
</P>
<P>
   The test vehicle came with a few options to dress it up,
including an interior package ($1,799) that added leather seating
surfaces, power front bucket seats, simulated leather door trim,
and side air bags for the front occupants; and the SE sunroof
package ($1,099) that brought a power sliding glass sunroof, dual
illuminated visor mirrors, Homelink universal garage-door opener,
and a digital temperature gauge/compass.
</P>
<P>
   Base price for the SE two-wheel-drive model is $28,349 plus $520
transportation. Our test car's sticker totaled $31,767, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Premium unleaded fuel is recommended, which will add to the cost
of operation of the new Pathfinder. Last year's model ran on
unleaded regular.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
