<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-VOLVO-S60-HNS &LR;      08-30 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-VOLVO-S60-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VOLVO THINKS OUTSIDE THE BOXINESS WITH NEW MIDSIZE SEDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Volvo is out to get more of your business, especially if you're
in the market for a high-end model of the Toyota Camry or Honda
Accord.
</P>
<P>
   Ante up just a few bucks more, and you can drive the newest and
most affordable midsize Volvo rather than a boring Camry or Accord,
Volvo officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the all-new S60 sedan, introduced recently in Sweden and
set to go on sale at U.S. Volvo dealerships in November with a base
price _ well-equipped _ of $27,075, including $575 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   You can load up an Accord or Camry to that kind of sticker
price, but Volvo believes that many consumers would rather have one
of its cars if the price were similar. I know I would. Besides the
inherent safety that comes with a Volvo, it has a lot more going
for it than a mass-produced car like a Camry or Accord.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Volvo expects the S60 to become its biggest seller
in the United States, with projected sales of 35,000 units for
2001, this car is not going to be in everyone's driveway, and
that's always a big plus for me. I've never been one to go with the
flow and buy what everyone else is buying; I prefer to drive
something that is a bit different, and perhaps even a lot more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'll concede that not many people equate Volvo with fun,
because this is a brand that has built its reputation worldwide on
such solid and sensible attributes as safety and longevity. In the
past, the cars have been boxy and rather dull performers, but in
the past two or three years, Volvo has taken great steps to shed
its stodgy image.
</P>
<P>
   The new S60 is about the sportiest-looking Volvo in decades at a
reasonably affordable price, although company officials are quick
to point out that it is a sporty car, not a sports car.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are flat and boring body panels; everything on the S60 is
curved or creased, giving it the most exciting Volvo styling yet.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hood, there will be three engine choices, ranging from
a more-than-adequate naturally aspirated 168-horsepower, 2.4-liter
five-cylinder, to a light-pressure turbo version of this engine
rated at 197 horsepower, to the top-of-the-line 2.3-liter
high-pressure turbo that cranks out 247 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that could be a problem as far as Volvo's safety
record goes. Turn a lot of people loose in a sporty sedan with 247
horsepower, and they might not be driving as safely and sanely as
the average middle-age female Volvo driver of days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be able to buy the S60 with a five-speed manual
transmission if you want to have more driving fun, and even if you
decide you need an automatic, there will be an optional five-speed
automatic with Geartronic manual clutchless shifting in addition to
the regular five-speed automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath, the S60 shares about 60 percent of its components _
including engines and transmissions _ with the luxury S80, Volvo's
$36,000-plus full-size sedan. That's a plus for consumers, because
you're essentially getting a more expensive car than you're paying
for. In fact, the S60 even bears a strong resemblance to the S80.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the car is designed to hold five adults quite
comfortably, and as usual, safety abounds. Driver and front
passenger get front and side air bags, while rear outboard
passengers have the safety benefits of a side-curtain air bag for
side-impact protection. Anitlock brakes are standard.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by length, the S60 is the smallest in the midsize class
at 180.2 inches long. That's more than eight inches shorter than
the Camry and Accord, and 17 inches shorter than the Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   But interior volume is on par with the competitors, keeping the
S60 in the midsize class.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this car really is sporty enough to give Volvo a big
boost out of the boxy-car syndrome will be up to the consumers, but
achieving the sales goal shouldn't be all that difficult _
considering that Toyota, Honda and Ford sell 300,000 to 400,000 of
their respective midsize cars each year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
