<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6131 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-CADILLAC-CATERA-     08-30 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CADILLAC-CATERA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EUROPE HELPS MAKE CATERA ANYTHING BUT A CADILLAC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors' luxury-car brand has never been popular with
baby boomers or Generation Xers, who haven't bought into the
gratuitous luxury trappings of traditional Cadillacs _ that cheap,
Las Vegas-giltzy stuff that starts falling off after a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Cadillac has been moving away from that silly
pseudo-luxury stuff for several years now, having seen its share of
the market fall dramatically over the past decade or so as affluent
boomers and Generation Xers have shown preference for European and
Japanese luxury vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the larger Cadillacs such as the Seville and the all-new
DeVille have a lot of negativity to overcome in the minds of
younger buyers, which is why GM chose to bring the Catera to
Cadillac showrooms three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Germany by GM's Opel subsidiary, the Catera really is
anything but a Cadillac. It's a version of the Opel Omega, softened
up a bit for the American market, but looking more like a high-end
model of a mainstream midsize sedan such as the Toyota Camry, Honda
Accord or Volkswagen Passat than a luxury car.
</P>
<P>
   GM says the Catera is designed to compete against near-luxury
midsize models such as the Mercedes C280, BMW 328i, Lexus ES300,
Volvo S70 GLT and Lincoln LS.
</P>
<P>
   As far as price goes, that's true. With a base price of $30,860
(plus $640 transportation), the Catera fits into that class, which
starts about $5,000 or more above the high-end models of the Camry,
Accord and Passat.
</P>
<P>
   But even with its European heritage, the Catera faces an uphill
battle with those $30,000-plus competitors, whose brand names are
well-represented in the driveways of affluent, educated people in
the 35-55 age bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Catera has a lot going for it, especially among
consumers who want an American brand (even if it is made in
Germany) with the style and driving characteristics of a premium
European or Japanese sedan.
</P>
<P>
   I can't say that I believe the Catera will take a lot of sales
away from Lexus, Acura, BMW or Mercedes, but it is doing a credible
job of taking sales away from some other brands besides those built
by General Motors (a so-called conquest sale). In a survey of
Catera buyers in 1998, GM found that 45 percent came from non-GM
brands, making the Catera the top conquest vehicle in the GM fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, Catera buyers have been averaging about 10 years
younger than the average age for buyers of Cadillac's other cars
(which is about 60). GM's target age group for the Catera is 35-49,
with average household income of $75,000 or more, primarily
college-educated professional and managerial consumers _ with a
50-50 split of male and female buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The gender split has been close to that 50 percent, as targeted,
although I believe more women than men will like this car.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, while the car has appealing if not exciting
styling, a very functional interior with comfortable seats and lots
of worthwhile amenities, overall performance is not on par with
that of some competitors.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that much like Cadillacs of the past, the
Catera is more of a riders' car than a driver's car. Roadhandling
isn't crisp and precise like that of a BMW or Audi; it's more like
that of a Volvo S70 or Lexus ES 300.
</P>
<P>
   That's not bad; those are fine automobiles. But they just don't
evoke the kind of driving excitement that is found in a driver's
car, and consumer studies have shown that men are more interested
in that kind of performance than women are (although I know there
are many women who like performance-oriented cars, and many men who
couldn't care less about performance).
</P>
<P>
   The Catera is 192 inches long _ about five inches longer than
the Camry and Accord _ and has only one engine available: a
3.0-liter, double-overhead-cam V-6 rated at 200 horsepower and 192
foot-pounds of torque. The only transmission available is a
four-speed automatic.
</P>
<P>
   The car will go from zero to 60 mph in 8.5 seconds, which is a
bit sluggish for this class, and top speed is 125 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Steering isn't as crisp as it could be, probably because of the
old-style recirculating-ball system in the Catera. BMW and Mercedes
held on to recirculating-ball steering for a long time, but
recently shifted to the more precise rack-and-pinion system that
the Japanese use.
</P>
<P>
   One plus for the Catera is its rear-wheel drive, which has
become a rare commodity among midsize premium sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Competing sedans from Lexus, Acura, Volvo, Saab, Volkswagen,
Lincoln and Infiniti come with front-wheel drive. BMW and Mercedes
are still clinging to rear drive. (There are a couple of Lexus
models with rear drive that are close to the price of the Catera,
however, including the GS 300 and all-new IS 300 sedans.) Rear
drive is generally preferred on a performance car because it often
creates better roadhandling.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car was the top-of-the-line Catera Sport, a version
that was introduced in 1999 and continued in 2000 as the sportiest
and most expensive model.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport package is a $2,510 option to the base Catera sedan
that includes such extras as a rear-deck spoiler, special 17-inch
tires and wheels, sport suspension, xenon high-intensity-discharge
headlights, eight-way power front passenger seat, memory driver's
seat and mirrors, heated front seats, exterior and interior special
Sport trim, audible theft-deterrent system and built-in garage-door
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Standard equipment on all Cateras includes eight-way power
driver's seat, front bucket seats, rear bench seat with 40/20/40
folding split to expand trunk capacity, power windows and door
locks with remote control, dual-zone automatic climate control,
front and side-impact air bags for driver and front-seat passenger,
unibody construction (with steel safety cage), four-wheel power
antilock disc brakes, cornering lights, cruise control, rear
defogger, electronic level control, fog lights, leather seats,
power outside mirrors, full-size spare tire, speed-sensitive power
steering, tilt steering wheel, traction control and
twilight-sentinel automatic headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Our test car came with the optional Bose audio system with
built-in AM/FM/weather band/cassette/single-disc CD player in the
dash ($973) and a power sunroof ($995). Total sticker was $35,978,
including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The Catera seats five adults rather comfortably, although with
the front seats pushed as far back as they will go to accommodate
tall people, leg room gets a bit tight for the rear passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The front bucket seats were among the most comfortable I've
tested this year, and the two cup holders that pop out of the
center console hold large soft-drink cups (but not the huge ones).
</P>
<P>
   The instrument panel and dash are simple and straightforward,
with clear, easy-to-read analog gauges and black plastic trim (with
no silly gold-looking trim stuck on that will fall off later). This
is definitely the kind of understated elegance and functionality
that will appeal to sophisticated buyers, the kind that GM is
targeting with the Catera.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
