   GROUND-LEVEL INNOVATION
</P>
<P>
   INNOVATION-IN-WORKPLACE-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ Innovation is hot
these days _ what company doesn't want to be considered innovative?
Unfortunately, many managers often assume that coming up with
creative ideas is somebody else's responsibility. After all, the
innovations that get the most attention are technologies or
services that find huge markets (Post-it notes, online trading) or
that somehow change the rules of the business game (a new
e-purchasing system). This articles offers tips to managers to
create a culture of innovation in the office. By the editorial
staff of the Harvard Management Update newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   TOP 5 PUBLIC SPEAKING ERRORS
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-SPEAKING-MISTAKES-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ Successful
presenters stand up, speak with confidence and passion, and sit
down in the time allotted to the warm applause of the contented
crowd. Unhappy presenters fail because of a huge variety of
individual mistakes, hang-ups and personal tics. Nonetheless, there
are whole categories of similar mistakes that unpracticed speakers
make and that are worth noting in order to avoid. Here are five of
the most common. By the editorial staff of the Harvard Management
Communication Letter.
