<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6148 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-INNOVATION-IN-WORKPLA     08-30 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOVATION-IN-WORKPLACE-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUND-LEVEL INNOVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Aug. 29, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT UPDATE  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Innovation is hot these days _ what company doesn't want to be
considered innovative?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many unit heads and managers often assume that
coming up with creative ideas is somebody else's responsibility.
After all, the innovations that get the most attention are
technologies or services that find huge markets (Post-it notes,
online trading) or that somehow change the rules of the business
game (a new e-purchasing system).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what might be called ground-level innovation _ new
products or processes developed on the shop or office floor _ can
be a powerful competitive weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following example: Managers and employees of
Gardner Merchant, a U.K.-based industrial food-service and catering
company, came up with a number of ideas to boost revenue. They
began profiling the customers at each location and tailoring the
food accordingly. They developed a frequent-flyer-style ``food
miles'' scheme to encourage more patronage of the cafeterias. They
even sponsored cooking demonstrations, which increased cafeteria
patronage 12.5 percent, according to Bob Nelson, author of the book
''1001 Ways to Take Initiative at Work'' (Workman Publishing,
2000).
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips to create a culture of everyday innovation:
</P>
<P>
   TALK TO CUSTOMERS
</P>
<P>
   That's a Marketing 101 lesson, and most business units with
external customers make a point of asking those customers what else
they might need.
</P>
<P>
   But even units such as human resources or maintenance have
customers; they're just inside the organization. How many such
departments ever ask the managers and employees they serve how they
could improve?
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems' famous real-time accounting system got its start
five years ago with one such step. According to Fortune's Thomas A.
Stewart, the company's salespeople were ``fuming'' because expense
reporting was cumbersome and reimbursement slow. The finance
department figured out how to move the process to the Web, thereby
speeding it up and delighting the salespeople. That move led to an
automated commission system, one big step toward real-time
financial reporting.
</P>
<P>
   LISTEN TO EMPLOYEES
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion systems, brainstorming sessions, ``innovation
challenge'' meetings _ there's no shortage of techniques to solicit
innovative ideas from employees.
</P>
<P>
   Set a goal of coming up with ideas for five product
improvements, 10 workable cost-cutting suggestions or three ways to
boost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   In many companies the main challenge isn't coming up with ideas.
It's figuring out whether and how to implement them. Experts
recommend these approaches:
</P>
<P>
   1. Guilty until proven innocent. In a brainstorming session,
every idea is worth writing down. When it comes to selecting,
evaluating and implementing innovative ideas, however, start by
assuming they're all worthless. This avoids wasting time on bad
ones.
</P>
<P>
   2. Not just the usual suspects. It's always tempting to populate
the research-and-evaluation team with people who are the most
knowledgeable in any given area. Trouble is, that's likely to
produce answers based on what these people already know.
</P>
<P>
   David Snowden, director of IBM Corp.'s Institute of Knowledge
Management, suggests mixing in some people who are good at
networking _ people who will ask around outside the group and get
ideas no one has thought of.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH FOR DISRUPTIVE INNOVATION
</P>
<P>
   The ground-level innovator faces the same potential pitfall as
the official new-product developer: Listening to customers and even
employees is likely to generate ideas for more of the same, only
better. Meanwhile, new technology or business practices may be
creating radical alternatives that you hardly notice until they
take away your reason for being.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate print shops and travel departments, for example, may
be great at what they do, yet still fall victim to sophisticated
and less expensive external service providers. But sometimes new
technology can be co-opted and implemented at home, as when a print
shop switches over to the latest desktop-publishing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-level innovation is like a stealth weapon, hardly visible
to competitors. But it may be one armament that distinguishes
victors from vanquished in today's business battles.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
