<HEADER>
A6149 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-PUBLIC-SPEAKING-MISTA     08-30 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-SPEAKING-MISTAKES-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP 5 PUBLIC SPEAKING ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release: Tue., Aug. 29, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Successful presenters stand up, speak with confidence and
passion, and sit down in the time allotted to the warm applause of
the contented crowd. Unhappy presenters fail because of a huge
variety of individual mistakes, hang-ups and personal tics.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there are whole categories of similar mistakes that
unpracticed speakers make and that are worth noting in order to
avoid. Here are five of the most common.
</P>
<P>
   NOT REHEARSING
</P>
<P>
   Lack of rehearsal is the most common mistake business presenters
make.
</P>
<P>
   Professional performers find this lapse in good sense
inexplicable. Musicians practice for hours daily. Actors rehearse
for up to six weeks before a show. And yet, business presenters
say, ``I'll just wing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the four saddest words in the business lexicon. Nine
times out of 10, they lead to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Why not rehearse? Afraid of looking silly? You'll feel much
worse bombing in front of the real crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Are you so nervous that the idea of rehearsing is almost as bad
as the speaking itself? Then you need rehearsal more than most.
Remember, the alternative is worse.
</P>
<P>
   NOT TELLING YOUR AUDIENCE WHY YOU'RE THERE
</P>
<P>
   Audiences come to hear a presentation with one question in their
minds: why are we here?
</P>
<P>
   Don't begin by giving them the information that you've carefully
prepared. Instead, tell them why your material is important. Only
then will they settle in to listen to all the brilliant material
you have to offer.
</P>
<P>
   How long should you spend framing the issue? It depends on how
familiar the audience is with the topic. If you're discussing a
well-known problem, you can dispense with the orientation in a few
minutes. If you're delving into material that's new to them, you
may want to take longer.
</P>
<P>
   INTRODUCING THE TOPIC, EXPLAINING IT, THEN SUMMARIZING WHAT WAS
SAID.
</P>
<P>
   This bit of advice has been a staple of public speaking courses.
The problem is that audiences today are quicker to pick up the
context than they used to be _ and they have shorter attention
spans.
</P>
<P>
   If you begin by giving them a quick summary of what you're going
to say, audiences will spend the time getting settled, scanning
their appointment books or deciding whether to attend another
presentation. Then, when you get to the end and offer a summary,
they'll start to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Endings are crucial for successful public speaking because they
are what people are most likely to remember. Skip the summary and
end with a bang _ something useful and new for the audience.
</P>
<P>
   USING TOO MANY SLIDES
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, probably because PowerPoint has made slide
creation far too easy, listeners everywhere are inundated with
massive numbers of slides.
</P>
<P>
   Slides should be used sparingly to show a powerful visual image
that reinforces a key point.
</P>
<P>
   A barrage of slides misuses the medium. Why? When your audience
is looking at the slide, it's not looking at you. You have lost the
attention of your listeners, even if for only a brief time. You
then must put out a great deal of extra energy to get that
attention back.
</P>
<P>
   Rule of thumb: Limit yourself to one slide every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   USING SLIDES AS A SPEECH OUTLINE
</P>
<P>
   Far too many speakers today create a slide ``deck'' by dumping
all the information they have into slides and, as a result,
presenting an endless show of data.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Word-heavy slides that essentially represent an
outline for the speaker to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But, you say, it's comforting for the presenter. So what's wrong
with presenting the audience with an outline of the speech through
slides?
</P>
<P>
   First, it kills the mystery out of the speech. The audience can
see where the speaker is going and get bored. Also, reading all
those words, and reconciling them with what the speaker actually
says, is tiring.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, the speaker will appear unprepared, and that
is both discourteous to the audience and a signal of disaster to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Don't join the throngs of boring business speakers and dull
presentations. Refuse to follow these surefire rules for failure.
</P>
<P>
   But be warned if you do: You may find your audiences actually
listening to what you have to say.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
