<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6153 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE CAN'T COUNT ON ASIAN-AMERICAN VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An Asian-American political action committee
called 80/20 made headlines last weekend when it endorsed the
presidential candidacy of Democrat Al Gore. Even some Republicans
in the nonpartisan group voted to support Gore over Republican
nominee George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But before anyone concludes that Asian-Americans lean
Democratic, let's examine the endorsement in political context.
</P>
<P>
   The 80/20 committee was started by S.B. Woo, a University of
Delaware physics professor, a former Democratic lieutenant governor
and an unsuccessful U.S. Senate candidate from that small state.
</P>
<P>
   His main issue is Asian-American empowerment through fair
representation in a presidential administration and major private-
and public-sector institutions. It is, in short, a ``glass
ceiling'' issue for well-educated, middle-class Asian-American
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   He recruited such well-known Asian-Americans as Chang-lin Tien,
the former chancellor at the University of California at Berkeley,
and launched an electronic mail campaign that now has an address
list exceeding 300,000 names.
</P>
<P>
   80/20's goal is to funnel 80 percent of the Asian-American
community's votes and financial contributions to the presidential
candidate who has shown the most support for the group's goals. A
committee made up of Democrats, Republicans and independents
debated endorsements over the weekend in Los Angeles. Their choice
was Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the group's endorsement drew national news media
attention indicates growing recognition of Asian-American political
empowerment issues. It would be a mistake, however, to assume
80/20's support of Gore means Asian-Americans will vote
overwhelmingly for the Democrat in November.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-Americans are maddeningly diverse in their political views
and actions and no one has yet been able to rely on significant
bloc votes the way the Democrats can count on African-American
support in presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 80/20 members will try to influence family and
friends, I doubt Gore will get 80 percent of the Asian-American
vote. I cannot think of a reliable way to measure whether 80
percent of Asian-American political contributions will go to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it is doubtful Gore would openly embrace getting
financial support from Asian-Americans, given his continuing
embarrassment over the infamous Buddhist temple fund-raiser four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While I personally like 80/20's presidential choice, there are
other issues to be considered. The Democratic fund-raising scandal,
for one.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American Democratic apparatchiks were stung when their
party questioned their loyalty after media and congressional
revelations of questionable Asia-based contributions to the
Clinton-Gore re-election campaign in 1996. In fact, a handful of
Asian-American Democratic operatives have been caught holding the
bag while Democratic big-shots like Clinton, Gore and party
higher-ups have escaped, relatively unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the Clinton administration's Justice
Department is pursuing the prosecution of Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born
computer scientist and U.S. citizen accused of mishandling
sensitive nuclear secrets and suspected of being a spy for China.
The Lee case has become a cause celebre among many 80/20 supporters
who, like Lee, are Asian immigrant scientists and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Third, while the Clinton-Gore administration supports continuing
``engagement'' with China, some Democrats have been openly hostile
to China over human-rights issues. In fact, Rep. David Wu, D-Ore.,
has lost some support among Chinese-Americans because of his stance
on China.
</P>
<P>
   These oddities don't mean 80/20 should have gone for Bush, even
though many Asian-Americans say they share similar ``family
values'' with Republicans. Some Republican leaders are as vehement
in their anti-China rhetoric and action as certain prominent
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Republican Party has nurtured leaders who have
shown a mean streak toward immigrants, including those from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: 80/20's endorsement of Gore makes for lively
political fodder, but one group's action isn't necessarily going to
sway many Asian-Americans one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
