<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS AN EDGY DAY FOR PATRIOTS ROOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was a Sunday morning in late August,
usually the quietest time of the week. A time to go to church, to
head to the beach or lake, to lounge in the yard, to nibble on
breakfast while perusing the Sunday papers.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few young men in Foxborough, those usually placid
hours were a time of angst. There was no football game, just a
wait. A wait to learn whether the direction of their lives would be
reversed 180 degrees. Boyhood dreams realized _ or perhaps gone
forever.
</P>
<P>
   They are football players. Last Sunday was the day the Patriots,
as well as 30 other National Football League teams, made the final
reductions to their squads. Those reductions are called ``cuts,'' a
most apt word, since cuts bring blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in my room at the End Zone Motel (in Foxborough),'' said
rookie wide receiver Dane Looker. ``My wife and I woke up about
8:30 in the morning, and I don't think I stopped staring at the
phone the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   A phone call would be catastrophe, Looker knew. His family was
back home in Washington state, three hours behind Foxborough time,
``and I knew if anybody called that early in the morning, it
wouldn't be anybody from the Left Coast,'' said Looker. ``It was
5:30 in the morning back there.''
</P>
<P>
   A phone call could only be bad news. A phone call would bring a
voice from Foxboro Stadium with instructions to bring his playbook
with him for a meeting with the coach.
</P>
<P>
   So Looker stared at the phone for nearly three hours. His wife
was with him, and she was scheduled to leave for home that night.
If the phone rang, Looker might be on the plane with her. Or on
another plane headed in another direction to another football team
where he would have to start all over. Already this summer, Looker
had had to start twice, first in St. Louis with the Rams and then
in New England with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times,'' said Looker, ``I thought I heard phantom
phone rings.''
</P>
<P>
   But the phone never rang. And, around noon, as anxious rookies
arrived at Foxboro Stadium, glancing at other anxious rookies,
Looker finally learned his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it really hit me that I'd made it until later in
the day,'' said the rookie. ``When you're around here, there are a
lot of guys who didn't make it, and you don't want to show any
emotions to make them feel bad. I finally took it in when I was
back with my wife at the End Zone Motel.''
</P>
<P>
   Looker recalled thinking, ``Finally. It seems like the longest
half a year in my life was finally over. Finally, it came to a
climax, and it was an amazing feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonie Paxton had a different reaction Sunday morning. Paxton is
a rookie long snapper from Sacramento State, and the combination of
``rookie'' and ``long snapper'' and ``Sacramento State'' put him
foremost on the list of the NFL's Most Endangered Species. Usually,
long snappers are grizzled veterans who not only snap the ball on
punts and kicks but can play some other position in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton is a long snapper. Period.
</P>
<P>
   He is a very good long snapper, one who sends laser beams back
to the punter or holder, snaps so crisp and sharp that Patriot
kicker Adam Vinatieri senses that he gets off his kicks a crucial
fraction of a second quicker than in previous years ``because Lonie
gets the ball back there so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday morning, Paxton recalled, he was not worried. ``This
was already a dream come true for me, just to be with an NFL team
in camp,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back on draft day in April, when Paxton had a backyard barbecue
to watch the draft, Paxton and his father cried when the phone call
came from New England and he was told that the Patriots wanted to
sign him as an undrafted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Were there calls from other teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``One was enough,'' said Paxton. ``I didn't want any more. One
call _ the Patriots _ that was enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxton said he decided to take Sunday morning ``hour by hour''
as he awaited his fate. ``It wouldn't have hurt my feelings too bad
because it's all been pleasant feelings just being here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his dream was so close.
</P>
<P>
   And when Paxton arrived at the stadium, he still didn't know. So
the rookie went to a team meeting and found out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess anybody who was left in there at the meeting,'' said
Paxton, ``was left in there. And then I went to our (special teams)
meeting and they told me, `Congratulations.' So I figured that was
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Tom Brady already had seen big-time football, having
played in college at Michigan, with 107,000 fans watching his every
pass at Ann Arbor. But last Sunday morning, Brady found himself
with a group of anxious rookies, few of whom knew whether they were
staying or going.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really wasn't nervous,'' said Brady, even though the
Patriots clearly had three quarterbacks already in front of him.
``The approach I took was that I had the ability to play in the
NFL, and hopefully my coaches had seen it. And hopefully I would
make it. And if they didn't want me, I would go somewhere else and
play football. That's because I'm confident in what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady, like the other rookies, found out at noon that he had
made the team. Once again, Brady's emotions were different from
those of some other rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking this wasn't the end but the beginning,''
he said. ``Just because I made the team is no guarantee that I'll
be here next week. I have to go out and earn my keep every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Shockmain Davis, a rookie free agent like Looker, spent Sunday
morning wondering ``if I was going to have to go somewhere and
start all over again. I didn't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis admittedly was nervous but steeled himself to come to the
stadium ``and take the news as best as possible.'' On one hand,
said the wide receiver, ``I knew I couldn't worry about it too much
because things happen. So I just tried to prepare myself for the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   And, at noon, Davis learned he had made the Patriots, learning
the best of news ``when the coaches didn't call me in. If the
coaches called you in, that means you was done. If the coaches
didn't call you in, that was good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
