<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$600,000 LIFESTYLE WON'T COME AUTOMATICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My goal is to retire at 60 at a level somewhat equal to the
lifestyle we are accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   W.K., Weston, Conn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yours is not all that different from most other people's
problems _ if I just divide everything by 10, I'm in familiar
territory. As the blues singer Big Bill Broonzy used to say,
retiring on your current savings with no impact on your lifestyle
is just a dream, just a dream you've got on your mind.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the budget and inflation. In six years, you
will need $737,553 to buy what $600,000 buys today, provided
inflation averages 3.5 percent annually. That means you would have
to draw $657,553 from your investments, which currently total
$3,567,500. If your portfolio averages 10 percent growth in the
next six years, it would reach $6,483,668 _ meaning you would have
to achieve returns slightly in excess of 10 percent. (That
calculation presumes reinvestment of dividends from your taxable
portfolio.) Even if your investment portfolio could reach that
$6.48 million level, it's unlikely it could do anything to protect
you against inflation in your later years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this doesn't include any portfolio additions in the
next six years. If you were to add $10,000 a month, the portfolio
would reach $7,464,750 _ again, not enough to prudently support
withdrawals at the level you seek. (You could withdraw $54,796 a
month, and the pool would last nearly 30 years, presuming overall
investment returns of 8 percent, but that ignores the fact that
after 10 years of your retirement, you will need $1,040,391 a year
to maintain your current $600,000 lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of things you can do, of course. The primary one
is to save as much as possible while you are working. Next comes
reducing your expectations. Third would be to get a financial
adviser to come up with specific plans and realistic income
projections, and to diversify more broadly your portfolio, which is
dominated by large-cap stocks _ unless your common stock portfolio
varies substantially from your tax-deferred positions. Finally,
despite your substantial wealth, you should begin establishing a
fixed-income portfolio that can predictably deliver some of the
substantial cash you will require.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to have $40,000 to supplement Social Security, plus
have a portion of my investment provide growth potential. My funds
are currently with Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Payson, Ariz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If your money is in one of Vanguard's money market funds, you
are already getting the desired income stream, although not much in
the way of growth. If I had to stick with Vanguard, I'd put a
quarter of the money into Vanguard GNMA, currently yielding 6.85
percent, and the rest in Vanguard Balanced Index, with a 3.14
percent yield.
</P>
<P>
   The latter fund holds 58 percent of its portfolio in stocks,
indexed in an effort to match the results of the Wilshire 5000
Index, the broadest index of stocks in captivity, roughly
equivalent to the stock market as a whole. But like most broad
indexes, it's dominated by large-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It should certainly provide plenty of long-term growth, though,
and combined with the GNMA position, the investment in Vanguard
Balanced Index would yield $40,675 a year. You could then reinvest
any capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not limited to Vanguard, go with a five-year jumbo CD
for that first $250,000. The current national high rate is 7.81
percent, which would mean a difference of $2,400 a year on a
$250,000 investment, compared to Vanguard GNMA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have been talking to a few people about switching to a Roth
IRA. Some say I can take the money out after five years without tax
or penalty. Others told me it is better to leave it alone, because
the tax and penalty would reduce my current account by about half.
I am not thinking of touching this account until I retire. What
should do?
</P>
<P>
   H.T., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer requires answers to other questions. First, let me
clear up some confusion. It is true that both the principal in a
Roth IRA and any earnings can be withdrawn tax-free at the option
of the owner. But this can be done without penalty only after the
owner has reached age 59 1/2 or has held the money being withdrawn
in the account for five years _ whichever comes second. Thus a
person of your age could not withdraw the money without penalty at
age 40, nor could a person who is aged 59 put money in a Roth IRA
and withdraw it without penalty until age 64.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if you transfer your IRA to a Roth you would pay no
penalty, but would pay taxes owed as if the amount transferred were
earned income. There is no penalty that stems from transferring
from a traditional IRA to a Roth account, unless you made the
unfortunate move of simply withdrawing the funds and then putting
the allowed maximum new contribution (up to $2,000 a year) in a
Roth account. So it's important the transaction be a transfer and
not a withdrawal. You should have no problem, especially if you
simply transfer the funds from one kind of account to the other
within the same institution.
</P>
<P>
   Those matters aside, the first question that arises concerns
your future income. If you think you will be in a lower tax bracket
in retirement than you are now, you would be better off sticking
with the traditional IRA. Conversely, if you are saving
aggressively for retirement and expect to be well fixed at that
point, the Roth will give you a great advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Another question is how you are saving. If you are using
conservative accounts such as bank programs, this will not make a
great deal of difference. But if you have a typical retirement
savings program, relying heavily on stocks, with a few aggressive
investments, the Roth can offer a wonderful advantage. You would
want to put your most aggressive investments _ which are
accordingly the ones upon which you expect the greatest long-term
gains _ in the Roth accounts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, say your retirement savings consist of a core
holding such as a Standard and Poor's Index fund, a balanced fund
that holds stocks and bonds, and two more-aggressive holdings _
let's suppose these include a health care stock fund and a
technology stock fund. Since you can expect these last two to
produce the greatest long-term gains, these are best held in a Roth
account.
</P>
<P>
   Next, if either you or your wife has a 401(k) plan or any other
tax-deferred retirement savings, holding some of your retirement
savings in a Roth IRA will offer you a great deal of flexibility in
managing your taxes in retirement. It's a pool of money you can
keep aside or draw upon without tax consequences, allowing you to
manage your tax-deferred and taxable accounts to best advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the younger you are and the wealthier you expect to
become, the greater the chances the Roth IRA will work to your
advantage. Moreover, the Roth account offers another protection,
which is that by the time that you are retired, tax rates in
general might be higher than they are now.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to answer these questions for yourself. Bear in
mind that if you use some of the traditional IRA balance to pay the
taxes that are due from the transfer, that amount is treated as a
withdrawal and accordingly is subject to a 10 percent penalty for
premature withdrawal, as well as being subject to tax. You might
decide to budget the transfers over the course of a number of
years, to keep you in the same tax bracket and give you a chance to
earn the money to pay the taxes that result from the transfers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6167 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RETAIL-TIMBERLAND-BOS     08-30 1935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-TIMBERLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMBERLAND TESTS `COMMUNITY STORE' CONCEPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Part social experiment, part listening post, a new
Timberland store in a city neighborhood long avoided by many
mainstream retailers aims to prove that doing well and doing good
are inextricably linked.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, shopper Greg Gaskins isn't much interested in
social experiments. He's browsing the store for size-15 shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're super comfortable,'' the contract worker says of
Timberland footwear. ``And they're super durable.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, black city residents such as Gaskins have
emerged as some of Timberland's best customers.
</P>
<P>
   That came as a bit of a surprise to a New Hampshire company best
known for $145 yellow boots and pricey outdoor gear, but not to
Calvin Johnson, a local businessman who is a part owner of the new
Timberland store.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood residents ``want good retail merchandise, not some
garbage,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly to learn more about the fashion preferences of
urban blacks and partly to advance a do-good social agenda that led
Timberland Co. to test what it calls a ``community store.''
</P>
<P>
   In a formula that may be unique, the store is a three-way
collaboration that teams Timberland with Johnson's company, Urban
Hospitality, which operates an Athlete's Foot store.
</P>
<P>
   The third member of the team is Community Impact, a group that
distributes scholarships to neighborhood students. Plans call for a
permanent profit-sharing arrangement between the store and the
scholarship fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gaskins is more interested in shoes than scholarships at the
moment. What impresses him is Timberland's breadth of selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have sizes that fit,'' he marvels.
</P>
<P>
   Buying shoes wasn't always so easy in this part of town. A
decade ago, most neighborhood retailers were ``liquor stores and
Chinese carryouts,'' Johnson says. To buy most things, residents
had to get in a car or get on a bus, and most of the dollars earned
by the community wound up being spent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the goals of the community store, which opened in
December _ to keep dollars in the neighborhood where the store does
business.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington store is the first to open using the new concept.
Similar stores may soon open in Cleveland and Detroit, and if
Timberland can find the right site and the right local partners,
Boston could see a community store some day.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Timberland hopes the community-store concept can
evolve into a franchising program.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the Washington store seems small and not very
unusual. On the back wall are Timberland boots and casual shoes.
Also on display are the clothing lines that have given the company
a lift at a time when many rivals are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   It's what customers can't see that may make this store unique,
according to the Initiative for Competitive Inner Cities, a
Boston-based group that studies the impact of the retailing
business on poor urban neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy booming, many national chains, especially
pharmacies, have begun to open stores aggressively in Roxbury,
Harlem, and Chicago's South Side, ICIC claims.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington shopping center where the Timberland store opened
may be evidence of this trend. Other tenants include a Safeway
supermarket, a Hollywood Video, and an Athlete's Foot store that
Johnson's company owns.
</P>
<P>
   But if many national chains are coming into the city, Timberland
may be the only retailer so far to set up a permanent
profit-sharing arrangement with the neighborhood it serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach could be unique,'' says ICIC executive vice
president Anne Habiby, who notes that retailers often have been
criticized for taking money out of poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing well by doing good'' is something Timberland has tried
to practice for many of the 48 years the Swartz family has been
associated with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in how a business can be a vehicle for social
justice,'' says chief executive Jeffrey B. Swartz, 40, the third
generation of his family to head Timberland.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Swartzes control half its stock, the company has
been traded publicly for nearly 15 years, and social goals have to
be pursued at the same time shareholders are kept happy.
</P>
<P>
   As Jeffrey Swartz sees it, doing well and doing good aren't
competing goals. Rather, when properly linked, they reinforce each
other. The thinking is that some consumers will reward a company
deemed socially responsible by purchasing its products.
</P>
<P>
   Given its modest sales projections, Timberland's community store
is unlikely to have much immediate top-line impact on a company
whose annual sales should exceed $1 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making footwear and clothing, Timberland operates 60
full-price stores and 90 outlet stores. In 1999, retail accounted
for a quarter of its $917.2 million in total revenues. The
community store is Timberland's third retail category.
</P>
<P>
   If a community store won't immediately give a major boost to
sales, it still could provide Timberland with something of value _
information about an important group of customers.
</P>
<P>
   By teaming up with a local businessman and by staffing the store
with young people from the neighborhood, Timberland hopes to gain
all sorts of insights into urban black consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' says Greg Taylor, executive director of
Community Impact. ``Calvin (Johnson) is going to help them learn
about urban (fashion) trends. Calvin is going to give them
information on how to better market to the inner city.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about five years ago that Timberland realized many black
consumers were embracing its boots as a fashion statement, and to
this day Swartz says he still isn't sure why.
</P>
<P>
   Though Timberland sometimes ran ads with such slogans as ``Give
racism the boot'' and though it was an early supporter of City Year
Inc., the self-described ``urban Peace Corps,'' the company never
deliberately set out to woo black consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly or wrongly, Swartz says, Timberland focused on the
quality of its product, figuring that if it made superior footwear,
consumers would respond.
</P>
<P>
   But following a mid-1990s slump, Timberland began paying more
attention to marketing and to its best customers.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressively marketing to urban black consumers could have an
additional payoff. As sneaker-maker Nike Inc. and many others have
learned, black teenagers often start fashion trends. Get young
blacks to wear your products, and affluent young suburbanites
sometimes will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Timberland become more attentive to marketing since
its rare money-losing year in 1995, it also has tried to reposition
itself. Instead of just a bootmaker, it now wants to be seen as a
``global lifestyle brand.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Timberland has placed more emphasis on clothing,
which now accounts for about 20 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Timberland has launched some ``sub-brands.'' One is
Mountain Athletics, which aims at off-road joggers and mountain
bikers. Another new line called Trek Travel targets the growing
segment of consumers who take ``adventure vacations'' such as
African safaris and hikes in the Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
   When companies attempt to reposition themselves or chase fashion
trends, they sometimes leave their customers confused. But
Timberland seems to be managing.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Timberland's recent success is because ``consumers know
what Timberland stands for,'' says Bob McGee, editor of Sporting
Goods Intelligence, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland's performance now outpaces an industry that is mostly
seeing 2 percent or 3 percent annual growth. Last year, Timberland
posted 6.4 percent sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   The move toward casual clothing has hurt many midprice shoe
companies, but high-end brands such as Timberland are doing much
better, says William Boettge, president of the National Shoe
Retailers Association.
</P>
<P>
   While others plod along, Timberland's 1999 profits rose 27
percent to $75.25 million. Recent quarterly earnings were even more
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Such success has given Jeffrey Swartz the opportunity to pursue
his goal of making Timberland an agent for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission now is to equip people to make a difference in the
world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics may sneer that tying a business to a social cause has
become a highly effective marketing technique of late.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Cone won't dispute that. Her firm, Cone Communications of
Boston, advises clients, including Timberland, on how to practice
so-called cause-related marketing. When so many products seem
similar, cause-related marketing is one way for one company to
stand out from a crowd of me-too rivals, she says.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many companies have jumped on the bandwagon,
but Cone says social values were already part of Timberland's
philosophy when she began advising the company in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot of companies, it's `Oh, God, we have to do this
because everyone else is doing it,' '' Cone says of cause-related
marketing. ``With Timberland, it's in the corporate DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   City Year can attest to Timberland's long involvement with
social issues. In 1989, few people had ever heard of the group. So
cofounder Alan Khazei concentrated early fund-raising efforts on
Boston companies and didn't expect to get much of a response from
Timberland, which by then was based in Stratham, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   To Khazei's surprise, Timberland instantly agreed to supply City
Year with work boots. True, Timberland has Boston roots. Previously
known as Abington Shoe Co., it made shoes in the South End before
moving to New Hampshire in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But Khazei says he thinks one reason for Timberland's immediate
generosity was that Swartz was so receptive to City Year's message
of community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like pushing on an open door,'' Khazei says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he says, Timberland has given City Year about
$10 million in either cash or product donations, making Timberland
the group's largest private contributor, and Swartz now chairs City
Year's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland's contributions to City Year soon could get larger.
Last year in Philadelphia, Timberland debuted a special edition of
its yellow boot in City Year's signature red color. The ``Red Boot
Collection,'' which includes some apparel offerings, soon will roll
out in selected urban markets. Khazei says a portion of the profits
from the Red Boot Collection will be shared with City Year.
</P>
<P>
   As Khazei notes, the Swartz family likes to sum up its three
generations at Timberland with the phrase, ``Boot, brand, belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Swartz was responsible for the famous Timberland boot.
Son Sidney W. Swartz made the boot into a brand. And now it's up to
grandson Jeffrey B. Swartz to deliver on the belief that a business
can be a force for social change.
</P>
<P>
   Timberland's latest effort at social change is the community
store in Washington. To be successful, it must be a win-win for all
three members of the team behind it _ Timberland, Johnson, and
Community Impact. Take profits out of the equation, and the
ambitious social goals that ride on the store cannot be attained,
team members stress.
</P>
<P>
   At ICIC, Habiby knows what a valuable asset a healthy retailer
can be to a poor city neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retail is the first visible sign that a neighborhood is
connected to the rest of the economy,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   To Timberland, retail means more.
</P>
<P>
   Says Swartz, ``We think a store can be a tool for social
engineering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
