u l BC-BASEBALL-CLUBBIE-ART-     08-30 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-CLUBBIE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (Attn.: N.Y.; l and s coding)  
 IN THE CLUBHOUSE, HE'S THE CLEANUP MAN  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. _ Had Andrew ``Woody'' Wittman's summer job been
advertised, the pitch might have gone like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Work from early June to Labor Day washing uniforms, organizing
sports equipment, preparing food, running errands, etc.
Fourteen-hour workdays common. Total of three days off. Lots of bus
travel. Pay: about $8 per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd heard about Clubbies, but I didn't know what they did,''
muses the 21-year-old senior at the State University of New York at
Albany. ``I didn't know about the hours, that's for damn sure. I
think they made certain not to tell me about the hours.'' Then he
smiles an I'm-a-little-wiser-now smile.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Wittman is serving his first and perhaps last season as
clubhouse manager of the Lowell Spinners, the popular (33 straight
sell-outs) ``short season-A'' affiliate of
</P>
<P>
   the Red Sox that plays in sweet little Edward A. LeLacheur Park,
hard by the Merrimack River. As the team's Clubbie, he does
everything from washing seven or so loads of laundry a day _ each
player has a home, away, and practice ``uni'' _ to making sure no
one runs short of sunflower seeds on which to munch during games.
</P>
<P>
   It was not how he planned to spend his summer. A political
science major who was raised in Middletown, N.Y., in a family of
Yankees worshipers, Wittman had only vague job plans when he was
approached in late April about the position via a circuitous
connection to Spinners trainer Keith Johnson. A little more than a
month later, he found himself tending to the needs of a couple
dozen entry-level professionals, ages 19 to 23, young men not too
different from himself who don't have major-league egos and
probably never will: Of the 141 players who performed for Lowell in
the four seasons prior to this one, only two have made it briefly
to the Red Sox, and both _ Wilton Veras and Steve Lomasney _ are
back in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting here because we're contending for a pennant,''
Wittman says of life among the Spinners, who were one and a half
games out of first place in the McNamara Division of the New
York-Pennsylvania League going into Tuesday night's game. ``But I'd
like to get back to my girlfriend and my friends. This work wears
on me, it really does.''
</P>
<P>
   He literally eats and sleeps the job, dining and living like the
players themselves on the neighboring campus of the University of
Massachusetts at Lowell. His office is the team's equipment room, a
windowless rectangle tucked beneath the grandstand and packed with,
among many other things, washers, dryers, bats, baseballs,
oversized coolers filled with thirst quenchers, and brightly
colored Canaligator outfits worn by the team's mascot. ``It's my
palace,'' Wittman says of the cluttered room, flashing a wry smile
again.
</P>
<P>
   Being a Clubbie is something of an entrepreneurial gig. Wittman
is paid $500 a month by the Spinners' front office, but himself
collects two dollars per day from each player and coach, who are
Red Sox employees. He also operates the soda machines in both the
home and visiting teams' clubhouses _ charging the out-of-towners
25 cents more per can than the locals _ and reaps their profits. He
figures to gross something over $7,000 this summer, or about $2,300
per month and around $8 per hour. (Spinners players earn only $850
per month.) Since there's little time or opportunity to spend this
stash _ and since he receives free room and board both in Lowell
and on the road _ Wittman will take most of it home come Labor Day.
``Maybe I'll open an IRA,'' he says, and he's serious.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll earn it. Arnold Beyeler, the 36-year-old manager of
the Spinners who never saw the big leagues as a player but has
observed a Clubbie or two in his career, defines Wittman's job in
simple terms: ``You want someone who's always around when you need
him and gets the unis dry.'' Then he adds: ``Woody does a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   On days in which the Spinners play at home, doing a good job
means piloting his vaguely maroon 1987 Buick Century 18 miles north
to BJ's Wholesale Club in Nashua, N.H. It is there that Wittman
purchases the all-important ``Spread,'' i.e. the
post-batting-practice clubhouse repast he prepares for Spinners
players and coaches. ``This is my twenty-third trip here,'' he
declares at BJ's on a recent Saturday afternoon as he fills his
grocery cart with $38.10 worth of white and wheat bread, chunky
peanut butter, Concord grape jelly, tortilla chips, salsa, babycut
carrots, veggie dip, and oranges. If his selection seems rather,
well, bush league, remember that his per-game budget is only $50
and that he must have money left over to purchase cold cuts for the
coaches and manager, whose status has earned them something a tad
better than PB&AMP;J. Remember, too, that the players, who tend to
approach the Spread as first-graders might a birthday buffet, seem
not to mind at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food preparation is something else they didn't tell me
about,'' Wittman says as he motors back to Lowell and looks forward
to laying out his purchases.
</P>
<P>
   No one warned him about nights like the previous one, either. He
arrived home with the team after an eight-game road trip at 1:30
a.m., washed uniforms and sorted out the equipment room before
going to bed at 6, and awakened at 9. ``I'm beat,'' he says softly
now between yawns. ``I'm not myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You absolutely have to be organized to do this job,'' he
declares a few minutes later. ``Procrastination will kill you. It's
the difference between getting eight hours' sleep and getting
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Team road trips are his salvation. Hotels take care of the
Spinners' laundry and the Spread is replaced by individual take-out
orders. There's actually time to go out with the boys after a game,
although you should remember that this is a league in which
Burlington, Vt., is considered the hot spot. ``We've got a
four-game series there soon and we're all looking forward to it,''
Wittman says, perking up at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   He's also juiced by the ballgame he's just watched both on the
clubhouse TV and in the runway leading to the Spinners dugout, a
3-2, 10-inning win over the Queens Kings on Lunch Cooler Giveaway
Night. Suddenly he's not so ambivalent about his summer. ``My goal
used to be to go into broadcasting,'' he says as the noisy players
file past him toward the showers. ``But the college I went to
didn't offer the kinds of courses I wanted. So I switched to
political science, and I'm not sure why. But since I got here I've
been thinking about going to grad school in sports management. I'm
thinking I'd like to become a general manager.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, he's still a Clubbie. Some of the
players may be off to the nearby Brewhouse Cafe &AMP; Grille, but
Wittman has many loads of laundry to go before he sleeps.
(Including, on this night, the other team's uniforms, an unexpected
chore for which the Kings will pay him $50.) He'll probably work
until 3:30 a.m., and then ``If I'm lucky I'll sleep till noon.''
</P>
<P>
   And before he leaves LeLacheur Park in the middle of the night,
Woody the Clubbie will have one more chore. He will arm the
security alarm. After all, he'll be the last one out of the
building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
