<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-INSIDER-TRADER-HNS &LR;      08-30 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDER-TRADER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAN CHARGED IN INSIDER TRADING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Silicon Valley man has been charged with
criminal securities fraud and civil insider trading violations. He
was accused of netting nearly $447,000 in illegal profits by buying
options on his company's stock after learning it had won a
lucrative contract to work on Microsoft's new video game console.
</P>
<P>
   Manu B. Shrivastava, 31, of San Jose was arrested at his home
Tuesday morning and taken before U.S. Magistrate Judge Joseph
Spero, who released him on $500,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities say an indictment must be filed in the case
by Sept. 12, at which point he would enter a plea in the case.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from Shrivastava's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Shrivastava was an engineer at nVidia, a Santa Clara-based
developer and marketer of computer graphics components. The
corporation's president and chief executive, Jen-Hsun Huang, sent
out a companywide e-mail to 400 employees March 5 informing them
the company had won a contract to design and manufacture computer
graphics and multimedia images for Microsoft's new video game
console, the X-Box.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail message said the contract could generate about $2
billion in sales over 5 years.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, nVidia's vice president of marketing sent a
subsequent e-mail to the entire staff, entitled ``xbox shhhhhh,''
telling them that news of the X-Box contract should be kept
confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities' eyebrows were raised by the wide dissemination of
the sensitive insider information. Generally, the problem occurs
with smaller companies that are about to go public, where
information is more free-flowing throughout the company. But
businesses that are becoming publicly traded companies are advised
by their attorneys to be much more conservative in disseminating
insider news.
</P>
<P>
   ``While you want to retain that corporate culture, you want to
keep from disseminating that kind of information on a broad
basis,'' said Jorge del Calvo, a partner with the law firm
Pillsbury, Madison &AMP; Sutro, which advises corporate clients on how
to handle insider information.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk that the information will leak exponentially
increases with each person you add to the list.'' Investor
confidence in companies, del Calvo pointed out, can be undermined
when they see stock prices moving up before company information is
publicly announced.
</P>
<P>
   According to a civil filing by the Securities and Exchange
Commission and an affidavit by an FBI agent, Shrivastava then
logged on to his on-line brokerage account and used it to begin
assembling 100 call options on nVidia stock, worth a total of
$30,825. By the time news of the contract was officially announced
by the two companies March 10, Shrivastava had sold all of the
options contracts, realizing net profits of $446,724, according to
the filings.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Caldwell, the head of the securities fraud division at
the U.S. attorney's office, said Shrivastava had made no effort to
conceal his identity in making the trades, logging on to his
brokerage account and buying the options in his own name.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at nVidia said Shrivastava had been fired in early
August when the matter came to their attention. They said
Shrivastava had signed an agreement that generally prohibited
trading on insider information and specifically barred buying
options on the company's own stock.
</P>
<P>
   They said Shrivastava was the only employee at the company who
had come under the scrutiny of securities regulators. The SEC said
its investigation was continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
