<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RELIGION-MORMON-ART-B     08-30 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MORMON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MORMONS TO OPEN THEIR 100TH TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The 90-year-old Mormon prophet looks out over
his religious statuary, past the six-towered Gothic temple and
beyond the Wasatch Mountains, and in his mind's eye sees a rocky
hilltop in Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Upon that hill is the realization of a Mormon dream. The world's
100th Mormon temple, a hulking rectangle of white Sardinian
granite, looms above Route 2, fulfilling Gordon B. Hinckley's goal
of having a century of temples in this first year of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley, a compact, energetic man who enjoys enormous
popularity among Mormons, calls the temple ``a reminder to the
world.'' It stands as evidence of a new aggressiveness by a faith
that sees itself as a religion of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormons have dramatically accelerated their pace of building
temples and winning converts; after taking 170 years to build the
first 55 temples, the church opened another 45 in just the last two
years, and at a time when some mainstream churches are losing
members, the Mormons now boast 11 million adherents, up from 1
million a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   For a church that has been persecuted ever since 14-year-old
Joseph Smith said that God and Jesus appeared to him in the woods
of western New York in 1820, the Belmont temple is a victory. The
70,000-square-foot structure sits just up the hill from where the
first Mormon meetinghouse in Belmont was destroyed in an apparent
arson in 1984, and it has opened despite ongoing legal battles that
have prevented the erection of the spire with a gold-leafed statue
of the angel Moroni that tops every other Mormon temple.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont temple is also a homecoming for a church whose
founding leaders _ Smith and Brigham Young _ came from Vermont, but
which had almost no presence in New England for its first 90 years,
when converts were encouraged to move to Utah. The president of the
Belmont temple, Loren Dunn, recalls being in Boston as a college
student in the 1960s when there were more Catholics in the
Archdiocese of Boston than Mormons in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church started here, but went away, and was not very large
in New England for a long time,'' said Kim B. Clark of Belmont, one
of the world's most prominent Mormons as the dean of Harvard
Business School and a candidate to be the next president of Harvard
University. Clark traces his own ancestry to the Bunker family, for
whom Bunker Hill is named.
</P>
<P>
   The two legal battles being waged against the Belmont temple by
a handful of neighbors have significant implications: At stake is
how much power, if any, cities and towns should have over the size
and design of religious and educational buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But with the temple opening this week for a month-long open
house, the building takes on new importance as the local heart of
the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as the Mormons are
formally known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mormonism is now a worshiping community that can make itself
established, if not fully at home, in any culture, and that is a
dramatic transformation from a community that was embedded in the
inner mountain West,'' said Jan Shipps, an expert on Mormonism at
Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   Being at home here means winning converts. In Massachusetts,
there are now about 16,000 Mormons, a small group in a state of 6
million, but a church whose size has tripled over the last
quarter-century while many other faiths have seen numbers dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission has always been to the world, but we haven't made
the kind of progress that we're making now,'' Hinckley said. ``Our
numbers are moving upward _ we're nearly 11 million strong now _
and that will continue. There is no doubt in my mind at all
concerning that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston and around the world, Mormons pose a challenge to
Catholics and Protestants with their success at evangelization. The
church's missionaries have been highly visible in the neighborhoods
of Boston most populated by immigrants and ethnic minorities, as
well as in the Belmont area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been canvassing the area _ visiting every home,'' said
the Rev. James E. O'Leary of Saint Camillus Catholic Church in
Arlington, across the street from the Mormon temple.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley, who as president of the Mormon church is revered as
prophet, seer, and revelator by Mormons, said that New England
isn't the strongest growth area of the church _ that would probably
be Mexico and other parts of Latin America _ but that the church is
making progress here. And Hinckley is unapologetic for his church's
zealous missionary efforts or its highly visible temple sites.
Belmont Hill is the second highest point inside Route 128; and in
Washington, D.C., a gigantic temple looms over the Capital Beltway,
Interstate 495.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley has his own strong connection to Massachusetts. He
traces his ancestry to Thomas Hinckley, who was the last governor
of Plymouth Colony. And there are parallels between the two men's
lives: Governor Hinckley was a member of a controversial religious
group, the Puritans, which fled persecution in England, and he was
an eager evangelist, in his case spreading the Christian gospel to
American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   For years, persecution of Mormons was driven in part by their
beliefs about the nature of God, which differ significantly from
other Christians, and in part by their support for polygamy, which
they renounced in 1890. Smith was murdered by an anti-Mormon mob in
Illinois in 1844. Two years later, his followers, led by Young,
began to flee the United States for a territory that has since
become Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Though the days of persecution are over, the church is often
criticized from the left for its political views and from the right
for its theological views. Evangelical Christians, competitors in
the marketplace of missoinary work, have been particularly
outspoken; the Promise Keepers, a national movement of Christian
men rallying in Worcester this weekend, refuse to allow Mormons to
speak at their events, declaring that ``the beliefs of the Mormon
Church are inconsistent with historic, orthodox Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   The church is so sensitive to criticism that at its Sunday
worship services, called sacrament meetings, speakers conclude
their remarks by saying ``I know this church is true. I know Gordon
Hinckley is a prophet of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of truth is particularly evident at temples, which,
unlike churches and synagogues, are not halls of communal worship
but a collection of small rooms used for the personal rituals
Mormons believe are essential for salvation. The open house in
Belmont provides a rare opportunity for the public to see the
spaces used for ceremonies that have long been secret. Once
dedicated, the temple will be closed forever to all but observant
Mormons whose moral conduct, as well as spiritual and financial
fealty, has been verified by a local bishop.
</P>
<P>
   The temple rituals include baptism, marriage, and a rite Mormons
call ``endowment,'' which entails receiving instruction in Mormon
beliefs, making promises about conduct, and a ceremony of
anointing. Because Mormons believe these rituals are an essential
condition for access to the highest level of heaven, they perform
them not only for themselves, but also vicariously for their
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience of going to the temple . . . helps you anchor
your life,'' said Michael D. Schetzel, the director of sales for
the Red Sox. ``It drives home your beliefs and your values, and to
have that experience more frequently makes your life a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mormon weddings inside the temple, vows do not include the
words ``till death do us part,'' because Mormons believe marriages
continue in the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marriage service will ensure that not only will my
husband and I be together after death, but our children will also
be able to be with us,'' said Josephine Nielsen, 25, of Hingham,
who expects to be the first bride married in the temple when she
weds Robert Pepe, 25, of Washington, D.C., just after the Oct. 1
dedication.
</P>
<P>
   The temples also seal relationships between parents and
children. Teresa Meredith, 43, of Acton, used a ceremony at a
temple in Spokane, Wash., to seal her relationship with a child who
died in infancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to know that he will be forever a part of our family, and
we'll be able to raise him again, it gave us a peace that I don't
know we would have had otherwise,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Local Mormons, who have had to travel long distances to
participate in a temple ceremony, are eagerly awaiting the Belmont
temple's opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great to have a temple closer to home,'' said Mitt
Romney, the Belmont Republican who ran for Senate in 1994 and is
now heading the Salt Lake City organizing committee for the 2002
winter Olympics. ``It makes you feel proud that the membership of
the church has grown large enough to merit a temple being
constructed so close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
