<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-PATENTS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-30 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-PATENTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PATENT APPLICATIONS BOOMING IN BIOTECH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc., the Cambridge, Mass.
biotechnology company that specializes in gene-based drug
discovery, has a staggering 1,500 applications pending at the US
Patent and Trademark Office.
</P>
<P>
   Even if only 40 percent of those applications are granted _ the
current success rate for the biotech industry _ the company will
more than quadruple its portfolio of 135 patents. And Millennium is
just one of many biotech companies rushing to nail down patents in
ever-increasing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The number of biotech patent applications nationally increased
15 percent last year to more than 20,000, according to the patent
office. It is expected to jump another 25 percent this year,
outpacing even the Internet and computer industry patent
applications, which have exploded in recent years. And despite this
year's addition of 80 examiners, the patent office's biotech
division just barely kept up with the workload.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in patents can be explained, in part, by the
unprecedented growth in the understanding of human biology and,
more specifically, of the human genetic code. Scientists are making
discoveries in record numbers. And more discoveries obviously mean
more patents.
</P>
<P>
   But industry professionals say there are business reasons as
well. For biotech companies, they say, patents are capital. More
than 1,300 companies are now competing to identify genes and
proteins, cure cancer and other diseases, and develop ways to speed
that research. Most aren't profitable for years. Some may never be.
So at the very least, investors want to know that the research and
the money they are pouring into it is protected by patents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not do a deal before we look closely at the intellectual
property,'' said Michael Carusi, general partner of Advanced
Technology Ventures, a Waltham venture capital firm. ``To me, this
is the fundamental difference between health care and some Internet
business models, even between biotechnology and some other areas of
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Often before a company gets started, it has patents, Carusi
said. Carusi is currently investigating the patent position of a
company that doesn't even have employees. Everyone, he said, wants
to be sure that the patents don't infringe on other existing
patents and that they would be defensible in court.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows anyone who invents or discovers ``a new and
useful process, machine, manufacture, or composition of matter'' to
get a patent. Processes used in making a drug as well as its
chemical recipe can be patented. But anything found in nature, such
as an element of the periodic table, can not. Gene patent holders
avoid that prohibition because genes must be isolated, cloned or
otherwise changed to be studied. And in the eyes of the law, once
genes have been manipulated, they are no longer in their natural
state.
</P>
<P>
   To get a patent, the applicant must also prove that the
invention or discovery is new and that it has a ``specific,
substantial and credible'' use. Once a patent is granted, it gives
its owner exclusive commercial rights to the invention or discovery
for 20 years from the date of the application.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Douglas, general counsel at Millennium, said patent
position is crucial for companies, whether they are large or small,
new or established. Companies devote years of work and millions of
dollars to develop potentially valuable cures. Without the patent
protection, he said, companies couldn't possibly recoup their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patents provide the incentive,'' Douglas said. ``They promise
a company a period of exclusivity, and without it companies
wouldn't make the investment. There's still healthy competition,
and it's resulting in companies investing a lot of resources in
what we all hope will be cures for diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said Millennium patents genes the company identifies as
well as its discoveries about the functions of genes in disease. It
also patents small fragments of genes, known as expressed sequence
tags, in hopes they will help identify genetic variations that make
a person susceptible to disease.
</P>
<P>
   He recognizes, however, that there is still a lot of uncertainty
about how some patents will stand up legally over time. Early gene
patents allowed companies to lay claim to future uses the company
didn't even know the gene had. Some hope that by patenting a piece
of a gene they will gain the rights to entire gene. And while the
patent office has raised its requirements, questions remain about
how far-reaching future patents will be.
</P>
<P>
   The issue troubles Dr. Aubrey Milunsky, director of the Center
for Human Genetics at the Boston University School of Medicine. The
BU lab already pays licensing fees to gene patent holders when
running certain diagnostic tests for patients. Now, he said,
companies like Celera Genomics Corp., which recently decoded the
human genome, want to patent thousands of genes without knowing
much about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing so, they would ultimately exclude someone else from
working on that gene,'' Milunsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas and others in the biotech industry disagree. They argue
that patents actually promote the free exchange of science.
Applications require the filer to explain the invention or
discovery in enough detail that it can be replicated. Researchers
are free to use the information as long as they don't profit from
it.
</P>
<P>
   The system also encourages companies to stake out different
areas of science, they say, ensuring a diversity of research that
will lead to more discoveries and more medical advances. And with
an estimated 120,000 genes and many more proteins, there is plenty
of work to be done, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Gene patent filings are growing even faster than patent
applications for the biotech industry as a whole, said John Doll,
who head the patent office's biotechnology division. He estimates
the number of gene applications will grow by a third this year and
expects the rate to accelerate in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have an emerging technology and new discoveries in
the emerging area, the patents tend to be broad because there is
nothing known about that area,'' Doll said. He said the first
patent in biotechnology ``was very, very broad. But it didn't stop
the technology. It allowed others to look at it and move it
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Watson, senior vice president of corporate development at
Cubist Pharmaceuticals Inc., a Cambridge biotech company, believes
many of these issues will eventually be resolved in court. In the
meantime, companies are protecting a single product with multiple
patents and using a variety of strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are expensive, however, so most companies don't file
applications indiscriminately. Fees run about $700 to apply,
another $1,200 when the patent is issued and $5,600 more to
maintain the patent during its 20-year lifespan. Cubist has 133
patents in its portfolio and has filed applications for another 40
in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start as broadly as you can,'' Watson said. ``As the
research narrows, you narrow your patent coverage and close in
around a product. As the science and the industry matures, you'll
start to see more specificity and more narrow claims. Right now,
it's like a lot of little insurance policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Most companies say they aren't trying to squeeze out the
competition. They are just trying to claim what competitive
advantages they can to survive and stay healthy. And patents are
the way to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Williams, general counsel for New England Biolabs Inc.,
said that is true even for established biotech companies. The
Beverly, Mass. company has been in business for 25 years and
supplies other biotech companies with research tools, primarily
enzymes that scientists use to isolate and cut up segments of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The company holds 88 patents, most of them for the DNA of those
enzymes, and has 23 applications pending. Without patent
protection, competitors could sell those enzymes for less than
Biolabs could because the competitors didn't invest the money to
discover them.
</P>
<P>
   Biolabs' patent portfolio has also aided partnerships with
companies interested in developing therapies or diagnostic tests
using the company's discoveries and technologies. Patents can
encourage cooperation between competitors, Wiliams said, giving
companies the incentive to trade information in ways that will
enhance their businesses and their research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology feeds on itself,'' Williams said. ``As the level of
technology and the level of skill is raised, it opens more doors. I
don't see it slowing down any time soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
