<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      08-30 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDS SOUTHERN; A NADER AIDER; POLITICAL BROW GESTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULES VERDONE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the end of the summer that never really was, there are at
least a few days left to grab The Oxford American's fourth annual
double issue (July/August) on Southern music before it's pulled
from the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   That's Oxford as in Mississippi, and the subtitle is The
Southern Magazine of Good Writing. And even if it's best known for
its publisher, John Grisham (the magazine is serializing his novel
``A Painted House,'' with Part 4 in this issue), some music lovers
know better. The special issue is a triumph in tone, and there's no
skimping on content: It's 208 pages and comes with a 23-song CD,
``Southern Sampler 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   What resounds here is an unabashed love of music instead of
clinical expertise. There are some lively Q&AMP;As (Sam Phillips, Tom
Petty, and Al Green's collaborator Teenie Hodges are among the
subjects) and two thoughtful remembrances of singer/songwriter Jeff
Buckley, but it's three of the magazine's short opening essays that
set a lasting mood.
</P>
<P>
   The title of editor Marc Smirnoff's piece on compiling the
enclosed CD sums up his strategy: ``More Personal Than
Scientific.'' And though the downside is that the outcome is
lopsidedly white, the upside is that Smirnoff's heart is all over
this thing. He wants you to love the songs he loves. Next, Hal
Crowther writes about a conference of new Southern writers and
Dolly Parton (whose gorgeous bluegrass take on ``Silver Dagger'' is
on the CD), connecting the topics with a sharp eye. ``One of my
litmus tests for Southern authenticity,'' Crowther writes, ``would
be the ability to appreciate the paradox of Dolly Parton: Beneath a
blinding surface of deliberate, exaggerated, self-satirizing
artifice lurks one of the most engagingly authentic individuals in
the Nashville pantheon.''
</P>
<P>
   Elvis biographer and Massachusetts resident Peter Guralnick
movingly recounts how he started writing about the blues. As he
puts it, ``What I was trying to capture . . . was the feeling, not
the technique. I was not trying to provide deconstructive analysis
. . . (but) writing that would bring the reader to the same
appreciation of the subject that I felt, that would in a sense
mimic the same emotions not just that I experienced but that I
believed the musician put into the music in the first place.''
Hear, hear.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is $8.50 or free to new subscribers; call 800-269-6926
or go to www.oxfordamericanmag.com; 10 percent of proceeds from
this issue will go to the Music Maker Relief Foundation, which
``helps support forgotten blues artists by giving them money for
basic living necessities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick wrote that he started his work ``when much of this
music was not simply ignored but reviled in the mainstream press.''
That sounds uncannily like Lewis Lapham's criticism about media
coverage of Ralph Nader's presidential campaign in the September
issue of Harper's Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Lapham, the editor of Harper's, is wise to call his piece an
essay, though part of it is based on an interview with Nader;
Lapham also spends a chunk of a day accompanying the Green Party
candidate to other press appointments. Lapham's heart is out there
throbbing on his sleeve. Big surprise. He holds as one of his
recurring themes that a healthy democracy should be unruly _ the
messier, the better. He doesn't think Nader can win, but he is
wide-eyed about how Nader's candidacy could affect the year's
debate, how the entire process might be more meaningful, and yes,
more sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Lapham spent June 30 with Nader, the same day The New York Times
published an editorial that called his campaign ``a self-indulgent
exercise'' and said that ``the public deserves to see the
major-party candidates compete on an uncluttered playing field.''
Lapham elaborates, sarcastically, that if Nader ``were a true
gentleman and a real liberal he would stay with the seat belts and
leave the politics to the professionals.'' Nader, reacting to the
editorial, tells Lapham, ``You've got to love these people. . . .
They think the American electoral process is a gated community.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader trots out some compelling stories, attacks the notion that
Gore is an ``outstanding environmentalist,'' and tells Jim Lehrer
that as president he would understand the complicated workings of
government agencies because ``I don't know anybody who has sued
more of them.'' Lapham is at his best here, in a story that calls
on him to report and not just editorialize. He is never going to
get out of the way when he tells a story _ why would he bother
telling it? _ but he does a good job of explaining why he loves the
third-party participation in this race. Lapham paints a picture of
an agitator who speaks to the integrity and intelligence of the
electorate and is ``less interested in the counting of votes than
in the lesson of freedom.'' (For another opinionated stand on the
state of our democracy, check out art critic Dave Hickey's ``A
World Like Santa Barbara'' in the same issue.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cover of October's Psychology Today promises a look at
``Election 2000: Gore &AMP; Bush on the Couch,'' but the story is about
as satisfying as one M&AMP;M. The analysis of the candidates' speeches
is statistically numbing, then the authors advise Gore to ``Stop
talking about the environment _ or start talking in more upbeat
terms about the possibility of change _ if you want to appeal to
the public.'' (Bush, it seems, is more optimistic, and optimism
gets one elected.)
</P>
<P>
   What's more entertaining are interpretations of the candidates'
facial expressions. Gore: ``Eyebrows down show dominance.'' Bush:
``Eyebrows up show submissiveness.'' Also, ``Gore shows
concentration, Bush playfulness.'' There's a funny shot of Bush
with his thumb up, but, as the caption asks, ``Why's his smile
upside down?'' Of Gore, it's wondered, ``Do tight lips mean
tight-lipped?'' His gestures ``reveal him to be more serious,
constrained, controlled, weighty, ponderous, dominant.'' Bush's
``gestures convey that he is less serious, silly, at times
contemptuous, though also open to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody remember Goofus and Gallant?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
