u l BC-CATHOLIC-WEDDING-ART-     08-30 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-WEDDING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 VIDEO OUTLINES CATHOLIC WEDDING RITES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUIS PORTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Denise Buckley and Jim Ryan were married back
in November, but they spent a recent Saturday walking down the
aisle of St. Peter's Church over and over again, as family and
friends watched from the pews.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryans, it turns out, were reenacting their wedding for a
video that will be distributed around the world to enable
prospective couples to see how the Roman Catholic Church recommends
that a ceremony be performed.
</P>
<P>
   The need for the video, called ``Our Catholic Wedding,'' may
come as a surprise to some, but it seems that few people,
especially in New England, have been paying much attention to the
1969 revision of the wedding rite, a change that followed the
Second Vatican Council.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Few people who are engaged are willing to break with
tradition on the all-important day by taking their vows in a new,
comparatively untested ceremony. This film _ produced and
distributed by Liturgy Training Publications _ will be the first to
show a complete ceremony conducted according to the revised rite.
</P>
<P>
   The company is under the jurisdiction of the Archdiocese of
Chicago, and it hopes this video will help overcome resistance to
the changes in the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The video will really be aimed at the bride and groom,'' says
Maria Leonard, executive producer of the film, who was overseeing
operations the day of the filming. ``Our goal is to give a common
vision of the wedding ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprising as it is, most New England Catholics have never seen
a wedding according to the revised rite, according to Paul Covino ,
a chaplain at the College of the Holy Cross in Worcester who is an
adviser for the film. With no example to guide them, many Catholics
continue to get married in the more traditional, somber ceremonies
that borrow from weddings of the Middle Ages, when marriages sealed
alliances and brides and grooms didn't see each other before they
were hitched.
</P>
<P>
   The revised ceremony is distinctly modern. For the bride, there
is no more hiding in a back room, no more being given away by her
nervous father, and no more symbolic burning of unity candles. Even
the guests participate before and during the ceremony, gathering to
say hello to the bride and groom at the front of the church and
singing during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest change was greeting people as they come in. . . .
After all, it is no surprise that Jim and I are getting married, so
why hide in the back?'' asks Denise. When she and Jim got married _
the first time _ they chose to follow the revised ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Denise works as a financial aid counselor at Harvard Law School
and Jim teaches Spanish at Milton Academy, where they live.
(``We're dorm parents to 40 girls,'' Denise says.) Both grew up in
the area _ Jim, 29, in Dorchester, and Denise, 34, in Waltham. St.
Peter's was, in fact, the Buckleys' church when Denise was growing
up, and she was baptized here, just about the time the changes to
the wedding rite were being written.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Ryans' marriage was performed by the book, the new
one, and because of Denise's work with the Office of Worship,
Liturgy Training Publications asked the Ryans, and many of the
wedding guests, to reenact the ceremony. ``We had experience. We
weren't really acting, but reenacting,'' Denise says. They agreed,
even though it meant 10 hours in wedding dresses, bridesmaids'
gowns, and tuxedos under movie lights in the overheated church.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's itself, with its pipe organ and stained glass
windows, was chosen because it had a large open space by the front
doors in which the assembly could gather (and be filmed) as they
came into the church. It also lent solemnity to the proceedings, as
the half-dozen members of the film crew hurried around to ready
shots, moving cameras and sound booms and wires into place before
calling for silence as each scene began.
</P>
<P>
   By volunteering to be in the video, the wedding party and guests
are helping to overcome resistance to the new ceremony, although
many of them did not intially agree with the changes. Patrick
Buckley, Denise's father, was especially wary of alterations in the
wedding processional. Instead of the bride being led up the aisle
and given away by her father, the bride and groom walk with their
parents, and approach the altar together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really think it was a good idea, but after the
rehearsal (for the November wedding), I thought it was great.
Especially walking down the aisle with them. That was completely
new to me,'' says Buckley, who has seen four of his five daughters
get married, giving three away in more traditional ceremonies
before Denise became a Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding rite was rewritten to bring the ceremony more in
line with the teachings of the Roman Catholic Church. This meant
including the church's guests in the ritual as well as the
betrothed, and excluding cultural practices that do not have a
foundation in the church or its teachings. Another major change is
the seating arrangement for the family. No longer is there a
bride's and a groom's side of the church _ instead, both families
sit together.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cultural practices that have been layered onto the
ceremony ``really come from a medieval, feudal expression of
marriage,'' says Jim Field, director of the Office of Worship. He
adds that the church revised the ceremony because it sees the bride
and groom as equals, and ``as adults, making mature adult
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the centuries things have crept in which really shouldn't
have been there,'' says the Rev. Austin Fleming, a parish priest in
Concord who presided over the videotaped wedding. One of the
examples he cites is the ubiquitous unity candle, a feature in many
weddings in different faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unity candle was invented by some company that markets
unity candles,'' he says, laughing. Fleming also acts as an adviser
on the ceremony, and has written several books about Catholic
weddings, including ``Parish Weddings'' and ``Prayerbook for
Engaged Couples.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to get it when they see it done. It's a woman
giving herself to her husband, and a man giving himself to his
wife,'' says Fleming, who dismisses the old practice under which
the groom would not see his bride before the ceremony as
``superstition.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the church does not insist that couples follow the
rewritten ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put in front of them the ways the church says to do it, and
I try and discourage what I call the marginalized groom approach,''
says Fleming, referring to the groom's awkward position when the
assembly turns away from him to watch the bride approach.
</P>
<P>
   The video will be sold primarily to parishes and churches in
English-speaking countries, which will in turn loan it to would-be
spouses. Copies will also be given to the members of the assembly
who volunteered to be in the video.
</P>
<P>
   And what is it like to be a model couple for Catholics
everywhere?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really real for us yet, at least until we see it in
January,'' Denise says.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said reenacting their ceremony had other benefits as
well. Some of their friends couldn't make it to their real wedding,
but showed up for the filming. All in all, it was fun to get their
friends and family together again, Jim says. ``It's not hard at all
to smile walking down the aisle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
