<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STYLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STYLE, MESSAGE, GOVERNOR GOES HIS OWN WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush talks a lot about being a
``compassionate conservative,'' but in conducting his campaign,
he's taken a decidely ``my-way-or-the-highway'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential contender still gets his principal
political advice from the ``Iron Triangle'' of aides who helped him
run for Texas governor in 1994, despite recommendations that he
expand his team for the general election with experienced
Washington operatives.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Bush is delivering pretty much the same speech he
has all year, focusing on the core themes of schools, Social
Security reform, military readiness, religion-based welfare
programs, and tax cuts. The message stays the same despite attacks
by Vice President Al Gore that Bush's $1.3 trillion tax-cut plan
``would wreck our good economy.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Commission on Presidential Debates, created to
organize the fall face-offs, has proposed three meetings between
Bush and Gore, the Texas governor has resisted the panel's
recommendation and is instead saying he may participate in only two
of those debates. Eager to control the format for his appearance,
he is toying with selecting a third debate from nontraditional
hosts such as late-night television's David Letterman or CNN's
Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   Even with his daily routine, Bush is breaking the mold for
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he wrapped up an appearance in Memphis and
decided to head immediately for Dallas, even though his traveling
press corps had spent thousands of dollars running phone lines and
ordering food for a filing center arranged by the campaign. The
reason for the change? Bush wanted to run at a favorite athletic
club in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has also refused to submit to the longheld practice
of moving everywhere with a small group of reporters in case
something unexpected happens while traveling from place to place.
Bush routinely leaves reporters behind and takes just his Secret
Service detail to fund-raisers or for exercise.
</P>
<P>
   While brashness and independence are hallmarks of Texans in
general, they are attributes of Bush in particular. His bravado has
manifested itself in ways big and small throughout his life. In
fact, his wry smile has often been interpreted as a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   As a child and teenager, he was forever the ring leader, setting
up neighborhood baseball games or a stickball league at Phillips
Academy in Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In his 20s and 30s, he was known for his hard-partying ways,
favoring bourbon and beer. In a rare sign of contrition, he quit
drinking in 1986 after repeated requests from his wife, Laura, and
overindulging at his 40th birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   In running for Texas governor, Bush broke with conventional
wisdom by challenging a popular incumbent, Democrat Ann Richards.
His chief political strategist, Karl Rove, outlined a strategy of
focusing on four core themes, and Bush executed the plan with
success, even as Richards derided him as ``Shrub'' and someone with
a limited vision.
</P>
<P>
   Today Bush still receives advice from Rove and the other two
members of the ``Triangle,'' campaign manager Joe Allbaugh and
communications director Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   He is sticking with his tax cut plan, which dwarfs cuts proposed
by Republicans in Congress, even though it was initially proposed
to entice voters in tax-free New Hampshire and to rally the GOP
base.
</P>
<P>
   When Rove's primary strategy appeared to falter with Bush's loss
in the first-in-the-nation primary, his boss scoffed at calls for a
staff shakeup and instead bore down on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Today, despite the pressure of being the Republican nominee,
Bush still moves to his own beat.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers to sleep in his own bed, so recent campaign weeks
have called for no more than three days on the road. When he
travels, he takes along his favorite feather pillow and eats peanut
butter-and-jelly sandwiches that airplane caterers make especially
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked last week when he would pick up the leisurely pace, Bush
sounded offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``You thought it was leisurely coming down the train in
California? I didn't think it was so leisurely,'' he said,
referring to his train trip with Senator John S. McCain of Arizona.
Most days featured only one public appearance, followed by hours on
the train. During that span, Bush was often out of public view,
conducting media interviews, some even by a satellite dish loaded
onto the train.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made it clear that he'll continue to set his own
cadence should he be elected president in November.
</P>
<P>
   While President Bush, the candidate's father, retreated to the
family compound in Kennebunkport, Maine, a resort community where
his staff and entourage could also take working vacations, the
governor insists he will seek refuge within a 1,500-acre ranch he
is building a ranch in Crawford, Texas, a one-stoplight town 30
miles outside of Waco. There is no hotel and only a few places to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   And the compassionate conservative delights at the prospect of
reporters who will cover him scratching around for a place to stay,
since the more comfortable hotels are located in the state capital,
some 100 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Four Seasons for y'all,'' he told reporters recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
