<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-APPLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     APPLE SAYS NEW OPERATING SYSTEM ON TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Apple Computer Inc. chief executive Steve Jobs
says the release of the next-generation Mac OS X is on schedule
with its first public test set for Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The new operating system, which Jobs called the ``future of the
Macintosh,'' will be released at the Apple Expo in Paris. The
company is on track to release the product to the general public in
early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has spent years preparing a rewritten version of the
operating system that runs its computers. Dubbed OS X (10), the
software program includes features such as a tool bar for
organizing frequently used documents and programs, a software
player for listening to music MP3 files and an updated Quicktime
player for viewing video.
</P>
<P>
   David Bailey, research analyst with Gerard Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co.
in New York, said that the Cupertino-based company is right on
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first major upgrade to the operating system in many
years, and it brings many fundamental benefits to users like
stability, reliability and performance,'' he said, adding it has a
greater affinity to Unix-type systems, such as Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs demonstrated the new system Tuesday at a convention in San
Francisco, but things didn't go as planned when he tried to show
how quickly the computer will resume working from sleep mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's going wrong here,'' he said when nothing happened.
``But when it works, it actually wakes up in 1 second.'' The
previous version, Mac OS 9, takes at least 8 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs spent much of his time Tuesday rehashing the new line of
products he debuted six weeks ago at the Macworld Expo show in New
York, including the widely acclaimed Power Mac G4 Cube.
</P>
<P>
   The Cube, which retails for $1,799, is a faster, more powerful
version of the existing G4 Power Mac packed into an 8- by 8-inch
cube. He said the company has already shipped ``tens of thousands''
of the new computers.
</P>
</TEXT>
