<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-KENNEDY-WORSHIP-BOS &LR;      08-30 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-WORSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY STATUE A BIT TOO SURREAL, CRITICS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS, Mass. _ Over the years, in its capacity as the Kennedy
family's summer retreat, this village has embodied sun-drenched
promise, numbing loss, and dreamlike elegy, but never, not until
now, has it ventured into the realm of the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   Here, where one family's past has become a local industry, the
bronze statue due to rise up next year at the corner of Ocean and
South streets will depict a moment that flies in the face of
history and physics: a 46-year-old John F. Kennedy, in an
open-necked Oxford and rolled-up khakis, with his arm slung around
the neck of his 38-year-old son, John Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Since preliminary drawings were made public last week, admirers
have praised the idea as a rendering of the two men as they could
be imagined today in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   But along Main Street last week, a number of people who were
asked about the plans used the same word: ``Bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the idea,'' said 64-year-old Grace Winters, a
clerk at Sullivan's religious supply store, where, she points out,
Ethel Kennedy frequently shopped for spiritual texts. ``He didn't
know John as a young man, he knew John as a child. If they wanted
to do the two John Kennedys, I think it should be father and baby
son.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials from the Hyannis Area Chamber of Commerce, which
commissioned the statue, said Kennedy relatives requested that both
men be depicted as adults.
</P>
<P>
   The way sculptor David Lewis sees it, the decision to portray a
fantasy is underlaid by a truth that is obvious to anyone who lives
here: It's not historical research that brings Kennedy buffs to
Hyannis. For 30 years, visitors have arrived as pilgrims as much as
tourists, pouring in to pass their hands over the Kennedy pews at
St. Francis Xavier Church and glimpse the Kennedy houses from the
distant vantage of a Hy-Line tour boat.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, in an effort to grasp something real out of the
haze of memories, they have gone further than that. Years ago,
before the stockade fence went up around the Kennedy compound in
Hyannis Port, people used to rip shingles off the sides of the
houses, said Harold Tobey, 64, who was a police officer here for 17
years. Another resident recalled watching visitors reach underneath
the stockade fence to grab dirt and grass.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Rusher, a longtime tour guide from Hyannis who gives her
age as ``almost 90,'' said the fence went up after an unpleasant
encounter between Rose Kennedy and a bus full of tourists who
``appeared to be, shall we say, pushy . . . and felt they should
touch Rose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hyannis Area Chamber of Commerce recognized long ago that
visitors came here in search of an uplifting emotional experience.
At the tiny JFK Museum, which is squeezed in between the Consumer
Credit Counseling Service and the Cape Cod Dispute Resolution
Center, the assassination of the president is barely mentioned.
It's in this spirit, Lewis said, that he is fixing the father and
son as two young men on an imaginary beach idyll. What this
sculpture is, he said, is ``a wish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have to get used to the fact that this is
poetical, mystical,'' said Lewis in his Osterville studio. ``Every
great figure in our history is a flawed human being like we are,
but their deeds take on aspects of mythology, and we strive for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he said, the responses he's heard have been
positive and emotional _ a boon for the $350,000 project, which
will be paid for with private donations. Within three days after
the concept was made public, to Lewis's surprise, four donors
offered $10,000, enough to earn each of them a limited-edition
miniature of the statue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get tearful and they get emotional. They love the idea. I
have heard very little skepticism,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some visitors interviewed, like John and Florence
Tutunjian, a Long Island couple of around 60, said they were
enraptured by the idea. The Tutunjians _ he in crisp nautical wear
and she in aqua, with a neck scarf and sunglasses _ were sitting
quietly at the JFK memorial, having come to Hyannis in search of
``a spirit,'' said John Tutunjian, a first-generation
Syrian-American who recalled hearing about the Kennedy compound as
a young man and assuming that someday he would have a Tutunjian
compound of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the statue would be ``almost a religious experience,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of local people interviewed said they found the
idea of the father and son strolling together jarring, to say the
least. Jacqui McGuire, 35, of Sandwich, shook her head and said the
idea was ``surreal.'' Tobey, a former president of the Town
Council, said the imaginary tete-a-tete ``just doesn't seem real to
me.'' Chuck Odams, who sells sculptures at Just Africa on Main
Street, called it ``an odd concept.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman just hummed the theme song to ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   If any event could elevate this coastal town from tourist
attraction to something like a shrine, though, it was the crash
last year that took the lives of 38-year-old John F. Kennedy Jr.;
his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, 33; and her sister, 34-year-old
Lauren Bessette. In the weeks after the plane went down, Hyannis
hosted a flood of visitors who followed some impulse across the
country so they could grieve here. In the first week after the
crash, 8,000 people walked through the tiny museum, which had
logged an average of 40,000 people a year since it opened in 1991.
By the end of last year, 70,000 had visited the museum, marking its
highest attendance rate ever, said Lynne Poyant, director of the
Hyannis Area Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing plans for a statue of John F. Kennedy and his son,
John Jr., some villagers wondered whether the massive upswelling of
emotion that followed last summer's plane crash might subside
dramatically, as it appears to have for Diana, Princess of Wales,
after her death in a 1998 car crash.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Stetson, a former president of the Chamber of Commerce
who sits on the advisory committee for the statue, doesn't believe
the fascination and grief will ever subside. If watching the
visitors here has taught him anything, it has taught him that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come looking for contact. And one of the reasons it's
continued so strong is that you can't get that contact,'' Stetson
said. ``You haven't really put your hands on anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
