<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEEN-PLAY-ART-BOS &LR;      08-30 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-PLAY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 TROUBLED YOUTHS' STORIES END UP ON OFF-BROADWAY STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. _ In the age of voyeurism and tell-all
stories, Diane Schwartz is the perfect Hollywood teen. She is
gutsy, street-chic hip, and she has the pouty lips and
honey-colored hair of a model.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she has a gut-wrenching story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz looks back to her early teens, and can now say,
bluntly, ``I was on the road to death.'' She was an anorexic who
would binge eat, then stick her fingers down her throat. She
overdosed four times, on whatever drugs she could find in the
medicine cabinet. The last time it was 36 Dexatrim diet pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to die, but I was too scared to die,'' said Schwartz,
now 18.
</P>
<P>
   So when she and her seven friends first took the stage at the
DeSisto School, a leafy campus in a former Berkshires mansion that
caters to emotionally troubled teens, she wasn't acting _ exactly.
</P>
<P>
   In a rock-musical about the anguish of teen life, she belts out
songs of despair. In one she cries out, ``Where were you when I
needed you? Why weren't you ever home, Daddy?''
</P>
<P>
   From a high-school auditorium in 1996, ``Inappropriate'' went to
an off-Broadway theater a year later, where it wowed critics who
called ``Inappropriate'' a prequel to ``Rent.'' During a run this
spring in Los Angeles with a different cast, film executives saw it
and were enraptured. Now three Hollywood studios are vying to turn
it into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tried-and-true Hollywood story,'' said Alan Shapiro,
a screenwriter best known for ``The Crush,'' which starred Alicia
Silverstone. ``Their stories are endemic to the struggles of
adolescents, and they are authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who graduated from DeSisto in 1975, has wanted to tell
this story _ which is also his story _ for 25 years, partly for
catharsis. But he also knows it will sell. The teen market is so
hot that even bad films, like this summer's ``Scary Movie,'' can
gross $145 million.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a treatment of the movie, three film studios are
negotiating a screenplay with him. School administrators say actor
Laurence Fishburne is interested in playing the leading adult role.
</P>
<P>
   The movie will be ``Fame'' meets ``The Breakfast Club,'' but in
a rawer, in-your-face style that's part ``Real World.'' It centers
on eight students who arrive at the school against their will, as
most do. Here, they slowly become friends. And along the way, as
the real-life drama unfolded, their theater director, Lonnie
McNeil, proposes a play about their struggles.
</P>
<P>
   But just putting it together, with a cast of clashing, sometimes
needy, teenagers, presented problems.
</P>
<P>
   One student at first refused to perform, saying he didn't want
people to think he was gay. Another performer, a female, ran away
during rehearsal season. On the road, they argued, sometimes over
the silliest things.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time when we were in New York I got into an argument with
Jamie about sponges. He was like, `Use the counter sponge for the
counter and the dishes sponge for the dishes,' '' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a big deal, but she got all upset,'' said Jamie
Ourisman, 20, sitting across from Schwartz in the campus's Rose
Room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was being controlling. I just ran into the
bathroom and cried,'' Schwartz said. ``I laugh now, thinking about
it. I would make a big deal out of little things.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems, though, was that some of the
students had never performed before. But what they lacked in
on-stage experience, they made up for digging into the emotions of
their real-life experiences.
</P>
<P>
   In 90 minutes, through rock, rap, poetry, and dance, the eight
actors deal with issues ranging from rape, to homophobia, to drug
abuse, to loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   When Adam Schiffman, 19, sings ``The Dream'' his arms tremor,
his eyes widen, as if he sees his dad's face:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(lyrics style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your finger points and puts me down
</P>
<P>
   Your words slice me like a knife
</P>
<P>
   in forming me to measure up
</P>
<P>
   to your own standards
</P>
<P>
   you say I need to make you proud and become more like you . . .
well . . . you are not my idol.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end lyrics style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One night, his father came to watch him perform. From the stage,
Schiffman could see his dad wiping a tear. It's the only time, he
said, he ever saw his father cry.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship, which was distant, is improving. But every
time Schiffman sings that song, he isn't acting. He's telling his
story.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Geyer, 16, who plays a gay teenager who is often taunted by
homophobes, takes his scenes from real life. He struggled with his
sexuality and two years ago came out of the closet, at the prodding
of his roommate, Ourisman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was. When you live with someone, you just know,''
Ourisman said.
</P>
<P>
   The students live on a 300-acre campus of rolling lawns, and
study in a Colonial mansion. About 110 students live here, in a
year-round program that combines scholastics, athletics, individual
therapy, and group counseling.
</P>
<P>
   It's a place of last resort for troubled youths whose parents
can afford the $60,000-a-year tuition. To learn Spanish, they live
in the school's villa in San Miguel de Allende, Mexico. A biology
program brings others to the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   Now the school can add ``Inappropriate'' to its list of unusual
programs. After all, how many schools can say their theater
students performed off Broadway?
</P>
<P>
   On its third run off Broadway, The New York Times reviewed it
and said: ``There are moments when this show really could be
compared to the brilliant use of anger, hurt and exuberance in
`Rent' and `Hair.' At other times, the show seems to have been
written and staged by a self-confident high school student.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a rave, but enough to draw hundreds to the Theater Row
Theater to see the students. Now, they are working on a deal to
bring ``Inappropriate'' to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The students are excited, not just because it would give them
celebrity status, but because they want people to know they're not
the only ones who have felt frustrated, bitter, and abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even believe that I'm alive,'' Schwartz said, ``and
now they want to make a movie about my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
