<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6265 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-REALCOOL-GUY0831-COX     08-30 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALCOOL-GUY0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's the guy you've got to know in Austin? The AC guy, that's
who
 &HT;    By Mark Lisheron
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - The most important man in Austin is touring
Robin's new apartment, letting the 90-degree air blowing from each
of the ceiling vents warm his calloused hand.
</P>
<P>
   On the kitchen counter hums a 10-inch plastic fan, the only
cooling implement Robin Schiller and her fiance, Christopher, have
had since their air conditioning unit quit the day before. Chris is
cooling himself at a University of Texas orientation day, leaving
Robin to wait for the most important man in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller looks upon this man the way one imagines Lazarus'
sister looking upon Jesus (at least Lazarus had a place to keep
cool). He doesn't disappoint. He removes a rusted facing plate from
a unit next to the front door and clamps an amperage meter around a
pipe. Suddenly, and for no reason he can explain, the unit comes to
life.
</P>
<P>
   After he refills a compressor at the back of the North Austin
apartment with Freon, the numbers on the digital thermometer in the
kitchen ceiling vent begin to plummet. Schiller bathes her hands in
the cool air. ``So, is that it?'' she asks, implying that miracles
oughtn't be this ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There it is,'' the most important man in Austin says, looking
at Schiller's face. ``There's the difference between the smile and
the frown. You get the smile when the place starts to cool down.''
</P>
<P>
   On 28 days this summer, the equivalent of February if February
was ever this cruel, the temperature has climbed past 100 degrees.
According to the National Weather Service, the average high
temperature for all of July was 99.4 degrees, and it's 99.7 degrees
so far in August.
</P>
<P>
   Into the Austin-area swamp venture approximately 5,000 air
conditioning repairmen, or technicians, as the Texas Air
Conditioning Contractors Association is wont to refer to them.
</P>
<P>
   Workweeks average between 50 and 60 hours in the summer, helping
a hard-working veteran technician make about $50,000 a year,
according to Nancy Jones, executive director of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get a lot of good press,'' Jones says. ``Especially
with the kind of summer this has been, it has been tremendously
stressful for our members. People die in this kind of weather. Air
conditioning technicians are true heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Hiesler, air conditioning tech, hero and the most
important man in Austin, is listening to what is supposed to be the
address of his next call, but is instead a crackling, broken CB
transmission in his Pronto Service Co. truck.
</P>
<P>
   He presses a Doral into an ashtray so full the butt falls to the
truck floor, trailing smoke behind it. He finishes the last of a
Sam's Choice cola and makes another deposit in the passenger side
footwell. Next to an unopened bag of pork rinds on the seat is a
copy of The Nelson Study Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I read it, it's something to do between calls,'' he
says. ``It was here when I got the truck. I found out later one of
the guys at work told me he tries to leave one in every truck.
That's the way to do it so you don't try to ram religion down
anyone's throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is not temperamentally inclined to think of himself
as heroic, Hiesler is well-aware of his importance. Before this day
is over he will have visited six homes, each in a particular state
of desperation. Some days he takes 12 calls and doesn't get home to
his wife, Alexandria, and two children, until 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta enjoy this business and everything that goes with
it,'' he says, ``or you better get out. People are either screaming
at you or complimenting you.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he leaves for the next call, Phyllis, a Lakeway homeowner
whose 1-year-old compressor failed, has come home to a cool house.
Hiesler has replaced the compressor and reset the thermostats,
while Avery, Phyllis' Yorkie, yaps at him from a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all these windows,'' Phyllis says. ``We do everything
we can to turn our homes into hotboxes and then complain when the
air goes out. But people just can't live here without air.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hiesler was a boy, he took calls with his father, who
repaired the old gas air conditioners for 31 years for Southern Gas
Co. ``You wouldn't believe it, I'm 31 and I tell people I've been
in the business for 20 years. That's how long I been doing it. I've
lived and breathed it all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, this isn't true. About five years ago, ground down
by the summers, Hiesler took some training and became an auto
mechanic. The apprenticeship didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five thousands dollars worth of tools got stole from me,'' he
says. ``I took it that the good Lord was telling me to go back to
air conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   The good Lord greets Hiesler at his next stop. In a brown back
yard across from a compressor low on Freon, a plaster Jesus on a
stump looks down on a hand-painted plaster angel. The Blessed
Mother looks out from behind the stump, and around the yard are
scattered various saintly figures.
</P>
<P>
   As he attaches pressure gauge hoses to the nipples on the pipes
of the second compressor, Julieanne, another Lakeway homeowner,
corners Hiesler, fingering a folded check. The date on the check
reads July 12, the date she tells Hiesler the first of four Pronto
technicians attempted to solve her problem. Hiesler listens and
shakes his head, a bead of sweat snapping off the tip of his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (she and her husband, John) have seven children, It's lucky
we have two units,'' she says. ``For a month we were sleeping on
one side of the house. You had people from this company telling us
someone would be there and they wouldn't come and when they did the
problem wasn't fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Julieanne follows Hiesler into the master bedroom, still
clutching the check. He is on the tips of his steel-toed boots at
the top of a ladder peeking through the ceiling hatch into an
attic, a most evil place.
</P>
<P>
   All manner of vermin may await you under a house. Tarred pea
gravel may roast you on a roof. These are islands of comfort
compared to the suffocating closeness of an attic, crawling on your
belly as a storm of insulation fiber rains down from lifeless air,
closing each and every sweaty pore.
</P>
<P>
   The most important man in Austin counts the seconds, gathering
strength from the silence. The involuntary spasms of the air
conditioning unit Julieanne had reported have mysteriously
subsided. Hiesler steps down, folds the ladder and invokes the
magic incantation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cycling off, just the way it's supposed to,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This visit has restored enough of Julieanne's faith in service
people to shake Hiesler's hand. He rewards her with a receipt that
indicates no charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no way of knowing how much of what she said was true,''
he says. ``You just have to take it with a smile. The first thing
that goes in the heat is the sense of humor. You got a lot of angry
people out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from where he parks the truck on Wrightwood
Road on the last call of the day is a man wearing no shirt and
sitting in a plastic chair next to the rear end of a rumbling wall
unit air conditioner. The front yard is obscured by beer cans and
bottles; Hiesler is too polite to describe the source of the odor
in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   The motor is going out on this air conditioner, he tells the
man. For the $250 it would cost to replace the motor, the man could
buy a brand-new wall unit, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hiesler is no whistle-blower, but he says there are some people
in the air conditioning industry who would have done the work.
What's more, there are a few who do work that isn't necessary, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   After his employers at Pronto interviewed Hiesler, he says he
interviewed them. He says he told them he couldn't work for a
company that would ask him to cheat. His father didn't teach him
that way.
</P>
<P>
   The most important man in Austin tells the man to pretend he
didn't stop by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why charge him $49.95 for a service call to tell him what he
probably already knows,'' Hiesler says, already thinking about the
cold beers he'll have when he gets home. ``You can see he hasn't
got a whole lot of money. I'm not gonna charge him. You gotta think
about things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: mlisheron(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
