<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOWERHEADS-NUTSBOLTS     08-30 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOWERHEADS-NUTSBOLTS-0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hardest part of replacing a shower head is removing old one
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - A lot of home improvement jobs turn out to be
more complicated than you expect. Others are so easy that one class
at a home-improvement store or 30 minutes helping someone with
experience will teach you all you need to know.
</P>
<P>
   Changing a shower head can fall into either category. The
hardest part is getting the old shower head off. If the old fixture
screws off without any trouble, the whole replacement process will
take less than half an hour. If the old shower head gets stuck, the
job will take more time and elbow grease.
</P>
<P>
   You need a pair of channel-type pliers and an adjustable wrench.
Working with an assistant can be helpful. You'll also need a roll
of Teflon tape.
</P>
<P>
   Home-improvement stores carry a wide selection of shower heads.
Simple replacement shower heads that do the same work as the
original equipment cost as little as $2, but you'll be happier in
the long run with something in the $10 to $30 range.
</P>
<P>
   Low-flow shower heads are designed to cut water and energy
usage. They cut the volume of water through the shower head but
pressurize it so that, theoretically, it feels like you're still
getting about the same amount as with a regular shower head. I
personally don't like low-flow heads because they seem to take
forever to rinse shampoo out of my hair, but they're quite popular
and sell for about $5 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   Massaging shower heads that can be adjusted to pulsating
patterns or fine sprays go for about $25 to $100. They come with
stationary heads or in hand-held models with wands that can direct
the spray to different parts of the body. Less-expensive models
tend to be plain and plastic; more expensive models come in
metallic finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can spend quite a bit for an exotic shower head.
One type gives a broad, rain-like spray. Another has twin heads
that spray two parts of the body at once. And you can find
adjustable-height shower heads that move up and down on a bar to
accommodate people of varying sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are shower systems with multiple shower heads
arrayed up the wall of the shower stall. Installing these systems,
though, is probably beyond the skill level of the typical
do-it-yourselfer and should be left to professional plumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-sensitive showers also are best left to professional
installers, said Ginny Long, a spokeswoman for Moen Inc.
Pressure-sensitive showers adjust themselves to avoid excessive
temperature swings associated with changes in water pressure that
can occur, for example, when a nearby toilet is flushed.
</P>
<P>
   These systems are becoming standard in new construction and in
major bathroom renovations, and cost about 20 percent more than
regular showers, Long said. To install such a system requires
getting behind the wall of the shower enclosure and replacing the
mechanism that mixes hot and cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to reduce scalding risk is to lower the temperature
at the water heater.
</P>
<P>
   To remove an existing shower head, start by wrapping the jaws of
a pair of channel-type pliers or an adjustable wrench with masking
tape. The tape keeps the tools from scratching the finish on the
shower head and shower arm, the angled pipe to which the shower
head is attached.
</P>
<P>
   Use the pliers or wrench to grasp the nut holding the shower
head to the shower arm and apply moderate pressure to loosen it. If
the nut doesn't turn readily, have a helper grasp the shower arm
with a pair of channel-type pliers while you apply more pressure to
the shower-head nut with the wrench. The jaws of both tools should
be wrapped with tape to prevent scratching.
</P>
<P>
   If the shower-arm threads have lime deposits on them, use a
small wire brush dipped in vinegar to clean the threads.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to clean and reuse the old shower head, remove it
and disassemble the portions that can be unscrewed. Poke a stiff
wire or a pipe cleaner through the inlet holes and outlet holes to
clean out deposits. If the shower head has a rubber O-ring, you
should replace it with a new one of the same size.
</P>
<P>
   Flush fresh water through the cleaned head. If it seems usable,
wrap the shower-arm threads with Teflon tape and screw the old head
back on, tightening it with only enough pressure to prevent leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Putting on most new shower heads is a two-step process. Metallic
shower heads require Teflon tape to attach to the shower arm. Some
plastic shower heads don't need tape. Read the installation
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where tape is required, wrap Teflon tape around the
threads on the shower arm. The tape both lubricates the connection
and helps seal the joint.
</P>
<P>
   The second step is tightening the fastening nut onto the shower
arm. Using one hand to hold the new shower head at the angle you
want it to face, apply moderate pressure to tighten the nut that
holds it to the shower arm. Don't bear down on the wrench to
tighten the nut; the connection should be firm, not tight. Many
plastic shower heads can be tightened by hand and don't need a
wrench or pliers at all. Turn on the water to see if the joint
leaks and tighten it a bit more if it does.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: jamescummings(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
