<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-30 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KNOW YOUR WEAKNESSES, BEFORE AND AFTER THE JOB INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you want to understand why relying too much
on job interviews is an idiotic way to hire people, think about one
of the all-time favorite interview questions and how conventional
wisdom says you should answer it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your biggest weakness?'' If you ask this and let the
applicant give a pat answer, you're wasting your time. If you stop
and think about it, anyone you hire who seriously believes in one
of those cliched answers would have a complete lack of
self-awareness and self-discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Probably not what you had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   So what IS your biggest weakness? A lot of job-hunting experts
say applicants should answer with something innocuous, with one
possible answer being that they work too hard and don't know when
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   If an applicant says his biggest problem is being a workaholic,
you probably will just move on and not give it another thought.
After all, it's not like he said something that would be a real
problem, like ``I just love to embezzle money'' or ``I can't keep
my hands off of co-workers'' or even ``I have no weaknesses. I am
the messiah, here to wash away your sins, cure world hunger and
wipe out Old Navy commercials.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time, just for the heck of it, give the answer another
thought. It can mean one of three things:
</P>
<P>
   _ He thinks you are easily snowed.
</P>
<P>
   If this is someone you're sincere about hiring, the interview is
the beginning of a long-term relationship. Do you really want your
subordinates to think you're that big of a sucker?
</P>
<P>
   _ He has you confused with a therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are truly workaholics do have a serious problem. They
are so focused on work that they have lost touch with reality, and
it has the potential to destroy their families and personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   But someone who does see that as a serious problem and has any
sense at all would get therapy or enroll in a 12-step program or
talk about it with close friends, not offer it as an answer to some
cliched job interview question. It's too personal to share with
someone you barely know, much less a prospective employer.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly some prospects, including recovering workaholics,
might say they want to limit themselves to a 40-hour workweek, but
they would consider that a lifestyle choice, not a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   _ He sincerely thinks that is his biggest weakness.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you hire him. And then, being a talented worker, he
strives to overcome his biggest weakness. Where does that leave
you?
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. His biggest weakness is that he works too hard. How,
oh how, can he overcome that? Maybe he could work less. That's it!
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations. You've hired someone who has already peaked.
You get to join him for that long downhill ride to retirement.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, though, he has bigger weaknesses, but he's
oblivious to them. That means he probably has an inflated view of
his own work or will resist you if you discover weaknesses down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is true if the applicant offers up any sort of
innocuous weakness; he's either snowing you or is clueless. Take
your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Another way applicants dodge the question is to point to some
past weakness, and how they've overcome it. That reminds me of a
wisecrack a friend used to make when we were teen-agers. ``I used
to be conceited,'' he'd say, ``but now I'm perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Pin the applicant down to get a real answer, or don't bother
asking the question.
</P>
<P>
   Good workers know they have weaknesses. They strive to overcome
them. That's what makes them good workers, rather than complacent
workers.
</P>
<P>
   From a worker's standpoint, understanding your weaknesses is
crucial to moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you know your weaknesses, you won't know what things you
need to improve upon or work around. Sometimes the best way to
handle a weakness is to team up with someone who complements you.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're a wonderful saleswoman who's lousy when it comes to
paperwork. Sure, you could make yourself a better paper pusher, but
it might be better to hire a detail-oriented assistant, so you can
spend more time doing what you do best: selling.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about turning something weak into something strong.
That applies to job interview questions, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
