<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-COWBOY-TOURISM-HNS &LR;      08-30 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-TOURISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS COWPOKE ENJOYS HIS AMBASSADORIAL ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZEKE MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDERA, Texas _ It doesn't take a rope and a whip to get
foreigners to visit Texas, but they sure help.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional tools of cowboys are public relations devices in
the gifted hands of Kevin Fitzpatrick, a trick roper who serves as
an international ambassador for the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick, 42, this year has cracked bullwhips at Canadians
and lassoed Swiss conventioneers on trips arranged by the San
Antonio Convention and Visitors Bureau and the Texas Department of
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick's friendly demeanor and playful antics have only
enhanced the international love affair with the American cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really ropes them in,'' said Gwen Spain, of the state
economic development agency.
</P>
<P>
   Gerlinde VanWerdt of the convention and visitors bureau said
there is more to Fitzpatrick than fancy tricks and cowboy looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really like him,'' she said. ``He's very personable. He
smiles and talks to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick said he loves meeting new people and promoting
Texas, a job for which he is not paid. Only his expenses are
covered.
</P>
<P>
   While on duty, he doesn't develop a thick drawl, feign having
bowlegs or put on other airs to fulfill expectations of the cowboy
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always myself,'' he said. ``I've always been a polite
person and had manners. I don't dip or chew or smoke or cuss.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that he comes from Bandera, the town in the Hill
Country northwest of San Antonio that bills itself as ``The Cowboy
Capital of the World.'' People here are happy to call him one of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is not just a show cowboy. He's a real cowboy. He keeps
his horses, he ropes on his range and he's got cattle,'' said
Patricia Moore, of the Bandera County Convention and Visitors
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick honed his skills working at festivals, rodeos, dude
ranches and parties around Texas over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   His horse, Wet, is a big part of his local act, but doesn't make
the out-of-country tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get on a horse seven different ways, like they do in the
movies,'' Fitzpatrick said in a rare display of self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   He is impressive nonetheless performing solo, whether jumping
through roomy lassos, rolling lassos across his shoulders or
dancing as lassos whirl around his feet.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he and some roping friends gathered at the Dixie Dude
Ranch, where Fitzpatrick was hired as a ranch hand in 1980 and
still appears regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Fitzpatrick for a little friendly competition was trick
roper Fred Schneider, a native of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand was Nathalie Menu, a trick roper on vacation from
France, where she recently began teaching the Texas two-step at her
dance studio.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider and Fitzpatrick competed last year in Munich to see
who could do the most Texas skips in one minute. They tied, each
jumping back and forth 79 times through a spinning lasso.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Fitzpatrick, who has made a living from his roping for a
decade, Schneider has a real job and does rope tricks for fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see me on a horse, I look silly,'' said Schneider, 45.
``If you see Kevin on a horse, he looks homogeneous. The horse, the
rope and Kevin are one.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay Conoly, the dude ranch's manager, called Fitzpatrick a
natural choice for cowboy ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even drinks Lone Star Beer, God help him,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
