<SLUG> BC-COOLMAX-FABRIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOLMAX TAKES ON TORRID TEXAS SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fashion magazines and catalogs have been featuring wool and
cuddly knits for weeks now. Meantime, we swelter through the long
Texas summer. It ends in October? Right?
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the world begins to bundle up, we are still in
search of the perfect summer clothes.
</P>
<P>
   We turn to CoolMax, the fabric DuPont introduced for sportswear.
No longer is CoolMax reserved for the gym or the golf course. This
summer, we've seen it show up in dresses, skirts, cardigans and
T-shirts suitable for the office. We've seen it in Casual Friday
polo shirts for guys, too.
</P>
<P>
   CoolMax, a fabric of Dacron fiber, is very lightweight; it
resists wrinkles, wicks moisture away quickly and dries much faster
than cotton. All of that makes it a great pick for a summer fabric.
Plus, it's great to stash in a suitcase. It unpacks ready to wear,
and it can be washed in a hotel-room sink and hung to dry without
needing to be ironed.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, we love the simple things in life. For now, forget the wool.
Our favorite spot for finding street-smart CoolMax is
www.travelsmith.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
