<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6307 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-HARDAWAY-0830-COX     08-30 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HARDAWAY-0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hardaway says no love is in the air
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The love of money is the root of all
evil, the scriptures say, but Tim Hardaway has his own
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Love is money, he believes, or so it is implied in the angry
avalanche of words he's pouring over reporters in Hawaii. There, in
paradise with the U.S. Olympic basketball team, the Miami Heat
point guard purports to be in purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency isn't supposed to be this frustrating for a
five-time All-Star like Timmy. Free agency is supposed to be a time
to savor, a time to be courted by NBA teams with championship
dreams, a time to ask for the moon, or at least the monetary
equivalent of what it took to send Neil Armstrong there.
</P>
<P>
   Something changed for Hardaway, however, something he can't see
and won't acknowledge. He got hurt, repeatedly. He got old,
inevitably. And he became, consequently, more of a health risk than
a supernatural contract reward warrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deserve a lot more respect than I'm getting,'' Hardaway
said, popping off about being made to wait on a new deal from Pat
Riley. ``I'm getting no love from the Miami Heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Love makes the world go 'round, the songwriter says, but
Hardaway has his own interpretation. Love makes the world revolve
around him, the hustling hero who has pushed his 6-foot body to
such heights over 11 NBA seasons that there's just got to be a $20
million lifetime achievement award in it.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's threatening, against his agent's advice, to sign a
one-year bargain basement deal with Indiana. He's playing in the
Olympics all next month, a deeply satisfying career highlight, and
asking the Heat to accept his personal guarantee that the
additional wear and tear on his knees and various other body parts
won't lead to another post-season breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is Hardaway's 34th birthday. Three more seasons seems a
perfectly reasonable goal to him, and at a very high level of
competition. Of course, it also seemed possible to him several
years back that the Heat might earn the everlasting honor of
knocking off the Chicago Bulls while Michael Jordan still was in
uniform. This is the aggressive attitude you want in your point
guard. In fact, it's probably what Riley loves most about the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, there's that word again. Love, in Hardaway's mind, means
never having to say you're all tapped out making other big deals
this summer. Pay me back, it means, for taking less to sign a
four-year deal with Miami in 1996 than might have been available in
Houston or New York. You owe me, big time, even though it really
was Gary Payton you wanted all along.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing is, all this ranting is almost certainly irrelevant.
The Heat aren't about to make any further personnel moves until the
Brian Grant trade is official, a formality that should be announced
this week. Only then will Riley turn his attention to Miami's proud
point man, unbound by salary cap concerns thanks to the wiggle room
allowed in the re-signing of a returning player.
</P>
<P>
   When Hardaway finally gets happy, it will be because the Heat
need him, not because they love him. If respect and genuine
affection alone were enough to protect a player, P.J. Brown would
have stayed on Riley's roster forever.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing will heal this breach. Hardaway might not love
Riley right now, but he needs the Heat right back.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: davegeorge(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
