<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RUNNING GAME IS KEY FOR THE 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The focus of the 49ers offense shouldn't be on
Terrell Owens, Jerry Rice, Jeff Garcia, Rick Mirer, J.J. Stokes or
Tai Streets _ even though they have proven worthy. The constant
emphasis on the team's passing game misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are a run team. That's what they do best and that's
where the focus of their offense should lie. If the team wants to
eke out every inch of success they can muster this year, they'll do
it by running.
</P>
<P>
   The team seems bound by tradition to hoist the ball skyward even
when logic dictates otherwise. The 49ers led the league in rushing
yardage and average yards per carry last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the team only rushed the ball 418 times. Twenty-one teams
rushed the ball more often, including Buffalo, which ran 101 more
times than the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Run naysayers say the 49ers were forced to pass last season
because they fell behind early in many of their games. But several
times, the 49ers abandoned the run far too soon.
</P>
<P>
   The offense's most talented player last year was running back
Charlie Garner, who darted and shimmied his way to 1,229 yards and
an impressive 5.1 yards per carry average. That's the highest
yardage per tote of the top 20 rushers from 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While Garner deserves credit for his production, the 49ers also
led the league a year earlier with Garrison Hearst, when he romped
for a franchise record 1,502 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the most talented players on offense the last few
years are not Hearst, Garner or even Steve Young. A strong argument
could be made for the guys with their bellies flowing over their
trousers. We're talking Ray Brown, Chris Dalman, Greg Clark,
Derrick Deese and Dave Fiore.
</P>
<P>
   These are the guys who brush aside defensive linemen and bowl
over linebackers so that Garner and Hearst can run unimpeded. They
could be the best run-blocking unit in the NFL right now, even
though Dalman will miss the season with a neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Jeremy Newberry, isn't as experienced, but he's
a more imposing physical player, which could make the 49ers even
better in the run game.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Jonas Lewis and Travis Jervey, players with resumes
devoid of impressive NFL rushing credentials. But, by the end of
preseason, Lewis was the division's leading rusher in exhibition
yards, and Jervey was averaging 4.8 per carry.
</P>
<P>
   And the 49ers could use a strong running game right now. Even
though the defense is improved, they're still vulnerable. By
running and controlling the clock, the 49ers would keep opposing
defenses on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the strategy could protect Garcia, who's still learning
the offense. Garcia could be more effective if he threw less. It
would mean fewer interceptions and sacks.
</P>
<P>
   And should defenses gear up to stop the 49ers' run, the passing
game would open up like a blooming rose. Single coverage on the
49ers talented corps of wide receivers would abound.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the ball on the ground could also slow down the blitz,
which shackled the passing game and led to sacks, interceptions and
the career-ending concussion to Steve Young. The right running
plays can burn the blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Running will also benefit an offensive line that only returns
Brown to the same position (right guard) he played last season.
Offensive lines love to run, and there's no better way to establish
chemistry among the group.
</P>
<P>
   Even the great 49ers offenses of the past ran more than most
realize. Of the 49ers' five championship teams, four finished the
regular season with more rushes than passes, including the 1981
club.
</P>
<P>
   With Joe Montana and renowned wide receivers Freddie Solomon and
Dwight Clark, the team ran 560 times and passed 517.
</P>
<P>
   Success with the run is also evident in the more recent era
under coach Steve Mariucci. He wisely decided to run the ball after
Rice and Young were injured in the 1997 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being without Rice, the 49ers went to the NFC title game
that season, the farthest any Mariucci coached team has ventured.
</P>
<P>
   The current team's run game is no passing fancy, and if the
49ers are wise they'll use it _ often.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
