<HEADLINE>
S&AMP;P 500'S RISE OFFERS SCANT EVIDENCE OF BROAD NEW RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may have noticed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index is
quietly inching toward record territory, modest though it is, in
these waning days of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Our first thought: that broadening market trend pundits keep
talking about, said to be widening Wall Street's circle of winners,
must be pushing lots of stocks higher to elevate the S&AMP;P near a
record.
</P>
<P>
   But when we looked closely, it was hard to find any evidence of
a broader rally producing more winners among the stocks that
currently make up that single, though important, stock index. The
breadth of gains inside the S&AMP;P 500 this year is virtually
unchanged from the performance of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Though the S&AMP;P 500 is 18 points away from an all-time high of
1527 set in March, this is not turning out to be a banner year for
the index. The S&AMP;P 500 has gained 2.8 percent so far in 2000, far
below its 21 percent advance of last year but much better than the
decline of more than 9 percent it had suffered in the first months
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts prefer broadly advancing stock markets, like the
bullish tide of 1995 that raised a large majority of S&AMP;P 500 stocks
and pushed the overall index up 37.6 percent that year.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of activity is considered more stable and much
healthier than markets propelled by a few high-flying stocks that
can mask a malaise _ or outright losses _ among a large percentage
of other equities.
</P>
<P>
   This much is true in 2000 so far: There are more different types
of stocks making gains in the S&AMP;P 500. There is also some evidence
of a larger number of advancing S&AMP;P stocks since the spring and
broadening gains may in fact be taking place in the overall market.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that last year there was a very narrow rise in
stock prices because there was only one kind of stock driving the
index, technology,'' said Hugh Johnson of First Albany Corp. ``This
year it's not just tech, but other sectors are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the similarities between one year and the next
are much more striking than any evidence of changing tides (One
important detail in the way we measured S&AMP;P 500 stocks: we followed
only the stocks that currently make up the index, including some
that were added in 1999 or earlier this year).
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, a total of 242 stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 have
posted some sort of gain for investors. The same group produced 243
stocks that were in the black throughout all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, similarly ranked stocks of this year and 1999
produced gains or losses that closely resembled each other. For
example, FleetBoston Financial Corp. is the S&AMP;P 500's 179th
best-performing stock so far this year with a return of 14 percent.
The same group's 179th rank stock of 1999, Unocal Corp., earned
14.99 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of parity, or at least something close to it, held
true through more than 400 places on each year's list.
</P>
<P>
   Performance was dramatically different on the top of the list,
where gains were much higher last year. That mostly reflectedly
hyper-growth that propelled smaller companies into the S&AMP;P 500 for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the top five gainers for 1999 were added to the index
that year or in 2000. They include technology hotshots like
Qualcomm Inc. (up 2,619 percent), JDS Uniphase (ahead by 830
percent), and Sapient Corp. of Cambridge, Mass. (up 403 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Top performers in the S&AMP;P 500 so far this year represent a
broader slice of the market, including the expected technology
industry hotshots as well as other companies like Reebok Inc. of
Canton, Mass. and Nabisco Group Holdings Inc.
</P>
<P>
   They also have generated more muted returns. The top S&AMP;P 500
stock so far this year, Scientific-Atlanta Inc., is up about 187
percent in 2000 to date.
</P>
<P>
   There are a handful of industries with S&AMP;P 500 stocks that
clearly have performed well this year, especially drugs, biotech,
and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But others still can't get anyone to pay attention, despite
attractive valuations caused by weak stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares about the industrial companies,'' said value
investor Scott Black of Delphi Management in Boston. ``People worry
if the economy close that their earnings power will collapse in a
lot of these companies. And nobody gets excited over 5 to 7 percent
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the S&AMP;P 500 index only represents a slice of the
stock market and many strategists, like Ned Riley of State Street
Global Advisors, argue that the important shift has begun among the
hottest technology stocks in the Nasdaq index.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that some investment money hot for New Economy
companies has tapered off, but probably continues to chase some
stocks too aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
