<P>
   GOOD-JUNK (Undated) _ The pin on Mimi Mannix's hat said it all.
``Junk 'til you drop'' it read, which is why Ms. Mannix was outside
the Strudel Haus in Covington, Ky., on a Thursday afternoon
painting a giant pig. Like a multitude of less colorful people, Ms.
Mannix, an Indiana collectibles dealer had come to this musty
little town across the Ohio River from Cincinnati to shop. ``I'm
selling, I'm buying, I'm doing my pig,'' Ms. Mannix said, dipping
into a vat of pink enamel. ``I'm having fun.'' Here at the
northernmost tip of an annual event known as the 450-Mile Route 127
Corridor Sale, it was no wonder why. A banner spanning Main Street
hailed, ``Welcome to the start of the world's largest yard sale.''
On the reverse it said, ``Welcome to the end of the world's largest
yard sale.'' Covington was the final destination if you started
your journey at the other end, 450 miles away in Gadsden, Ala. Like
everything about this multistate flea market, it was all in how you
looked at it. By Frank DeCaro.
</P>
