<SLUG> BC-MINORCOLUMN0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barbie still has intrinsic value for parts only)
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - I've been feeling a little rough around
the edges lately, what with ``Survivor'' over and all, so thank God
for mothers and their ability to divert. Mine called the other day
under the pretense of wanting to know how her youngest grandson is
doing in the fourth grade when, lo and behold, she let the real cat
out of the bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emily,'' she asked casually, ``do you still have your
Barbies?''
</P>
<P>
   She asked this as though she and I have discussed Barbie, Midge
and Ken and their black patent-leather case every day for the past
37 years, which we have not.
</P>
<P>
   When this casual inquisition began, my heart leaped, my breath
stopped, for even at age 44, it's difficult to disappoint one's
mother. How could I tell her Ken's arm is missing? Indeed, Ken
himself has not been seen in months.
</P>
<P>
   Midge is in good shape, freckles and all, but Barbie _ well, she
has a little problem with her head.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps falling off.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I saw Midge and Babs, they were sitting on a shelf
in our bedroom next to my white wedding boots, Barbie's loose head
sitting in Midge's lap. Please, don't write me with your analysis
of what all that might mean. I don't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' my mother continued, ignoring my tense breathing.
``I heard those dolls are worth $4,000.'' I have to admit, I had a
brief flash of hope. Four grand! Then I remembered the source. This
was the same woman who once suggested you could die from one puff
of a marijuana cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom,'' I said, with daughterly reproach, ``they're not worth
$4,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I only know what people tell me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you've got to give a person her due when it's her due,
and my mother gets all the Barbie dues. It was she who insisted,
sometimes quite loudly, that I keep those Barbies. Indeed, she
pretty much forced me to lug my entire youth around the country
after I graduated from college.
</P>
<P>
   Baby pictures. Nancy Drew books. The Barbies _ Ken, Midge and
the Queen herself.
</P>
<P>
   I did what she told me, my first real act of obedience, although
somewhere along the line, I lost the Nancy Drew books (still
hearing about that one), and some of the baby pictures got wet. But
Barbie and her friends? They're made of fine, fine plastic. They
survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep those Barbies for your kids,'' my mother would tell
me when I'd call collect from remote corners of the earth. ``One
day they'll be worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day came, and I got married and had a kid, and I made
the mistake of getting out the Barbies and allowing actual children
to play with them, a little something that caused Ken to turn up
one-armed and missing and Barbie to lose her head.
</P>
<P>
   And now this. The awful truth.
</P>
<P>
   My Barbies are pretty much worthless.
</P>
<P>
   The 1963 Barbie Graduation Doll. She's worth $120 or so. The
1963 vintage Barbie in mint condition is going for about $100. But
plain old dirty, tired, been-around-the-country Barbie?
</P>
<P>
   She's worth about 50 bucks. I will not be paying off my son's
new braces with the plastic pieces of my past. Indeed, I would have
been better off keeping track of Nancy Drew. Story of my life. And
my mother's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
