<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6349 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-L.A.-CLUB-LADN &LR;      08-30 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-CLUB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DORF'S FACTORY DIRECT
</HEADLINE>
  Edgy N.Y.C. transplant hoping to mesh with mainstream L.A. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a long trip, in a lot of ways, from downtown New York to
downtown Hollywood, from the avant-garde edges of jazz and blues to
the absolute epicenter of mass-market pop music.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly the trip Michael Dorf is taking with the
Knitting Factory, his edgy New York club that has limned the
fringes of popular music for 13 years, with the opening of a
sleekly designed second venue just a hop, skip and walk of fame
down the block from Mann's Chinese Theater on a Hollywood
Boulevard, a venue that is trying to reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, Dorf is doing it as much out of love of
music as of money, a bit of heresy in a town known for figuring all
the angles on any entertainment venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money isn't the end goal,'' said Dorf, founder and president
of the club and its parent company, KnitMedia, which also runs a
record label and music-oriented Web site (www.knittingfactory.com).
``The end goal is to have a compelling business model that balances
commercial and artistic needs. It's a huge idea, and you know
what's amazing is that we've delivered on the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The club is tucked behind the Hollywood Entertainment Museum in
a long- struggling commercial center a block west of a massive $300
million development project whose centerpiece is the Chinese
Theater. Dorf's neighbor won't open for another year, but is
expected to draw huge crowds to the reviving Hollywood area when it
does.
</P>
<P>
   Dorf is hoping to enjoy some spillover from the revival, but his
club is actually constructed as much for people who can't make it
through the club doors as for those who can.
</P>
<P>
   It comes loaded with high-tech features, such as computer kiosks
in the bar where you can literally share a face-to-face virtual
drink with someone in the New York club. The wall of one hallway is
lined with computers connecting to the Web sites of several online
partners. Gas-plasma flat- screen displays ring the bar area,
continually televising concerts and other activities at the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The club is wired with high-speed Net connections so it can
Webcast high-quality broadband versions of concerts and other
events it is hosting. Wedged between the club's two performance
spaces and visible from the bar and restaurant is a glassed-in
digital control room that oversees the technology and cameras
involved in televising on-stage events.
</P>
<P>
   Mix in a post-modern design for the restaurant and bar, large
and small performance spaces that are all polished wood and steel,
and you have a very different Knitting Factory from its New York
progenitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clubs don't look identical,'' said Ric Dube, an analyst
with Webnoize, a Massachussetts-based Internet music consultancy.
``The New York club is awfully ragged; you can see the pipes. The
L.A. one, the lines are cleaner, the colors are softer, there's a
lot more attention paid to a cool sleekness.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the Net capabilities of the new Knitting Factory that
make it more than just another club, Dube said. That ability is
crucial to Dorf's vision of putting Knitting Factories in major
cities around the world, the next to be in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we build something that on its veneer works like a club
and can be profitable, but with the backing of a studio to create
branding content?'' Dorf asks. ``More and more people are going to
be online listening to their music, whether it's Napster or
downloadable concerts. But those people who are getting their music
via their computer or Palm Pilot are still going to need to and
want to go to a club. And we've got a great club. People are going
to want to see music there.''
</P>
<P>
   The club also comes with artist-friendly touches such as
oversize stages connected directly to a loading dock by a series of
easy-on-the-back ramps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we went with a larger stage and camera platforms:
If an artist has an amazing experience performing there, that's
their stage and their home from then on,'' Dorf said. ``That's the
place they want that performance captured. We want the artist to
feel it's as great a musical experience as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting the club opened, however, has proved expensive and
frustrating. More than two years in the planning, the club was
supposed to open in mid-June with a big kickoff party.
</P>
<P>
   But construction was nowhere near done, forcing the cancellation
of the event, and many more concerts after it, costing the company
more than $250,000 just to pay off guarantees and appearance fees
to high-profile musicians who couldn't play. The club lost another
$100,000 in fixed overhead costs and had to forgo unknown amounts
of revenue that it had counted on.
</P>
<P>
   Dorf finally opened the club in mid-August with lower-profile
acts while work continued on many of the club's high-tech features.
A grand-opening event, featuring New York stalwart Arto Lindsay and
others, is now scheduled for Sept. 18, and Dorf is upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything paid off,'' he said. ``The layout to capture
content and deliver it to broadband platforms means we're able to
get stuff out there in a significantly more functional way than we
have been able to do in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   It's uncertain, however, how Dorf will translate his New York
booking policies to the more mainstream tastes of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Knitting Factory New York says in its literature that ``downtown
isn't just an address,'' a reference to the quirky tastes it has
fostered by repeatedly booking challenging artists such as John
Zorn, Lindsay and Philip Glass. But Dorf freely acknowledges L.A.
will force changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, `downtown,' as almost the word `jazz,' has incredible
ambiguity,'' Dorf said. ``The whole concept of not being a ZIP code
means it can be adjusted. We're going to reach into a much more
mainstream, pop, radio-friendly group of bookings.''
</P>
<P>
   The two performance areas _ one capable of holding about 440
people, the other only 40, both closed off from the bar and dining
room _ will provide greater flexibilty, Dorf said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to touch on acts that are a little bit downtown, like
Elliott Smith or Martin Sexton, but are still commercial enough
that they will draw an audience,'' Dorf said. ``L.A. will be more
poppy, more reflective of Los Angeles. But thank God for that
second room. We can worry more about the aesthetics there.''
</P>
<P>
   The club's construction headaches cost it the chance to book
some natural allies, such as Marc Ribot, the avant-garde jazz and
rock guitarist who has frequently played the New York Knitting
Factory. But for his Sept. 6 Los Angeles performance, Ribot and his
Los Cubanos Postizos band will play the Conga Room, a frustration
for Dorf, who says his club just wasn't ready when it came time to
book the Ribot concert.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ribot said the Knitting Factory faces some serious
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen how the Knitting Factory will play into
the L.A. scene,'' Ribot said. ``In New York, it brought a
medium-sized venue where bands like my own can perform. In the
past, it's been more open to experimental music, but that seems to
be changing. At the last Knitting Factory festival, they moved
towards mainstream jazz, which is unfortunate, because I always
thought experimental music was their raison d'etre.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ribot added that he hopes the Knitting Factory Hollywood
will feed a Los Angeles new-music scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, a scene grows into the space,'' he said. ``You
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Monaco _ a DJ, founding partner in the Hollywood club
Vynyl and head of international marketing at Spike Radio _ said the
Knitting Factory can create a worldwide club franchise that can
accommodate the tours of edgier, mid-size artists, much as House of
Blues revived a mainstream slice of that same concert business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be there was either the large national tour or the
small-venue shows,'' said Monaco. ``Then House of Blues came along
and somewhat commoditized it. In relative terms, it wasn't a
straight sell-out type of venture, because it helped put a lot of
alternative acts onto stages where people will go see them. Now
these people can go headline a show.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the New York sensibility translates is a trickier
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing in New York works for them in New York,''
Monaco said. ``But a lot of New York people come out to L.A. and
find out this is L.A. They're going to have to appeal somewhat to
what works in L.A. These guys are really going to have to take it
to a broader audience. I actually think they're going to be not
avant-garde, but to the left of center.''
</P>
<P>
   Webnoize's Dube thinks the translation can be done, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful company run by a very nice music lover,''
said Dube. ``The Knitting Factory has always been open-minded to
include anything and everything. The experiment is to see how L.A.
adopts a New York City sensibility and makes it its own. And I
think there will be a way to make it L.A.'s own.''
</P>
<P>
   (Fred Shuster contributed to this story.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
