A6353 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TEXAS-SATS-HNS &LR;      08-30 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SATS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAT SCORES IN TEXAS REMAIN STATIC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDMUND S. TIJERINA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Math scores for Texas high school students taking
the Scholastic Assessment Test were static in 1999 even though the
nationwide scores hit a 30-year high. Educators and business
leaders in the state said the scores show that Texas' education
reforms now must move to the high school level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to have built a four-lane highway for the elementary
division and it's beautiful,'' said State Board of Education member
Joe Bernal. ``And we're driving right into a marshland, which is
the secondary areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, mean scores on the SAT this year rose 3 points over
in 1999, from 1016 to 1019, the College Board announced Tuesday.
Math scores rose 3 points to a 30-year high, from 511 to 514, while
verbal scores held at 505.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, scores for the math and verbal tests combined remained
below the national average, at 993.
</P>
<P>
   The math score went up a point, from 499 to 500, while the
verbal score dropped a point, from 494 to 493.
</P>
<P>
   The SAT, along with the American College Test or ACT, have been
used as a college admissions standard for decades and long have
been criticized as not accurately reflecting the abilities of
low-income and minority students. Scores on each section of the
test, verbal and math, range from 200 to a perfect 800.
</P>
<P>
   Scores for Mexican-Americans in Texas remained below the
national and state averages _ up a single point from 904 to 905 for
both verbal and math scores.
</P>
<P>
   For blacks, the combined score rose slightly but remained low,
from 847 to 850. The scores for white students rose from 1048 to
1051.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of Texas high school students
taking the SAT increased.
</P>
<P>
   Of the class of 2000, 52 percent of the state's graduating
seniors took the test, or 108,919 students. Last year, 50 percent
of the state's seniors took the test. Both years are significantly
higher than the national average, in which 44 percent of the
country's students took the exam.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Texas Education Agency say that the increased
number of students taking the test is responsible for the scores
staying put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad so many Texas young people are interested in going to
college,'' Education Commissioner Jim Nelson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, students throughout the state have shown consistently
higher scores on the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills, a
standardized exam students take in grades 3-8 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a record-breaking 80 percent of students in the state
passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   John Stevens, executive director of the Texas Business and
Education Coalition, said the combination of results shows the need
to concentrate on a coming 11th-grade exit test, which will be
designed to reflect skills that high school graduates will need in
the working world and in college.
</P>
<P>
   The organization formed in response to complaints from business
leaders that they were shut out of the state's efforts to improve
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have focused on lower grades, and that has worked,''
Stevens said. ``Now we have to focus on the performance of students
in the upper grades.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
