<HEADER>
A6355 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-DOMINGO-VOIGT31     08-30 0252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-DOMINGO-VOIGT31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For love, tenor turns on the power
 &HT;    By Pierre Ruhe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's a lyrical Spanish tenor doing belting out Teutonic love
songs? Following the composer's orders, it turns out. Richard
Wagner, master of heavy German opera, wanted his music sung like
Italian bel canto, with smooth phrasing and an emphasis on the long
line. Placido Domingo is one of the only singers around with enough
thrust to carry the roles of Siegfried and Tristan and bring them
to full blossom with effortless beauty of tone. But he's
approaching retirement and will likely never sing these
ultra-demanding roles complete. For now, these excerpts _ the final
scene from ``Siegfried'' and the charged love scene from Act 2 of
``Tristan und Isolde'' (in Wagner's own curious concert
arrangement) _ are the among the best on disc. Domingo's love
interests are sung by Deborah Voigt. As Brunnhilde, she doesn't
have the vocal acting abilities of her paramour, which leads to
some imbalance in passion. Yet her tone is flowing and elegant.
London's Covent Garden Orchestra performs magnificently, conducted
by Antonio Pappano.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on EMI Records: www.emiclassics.com/
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``Domingo and Voigt sing Wagner Love Duets''
</P>
<P>
   Placido Domingo, Deborah Voigt. EMI Classics. 57 minutes Grade:
A
</P>
<P>
   _Pierre Ruhe writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
