<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6356 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS31-COX     08-30 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS31-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CD mini reviews
</P>
<P>
   By Russ DeVault, Don Melvin, Eileen Drennen and Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BLUEGRASS
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Mon _ The Songs of Bill Monroe''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Skaggs Family Records. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Most tribute records are about making money. But here's one
steeped in respect, because most, if not all, of the artists played
with, or at least stood onstage in awe of, Bill Monroe, the creator
of bluegrass, who died in 1996 at 84. I expected Monroe protege
Ricky Skaggs and veterans who grew up in Appalachia (notably, Dolly
Parton, Steve Wariner and Dwight Yoakam) to expertly perform
Monroe's songs. But what a nice surprise to hear solid salutes from
John Fogerty (``Blue Moon of Kentucky''), the Dixie Chicks (``Walk
Softly on This Heart of Mine'') and Travis Tritt (``My Little
Georgia Rose,'' supposedly Monroe's ode to a child born out of
wedlock). The master of that high, lonesome sound that is bluegrass
would be proud.
</P>
<P>
   _Russ DeVault
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Bill Monroe:
www.billmonroebluegrass.com
</P>
<P>
   More on Skaggs Family Records: www.skaggsfamilyrecords.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Home to Me''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bibb. EarthBeat! 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Recently, several artists _ notably, Corey Harris, Guy Davis and
Keb' Mo' _ have worked to revive acoustic blues, those from which
all others sprang. Add now Eric Bibb, who with this graceful album
establishes himself as an innovative voice in a historic genre. The
son of a folk singer, he was exposed early to Pete Seeger, Odetta
and Bob Dylan; he colors these 13 songs _ 10 are originals _ with
tinges of folk, gospel and pop. Purists may say it ain't the blues,
but Bibb honors tradition by breathing life into it. On two songs,
he haunts us with only his voice, guitar and soul. He ends with
``Sing Your Song,'' a finger-popping duet with that old revivalist
Taj Majal.
</P>
<P>
   _Don Melvin
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Eric Bibb, EarthBeat! Records:
www.earthbeatrecords.com
</P>
<P>
   /ErthBeatLinks.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``My Heart's in Memphis: The Songs of Dan Penn''
</P>
<P>
   Irma Thomas. Rounder. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Dan Penn and Irma Thomas have the kind of deep soul
cred you can't buy. The legendary Memphis songwriter has penned
such classics as ``Dark End of the Street'' and ``Do Right Woman.''
The Soul Queen of New Orleans has the kind of earthy alto that can
shake you to your roots. Their collaboration here is unfortunately
not as strong as their separate efforts. Though it has its high
points _ the evocative title track, steeped in moody sax and
Hammond B3, the slow-burning ``Not Enough Time to Change'' and the
vintage lament ``Woman Left Lonely,'' written with Spooner Oldham _
the album doesn't have the kind of flow you'd expect from a
collaboration this fine. The highs aren't as high, nor the lows as
low, as on the best Memphis soul recordings (think Hi Records, Stax
and Aretha) _ too much just slides along in a middling modern
groove. Penn says in the liner notes he wrote new songs because he
didn't want Thomas to have to record his old stuff. Hate to dispute
the master on that one, but setting Irma's voice loose on Penn's
best material would have made for an entire album of keepers.
</P>
<P>
   _Eileen M. Drennen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Irma Thomas:
harp.rounder.com/rounder/artists/thomas
</P>
<P>
   irma/profile.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Presents: The Best of the Summer Concert Series''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. NBC Records. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   NBC isn't as hip as MTV, but network producers know a good
performance when they hear it. Most of the time, anyway. This
collection, though spotty as a rug in a coffeeshop, gathers some
strong musical outtakes from recent ``Today'' spots. Sheryl Crow
delivers a blistering reworking of ``If It Makes You Happy,''
Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish get funky on ``Hold My Hand,'' and Brian
Setzer obviates the need for coffee with a hyperactive ``Rock This
Town.'' Too bad the also-rans get equal time: Lionel Richie's
insipid ``Easy,'' Phil Collins' bloodless gutting of ``You Can't
Hurry Love'' and Amy Grant's pale ``Baby Baby.'' The CD also
includes some cheeky, wince-inducing artist intros by Katie Couric
and Co. and a goofy ``Theme 2000'' track. Still, the highlights
make the disc worth your while _ even as the lesser efforts make
you grateful for the CD ``skip'' function.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : www.msnbc.com/news
</P>
<P>
   /TODAYfront.asp?ta &QC; y
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
