<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MONONOKE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A natural enchantress
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillsepie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not Disney kid stuff. There's so much going on in this
astonishing, mystically complex animated epic from Japan that it
makes Wagner's Ring Cycle look like the Teletubbies. It's a ``once
upon a time'' tale about the battle between nature and
civilization. Boldly innovative yet eerily innocent, it's the sort
of thing you simply have to see for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a fan site:
http://clubs.yahoo.com/clubs/mononokehime
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Big Kahuna'' (R) _ This one's well worth your time for
the terrific acting. Three salesmen _ a corrosive cynic (Kevin
Spacey), a resigned old-timer (Danny DeVito) and an eager-beaver
newcomer (Bob Facinelli) _ wait in their version of hell, i.e., a
hospitality suite in Wichita, for the chance to land that one
all-important client. Spacey and DeVito's performances are bracing
and brainy. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ERG
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Deterrence'' (R) _ In 2008, an eclectic collection of folks
is stranded in a Colorado diner. Among them, the U.S. president
(Kevin Pollak). Then comes news that Saddam Hussein's son has
invaded Kuwait. What's a second-string prez to do? Why, drop the
bomb, of course. The film wants to be a taut nuclear-showdown
debate, but the talk grows less interesting and the tension never
grows at all. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _ERG
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I Dreamed of Africa'' (PG-13) _ Cardboard figures have
adventures in Africa. Kim Basinger stars as the real-life Kuki
Gallmann, who up and moves her family from Italy to the dangerous
Dark Continent because, as she tells her son, ``I've stopped
growing.'' Considering all the calamities that befall her family
after their move, you realize she should have considered something
like a yoga class instead. Directed by one-hit wonder Hugh Hudson
(``Chariots of Fire''), the movie never slows down long enough to
get inside the heads of its characters. Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Next Best Thing'' (PG-13) _ Madonna and Rupert Everett
play a yoga instructor and her gay best pal who spend a drunken
night together and end up parents of a darling son. The would-be
wacky comedy (the writers forgot to supply good lines) turns into a
tiresome custody battle. Most of the effort seems to have gone into
making sure Madonna's eyes are lit in a flattering way at all
times. Grade: D +
</P>
<P>
   _SM
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
<P>
   `Princess Mononoke'
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13 / Our critic's grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillsepie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
