<HEADER>
A6359 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL31-COX     08-30 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some films about labor that work
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, Labor Day. That conundrum of a holiday on which labor is the
one thing we're not supposed to do. Rather, it's a time to laze
around, say goodbye to summer, have a cookout and maybe watch a few
videos. Here are some rental ideas if you want to be reminded what
Labor Day is all about. Beyond the long weekend, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Matewan'' (1987): John Sayles' very fine, fact-based tale of
a miners' strike in West Virginia in the 1920s, which culminated in
the bloodiest confrontation between government and labor in U.S.
history. Chris Cooper, now best-known as the military madman living
next door to Kevin Spacey in ``American Beauty,'' plays a union
representative sent to the company town of Matewan to organize the
strikers. The mining company retaliates by hiring blacks and
Italians. The result is a struggle that pits white against black,
immigrant against longtime mountain man. Cooper, meanwhile, strives
to get the men to recognize that the real fight is against the
owners. Look for Sayles in the role of the shrill local minister
who's more or less in the owners' pockets, for David Straithairn as
the town's conscionable, caught-in-the-middle sheriff, and for
James Earl Jones, who agreed to play the leader of the black miners
for scale because he believed in the project so much.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Big One'' (1997): The moral of this movie may well be
never turn your back on Michael Moore. The maker of ``Roger &AMP; Me''
strikes again with this ruthless, inventive and often scathingly
hilarious documentary/essay about the insatiable greed that fuels
corporate America. While on a promotional tour for his book
``Downsize This!,'' Moore brings along a skeletal film crew and
uses the various stopovers to look at the way most major
corporations treat their employees. His wiseguy approach can be
cruel; typically, he ends up needling mindless midlevel management
types who haven't made a decision in years _aside from how to
better play up to their boss. But Nike CEO Phil Knight decides to
play along and agrees to meet with Moore. For his trouble, he gets
presented a plane ticket to Indonesia so he can visit the
14-year-olds who make his shoes. Just do it?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hoffa'' (1992): It took 'em years, but they finally found
Jimmy Hoffa, the labor leader who mysteriously disappeared in 1975.
He resurfaced in 1992 in the person of Jack Nicholson, who gives a
brave, forceful performance in an admittedly uneven film that never
quite fulfills its initial promise. Written by David Mamet and
directed by Danny DeVito, the movie begins on that fateful day when
somebody did something to the former Teamsters president. But the
fill-in-the-blanks flashbacks can be confusing if you don't know
Hoffa's story as well as the filmmakers. Even so, the picture is
worth seeing _ as a thoughtful gloss on an ongoing mystery and for
Nicholson's thuggish magnetism in the title role. The movie is
something of a family affair as well; his daughter Jennifer makes
her screen debut in a small role as a nun.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``On the Waterfront'' (1954): OK, so many of us have already
seen it and many of us know that it's as much about Marlon Brando's
union troubles on the waterfront as it is about director Elia
Kazan's willingness to cooperate with House Un-American Activities
Committee. In other words, Kazan is insisting that, under certain
circumstances, it's OK to be a stool pigeon. Well, we all have our
agendas, and while the overall power of this Oscar winner (best
picture) may seem somewhat diminished _ it's full of '50s
morality-play bombast _ the performances remain as memorable as
ever. Brando won an Oscar. Lee J. Cobb, Rod Steiger and Karl Malden
were all supporting nominees, but the team-player winner was Eva
Marie Saint, whose leading-lady role was shrewdly pushed into the
supporting category, thus improving her chances. It also helped
pave the way for similar strategies by Goldie Hawn, Geena Davis and
Marisa Tomei.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
