<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6360 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION3     08-30 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Northport, Ala.
 &HT;    Art at heart of many businesses, residents
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHPORT, Ala. _ f you enjoy paintings as well as pigskin play,
head for this artsy town across the Black Warrior River from
Tuscaloosa, home to the University of Alabama's Crimson Tide
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Here in this revitalized community of 24,000, you can view Ann
Mottershead Betak's romantic oil landscapes in her studio, shop for
an Italian bronze at Adams Antiques and meet artist Danny Rountree.
His watercolor of Main Avenue was commissioned by Friends of
Northport and is a colorful symbol of this charming town.
</P>
<P>
   You can also tour the Kentuck Art Center, located in a 1920
masonry building. Nestled around a landscaped courtyard, Kentuck _
Northport's original name _ houses an art museum, a gallery, seven
artists' studios and a shop selling folk and contemporary art and
traditional crafts. Look for Jerry Brown's face jugs, Edwin D.
Walter's glassware and T.R. Reed's fanciful wood whirligigs.
</P>
<P>
   The art center also stages the juried Kentuck Festival of the
Arts, which began in 1971. More than 300 invited artists from
around the country will converge Oct. 21-22 in Kentuck Park near
the Black Warrior River. The two-day event will feature craft
demonstrations by basketmakers, blacksmiths, furniture makers,
quilters and potters. It offers activities for kids, continuous
music and plenty of food as well. For information, call
205-758-1257.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Northport is listed in John Villani's book, ``The
100 Best Small Arts Towns in America'' (John Muir Publications,
$16.95), is no accident.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry designer Celia O'Kelley, who works in precious metals
and enamel, says the town works hard to attract its art crowd. ``A
couple of artists came here and were treated well by the locals,''
she says. ``Others arrived and soon the arts community flourished.
It succeeds because we have lots of diversity among our artisans,
from metalsmithing to digital art. We are not just painters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Renaissance Gallery on Main Avenue represents 23 artists.
``Our goal is to bring as much different art as possible to
Northport,'' says co-owner and artist Kathy Groshong. ``My Atlanta
customers like variety, from traditional to contemporary. Often,
they say, an Atlanta gallery focuses on just one or two styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Northport's history follows the river. More than 200 years ago,
the settlement of Kentuck was a convenient ford for those crossing
the Alabama Territory. Kentuck, so named because it was a canebrake
wilderness, eventually became known as North Port, the farthest
navigable point on the Black Warrior River. The city of Northport
was incorporated in 1871.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the charm of downtown Northport's Main Avenue comes from
its renovated buildings, ornate light poles, and baskets of
colorful flowers. And you can't miss the 102-year-old wooden train
trestle _ still in use _ which serves as the area landmark. When
the town needed new sidewalks, merchants spearheaded the drive to
``sell'' commemorative bricks and raised $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not all businesses are art influenced. Since 1909, Anders
Hardware has stocked more than 65,000 items, from screws to mule
collars, from fertilizer to pumps. Faucett's women's clothing store
has been in business since 1881 and in its present location on Main
Avenue since 1937, according to John Faucett, a descendant of the
founder.
</P>
<P>
   And the Northport 5 &AMP; 10 _ ``the store with a little bit of
everything!'' _ carries squirt rings for a nickel, pirate eye
patches for a dime as well as candies, sodas and notions.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the prettiest shops in Northport are the Potager, which
carries English statuary and everything for the gardener, and Wild
Birds Unlimited, housed in a restored Victorian home.
</P>
<P>
   With its small-town Southern charm, Northport grabs visitors and
residents alike. ``It reminds me of Mayberry,'' says Beth Campbell,
referring to the fictional town in the TV series ``The Andy
Griffith Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here five years and found that it has a wonderful
sense of community. People know each other and they wave at you. In
larger cities you don't find that.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Northport is about 205 miles west of downtown
Atlanta. Take I-20 west to Birmingham. It joins with I-59. Take
Exit 136 to I-459, which circles Birmingham. Eventually you will
find yourself back on 1-59 and I-20. Follow the signs to
Tuscaloosa. Take Exit 71B (I-359) and exit to right. Take second
exit, 15th Street, and follow signs to Northport.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 9:30 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays.
A few are closed on Mondays and a few open on Sundays. Some studios
are open by appointment only.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free on-street parking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: In stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most shops are accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tuscaloosa Convention and Visitors Bureau,
205-391-9200; www.tcvb.org. Or call the Kentuck Art Center
205-758-1257.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hummer's on Main is the perfect lunch spot for a made-to-order
chicken salad, pimento cheese (each $6.25) or turkey ($6.95)
sandwich served with chips and fresh fruit. Take home a fresh-baked
loaf of sourdough, honey wheat, sun-dried tomato or multigrain
walnut ($7). 11 a.m.-6 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays. 433 Main Ave.
205-345-2119.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you don't mind waiting in line, eat at City Cafe. For 26
years, Joe Barger has offered a choice of 12 veggies and six meats
everyday. Choose field peas, string beans or fried okra; country
fried steak, beef stew, chicken and dumplings. Combo plates:
$1.10-$3.40. Barger also serves breakfast. 4 a.m.-3:30 p.m.
Mondays-Fridays. 408 Main Ave. 205-758-9171.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Globe. Located in a former dry goods store, this eatery
named after Shakespeare's first theater features large line
drawings of famous scenes from the Bard's plays. The international
menu includes Thai emerald curry ($15.95), Jamaican jerk chicken
($12.95) and Athenian pasta salad ($7.95). 11 a.m.-3 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays; 5-11 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays. 430 Main Ave.
205-391-0949.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To indulge a sweet tooth, stop at Celebrations Bakery for a
slice of delectable cake ($3). 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m. Tuesdays-Fridays; 9
a.m.-noon Saturdays. 422 Main Ave. 205-759-2253.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Crimson Inn. If you want to be in ``Roll Tide'' country, stay
in this 75-year-old restored Dutch colonial home _ five blocks from
Bryant-Denny Stadium and a five-minute drive to Northport. Four
rooms are available, including the 'Bama room, decorated with
University of Alabama memorabilia. $100. 1509 University Blvd.
1-877-424-6622; www
</P>
<P>
   .bbonline.com/al/crimsoninn/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Within walking distance of downtown Northport is the Three
Bears bed-and-breakfast. Run by Linda Campbell, the charming 1920s
carpenter-style home has three rooms, each with private bath. $75.
2415 Fifth St. 205-752-2534.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
