r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE31-COX     08-30 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife enjoyed wearing her Laurel Burch jewelry, which is
made in San Francisco. But she lost much of it during a burglary a
few years ago. I have not been able to find a source in Atlanta. We
have our 54th wedding anniversary coming up and I would love to
surprise her with some jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gil Tauffner, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: What a thoughtful husband you are! Laurel Burch is a
self-taught California artist and her jewelry is sold at The Classy
Cat, 2900 Delk Road, Marietta (770-850-7240). The feline pin is $72
and the pair of earrings is $39.75. Burch is known for her
colorful, stylized animals, including cats and horses. The shop
also stocks the artist's posters, wooden masks, wall hangings and
throws as well as her line of ceramics, including teapots and mugs.
Her designs are also on note cards, T-shirts and totes, scarves and
socks. For more information, see www.laurelburch.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Sen-Sen, the breath enhancer. It tastes like
licorice and is used to kill cigarette and alcohol breath.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gary Furin, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Valuable to singers, speakers and smokers, Sen-Sen, the tiny
black-square breath freshener, was created in the mid-1890s and
described as a ``throat ease and breath perfume.'' The product is
made from licorice and rare herbs, says the manufacturer F&AMP;F Foods.
You can have it mailed by calling 1-800-621-0225. Twelve foil
packets of 0.1-ounce each are $7.80 including shipping. A literary
note: Sen-Sen garnered a mention in Stephen King's novel ``Four
Past Midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few months ago, I read about a person who holds the
Guinness record for being the loudest snorer. He said the only
thing that stopped his snoring was ySnore. I've looked everywhere
for this product but can't find it. You probably guessed it, my
husband is a very loud snorer, and I need this product desperately!
</P>
<P>
   _ Shirley Dutton, Villa Rica, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We have a quiet, and hopefully happy, solution to your
problem. You can buy ySnore, the anti-snoring nose drops at Eckerd.
We found our bottle at the location in Ansley Square, 1512 Piedmont
Ave. N.E. (404-876-2263). A 5-milliliter bottle is $6.49. The
product is simple to use. Have the snorer place two to four drops
into each nostril before retiring. Then the entire family might
enjoy a quiet night's rest. Check out the company's Web site,
www.ysnore.com, for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for Di Gas or Mildewcide made in Florida by
Vapor Products. It's a small bag of powder that you can put inside
a suitcase with woolen items, paperwork or records and it stops any
smell of mildew or moths. I bought it for years but now I can't
find it. Can you?
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Barnett, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: No wonder you can't find it _ Vapor Products no longer makes
the item. However, another Florida company, Damp Check, markets
Damp Check Mildewcide, which has the same ingredients as the
discontinued product. While not available in stores, you can order
it via 1-800-339-8603. Six 4-ounce packages are $21, including
postage. For more information, check out the company's Web site,
www.dampcheck.com. A. Vaughn Williams, president of Damp Check,
refers to his product as ``packaged sunshine.'' The active
ingredient is paraformaldehyde. Says Williams: ``It kills mildew
and musty odors and protects clothing, leather, paper and wood
items in closets for months.'' He says it can also be used to
protect vacation homes, RVs and boats during non-use.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was a kid, I enjoyed Sky Bar candy. It came in four
sections and each section, which you broke off, had a different
filling. Can you find it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Stan Funk, Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And another candy request: I am looking for a product, probably
discontinued, called a Sky Bar, which I enjoyed 35 years ago. It
was a sectioned bar with four flavors, chocolate, vanilla, peanut
butter and caramel, and came in a yellow-wrapped package. Let me
know if it is still in production.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Arth, Roswell, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: We salivated over this request, you sweet tooth fans, then
tracked down the bars at Cracker Barrel, 2150 Delk Road S.E.,
Marietta (770-951-2602). Each bar, made by Necco, is 69 cents and
contains 190 calories. And the candy bar is just as our readers
fondly remembered, with four flavors in a yellow wrapper. Personal
note: It's also yummy.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
