</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      08-30 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KEEP THE WALL BETWEEN CHURCH AND STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _The time has come for all the candidates on the
national tickets to reaffirm their belief in the constitutional
separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts the spirituality of each of the candidates. But
these days they all seem bent on blurring the line between religion
and politics. God is not on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   No one made clearer his devotion to the wall between the church
and state than John F. Kennedy when he ran for the presidency in
1960. When Kennedy's Roman Catholic faith became a political issue
in the campaign, he was able to dispel fears that he would be
taking orders from the pope.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks before the Greater Houston Ministerial Association on
Sept. 12, 1960, he said: ``I believe in an America where the
separation of church and state is absolute, where no Catholic
prelate would tell the president (should he be Catholic) how to
act, and no Protestant minister would tell his parishioners for
whom to vote''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of religion in politics has been on the back burner
until the current campaign. Today, the four national candidates are
flaunting their spiritual beliefs as they run for the top jobs in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore, a Baptist and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, a Methodist, have announced they are ``born again
Christians.'' Bush also said that Jesus Christ was his favorite
philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's running mate, Richard Cheney, is also a Methodist while
Gore chose Sen. Joseph Lieberman, who is the first national
candidate of Jewish faith in history. Lieberman has called his
selection a ``miracle.'' He invokes ``God'' in many of his stump
speeches and is profuse in his Biblical references. He likened the
election of Bill Clinton as president and Gore as vice president to
the parting of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously enjoys his self-appointed role as the voice of
morality in the Senate for having publicly denounced Clinton for
his affair with intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But he also seems to have forgotten that the vice presidency is
a secular post.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking recently at a black church in Detroit, Lieberman said:
``There must be and can be a constitutional place for faith in our
public life.''
</P>
<P>
   The following day, he attended an interfaith breakfast in
Chicago where he declared: ``We are not only citizens of this
country, we are citizens of the same awesome God.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Bush told B'nai Brith, a Jewish service
organization: ``Our nation was chosen by God and commissioned by
history to be a model to the world of justice and inclusion and
diversity without division''
</P>
<P>
   The mixing of politics and religion is causing alarm in some
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham H. Foxman, national director of B'nai Brith's Anti
Defamation League, called on Lieberman to refrain from using
``overt expressions'' of religious beliefs, saying they were not
appropriate in campaign speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki McLean, Lieberman's spokeswoman, said the senator's `faith
is an important component of who Joe Lieberman is.'' She also said
Lieberman ``always expresses his support of tolerance and the
separation of church and state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's spokesman, Douglas Hattaway, says Gore has no problem
with Lieberman's spiritual emphasis on the campaign trail. Gore, he
added, recognizes ``that government can't solve every problem,''
and believes religion can enhance people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a leap of faith to believe that Gore is not also
trying to steal the script of the religious right and to deflect
the taint of the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   Others on the campaign trail also seem to want to cross the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore promote ``faith-based charity,'' hopefully
not in lieu of government-backed social programs that have a wider
reach to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Every president has proclaimed his faith. It's fair to say there
have been no atheists in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   President Richard Nixon held Sunday prayer services in the White
House, inviting prominent ministers to preach in the East Room. For
members of the Cabinet, it was almost a command performance.
Government officials as well as outsiders were invited to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   As a White House correspondent, I thought that covering the
prayer service would give me easy access to the government elite,
that is until one Cabinet official stared me down and chided me for
asking him a news question ``in church.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to religion and the campaign, one might ask:
``Which side is God on.''
</P>
<P>
   The same question might be asked of the defiant students and
parents, urged on by some pastors and Christian broadcasters, who
stood in the bleachers in high school stadiums across the South
last weekend to recite the Lord's Prayer before the opening
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   All the candidates have to do is look around the world to see
how well religion and politics mix.
</P>
<P>
   The Founding Fathers certainly knew and protected us from the
combination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
helent &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
