NYT-08-30-00 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6366 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-AUSTRALIA31-COX     08-30 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AUSTRALIA31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Asian influence, seafood abound in Australia's dashing `Mod-Oz'
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The best food in Sydney doesn't start in the
chic bistros that have multiplied during the lead-up to the
Olympics. It begins where it has for decades: under the wings of
seagulls circling a hangarlike structure beside Blackwattle Bay _
the Sydney Fish Market.
</P>
<P>
   Every weekday before dawn, the largest fish market in the
Southern Hemisphere springs to life with the snort of refrigerated
trucks, the rattle of handcarts and the crunch of shovels thrust
into ice. Scores of fishmongers sit in a grandstand facing a huge
electronic tote board and bid on the catch. It could be an
off-track betting parlor in Vegas except for the briny smell and
the water-slicked floor, lined with blue bins full of cold eyes and
spiky fins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got bream and snappah!'' the auctioneer announces,
cracking off the last syllable like a crab claw. ``Bream and
snappah!''
</P>
<P>
   They've also got squid and barramundi and John Dory and
sashimi-grade tuna and Tiger prawns and rock oysters and
crustaceans with strange names like yabbies and Balmain bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our seafood,'' says Neil Perry, one of Sydney's top chefs,
``is simply amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The seafood has always been here. It's what the cooks are doing
with it that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Australia used to be strictly a fish-and-chips kind of place.
From its beginnings as a British penal colony, the nation was a
culinary prisoner, its cooking a distant imitation of the
not-so-enticing food back home. Its reputation was such that Calvin
Trillin, writing about expense-account restaurants in the States,
once complained that their continental cuisine tasted ``as if the
continent they had in mind was Australia.''
</P>
<P>
   No more. As the world tunes in to the Sydney Games in September,
it will discover a city and nation undergoing a transformation that
reminds some people of the gastronomical reawakening that began in
California a generation ago. Sydney is a city of markets and
coffeehouses and stylish restaurants where chefs are combining
local ingredients and international cooking styles _ especially
Asian and Mediterranean _ to create something fresh. Most of the
restaurants describe themselves as Modern Australian, or Mod-Oz, a
designation that didn't even appear in the Sydney Morning Herald's
dining guide a dozen years ago. Now almost half the establishments
listed come under the heading.
</P>
<P>
   The new flavors of Australia startle outsiders expecting
warmed-over roasts and puddings. ``I assumed everything was going
to be British,'' says Nathalie Dupree, the TV cook and Southern
food authority, who first visited a few years ago. ``But some of
the food just dazzled me. I was struck with how free their cooking
is of any constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly true in Sydney, where Pacific Rim is all the
rage. The hottest chefs in town these days are wok-slingers. Whole
streets in the suburbs have been taken over by Vietnamese,
Malaysian and Singaporean restaurants. Thai kitchens have become as
common as Tex-Mex in Atlanta. The slurp of noodles has joined horns
on the harbor as a definitive sound of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Oz discovers Asia
</P>
<P>
   Yet news of the evolving Australian palate has scarcely washed
ashore on the other side of the Pacific Rim. While Australian wines
have attracted a following, Mod-Oz restaurants aren't exactly
carving a niche in America. There's only one in Manhattan, a new
place called Eight Mile Creek, and there are none in Atlanta
(although the downtown Hilton will get in the Olympic spirit with a
special Sydney brunch Sept. 17.) If the average American thinks of
Aussie eats at all, it's usually shrimp on the barbie or a Vegemite
sandwich or the bloomin' onions that Outback Steakhouse serves in a
g'day cliche out of ```Crocodile' Dundee.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that they don't deep-fry onions in the real Outback;
the Tampa-based chain, which will open its first franchise in
Sydney this December, makes no claim to culinary authenticity.
``Australia,'' says vice president for marketing Nancy Schneid,
``has never been known as a food capital.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when few Australians would have debated the
point. During its first century and a half, the nation's prime
contribution to world cuisine was Dame Nellie Melba, an opera
singer who went to Paris in the 1880s and impressed Escoffier so
much that he named a dessert after her _ Peach Melba.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian diet back then was larded with meat, stews and
puddings. ``It was nothing like what you find over there now,''
says Josephine Marcinek, an accountant in DeKalb County who grew up
in Brisbane during the '30s and '40s. ``Every week we had Sunday
tea with sliced cold joint (beef roast) and lemon-curd tarts. Very
English.''
</P>
<P>
   The fare started to modify after World War II, as immigration
laws that had once barred nonwhites were liberalized. Greeks and
Italians and Lebanese began to enter the country, bringing with
them a taste for new foods and spices.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Ripe, the deliciously named food columnist for The
Australian newspaper, wrote about the dawning era of multicultural
cooking in her book ``Goodbye Culinary Cringe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother used to go to the greengrocer and just cry, it was
so bleak,'' she remembers. ``Then she started coming back all
excited. `You'll never guess what I found today.' A baby carrot one
time. Maybe a telescope cucumber the next. Each new vegetable was a
cause for celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   The melting pot really started to bubble in the '70s as
Australia opened its doors to Vietnamese refugees and other Asian
immigrants. The newcomers brought lemongrass, turmeric, Thai basil
_ and a sense of liberation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time we realized how close we were to Asia,''
says Perry, the chef/owner of Rockpool, one of Sydney's most
honored restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no cook better embodies the metamorphosis of Australian
food than Perry. At 43, the ponytailed son of a Sydney butcher runs
three restaurants, issues best-selling cookbooks and has a
consulting business that recently refashioned the first-class meals
on Qantas airlines. He's the Wolfgang Puck of Oz.
</P>
<P>
   Perry has relished Asian cooking since he was a boy and two of
his best friends were Chinese. His menus are full of bilingual
dishes that combine local seafood and Asian flavors, like his
blue-swimmer crab omelet stir-fried in fish sauce and sesame oil
(see recipe, H4).
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that mix of cultures is Australia,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the bush
</P>
<P>
   But some people think the Pac-Rim chefs have overlooked a
culture, the oldest one in Australia: that of the Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find fusion food in California, London, Tokyo. But if
you want to really represent our cuisine to the world, you have to
include the native foods that are uniquely Australian,'' says
Sydney cookbook author Vic Cherikoff.
</P>
<P>
   He's talking about bush tucker, the indigenous nuts, berries,
fruits and critters that Aborigines have eaten since before England
existed. Cherikoff sells many of them through his native foods
supply business _ uncultivated flavors like lemon aspen, a wild
citrus that's somewhere between lime and grapefruit, and wattle
seeds, a chocolaty nut that he uses to brew ``wattleccino.''
</P>
<P>
   If they're up for it, foreign journalists can sample some of the
more exotic indigenous foods during the Olympics. At the main press
center, Edna's Table, a Sydney restaurant known for its game, will
be serving emu, crocodile and kangaroo to the intrepid. (They won't
go so far as to offer the ultimate dare of Australian food _
witchetty grubs _ the plump white larvae that some Aborigines pop
into their mouths raw.)
</P>
<P>
   Should some of the media enjoy kangaroo, they wouldn't be the
first. Many visitors like it. Nathalie Dupree tried it during a
nature walk, the guide grilling kangaroo steaks as koalas looked
down from eucalyptus trees. She thought it a tasty cross between
lamb and rare duck breast.
</P>
<P>
   Australians have mixed feelings about consuming kangaroo. While
Aborigines have hunted and roasted them for thousands of years, it
was illegal until recently to sell the meat for human consumption
in parts of the country. Some Aussies still can't bring themselves
to ``eat Skippy,'' as they say, referring to ``Skippy the Bush
Kangaroo,'' a TV show that featured a heroic marsupial as a sort of
spring-loaded Lassie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eating kangaroo would be like eating a cat,'' says Terri
Steel, a Sydney native who runs the Australian Catalogue Co.
mail-order business in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Steel's cats have no such compunctions. When she lived in
Sydney, they devoured the frozen kangaroo meat she bought at the
store. Now that she's living in Georgia and 'roo is tough to find,
she gives them something else to maintain their ties to the
homeland: that salty yeast extract that can bring tears of
nostalgia to any Aussie expatriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cats,'' she says, ``love Vegemite.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
