<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6367 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE31-COX     08-30 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All about Aussie, at your fingertips
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happens every four years. When a city hosts the Olympics, a
veritable polyglot nation of the world's media descends upon it.
Not just to relay scores and sports news but to dissect and report
upon every aspect of life in the Olympic city. The good, the bad
and the ugly of a city, along with who wins the medals, are exposed
to the world. Including the food.
</P>
<P>
   When the Games were held in Atlanta in 1996, reporting on
Southern cooking was a fairly easy task. Before long, people from
around the globe had read or heard of or tasted such Southern
classics as grits, barbecue, corn bread, peach cobbler and catfish.
But the job of the media to report on the food of Australia will
not be such a cinch. The cuisine from Down Under is so diverse and
so different from that of any other place in the world, it's
difficult to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   To better understand the fascinating cuisine of this most
fascinating country and to search out some Aussie recipes to help
you cook up some Olympic spirit while you watch the Games, see
these Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Food Lovers Guide to Australia (detail at right)
</P>
<P>
   This excellent site, at www.sbs.com.au
</P>
<P>
   /foodlovers, is the Internet companion to a 13-week television
series. Working your way through the contents of the 13 episodes
will give you an idea of the diversity of Australian cuisine. Each
show spotlights amazing ingredients, a chef, a feast and foods and
menus that uniquely blend together cuisines from the world over.
Chinese, Italian, Belgian, German, French, Dutch, African,
Caribbean, Hungarian, Cuban and Spanish are just a sample of the
cuisines of Australia. Talk about fusion. The recipes, which are a
bit challenging, come from Australia's top professional chefs and
include wonderful color pictures and explanations and origins of
each dish.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kangaroo
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they really do eat kangaroo in Australia _ from 'roo
burgers to kangaroo medallions in bearnaise sauce. To learn all
about kangaroo as a food, see the kangaroo industry's site at www
</P>
<P>
   .kangaroo-industry.asn.au/recipes/recipeframe.htm. Recipes
include Wallaby Bolognese, Thai Wallaby Meat Balls, Roo Fillets
With Blueberry Sauce and Kangaroo Stir-fry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bush food
</P>
<P>
   Australian Aborigines have been preparing this land's food
resources for the past 40,000 years and have a unique cuisine using
fruits, berries, herbs, plants, game and even insects that the rest
of the world has never heard of, much less tasted.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, Aboriginal foods are coming into mainstream
kitchens as chefs _ specifically, Chinese, Italian, Thai and French
_ discover and incorporate the unique flavors into their menus.
</P>
<P>
   See www.bushtucker.com.au (also www.cherikoff.com.au), the site
for Cherikoff the Rare Spice Co., for an overview of these foods
and sources to acquire such bush delicacies as akudjura (ground
bush tomato), illawarra plums, lemon aspen juice and munthari
berry.
</P>
<P>
   There, you'll also find numerous recipes using this exotica,
including a Sydney Salad composed of native delicacies _ such as
akudjura, emu prosciutto and lemon myrtle mayonnaise _ arranged to
look like the famed opera house.
</P>
<P>
   Other bush food sites you may want to look at include a Taste of
the Bush at www.arts.unimelb.edu.au/amu/ucr/student/1997
</P>
<P>
   /silva and homepages.go.com/(tilde)edutech/0005.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recipes from early Australia
</P>
<P>
   Www.colourshop.com.au/recipies is dedicated to old-time Aussie
recipes before all the fusion. Recipes are heavy on English foods
like kidney pies and scones. There's lots of mutton, rabbit and
tripe. For more classic dishes from the Colonial period, see
www.toptown.com/theedge/yaleman/foodold.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Classic Australian recipes
</P>
<P>
   For classic Australian recipes, with descriptions and origins of
each dish, see All Recipes.com at www.allrecipes.com/directory
</P>
<P>
   /744.asp. You will find recipes and learn about such everyday
Aussie fare as Anzac biscuits (we offer a recipe at left), a simple
cookie that honors the Australia New Zealand Army Corps of World
War I; damper bread, a staple of the early settlers' diet; and
Lamingtons, little sponge cakes coated in chocolate and grated
coconut.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Culinary tour of Australia
</P>
<P>
   Let World in Your Kitchen take you on a culinary tour of
Australia at www.creative-homeliving.com/worldkitchen
</P>
<P>
   /cuisinetours/australia.htm. This is an excellent site to get an
overall view of the food and culture of Australia. There are
recipes and links with info on all the variations of Australian
cuisine, from the Aborginal to swanky fusion restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ABC (that's the Australian Broadcasting Co.) offers some recipes
direct from Sydney, the Olympic city, at local.abc.net.au
</P>
<P>
   /recipes/2bl/2BLsubject.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shopping resources:
</P>
<P>
   Yabbies . . . in Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go all the way to Australia to get Australian
food. Here are some places to look:
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Food Source at www.eatyabbies.com gets you to the
site of a New York company that sells yabbies (a freshwater
crawfish), barramundi (a tasty tropical fish) and other Aussie
delicacies. The importer is supplying live, farm-raised yabbies to
Whole Foods Market in Atlanta, which should have them for sale any
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Catalogue Co. at www.aussiecatalog.com is run by
Terri Steel of Marietta, a native of Sydney. She sells all sorts of
Australia stuff, including a bunch of packaged foods like Vegemite,
Tim Tam biscuits (cookies) and musk Lifesavers. She even sells a
Vegemite cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Vegemite, if you are a fan of Australia's national
spread, see www.ozchannel.com/vegemite.
</P>
<P>
   If you're hankering for emu, see the American Emu Association's
site at www.aea-emu.org. Unlike kangaroo, the other native animal
that Australians eat, emu is raised in the United States. The site
lists local suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
