<HEADER>
A6377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-EYEBROWS0831-COX     08-30 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYEBROWS0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think of your brows as just hair above your eyes? Browse this!
 &HT;    By Kim Folstad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Chances are slim that a course in
eyebrow history will be added to women's studies curricula any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   But the evolution of that expressive arch can tell us a lot
about feminism, as well as femininity, says Cynthia Robins,
co-author of ``The Eyebrow'' (ReganBooks, $30).
</P>
<P>
   In this glossy new guide dedicated solely to our uppermost
facial feature, Robins and celebrity makeup artist Robyn Cosio
explore how cultural changes have shaped women's brows. And they
chart those changes through the centuries, from the exaggerated
eyebrows of the ancient Egyptians to the pierced brows of today.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, there's more behind a trend than mere whim, Robins
says. Take, for example, the switch from the all-out glamour of the
'30s to the fuss-free look of the '40s, when women tried to achieve
``a beauty that's responsible _ not a responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The men had gone to war, and ``Rosie the Riveter'' went to work;
beauty products and the time it took to use them were a luxury. ``A
woman wasn't going to sit there for an hour, plucking her
eyebrows,'' Robins says.
</P>
<P>
   And again, when women transitioned from the ``skinny commas,
paisleys or tadpoles'' of the '70s to the ``generous'' brows of the
'80s, it wasn't just to provide visual balance to their shoulder
pads. ``Greed is good'' was a mantra for the times, the authors of
``The Eyebrow'' point out. ``Everything about the 1980s was
generous and overblown,'' and makeup styles reflected that
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   So what will an aesthetic anthropologist write some day about
the brows at the turn of this century?
</P>
<P>
   Ahhhh.
</P>
<P>
   The style for 2000 is a clean but natural brow _ geared to the
face instead of what's in vogue, says Robins, who is fashion and
beauty editor at the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   This is the brow that Cosio _ whose client list includes Jamie
Lee Curtis, Vanessa Redgrave and Lesley Stahl _ has been touting
for years. ``She designs an eyebrow for the face. The hell with the
trend,'' Robins adds.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every woman is ready to give up on the brow-do to
which she's become attached, Robins knows. A woman can get
``permaplaqued in time'' when she gets wedded to the look she had
when she felt the prettiest, or most confident, or was at her
sexual peak.
</P>
<P>
   Just as you'll see a woman who's held onto a favorite hairstyle
long past its freshness date (Farrah Fawcett feathering, for
example, or the Dorothy Hamill wedge), there are those whose brows
still reflect their hippie or disco heydays.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the ``back-to-earthers,'' who protest plucking
even one out-of-place hair, Robins says, and the ``mommies'' who
are so busy they reluctantly retire their tweezers for a few years.
Robins understands, but she warns: ``Your eyebrows can change how
people think about you. And we all know you only get one chance to
make a first impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy brows that sit too close together can make a person look
angry, Robins and Cosio have found. On the flip side, brows that
have been shaved or plucked to a thin semicircle can be just as
off-putting, they caution.
</P>
<P>
   Robins recommends going to a professional regularly to have
brows properly groomed, even for today's ``natural'' look.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, plucking your own eyebrows is asking for trouble,'' she
says. ``But not everyone can afford to have it done.'' For those
who don't have the time or the cash to make that monthly trip to
the salon, ``The Eyebrow `` (and, often, beauty magazines and
books) includes a do-it-yourself guide.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it may take a while to get your brows just the way
you want them. But with patience and a little pain, you can get
what aestheticians call an ``instant face-lift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of it,'' Robins says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: kimfolstad(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
