<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6379 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-ROADFOOD-CALIFORNIA-2     08-30 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROADFOOD-CALIFORNIA-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 LOS ANGELES: in Moss Beach. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moss Beach Distillery Restaurant, Beach Way and Ocean Boulevard,
Moss Beach, (650) 728-5595
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly haunted, this ramshackle building was a delivery
point for liquor smugglers during Prohibition. The place still
rests on those laurels (and the killer view). The food is not much,
but they charge a lot for it. Buffalo wings are $13.95, a Caesar
salad is $8.95. But if you're tempted to stop _ and you will be,
because the patio is outfitted with chairs and blankets _ order the
steamers. A pound of clams and mussels cooked in herb butter is
$15.95 and is plenty for two to share.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult not to love San Francisco, despite $3,000-a-month
rents for an 1,800-square-foot loft, parking fees to grocery shop
and unpredictable cab service. The women don't use hairspray, the
men all travel in comfortable shoes and there's further evidence of
laissez faire across the bridge in Berkeley. There's a visible lack
of the dot.com money that is pumping through the city these days.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Driving over San Francisco hills, getting lost only twice, we
spotted Thanh Long on the edge of Golden Gate Park.
</P>
<P>
   Thanh Long, 4101 Judah St., San Franciso, (415) 665-1146: Opened
in 1971 by Diana An, this wandering maze of rooms bustles with
families late on a Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tab for two that runs near $100, families of eight to
12 diners are tucking into whole Dungeness crab roasted in butter
and cracked black pepper _ at a market price of $32 each in August.
The rest of the menu is surprising fusionesque with dishes such as
shaken beef _ cubes of New York steak flambeed medium rare and
served ``au jus'' on a bed of potatoes, mixed greens and cherry
tomatoes for $16.50.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the creative menu, the crowd is not avocational
restaurant grazers, it's Asian families ending (or beginning) the
week. Perhaps this is where all the dot.com money goes. It
certainly makes more sense than an 8,000-square-foot zero-lot-line
home with bathrooms the size of Delaware and a room devoted to gift
wrapping. Make reservations _ dot.coms are still doing fine,
despite the March scare.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I scheduled Gilroy as a mandatory stop on my journey through
California. My resume must note that I've eaten in the Garlic
Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   But when I stopped in at the Gilroy Garlic Festival office to
get some restaurant recommendations, the festival representative
looked as if I'd asked for the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there really is no special garlic dish. A continental
place down the street has a garlic soup sometime, but I don't know
if they'll have it today. But they do have a garlic burger. And
there's an Italian place down the road that, of course, uses a lot
of garlic.''
</P>
<P>
   Allllrighty then. I'd try the burger, but if that didn't work
out, maybe I could find some garlic earrings to prove my
pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Time Restaurant, 7397 Monterey St., Gilroy, (408)
842-7575
</P>
<P>
   Here's the difference between loving garlic, to which I
willingly confess, and living with garlic. Ms. Festival
Representative, living with garlic, is oblivious to its presence.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest Time, the ``continental'' restaurant down the street, is
delightful, a toughened-up tea room that won't keep away the ladies
but also won't simper to the brokers and farmers who might stop in.
It was full with both during a Tuesday lunch.
</P>
<P>
   I ordered that recommended garlic burger _ a hamburger basted
with roasted garlic _ and for good measure, added the appetizer of
baked heads of whole garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heavy on the garlic, but I'm not a woman of halves.
However, I knew I was sunk when the waitress delivered the
pre-lunch bread. At Harvest, the bread is served with a bowl of
garlic butter plus a dish of pickled garlic cloves. Hmmm _ what to
do? Well, here's the benefit of dining alone _ I ate it all.
</P>
<P>
   Then I dug into the appetizer: three baked heads of garlic. I
squeezed the soft pulp from the silvery peel, smearing it onto the
bread and then topping it with a swipe of equally subtle feta
spread.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the burger _ an (almost) Texas size affair with an
aroma of more garlic _ soaked up (well, sorta) by the fries on the
side. Oh, boy, I wasn't going to need to buy those earrings after
all.
</P>
<P>
   I did, however, have to make a stop before hitting the highway.
Thank goodness Texaco stocks Rolaids.
</P>
<P>
   Next week: Only in California _ a 50-year-old Los Angeles
hamburger chain, complete with paper-boat hats for the servers,
caters to diners on today's popular low-carbohydrate diets.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
