<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA, HERE I COME, PACKING AN APPETITE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Do not think that all of California is Wolfgang
Puck. In fact, most of California is Spago-free, tending more
toward Spaghetti Warehouse than pizza with artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than spaghetti, I drove into flat 1950s-movie-set
Bakersfield wanting to check out one of this agricultural town's
Basque restaurants _ legendary trencherman spots that originated to
serve the Spanish shepherds who helped settle the area.
</P>
<P>
   But I had car trouble outside Barstow _ my rental car decided to
shut off in the middle of the Mojave Desert _ and didn't pull in
until linner, those weird hours between lunch and dinner when
decent people are at their desks. And the Basques are punctual,
shutting their restaurants promptly at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if I couldn't have Basque, what would be next best? Buck
Owens is known to serve a mean chicken-fried steak at his
honky-tonk, but the Crystal Palace also shuts up its sequins during
the day.
</P>
<P>
   So I opted for the next best thing for a Texas girl on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Hodel's, 5917 Knudsen Drive, Bakersfield (661) 399-3341:)
</P>
<P>
   The Hodel's complex is a family-owned version of Luby's _ minus
the tea ladies and the LuAnn platter. It's more what hearty
Midwesterners call a smorgasbord _ a church-supper version of home
cooking with as many return trips as you could ever pray for. (More
polite versions are called buffets and add sushi and a Champagne
fountain to the salads so they can charge $20 a person, plus
parking.)
</P>
<P>
   But the Hodel family _ Mom Hodel was the founder _ would feel
quite at home in Texas. The groaning tables were filled with all
sorts of things that we love: lots of mayonnaise-based salads,
mashed potatoes, fall-apart pot roast plus a couple of colors of
Jell-O. And on the end of one of the steam tables is a bowl of
escabeche, those hot pickled peppers that seem to have made their
way from Mexico out into the great big world.
</P>
<P>
   Hodel's is the perfect place to make a family stop when driving
through the flatlands of California. You might even think you're
still in Texas;_ the surrounding territory looks an awful lot like
Midland-Odessa on a bad hair day.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   As much as I appreciate the agricultural bounty that California
delivers to the rest of the country, I was headed for the bridges
of San Francisco. I drove across the dinge of central California to
reach the lushness _ day lilies blooming in August, a morning of no
moisturizer needed _ just at dusk. As in dark, as in having no clue
where I was going. As in, don't you remember this same car stopping
outside of Barstow and what makes you think it's not going to stop
going across the Bay Bridge? As in, you're already training your
8-year-old son how to ask for directions.
</P>
<P>
   As in, two hours later (after, ahem, a couple of trips back and
forth over that same Bay Bridge) I arrived at my destination. No
dinner for this girl _ a bottle of that California wine will be
lovely, thank you so much.
</P>
<P>
   The next day is northern California summer heaven; it's sunny,
but a Texan is tempted to grab a sweater because of a morning
temperature less than 90 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a drive in a convertible _ this is really possible,
fellow Texans, during August, in other parts of the country _ down
the edge of the state just south of San Francisco. And then I run
into another peculiarity of California:
</P>
<P>
   The highways are so revered that they have more than one name.
This one has at least three: El Camino Highway, California Highway
1 and Pacific Coast Highway. Despite the identity crisis, it is one
of the country's great paved stretches.
</P>
<P>
   Ice plant crops up along the dunes, surfers are dancing the
waves, and I've not sneezed once because of the ozone. Ahhhh. Then
I see it _ a piece of home.
</P>
<P>
   The Taco Bell With The World's Best View, 5200 Cabrillo Highway,
California Highway 1 or Pacific Coast Highway (650) 355-0591
</P>
<P>
   Texans who have relocated to California complain about the
Mexican food. Too much sour cream, they say. No cumin, they note.
Fajitas that are stir-fried, they complain. So when a Tex-Mex fix
hits, they generally head for Taco Bell, the closest thing they can
find.
</P>
<P>
   If they're lucky, they find this Taco Bell, a former upscale
seafood restaurant that couldn't make the rent. It's no wonder that
corporate food does the trick here. The kids will eat the food,
you'll get a vacation price break and with the stunning view of the
Pacific, the rocks, the surf, the day trippers, you can also get an
ersatz gordita.
</P>
<P>
   The food may be familiar, but be certain _ you're nowhere near
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Moving farther down the highway, it's difficult not to stop
again. And if you'd like something a bit more historic than the
home of the chihuahua, there are several possibilities. One is an
old rum-running spot in Moss Beach.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
