<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE REALLY LIKE `PEOPLE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Was the song ``People'' recorded first by a male vocalist
prior to Barbara Streisand?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.W., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The song originated with Barbara Streisand in the 1964
musical ``Funny Girl'' and was included on her album ``People,''
released the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few ``People'' covers turned up in a search of music
databases on the Internet: Wayne King recorded a waltz included on
``The Best of Wayne King'' in 1987, Shirley Bassey's 1960s-era
version was included on her 1997 collection ``I'm in the Mood for
Love'' and Claire Moore recorded it for the CD ``Celebrating Jule
Styne,'' released in February.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand told CNN in 1996 that she once disliked the song,
changing her mind by the time she left ``Funny Girl'' in 1965. ``I
remember my first argument with Jule Styne and Bob Merrill, saying,
`Isn't it people who don't need people who are the luckiest people
in the world?' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to ``Wimpy,'' the commentator for Chicago White
Sox games?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Tom ``Wimpy'' Paciorek resigned in October 1999 to spend more
time with his family, ending a 12-season streak of broadcasting
games with Ken ``Hawk'' Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   A Detroit native and University of Houston graduate, Paciorek
occasionally fills in for Kirk Gibson on Detroit Tigers TV
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox replaced Paciorek during the off-season with one
of the team's players, 36-year-old outfielder Darren Jackson, who
retired after 12 seasons in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Write to Paciorek in care of the Detroit Tigers, 2100 Woodward
Ave., Detroit, MI 48201.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Jennifer Ehle, the actress who won a
Tony award for ``The Real Thing''?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.L.S., Holden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to her in care of International Creative Management,
8942 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90211.
</P>
<P>
   Ehle, 30, is the daughter of actress Rosemary Harris and
screenwriter John Ehle. She had a lead role in the 1995 miniseries
``Pride and Prejudice'' and was in the films ``This Year's Love''
and ``Sunshine'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   When she won the best actress Tony Award for the Tom Stoppard
play ``The Real Thing'' this year, one of the other nominees was
her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only time I can genuinely say it's as nice to be
nominated as to win,'' Harris, 69, told Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
