<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA WAITS TO SEE IF SUHARTO WILL ATTEND HIS OWN TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ As Indonesia prepared to put its fallen
leader, Suharto, on trial here Thursday, the government on
Wednesday finished elaborate preparations _ converting the
auditorium of a state ministry into an oversized courtroom,
enlisting 1,200 police officers for security, even requisitioning a
helicopter to evacuate Suharto in case he comes under threat or
needs medical help.
</P>
<P>
   But the one thing prosecutors cannot control is the defendant
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's doctors are scheduled to examine him three hours
before the hearing begins on Thursday. If they determine that the
79-year-old former president is too ill to attend, the trial will
stop before it starts.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Suharto's lawyers have said that their client, who
was hospitalized twice last year after a stroke, is too frail to
answer charges that he swindled hundreds of millions of dollars
through his charitable organizations during his three decades as
Indonesia's ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have vowed to pursue the case, even if Suharto fails
to appear. An adviser to Attorney General Marsuki Darusman said
Wednesday evening that ``It's 50-50 that Suharto will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Guessing whether the defendant will show up has become a sort of
parlor game here in recent days, as demonstrators have marched,
prosecutors have made tough statements and newspapers have mused
about Suharto's state of mind. Few people will be surprised if he
pleads illness.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the tumultuous changes that followed Suharto's ouster
in May 1998, people here are skeptical that their stunted legal
system can take on a strongman who ruled this country for 32 years,
amassing a vast fortune and turning Indonesia into a byword for
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes go beyond Suharto's own future. Legal experts and
political analysts said that unless the government successfully
prosecutes the former president, Indonesia will never cleanse
itself of a legacy of corruption and impunity that ranges from
financial scandals to military massacres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make an example of Suharto,'' said Umar Juoro, a
former adviser to Suharto's successor, B.J. Habibie. ``Bring him
into the court, charge him, convict him and then pardon him if
necessary. But we must demonstrate that everybody is the same
before the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Suharto was dealt its first setback under
former President Habibie, when his government dropped its
investigation of him in October, saying it could not turn up enough
evidence. That decision drew howls of protest from people here, and
it contributed to Habibie's ignominious withdrawal from the
presidential election held later that month.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's successor, President Abdurrahman Wahid, swiftly
reopened the case. And his prosecutors have steadily tightened the
noose around Suharto _ placing him under city arrest in April,
house arrest in May and formally charging him with corruption
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid has promised to pardon Suharto _ but only after he is
judged. The president has also suggested that Suharto could strike
a deal by returning money stolen from the state. One of Wahid's
senior advisers, Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, began negotiations with
members of the Suharto family. But he said Wednesday that those
talks had been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto and his family are accused of building a
multibillion-dollar fortune by siphoning off state funds and
steering contracts to family-owned firms. But Darusman, the
attorney general, has focused on a narrower set of allegations
involving seven tax-free foundations. Suharto is accused of
funneling at least $150 million through the foundations into
personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   While Jakarta has been peaceful in recent months, people worry
that Suharto's trial could inflame old passions. Demonstrators for
and against the former president have rallied this week in front of
the South Jakarta District Court. Student leaders said Wednesday
that they would gather Thursday at the site of the trial, defying a
police ban on demonstrations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Critics say the case falls far short of the broad prosecution
that Suharto deserves. The prosecutors say they are sticking to
charges that they can prove. Suharto threw a cloak of legitimacy
over many of his financial deals by issuing presidential decrees,
which have legal standing.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's trial is so important because it comes at a time when
the struggle for Indonesia's future has shifted from the streets
into the courtroom. His case is one of nearly a dozen
investigations and prosecutions of people who were officials,
cronies or tycoons in the Suharto era.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's record with legal cases is uneven. On Monday,
parliament voted to investigate allegations that close aides to
Wahid had misappropriated $4.2 million from the state logistics
agency and a $2 million donation from the Sultan of Brunei.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, a Jakarta court acquitted a central figure in a
scandal involving one of Indonesia's largest banks, Bank Bali.
Noting that the defendant had admitted taking $64 million, The
Jakarta Post said the ruling ``created a very large dent in the
nationwide campaign against corruption.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
