<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6398 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-GRILLINGDEBATE-TEX     08-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLINGDEBATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SQUARE OFF IN A HEATED DEBATE ON THE BEST WAY TO GRILL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ They're the best of friends, these three
cookbook writers, but when it comes to the art of grilling, they
march to different kettledrums.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Alters Jamison and Bill Jamison have written a phalanx of
award-winning grilling books, including ``Born To Grill'' and
``Smoke &AMP; Spice,'' testing and creating recipes at their converted
adobe dairy barn in Tesuque, N.M., just outside Santa Fe.
Outfitting their enclosed garden with smokers, kettles, gas grills
and an outdoor fireplace, they've run food through countless trials
by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, Michael McLaughlin has done the same. McLaughlin's
latest books, ``The Southwestern Grill'' and ``All on The Grill,''
are a continuation of more than 25 years of cheffing and writing
and co-writing books, including ``The Silver Palate Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   So when open-fire restrictions in conflagration-plagued New
Mexico were lifted this summer, the trio took off the oven mitts
and pleasantly thrashed out their grilling differences.
</P>
<P>
   After mixing a batch of margaritas, substituting blackberry
brandy for the empty bottle of Triple Sec, they set to work cooking
recipes from their books. (It should be noted, all recipe-dependent
readers, that authors do look up their own recipes in their
cookbooks when they're cooking at home.)
</P>
<P>
   The Jamisons prefer using an open fire of natural charcoal. In
fact, almost all of their test equipment (except their beloved
smokers) has been discarded in favor of their fireplace _ a simple
grate that straddles a hot fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bill, a cerebral sort, explains the choice in almost scholarly
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grilling is using the highest heat possible to create a crust
on the surface of the food. We don't think cooking on a covered
kettle is technically grilling.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a purist approach.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl, the practical sort, agrees with her husband but sees the
process more in cooking terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the popularity of the Weber exploded because backyard
cooks had so many flare-ups. The flare-ups were a result of all the
marinades and the sauces people were using back in the 1950s. Some
of those marinades had a cup of oil in them,'' Cheryl says.
``People take the food out of the marinades and throw it sopping
wet onto the grill. What you get is steamed food, not grill food,
from the smoke that occurs when the sauce hits the charcoal and
then the cover is put on the grill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's another issue I have. A lot of recipes call for cooking
shrimp in the peel on the grill. Again, you're steaming the shrimp
and not getting the grill flavor onto the meat,'' she says as she
piles tail-on grilled shrimp into a large margarita glass. The
presentation is restaurant-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Bill says in passing to McLaughlin, ``You're using Pam
on the grill?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm using it on the quesadilla,'' replies McLaughlin,
wincing at the design flaw in his brand-new Weber Genesis Platinum
that renders the metal handle of the $1,500 gas grill untouchable.
Despite the glitch, McLaughlin prefers cooking with covered grills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking with charcoal is an art form,'' McLaughlin says, ``and
I think beginners have better control with gas. A covered grill,
gas or charcoal, is more controlled and more reliable, especially
if you live in a windy place. The heat stays more even, if you work
with wood chips the flavor goes into the food, and flare-ups are
reduced, though not eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like gas because it eliminates the guesswork, not causes it.
It's charcoal for me that requires holding the hand over the flame
and waiting for the pan, all very awkward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grilling over an open flame for fairly small or thin foods
works great,'' McLaughlin says in agreement with the Jamisons.
``I'm not against much except precooking foods for the grill, which
is almost never necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the tongs are put away and the three tuck into one
anothers' tenderloin sandwiches and fish tacos, they agree _
everything grilled tastes great under a starry New Mexico sky.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
