A6401 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES31-COX     08-30 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Publishers now courting African-American readers
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until Terry McMillan proved them wrong with her best-selling
``Waiting to Exhale,'' most New York publishers ignored the
African-American market as basically a non-reading audience.
</P>
<P>
   Authors such as Tajuana ``TJ'' Butler and former Atlantan E.
Lynn Harris had to resort to publishing their own books. Harris
sold copies of ``Invisible Life'' out of the back of his car and in
beauty parlors. Butler, whose novel ``Sorority Sisters'' was
published this year by Villard, peddled copies of her
self-published books to black-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started publishing myself, I was advised against
it because I was told the industry frowned upon it. But within the
African-American community I saw lots of sales,'' says Harris, a
Doubleday author with 2 million books in print.
</P>
<P>
   With Harris and fellow author Eric Jerome Dickey now regularly
landing on the best-seller list, more doors are opening for black
writers.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Kensington Publishing will launch a new line of
fiction and nonfiction for African-Americans, and next winter
Random House will follow suit with its Strivers Row imprint.
</P>
<P>
   Kensington plans 12 titles for the first year on topics from
mysteries to health. The list includes ``Souls of My Sisters: Black
Women Break Their Silence, Tell Their Stories and Heal Their
Spirit'' by Dawn Marie Daniels and Candace Sandy, and ``Looking for
Luv,'' a novel by Carl Weber.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Terry McMillan's success, blacks were buying books (by
African-Americans) just because of the novelty. Taste wasn't really
involved,'' says Manie Barron, publisher of Amistad Press, an
imprint of HarperCollins that publishes fiction and nonfiction by
blacks. ``Now, a decade later, readers are more discerning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Movies and the morgue: Ever since Jodie Foster rejected offers
to play medical examiner Kay Scarpetta, Patricia Cornwell has
resisted making any movie deals. But now the Richmond author has
sold the rights to all 11 Scarpetta novels to Sony Pictures.
Publishers Weekly reports that the $5 million price tag includes a
five-year option on future novels. Cornwell's latest novel, ``The
Last Precinct'' _ which will hit stores in October _ focuses on
Scarpetta's investigation of the 400-year-old violent death of one
of the Jamestown, Va., settlers. In the process, Scarpetta, her
niece Lucy, and detective Pete Marino become the targets of vicious
hate crimes apparently connected to the excavation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Like, Harry Who? Younger readers may be devouring J.K.
Rowling's Harry Potter novels with a passion, but many teenagers
apparently have no time for literary pursuits. When teenmag.com,
the Web site of Teen Magazine, asked 3,090 teens how many books
they read for fun this summer, 41 percent said none; 30 percent
said fewer than five; 17 percent said between five and 10; and
slightly more than 11 percent said more than 10 books.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
