r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE31-COX     08-30 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Herb by any name still tastes as sweet
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE _ The night was warm, and the mood was mellow. The
three of us, my host Debbie Moore Clark, her pal Christine Lange
and I, were motoring back to Debbie's home after a festive
gathering of the Charlotte Herb Guild, where I had done a little
speechifying.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, we began talking about how different words are used in
different regions of the country. And how some are passed down in
families, even after passing out of general use. In Debbie's
family, bedspreads were ``counterpanes,'' and coverlets were
``kiverlets'' (many of my Alabama ancestors called bedcovers
``kiver,'' rhyming with river).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, conversation got around to herbs. And from there it
didn't take long for the three of us language lovers to get to how
the word ``herb'' is pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Christine and I quickly agreed that not pronouncing the ``h''
was our way, always had been, always would be. That ``herb''
wouldn't be like some other words we could think of, words that
started out one way and got dragged into another pronunciation by
some style whim.
</P>
<P>
   Halley's Comet, for example. Most of my life, I heard it
pronounced to rhyme with ``Bailey's'' (admittedly, my world was far
from worldly). Then I started hearing it rhyme with ``Sally's.''
Everyone I knew used to say ``ha-rass.'' Lately, I hear (especially
among TV news readers) as many accents on the first syllable,
making it sound like somebody's name.
</P>
<P>
   All of us laughed when we noted how the pronunciation of some
words _ ``vase'' and ``tomato'' among them _ makes some people
sound as if they're putting on airs: ``Vahz.'' ``To-mah-toe.''
</P>
<P>
   When conversation got back to herbs, Martha Stewart was not far
behind. She pronounces them ``herbs,'' with an ``h,'' as do the
Brits. But because Martha so inspires ridicule, her pronunciation
seems affected, even if it isn't. As Debbie learned a few years
ago, in some places, even in America, herbs' ``h'' comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   From 1989 to 1996 Debbie lived in Roanoke, Va., where friends
from the Herb Society of Southwestern Virginia introduced her to
the ``pristinely beautiful'' Buffalo Springs Herb Farm, near
Lexington. After a year of frequent visits to the farm, immersing
herself in the study of herb culture, harvesting and use, Debbie
noticed that ``most, if not all, the professional herb growers and
speakers voiced the `h' when pronouncing the word `herb.' I had
always said `erb,' the American version of the British `herb.'''
</P>
<P>
   As the saying goes, when in Roanoke. ... ``I decided to change
my pronunciation to `herb,' voicing the long-silent `h.' Once
determined, it did not take me long to feel comfortable with the
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, she and her husband, Mack, moved to Charlotte,
where they built their home (Maison Aurore), moving in last year.
Here, Debbie's diligently acquired knowledge has been loosed in a
space that grows herbs galore, including basil (her pesto is
legendary) so big and healthy that it looks illegal, along with
mountains of one of my favorites, rosemary. It always invites
touches and sniffs when planted along pathways.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in the Queen City, Debbie of course reached out
to other herb people, carrying with her that British-sounding `h.'
``Without fail,'' she said, ``my pronunciation was politely
corrected: `Don't you mean ``erb?'''''
</P>
<P>
   Once, during her ultimately successful search for kindred herb
souls, she telephoned the Chamber of Commerce, where the
receptionist asked, ``Herb who?''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Debbie do when the word comes up these days?
</P>
<P>
   Skillfully wheeling through traffic, she answered without
'esitation: ``Now, I say it both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? In language (especially English) as in gardening, if
you're looking for blind consistency, fuggiddabouddit.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May's column appears weekly.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail him at leemay(at)att.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
