<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-KIDS-MANAGINGMONEY-TE     08-30 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MANAGINGMONEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS TO HELP KIDS MANAGE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids tend to be overly conscious or totally clueless when it
comes to money; some want to own the stock market by the time
they're 10, and others don't understand the difference between 50
cents and $50.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you teach your kids about money? Dr. Spock never
covered the Dow, but an entire subcategory of parenting books
offers advice about kids and finances. We've rounded up some of the
most promising books we've found. Most are written by financial
experts, and they're full of advice about allowances and
investments and teaching children the value of a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Kids and Money: Giving Them the Savvy to Succeed
Financially'' by Jayne A. Pearl (Bloomberg Press, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   This book covers just about everything: allowances and first
investments, financial aid for college and profitable first jobs.
Jayne A. Pearl, a former business reporter and editor, offers
advice and personal stories from parents, kids and financial
experts, which makes ``Kids and Money'' informative and readable.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Kids and Money: A Hands-On Parent's Guide to Teach Children
About Money Management and Business Basics'' by Michael J. Searls
(Summit Financial Products, $9.95).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, another book called ``Kids and Money'' _ but this one's
different. This book teaches parents how they can encourage wise
spending, saving and investing; the emphasis is on good money
management all the way through adulthood. Michael J. Searls, a
former Wall Street adviser, also offers ideas for kids with an
entrepreneurial streak.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Kiplinger's Dollars &AMP; Sense for Kids'' by Janet Bodnar
(Kiplinger Books, $17.95).
</P>
<P>
   Janet Bodnar (who writes a nationally syndicated column as ``Dr.
Tightwad'') is a senior editor at ``Kiplinger's Personal Finance
Magazine'' _ and she has three children. In this book for parents,
Bodnar reminds parents that they are the ones with the authority
and responsibility to teach their kids the value of money. Excerpts
from her syndicated question-and-answer column are interspersed
with advice on educating kids and handling sticky financial
situations.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Kids' Allowances: How Much, How Often &AMP; How Come'' by David
McCurrach (Kids' Money Press, $8.95).
</P>
<P>
   Financial adviser David McCurrach helps readers determine how
much allowance to give kids _ what amount will teach them how to
manage money but won't be more than they need. One chapter provides
tips from money experts; you can also read how other parents
developed their allowance system and learn the average amount that
thousands of parents give their children. A separate workbook lets
you sit down with your child and figure out the right amount
together.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Growing Money: A Complete Investing Guide for Kids'' by
Gail Karlitz and Debbie Honig (Price Stern Sloan Pub., $6.99).
</P>
<P>
   This is a book for parents and kids (ages 9-12) to read
together; it teaches kids (and confused adults) the basics of the
stock market. After spilling all the facts, ``Growing Money'' lets
kids practice what they've learned: Readers get a fund of imaginary
dollars, and the book takes them through the process of investing
it wisely. They learn how to read stock pages and can use a chart
to track their earnings and losses. By the end, they'll understand
the process and the risks of investing real money.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
