<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMMERS: THE ADVANCED COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hammering nails is such an elementary task that it would seem
that no explanation is needed. Yet professional carpenters and shop
instructors say that many do-it-yourselfers don't know how to drive
nails efficiently. The most common mistake is in holding the hammer
too close to the head.
</P>
<P>
   If you only use a hammer for an occasional task, like hanging a
picture, then you can use almost any method to get the job done,
provided you don't damage the work or hurt yourself. But if an
involved construction project requires driving a lot of nails, then
proper technique is essential to avoid arm fatigue and mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   Good nailing technique starts by choosing the right hammer. The
claw hammer is the traditional tool because it can be used to pull
nails as well as drive them. Until recently, most claw hammers came
with wooden handles. A wooden handle has a natural resiliency that
absorbs the shock generated when the hammer strikes the nail.
</P>
<P>
   The main drawback to the wooden handle is that it will split or
crack when subjected to a lot of nail pulling. In an effort to
produce a more durable handle, tool manufacturers introduced
steel-shank hammers. These stand up to strenuous nail pulling, but
they have little spring and they can cause arm fatigue. Tubular
steel and fiberglass handles are an attempt to combine the best of
both materials.
</P>
<P>
   The handle is only part of the hammer; it is also important to
consider the working end of the hammer, the head. Hammerheads are
available in weights ranging from 16 to 22 ounces. (Some specialty
dealers offer hammers in lighter weights for model makers.)
Generally, the 16-ounce head is better for light construction,
finishing and repair work. Choose a hammer with the heavier
22-ounce head for framing work.
</P>
<P>
   The face of the hammer may be either smooth or textured. A
smooth face is designed for finish work. If the hammer slips from
the nail, the wood will be dented but not scratched. A hammer with
a smooth face, however, will often slip off the nail head if the
carpenter works too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Textured faces are designed to grip a nail head even if the
hammer doesn't land squarely. There are two types: One is milled
(also called a serrated or waffle face). It has a series of
parallel grooves cut across the hammer face in a checkerboard
pattern. Milled-face hammers are good for driving galvanized nails
because the rough face pattern will not rub the galvanized coating
off the nails. The main disadvantage to a milled-faced hammer is
that it can leave an ugly hammer track if it strikes the wood.
</P>
<P>
   The second type of textured face is the sandpaper face, which
has more grip than a smooth face but won't scar a wood surface.
</P>
<P>
   Nailing technique consists of tapping the nail lightly to give
it a good start in the wood, then swinging the hammer properly to
drive the nail home with the least amount of effort. For a large
nail, grip the shaft of the nail between the thumb and index finger
using the other three fingers to brace the hand. For smaller nails,
like roofing nails or brads, it is easier to keep the hand flat,
palm up, and grip the nail between the first two fingers. With this
approach, the knuckles of the holding hand are out of the way and
you have a clear view of the nail.
</P>
<P>
   When starting the nail, hold the hammer toward the middle of the
handle for greater control. Give the nail a few light taps to seat
it into the wood, then remove the nail-holding hand. Slide the hand
on the hammer toward the end of the handle. This position will give
you greater driving force.
</P>
<P>
   Your hammer grip should be firm. If the handle is slippery and
difficult to hold, try roughening it with coarse-grit sandpaper.
Some carpenters rub their hammers with pine tar (available at
sporting good stores for baseball bats), but too much can make the
handle sticky.
</P>
<P>
   There may be times when you have to start a nail in a
hard-to-reach spot. For example, if you are working from a ladder,
you have to hold the ladder rung with one hand while starting the
nail with the other. You can accomplish this with a special
nail-hammer grip. Wrap the fingers around the hammerhead and hold
the nail so the head rests against the hammer cheek. Drive the nail
into the wood by punching the hammerhead with the heel of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hammering a nail seems relatively simple, but it can be
dangerous. A glancing hammer blow can cause nails to become
projectiles. Always wear eye protection. Never hold nails in your
mouth; the coating on some nails, galvanized or resin compounds,
could cause a toxic reaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
