<HEADER>
A6440 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BATTLING-BLUESFESTS-T     08-30 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTLING-BLUESFESTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BEDFORD BLUES FESTS, BUT ONE'S IN DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Sit down. Take a deep breath. This gets
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the Bedford Blues Festival &AMP; Art Fair brought
artists such as Delbert McClinton, Jimmie Vaughan and Keb' Mo' to a
large field adjacent to Harris Methodist H.E.B. hospital just in
Bedford, a Fort Worth suburs.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, there is a festival in the same place, but it's
called the City of Bedford Labor Day BluesFest. McClinton, soul
queen Irma Thomas, New Orleans' Funky Meters, Wilson Pickett and
many more will be playing.
</P>
<P>
   The festival ends Sunday, the day before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Wait, there's more.
</P>
<P>
   A blues festival called, once again, the Bedford Blues Festival
&AMP; Art Fair will also go on this Friday, Saturday and Sunday _ in
downtown Dallas. This Bedford blues festival will include sets by
Shemekia Copeland, Coco Montoya and Cowtown's own Robert Ealey, all
at City Hall Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   This festival is being put on by the same company, Main Events
International, that put on the Bedford Blues Festival &AMP; Art Fair
for five years in Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   Got all that? Good. Now the question is: How did this confusing
situation happen? The answer, of course, depends largely on whom
you ask.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hair, who has booked every Bedford blues festival held ``in
Bedford,'' and Sherri Strayer, the city's special events
coordinator, say that Stephen Millard, MEI's president, has been
sneaky, right down to copyrighting the name Bedford Blues Festival
&AMP; Art Fair and the logo.
</P>
<P>
   Two festivals with ``Bedford'' in the name, both running on the
same days, will only confuse blues fans, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy, isn't it?'' asks Hair. ``Millard doesn't have
Bedford behind his event _ we have the same staging and the same
location. And ours is free. I think he's just hurting himself. He's
attempting to portray his event as the same event it's been for the
past five years, and it's not. It's misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Millard, naturally, doesn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started this event, there was nothing going on as far
as blues in the Metroplex,'' he says. ``We put Bedford on the map.
We already had this year's festival on the books and the talent
hired and they decided to do their own festival in Bedford. And
it's not just the music _ it's the party. And we know how to throw
a good party. This is a community celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   What we know for sure is that in January, the city of Bedford
cut its ties to Millard and MEI. The reasons included wanting to
get more local artists and performers and advertisers, according to
Strayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't moving the festival in the way we wanted it to
go,'' she says. ``And last year there was a $5 admission; we wanted
the festival to be free. There were continuous disagreements, and
we had to make our decision and move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The final straw, she says, was learning that Millard had
copyrighted the name and logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff felt betrayed,'' she says. ``Obviously this was not
done in a forthright way. That was the final point; and at that
point, we decided we'd part ways and didn't need MEI's services.''
</P>
<P>
   Millard sharply disagrees, saying he registered the name in 1995
as a business under the MEI umbrella and that he copyrighted the
logo only to protect it. It just made good sense, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we'd been used,'' he says of his dealings with the
city. ``We brought this event to the city of Bedford. They saw us
struggle with the event for the first three years, and in the
fourth year we made a profit and they said, `Hey, we could do that'
and tried to take it over. We accepted all the responsibility on
this event, and they took us out.''
</P>
<P>
   So the two sides split, and each decided to put together its own
festival. At that point, Hair and MEI's Abby Goldstein worked on
booking the talent for their respective festivals. Hair's lineup _
that is, the one in Bedford _ is a more diverse blend of blues,
soul, funk and (with Joe Ely and Monte Montgomery aboard) Texas
roots music.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who's part of the Bedford festival in Dallas, says
she concentrated more on a ``traditional blues lineup and giving an
opportunity to local and regional people as well as those with a
national reputation.'' Admission to the Dallas-based festival
ranges from $8 to $20, with limited opportunities to get in free.
</P>
<P>
   Hair says that there was only one act that both festivals were
going for: youngster Kenny Wayne Shephard. In the end, neither
festival could book him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millard is closing his event with people who were openers for
us, such as Shemekia Copeland and Coco Montoya,'' he says. ``They
would still be openers for our show. The talent we have blows his
out of the water, and you can quote me.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, several local musicians say that having two
blues festivals over the same weekend won't help anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of stupid,'' says Fort Worth-based guitarist
Sumter Bruton. ``The one in Dallas is a little bluesier, but the
Bedford one has bigger names. The one in Dallas is the way the one
in Bedford was five years ago. A lot of people are confused. It's
like a couple kids saying, `I'll show you.' ... I'm not going to
drive to Dallas, but people there might not drive to Bedford,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist David Millsap, who has toured with McClinton, compares
the situation to ``takin' the football and going home _ it's kinda
childish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-win situation,'' says Millsap, who will be
performing in Bedford on the second stage. ``A lot of things don't
add up to me. A lot of people will show up in Bedford not ever
knowing the difference. If anybody gets hurt, it's going to be the
people who moved to Dallas _ people are just used to the routine
and the place in Bedford. The Bedford blues festival is in
Bedford.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, Millard says. He has plans to take the Bedford
festival on the road to other Texas cities next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedford's just a name,'' he says. ``You could do the New
Orleans jazz festival outside New Orleans. We could have the
Bedford Blues Festival of San Antonio or something like that. We
were even approached once to have the New Bedford Blues Festival in
a New England town called New Bedford. Bedford rolls nicely off the
tongue and always has.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Millard and the folks in Bedford say they are happy
with the festival they'll be presenting this coming weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Millard says he loves the new site and predicts that the Dallas
Bedford will be a big ol' Texas blues party.
</P>
<P>
   Strayer says the ``Bedford'' Bedford festival is once again free
and includes more artists (15 to 20, as opposed to five last year)
and the contributions of local businesses and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the fans will decide where to get their blues.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
