<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6443 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DRACULA-GAME-NYT &LR;      08-30 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DRACULA-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DESIGN FOR A LITTLE FUN: EASY TO PLAY, AND TO FORGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By CHARLES HEROLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kiss Psycho Circus: The Nightmare Child; published by Gathering
of Developers and developed by Third Law Interactive; for Windows
95, 98 and 2000 (Dreamcast version scheduled for October); $39.99;
for players 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Dracula Resurrection; published by Dreamcatcher Interactive and
developed by Index Multimedia; for Windows 95, 98 and NT (Macintosh
version will be available sometime this fall); $19.95; for players
17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Some games are so original or technically innovative or visually
powerful that the game world is never quite the same. Games like
Doom, Myst and Sim City are not only fondly remembered but are
still played. But there are other entertaining games that are
forgotten almost as soon as they are played. If there are B movies,
then these are B games.
</P>
<P>
   Two such games are Kiss Psycho Circus: The Nightmare Child, an
action game based on the Kiss Psycho Circus comic books, which are
inspired by the rock band Kiss, and Dracula Resurrection, an
adventure game.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Nightmare Child combines three of the things that
have been blamed for the degeneration of America's youth, it is
unlikely to have parents up in arms. You don't shoot anything human
in this game. Your foes are mutant circus freaks: Clowns with
spidery metallic legs, strongmen with weights grafted to their
arms, human balloons who spit poisonous gas. While the game is
quite violent, it seems harmless when compared with more sadistic
fare, like Soldier of Fortune or Kingpin.
</P>
<P>
   The framework is silly but functional. The members of Kiss
arrive without makeup to play a concert but instead find themselves
confronted by a gypsy fortuneteller who demands that they save the
world from a ``nightmare child'' that is approaching consciousness.
The setup is reminiscent of an episode of ``The Monkees'' or
``Scooby-Doo,'' only here each band member is fitted out with
artillery and must seek out supernatural armor that will both give
him extraordinary powers and make him look just like his stage
persona in Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting element of Nightmare Child is its circus
motif. There is a perverse, comic-book feel to enemies like an evil
clown throwing deadly juggling clubs or a zombie fat lady throwing
globs of toxic cellulite. If the rest of the game had shown as much
originality, Nightmare Child could have truly been memorable.
</P>
<P>
   But coming on the heels of a string of games like Half-Life and
Deus Ex, which have expanded the whole concept of what a good
action game should be, Nightmare Child's old-fashioned plotless
killfest seems hollow, like mayhem without context, violence
without purpose. Nightmare Child is a throwback to a time when
killing was enough.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the Kiss tie-in, Nightmare Child has little rock
flavor. While you might occasionally come across a jukebox playing
a Kiss song, the score is a fairly standard one, without screaming
guitars and hoarse vocals. The game might have been more
interesting if it had been as over the top as the band.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare Child can be a lot of fun at times, and some
confrontations are very exciting. But as you have to blast away at
yet another monster-spawning machine spitting out yet another horde
of headless bugs, it becomes increasingly hard to stay interested.
Nightmare Child's lack of fresh ideas makes it exciting for only
half of the 40 or so hours it takes to play it.
</P>
<P>
   You're less likely to feel that Dracula Resurrection has worn
out its welcome. It can be finished by any experienced gamer in 10
hours or so, hardly enough time to get bored. Like Nightmare Child,
Resurrection is good-looking and unoriginal. The puzzles are
unexceptional in design and ingenuity and are truly notable only
for their remarkable lack of challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But like Nightmare Child, Resurrection has a certain B-game
charm. Much of the game feels like one of those old Dracula movies
with Christopher Lee. It's all there: Fearful villagers, sinister
demons, a damsel in distress. Every time you solve a puzzle, the
game moves forward with a brief animated scene. It's as if a
projectionist kept stopping the movie to ask you simple riddles,
then showed you a little more once you've answered.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes are quite enjoyable, whether they show a frightened
innkeeper warning you of danger while you study the veins in her
nose or a trio of half-naked female vampires who threaten you while
doing turns and cartwheels that suggest they're planning to take
their act to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrection has almost every puzzle-design flaw common to the
adventure game, yet it never mires the player in an insoluble
muddle. Some puzzles are provided with insufficient clues and one
must use trial and error, but the choices are limited enough that a
trial-and-error approach can be done quickly. Sometimes an
important item is barely visible, but you will find everything
eventually because the game is compartmentalized into small
discrete spaces that limit the area you have to search.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrection may not have any puzzles that will excite you, but
it is also free of puzzles that will send you into a blind rage. If
you've never played an adventure game, Resurrection might be a good
place to start. If you can't get through this one, there's not much
point in going out and buying a difficult adventure game like Grim
Fandango.
</P>
<P>
   At times a B movie can be more fun than a Hollywood epic. One
doesn't always want to be challenged, to be forced to think or
confront something new and unexpected. The same is true of games,
where originality can be both exhilarating and exhausting.
Nightmare Child and Resurrection are games designed to give you a
little fun without disturbing the status quo, and they are
successful in doing that. They are as simple to play as they are
easy to forget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
