<SLUG> BC-WHIPPED-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATING AUDIENCE WITH VULGARITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sleazoid summer of '00 ends, appropriately, with the nadir
of foulmouthed shock movies. ``Whipped's'' only apparent ambition
is to discover just how degradable the young male mindset can be.
Pretty depraved, according to this.
</P>
<P>
   It fancies itself a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is about what the kids these days may or may not call
``scamming.'' (Since little about the characters' behavior is
recognizably human, let alone believable, every aspect of the
picture is called into question.) That's, basically, trying to
achieve as much commitment-free sex as possible by any means
necessary. It's been done before, and for countless generations, I
might add. But it's never been approached with quite the disgusting
avidity of ``Whipped's'' dog-pound quartet.
</P>
<P>
   The four friends meet every Sunday morning at a Manhattan diner
to discuss _ in heartless, excruciating detail _ their weekend's
erotic escapades. Handsome stockbroker Brad (Brian Van Holt)
usually lies his way into women's graces. Faux sensitive writer
manque Zeke (Zorie Barber) is not above picking up larcenous combos
for menages-a-trois; he figures losing a TV set in the morning is a
small price to pay for the experience. Loser-ish Jonathan (Jonathan
Abrahams) tends to choke in the seduction stretch and usually goes
home alone. And their pathetic married bud Eric (Judah Domke)
religiously shows up to live vicariously through the others'
recounted adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Crudely grotesque as their witless sex patter is, things take an
even more dire turn when all three bachelors show up one morning in
love. Brad has met a girl who's genuinely interested in securities
analysis. Zeke's new lady is, well, literate. Jonathan's
acquaintance shares his passion for a certain solitary pursuit and
isn't embarrassed to discuss its joys with him.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the guys soon discover that they've all fallen for
the same girl. Mia is inarguably a dream come true, sweet and
intelligent and certainly accommodating. Her only weensy little
flaw is that she can't make up her mind, and soon the pals are at
each other's throats over who'll become her main man.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's one virtue is the casting of Amanda Peet as Mia. The
wily and evidently fearless actress is also absolutely captivating,
much like she was earlier this year when she stole the show as
``The Whole Nine Yards' '' eager hit woman, but this time in a
generally reactive role. It isn't until the see-it-from-a-mile-away
``surprise'' ending that Peet takes charge of the film's definition
of humor. Considering how lame the boys' antics are leading up to
then _ they drop things in toilets, they get caught in compromising
positions wearing tiger-striped skivvies, etc. _ Peet probably
comes off as well as she does by wisely playing so much of it
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whipped'' is the feature writing, directing and producing
debut of an advertising person named Peter M. Cohen. It has all the
insight into the battle of the sexes of a tire commercial, with
noticeably less wit and taste than most. In fact, it's not off-base
to call ``Whipped'' the Firestone recall of gross-out comedies. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The film: ``Whipped'' (R; language, sex). &QL; 
The stars: Amanda Peet, Brian Van Holt, Jonathan Abrahams, Zorie
Barber, Judah Domke. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written, directed and produced by Peter M.
Cohen. Released by Destination Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 22 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
