<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SMOOTH-JAZZ-LADN &LR;      08-30 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOOTH-JAZZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTTISTS JAM AT SMOOTH-JAZZ FEST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Friday' refers to Sept. 1,2000.) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smooth-jazz may be the Rodney Dangerfield of pop genres _ it
gets no respect.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons for this. Some say smooth-jazz is jazz
for people who hate jazz, or know nothing about it. Some say it's
new age with saxophones.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, smooth-jazz is the radio format that's home to the
likes of the dreaded (by true jazzers) Kenny G, Boney James and
Dave Koz. One of the genre's biggest outlets is local station
KTWV-FM (94.7) _ the Wave. But that station has found room to play
some imaginative music _ specifically, pianist Brad Mehldau's cover
of Neil Young's ``Old Man'' from the ``Space Cowboys'' soundtrack,
among other pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them go that far.
</P>
<P>
   Some artists involved in the music refuse to even cop to the
smooth-jazz label. For example, of the acts on Friday's ``Montreux
Festival on Tour'' show at the Universal Amphitheatre, featuring Al
Jarreau, Roberta Flack, David Sanborn, Joe Sample and George Duke,
few would admit to playing that type of music, which partly has its
origins in the mid-'70s work of saxophonist John Klemmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a smooth-jazz show in the classic sense,'' insists
tour musical director Duke, the eclectic keyboardist, producer and
singer who made trend-setting fusion albums in the '70s and went on
to produce some of the biggest names in r&AMP;b and jazz. ``The term is
a little strange because there's not a lot of jazz in the smooth.
We're a nation of musical followers instead of innovators.
Smooth-jazz sounds manufactured, like it comes from Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   For 34 years, international jazz, rock, gospel, pop and blues
acts have jammed on the stages of the Montreux Jazz Festival in
Montreux, Switzerland. This is the first year the concept has been
taken on the road, to 21 cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most wonderful thing about it is the jam session
approach,'' says veteran crooner and five-time Grammy winner
Jarreau. ``It makes people's eyes light up. On these multiple-act
bills _ unless you go to a late-night jazz spot _ you don't usually
see these kinds of mixes and matches in these interesting
combinations, everyone playing with everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Jarreau, whose current album, ``Tomorrow Today''
(GRP/VMG), has spent 23 weeks in Billboard's Top Contemporary Jazz
Albums chart, will sing the Count Basie tune, ``Shiny Stockings,''
with Duke, while saxophonist Sanborn will be involved in numerous
musical meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supporting each other at various times,'' says
keyboardist Sample, whose current hit album, ``The Song Lives On''
(PRA/GRP), features singer Lalah Hathaway, daughter of the late r&AMP;b
great Donny Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no formulas on this stage,'' he adds. ``It's a
compilation of various artists and sidemen and musicians and
vocalists who have something to say. It's a very unformulized
concept. These are the types of acts that the smooth-jazz stations
have created from.''
</P>
<P>
   While Los Angeles' highly successful Wave shows imagination,
other new adult contemporary/smooth-jazz formats across the country
reveal less. At smooth-jazz stations elsewhere, a typical playlist
includes generous helpings of often bland pop instrumentals by the
likes of Kenny G, David Benoit, James, Koz and Fourplay _ and no
Steely Dan, Kenny Garrett, George Benson, Ronny Jordan or Mehldau,
artists that could easily fit the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's room for all of it,'' declares L.A. Wave music
director Ralph Stewart. ``There are a number of smooth-jazz
stations in the top five of their markets. We all know where our
sweet spot is. I believe there's room to grow the format. People
want a little surprise in the music programming.''
</P>
<P>
   Sample believes the music would be better off if it wasn't so
heavily researched by radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smooth-jazz wouldn't be an offensive term if they were doing
it without consultants and one guy ruling it and they were really
getting into the music of the artist,'' says Sample, one of the
founders of pioneering jazz-funk group the Jazz Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the Montreux tour travels the country, audiences
are getting something they rarely see these days _ musical
experimentation and improvisation, even if the results are
decidedly easy to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowds, ranging widely in age and makeup, have been
coming in droves.
</P>
<P>
   At a show a few days ago in Tampa, Fla., for instance, Jarreau
called for the house lights to be turned up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like the United Nations in there _ white, black,
Asians, Cubans, Puerto Ricans _ an interesting mix of ages and
musical backgrounds,'' says Duke, whose new largely vocal-oriented
album, ``Cool,'' is due in early October. ``The show is so diverse.
It's really a variety show, a thoroughly integrated variety show.
Like, I'll be playing something and all of a sudden David Sanborn
will come out and start jamming with me. Last night, I was playing
some space music and a guy from the crew came out in an alien mask.
Stuff like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau is an artist who is comfortable both in improv sessions
and more controlled musical environments. Dubbed ``the voice of
versatility,'' the singer has performed many times at the Montreux
Festival in its home base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky,'' he says. ``I'm getting a lot of airplay without
having to change what I do. I'm not gonna rap and nothing's
sampled, but we have kept the sound current.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau bemoans the fact that there isn't a lot of competition
waiting in the wings these days. In the age of hip-hop, few
memorable singers are being produced, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hip-hop is the sound kids want today,'' Jarreau says. ``We've
kind of lost a generation, sadly. There's a fine group of young
singers out there, but their music doesn't offer them a broad
format for singing as it could. I wish there were more singers, but
this is the day of the rapper. There's great rap and mediocre rap,
like anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally disappointing, Jarreau continues, is the lack of
exciting new instrumentalists on the scene. He chalks that up to
the all-encompassing commercial effects of hip-hop, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a generation who might've learned an instrument,''
the singer says. ``Today, it's all about sampling and rapping. Kids
who might've looked up to Herbie Hancock or any number of players
aren't doing that. They're sampling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other upsetting trend is the closing of the clubs _ not
just jazz clubs but Top 40 _ where people can hear actual music
being performed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sample went even further: ``I wish they would put a jazz club
back into every black neighborhood in every American city.''
---What: ``Montreux Festival on Tour.'' &QL; 
Who: Al Jarreau, Roberta Flack, David Sanborn, Joe Sample and
George Duke. &QL; 
Where: Universal Amphitheatre, 100 Universal City Plaza, Universal
City. &QL; 
When: 7:15 p.m. Friday. &QL; 
Tickets: $20 to $70.50. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGE-(     08-30 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGE-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REJECTS DIRECT TALKS WITH REBEL GROUP HOLDING AMERICAN
TOURIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ The Muslim rebel gunmen who have kidnapped
an American tourist in the southern Philippines belong to a
particularly brutal faction that has tortured and killed hostages
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after seizing the tourist, Jeffrey Schilling, 24, a
member of the group told a local radio station Wednesday that it
was ``fully prepared'' to talk with the United States, but only if
Libya, Iraq, North Korea and China also took part.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, said the group member, Abu Sabaya, ``Maybe we
will behead him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a spokesman for the State Department, Philip
Reeker, ruled out negotiations, saying, ``The United States does
not make deals with terrorists, and this organization, the Abu
Sayyaf group, is an organization which is listed in our patterns of
global terrorism as one of the radical Islamic separatist groups
operating in the southern Philippines.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed that the United States would not pay ransom money
but, in answer to a question, said mediation by other nations like
Libya would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Libya, which has longstanding contacts with the rebels, has
stepped in to negotiate for the release of a dozen Western hostages
kidnapped four months ago by the Abu Sayyaf group. Libyan officials
said on Tuesday that they would be willing to help in the case of
Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Libya has secured the release of six of the Westerners,
paying a ransom of $1 million for each of them. The chief
Philippine negotiator, Roberto Aventajado, said Wednesday that he
expected the last six Westerners to be released soon.
</P>
<P>
   But in what could be a troublesome sign for the case of
Schilling, Aventajado said he was optimistic because those other
hostages are being held by a separate, and perhaps more amenable,
faction of the Abu Sayyaf group.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf is a minor group in a long-running Muslim separatist
war in the south of the Philippines, an overwhelmingly Roman
Catholic nation. Unlike the major participants, it has occupied
itself more with terror and ransom kidnappings than with
ideological warfare.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1991 by a veteran of the anti-Soviet war in
Afghanistan, Abu Sayyaf, which means ``Bearer of the Sword,'' has
earned a reputation as one of the more aggressive of the region's
armed groups.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 it killed seven people by rolling grenades down the
aisle of a Roman Catholic cathedral. In 1995 it massacred 53 people
in a shooting spree in a Christian-dominated village. Its kidnap
victims have included Spanish nuns, an American Bible translator
and a fishery worker from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   But it had remained a small group of perhaps 200 armed men until
the windfall of ransom money from its recent kidnappings. According
to some reports, new recruits have swelled its number to as many as
5,000 fighters.
</P>
<P>
   As it grew, Abu Sayyaf fragmented into a half dozen sometimes
squabbling factions spread across several tiny islands. Its
internal divisions over tactics and money have complicated recent
hostage negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The faction with which Aventajado has been negotiating has
treated its hostages carefully and has already released two dozen
of them _ in return for a reported total of at least $11.5 million
_ since its latest spate of kidnappings began in April.
</P>
<P>
   Naming two leaders of this faction, Aventajado said Wednesday
that ``I have received a letter from Robot and Mujib assuring me
that they don't have anything to do with this Schilling
abduction.''
</P>
<P>
   The separate faction that apparently seized Schilling is
responsible for the kidnapping earlier this year of about 50
Philippine schoolchildren and teachers whom it held for months,
sometimes in underground pits.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At one point it apparently tortured and killed a Catholic
priest. At another it beheaded two teachers when the United States
did not respond to its demand for the release of Arab terrorists
convicted in the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   In a rambling radio interview, an Abu Sayyaf member suggested
that the group might make a similar demand in return for the
release of Schilling. He said formal demands would be announced on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel member asserted that Schilling worked for the Central
Intelligence Agency, but both his family and U.S. officials
dismissed that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``This individual is a completely innocent person who has been
unjustifiably seized,'' said John Caulfield, the U.S. consul
general in Manila.
</P>
<P>
   In Oakland, Calif., Schilling's home, a friend, Anthony Rodgers,
said: ``There's no CIA involvement. He's apolitical. He's just a
guy who happens to be in love. That's all it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling is a graduate of the University of California,
Berkeley, who majored in Near Eastern studies and converted to
Islam, his friends said.
</P>
<P>
   According to his mother, Carol, he had gone to the Philippines
in March because of a longstanding interest in the region and had
stayed on because he fell in love with a woman from the southern
Philippines, Ivi V. Osani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get him out of the country three times but he
didn't come out,'' his mother said. ``He was too much in love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-WOBBLIES-NNS &LR;      08-30 2051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOBBLIES-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST ODDS IN TODAY'S LABOR MOVEMENT, THE WOBBLIES ARE ON FIRMER
FOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
WEDNESDAY, Aug. 30, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With three photos, of Alexis Buss (NNS1 and NNS2) and
of an IWW recruiting poster (NNS3). For information about
purchasing these photos call 202-383-7824.
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Wobblies, diehard iconoclasts of the labor
movement, are still around. Still organizing. Still looking to
transform the world order.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, the tiny yet feisty Industrial Workers
of the World has seen its membership grow _ to 1,000 worldwide, up
from a low of fewer than 100 in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   And those members remain true to the concept of ``one big
union.'' They're radical syndicalists, as they have been since the
IWW's founding in 1905 in Chicago. (Quick labor history review: A
syndicalist favors bringing government and industry under control
of labor unions by means of ``direct action,'' such as general
strikes and, if need be, sabotage.)
</P>
<P>
   They fight to transfer all profits and power from bosses to
workers, because it's the workers who do all the work. That victory
would form the shell of a new society, they say _ as they have
said, loudly, for all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Their idealistic battle was ignited generations ago by Wobblies
that became legendary: Mother Jones, who agitated for labor rights
into her 90s and inspired a magazine that still bears her name.
Elizabeth Gurley Flynn, a co-founder of the American Civil
Liberties Union. Balladeer Joe Hill, whose last words were, ``Don't
waste time in mourning. Organize.'' Eugene Debs, who helped create
the Socialist Party in America.
</P>
<P>
   That the Wobblies still exist, much less are growing, runs
against a decadeslong decline in mainstream American labor union
membership. It hit a high of 27 percent of the workforce in 1953;
its current 14 percent is an all-time low, according to the Bureau
of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The IWW has made inroads recently, organizing bookstores, small
shops, college-student workers and temporary employees. It got a
smattering of national publicity in 1996 when an employee was fired
after trying, unsuccessfully, to organize a Borders Books &AMP; Music
store in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The national IWW headquarters shifted this year from Ypsilanti,
Mich., to Philadelphia, site of former glory days: Back in 1916,
all but two of the bustling docks at this port were under IWW
control.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the top Wob is a young woman. She is Alexis Buss, a
slight, 27-year-old freckled Philadelphian who wears her IWW cap
backward. Buss was elected in January, after pledging ``to make the
IWW a cohesive fighting organization, rather than a collection of
isolated activists.'' To reinvigorate the IWW, once known_ and
feared _ as ``the fighting union.''
</P>
<P>
   No one remembers exactly why members are called Wobblies, or
Wobs for short, as they have been since the early 1900s. Some say
it's symbolic of the wobble saw, mounted to cut a groove wider than
the saw is thick. Others think it's based on an immigrant's
mispronounciation of the letters IWW _ ``eye
wobble-you-wobble-you.''
</P>
<P>
   From its founding, the IWW has been one intense bunch:
</P>
<P>
   _ They wrote and sang the most enduring labor songs, including
``Solidarity Forever,'' ``Rebel Girl'' and ``The Preacher and the
Slave,'' origin of the phrase, ``pie in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   _ They staged dramatic job actions: In 1912, Wobs lead 10,000
strikers at the American Woolen Co. mills in Lawrence, Mass.,
forcing managers to give workers significant pay raises. Strikers
were beaten and a woman worker was killed by shots from the swarms
of 22,000 military police.
</P>
<P>
   _ They were famous for their propaganda: ``Keep warm, burn out
the rich.'' ``The boss needs you, you don't need him.'' ``Good pay
or bum work.''
</P>
<P>
   _ They've constantly fought for a seemingly unattainable goal:
As the preamble to the IWW constitution reads, ''... a struggle
must go on until the workers of the world organize as a class, take
possession of the means of production, abolish the wage system, and
live in harmony with the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   But now, ``what I hear all the time is, `Wobblies? You guys
still around?' '' Buss says at a recent protest march while hawking
buttons with such slogans as ''4 Hour Day, 4 Day Week'' and ``Stop
Exploiting Student Workers!''
</P>
<P>
   A tattooed man toting a motorcycle helmet approaches. He eyes
the selection on the corkboard leaning against Buss' leg.
``Wobblies? Cool,'' he says. He pays her for several pins, offers a
variation on ``glad to know you guys are still around,'' and shakes
her hand.
</P>
<P>
   The day is hot. Buss is standing in the sun. She shifts feet.
It's important to sell buttons, she says. ``They're popular. They
bring in money.'' Bumper stickers, too. One says, ``Because
capitalism cannot be reformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss is a 21st-century Wobbly. She works to generate revenue,
while still supporting the overthrow of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   She laments the ``squandering'' of a $200,000 bequest to the IWW
in the early 1990s. ``Let's just say that it wasn't as well spent
as it should have been,'' she says. Instead, the money, from two
former members in the Pacific Northwest, ``just kind of went away,
into lots of little places.'' Buss would rather have invested it _
which runs counter to that old Wobbly saying that the ``the union
treasury is in the members' pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss once even accepted a management job _ forfeiting her IWW
membership _ to ensure that workers at a print shop had a fair
boss. ``We figured, better me than somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   She comes from traditional Pennsylvania blue-collar roots, and
joined the IWW at age 19. Her grandfather was a longtime union
organizer at a steel plant. ``Working there totally destroyed his
hearing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even after he'd been incapacitated by Alzheimer's disease,
``he'd see me and say, `How's the union?' I was happy we had that
link.''
</P>
<P>
   She passed on a college education, taking just one labor law
course.
</P>
<P>
   Now her title is IWW general secretary-treasurer. It reflects
the union's disdain of authority. ``We tried having a president
awhile back, members didn't go for that,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Buss heads a movement based on ideals that, ironically, hinder
it from gaining any real power.
</P>
<P>
   The IWW is a pure democracy, controlled by its rank and file
without a traditional leadership structure. Dues start at just $5 a
month, so it's perpetually cash-poor.
</P>
<P>
   Members, tasked with literally organizing the entire world, are
themselves difficult to corral. Most are independent thinkers who
lean toward the cantakerous. They are socialists, atheists,
intellectuals, dreamers. Some have multiple piercings and tatoos;
others, gray ponytails.
</P>
<P>
   Even determining just how many Wobblies there are is tricky.
``It varies by month, when people pay their dues,'' Buss says.
There is no demographic information on the thousand or so members.
(By comparison, the AFL-CIO currently has about 13 million
members.)
</P>
<P>
   Wobbly locals are active across the country, from Boston
(Education Workers Industrial Union 620) to San Francisco (Marine
Transport Workers Industrial Union 510). There also are branches in
England, Australia, South Africa _ ``traditional Wobbly
strongholds,'' as Buss says.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition is what lures, and inspires, most Wobblies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in unionism, that all labor unions must come
together,'' says Miriam Fried of Philadelphia, the employee fired
after the '96 organizing drive at Borders. ``The Wobblies are the
most dedicated union around. I believe workers should make their
own decisions. In the IWW, it's direct democracy, from the bottom
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Vance, another Philadelphia Wobbly, says the IWW has
``the big advantages without the big disadvantages of other
unions.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes representing workers usually overlooked. ``Even if
it's a workplace with just two people and one boss, we're there to
organize,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn Dubofsky is an expert on the IWW. He's a history
professor at Binghamton University-State University of New York and
author of the definitive, ``We Shall Be All: A History of the
Industrial Workers of the World,'' being reissued this November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IWW reached their real peak during World War I,'' Dubofsky
says. ``So, actually, they've survived as a miniscule force for
more than 80 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the passionate Wobblies have become part of the
cultural texture of America, he says. They appear as characters in
Dashiel Hammett's ``Red Harvest,'' in John Dos Passos' ``U.S.A
Trilogy,'' in ``From Here to Eternity'' by James Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the enduring myth of larger-than-life Wobbly
martyr Joe Hill, executed by a Utah firing squad for a murder that
many still insist he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   As the song goes, ``And standing there as big as life, / And
smiling with his eyes, / Joe says, ``What they forgot to kill /
Went on to organize, / Went on to organize.''
</P>
<P>
   What union bosses ``forgot to kill'' was the Wobbly dream of one
union for all, regardless of race, nationality, gender, income or
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different people and different generations find parts of that
dream that appeals to them,'' Dubofsky says.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what keeps the movement going. Just barely.
</P>
<P>
   IWW headquarters is in a gritty Philadelphia neighborhood, with
an address that belies its name: Spring Garden Street. There are no
gardens here, only rundown buildings, pitted curbs, worn and
splintered front doors.
</P>
<P>
   Behind one is the old walk-up that Wobblies are slowly
renovating. There will be an office for Buss, a conference room, a
library for IWW books and pamphlets. The rooms are now a jumble of
bookshelves and desks and half-unpacked boxes and construction
tools. A window fan whirrs in the dusty humidity.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   What decor there is leans toward red, the color of socialism,
the Wobbly color. There's a red phone, piles of copies of the
legendary ``Little Red Songbook.'' A massive banner nearly covers
one wall: ``AN INJURY TO ONE IS AN INJURY TO ALL.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss is greeting visitors at the headquarters' first open house.
The event has drawn about 30, mainly young people wearing red or
black T-shirts. Causing a quiet buzz of excitement is a celebrity
guest, Socialist Party presidential candidate David McReynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My young comrades in the party persuaded me to run,'' says
McReynolds, 70, a retired peace activist who lives in New York's
East Village.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors circle a long table filled with platters of leftovers
from a fund-raiser the night before for another presidential
candidate, Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our landlord is a member of the Green Party,'' Buss says. ``He
said they had extra food, and asked if we wanted it. I said sure.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Buss is a pragmatist. When she took over, the IWW had an $8,000
deficit; now it's solvent. She aims to be able to accept a small
salary so she can drop her part-time typesetting job. She wants to
reach out to younger retail workers and workers toiling too many
hours without overtime. She hopes to circulate more literature,
increase the Wobbly Web presence, organize job actions, build cash
reserves, and, of course, sign up more members.
</P>
<P>
   And she has one more goal:
</P>
<P>
   After his cremation, Joe Hill's ashes were divided and sent to
IWW delegates to be scattered around the world. A small pillbox of
his cremains, after taking a circuitous route, finally ended up
back at the headquarters of the IWW, the union Hill helped to make
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get an urn, but we can't afford it,'' Buss says.
``We'll have to raise some money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6469 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-WOBBLIES-NNS &LR;      08-30 2051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOBBLIES-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAINST ODDS IN TODAY'S LABOR MOVEMENT, THE WOBBLIES ARE ON FIRMER
FOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
WEDNESDAY, Aug. 30, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With three photos, of Alexis Buss (NNS1 and NNS2) and
of an IWW recruiting poster (NNS3). For information about
purchasing these photos call 202-383-7824.
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
