<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKFURT-LONDON-EXCHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE BOERSE CHIEF SCOFFS AT RIVAL BID FOR LONDON STOCK
EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Werner Seifert, the head of Germany's stock
exchange, refused Wednesday to sweeten the terms of a proposed
merger with the London Stock Exchange, dismissing a rival bid of
$1.2 billion by OM Gruppen AB of Sweden as ``ridiculous and
derisory.''
</P>
<P>
   But the unexpected, and hostile, bid by OM, which owns the
Stockholm stock exchange, has ignited speculation about other
takeover bids for the London market, potentially from companies
that do not even operate securities exchanges at the moment. It has
already temporarily blocked the planned merger with Deutsche Boerse
AG, parent of the Frankfurt market.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert and other German executives asserted Wednesday that they
would press ahead with their plans, and that Deutsche Boerse's
shareholders would still vote on the merger plan as previously
scheduled on Sept. 14. But the London Stock Exchange has postponed
its own shareholder vote, and the plan is for all practical
purposes in at least temporary hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Breuer, chief executive of Deutsche Bank AG and chairman of
Deutsche Boerse, said the exchange might consider organizing a
higher counterbid, possibly in conjunction with the Milan, Italy,
and Madrid, Spain, exchanges, but said they had no plans to mount
such an action yet. In a deal reached this spring, the London and
Frankfurt markets form a carefully-balanced ``merger of equals''
and create a pan-European equities exchanged called iX.
</P>
<P>
   German executives said Wednesday that they were confident that
OM's bid would fail to win 75 percent of the shareholder votes at
the London Stock Exchange, the minimum percentage required for the
takeover to succeed. At least for the moment, Seifert said, the
Deutsche Boerse will simply watch the situation unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll decide to make a move when we feel it's right,'' Seifert
said here Wednesday. ``The situation is different now, but not
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial executives across Europe, however, are bracing for the
possibility of yet more bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The London exchange is a sitting duck,'' one executive said.
``This has completely changed the game board.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate is no longer about the ins and outs of the iX
proposal,'' the executive said. ``The debate is now about who will
come along with a biggish wad of cash. Anyone who thinks they would
be good at running an exchange can try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
