<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6472 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-LIEBERMAN-NEWH     08-30 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-LIEBERMAN-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THAT OTHER JOE WORRIES ABOUT LIEBERMAN  
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 29, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(AT)nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Eszterhas is nervous. You know Joe _ he wrote Sharon Stone's
flasher pic, ``Basic Instinct.'' This is the guy who gave the world
the movie ``Showgirls'' _ and even though the world gave it right
back to him, holding it with tongs, he continues to be a Famous
Screenwriter. He's worried about Gore-Lieberman; he thinks they'll
start a new reign of virtue, so he took out a full-page ad in
Variety to warn his fellow sybarites. ``No more Hollywood money for
Al Gore,'' Eszterhas demanded. ``I'm a writer who likes pushing the
envelope, and Joe Lieberman frightens me.''
</P>
<P>
   Could the Democrats ask for anything more? It fits perfectly
with their new role as Safely Devout. Gore, according to The New
York Times, has said he asks himself ``What would Jesus do?'' when
confronted with a thorny moral dilemma. (Perhaps Jesus would tell
Pilate there is No Controlling Roman Authority.) Lieberman has been
making speeches so ridden with references to the Creator that even
the Anti-Defamation League is getting annoyed. If the Father of
``Showgirls'' is worried about these guys, they must be for real.
</P>
<P>
   The secular left wonders when someone will stand up to these
moralizing spiritualists. The religious right barks: How come these
guys can mention God without getting in trouble?
</P>
<P>
   Into this fray rides Eszterhas, warning the land that the very
future of envelope-pushing is in danger. And of course we must push
it, and push it again, even though it's been pushed and stretched
so much that it sags like the skin of a sick elephant. If Eszterhas
had directed ``Saving Private Ryan,'' he would have staged the
invasion of Normandy with an army of lesbian strippers. That's
pushing the envelope. ``Apollo 13''? Simple: three strippers
marooned in space. Which one is a bisexual murderess? Houston, we
have a problem _ and it's not wearing underwear!
</P>
<P>
   Take that, envelope!
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas is not the mainstream. But people like him are always
redefining the mainstream, pumping the tributaries full of brackish
water until the mainstream overflows its banks. Politicians like
Lieberman, earnest and clueless, are bailing with a pop-bottle cap.
George Bush pere, for example, once made the famous remark that the
nation needed to emulate the Waltons, not the Simpsons. This struck
the Gen X demographic as a classic clueless grandpa quote; he
probably cost the GOP 20 million votes for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Same thing with Lieberman's pronouncements. In an interview with
Variety, Lieberman suggested that ``Friends'' was not fit for prime
time, but should be shown in movie theaters. Yes, raincoated
debauchers would have to skulk off to the triple XXX pornhouse to
see ``Friends'' and wait in moist, panting anticipation for the
next naughty single-entendre. If Lieberman is offended by
``Friends,'' someone show him the ``Tom Green Show'' and watch him
dissolve into a smoking puddle of embarrassed goo.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman has been talking about using the power of
government to affect your entertainment choices, and that's what
steams Eszterhas and others. Lieberman's made earnest, nerdy noises
about making TV stations' licenses contingent on a review of their
programming, and making it illegal for minors to be the targets of
ad campaigns for R-rated movies. Of course, no one wants minors to
be the targets, but how would you prove such a thing?
</P>
<P>
   It's the New Democrat approach. Small, precise, targeted laws
that make great sound bites and accomplish nothing. That's why
Eszterhas' campaign will be ignored by his fellow
envelope-piercers. Let Gore and Lieberman make their pious peeps.
Nothing will change.
</P>
<P>
   As for Eszterhas, well, Hollywood knows the score there, too.
Joe has a book to sell _ ``American Rhapsody,'' a funny and
coruscating account of impeachment. This is good publicity. And he
needs it: Once upon a time, the words ``From the Writer of `Basic
Instinct''' sold a few tickets, but people have come to realize
that's now a warning label.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps people will head to Amazon.com to buy his book. If they
do, they'll see a thumbnail biography with this precious line: ``He
has also won awards for attending every one of his son's Little
League games and for writing `Showgirls.'''
</P>
<P>
   What makes him prouder _ mainstreaming the crotch shot or
cheering from the sidelines of his son's games? The latter,
probably. But woe to the God-bothering moralist who thinks he
should be prouder of his son than his movies. Lunatics like that
are downright dangerous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
