<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PURSES-TEX     08-30 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURSES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURSES WITH PERSONALITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CATHERINE NEWTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe this has happened to you. You go to your book club, your
PTA meeting or the office, and three of your fellow females are
toting the exact same Kate Spade bag you just bought instead of
this week's groceries.
</P>
<P>
   This is life with purses in 2000. Amazing. Amazingly redundant.
</P>
<P>
   Sherie D. Giles of Houston is a woman with a solution. A year
ago, she quit her job as a computer software consultant and started
designing a line of handmade bags, dubbed Cocktail Fusion. The bags
are made from a wide range of fabrics that she hunts down from the
Far East to the East Coast. Trims include one-of-a-kind beading,
fabric flowers and outlandish feathers and furs. The bags are fun,
sassy, sometimes sophisticated _ and always unique.
</P>
<P>
   Giles says she'll never make more than four bags from the same
fabrics, and all are reversible. So if you do find yourself in the
company of another Giles purse, you can always turn your bag inside
out. Reverse course, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   The purses have stories. Here's one, in a gold silk fabric
printed with red fish silhouettes. The material comes from Austin,
Giles says. She got it from a woman who sits on her porch, drinks
beer and stamps fabric. And there's a black velvet bag, handpainted
in gold, from Asia. A red bag with a monkey print has tiny glass
beads as fringe. There's an animal-print bag with fur trim that
reverses to a honey-brown velvet. And a red and black silk bag with
a feathery plumage that reverses to elegant basic black. Retail
prices for the bags range from about $75 to $135.
</P>
<P>
   Giles' purse persuasion began when the similarly whimsical
Christmas stockings she made for a home arts-and-crafts show _ most
in animal prints _ sold out. She did some prototypes of the
cocktail purses, enlisted her mother, Mickey, as seamstress and
took her wares to statewide arts fairs _ where, again, they sold
big. Soon, Giles' sister Ginny was able to leave her full-time
banking job and join the growing family sewing circle. Today, Giles
concentrates on finding fabrics and designing the purses, which
Ginny and Mickey piece together in their homes in Liberty, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gearing up for the holiday season, Giles says the trio currently
produce about 300 purses a month _ which is just fine with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives my mom something to do,'' she says, ``and my sister
got to quit her job.'' As for Giles, ``It fixes my shopping
fetish.''
</P>
<P>
   What's in the future for the woman with a purse passion? Giles
says that she's happy with the pace of the company and that she
doesn't want it to get too large. Although, she says, ``My husband
wants it huge.''
</P>
<P>
   And it may have to get bigger. Because couldn't we all _ Spade,
Coach and Fendi fans that we are _ use a little more purse-onality
in our lives?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6475 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TINAHOWE-INTERVIEW-TE     08-30 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINA </SLUG>
 HOWE-INTERVIEW-TEX
 CAN A PLAYWRIGHT CORRECT PAST INJUSTICES? AND HOWE
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
 By MARK LOWRY
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   If she could accomplish one athletic feat, says playwright Tina
Howe, it would be to traverse the unpredictable waters of the
English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the (idea) of traveling through the water,'' she says.
``To me, there's something so elegant and elemental'' about
swimming.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of making that challenging voyage herself, she wrote a
play about a woman from an upper-crust Boston family whose
rebellious spirit led her to become the first woman to swim the
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   That play is ``Pride's Crossing,'' a 1997 Pulitzer Prize
finalist. The 1997 production at Lincoln Center in New York earned
kudos from critics, including New York Post critic Clive Barnes,
who wrote: ``Most plays you watch, but every so often there comes
one you experience. Tina Howe's delightful and moving `Pride's
Crossing' is definitely one you experience and savor.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the critical raves, the play also garnered a Drama
Desk award for actress Cherry Jones in the lead role of the
fictional Mabel Tidings Bigelow. In the play, at age 90, Bigelow
recalls life experiences from ages 10 to 60 while planning a Fourth
of July croquet party.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the reminiscences parallel the author's own. Born in New
York, Howe, 62, grew up in what she calls a wealthy New England
family of eccentrics. Her plays and characters reflect that life of
extravagance, excess and intellect, but like herself, her heroes
have a wild side, which she considers essential if those to the
manor born are to accomplish anything significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what growing up in a privileged life did to my parents.
I think it's poison,'' she says. ``When I was growing up, I was in
constant rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabel, the marathon swimmer of ``Pride's Crossing,'' is a
composite of the author and her Aunt Maddy, who is approaching 100.
Maddy also had a rebellious spirit, Howe says, but never acted upon
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had boundless amounts of love and tolerance. Even though
she had grown up in this rather punishing, elitist world. It always
angered me that she wasn't allowed to reach her full potential,''
Howe says of the society and era that discouraged women from
pursuing their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things one can do as a playwright is change the
facts of life. I just felt that I wanted to rewrite Maddy's past
for her, and I wanted to give her an opportunity to achieve
something extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe, who teaches at Hunter College and New York University, has
been writing plays for 30 years, including the 1984 Pulitzer
finalist ``Painting Churches'' and the 1987 Tony-nominated
``Coastal Disturbances.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the awards and praise she's received, Howe has also
met with fierce criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Her first two works, ``The Nest'' and ``Birth and After Birth,''
delved into gender politics in the early '70s, and audiences
weren't ready for such challenging fare. So Howe decided to
re-evaluate her subject matter and looked around to see what kinds
of material were successful and jibed with her artistic vision. It
was 1973, and Edward Albee and Tom Stoppard were drawing notice.
``It was clear audiences were into escape, so I decided to write a
play set in a museum. I wrote a smart piece about aesthetics that
had 55 characters that were played by a cast of 18. This was my
attempt to be commercial,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The play was ``Museum,'' in which visitors to a modern art
exhibit debate over white canvases presented as art, tackling
perceptions about what constitutes art long before Yasmina Reza's
recent Broadway hit ``Art.'' Howe also pays homage to the aesthetic
world in ``The Art of Dining,'' in which a brilliant writer shows
her shocking lack of table etiquette. This she counts as her most
autobiographical play, and her personal favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Howe acknowledges a debt to the Absurdists: Luigi Pirandello,
Samuel Beckett, Jean Genet, Albee. In fact, she counts seeing a
1960 production of Ionesco's ``The Bald Soprano'' in Paris as the
moment that changed her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never seen theater like that,'' says Howe. ``What I
particularly loved about Ionesco was the joy and irreverence with
which he approached theater, the extravagance of language and the
extravagance of event, and the daring and mischief he was willing
to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's what the theater is supposed to do. It's
supposed to challenge an audience and shake them up. It's not
supposed to be well-behaved and well-manicured like television.
It's supposed to test the limit of word and action.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Howe's work isn't considered absurd _ a style
characterized by seemingly meaningless dialogue in which the
significance is buried beneath what is (and is not) said _ her
reverence for the genre occasionally pops up in her work, such as
in the open-ended expression of ``Approaching Zanzibar.''
</P>
<P>
   She refers to Zanzibar, as well as ``Birth and After Birth'' and
``One Shoe Off,'' as ``the plays that got me into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have characters break into jigs or put out
imaginary fires, or go completely berserk on the stage,'' she says
of ``The Bald Soprano,'' ``or even what Beckett was having Pozzo
and Lucky do'' in ``Waiting for Godot.'' ``It's one thing when a
man can go to the outer edge, but to have a woman explode her own
domestic arena, I think that really frightened the critics.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not she has the critics on the run, Howe likes to
keep busy. Her next project is getting her new play ``Women in
Flames,'' about a middle-aged female playwright who falls in love
with a young leading man, produced. She's also negotiating with the
Ionesco estate to write translations of ``The Bald Soprano'' and
``The Lesson.'' Last year, she even performed as the maid in a
student production of ``The Bald Soprano.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't terribly good; I got better as I went along,'' she
says. ``It was very frightening, but it was a benchmark experience.
I think it taught me that I don't belong on the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
