<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6477 &Cx1f; tad-z
a p BC-GLASS-COLUMN0903-COX     08-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN0903-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: SAY IT AIN'T SO JOE
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (p) political categories for
release
 &HT;    Sunday, Sept. 3.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON As Sen. Joe Lieberman approached the podium at the
Democratic National Convention, the band struck up the theme from
``Chariots of Fire,'' a movie that featured a Jewish track star who
overcame bias and emerged as a winner.
</P>
<P>
   But the real bias that Lieberman faces these days arises from
his fellow Jews. As Lieberman began his quest for the vice
presidency, some prominent Jewish leaders urged him privately not
to talk so much about his faith. When he ignored their advice, they
went public with their criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins in November, that underlying problem won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League was founded by Jews in 1913 to fight
bigots, especially anti-Semites. The group believes that the best
way to insure the well-being of Jewish Americans, who comprise 2
per cent of the U.S. population, is by strict adherence to
separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who defines himself as an observant Jew, has invoked
his faith in public throughout his long political career. He has no
intention of changing his stance.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1940s (when I arrived on these shores with my
parents, fleeing the Nazi terror), a Gallup Poll revealed that 37
percent of Americans would be comfortable voting for a Jewish
president. Fifty years, later 92 percent answered ``yes'' to the
same question.
</P>
<P>
   What continues is a poorly understood struggle between
tradition-minded ``Orthodox'' Jews and modern ``progressive'' Jews,
whose forebears were strongly influenced by the European
Enlightenment and who have generally sought to assimilate
themselves into the mainstream culture.
</P>
<P>
   In a religious context, the word ``Orthodox,'' which means
``correct belief,'' initially arose within Christianity, where it
denoted, from the viewpoint of liberal Protestants, a cast of mind
that relied too heavily on ritual. The term was first applied
derisively to conservative Jews by their reform-minded critics.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman observes most of the 613 ancient Jewish religious
rites that stem from the Torah, the first five books of the Old
Testament. He worships at Kesher Israel, an Orthodox synagogue in
Georgetown, where men and women remain segregated, sends his son to
a Orthodox Jewish day school and refuses to campaign on Saturday,
the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the senator often greets women by shaking
hands, which many observant Jews and Muslims regard as a religious
abomination. And he attends Saturday sessions of the Senate,
although he walks the five miles from his home to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Farrakhan, the Nation of Islam leader, raises the wrong
question when he asks whether ``white America (is) ready to have a
Jewish vice president who is a heartbeat away from being president
of the United States of America?'' (''Black America,'' he adds,
``would always be ready to receive a Jewish vice president because
it has never been a problem for black people what a person's faith
is if that person is qualified.'')
</P>
<P>
   Americans of all hues have moved beyond that. Rather, the real
schism persists between Jews who would remove religion from the
public discourse and an observant politician who would not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
