<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Texas gets court order on health care
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge, saying Texas has not lived up to a 1996
agreement to make major changes in its Medicaid system, has ordered
the state to improve access for children and fix other problems in
medical coverage for low-income Texans. The ruling, by U.S.
District Judge William Wayne Justice, comes as Texas Gov. George W.
Bush has been drawing criticism on the subject from Al Gore. The
order could trigger sweeping changes in the state's program,
prompting officials to back off a plan to transfer most poor people
into managed care and to raise reimbursements to dentists who treat
Medicaid patients. Bush campaign officials noted that the case grew
out of a lawsuit filed in 1993, predating Bush's election as
governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   CONFRONTATION ON MEDICARE
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the focus on health care, Al Gore is demanding that
George W. Bush say what he is willing to do to save Medicare, all
the while promoting his own $400 billion boost for the program.
Gore was holding a town hall meeting with running mate Joe
Lieberman in Portland, Ore., to discuss his plan to preserve
Medicare and offer a new prescription drug benefit for senior
citizens. Bush, who plans to issue details of his Medicare plan
next week, responded today on a live on-air and online CNN
interview. He said the Clinton-Gore administration squandered
opportunities during the past seven years to shore up Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S EDUCATION PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush kept his focus today on education, which he sees
as a winning voter issue. ``When you raise standards, students will
follow,'' Bush told students at a high school in Portsmouth, N.H.
Bush's plan: increase the maximum Pell grant for first-year
students from $3,300 to $5,100; a tax exemption for participating
in tuition savings plans; a $1.5 billion grant to help states pay
for aid for advanced-placement high school students; and education
savings accounts that would allow contribution up to $5,000
annually per child, with tax-free withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING ABOUT HOW TO DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is dispatching aides to meet with major TV
network execs and the special debate commission to decide on times,
places and formats for the debates that Al Gore accuses him of
trying to duck. Bush denies trying to avoid prime-time face-offs,
and says he'd welcome them. Top advisers Joe Allbaugh, Andrew Card
and Don Evans are in Washington now to discuss debate scenarios
with officials at CNN, ABC, CBS, NBC, Fox, PBS and the Commission
on Presidential Debates. The Bush aides also plan to meet this week
and next with potential debate sponsors. After those sessions, Bush
will present his debate schedule, a counteroffer to Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY AND TAXES ON SOUTHERN TOUR
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney made stops today in North Carolina and Georgia to
talk about defense spending and his concerns that the military is
overstretched. In North Carolina, he pushed for the Republican
ticket's tax-cut proposal and said a Bush administration would let
citizens decide how to spend the federal budget surplus. In
Georgia, Cheney blasted the Clinton-Gore administration for what he
says is a poor record of support for the military. Georgia
Democrats slapped back, saying Cheney is resorting to a tired
Republican line of attacking Democrats on the military to avoid
getting into the real issues: health insurance for children and
prescription drug coverage for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   GORE MAKES PROGRESS IN THREE STATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has reclaimed a double-digit lead in Maryland, has an
edge in Illinois, and has closed to a dead heat with George W. Bush
in New Hampshire, according to new state polls of the presidential
race. In Maryland, with 10 electoral votes, Gore led Bush 51-36
percent in a Gonzales-Arscott poll. In Illinois, with 22 electoral
votes, Gore had a 46-41 percent edge over Bush in a Mason-Dixon
poll. In New Hampshire, with 4 electoral votes, Bush had a 48-44
percent lead. The error margin in all three surveys was 4
percentage points. In polls taken before the party conventions,
Bush had been about even in Maryland and Illinois and ahead by 10
points in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE PULLS OUT OF REFORM PARTY BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Lynchburg, Va., ruled today that he doesn't
have jurisdiction to decide who is the Reform Party's real
presidential nominee. Allies of Pat Buchanan sought an order
barring an opposing faction backing John Hagelin from operating
under the party's name. U.S. District Judge Norman Moon said he
lacked jurisdiction because the power struggle did not raise any
constitutional issue. Both sides are seeking $12.6 million in
Federal Election Commission money. Dale Cooter, lawyer for the
Buchanan faction, said he will take the issue to a state court,
possibly as early as next week. But he wasn't sure in which state
he would file.
</P>
<P>
   OUTREACH BY MAIL AND PHONE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush spent more than $40 million trying to reach
voters through advertising and by mail and telephone, nearly as
much as Al Gore doled out for his campaign during the primaries. An
analysis of campaign spending records shows that through July 31
shows that Bush spent $43 million _ nearly half of his
record-shattering $100 million campaign treasury _ on efforts to
reach voters, including $25 million on TV and radio ads. Gore spent
just $14 million on similar voter-targeted activity. Campaign
strategists say the spending spree should give Bush an edge with
voters for the fall campaign, when each candidate will be limited
to spending $67.6 million in federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE, BACK AT THE RANCH
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service is asking local county commissioners to do
more to control traffic and parking around George W. Bush's new
ranch near Waco, Texas. R.L. Smith, in charge of the Austin Secret
Service office, said his agency requested changes ``to get
clarification'' about local laws, especially since there is no
posted speed limit on the roads. Most of the problems have been
caused by the media, including trucks parked with satellite dishes
along the 22-foot wide road outside Bush's front gate. McLennan
County Commissioner Ray Meadows said officials had hoped they could
wait to see how Bush fared in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   SHOCKER FROM ELECTRICAL WORKERS?
</P>
<P>
   The United Electrical, Radio and Machine Workers of America was
debating today whether to endorse Green Party presidential
candidate Ralph Nader. Appearing at the union's annual convention
in Erie, Pa., Nader told the members that the Democratic Party,
labor's traditional partner in politics, promises too much and
delivers too little. He offered himself as a strong alternative,
claiming that President Clinton and Al Gore have failed to push
hard for a ban on hiring permanent replacements for striking
workers despite voicing support for it. A Nader endorsement, if it
comes, would be its first departure from backing Democrats, said
union spokesman Peter Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR ONLINE FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has created a Web site for Al Gore to hold a live
Web cast on Labor Day for union members. The Web site will allow
union members to send e-mail messages to political candidates,
including Gore, George W. Bush and members of Congress. The Web
site _ www.workingfamilies.com _ also will feature a speech by John
Sweeney, the union president, and video messages from the ``Texas
Truth Squad,'' a group of workers who are traveling the country to
accuse Bush of doing little on issues that unions care about. Web
site users also will be able to register to vote, and can examine
the voting record of candidates for federal office. The site will
be up through Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN LEADS ROBB IN VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Virginia Gov. George Allen, the architect of Virginia's
Republican revival, holds an early lead over incumbent Sen. Charles
Robb in nearly every corner of the state, according to a new
Washington Post survey. Statewide, Allen leads Robb 48-43 percent
among registered voters and by 8 percentage points among those most
likely to vote. Allen enjoys wide margins of support among men,
married couples with children, whites, voters in their 20s,
veterans, the wealthy and newcomers to the state, the survey found.
Robb leads only in vote-rich Northern Virginia, but only by 6
percentage points, and in the Democratic stronghold of southwest
Virginia. The poll's margin of error for the overall results is 3
percentage points, and 4 percentage points for results based only
on likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY ARTILLERY FIRING IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   New York Senate candidates Hillary Clinton and Rick Lazio rolled
out the big guns today, with the first lady releasing a
fund-raising letter from President Clinton and the congressman
running a TV ad starring John McCain. ```I have worked as hard as I
could to turn our country around,'' the president writes in the
appeal. ``Now, the work must be carried on by others. No one is
more qualified than Hillary to do it.'' In the new Lazio ad, McCain
casts doubt on Clinton's claim that she is willing to give up
unlimited soft-money campaign contributions if her Republican
opponent does the same.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN OUT OF ACTION
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan will have no
public appearances until after Labor Day. He underwent gall bladder
surgery Aug. 19, and had a second operation four days later when
doctors found another stone. Now, ``he feels a lot better and is
coming along fine,'' said campaign spokesman Brian Doherty. ``But
after two operations and losing 15 pounds or so from not being able
to eat much, he needs to rest another week.'' Buchanan plans to
remain at home until Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   JILTED WIFE HEADS FOE'S CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Rep. Albert Wynn's worst enemy may be his estranged
wife, who is lending her services _ and her intimate knowledge of
the Democratic congressman _ to his GOP opponent. Jessie Wynn, who
is locked in a bitter divorce and custody battle with her husband,
a black Democrat, is serving as John Kimble's campaign chief. And
she has recorded this blistering message being transmitted by
telephone to thousands of homes in the Maryland suburbs of
Washington: ``Hi, this is Jessie Wynn, wife of Congressman Albert
Wynn. Albert Wynn does not respect black women. He left me for a
white woman. . . . Please help us defeat Albert Wynn.'' Kimble, who
is white, said he hopes to reach every home in the mostly black
district.
</P>
<P>
   ABOVE ALL, HE'S G. GORDON'S SON
</P>
<P>
   His name stands out among the crowded field of candidates for an
Arizona congressional seat. Tom Liddy is a Phoenix attorney, Marine
Corps veteran, party activist and ex-schoolteacher. But as the son
of G. Gordon Liddy, the Watergate henchman, Tom Liddy can't stray
too far from his heritage. ``My dad has given me a name that is
very high profile,'' he said. ``He's a guy who never backed away
from a fight and relished some of them. Like father, like son.''
The son now seeks to succeed Rep. Matt Salmon, who is keeping a
term-limit pledge to only serve six years in Congress. Liddy is
being supported by Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   FEW WORDS SAY IT ALL
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney says he's a ``man of few words'' who prefers low-key
campaign events without a lot of hoopla. Making a swing of Southern
states, he and his wife, Lynne, had spent Tuesday night, their 36th
wedding anniversary, in Jackson, Miss. His few words to several
hundred people at the local airport there: ``I can't think of a
better place to spend it than Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA EYES NEW PRIMARY SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   California lawmakers are trying to revamp a wide-open primary
election process that was struck down by the U.S. Supreme Court. A
bill in the Legislature would implement a new primary system that
would permit independent voters to participate in primaries, but
limit them to voting for one party's candidates. The Democratic and
Republican parties bitterly fought the state's ``blanket primary''
approved by voters in 1996, contending it violated their
association rights by letting voters choose any candidate,
regardless of party affiliation. The Supreme Court agreed and
overturned the system in June. Alaska and Washington state have
similar primaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
