<HEADER>
A6486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NIXON-DRUG-NYT &LR;      08-30 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO NIXON AIDES DENY HE MEDICATED HIMSELF IN THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two aides to President Richard M. Nixon said
Wednesday that they doubted he ever took the drug Dilantin, which
can induce mental confusion and nervousness, despite a new book
that says he did.
</P>
<P>
   The aides, John H. Taylor, the director of the Nixon Library in
Yorba Linda, Calif., who knew Nixon from the mid-1980s until the
former president's death in 1994, and Steve Bull, who was Nixon's
personal aide from mid-1969 until late 1974, said they were
skeptical of assertions in the book that Nixon medicated himself
with Dilantin given to him by Jack Dreyfus, the founder of the
Dreyfus Fund and an avid promoter of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus said last week that an account in ``The Arrogance of
Power: The Secret World of Richard Nixon'' that he gave Dilantin to
Nixon in 1968 was correct. Dreyfus said he gave him a bottle of
1,000 capsules of 100 milligrams each ``when his mood wasn't too
good,'' and later gave him another bottle of 1,000 capsules.
</P>
<P>
   The book written by Anthony Summers and published by Viking
paints an unfavorable portrait of Nixon politically and personally.
Its assertion that he freely medicated himself while coping with
the burdens of the White House is one of several contentions that
have been disputed by Nixon's relatives and associates. Taylor and
Bull volunteered their views in reaction to reports about the book.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the Richard Nixon he knew ``went to traditional
doctors when he was sick and always did what they said.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Dilantin, Bull, who is now director of government
relations for the U.S. Olympic Committee, said, ``I never saw any
evidence that he used any medication of that kind. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus has advocated the drug as being effective in dealing
with anxiety, anger, depression and other troubling conditions. The
Physicians' Desk Reference describes Dilantin as a barbiturate
relative used to treat seizures and says its side effects include
mental confusion, slurred speech, insomnia and nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor produced a summary of White House records from April 1969
through mid-1973 recalling numerous attempts by Dreyfus to gain
government backing for Dilantin through Nixon. The records state
that Nixon met with Dreyfus now and then socially, but they portray
the president as reluctant to get into lengthy discussions about
Dilantin.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Nixon might have accepted Dilantin from Dreyfus so
as not to hurt his feelings, but that if he did he threw it out
rather than take it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-TIRES-NYT &LR;      08-30 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-TIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS INVESTIGATE FORD'S HANDLING OF DEFECTIVE TIRES ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under growing political pressure, federal
regulators announced Wednesday that they had significantly
broadened their investigation of the Ford Motor Co. to examine its
handling of replacing potentially defective tires in 16 countries
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure was made in a letter to Ford that was made public
Wednesday by the National Highway Transportation Safety
Administration asking the company to describe in detail the reasons
for the recall.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement followed the emergence of disputes between Ford
and Bridgestone/Firestone, the U.S. unit of Japan's Bridgestone,
about tire problems in Venezuela and Thailand. Ford recalled
Explorers equipped with Firestone tires in Venezuela last May after
a dispute in which Ford claimed the tires were defective and
Bridgestone said they were not. Ford is replacing the Firestone
tires with ones manufactured by Goodyear. But Bridgestone has
repeatedly assured Ford that there are no problems with the tires.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a government agency in Venezuela is expected to
issue a report criticizing both Ford and Bridgestone.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies and American auto regulators are expected to
face intensive questioning next week when congressional hearings
begin over the tire recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers have certain legal obligations to report defect
problems and NHTSA has some obligations to Congress,'' said Ken
Johnson, a spokesman for Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who heads one of
the House committees investigating the tire recall. ``Someone
dropped the ball and we're trying to find out who. But we're really
trying to figure out some broader issues. Did Firestone break the
law or is the law broken? We're going to have to take a hard look
at the law to make sure it's strong enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Set to testify next week are Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater, federal highway safety officials, executives from the two
companies and safety experts. Congressional aides say they may also
take testimony from owners of Explorers involved in traffic
accidents that were caused by the tire defects.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has been bombarded with complaints in the weeks after
Bridgestone announced a recall of 6.5 million Firestone tires in
the United States, many of which were installed on Ford Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and safety investigators have said the tread can
separate when underinflated. Damage to the tires has been linked to
hundreds of accidents and dozens of deaths, according to safety
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Ford's troubles this week was a preliminary ruling by
a California judge that Ford installed defective ignition modules
in 2 million vehicles between 1983 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Ballachey, a Superior Court judge in Alameda County,
east of San Francisco, said Tuesday he intended to order the
company to recall and repair the cars and trucks. Plaintiffs have
alleged that the ignition mechanisms fail at high temperatures and
cause the engines to stall.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision will be issued Sept. 28. Ford has denied the
ignitions are faulty and has said they will appeal any decision
ordering a recall. Complying with an ignition recall could cost
Ford between $70 million to $250 million, consumer advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone, meanwhile, has been fighting to maintain its
reputation and public trust after the tire recall.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bridgestone and Ford had been working together on the
recall, and trying to reassure consumers who have bought the tires,
there are growing signs of tension between the two companies like
the tussle over Venezuelan tires.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bridgestone announced its chief executive would fly
from Japan to Washington to testify before congressional committees
investigating the tire failure. But Ford's chief executive, Jacques
A. Nasser, has declined the invitation to testify next week,
prompting criticism from a subcommittee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Ford official and congressional staff members are negotiating to
see if Nasser will appear before the House committee next week. A
scheduled hearing before the Senate Commerce Committee has been put
off until Sept. 13 because the committee chairman, Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., is recovering from skin cancer surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
