<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      08-30 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Telnet Still Available For Cruising the Web
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is Telnet, and what can it do? I have Windows 98. Can I
use Telnet?
</P>
<P>
   A. Although it is not used as much as it once was because of the
Web, Telnet can still be a good way to connect to other computers
from your own machine. It is a text-based system that dates to the
1970s, and some users who are used to point-and-click browsing may
find Telnet a bit arcane. If one doesn't mind the old-fashioned
interface of typed commands and numbered choices, however, it is a
speedy way to connect to systems like online library catalogs and
electronic bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can use Telnet with Windows 98, as long as you have a
Telnet program installed on your computer. (If you have configured
your Web browser properly, you can also use Telnet with it by
typing a command in the browser's URL box.)
</P>
<P>
   Most recent versions of Windows come with a program called
HyperTerminal already installed with the communications programs.
There are other Telnet programs, like NetTerm, that you can
download from shareware Web sites as well. Several Telnet programs,
including ones for Windows, Macintosh and Unix, are available from
the TuCows shareware site at www.tucows.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some popular Mac Telnet programs are BetterTelnet, dataComet and
NiftyTelnet. The National Center for Supercomputing Applications
keeps an informative (but no longer updated) page on its Telnet
program at www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Homepage/telnet.html. The site
also provides a program manual that can be downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have become acquainted with your Telnet software, you
can use it to tap in remotely to other computers around the world.
The Library of Congress has a Web site but still allows users to
Telnet in to search its databases. Type locis.loc.gov in the Telnet
address box to get there. A list of other places to Telnet into can
be found at www.anzio.com/telnetsites.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I use a Macintosh and have been getting a disturbing error
message from my Eudora e-mail program. It keeps saying something
about memory, then gives me these options: Quit or Live
Dangerously. What happens if I decide to live dangerously?
</P>
<P>
   A. Living dangerously can be a bit of an adrenaline rush, but if
you choose to do that with your e-mail program, it may soon start
crashing or have trouble starting up when you least expect it. That
particular alert box is warning you that the Eudora program is just
about out of the system memory that it needs to operate properly.
To make the message go away, you need to allot more of your Mac's
RAM to the program or start deleting old messages and mailboxes
that you don't need anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Quit option you were given in the dialogue box anticipates
that you will tell your Mac to give Eudora more RAM to work with
because you need to shut down the program to adjust the memory
settings. Once you quit Eudora, go to your hard drive and locate
the program's icon. Click once on the icon, then press Command I on
the keyboard to call up the Get Information box for Eudora. You can
also get that box by selecting Get Information from the File menu.
</P>
<P>
   In the Get Information box, you will see the settings for
Suggested, Minimum and Preferred Memory size. (Some later versions
of the Macintosh operating system keep the Memory settings under a
pop-up tab at the top of the box.) To give Eudora more memory,
increase the numbers in both the Minimum and Preferred size boxes.
For example, if the minimum and preferred sizes are both listed as
1,024 kilobytes, changing both numbers to 3,072 kilobytes will
increase Eudora's share of RAM from one megabyte to three
megabytes. Once you have adjusted your settings, close the Get
Information box and restart Eudora. If you are still getting
messages about tight memory, repeat the process and increase the
memory settings even more.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 West 43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
