A6495 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TAILHOOK-MARINES-HNS &LR;      08-30 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILHOOK-MARINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MARINE OFFICIAL CALLS LATEST TAILHOOK INCIDENT `ISOLATED' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gen. Terrence R. Dake, the No. 2 Marine Corps
official, said Wednesday that the reported sexual harassment at a
recent Tailhook Association convention was isolated and not like
the Tailhook gathering of 1991 in which 140 officers sexually
assaulted 83 women.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy said last week that it was investigating a complaint by
a civilian couple that at least one servicemember staying at a
Sparks, Nev., hotel ``inappropriately'' touched the wife as she was
making her way though a hallway and that several servicemen made
``inappropriate comments,'' according to Lt. Com. Cate Mueller, a
Navy spokeswoman. Mueller added that the investigation would
determine to which military service the alleged offenders belonged.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents are alleged to have taken place during the Aug.
17-20 Tailhook convention at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego-based Tailhook Association, named for the hook on
the rear of many Navy and Marine Corps aircraft that allow them to
land on a carrier, is a private organization that represents
aviators. The Navy suspended its relationship with the group
following the 1991 episode and only restored a connection this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dake said the allegations arising out of the recent convention
are ``troubling'' especially given that the Navy and Marines
``fought so hard'' to renew the relationship with the association.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Dake, ``my sensing is that what we are seeing is not
as widespread as the previous Tailhook 1991.''
</P>
<P>
   Dake, the assistant commandant of the Marine Corps, defended the
renewed relationship. The group ``has a lot to offer if in fact it
can police itself and can maintain its dignity as an organization
that should be (used for) an exchange of professional ideas.
There's great merit to having that type of organization.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that ``Tailhook has to deserve the Navy's
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Dake, a pilot, previously served as the deputy chief of staff
for Marine Corps aviation and inspector general of the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the 1991 convention, the Tailhook group was
criticized for letting the event get out of hand at after-hours
parties where alcohol flowed freely and Navy and Marine pilots got
drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 convention shook the Navy to its roots and led to
resignations of the Navy Secretary and chief of naval operations.
It also generated questions about the service's ability to
investigate itself.
</P>
<P>
   The service was criticized for belatedly beginning an
investigation into charges of sexual harassment and abuse made by
several female Navy personnel. The Navy's probe found little or no
culpability.
</P>
<P>
   Dake acknowledged that all eyes will be on the service's
investigative process, but he added that the Navy and Marines have
learned from its mistakes. This time he said that he had ``every
expectation'' that the Navy investigation would be thorough and
timely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
