<HEADER>
A6497 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-LIVE-FOOTBALL-NYT     08-30 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LIVE-FOOTBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KICKOFF FOR ONLINE COLLEGE FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MINDY SINK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time, not long ago, when football and computers had
as much to do with each other as touchdowns and home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But the two are merging this weekend in the first live Webcast
of a major college football game _ between the No. 1 University of
Nebraska Cornhuskers and the unranked and unsung Spartans of San
Jose State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity to bring the game to people who
otherwise couldn't watch it unless they were in the stadium,'' said
Danny Greenberg, senior vice president of FoxSports.com, which is
working with the University of Nebraska to provide the Webcast of
the game that will be played Saturday at Memorial Stadium in
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of the Cornhuskers, the game is not being
televised. ``That probably has more to do with how they feel the
game might turn out than the size of one of the schools,'' said
Chris Anderson, sports information director at the University of
Nebraska. ``We had been wanting to try this, and it was a unique
opportunity to do it with the first game at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Webcast will be available free, but it is recommended that
potential viewers log on ahead of time to register and to download
necessary programs, like RealPlayer. In conjunction with
FoxSports.com, the University of Nebraska will be providing the
game to Internet users at Huskers.com by using four cameras inside
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   FoxSports.com has produced five Webcasts of high school all-star
football games this summer, and high school basketball games last
season. Although audio broadcasts of college and professional
sports are common on the Web, this is the first Division I college
football game to be broadcast online with streaming video and
audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that San Jose is in the heart of Silicon Valley, it
seems appropriate to be part of something new, to be a pioneer in
this particular venture,'' said Lawrence Fan, sports information
director at San Jose State. The university will also provide a link
from its site, www.sjsuspartans.com.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Nebraska has had audio play-by-play of its
football games on the Internet for years. ``We found we have a huge
following on the Internet already,'' Anderson said. ``In other
nontelevised games we've had more than half a million people from
20 countries listening.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the video and play-by-play commentary, the site
will provide real-time game statistics, chats and live polling, as
well as a pregame show. Yet given the quality of streaming video,
television broadcasts will probably remain the favorite for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an experiment,'' Greenberg said. ``It's not meant to
be what you see on your TV.'' He said viewers using a typical modem
speed of about 56k would see jerky or jumpy movements, but that a
higher speed connection would provide an experience closer to that
of television.
</P>
<P>
   One difference with the Webcast is the starting time of the
game, which was moved to 11:30 a.m. CST so as not to conflict with
televised broadcasts of other Big 12 games _ and with the opening
of the Nebraska State Fair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
