<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: COURT TV; OZ; NICKELODEON; MAKING THE BAND; NIGHTLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the Tape for Confessions
</P>
<P>
   Early last week Court TV announced it would begin showing a new
series featuring the videotaped confessions of murderers, rapists
and other offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The program, Court TV executives said, would feature segments
from the confessions _ recorded by district attorneys and the
police during the course of criminal investigations _ accompanied
by crime scene photographs and eerie video of the locations where
the incidents had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   It will run for half an hour and have neither a host nor a legal
analyst, the executives said, adding that those looking for further
explanation and interpretation of the confessions could find some
on the Court TV Web site (www.courttv.com). ``Confessions'' is to
have its debut on Sunday night, Sept. 10, at 10.
</P>
<P>
   By producing such a program, executives said, they knew they
were inviting controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems Court TV may have gotten more than it bargained
for. In the days after the announcement, the network was heavily
criticized throughout the media, with many saying it was
inappropriate to show criminals' confessions as entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Disputing Court TV's argument that the series was intended to
give the public a better idea of how the criminal justice system
works, critics said it could not successfully do so without
offering its viewers analysis or explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles City Councilman Nate Holden demanded that Court TV
not show the program, warning that it could spur copycat crimes.
The New York Times, in an editorial, referred to it as ``a rank
appeal to prurience and the thrill of violence, motivated by the
network's desire for an audience-grabbing hit.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Court TV announced it would make a concession to its
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Schleiff, the Court TV chairman, said the series premiere
would be followed by a half-hour panel discussion about the
confessions, featuring experts in crime and psychology. It is
possible there will be similar panel discussions following
subsequent episodes, but that, Schleiff said, will be determined
later.
</P>
<P>
   Schleiff said that when it makes its actual debut, the program
could also have further explanation of the various cases that would
run somewhere on the screen while the confessions are playing.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot episode the confessions are introduced with tersely
worded introductions detailing the charges and followed with terse
conclusions describing the outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing here is that Court TV prides itself
on being responsible,'' Schleiff said. ``And where there is valid
concern, I think, we're responding to that in a responsible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ruhe-Munch, executive director of the National
Organization of Parents of Murdered Children, said the announced
changes did not satisfy her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that would appease me is not to air these
confessions,'' she said. ``How much pain do they think family
members need to go through?''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, a law professor at New York University who
specializes in legal ethics and had described the program as
voyeuristic, said he thought the changes could improve it,
depending on how they are done.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is just a veneer, it is not enough,'' he said. ``If it
is a real effort to deal with the legal issues, then I think it
could be valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   `Oz' Steps In
</P>
<P>
   When David Chase decided to delay the new season of ``The
Sopranos'' to March instead of January, HBO was faced with a hole
on its Sunday night lineup. Coincidentally, Tom Fontana, the
creator of HBO's other high-rated drama, ``Oz,'' had been told by
his production studio in Manhattan that, as he put it, ``They were
kicking us out.'' Fontana's elaborate prison set for ``Oz'' takes
up 60,000 square feet and only had a year-by-year lease.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got an offer for a 10-year lease from New York 1,''
Fontana said, ``Which, ironically enough, is a Time Warner sister
entity.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the loss of his space, Fontana asked whether HBO
wanted him to produce his next eight episodes of ``Oz'' early.
Chris Albrecht, the president of original programming for HBO,
responded immediately, saying that the network had that hole in its
January schedule coming up, and that ``Oz'' would fit in nicely.
</P>
<P>
   So Fontana kept his show in production and this week will finish
shooting the eight new episodes of ``Oz'' that will begin in
January. The series had previously played only in the summer. The
January season will also reflect the growing respect the show is
enjoying by including appearances by guest stars like Luke Perry,
Roger Rees, Ally Sheedy and Betty Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile HBO is also shooting a pilot for a dark comedy from
Alan Ball, writer of ``American Beauty.'' This one, called ``Six
Feet Under,'' is about the funeral business.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   `Arliss' Unsure
</P>
<P>
   The only HBO series apparently unsure of its future is
``Arliss,'' the five-year-old comedy about a sports agent. Robert
Wuhl, who produces, stars in and writes for the show, is also its
unrelenting advocate. On at least two earlier occasions he lobbied
hard to keep the show alive and succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having been paired with the ultra-hot ``Sex and the City,''
``Arliss'' has seen its ratings improve about 7 percent for the
season that just ended. Wuhl said in a telephone interview that HBO
had ordered him to write six more scripts. ``It may be because of
the possible strike'' of actors and writers, Wuhl said. ``This is a
way to get us started early.'' But whatever the reason, he is eager
to keep his show going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we bring a new audience after `Sex and the City,''' he
said, `though we've been keeping more and more of their viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   An HBO spokesman said that ``Six Feet Under,'' if it becomes a
series, may get a shot at filling the half-hour behind ``Sex and
the City,'' which may have some impact on the future of ``Arliss.''
But Albrecht has said he would like to keep expanding the number of
series on HBO, which may mean more seasons for all the current
entries.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
