<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NOTES-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      08-30 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: BILL CARTER  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nickelodeon Shifts
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 10 years, Nickelodeon, the top-rated
network on basic cable, is changing its look. Starting in early
September, executives said Wednesday, they will introduce new
promotional spots and graphics for its children's programming. They
said the spots would be less erratic and more uniform than they are
currently.
</P>
<P>
   The promotional spots will feature variations of the Nickelodeon
logo, quick shots of characters from the show in progress and the
children's voices alerting the audience to stay put during the
commercial breaks or that a show is returning from commercial
break.
</P>
<P>
   The change is notable because the network's brightly colored
graphics and overall lively appearance _ established through
promotions as much as programming _ have been considered a vital
ingredient to its success.
</P>
<P>
   They were devised to make children feel that Nickelodeon is
their home base on television.
</P>
<P>
   But Nickelodeon has in some respects become a victim of its own
success, inspiring others, like Walt Disney Co., Fox and Turner
Broadcasting to form their own channels with similar approaches to
Nickelodeon's.
</P>
<P>
   Cyma Zarghami, Nickelodeon's executive vice president and
general manager, said it was with that in mind that she and her
fellow executives had decided to devise the changes. ``There are a
lot of players in our game right now, and there are a lot of
copycats,'' she said. ``While everybody has gotten to look a lot
like we look, we're changing our look.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   More `Band'
</P>
<P>
   ABC announced that it will order a second season for a show once
thought irretrievably dead: `Making the Band.'' The network ordered
13 more episodes Wednesday and may have it available for
mid-season.
</P>
<P>
   While it has never exploded in the ratings, the series, about
the development of a boy band, has attracted something of a cult
following. It also fits the genre of reality programming, which
means it would not be affected by a strike of actors and writers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Hip `Nightline'
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ``Nightline'' is venturing into uncharted territory.
</P>
<P>
   Next Wednesday it begins a three-part series on the rap music
industry, a decidedly young and hip topic for the late-night news
program. Robert Krulwich, an ABC News correspondent on the series,
said one hope was that it would lure younger people, who tend to
watch less news than their elders.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, he thought it was an important topic that has been
somewhat neglected by major news organizations in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a culture that has remained somewhat under the
radar,'' he said. ``You hear the noise of it. You smell the
violence of it, and that's pretty much all you notice _ other than
the fact that kids are spending long, long periods of time in their
rooms listening to it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
