<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     08-30 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV03-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S., CANADA SHOULD CONSIDER MEXICO'S ECONOMIC PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Sept. 3)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sweeping out of Mexico like a fast-moving tropical
storm, Vicente Fox, who revolutionized politics in his homeland,
has injected some revolutionary concepts into Mexico's relationship
with the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In separate visits with leaders of his two northern neighbors,
Mexico's president-elect suggested that the two countries consider
helping Mexico expand its economy in order to create new,
well-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, would deter workers from trying to leave Mexico.
At the same time, he urged a shift in American policy so that
Mexican workers coming to the United States would be viewed ``as an
opportunity, not a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The towering (6 foot, 4 inch) former Coca Cola executive, who
will be inaugurated as president of Mexico Dec. 1, also spoke in
visionary terms about developing a closer interdependence among the
three North American allies.
</P>
<P>
   His remarkable election on July 2 as the candidate of the
center-right National Action Party marked the first time in 71
years that a candidate of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI) had been defeated. Throughout Mexico, people rejoiced
over Fox's triumph.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Fox Aug. 24 at the White House, President
Clinton also predicted an eventual ``growing interdependence in our
hemisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not commit himself on the specifics of Fox's proposal.
But Clinton, whose term ends Jan. 20, said of interdependence, ``I
think it will be the way of the world. I regret I won't be around
for a lot of it. But it is a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who also
met with Fox, were equally noncommittal on his proposals. But the
Republican presidential nominee, whose state has the longest border
with Mexico, said he will continue to enforce laws that protect
America's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Both presidential nominees are internationalists who can be
counted on to seek improved relations with all of Latin America,
especially Mexico, which, next to Canada, is the United States'
chief trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Fox insists that in this global era barriers must come down
along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Mexico to visit Washington and Ottawa, Fox said
that ``building up walls putting up arms (and) dedicating billions
of dollars to avoid migration (are) not the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, debate over Mexican migration into the United
States has festered, and sometimes it has exploded. In 1994
California voters passed a ballot initiative, Proposition 187, that
prohibited children of illegal immigrants from going to school and
receiving most health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, supported by then Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, was
later declared unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Its impact was to help diminish GOP power in a state with a huge
Hispanic population that had been dominated by Republicans for
years. The furious reaction of Latinos and Asian Americans to what
they saw as immigrant-bashing by California Republicans was a big
factor in the 1998 election of Gray Davis, the state's first
Democratic governor in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, we in the United States have failed to look seriously
at the problems of Mexico. For too long we viewed Mexico through
the stereotypes created by Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Few visitors to Mexico noticed its vast areas of poverty and
deprivation. Instead, they refreshed themselves with visits to
Acapulco and Cancun, inspected magnificent Mayan ruins and enjoyed
Mexico's Ballet Folklorico.
</P>
<P>
   Every seven years, Mexico would automatically elect the
presidential candidate of the ruling PRI party. The new leader
would meet with the U.S. president and exchange pleasantries, and
the United States would pledge various forms of aid to its sister
republic.
</P>
<P>
   But poverty-stricken Mexicans continue to try in every way to
sneak into this country, which in turn spends millions of dollars
each year trying to keep them out.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's visionary proposals should neither be rejected out of hand
nor accepted without thorough study. But Mexico needs our help, and
we need to find better ways to curtail illegal immigration from
that country.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to move together into a brighter future, we cannot do
so simply by cursing illegal immigrants or building higher,
stronger fences along the border.
</P>
<P>
   There must be, as Fox and Clinton have suggested, more
enlightened ways to bolster Mexico's economy and job expansion
while at the same time reducing illegal immigration and
strengthening our own economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The time has come to try a new approach.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
