<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-CRENSHAW-HNS &LR;      08-30 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CRENSHAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARSHALL CRENSHAW _ UNSUNG GENIUS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Should Marshall Crenshaw stick to any of his many musical interests
for an extended period, he could probably call one of them his own.
Ironically, the prolific Brooklynite appears to prefer the life of
unsung cult genius.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least unsung by him.
</P>
<P>
   Scroll down his songwriting credits and one finds a bevy of
other vocalists who have had success with Crenshaw's music. His
witty ``You're My Favorite Waste of Time'' has become a beloved
standard of the divine Ms. Bette Midler. Kelly Willis' 1993
self-titled debut was anchored with a mandolin treatment of
Crenshaw's ``Whatever Way the Wind Blows.''
</P>
<P>
   Most successful was the 1996 Gin Blossoms hit ``Til I Hear It
From You.'' Crenshaw co-wrote the song with the band for the
``Empire Records'' soundtrack. The resulting fervor helped make the
movie an underground curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   If Crenshaw is carrying a grudge about the lack of credit, he's
not letting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gin Blossoms thing was never going to be one of mine,''
Crenshaw says by phone from the Savoy Hotel in San Francisco, where
he's resting before a recent gig. ``I do have some regrets, but
they're not killing me. I feel I have had an interesting and varied
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Varied is the perfect definition of the underground renaissance
man's two decades standing in the spotlight's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before cutting his first solo album, he tried out for
a role in ``Beatlemania'' and wound up playing John Lennon for the
West Coast tour. He portrayed his main musical influence, the
square-spectacled Buddy Holly, in the 1987 Ritchie Valens biopic
``La Bamba'' and had a walk-on role as a member of the high school
reunion band in Francis Ford Coppola's ``Peggy Sue Got Married.''
</P>
<P>
   Trading his guitar for a pen, Crenshaw wrote and compiled
critical input for ``Hollywood Rock: A Guide to Rock N' Roll in the
Movies,'' and has written liner notes for compilation albums for
artists ranging from Rick Nelson to the Louvin Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have probably heard the multi-instrumentalist's
music without even knowing it. He performed the theme song _ a
cover of Larry Williams' ``Bad Boy'' _ for the short-lived Rob
``Makin' copies!!'' Schneider sitcom, ``Men Behaving Badly,'' in
1996. Last year he composed the score for the PBS baseball-legend
documentary ``Yogi Berra: Deja Vu All Over Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his own name, however, Crenshaw is mainstream and pop
chart anesthesia. His early punk poetry is a cross between Holly's
rockabilly and Elvis Costello's sneering cynicism. In a career
spanning eight critically revered studio albums, the highest peak
he reached was No. 36 on the Hot 100 for ``Someday, Someway'' in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else has come close, and maybe that's the point. Art
over the shopping cart. Through touring and his various acting
roles, Crenshaw has acquired a devoted underground audience.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who catch him in concert probably will be thrilled that a
favored wandering minstrel continues to have a voice without having
to mix and mingle with Eminem and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, so does Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you came to me when I was 17 and told me I would have the
career I've had, I would've felt pretty good,'' Crenshaw says. ``My
ego is very resilient. I refused to be crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhino Records is also refusing to let Crenshaw be crushed _ or
forgotten. Earlier this month the label remastered, refined and
reissued his self-titled debut album. The new incarnation adds nine
songs to the set, including original B-sides, previously unreleased
tracks and a couple of covers, such as the Motown classic ``Stop
Her on Sight (S.O.S.).''
</P>
<P>
   Rhino simultaneously released the first-ever Crenshaw anthology,
``The Best of Marshall Crenshaw: This Is Easy!'' The 22-song
retrospective captures his reliance on shuffling early-rock licks
in ``There She Goes Again'' and ``Someday, Someway'' to the more
plodding and sullen ``I'm Sorry (But So Is Brenda Lee).''
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is Easy!'' draws to a close with a much more mature and
complex Crenshaw remaking John Hiatt's ``Someplace Where You Can't
Love Me'' and the deep melancholy of 1996's (the set's most recent
entry) ``What Do You Dream Of?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool, and it's novel. The track list wasn't my final say,
but I was definitely consulted,'' Crenshaw says of ``This Is
Easy!'' ``I'm very self-critical, and there are two or three songs
I would have personally left off. I'm not going to tell you which
ones, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea to reissue the songs was the brainchild of a Rhino
senior vice president, Gary Stewart, one of many in the music
industry who describes himself as a ``Marshall maniac.'' According
to Stewart, there has been talk of reissuing Crenshaw's other
mid-'80s out-of-print records, ``Down Town'' and ``Mary Jean and 9
Others.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're done with Marshall,'' says Stewart, who
had approached the anthology project as far back as five years ago
but was only able to make it happen when Rhino got access to
Crenshaw's Warner Bros. catalog in 1998. ``Rhino is kind of
treating this like the new Limp Bizkit record, and we don't often
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is in addition to Crenshaw's most recent studio
album for the New York indie label Razor &AMP; Tie, the jazz-inflected
No. 447. Beginning with the big-band swing and horns of
``Opening,'' the 45-second song snippet immediately suggests
Crenshaw has _ once again _ changed muses. ``Dime a Dozen Guy''
unearths surf rock with a stand-up bass, while ``Glad Goodbye''
finds his inner-folkie with a dobro as accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eydie's Tune'' and ``You Said What'' are easy-groove
instrumentals that stray from Crenshaw's quick, catchy lyrics and
crushed grooves into experimental territory. It's a vibe he grabbed
sometime between the making of ``No. 447'' and the ``Yogi Berra''
score. The songs are featured on both.
</P>
<P>
   Just like most of his albums, ``No. 447'' works better as a
whole than it does cut into individual pieces. It makes the current
live set a particular challenge. How do you please an audience that
wants both the new, spacey and improvised music, as well as the
skiffle of the early hits? And how do you re-create the
multiple-layer melodies as a solo artist?
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw chooses to let instinct and the limits of his long-term
memory make the call from night to night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I happen to suddenly remember a song I haven't done in a
while, I play it,'' Crenshaw says tongue-in-cheek. ``On each of my
records I was pleased that I had the nerve to change the songs each
time around. It's no different live.
</P>
<P>
   ``It perfectly sums up the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
