<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Periods of rain will linger from the Middle Atlantic coast to
the southern Appalachians on Thursday as low pressure drifts west
across the Carolinas. The steadiest rain will be near the east
slopes of the mountains from Virginia to northern Georgia, where
moist winds ascend the sloping terrain. Meanwhile, plenty of clouds
and limited sunshine will linger from southern New England to the
central Appalachians. Farther north in the Northeastern States, it
will be partly sunny and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Searing heat with little chance for rain will persist from the
southern Plains to the lower Mississippi Valley. The hot air mass
will surge temporarily into the southern Great Lakes on Thursday as
breezes from the southwest increase ahead of a cold front.
</P>
<P>
   Cool air will cover most of the Northwest and northern Plains.
Plenty of clouds and scattered showers will prevail from the Sierra
to the Rockies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: POWER OF WATER
</P>
<P>
   Water in motion can be a powerful force. A cube of water
measuring just 3 feet on each side weighs more than 2,000 pounds.
On Monday, several cars were swept away by relatively shallow flash
flood waters north of Las Vegas. The majority of flood-related
deaths occur when motorists attempt to drive their cars through
flooded crossings and are carried rapidly away by swift currents.
The best rule to follow is to avoid driving through any flooded
areas, particularly in unfamiliar territory where the depth of the
water is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
