<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLYMPICTECH-0831-COX     08-30 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICTECH-0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALL TECH FIRM IS CHOSEN FOR OLYMPIAN WEB SITE TASK
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (s) sports and (f) financial
categories
 &HT;    By BOB KEEFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MATEO, Calif. _ The Winter Olympics are still two years
away, but already they're producing a tale
</P>
<P>
   of a little-known underdog winning out in a contest of Olympian
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the 2002 Olympic Winter Games on Wednesday picked
an upstart Internet company called LogicTier Inc. to run its Web
operations _ a huge job given that the Games' Web site is predicted
to be the most heavily trafficked of any event in history, with as
many as 20 billion hits.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard of LogicTier, don't be surprised. The
company was started less than a year ago and didn't really get
rolling until April.
</P>
<P>
   Its biggest clients so far include a company that auctions
bulldozers and other heavy equipment over the Internet and an
operator of an online trivia game called Duckets.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the company in charge of technology for the
Olympics for the past 40 years _ and the Games' Web sites in recent
years _ is a bit better known: IBM Corp. IBM has said September's
Summer Olympics in Sydney will be its last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the equivalent of winning the gold,'' LogicTier Chief
Executive Mary Ann Byrnes said Wednesday while on her way to an
employee party featuring former Olympic skater Dan Jansen. ``It's
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also another sign that in today's technology age, companies
don't have to be behemoths to be big-time players. San Mateo,
Calif.-based LogicTier is one of hundreds of small technology
companies tucked away
</P>
<P>
   in Silicon Valley looking for a big break. Managing the Web site
and all of the Internet infrastructure for the Olympics _
everything from computers and software to the bandwidth needed to
move up-to-date scores
</P>
<P>
   and video clips _ is about as big as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic officials in Salt Lake City picked LogicTier over more
than a dozen companies in part because its executives have
experience with major Web sites ranging from USA Today's to
ESPN.com. Byrnes, one of
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley's more experienced female executives, ran Corsair
Communications Inc., which develops software for the wireless
industry, before joining LogicTier earlier this year. Also lending
credence to the
</P>
<P>
   company is the venerable Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers
venture capital firm, one of several that sunk $41 million into the
company just a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mitt Romney, president of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee,
declined to name other companies that were considered to run the
Games' Web operations, but said size didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of companies that have been around on the
Internet for more than a couple of years,'' said Romney, a former
Boston-based venture capitalist. ``And on the Internet, everybody's
small.''
</P>
<P>
   LogicTier isn't expected to see any direct revenues from the
deal with the Olympics. Technically, in fact, it's just another
sponsor, meaning it is providing its equipment and management
essentially for free. But
</P>
<P>
   the value of the resulting exposure _ and potential customers _
is incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will definitely put them in the running'' with bigger
companies in the future, said Rick Juarez, an Internet analyst with
investment banking firm Robertson Stephens Inc. ``The public is
going to hear more
</P>
<P>
   from them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe can be e-mailed at: bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1751EDT &QL; 
