<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-CONTRACTOR-SEARCH-NYT     08-30 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTRACTOR-SEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME IMPROVEMENT THAT COMES TO YOU VIA THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Economists will tell you that one hallmark of a hot economy is
an increase in the amount of money homeowners are willing to spend
on upgrading, repairing and maintaining their homes.
</P>
<P>
   What they won't tell you is how to find a good contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, any homeowner who has scoured the telephone book looking
for a contractor has discovered that it is often the contractor who
gets to pick and choose customers rather than the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Internet-based services, however, have been set up
to help consumers find qualified and reliable contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide a free service to homeowners by matching them with
prescreened contractors, architects and designers in their
geographic area,'' said Sharon Land, a manager with ImproveNet, an
online contractor referral service based in Redwood City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Land said that the company has about 40,000 registered
contractors who have passed a stringent prequalification procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We screen under four criteria,'' she said, explaining that
before contractors will be accepted by ImproveNet they must have
been in business under the same name for at least three years, must
have a clean legal history (which means that the company cannot
have been on the losing end of any lawsuits brought by clients or
creditors) and a clean credit history, and must provide proof of
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half the contractors who apply fail the screening
process,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   Nora DePalma, a spokeswoman for ImproveNet, said the company had
registered contractors in every state who were experts in just
about every home improvement specialty. But unlike most referral
services _ which provide homeowners with lists of contractors based
on geographical factors or the type of project contemplated _
ImproveNet provides the contractors with the names of homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we work is the homeowner describes the project by
filling out an online form,'' DePalma said, adding that a
description of the work to be performed, along with a hoped-for
start date and a range of what the customer can afford, is then
passed along to contractors in the homeowner's general vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   The service is free to homeowners, DePalma said, because the
contractors pay ImproveNet a commission for every job they get
through the company. ``They pay us between 2 and 10 percent of the
job, depending on the type of work they do,'' she said, adding that
the maximum amount a contractor is required to pay ImproveNet for
any individual job is $995.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to simply matching up homeowners with contractors,
ImproveNet also monitors the process to provide additional
assistance and follow-up. ``We assign a personal project adviser to
monitor the relationship between the homeowner and the
contractor,'' Land said, explaining that the adviser is available
to answer questions the homeowner may have and to assess the
results of the matchup when the work is done. The Internet address
of ImproveNet is www.ImproveNet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another nationwide online contractor referral service is
Handyman Online, a company based in Beaverton, Ore. ``We just
recently referred out our 100,000th home improvement project,''
said Bruce Stahl, director of marketing for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl said that Handyman Online (www.handymanonline.com) was
formed in 1997 by two former contractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that there was a real consumer need for this type
of service,'' Stahl said. ``And the service works well for the
contractors, too, because it's a more efficient way for them to
find customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl explained that the 8,000 or so contractors currently
registered with Handyman Online had all been prescreened by the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we send anyone out to a customer we check to make sure
that the contractor has insurance and that he is licensed if
licensing is required in the state where he's doing business,''
Stahl said. ``We also require every contractor to provide three
references and to sit down with us for a personal interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ImproveNet, Handyman Online is free to customers because
contractors pay the company when they land jobs. ``Our contractors
pay us a fee of anywhere from $10 to several hundred dollars,
depending on the size and type of the job,'' Stahl said, adding
that his company also assigns a customer service representative to
each homeowner who requests a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We contact the customer to make sure that a contractor has
called,'' he said. ``And then we follow up on the job until the
project is completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet sites that provide online contractor referrals
include www.nari.org, the Web site of the National Association of
the Remodeling Industry; www.ServiceMagic.com, a company that
provides consumers who submit project descriptions with up to three
qualified professionals, and www.NationalContractors.com, a company
that specializes in providing preconstruction project planning
experts for remodeling projects costing $25,000 or more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-QUEENS-BOTANICAL-GARD     08-30 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEENS-BOTANICAL-GARDEN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM TAI CHI TO COLLARD GREENS, A FLOWERING OF DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT12 and 13 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It isn't easy to find the Queens Botanical Garden,
unless you live on Main Street in Flushing, or down one of those
little one-way streets like Dahlia or Blossom. The 39-acre garden,
with its campy, low-slung buildings and boisterous plantings, is
tucked into the northeastern corner of Flushing Meadows-Corona
Park, cinched in by a pretzel of highways: the Grand Central
Parkway, the Van Wyck Expressway, the Long Island Expressway. One
wrong turn, and you're heading for the Whitestone Bridge, an
18-wheeler on your rear bumper. (You can always take the No. 7
train to the end of the line, and walk eight blocks.)
</P>
<P>
   This garden, which was seized by the city eight years ago when
its director and 20 members of its board were removed for misuse of
funds and negligence, is experiencing a rebirth that can only be
described as joyful. ``We want to be a botanic garden for cultural
diversity and education,'' said Susan Lacerte, the garden's
executive director. She was appointed six years ago by the board of
the Queens Botanical Garden Society, which regained control of the
garden in 1993 and has new corporate connections and a bent for
fund raising. ``There are plenty of other botanic gardens doing
scientific research,'' she continued. ``Our research is cultural
research, how people use plants around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Queens Botanical Garden welcomes just about anyone with a
passion: a Russian opera singer who manages the beehives, a
meteorologist in love with composting. Bird walkers. (``Baby! Baby!
Baby!'' a Chinese woman cried one morning. Her bird had flown off
its string.) And then there's tai chi, the ancient Chinese exercise
that evolved from the martial arts centuries ago, practiced here
from 7 to 9 every morning, 365 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   Just walk through the gate (no admission charge!), pass the
garden shop in a Quonset hut and the composting office in a
green-shingled trailer, and join the Happy Exercise Club ($5 for a
life membership) under the allee of grand old oaks. It's like
slipping into a quiet pond, moving arms and legs so deliberately
they seem to be pushing water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slow,'' said Raymond Chen, 70, as he followed the
movements of Hansong Huang, the 82-year-old master, who leaned
back, and then forward, impossibly balanced for a man his age.
``You've got to use concentration.'' As mist cleared over the
European hornbeam, hovering like a green unisphere over a sea of
giant hibiscus, men and women of all ages followed Master Huang
through 24 movements with names like Parting the Horse's Mane,
Grasping the Swallow's Tail and Clouds Roll By.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Korean gardeners tended their wild sesame and angelica,
a Japanese woman weeded the soybeans she had planted from seeds
sent from Kyoto, a Latino gardener picked the thick leaves of a
``Vicks'' plant (after Vicks VapoRub), started from a cutting he
spirited out of Puerto Rico in his suitcase. An African-American
man harvested leaves from his patch of collard greens, taking a
leaf here, a leaf there, so as not to destroy the whole.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census made it clear that Queens was the most
ethnically diverse county in the United States. Since then,
immigrants have continued to stream into the borough. A botanical
garden in such a setting must take a universal approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is moving all these groups into the garden,'' said
David Quintas-Parquet, a Cuban-born, Miami-raised Verizon executive
who lives in Forest Hills and serves on the board. ``Most
mainstream institutions never make the point to reach out to these
communities. But we're saying we have to, for moral as well as
economic reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Quintas-Parquet makes a point of coming to the garden for Latino
outreach days, where he has been known to wax poetic about the
tuberoses that grew in his mother's garden in Miami. ``They don't
look like much, but they have a fragrance I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people, more than half of them Asian, came to
Gardening Day in April 1997, when a local florist translated into
Chinese a lecture by David and Kasha Furman on the Chinese tree
peony, long a symbol of love and prosperity. In 1998, Gardening Day
concentrated on Hispanic traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Korean gardeners planted their national flower, the Rose of
Sharon, in a wide swath behind the Wedding Garden, booked for
ceremonies in Hindi, Hebrew, Spanish, Korean, Pakistani and
Chinese. (Garden regulars park their lawn chairs outside the gate
and offer ruthless commentary on the best, ugliest, happiest or
saddest bride.)
</P>
<P>
   When the city returned control to the Queens group, it had
operated on a deficit for five years. ``When I took over in July
1994, the garden had $38,000 in the bank,'' said Lacerte, who has a
degree in public administration and cut her teeth on finance as an
intern in City Councilman Peter F. Vallone's office. ``The garden
uses that much money in two to three weeks. I couldn't meet the
payrolls without help from the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The garden itself was a wreck. The demoralized staff had stopped
weeding. The bathrooms weren't working. There were no supplies.
``No peat moss, no paper clips,'' Lacerte said. ``They didn't even
have a Band-Aid. A public place with 300,000 visitors a year, and
no Band-Aid?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She hired two supervisors to energize the garden crew and
started steering the garden into the black. The board brainstormed
ways to draw the area's diverse population through the gates.
Community leaders and neighbors were invited to air their opinions,
as master planners considered how to turn this former swamp into a
cultural, and sustainable, landscape. The ambitious plan, which
could cost from $50 million to $80 million, is in its preliminary
stages, and could take 15 years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just started securing the perimeter of the garden, which is
a $3.3 million project,'' Lacerte said, adding that without a
fence, plants are too easily vandalized. ``And we want to make
water a unifying element of the garden,'' she said. ``A branch of
the Flushing River is buried under here. We want to uncover it, and
build a constructed wetlands.''
</P>
<P>
   The garden evolved out of a swamp that was filled in to build
the 1939 World's Fair, which featured a five-acre horticultural
extravaganza called ``Gardens on Parade.'' A group of Queens
residents restored the gardens in 1948 and set up the Queens
Botanical Garden Society. They were bumped from the site by the
1964 World's Fair, and moved to the northeast corner of Flushing
Meadows-Corona Park, but they took three blue atlas cedars,
survivors from 1939, with them.
</P>
<P>
   These elegant evergreens now stand rather incongruously over
Victorian bedding schemes that flaunt 12,000 tulips in spring and
ever-changing annuals circling a spiky cycad shrub. That's known as
Bernie's Bed. Nobody can remember who Bernie was, but they plant it
the way Bernie did, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   A fragrance garden, full of lilacs, clethra, viburnum, nicotiana
and many other sweet bloomers, wages a questionable battle with the
fumes of Main Street's nearby heavy traffic (master planners
suggested this garden be moved). And the old fountain _ drained
because so many homeless people bathed there _ is now full of
summer bloomers like Indian Summer rudbeckia and 10-foot-tall
purple ironweed.
</P>
<P>
   It's this very live-and-let-live theory of gardening that is so
engaging when public gardens are usually so polished and manicured.
Here, the atmosphere is as free as the admission. ``It's very
folksy,'' Lacerte said. ``It's a welcoming place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's of the community, by the community, and we don't want to
lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   The master plan, for example, drawn up by the landscape
architects Susan Wisniewski and Jamie Crelly Purinton, urges a
return to the native plants that would work well as part of a
sustainable landscape. ``I think that's smart, but we can't be all
native,'' Lacerte said. ``I don't think that's what we're all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   But she loves the vision of returning natural water systems to
the land. ``I could see a water wall in the new administration
building,'' Lacerte said. The new greenhouse could include tanks of
fish and plants that thrive on nitrates and purify water that can
be recycled through the garden.
</P>
<P>
   And if anything, these master planners are trying to preserve,
even cultivate, the garden's zany, anything-goes atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The master planners observed we had interesting staff gardens
that should be open to the public,'' Marianne Kristoff, the
supervisor of gardens, said, leading the way through a maze of
trellises built from scrap wood, branches and twigs. (They are
open.) Here, melons are supported way off the ground, in little
hammocks made of string. Garlic chives are buried in rich compost,
to keep their stalks white and tender.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring over this global farm is a boxwood airplane, a whimsical
salute to La Guardia and Kennedy Airports' deafening jets
constantly crossing overhead. There's a train too, and a pouncing
cat, and a hand with two fingers raised in the sign language for
``I love you,'' all made by Louis Quiles, who has tended the
grounds for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't make this stuff up if you tried,'' said Kristoff,
who came here from the lavish sculpture gardens at PepsiCo's
corporate headquarters in Purchase. ``There, everything was
planned. Here, you can say, `Oh, that's a good idea,' and it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The statue ``Jesus and St. John in the Corn Field,'' on loan
from the Brooklyn Museum, stands in a bed of red begonias. ``I keep
saying we should grow corn'' around it, Kristoff said, but her
gardeners keep planting flowers.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical botanical garden, the suggestions from the
supervisor of gardens might well be heeded. But this is no typical
botanical garden, and there isn't really a botanical name for what
is growing here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
