<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6527 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-1STLD-     08-30 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDS-NEXTGEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENS X AND WHY PICK THEIR CABLE CHANNEL FAVS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release August 30, 2000.)  
 NOTE: SUBS TO RESTORE DROPPED WORD ``TO'' IN GRAF 7.
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's TRENDS-NEXTGEN column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of TRENDS-NEXTGEN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By JANE RINZLER BUCKINGHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be hard enough to keep up with all the new TV series
and schedules. But these days, you also have to keep up with the
new networks vying for your attention. And with each one offering
24/7 programming, even if you have one of those digital video
recorders that will scout out your favorite programs and record
them on a hard drive, you may no longer know what to record.
</P>
<P>
   My company, Youth Intelligence, surveyed 1,000 teens from all
around the country, asking them which channels they consider to be
the hottest new offerings.
</P>
<P>
   HBO and SHOWTIME
</P>
<P>
   From ``Sex &AMP; the City'' to ``The Sopranos,'' HBO has some of the
most talked-about TV shows, and the upcoming series ``Band of
Brothers'' (with Tom Hanks) may make the biggest splash yet.
</P>
<P>
   When Youth Intelligence asked trendsetting teens where they
thought the next ``big thing'' in TV would come from, many said
``HBO.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young people say that the big networks' hands are tied.
(``They can't do anything risky! Their advertisers would get mad,''
said a 16-year-old in New York.) As a result, they look to HBO and
Showtime to provide new, more original entertainment. And as they
become more accustomed to commercial-free and censor-free
television, they seem less averse to having to pay for these
channels.
</P>
<P>
   MTV
</P>
<P>
   While MTV went through a rough period of reduced focus, the
network is clearly on the upswing. MTV is ever-popular with Gens X
and Why, and remains the No. 1 rated cable network for 12- to
24-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   MTV offers a good mix of programming and remains edgy, fun and
still about music. While many networks are having trouble with
comedy, ``Lyricists Lounge'' and ``The Tom Green Show'' remain
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Already a favorite with teens who set trends, ``Comedy Central''
is likely to become more popular with mainstream teen audiences as
well.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first to shift from fall to summer premieres, their
summer lineup combined the highly sought-after audience
participation show, ``Don't Forget Your Toothbrush'' with the
outrageous serialized comedy, ``Strip Mall,'' and the British
import, ``League of Gentlemen.'' In conjunction with the existing
hits (``The Man Show,'' ``Strangers With Candy,'' ``The Daily
Show'' and ``Win Ben Stein's Money''), Comedy Central's 2000
program schedule means we'll be laughing with them, not at them.
</P>
<P>
   E! NETWORKS
</P>
<P>
   Young people just can't seem to get enough eye candy, and E! is
willing to endlessly support their habit. They are the authorities
on entertainment news and lifestyle-related programming and
therefore a must-watch for trendsetters and anyone wanting to stay
``in the know.'' As one 23-year-old explained, ``E! is addictive! I
can watch the same fashion special or celebrity profile five times
and not get bored.''
</P>
<P>
   With the recent launch of ``Style!'' a 24-hour network devoted
to style, fashion and design from the people who brought us E!,
look for the brand to garner even more of a following. (In the
interest of full disclosure, I'm a correspondent for ``Style!,''
but, as they say, also a user!)
</P>
<P>
   DISCOVERY CHANNEL
</P>
<P>
   If your teen suddenly flips the TV channel when you walk into
the room, the good news is he may not be surreptitiously trying to
unscramble the X-rated channels. Instead, he may just be hiding his
love of learning.
</P>
<P>
   Young people tell us they love finding out new things, as long
as it's done in an engaging manner. From ``Shark Week'' to ``The
FBI Files,'' Discovery offers some of the best learning around
(although TLC _ The Learning Channel _ also gets high fives for its
``Live Surgeries.'')
</P>
<P>
   THE SUNDANCE CHANNEL
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the growing popularity of The Sundance Film
Festival and its independent films, comes its related network. The
Sundance film channel has appeared on trendsetters' radar screens
for the last couple of years and is growing hotter even among
mainstream youth.
</P>
<P>
   With a growing following for ``indie'' films, teens are
interested in seeing movies that they may have missed in the art
houses or ones that never made it to the big screen at all.
</P>
<P>
   BBC AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   This network is the product of an alliance between the British
Broadcasting Corporation and Discovery Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   BBC America is known for its outlandish comedies including
``Brilliant!,'' ``The League of Gentlemen'' and ``People Like Us''
as well as its British-style shows, ``Cool Britannia'' and ``This
Life.'' You don't have to be an Anglophile to want to tune in.
</P>
<P>
   BE ON THE LOOKOUT FOR
</P>
<P>
   Tarte Makeup
</P>
<P>
   The Man Who Ate the 747 (Book)
</P>
<P>
   Hair Chopsticks (Barrettes)
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham is the president of Youth Intelligence,
a market-research firm specializing in the 7- to 35-year-old
market. Her company publishes the Cassandra Report, a comprehensive
survey focused on identifying emerging trends among Generations X
and Why?
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on TREND
WATCH and other features. &QL;
</P>
