<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMONDS _ As the diamond industry around the world struggles to
free itself from conflict diamonds _ so that consumers can be sure
the rings on their fingers didn't pay to cut of someone else's arm
_ we look at how local diamond dealers are trying to deal with the
issue. (Searer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY _ GOP vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney campaigns in
Atlanta Wednesday, blasting the Clinton-Gore administration for
what he says is a poor record of support for the military. Georgia
Democrats slap back, saying Cheney is resorting to a tired
Republican line of attacking Democrats on the military to avoid
getting into the real issues _ the lack of detail by the
Bush-Cheney ticket on health insurance for children and plans for
providing prescription drug coverage for the elderly. (Pruitt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-CHENEY _ Tom Baxter is with Dick Cheney in Atlanta. We
take a look at how the GOP campaign is going. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Paralyzed since a May 15
shooting, Dayton police officer Mary Beall has been undergoing
intensive therapy since being transferred from Good Samaritan
Hospital in mid-June. The hospital staff had come to regard her as
family. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ People who want to mingle government and
religion argue that the words ``separation of church and state'' do
not appear in the Constitution. They're right. But neither do the
words ``interstate commerce,'' ``separation of powers'' or ``right
to privacy.'' They are, however, fundamental constitutional
principles. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ Now that roosters have been relegated to a cage
at one South Austin homestead, it's a sure sign of yuppification.
(Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ My mother called to say Barbie dolls are worth
$4,000. I should have kept mine. Real life column. (Minor, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   APOLOGY _ Corporate America is learning a word that's old hat to
most folks. Sorry. That's the subtext of high-profile TV
commercials from Ford Motor Co. concerning the Firestone tire
fiasco and from United Airlines about a summer-long spate of flight
delays and cancellations. The ads feature top executives.
``Clearly, the most effective way to deal with a crisis is full
disclosure, right up front,'' said Jeff Springston, an associate
professor of advertising and marketing at the University of
Georgia. ``The public will forgive mistakes, but they'll never
forgive a lie.'' (Leith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN _ Rick Kaplan's departure from CNN is part of a larger
executive shake-up announced today by the Atlanta-based network.
Phil Kent, formerly chief of Turner Broadcasting's international
unit, assumes the newly created job of president and coo of CNN
News Group, while three other network insiders are being promoted.
The moves, which could make Kent the heir apparent to CNN Chairman
Tom Johnson, come as the network faces two big issues: sagging
ratings and a pending merger with AOL. (Kempner/Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in entertainment (e) category
</P>
<P>
   ENRON _ The president of Enron Corp. of Houston, the giant
energy company and often-cited example of how Old Economy companies
can get with the New Economy, speaks at InteractiveTexas today. He
will provide some detail about how the former gas pipeline company
crossed the corporate digital divide. (Mahoney, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KOOP _ Ailing company lays off a bunch of people, now down to
the same staff it had when it went public. How are they going to
maintain the content with a lean staff? (Park, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GP-MILLS _ As expected, Georgia-Pacific has put several of its
pulp mills up for sale, including its large plant in Brunswick. At
least a half dozen other sites are up for sale, in New York,
Mississippi and Maine. The divestiture is part of GP's plan to move
away from the commodity side of the business in its merger with
tissue giant Fort James. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ Thursday is the last day of August and BellSouth
(again) has reached a self-imposed deadline for making its request
to enter long-distance. And BellSouth (again) is not ready to make
that request. Clearly frustrated by the continued delays, BellSouth
is starting to see some real attacks on its home markets. This
month, AT&AMP;T planted its own name on MediaOne and is ramping up
efforts to sell phone service along with Internet access and
television via its upgraded cable lines. Meanwhile, SBC is in
long-distance in Texas and has signed up hundreds of thousands of
customers. Verizon, the former Bell Atlantic, has signed up more
than 1 million after receiving long distance approval in New York.
And then there's BellSouth.... (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (EDS: Moving on l (Lifestyle) and a
(General News) categories.) MOVED. REALCOOL-GUY _ Who is the most
valuable person in Austin in the summer? The air conditioning
repair guy. What's a day with this hero like? (Lisheron, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER NEWS
</P>
<P>
   SHOWERHEADS _ A lot of home improvement jobs are tricky and may
turn out to be more complicated than you expect. Other jobs are so
easy that one class at a home improvement store or 30 minutes
helping someone with experience will teach you all you need to
know. I've found that changing a shower head can fall into either
category. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHERS _ Automatic washers and dryers have taken most of the
physical labor out of getting our clothes and linens clean, but it
now takes smarts to do the laundry. A look at the new generation of
washers and dryers, plus a sidebar on energy labels. (Dayton Daily
News) WITH PHOTOS AND ILLUSTRATION. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYEBROWS _Think of your brows as just hair above your eyes?
Browse this! Arch concerns. (tied to a new book ``The Eyebrow.'')
(Folstad, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ Totes for tots (and the people who love them)
How-to-buy and what-to-look-for guide to diaper bags for the modern
mother (and father) _ forget the cutesy baby pinks and blues. Even
handbag designer Kate Spade has come out with a version of the old
standby. And there are back-pack styles that are easy to carry.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-GUIDE _ A weekly feature telling how to locate
hard-to-find items. This week: (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT.
