Donavan McNabb. The Eagles play at the Dallas Cowboys on Sunday.
(Cantu, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SLUR _ Aussie long jumper says you can discount the American
jumpers, who are black, because ``the temperature will be cool at
Sydney Games.'' He goes on to say the Americans ``only jump big in
America'' and he's not worried about them. Americans respond,
likening him to John Rocker and that the racial attack is
unwarranted. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TECH _ SAN MATEO, Calif. - The winter Olympics don't start
for another two years, but already it has produced the tale of a
little-known underdog winning out in a contest of truly Olympian
proportions. Organizers of the 2002 Winter Olympics on Wednesday
selected an outfit called Logictier Inc. to handle all of its
Internet operations. If you haven't heard of Logictier, don't be
surprised. It's less than a year old and its biggest Web projects
so far include running the sites of a company that auctions
bulldozers and other heavy equipment and an online trivia game
called Duckets. Winning the Olympic contract could be huge for
little San Mateo, Calif.-based Logictier. For the past 40 years,
the company in charge of technology at the games has been an outfit
called IBM Corp. It just goes to show again that in today's
technology age, you don't have to be a behemoth to be a big-time
player. (Keefe, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
