<P>
   These business stories for release THURSDAY, AUGUST 31, 2000,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   APOLOGY _ Corporate America is learning a word that's old hat to
most folks. Sorry. That's the subtext of high-profile TV
commercials from Ford Motor Co. concerning the Firestone tire
fiasco and from United Airlines about a summer-long spate of flight
delays and cancellations. The ads feature top executives.
``Clearly, the most effective way to deal with a crisis is full
disclosure, right up front,'' said Jeff Springston, an associate
professor of advertising and marketing at the University of
Georgia. ``The public will forgive mistakes, but they'll never
forgive a lie.'' (Leith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN _ Rick Kaplan's departure from CNN is part of a larger
executive shake-up announced today by the Atlanta-based network.
Phil Kent, formerly chief of Turner Broadcasting's international
unit, assumes the newly created job of president and coo of CNN
News Group, while three other network insiders are being promoted.
The moves, which could make Kent the heir apparent to CNN Chairman
Tom Johnson, come as the network faces two big issues: sagging
ratings and a pending merger with AOL. (Kempner/Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Also moving in entertainment (e) category
</P>
<P>
   ENRON _ The president of Enron Corp. of Houston, the giant
energy company and often-cited example of how Old Economy companies
can get with the New Economy, speaks at InteractiveTexas today. He
will provide some detail about how the former gas pipeline company
crossed the corporate digital divide. (Mahoney, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KOOP _ Ailing company lays off a bunch of people, now down to
the same staff it had when it went public. How are they going to
maintain the content with a lean staff? (Park, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GP-MILLS _ As expected, Georgia-Pacific has put several of its
pulp mills up for sale, including its large plant in Brunswick. At
least a half dozen other sites are up for sale, in New York,
Mississippi and Maine. The divestiture is part of GP's plan to move
away from the commodity side of the business in its merger with
tissue giant Fort James. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ Thursday is the last day of August and BellSouth
(again) has reached a self-imposed deadline for making its request
to enter long-distance. And BellSouth (again) is not ready to make
that request. Clearly frustrated by the continued delays, BellSouth
is starting to see some real attacks on its home markets. This
month, AT&AMP;T planted its own name on MediaOne and is ramping up
efforts to sell phone service along with Internet access and
television via its upgraded cable lines. Meanwhile, SBC is in
long-distance in Texas and has signed up hundreds of thousands of
customers. Verizon, the former Bell Atlantic, has signed up more
than 1 million after receiving long distance approval in New York.
And then there's BellSouth.... (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
