<HEADLINE>
NEO-NAZI YOUTHS SENTENCED IN BEATING DEATH OF IMMIGRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Three young neo-Nazis were convicted of murder
Wednesday for beating an African immigrant to death, and one of
them was sentenced to life imprisonment, the heaviest punishment
under German law.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberating in a case that has become a symbol of the virulence
of anti-immigrant sentiment among many youths in the former East
Germany, Judge Albrecht Hennig said the victim, Alberto Adriano, a
39-year-old meatpacker from Mozambique, had been killed because of
the color of his skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the latest in a long series of attacks to which we must
put an end,'' Hennig said. That series began on Nov. 25, 1990, when
an Angolan was killed by rightists in the eastern town of
Eberswalde, and has continued sporadically ever since, drawing
occasional national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Such attention has grown of late, with the government seemingly
awakening to the fact that neo-Nazi violence, however marginal, has
a terrible impact on Germany's image. Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
who is likely to visit a small memorial to Adriano this week in
Dessau, where he lived, appealed Wednesday for a mass movement
against racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the engagement of civil society,'' Schroeder said in a
television interview. ``We need a repeat of what the people in the
east of our country did in the peaceful revolution of 10 years ago,
an involvement in the fight for what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor was referring to the demonstrations that led to
the collapse of the East German state and the Berlin Wall, a time
of euphoric optimism. But a tough reality has emerged since then:
high unemployment in the east, bitterness at the western takeover
of the area, nostalgia for the security of socialism and its proud
slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, rightist, anti-foreigner movements have
proved attractive to some youths in the east, despite the fact that
the overwhelming majority of immigrants in Germany live in the
west. Christian Richter, one of the convicted men, said he had
attacked Adriano ``because foreigners take our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Adriano was kicked and beaten in a Dessau park on June 11 and
died three days later without recovering consciousness. He was
married to a German woman and had three children, the youngest 7
months old.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Angelika, did not appear in court Wednesday after
receiving a threatening letter now being examined by the
prosecutor's office in Dessau. Razak Minhel, the Dessau city
official responsible for foreigners, said Mrs. Adriano was ``too
scared to leave her children alone and come to court.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The court sentenced Enrico Hilprecht, 24, to life imprisonment.
Richter, 16, and Frank Miethbauer, also 16, were sentenced to nine
years of detention, one year less than the maximum sentence under
Germany's juvenile law.
</P>
<P>
   In a climate of considerable agitation over rightist violence
since a bomb in Duesseldorf last month wounded nine immigrants, the
sentences were clearly intended to send a signal that Germany has
lost patience with xenophobia and rightist nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   In the television interview, Schroeder said the police and
judiciary needed to be tougher on extremists. Some evidence has
emerged that the police in the east, who are sometimes former
police employees of the defunct communist state, are reluctant to
crack down on the rightists because of tacit sympathy for their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest incident of racist violence, prosecutors in the
northern town of Luebeck said Wednesday that they had arrested two
skinheads for wounding a 33-year-old African in an attack on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
