<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6540 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FRIENDSHIP-SIDE-HNS &LR;      08-30 0185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDSHIP-SIDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
KEEPING FRIENDS FOR A LIFETIME &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Author Sandy Sheehy learned that despite the demands of jobs,
families and other commitments, women have found ways to nurture
close friendships. Here are tips on keeping friends for life,
culled from her interviews with more than 300 women and girls:
</P>
<P>
   Make friendship a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Value friendships for what they are, rather than fretting over
their limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Learn to listen and when to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
   Express your feelings directly.
</P>
<P>
   Handle conflict and competition constructively.
</P>
<P>
   Take the initiative in making up after fights.
</P>
<P>
   Stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Adapt to change.
</P>
<P>
   Be there for your friends.
</P>
<P>
   Know your limits.
</P>
<P>
   Master the art of reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
   Give gifts from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Learn to end friendships without making enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Reconnect with old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Be open to new friends.
</P>
<P>
   Help your daughters and mothers to have strong friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate friends and friendship.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
