<HEADER>
A6543 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BELLSBC0831-COX     08-30 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSBC0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth-SBC wireless marriage clears Justice Department
barrier
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The Justice Department has given conditional
endorsement to the plan of BellSouth and SBC to merge wireless
units, a deal that will assemble the nation's second-largest
wireless carrier.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas-based SBC and BellSouth receive final approval from the
Federal Communications Commission on Oct. 1 _ as they hope _ then
they will announce a name for the venture, which will be
headquartered in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approval is a major step toward the launch of a
world-class national wireless company,'' said Stephen Carter, the
SBC executive named president and chief executive of the newly
formed wireless company.
</P>
<P>
   The company will start with about 18 million subscribers,
comfortably ahead of AT&AMP;T's 13 million and behind only Verizon,
which has about 26 million. SBC will be majority owner of the
venture, but the companies have pledged to split the management.
</P>
<P>
   The companies must only sell interests in four cities where they
each have investments, with one company or the other shedding its
wireless property, said the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, SBC will sell its interests to AT&AMP;T. In New
Orleans and Baton Rouge, La., SBC will sell its interests to Little
Rock, Ark.,-based Alltel. In Los Angeles, no decision has been made
yet as to which company will sell its interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's action by the department ensures that this joint
venture will not reduce competition in these local markets,'' said
Joel I. Klein, who heads the agency's antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   Since the companies had said they would sell overlapping
properties, Justice Department approval was expected. Still, the
agency is flush with an antitrust court victory over Microsoft
followed by its objections to WorldCom's purchase of Sprint, which
killed that deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't emphasize it enough _ this is a big piece,'' said
BellSouth spokesman Jeff Battcher. ``This is very good news to so
quickly get the DOJ blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   The areas covered by the SBC-BellSouth venture will include 34
states, the District of Columbia and two territories. On that turf,
the venture will have 175 million potential customers _ along with
a raft of competition.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC and BellSouth have vowed to become as national as Sprint
or AT&AMP;T, which both tout coast-to-coast reach. The companies won't
saywhether they will pick up wireless licenses in coming FCC
auctions or if they will buy struggling carriers that serve those
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
