<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FRIENDSHIP-HNS &LR;      08-30 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALVESTON AUTHOR'S NEWEST BOOK GOES TOTHE HEART OF FRIENDSHIP 
(WITH PHOTO AND SIDEBAR)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BARBARA KARKABI 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
GALVESTON, Texas _ For much of her life, writer Sandy Sheehy was
terrible at making and keeping friends.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When teams were picked in high school, she was generally the
next to last choice. Even though she was on the newspaper and
literary magazine, Sheehy never really had the elusive ``best''
friend.
</P>
<P>
   While a student at Vassar College, she was so focused on meeting
guys that she ignored the many potential female friends. It wasn't
until she was in her mid-30s that Sheehy began reaching out to
other women. It took another decade before she understood what it
meant to be a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   And at her 40th birthday party, she had what might be called a
friendship wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband got a bunch of friends together for dinner,'' she
recalled. ``I looked around the table at the five couples, and they
were all people who really mattered to me. But they were all couple
friends. In some cases the bond was between me and the women. In
others between my husband and the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy remembers thinking: ``I want some relationships with
women that are relationships of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years later, Sheehy looks back on the night as the
beginning of a journey that has enriched her life. It gave her the
idea for her second book: ``Connecting: The Enduring Power of
Female Friendship'' (William Morrow, $25) and in the process, she
said, made her a better friend.
</P>
<P>
   A former Houstonian who now lives in Galveston, Sheehy learned
that until late in the 20th century, women were asked to believe
what she calls ``two lies'': Other women aren't worth our time, and
neither is friendship. Instead, romance and family bonds were what
women should seek.
</P>
<P>
   That was especially true for women born before 1940, she found
out. Women born after 1950, who came of age in the first wave of
feminism, felt differently about female friendships. But Sheehy was
an early baby boomer _ born between 1940 and 1950 _ so she had to
figure things out for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt like there was a lack in my life,'' Sheehy said.
``I hadn't built much time into just seeing my women friends, and I
wanted more than I had. I felt like there was an important
relationship missing, and I also suspected there was power in the
friendship of women to help us become our best selves.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sheehy began thinking about this personal issue, she wrote
about it for Self and Working Woman magazines. The stories weren't
always positive. One was on how to end a friendship without making
an enemy, and another was on how to keep money problems from
interfering with a friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually it became her next book project. Her first book,
``Texas Rich,'' was published in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `If I'm becoming intensely interested about
something, there is this whole bulge of people who will be
interested, too,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But getting it published was another story. Sheehy wrote a
proposal and sent it to the man who then was her agent. He returned
it after a couple of women in his office told him that women don't
have friendships.
</P>
<P>
   She found a new agent, rewrote her proposal and got a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Because she had been a philosophy graduate student, Sheehy said,
she loves to analyze things and figure out how they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to look at friendship and what it does for us,'' she
said. ``I wanted to find the answers to questions like: Why do some
friendships last and others don't? What are women's main challenges
in friendship? What do we do well in friendship, and what do we
need to improve?''
</P>
<P>
   She began by talking to her own friends and researching the
database at University of Houston. Eventually, Sheehy found about
two dozen social scientists and therapists who had written about
and studied aspects of women's friendship or friendship in general.
</P>
<P>
   To conduct her own research, she made a questionnaire and
interviewed more than 200 women and girls around the country. They
ranged in ages from 8 to 90. About half were married, a quarter
were single and a quarter divorced; 13 were lesbians. Most were
middle-class, but a few were just above poverty level, and a couple
were millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised by several things. First was how many people
said that a sense of humor played a big part in selecting someone
as a friend,'' Sheehy said. ``That was right up there with shared
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise was how much the teen-age girls she talked to
had thought about their friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think when I was a teen, 30-something years ago, that
we gave our friendships with other girls a lot of thought,'' she
said. ``Unless one of them blew up, and we wondered what to do. But
we didn't think: What does this bring to my life, and how does this
help me gain independence from my family?''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about ``best friends,'' Sheehy found that most women
had four to seven close friends at any given time. Then they had
good friends _ people they are in contact with less often, followed
by a layer of acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often when someone moves who is part of your closest circle,
you will draw someone in from the next circle of friends,'' Sheehy
said. ``It doesn't mean you will lose a friendship if a woman
moves, but it may take a different form.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaving the women's stories and voices together with the
research of sociologists and therapists, Sheehy found seven stages
of female friendship: attraction, initiation, structuring, comfort,
strengthening, testing and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can take years to go through those and may stop at some
initial stage,'' she said. ``Or it could go through all of those
stages pretty much on fast-forward.''
</P>
<P>
   She also puts the friendships women make into 10 categories:
soul mates, life mates, companions in crisis, nurturers and
nurtured, playmates and work mates, allies, complementary
opposites, mentor and protege, history friends and ensemble
friends.
</P>
<P>
   As important as friendship was to all the women interviewed, it
was obvious there were different phases. From ages 8 to 12, Sheehy
found that girls had a variety of friends for different things.
They tended to have playmates and soul mates who felt and reacted
the way they did.
</P>
<P>
   For teens, 13 to 17, friendships were in groups of people who
did things together. College friendships, from 18 to 22, were made
closer by shared living experiences.
</P>
<P>
   But from ages 23 to 39, Sheehy found, women had a hard time
maintaining friendships _ often because of career moves or work and
family commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to women who weren't married and didn't have kids and
weren't necessarily working in 80-hour-a-week jobs,'' Sheehy said.
``They still had a few friends, and they were close, but they
didn't have the sort of enriching network of friends they had
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that around age 40, women start acquiring more
friends, spending more time with existing pals and reconnecting
with old friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you have a supportive husband, mother or sister, you
need a friend who sees you as an individual,'' she said. ``Someone
who values you not because you are a daughter or wife, but solely
because of your individual qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
