<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GOOD-JUNK-ART-2TAKES-     08-30 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOD-JUNK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MT. EVEREST OF YARD SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT15, 16 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pin on Mimi Mannix's hat said it all. ``Junk 'til you drop''
it read, which is why Mannix _ was outside the Strudel Haus in
Covington, Ky., on a Thursday afternoon painting a giant pig. Like
a multitude of less colorful people, Mannix, an Indiana
collectibles dealer, and her capacious yellow porker, a mascot long
ago rescued from the roof of a Piggly Wiggly grocery store, had
come to this musty little town across the Ohio River from
Cincinnati to shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm selling, I'm buying, I'm doing my pig,'' Mannix said,
dipping into a vat of pink enamel. ``I'm having fun.'' Here at the
northernmost tip of an annual event known as the 450-Mile Route 127
Corridor Sale, it was no wonder why. A banner spanning Main Street
hailed, ``Welcome to the start of the world's largest yard sale.''
On the reverse it said, ``Welcome to the end of the world's largest
yard sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Covington was the final destination if you started your journey
at the other end, 450 miles away in Gadsden, Ala. Like everything
about this multistate flea market, it was all in how you looked at
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Route 127 Corridor, as this scenically rich, economically
underprivileged stretch is called, is not lined with Heywood
Wakefield dining room sets and paved with lilac Fiesta Ware. But
for a few very busy days every August, there is good junk as far as
the eye can see. A 1966 Batman lunchbox for $50, a Shawnee
Polynesian lady head vase for $40, a Continental Kilns Bali Hai
vegetable bowl for $5, a set of Tiki spice shakers for $6, cartoon
figurines from fast-food shops for a quarter. It is as if, for one
long weekend a year, the 26th Street Flea Market extended from New
York to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers like my junking buddy, Chuck Hettinger, and me,
longtime collectors who live by the words ``Have Bubble Wrap, Will
Travel,'' this was a four-day odyssey like no other. Although eBay
and a plethora of guidebooks have inflated the prices of
collectibles the world over, this rural flea market has not been
completely spoiled by price-gouging dealers and pay-anything urban
aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   Trendy collectors _ the internationally known fashion designers,
interior decorators and celebrities who frequent the flea markets
of Manhattan or Pasadena, Calif. _ were not perusing Covington's
card tables. Nor were they pawing the racks at Possum Trot Antiques
in Pall Mall, Tenn., a day's drive away and one of the many antique
stores dotting the route.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Possum Trot's Doris Doss was selling poodle-shaped
liquor decanters and lunches of country ham, candied sweet potatoes
with toasted marshmallows and slices of ``Million Dollar Pie'' to
customers who came from as far away as Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by such artery-clogging foods, we made our way along the
mostly two-lane road that snaked through Kentucky and Tennessee.
The slow-going drive continued into Georgia and Alabama. But after
shopping for 12 hours a day for three days straight, we never made
it past Chattanooga, Tenn. By then, we were just too junked out to
go any farther than an antiques mall in East Ridge, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising past Baptist churches, double-wide trailers, green
tobacco fields and solemn graveyards, we stopped our rented minivan
every few minutes to browse through wares set out in the driveways
of private homes, along sidewalks, in high school parking lots, in
former chicken coops and on flatbed trailers parked in muddy
fields. A pickup parked on the bank of the Ohio River near the
Indiana border produced a 1950s tropical leaf-shaped dish from Hull
pottery marked $35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you take $20?'' I asked a man who had fashioned his
T-shirt into a hat. ``Make it $22, so my wife won't kill me,'' he
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Among the detritus of the 20th century _ from guns to gravy
boats _ we perused pressed-glass pitchers, old Louis L'Amour
paperbacks, Fire King mugs, confederate flags, hubcaps and talking
Pee-wee Herman dolls who uttered their last ``I know you are, but
what am I?'' years ago. Empty Mrs. Butterworth's bottles shared
tables with several decades' worth of Kentucky Derby glasses.
Barbie dolls in hand-crocheted Southern belle dresses stood next to
an unopened box of ``Mork and Mindy'' trading cards from the 1970s.
Baby clothes cried out for a new generation of wearers.
</P>
<P>
   There were some real finds on our trip _ a $10 box of Eva Zeisel
Town and Country dishware that might fetch $500 on eBay, for
instance. But a lot was the kind of stuff Housing Works would
reject as too cruddy to sell in its New York City thrift shops.
Still, the pleasure of the world's longest yard sale was in the
hunt, the joy of uncovering that one coveted piece that made the
trip spiritually, if not economically, worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   My accomplice in all this, Chuck, is a decorative painter whose
collections include cookie jars, tin noisemakers and Lu-Ray Pastel
dishes. For him, the Holy Grail was a 3-foot-tall blown-glass
bottle made by a company called Blenko in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   After looking through hundreds of thousands of items, we felt
the junker's tingle in a scraggly crescent of grass and gravel with
nothing else even remotely attractive for sale. There we found,
lying on its side, the oversized decanter, a giant yellow vessel
with its stopper still intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much is that big bottle?'' I asked the man standing near
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh that's not for sale,'' he said. We hadn't come all this way
to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not for sale, why is it here?'' Chuck asked.
</P>
<P>
   The man explained that he had bought the bottle that morning for
$25, and didn't want to part with it. ``I'll give you $50,'' Chuck
said.
</P>
<P>
   No thanks, the man replied. On it went, $75, $100, finally $125.
</P>
<P>
   That was the magic number. ``I can't say no to making a hundred
dollars,'' the man said. A few minutes later, I overheard one
female shopper say to another, ``That guy must know something if
he's willing to spend that much for a bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   We both did. Chuck knew a similar Blenko bottle recently sold on
eBay for close to $1,000. I knew I didn't want to be in that
minivan if the guy had refused to sell it to Chuck.
</P>
<P>
   Steals like that one, we've since been told, have gotten fewer
and farther between as the sale has grown. ``Four years ago, before
eBay, there was a lot more collectible stuff for a quarter,'' said
Ryan Lance, a proprietor of a store called Howdy Do on East 7th
Street in Manhattan, which sells campy pop culture items like
``Cher's Dressing Room Play Set'' and ``H.R. Pufnstuf'' coloring
books.
</P>
<P>
   Programs like ``Antiques Roadshow'' and published guides to all
types of collectibles have helped to jack up prices, too, he said.
``I saw a rusted-out, horrible old `Charlie's Angels' lunchbox _
the handle was half melted _ and the lady had $95 on it,'' Lance
said. ``I asked her, `Why is it this much?' and she said, `That's
what it books for.'''
</P>
<P>
   His partner, Michael Torres, added, ``People this year were much
more aware of what they have in their homes and in their
basements.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At least one thing hasn't changed: The so-bad-it's-good
aesthetic hasn't reached these parts yet. ``The people down there
don't appreciate black velvet paintings,'' Lance noted. ``They're
$3 apiece there, and we can get $75 here. What's sad is that people
probably took them down off their walls for the sale.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who live in these economically depressed environs _
particularly junk dealers, restaurant operators and motel owners _
the Route 127 sale is a significant source of income. ``This is by
far the biggest week of the year here,'' said Scott Sandman,
executive director of the Jamestown, Tenn., Chamber of Commerce,
which promotes the event. ``There are sellers who make 8 or 10
thousand dollars in these four days,'' he said. The median
household income in 1999 for Fentress County, Tenn., was $21,293.
</P>
<P>
   As Doss of Possum Trot Antiques said, ``In four days, we do what
we usually do in two months.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Barnett, who owns the County Line Antiques Mall in
Lawrenceburg, Ky., said, ``People buy for it all year long, box it
up and store it until 127.'' She sees 50 to 100 customers on a
typical day. During the sale, she estimated that 2,500 people a day
browsed through her bric-a-brac. It is so busy, in fact, that she
never leaves the store during the four-day yard sale, sleeping on a
cot rather than going home to Lexington, which is a half-hour away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had people peeking in the door at 6:30 a.m.,''
she said. ``And we stay open until they stop coming.'' That may be
as late as midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Started more than a dozen years ago, the giant yard sale has
grown since the days when a former county executive named Mike
Walker, a lawyer in Jamestown, came up with the idea of a crafts
sale to lure tourists off the interstate. ``The first year, we put
out crafts and didn't sell anything,'' Doss said. ``But after that
we put out junk and whatnot, and it sold.''
</P>
<P>
   The Route 127 Corridor Sale is no longer much of a secret. On
June 14, HGTV, the home and garden cable channel, presented a
one-hour documentary called ``The Longest Yard Sale.'' ``They aired
that special on a Wednesday, and the next day the phones wouldn't
quit,'' Sandman said. ``We had 400 calls.''
</P>
<P>
   One was from Allen Holladay, a machinist from Rock Island, Ill.
He and his girlfriend, Lori Bitterman, a nursing instructor, had
driven 750 miles from home when I caught up with them, near the
Isaac Shelby Cemetery State Historic Site, 7 miles northwest of
Stanford, Ky. ``We were sitting watching the Home and Garden
network and heard about this,'' Holladay said. ``We hadn't planned
a vacation, so we decided to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple were carting furniture home in a blue van with an
open trailer attached. ``It looks like the Beverly Hillbillies,''
he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   For next summer, PBS plans to show ``A Flea Market
Documentary,'' another special featuring the Route 127 sale. At the
Lake Cumberland Motel in Jamestown, Ky., Rick Sebak, a bearish
television producer with a jovial demeanor, was conducting
interviews for it. Sebak, who produced the critically lauded PBS
specials ``An Ice Cream Show'' and ``A Hot Dog Program,'' said that
he and his crew ``have been totally flabbergasted by it all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than we expected,'' he said. ``In rural Kentucky
and Tennessee, there's still cool stuff left in people's houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for long, perhaps. But for now, the sale still has the
feeling that around the next corner will be another Blenko bottle,
another '60s lunchbox in fabulous condition and another woman
painting a giant pig. When I think of Mannix back in Covington
pointing to her hat, I laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``See this button?'' she asked. ``It says, `Don't pay department
store prices.' I raised four kids on yard sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as she had probably done at least a hundred times before,
Mannix went into a story about the time she dressed the giant pig
up as Zsa Zsa Gabor and took him to the Queen Kumquat Sashay in
Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The story was free. No purchase required.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
