<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      08-30 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calendula Choices
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I lived in New Hampshire, I grew calendulas in my herb
garden that were to die for. Now, we have moved near Washington,
and they just aren't performing well. I'm baffled and need your
help, please, as these are among my favorite easy-to-grow annuals.
</P>
<P>
   A. Welcome to summer heat. Calendula, also called pot marigold,
takes little effort to grow other than remembering to put it in
full sun. But while it loves cool climates, in warmer areas it
quits blooming in midsummer. If the selection you have has grown
long and rangy, this is a perfect time to cut them back by a third
to a half. As cool weather returns, they'll rebloom. When they
start again, continue your religious devotion to deadheading, so
they will keep flowering cheerfully right until hard frost finally
takes them.
</P>
<P>
   Calendula selections range from under 1 foot tall to over 2. The
flowers are usually bright orange or shades of yellow, and are
often fully double. Knockout cultivars include Pink Surprise, with
soft peach melba petals and a well-behaved habit, and Touch of Red,
whose many petals are edged in a mahogany blush.
</P>
<P>
   Seed sources include Pinetree Garden Seeds, Box 300, New
Gloucester, Maine 04260, (207) 926-3400; and Thompson &AMP; Morgan, Box
1308, Jackson, N.J. 08527, (800) 274-7333. Both catalogs are free.
</P>
<P>
   Best and Worst of Crab Apples
</P>
<P>
   Q. This is a tale of two crab apples, and I hope you know a
happy ending. Both trees were on the property when we bought our
house last year, so I don't have any information about them. This
summer the backyard tree has lost all its leaves. The front tree
looks fine, but I am afraid that it will also succumb. What steps
can we take to help the remaining tree?
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't cut the backyard tree down _ it isn't dead. Crab
apples, lovely as they are, attract not only humans and birds, but
also a whole host of fungi. Your backyard tree has apple scab,
which the wet, cool weather has encouraged this summer. But if it
hadn't been scab, it might have been cedar-apple rust, fire blight
or powdery mildew.
</P>
<P>
   When buying one of the trees, the previous owner of your house
may have fallen in love with a pretty flower and forgot to ask
about disease resistance. Considering everything there is to decide
when choosing a crab apple _ like size and shape of the tree when
mature; size, color and persistence of the fruit; single or double
flowers in red, white, or pink; and whether it's an alternate-year
bloomer _ he or she may have just been awestruck in the middle of
all those trees in glorious flower at the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Scab is a surprising disease. You may not notice the dull, smoky
or sooty area on new leaves, or even the irregular olive-green or
brown velvety spots. But you sure notice when all the leaves fall
off in midsummer. Rake up and destroy all those fallen leaves,
because the fungus overwinters on them and can reinfect the tree
next year. Spraying an entire tree every eight to 10 days with
fungicides to prevent scab is not just difficult, but also silly
when disease-resistant crab apples are available everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance does not mean invulnerability, and a summer of
perfect fungus weather can overcome the most resistant of trees, so
some cultivars are clearly better than others. High on everyone's
list are Adams, Adirondack, Donald Wyman, Harvest Gold, Indian
Summer, Professor Sprenger, Prairifire, Snowdrift and Sugar Tyme.
By the way, all of these have excellent resistance to cedar-apple
rust, too.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(at)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
