<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FASH-COLOR-HNS &LR;      08-30 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASH-COLOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING LIKE SPRING, AUTUMN FASHIONS ARE COLOR CODED 
WITH PHOTOS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
HOUSTON _ Fall is that time of year when fashion traditionally
folds its colorful summer beach umbrella and heads for the security
of dune-dull neutrals or the colors of autumn foliage.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bring on the beige. Stock up on little black dresses. Rake in a
few forest green or rusty orange cashmere sweaters or wool suits.
That's what fall shopping is all about, right?
</P>
<P>
   Fall is not about racks newly stocked with baby blue, bubblegum
pink, grass green or neon orange. Not, that is, until fall 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's millennium madness, but designers have dictated a new
attitude that includes the wearing of color all year round. Exactly
what color, however, is up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red, orange, olive and tobacco or camel,'' said Lisa Spain,
owner of the Cotton Club stores. She bought a lot of camel, ``but
not for wearing near the face. It looks too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain is also seeing baby blue and pink, traditional
warm-weather colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the customer who liked spring because it was colorful
will like this fall and winter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any shade of the purple family,'' said Fred McCann, owner of
Esther Wolf. ``We can't keep it in.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann said lilac is the shade of purple attracting the most
attention because it is perfect to update last year's gray suits
and separates but also brightens any neutral, ``especially dark
brown.''
</P>
<P>
   At Arden B, stores young in outlook, the main colors of the
season are shaping up as purple, red, brick, orange and the brown
family, said Tess Hall, manager of the Galleria store.
Surprisingly, these are not necessarily the neon-bright colors one
associates with the very young.
</P>
<P>
   Hall sees these fall and winter colors as deeper, richer
continuations of spring and summer colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The color green is (begin ital)very(end ital) important,''
said Stephanie McKinley, owner of Pixie &AMP; Ivy. And navy blue,
especially in sheer fabrics or in combination with black, is the
unexpected new color for evening.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley is one of the people who wholeheartedly approve of
springlike pastel colors done in fall fabrics, such as leather.
``They make me feel so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Roz Pactor, vice president/fashion director of Foley's, said the
whole family of reds is important for early fall, with warm tones
such as loden green and spicy oranges, but she sees a lot of true
red returning for holiday wear.
</P>
<P>
   Women who are more timid about taking a major plunge into bright
colors might instead settle on bright separates or accessories _
and many stores anticipated this possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Sweater sets abound again this fall, but with more
unconventional pieces such as sleeveless turtlenecks instead of the
traditional short-sleeved shells.
</P>
<P>
   Furry and fuzzy sweaters, those that incorporate angora or
mohair, are also excellent ways to soften ultrabright colors or
accentuate icy pastels.
</P>
<P>
   At Saks Fifth Avenue, corduroy pants appear in bright colors,
said Jaqui Lividini, senior vice president of fashion merchandising
and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Fishnet stockings are one of the hottest accessories at
Pryorities, said owner Judy Pryor. She is selling them in purple
and red, as well as black.
</P>
<P>
   One of the color compromises this season is the popularity of
Emilio Pucci and Pucci-like prints _ wild graphic designs that
combine colors such as pink and brown or orange, lime and purple,
said Cari Kerns, buyer for Leonard Rutan.
</P>
<P>
   Another color ploy is tie dye. Strong for summer and pool or
beach wear, now it is showing up in one-ply cashmere sweaters in,
say, cherry red and fuchsia, said Evelyn Gorman, owner of Mix
boutique.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to color, this season will see the return of one
color head to toe. Very matchy, matchy.
</P>
<P>
   Some store executives believe that with the brilliant colors of
spring and summer 2000, women may be looking forward to a more
subdued and sophisticated fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camel looks great as the new neutral,'' said Penne Weidig,
designer buyer for Tootsies. And although Weidig bought shades of
purple and green for fall, she was surprised to note that the first
color to sell was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a backlash to all the color,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
