</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLSHOI-DIRECTOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTRUCTURING AT THE BOLSHOI COSTS DIRECTOR HIS POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SOPHIA KISHKOVSKY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the latest twist to years of artistic and
administrative turmoil, Vladimir Vasilyev was dismissed as director
of the Bolshoi Theater, Russia's premier opera and ballet company,
in a decree signed on Monday by President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Vasilyev and a deputy, Vladimir Kokonin, were removed and their
posts eliminated. The theater will now be run by a general director
and an artistic director, who have not been officially named.
Vasilyev was not informed in advance but heard about the decision
on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   As head of entire Bolshoi Theater, Vasilyev, a former ballet
star, was responsible for both artistic and administrative policy.
He was appointed in 1995 by President Boris Yeltsin in a decision
meant to put an end to the divisive rule over the ballet company by
Yuri Grigorovich, a brilliant choreographer whose policies were
attacked as dictatorial.
</P>
<P>
   Although the timing of the decision was a surprise, with the
theater closed on Monday and both companies on tour, people
familiar with the Bolshoi had speculated for months about impending
changes there. Rumors had circulated that Valery Gergiev, the
conductor and artistic director of St. Petersburg's Mariinsky
Theater, would be charged with restoring the Bolshoi's faded glory.
</P>
<P>
   The likely appointees, however, are Anatoly Iksanov, a former
director of St. Petersburg's Bolshoi Drama Theater, who is not well
known to the public but is respected in theater circles, as general
director, and Gennady Rozhdestvensky, the conductor, as artistic
director. But Gergiev's Mariinsky is clearly a model for the new
direction. Russia's culture minister, Mikhail Shvydkoi, said the
main reason for reorganizing the theater's management was an
extremely expensive project to renovate the main Bolshoi building,
which is 143 years old and deteriorating significantly, and to
construct an adjacent sister theater.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, announced in December, with work on the main building
scheduled to begin in 2001, has drawn criticism. Parts of the plan
are half completed, and others have never been clearly defined. The
project is being supported by UNESCO, but agency officials have
complained of difficulties in dealing with Bolshoi bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater must be under the authority of those who are
responsible for the financial flow and are called upon to ensure
its reconstruction and construction,'' Shvydkoi told Moskovskiye
Novosti, a Moscow newspaper. ``For a minimum of the next five years
the key figure will be the administrative and not the artistic
director. Moreover, the volume of building and technological work
is so great that it is unlikely, I think, that a serious cultural
figure will risk taking on such responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Shvydkoi spoke of the realities of the market economy, which is
reshaping the way Russian cultural institutions function after
decades of state control and financing and years of post-Soviet
decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will restore the system of administration, which will be
headed by a manager,'' Shvydkoi said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's decree subordinates the theater to the Ministry of
Culture. According to Yeltsin's 1995 order, the Bolshoi
administration answered to the prime minister, which according to
critics meant that in effect it answered to no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theater demanded everything from everyone, but didn't have
to do anything for anyone,'' said Yaroslav Sedov, a music and dance
critic for the news magazine Itogi.
</P>
<P>
   Some, though, have criticized the culture minister for trying to
take too much under his control. Shvydkoi's ministry recently took
over the state film ministry.
</P>
<P>
   While critics could forgive Vasilyev his shortcomings as an
administrator, they were angry about his failure to revive the
Bolshoi artistically. His staging of ``Swan Lake'' was deemed a
flop, but what critics found even more dismaying was his inability
to introduce the new ideas he had promised when appointed.
</P>
<P>
   The touring success of the Bolshoi, critics say, was built on
the strength of highly talented dancers and fail-safe favorites
like ``Don Quixote,'' performed during this summer's U.S. tour. And
while foreigners know the Bolshoi primarily as a ballet company, in
Russia it has historically been revered for its opera. Critics hope
a new director will be able to restore that luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young opera directors need to be invited,'' said Vadim
Gayevsky, a ballet scholar and critic. ``There are wonderful,
unknown directors here. They won't stage nonsense, but real operas.
They will stage Prokofiev and Shostakovich. Right now there is only
one Prokofiev in the repertory. The revival must first of all be in
opera. If they open the door to the young generation, then
everything can become brilliant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
