<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-COPYRIGHT-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT BACKS COPYRIGHT ON RECONSTRUCTION OF ANCIENT SCROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that an
Israeli scholar had a copyright on his reconstruction of an
important Dead Sea Scroll and that his right had been violated by
an unauthorized early publication of his work.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who arguing the case said that it was the first in which
copyright law had been applied in court to a reconstruction of an
ancient document.
</P>
<P>
   Upholding the ruling of a lower court seven years ago, the
decision evoked what had been a heated debate over access to the
2,000-year-old scrolls, once restricted to a small group of
scholars but now open to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Discovered in the late 1940s and 1950s in caves near the Dead
Sea, the more than 800 scrolls, including the oldest known copies
of Old Testament books, are thought to have been written between
the second century B.C. and A.D. 70. Scholars believe they provide
valuable insights into the history of Judaism and the origins of
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Their study was dominated for years by a team of editors
overseen by the Israel Antiquities Authority, but mounting
criticism of restricted access to the manuscripts led to a wide
expansion of the circle of editors and the eventual release of
photographs of the scrolls to all scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ruling rejected an appeal by Hershel Shanks,
president of the Biblical Archaeology Society in the United States
and editor of Biblical Archaeology Review, a strong advocate of
free access to the scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Shanks appealed a Jerusalem District Court ruling that he had
infringed the copyright of the Israeli scholar, Dr. Elisha Qimron,
by publishing Qimron's reconstruction of a scroll without credit or
permission before the planned publication of the work.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction appeared in an appendix to Shanks' forward to
``A Facsimile Edition of the Dead Sea Scrolls,'' a collection of
more than 1,700 photographs of scroll fragments published in 1991
by his society in an effort to bring previously unpublished
documents to light.
</P>
<P>
   The editors, who were also sued by Qimron and joined the appeal,
were Robert H. Eisenman of California State University at Long
Beach and James M. Robinson of the Claremont Graduate School in
California.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The reconstruction was photocopied from a Polish journal, The
Qumran Chronicle, where it had been published as an anonymously
received manuscript after Qimron and John Strugnell, a Harvard
scholar who had also worked on the scroll, circulated drafts of
their work to colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Qimron spent more than a decade deciphering and reconstructing
the text of the scroll, known as MMT, initials of the Hebrew words
for ``Some Precepts of the Torah.''
</P>
<P>
   Arranging scroll fragments and filling in some 40 percent of the
restored text based on an analysis of the context, Qimron
reconstructed 121 lines of the manuscript, which lists differences
over religious laws that divided the sect that wrote the scrolls
from mainstream Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Shanks and his lawyers argued in court that Qimron was
uncovering an existing composition and could not claim a copyright
for reconstructing an ancient text he did not write.
</P>
<P>
   They asserted that granting Qimron a copyright could inhibit
further study of the reconstructed manuscript and harm academic
freedom by giving him a monopoly over what was rightly ``part of
the cultural heritage of the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Jacob Turkel wrote in the decision Wednesday that by
filling in gaps of missing text, deciphering and putting together
scroll fragments, Qimron had shown ``originality and creativity''
that earned him a copyright that had been infringed by Shanks.
</P>
<P>
   Qimron said the case had nothing to do with academic freedom and
everything to do with theft of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling showed that intellectual property also comes under
the commandment: Thou shalt not steal,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
