<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-DEFAMATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN CRITIC HIJACKS THE ADL PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    There was once a congregation in need of a clergyman, a
community leader. They advertised in the local paper and two
candidates applied. One was a rich and successful cleric while the
other was as poor as a church mouse. Each was given a chance to
address the congregation.
 &HT;    The first told the people to attend daily prayer groups and
weekend retreats. He said families that prayed together had a
better chance of staying together, and that God was needed in all
decisions.
 &HT;    After his speech the executive board met and declined to give
him the job. ``He is too rich and has nothing to do with his time _
so he prays all day and wants us to do the same. We need a regular
clergyman.''
 &HT;    The second candidate addressed the people. He said that all of
society's problems were caused by the lack of religion. We need to
integrate God into our daily lives. Movies and TV shows are too
corrupt, polluting our minds and the minds of our children.
 &HT;    Once again the board met and rejected the second candidate. ``He
is so poor and has nothing to do except find faults with our way of
life. Now he wants us to give up our lifestyles. We need a regular
person to be a clergyman.''
 &HT;    So the story goes and a third candidate was interviewed. When he
spoke he said, ``You don't like the rich, you don't like the poor.
You have all the excuses for not having religion. Well, I was once
rich and once poor. Now I am a regular guy and I believe that
religion is the greatest. It gives us the moral background and
strength to build our country. Faith is indeed the mother and hope
for our survival.'' Needless to say, he got the job.
 &HT;    This story comes to mind when I hear that some Jewish leaders,
especially Abraham Foxman of the Anti-Defamation League, have asked
the Democratic vice presidential candidate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
to desist from speaking about religion on the campaign trail.
 &HT;    In a letter to the senator, Foxman has accused Lieberman of
``overt expressions'' that cross the line between politics and
religion.
 &HT;    What chutzpah. Nothing could be further from the truth.
Lieberman, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush all
profess their faith and interject it in their political speeches.
When did we give up free speech? Is religious expression
anti-democratic? Do we need protection from leaders who are
religious?
 &HT;    I believe Foxman's actions are the antithesis of religious
freedom. By demanding that Lieberman stop expressing religious
sentiments, he hijacks the Anti-Defamation League program. Foxman
misrepresents the Jewish and non-Jewish religious needs of our
country.
 &HT;    He is guilty of the very crimes the Anti-Defamation League was
meant to combat.
 &HT;    There is no greater defamation than for a Jew in a leadership
position to tell another Jew, elected by the people of our glorious
country, that he can't speak his mind. Ironically, it sounds
anti-Semitic.
 &HT;    Asking elected officials to stop speaking their minds about
religion is tantamount to asking Congress to stop opening its
session with a prayer or to remove the slogan ``In God We Trust.''
 &HT;    Lieberman is the epitome of the American dream. Luckily, he
dreams with his eyes open. He is a regular guy, elected by the
people, for the people. He shouldn't be censored because of his
religious beliefs. It is stated in the U.S. Constitution that
``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof.''
 &HT;    Remember, God has granted us prosperity and peace because of our
religious beliefs and not in spite of them.
 &HT;    It was said by the great President Abraham Lincoln, ``We trust
sir, that God is on our side. It is more important to know that we
are on God's side.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.2000 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
