<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Aug. 31 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY (Atlanta) _ Dick Cheney said a military made strong in
the 1980s by Republican-led defense spending is now low on morale,
weapons and soldiers because of ``eight years of neglect and
misplaced priorities'' by the Clinton-Gore administration. Cheney,
the former defense secretary and now Republican vice presidential
candidate, said troops that were victorious in the Persian Gulf War
have been hurt by spending cuts ``far beyond any careful weighing
of the national interest.'' (Summary from wires) By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-VEEPS (Undated) _ Joseph Lieberman and Dick Cheney are
waging starkly different campaigns as they strike out on their own
for the first time since each party's national convention. Cheney,
who has confronted questions about his health, his voting record in
Congress and his multimillion-dollar retirement package from a
major oil services corporation, has largely kept a low profile,
staging small events, sticking to a safe speech script, generally
staying clear of reporters from national news organizations.
Lieberman has been a more active campaigner, drawing far larger
crowds and attracting _ indeed courting _ more media coverage. By
David Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CLINTON (Cartagena, Colombia) _ In a show of
solidarity, President Clinton visited Colombia Wednesday with $1.3
billion in U.S. aid aimed at propping up the South American
nation's fight against drugs, insurgents and recession. (Summary
from wires) By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PRIMARY (New York) _ It is a primary race that has spawned a
soap opera-like drama. The bitterness of a feud between two
Democrats in the 11th Congressional District in Brooklyn has not
only torn apart a longstanding relationship but has delivered some
of that anguish to the doorstep of other politicians and voters in
the borough. But it is also a race that has brought to the surface
simmering _ and often unspoken _ unease between black New Yorkers
whose roots are in the United States and those with Caribbean
heritage. By Jonathan P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Tianjin, China) _ The brick-walled Meite
Packaging factory at 208 Hongqi Street is nearly deserted now, its
managers and machines all hastily transferred over the last two
days to an isolated development zone. Although the closure had long
been planned, the precipitous departure was necessitated by an
extraordinary event: Last week, desperate Chinese workers fearing
layoffs kept six foreign managers from Meite's U.S. parent company
hostage in the factory for 40 hours, holding them incommunicado.
Taking foreign businessmen hostage is virtually unheard of in
China, despite the thousands of often fractious business
partnerships between Chinese and foreign companies that now exist
here. But the workers' frustrations that sparked this unusual
incident are extremely commonplace, leading to hundreds of worker
protests in the last 3 years. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA-POLITICS (Mogadishu, Somalia) _ Somalia finally has a
government, and its first president in nearly a decade arrived here
Wednesday escorted by at least 120 pickup trucks carrying well over
1,000 militia members armed with rifles, rocket launchers, even
double-barreled anti-aircraft guns. And just to be on the safe
side, the president wore a bullet-proof vest. Despite the fears,
the closest the new president, Abdikassim Salad Hassan, came to
harm was from Somalis a little too eager to show their affection.
For the new leaders of Somalia, elected during the last few weeks
at a peace conference in neighboring Djibouti, it was a hopeful
first step in restoring order and a central government to a nation
with neither since 1991. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT18,19,20.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ROBOTS-REPRODUCE (Undated) _ For the first time, computer
scientists have created a robot that designs and builds other
robots, almost entirely without human help or expertise. In the
short run, this advance could lead to a new industry of inexpensive
robots customized for specific tasks. In the long run _ decades at
least _ robots may one day be truly regarded as ``artificial life''
_ able to reproduce and evolve, building improved versions of
themselves. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT19.
</P>
</TEXT>
