<HEADER>
A6569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-LOVE&AMP;SEX-REVIEW-     08-30 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOVE&AMP;SEX-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NOT MUCH TO LOVE IN `LOVE &AMP; SEX'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Sex'' is an intermittently funny comedy about an angry,
unfulfilled tall person who has lots and lots of sex. The tall
person is Famke Janssen, who has good cheek bones and is very
persuasive as an angry, unfulfilled tall person. Especially the
tall part.
</P>
<P>
   Her character, Kate, is a writer for a women's magazine. When
asked to write an article about relationships, she writes one
instead about the intricacies of a certain sex act at which she
apparently excels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant draw from your own experience and relationships,'' her
editor tells her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I did,'' Kate replies.
</P>
<P>
   Kate has sex in restaurant men's rooms, and she engages in lots
of groping and smooching in public. None of this is particularly
sexy to watch.
</P>
<P>
   She has sex in lieu of relationships. This is told to us
repeatedly. Otherwise, we'd never guess there was any connection
between what one of her boyfriends calls her promiscuity and the
unhappiness she keeps talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The script doesn't really dramatize the ramifications. She talks
about ``living alone with four cats'' because she doesn't know what
makes relationships work. But we hardly ever see her outside of a
relationship. We see her with one boyfriend after another, starting
with her high school French teacher and progressing through to an
airhead actor, a painter, a guy who runs into her car, and on and
on.
</P>
<P>
   We never really get to know or to like Kate, because every time
we see her she's either wild with lust, crazy in love or grumpy. We
hardly ever even see her at work, even though the movie starts off
there with a work-related crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The movie _ the first for writer-director Valerie Breiman _
feels autobiographical in the same tired way that many first movies
and first novels feel drawn from life. It needed a mediating
intelligence to shape the raw material into a story that might
interest anyone whose initials aren't V.B.
</P>
<P>
   The painter, Adam Levy, is the boyfriend Kate is with the
longest. As played by Jon Favreau, he is a younger, stouter,
less-shaggy-haired Woody Allen. His personality, his gestures, even
his manner of speaking all are swiped from Allen, which makes it
only more painfully obvious that ``Annie Hall'' was the model for
this movie.
</P>
<P>
   That, like this, was a romantic comedy about a relationship
between two neurotics. It also was drawn from life and was narrated
by Allen at a point in the story where his relationship with the
title character was over. As Kate does in ``Love &AMP; Sex,'' he was
looking back, still in pain, but wiser for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Hall'' feels loosely plotted and casual, but this is
deceptive. Making a tightly constructed movie feel loose isn't
easy. Breiman's movie feels loose because it is. And having Kate
narrate the story (she's rehashing her past relationships for the
rewrite of that article) is a crutch. Kate tells us what the movie
should be showing us.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Allen's Alvie Singer character was sympathetic. We
laughed at his neurosis just as we laughed at his jokes. Janssen's
Kate, on the other hand, is a bitter pill. The movie is set in Los
Angeles, but she's so tightly wound she should be in New York. She
lashes out at the slightest insult.
</P>
<P>
   Janssen used to be a fashion model. As an actress, she's good at
filling in the outline of her character with primary colors. She
can do angry, harried, happy, elated and bored. But there's no
shading, no layering or blending of hues. Nothing peeks out from
beneath her thickly applied brush strokes because, one suspects,
there isn't anything to peek out.
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious pretty early how a movie like this will end. The
fun, if there is any, is in the getting there. Most of the fun
drains out of this movie in the first 30 minutes. After that, it
becomes all too obvious why Kate's boyfriends don't stick around
because we don't want to either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love &AMP; Sex''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Famke Janssen, Jon Favreau, Noah Emmerich
</P>
<P>
   Director-Screenwriter: Valerie Breiman
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Not rated. Despite the title, its sexual situations and
language are somewhat tame.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
