<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6573 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS0831-COX     08-30 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Led by McNabb, improving Eagles will be a tough test in Cowboys
opener
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It did not take Donovan McNabb long to become a
familiar face in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year quarterback from Syracuse has his own radio
show. He has a weekly TV show that is filmed at his home.
Billboards promoting the Philadelphia Eagles sport McNabb's image.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb's light-hearted shows are a hit with fans and teammates
alike. The most important football player in Philadelphia has
become the man.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, the same man Eagles fans booed when he was picked over
Texas icon Ricky Williams in the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. When Philadelphia and Dallas open the season
Sunday afternoon at Texas Stadium, McNabb's performance could spell
the difference between victory and defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who can create something on a busted play,'' Dallas
cornerback Ryan McNeil said Wednesday. ``Our job is to be
disciplined, to not let him get outside. If a play's busted, it
should become a sack or an interception.... Is he a difficult
player to bring down? Yeah. Should it be difficult if we do our
job? No.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb was the second player chosen in the 1999 draft, but was
not a major factor in Philadelphia's 5-11 season. He started six
games, completing 49 percent of his passes, including eight
touchdowns and seven interceptions. He is considered one of the
league's most mobile quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   When McNabb isn't spreading his charms on radio or TV, he is
scrambling to become the leader of an improving offense. Yet
getting him to open up about this week's opponent is like taking a
bone from a hungry dog.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday McNabb had nothing but positive remarks about the
Cowboys. The Cowboys have an ``established'' defensive line, he
said. When asked if he will exploit rookie cornerback Kareem
Larrimore, he said no.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb is smart enough to know any negative comments will become
bulletin-board material in the Cowboys locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't worry about what other people think (about the
Eagles),'' he said. ``Everyone has their own expectations. We have
goals and we'll do whatever we can to achieve those goals.''
</P>
<P>
   What are those goals?
</P>
<P>
   ``That something I keep to myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many football experts project the Eagles to have a breakout
season. The strength of their schedule ranks last in the league,
McNabb has matured into an effective quarterback, and former Tampa
Bay right tackle Jon Runyan has emerged as leader of the improved
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   There is pressure on Philadelphia to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get pressure no matter what,'' Eagles coach Andy Reid
said. ``That's part of the job, part of the game. That includes
players, coaches, the front offense, (newspaper) writers.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorable schedule is one reason the Eagles will be 4-1 after
five games, one Philadelphia columnist wrote. First place in the
NFC East will be at stake when the Eagles take on 4-1 Washington in
week six.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, that is how many people see the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter who we play (Sunday), but I think it
is a little bit of added incentive that some publications are
picking Philadelphia,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said. ``Starting
out in your own division adds a little significance to what you do
in preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles were picked to finish 9-7 and in second place in the
NFC East by Sports Illustrated writer Paul Zimmerman, better known
as Dr. Z. He had the Cowboys at 8-8, fourth in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Dr. Z,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Email: rcantu(at)statesman.com or 445-3953.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
