<SLUG> BC-GP-MILLS0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Pacific seeks buyers for tissue, pulp mills
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Georgia-Pacific plans to sell several pulp and tissue
mills, including its large Brunswick mill, as it moves away from
the commodity side of the business.
</P>
<P>
   At least 11 mills in seven states are on the auction block.
Georgia-Pacific, which recently notified mill workers about the
pending sales, could not identify potential buyers because of
confidentiality agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the divestiture planning process. We're proceeding
with discussions with potential buyers, but we've not made any
final decisions,'' said spokesman Ken Haldin.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the mills produce tissue and related products, including
a small plant in LaGrange that employs 130. Last month, the
Atlanta-based forest products giant said it planned to buy rival
Fort James and become the world's largest maker of toilet tissue
and paper towels. Georgia-Pacific agreed to get rid of at least
250,000 tons of tissue capacity to alleviate antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Fort James announcement, Georgia-Pacific also
said it would shed operations that don't fit its new strategy as a
marketer of branded household products.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Chairman and Chief Executive Pete Correll wants
to focus more on finished products instead of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
   The company seems ready to yield its status as the
second-largest maker of pulp, which is prone to large price swings.
Two of its largest pulp mills, in Brunswick and New Augusta, Miss.,
are up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Brunswick plant, which employs 770, makes 700,000 tons of
pulp a year and is the company's largest pulp mill. Haldin said
Georgia-Pacific couldn't comment on the status of three remaining
pulp operations in Arkansas, Maine and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the LaGrange plant, the tissue mills for sale
include plants in Arizona, Illinois, Indiana, New York and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific also wants to sell 5 million acres of timberland
to Seattle-based Plum Creek Timber Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership of pulp, paper and timber operations has shuffled
considerably this year due to several mega-mergers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Finnish-Swedish forestry group Stora Enso said
shareholders of U.S. Consolidated Papers have approved Stora Enso's
takeover bid. That creates the world's second-largest paper and
board producer behind International Paper-Champion International,
which merged earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
