<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE CONFIDENT ENTERING BELICHICK-WEIS ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ At the start of last season, Drew Bledsoe
was ranked among the best National Football League quarterbacks. By
season's end, he was playing like the worst NFL quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   And if the irony is that it was the Bill Belichick's defensive
schemes with the Jets at the halfway point of the season that
helped turn New England from a 6-2 team with hope to an
indescribably inept offensive team the second half of the season,
all the while setting Bledsoe on a downward spiral like no other in
his career, it is now Belichick and his coaching staff that Bledsoe
turns to for his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't go into the specifics of it because I don't want to
give away too much,'' Bledsoe said of offensive coordinator Charlie
Weis's system, ``but I think Charlie and I on offense believe in
some of the same things. I won't go into the specifics of exactly
what those things are, but one of the things that benefits Charlie
is that he has worked with a number of different (head coaches).''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe then chose to open up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie's also a younger guy who hasn't been around,'' Bledsoe
said. ``He doesn't have these ideas ingrained in his head from the
'70s and the '60s. He's a young guy who has his own ideas how to
attack somebody offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   A football Sherlock Holmes would not be needed to discern that
Bledsoe was thinking of his last coordinator, Ernie Zampese, who
was older and had derived many of his offensive schemes from former
Chargers coach Don Coryell and his air shows from the late 1970s
and early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   And that is a hint that Bledsoe might believe, as some did, that
Zampese's scheme was one of the reasons New England's offense
hitting rock bottom last season by early December. There were
Bledsoe bashers, blaming the quarterback for the offense's woes;
there were offensive line bashers, blaming the linemen for the
fierce physical throttling that Bledsoe took from defenders; and
there were Zampese bashers, who blamed the coordinator for not
adjusting to changing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Whomever and whatever was at fault, though, it was abundantly
clear the second half of the season that New England's offense was
not attacking anyone. Instead, it was reacting to opposing
defenses. Even worse, it seemed the New England coaches and
offensive players had never seen a blitz before. Teams blitzed the
Patriots at will, and rarely paid the as New England seldom
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe paid a price. The quarterback was hammered, both
physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, through those eight games, I looked forward to each
one, with the next one being better,'' Bledsoe said.
``Unfortunately, I didn't have success and we didn't have success
through that stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Some quarterbacks never recover their confidence after such a
beating. And confidence always has been Bledsoe's strongest weapon,
even stronger than his right arm. But Wednesday, Bledsoe reassured
all that what happened in the past is where it will stay . . . in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to do as an athlete in general, and as a
quarterback especially,'' he said, ``is forget what happened the
last play, the last game, the last season, and move on to the next
one. And I feel that has been a strength of mine, through high
school, through college, and in my NFL career. You know, move on
after the last one. That applies to my attitude toward last season
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is easier said than done won't be known until the
regular season opens Sunday against Tampa Bay and in the following
weeks. Bledsoe, for his part, said he went back and studied film of
those horrid offensive games the last half of the season, trying to
find out what had gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gone back and looked back at a number of those games,
and the bad plays in particular,'' he said. ``During the offseason,
I went back and watched those, as painful as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   As his eighth season as New England's quarterback opens, Bledsoe
said he's eager to begin anew. What is different from past Patriot
offenses, though, is that Bledsoe seems to have fewer weapons at
his disposal, and many more questions, especially with the
instability on the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The only true threat on offense appears to be wide receiver
Terry Glenn and ``it's important for us that Terry touch the ball
often,'' said Bledose. But New England again has question marks at
running back, and this time tight end is an unknown, for the first
time since Bledsoe has been in New England. Weis's many formations
may have to disguise many problems.
</P>
<P>
   By late last season, when some Patriot watchers were so aghast
at what passed for a New England offense that they were yearning
for the days of Tony Eason, or even Mike Taliaferro, others were
creating a ruckus by calling for Michael Bishop, then a rookie, to
play more. That brouhaha caused barely a dent in Bledsoe's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason that it's easy for me is because of the
situation I'm in,'' he said. ``I don't think there's been a
question for a long time who's the quarterback of this team. I
don't think that's ever come into question. And, for that reason,
if we bring in Mike for a few plays here and there and help our
team score points, I've got zero problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has done for the last five or six years, Bledsoe Wednesday
spoke confidently of the offense and the team's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we're capable of that,'' said Bledsoe when asked if
New England has a chance to make it to the Super Bowl. ``I really
believe that and I think everybody on this team does. I have
confidence and the team has confidence that we can go and compete
for a championship this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
