<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO DOWNPLAYS NO-HITTER STATUS, BUT SOME WONDER... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro says it's no big deal, that a no-hitter doesn't define a
pitcher's career, and, as usual, he is correct. Otherwise, we'd be
saying that such pitchers as Grover Cleveland Alexander, Lefty
Grove, Dizzy Dean, Steve Carlton, Early Wynn, Robin Roberts,
Ferguson Jenkins, Whitey Ford, and Don Sutton _ Hall of Famers, all
_ would have tarnished resumes.
</P>
<P>
   No-hitters are freaky. Anybody, absolutely anybody, can pitch a
major league no-hitter if the sun, moon, and stars are in the
proper alignment and baseballs are hit in the proper direction.
Alva ``Bobo'' Holloman threw a no-hitter in his first big league
start May 6, 1953. He won two more big-league games before fading
into obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Was Ed Halicki a great pitcher? He threw a no-hitter. So did
Juan Nieves. And Bo Belinsky makes three.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the chances are that if you are a certifiably great pitcher
you will throw one, sooner or later. If you're Vida Blue, it's
sooner. Vida was 21 when he no-hit Minnesota Sept. 21, 1970. But if
you're Warren Spahn, it's later. The great Spahnie was 39 and a
10-time 20-game winner when he no-hit the Phillies Aug. 18, 1960.
He apparently liked the feeling so much he felt compelled to throw
a second no-no 13 months later, this one against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Cy Young threw three, including a perfect game. Walter Johnson
had one, against our Red Sox. Bob Feller had three. Christy
Mathewson had one, as did Carl Hubbell, Dazzy Vance, Ted Lyons, Bob
Lemon, Juan Marichal, Bob Gibson, Jim Palmer, and Tom Seaver.
Catfish Hunter had a perfect game. So did Jim Bunning as a Phillie.
He also no-hit the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't think a knuckleballer would throw a no-hitter, but
Hoyt Wilhelm and Phil Niekro each had one.
</P>
<P>
   Dizzy Dean never threw one, but brother Paul did in the second
game of an Ebbets Field doubleheader in which Ol' Diz had thrown a
three-hitter in the opener. ``Shucks,'' drawled, Diz, ``If I'da
knowed Paul was gonna throw one, I'da throwed one, too.'' Or words
to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Way up in some unimaginable realm, Sandy Koufax had three no-nos
and a perfect game in four years. Then there's Nolan Ryan, who was
the personification of a guy with ``no-hit stuff.'' He retired with
seven, the last in 1991, when he was 44.
</P>
<P>
   Great. But can anyone explain how Bill Stoneman (54-85 lifetime)
threw two?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even though Hideo Nomos and Kent Merckers and Chris
Bosios can throw no-hitters, we are coming up to the 35th
anniversary of both the last no-hitter thrown by a Red Sox pitcher
and the last no-hitter thrown by anyone at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone tells you he or she saw the last no-hitter at Fenway,
demand proof. On Sept. 16, 1965, the  &UR; afternoon &LR;  crowd was 2,370
when 22-year-old Dave Morehead no-hit the Cleveland Indians to
raise his season's record to 10-16. That's correct: 2,370, broken
down as follows: 1,247 paid, 1,019 guests, and 104 Ladies Day.
</P>
<P>
   Morehead was a kid from San Diego _ Ted Williams's high school,
no less _ who had a good, live fastball, a knee-buckling curve, and
absolutely no command of either pitch. He had come up in 1963, even
though he wasn't really ready. On those Red Sox teams, any live arm
was a good arm.
</P>
<P>
   His mound opponent on that September afternoon was Luis Tiant,
who had allowed just one hit through five. Then Jim Gosger singled
and Dalton Jones tripled for the first run. An inning later, Lee
Thomas, now a Red Sox executive, hit his 20th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Morehead had been working with pitching coach Mace Brown on a
more compact delivery, and on this occasion everything was in
synch. He had walked Rocky Colavito on a 3-2 pitch in the second,
but there were no other base runners as the game moved into the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland skipper Birdie Tebbetts wasn't going down easily. He
pinch hit Bill Davis for Pedro Gonzalez to conclude the eighth (a
fly to center) and then came back with three more pinch hitters in
the ninth. Larry Brown, batting for Duke Sims, lined to short. Lou
Clinton (a former Red Sox), batting for Tiant, flied to center. One
out to go.
</P>
<P>
   Tebbetts's choice to bat for Dick Howser was the crafty, pesky,
irritating, and downright dangerous Venezuelan Vic Davalillo, who
was just the type of speedy player you don't want up in a situation
like this. The count went to 0-2, at which point Tebbetts called
time in order to have a chat with his batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take anything close,'' he ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years after the fact, Tebbetts, good baseball man that he
was, was carrying the memory of Dale Mitchell being called out by
Babe Pinelli on a borderline pitch to complete Don Larsen's World
Series perfect game. He obviously thought the pitch should have
been ruled ball three. He assumed that Bill McKinley would
similarly ring up his man on anything remotely looking like a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch came and Davalillo tapped it back to the box on one
hop. The ball hit off the heel of Morehead's glove and rolled a
foot or two toward the third-base line. Morehead scrambled after
it, and came up throwing. It was a very low throw, but Thomas
scooped it, with Davalillo, according to the Globe's venerable
Roger Birtwell, ``20 inches, perhaps less,'' from the bag.
</P>
<P>
   What did the no-hitter mean for Dave Morehead's career? Nothing.
He lost his last two decisions in '65, and he eventually came up
with the proverbial sore arm. He would only win 12 more games. The
man who one overly exuberant friend of mine believed to be the
``righthanded Sandy Koufax'' finished his eight-year career with a
record of 40-64.
</P>
<P>
   But he had his no-hitter, despite Birdie Tebbetts's best efforts
to stop him. ``Nobody who saw this game can ever say Morehead
didn't earn it,'' Birdie chirped.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Billy Rohr came within one out of a no-hitter
in Yankee Stadium. Rick Wise likewise came within an out of a no-no
in 1976. Marty Pattin, Steve Renko, and Frank Viola have all gotten
through eight no-hit innings. But no one, not Tiant, not Roger
Clemens, not even Pedro Martinez has been able to throw one for the
Red Sox since Morehead did it nearly 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A no-hitter doesn't change anything or even mean it was anything
more than a reasonably well-pitched game. You could, in theory,
throw a perfect game with 27 line drive outs. Would we have ranked
Tuesday night's performance ahead of the 17-strikeout one-hitter
against New York that wasn't even a shutout? Uh-uh. But I've got to
believe Pedro still wants one. He may not know who Bobo Holloman
was, but he's aware of Jose Jiminez. No way he wants that chump
with a no-no on his dossier while Pedro is still waiting to get one
for himself.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing we ask, Pedro, is to make sure you do it at home.
Oh, and it would sure help out us press guys if you'd do it in the
daytime. Finally, a personal note. Wait till next year, OK? I'd
sure hate to be in Sydney when _ and it is when, not if _ you do
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
