<SLUG> BC-MSN-AOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MSN TO OFFER HIGH-SPEED INTERNET ACCESS THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Making another run at America Online Inc.,
Microsoft Corp. will begin offering high-speed Internet access in
the fall, coupled with a makeover of its MSN online portal.
</P>
<P>
   The project, dubbed ``MSN 2001'' within the company, is aimed
squarely at luring Web surfers away from AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to leapfrog AOL,'' said Mike Nichols, MSN's
product manager, Wednesday. ``We think we have a product that is
superior to AOL.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL, the nation's largest Internet service provider, has more
than 23 million users. MSN has just 3 million, despite having been
in existence since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   MSN is also targeting an estimated 14 million first-time Web
users who are expected to sign up for Internet access over the next
12 months. By emphasizing simplicity and ease of use, AOL has
traditionally fared well with first-time users.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, based in Redmond, Wash., hopes to mimick AOL's
success by revamping its portal _ to be called MSN Explorer _ to
make it friendlier for new users. Colorful, rounded icons will
replace plain-text tabs, making MSN look more like a browser and
less like a Web site. The browser will contain more customized
information, such as local weather reports and news. A multimedia
player on the lower left hand corner will let users listen to
Internet radio or watch videos while surfing the Web. MSN's instant
messaging will also let users make free long-distance calls over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks very good,'' said Bruce Kasrel, senior analyst at
Forrester Research in Cambridge. ``I'm impressed. But it's going to
take more than a good browser to get people to switch'' from AOL.
</P>
<P>
   MSN hopes to one-up AOL by offering high-speed Internet access
in major metropolitan areas, including Boston, starting this fall.
The company is currently testing the high-speed service in Boston,
San Francisco, and Dallas. The vast majority of AOL customers rely
on dial-up access, which is considerably slower.
</P>
<P>
   Access to MSN will be provided via digital subscriber lines
(DSL) by a network of local providers contracted by MSN. Consumers
in outlying areas with no access to DSL will have access through
high-speed satellite service from Gilat Satellite Networks Ltd., an
Israeli company in which Microsoft has invested $50 million.
Nichols declined to say how much MSN will charge for high-speed
service.
</P>
<P>
   Despite massive investments by Microsoft over the years, MSN has
languished behind AOL. Part of the problem has been Microsoft's
ambivalent, piecemeal approach to the Internet. MSN started five
years ago as a proprietary service with no access to the Web.
Later, it provided Web access, but then began to produce original
entertainment, an expensive gambit that failed to add substantial
numbers of new subscribers. Meanwhile, Microsoft launched Web sites
and services that were not well integrated, such as Hotmail,
Expedia, MSNBC, Gaming Zone, and Money Central.
</P>
<P>
   The new MSN promises to ``put these loose offerings together and
make it much more easy and seamless for users,'' Nichols said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
