<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY EXPERT SEES LEAK WITH MICROSOFT OFFICE SUITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you read a document prepared with the popular
Microsoft Word program, the document may also be reading you.
</P>
<P>
   Computer security expert Richard Smith says he's found a feature
in Word that allows a document to transmit information about the
person reading it over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The same feature exists in other parts of Microsoft Corp.'s
Office software suite, including the Excel spreadsheet program and
the PowerPoint presentation graphics program. Documents created
with these programs, if used on a machine connected to the
Internet, can transmit the ``IP address'' of the reader's computer.
By entering the IP address in an online directory, it's possible to
find out the owner of the address.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Smith said a government agency could embed a ``Web
bug'' in a Microsoft Word document in order to keep track of where
it's being read.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose a whistle-blower leaks a copy of the document to a
Boston Globe reporter. If the reporter reads the document on a
computer attached to the Internet, a copy of his IP address is
instantly relayed to the government agency. By running an IP
address look-up, ``They could know (that) somebody at the Boston
Globe is reading this document,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Culp, of Microsoft Corp.'s Security Response Center,
described the issue as ``much ado about very little.''
</P>
<P>
   Culp said that Smith has not discovered a security bug in Word.
Instead, it's an inevitable consequence of making the program
capable of interacting with the Internet, he said. Whenever a
program exchanges data over the Internet, it must send out its IP
address in order to receive a reply. All Internet-enabled office
software programs, from Microsoft or any other firm, will do the
same thing, Culp said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, of Brookline, Mass., agreed other products probably
transmit IP addresses but said he hasn't tested them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
