A6590 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-MACK-BOS &LR;      08-30 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERRI L. MACK, 40; GRAPHIC DESIGNER, CONSULTANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sherri Lynne Mack of Boston, a graphic designer and
management consultant, died Friday at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center after a three-week illness. She was 40.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Seattle, she studied communications at Santa Clara
University in California, where she joined the Delta Sigma Theta
sorority. After graduation she pursued her master's degree in media
and communications management at Emerson College in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived in Boston in 1983, she became active in the
public-service activities of the Boston chapter of her sorority,
which included community outreach through Crittenton-Hastings
House, Project Homeless, Jabberwock, and the Social Action
Committees.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mack was also an organizer of The Supper Club, a group of
black professional women.
</P>
<P>
   She had a great love of books and reading, and wanted people
with special needs to have the same pleasure. For several years she
was a volunteer reader for the Commonwealth of Massachusetts
Commission for the Blind. In this role she would record novels and
textbooks for visually impaired people.
</P>
<P>
   Her spirit of volunteerism led her to share her talents as a
graphic designer and desktop publisher with the People's Voice
Newspaper. She was also a member of the President's Circle at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mack's experience as a self-employed management consultant
enabled her to teach desktop publishing, Web and graphic design at
various adult education centers in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   She was active at Bethel African Methodist Church in Boston's
Jamaica Plain neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her parents, Daniel and Sandra Mack of San Jose,
Calif; a brother, Ronald Miles of San Jose; a sister, Lori (Melvin)
Howard of Oakland, Calif.; and her two grandmothers, Wilma D. Wiles
of Altadena, Calif., and Seberia Mack of Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
