<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-SALINGER-MEMOIR-ABRID     08-30 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALINGER-MEMOIR-ABRIDGED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALINGER'S DAUGHTER WRITES OF HER FATHER'S OBSESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A longer version slugged SALINGER-MEMOIR is also moving.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT37, 38, 39 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ J.D. Salinger's daughter has written a book that
reveals previously unknown and deeply intimate aspects of the
famously private writer's life, including that he fears the female
body, abstained from sex as a young man to achieve enlightenment
and drank urine as a home remedy.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Margaret, also writes in her memoir, ``Dream
Catcher,'' that her father, who was a counterintelligence agent in
World War II, was briefly married to a woman he had arrested as a
Nazi Party functionary.
</P>
<P>
   And when he was a teen-ager, Salinger discovered that his mother
was not Jewish, as he had been brought up to believe, but Irish
Catholic, his daughter writes. The book is due out Sept. 6 from
Pocket Books.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger, in an intervew at the Plaza Hotel in New York,
said she wrote the book to make sense of her strange childhood,
adding that she is willing to take the risk that her father might
not speak to her again. She has taken precautions _ like staying at
the hotel under an assumed name _ against the possibility that her
father will try to stop her from publishing the memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Salinger, 81, who has not published anything since 1965 and has
not spoken publicly for years, is so determined in his seclusion
that he successfully delayed the publication of a biography because
the writer had sought to use some of his letters.
</P>
<P>
   Her father was pathologically self-centered, Ms. Salinger says.
Nothing could interrupt his work, which he likened to a quest for
enlightenment. He was also abusive toward her mother, Claire
Douglas, Ms. Salinger says, keeping her a virtual prisoner in his
house in Cornish, N.H., refusing to allow her to see friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger said that when Ms. Douglas was pregnant, her father
found her abhorrent. She said that since her parents rarely had
sex, she feels her birth was almost an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger also says that when she was 13 months old, her
mother planned to kill her and commit suicide, and later did indeed
burn the house down. Ms. Salinger said her mother denied setting
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Douglas is now a Jungian analyst in California and ``a
terrific grandma,'' Ms. Salinger said. She did not respond to
messages left on her answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her father pursued Scientology, homeopathy and
Christian Science, drank urine and sat in an orgone box, Ms.
Salinger writes. And he spoke in tongues, fasted until he turned
greenish and as an older man had pen pal relationships with
teen-age girls, she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents divorced in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Does her father know about her book? ``He does now,'' said Ms.
Salinger, because of newspaper articles. Has she spoken to him
since then? She laughs. ``I may be 44,'' she said, ``but I still
don't want to get yelled at.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``it's not unusual at all to not speak for several
months,'' said Ms. Salinger. ``We're not officially estranged,''
she said. ``What other people might call weird is just regular for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father loves her, she said, but ``he probably hates my guts,
too, I would say, operatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinger's agent, Phyllis Westberg of Harold Ober Associates,
said he would not comment on Ms. Salinger's book.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger refused to give the name of her husband or son, or
give her son's age. She said she wrote ``Dream Catcher'' because
``I was absolutely determined not to repeat with my son what had
been done with me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one moment that stands out above all, she said. ``It is
so horrible, it's so powerful.'' When she was pregnant and sick,
instead of offering help, her father ``said I had no right to bring
a child into this lousy world,'' she writes, ``and he hoped I was
considering an abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   From her Aunt Doris, her father's sister who is six years older
and in failing health, Ms. Salinger said she learned about her
father's childhood as Jerome David Salinger, son of Miriam and Sol
Salinger, who became a prosperous food merchant in New York. Jerome
was the center of his mother's life, Ms. Salinger said her aunt
told her. But Miriam was also overprotective. Salinger once wrote
in a letter to Hemingway that his mother walked him to school until
he was 24, Ms. Salinger said.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II he was a counterintelligence agent assigned
to the Twelfth Regiment of the Fourth Division, interrogating
POW's. He served in the most brutal campaigns of the European
theater, including D-Day and the Battle of the Bulge. In 1945 in
Germany he was hospitalized for ``battle fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the book's surprises, Ms. Salinger writes that her
father arrested a young Nazi Party functionary, Sylvia, then
married her. The marriage was brief, and forever after he referred
to her as Saliva.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger's parents met in 1950 when Claire Douglas was about
16 and Salinger about 31. At the time Ms. Douglas and Salinger met,
he abstained from sex, her mother told Ms. Salinger, because he was
studying with an Indian mystic who taught that it interfered with
enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Just months before her high school graduation, Ms. Douglas
married Salinger and moved with him to Cornish. Ms. Douglas told
her daughter that he demanded elaborate meals and that the sheets
had to be laundered twice weekly, though there was no heat or hot
water. When her mother became pregnant, Ms. Salinger writes, she
fell into ``a suicidal depression when she realized that her
pregnancy only repulsed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger was born in 1955, and her father, she says, seemed
more comfortable in the magic world of childhood. Her imaginary
friends were real to him, too, she says, as were the characters in
his books. ``The world of fiction and reality were very blurred,''
she writes.
</P>
<P>
   But, her mother felt ``jealousy and rage over my replacement of
her in my father's affections.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960 the Salingers had a son, Matthew, who is now an actor
and producer in California. Last month The Sunday Times of London
quoted him as saying of his sister: ``I guess she's got a lot of
anger. But to write a book just isn't right. It's kind of
pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salinger says she does not believe he said it: ``I love my
brother dearly. It just doesn't sound like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach him by telephone or through friends were not
successful.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, Salinger had a relationship with Joyce
Maynard, a journalist, who was two years older than his daughter.
Salinger induced Ms. Maynard to leave college and live in isolation
with him, Ms. Maynard wrote her 1998 memoir, ``At Home in the
World'' (Picador, 1998), which included details of her romance with
Salinger when she was 18 and he was 53.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Salinger it was a repeat of his relationship with her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Today Salinger is married to his third wife, Colleen, a nurse,
some 50 years younger than he. Ms. Salinger writes that her father
berates Colleen, as he did her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Salinger still lives in Cornish. He is still writing, and lives
on royalties. ``Catcher in the Rye'' sells ``at least'' 250,000
copies annually, his daughter said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she did not know why her father has refused to publish
his work. ``My aunt thinks he can't stand any criticism,'' she
said. ``He sure doles it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
