<HEADER>
A6593 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SOMALIA-POLITICS-ART-     08-30 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOMALIA-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRIVING IN SOMALIA, NEW PRESIDENT WILL TRY TO GOVERN AFTER YEARS
OF CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT18, 29 and 30 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. For descriptions of photos, see
BC-SOMALIA-PHOTO-ADVISORY-NYT. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time
rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOGADISHU, Somalia _ Somalia finally has a government, and its
first president in nearly a decade arrived here Wednesday escorted
by at least 120 pickup trucks carrying more than 1,000 militiamen
armed with rifles, rocket launchers, even double-barreled
anti-aircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
   And just to be on the safe side, the president wore a
bullet-proof vest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fears, the closest the new president, Abdikassim
Salad, came to harm was from Somalis a little too eager to show
their affection _ and overjoyed that their country might finally be
leaving behind years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Salad arrived at midday a downtown soccer stadium packed with
tens of thousands of people cheering and waving sprigs of small red
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to speak. But after just a few words, he was nearly
crushed by well-wishers, forcing him to flee the stadium, jostled
around the eye of a dangerous storm of happy people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new president _ too much they like him,'' said Sandal
Agdige, 31, an unemployed driver who had just pried himself loose
from the swarming crowds at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For the new leaders of Somalia, who were chosen during the past
few weeks at a peace conference in Djibouti, the country to the
northwest, it was a hopeful first step in restoring order and a
central government to a nation with neither since 1991. The
conference had been organized by Djibouti's president, Ismail Omar
Guelleh, who also spent much of his nation's meager resources on
it, eager to see stability brought to the region.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate worry for Salad's safety arose because of the
warlords who have divided power in the nine years of chaos, and who
in recent weeks have vowed to oppose the new government. Some had
said they would even physically block the arrival of its new
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing happened on this first day. Some militiamen aligned
with the warlords even bucked their leaders to greet Salad, who
said his first day back home as president convinced him that this
new government would work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Somalia are fed up with wars, violence, killing,
tribalism,'' said Salad, 58, in an interview later in the calm of
his hotel room in north Mogadishu. ``You have seen the people, many
thousands, hundreds of thousands, of people. No one can have fear
if he is surrounded by such well meaning crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For some in the entourage that flew in on two chartered
airplanes from Djibouti _ many of whom had not been to Somalia for
10 years or more _ it was a moment of high emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must be honest with you, this was really overwhelming,''
said Ali Khalif Galaydh, also 58, a former government official who
left Somalia in 1982 and has since taught at Harvard and Syracuse
universities. Khalif, a member of the new Somali assembly and a
leading candidate to be prime minister, added that the reception
showed ``how hungry people are for good news.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was only a tentative victory, and a reminder of the
huge job before Somalis, whose last government crumbled in civil
war when its long-time dictator, Siad Barre, fell from power in
1991. Three of the main warlords in Mogadishu happened to be out of
town, meeting with the president of Yemen, who was trying to
persuade them to support Salad. But they remain a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the warlords end up on Salad's side, the streets that he
drove through Wednesday served as one vivid indication of how
scarred Somalia remains from its civil war and a later attempt by
the United Nations to feed the hungry in the early 1990s. On one
main road, twisted and rusty cars are piled up along the median. On
another lay the skeleton of a United Nations armored vehicle. Trash
is scattered everywhere, in a once-beautiful sea-side city with no
central electricity, water, police or schools. The outside world,
exhausted with Somalia, has not been eager to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very difficult task,'' Salad said in the interview.
``We need everything. Every sector is in shambles.'' In fact,
Salad's presidency is itself but an idea. He does not even have an
office to work out of, much less an organized army to command or
any government ministers to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Salad's transitional government must still deal with
the leaders of two autonomous regions in the north who have refused
to recognize his authority. The regions, Somaliland and Puntland,
had gone their own way and established relatively peaceful pockets
outside of the violence of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new president must also contend with the nearly impossible
expectations of Somalis, who seem to believe a government will be
panacea for all their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a job,'' said Aweys Salad, 18, no relation to the
president, at the stadium. ``When I get a government I will get
everything I need. I want an education. We need education.
Education is the light of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Salad was elected during the weekend in an unusual peace
conference of more than 2,000 Somalis _ a cross-section of Somalis
and representatives of every clan _ who had gathered in Djibouti
for five months of touchy negotiations. During that time, they
managed to create a national charter _ something like a
transitional constitution _ and chose a temporary capital, the
southern city of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Salad was chosen by a 245-member assembly also formed in
Djibouti, which will sit for three years as a transitional
government before national elections. The conference purposely
sidelined the warlords, one reason for their opposition. Though
Somalis often talk about the dangers of clan _ the tribal groupings
that have divided the nation _ one of Salad's main qualifications
was, in fact, his background: He is a leader of the Hawiye clan,
more specifically the Habr Gidir subclan, that dominates in
Mogadishu, the main area of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   But Salad, a trim man with still black hair and a greying beard,
had also campaigned on a law-and-order platform attractive to many
Somalis. He has close ties to the Islamic courts _ with their own
police and jails _ that were established in the past few years. And
he has support among Mogadishu's increasingly influential business
community, which pushed for peace as a bottom line for making
money.
</P>
<P>
   He also gained credibility in the election because, unlike some
candidates, he lives in Mogadishu, and in recent years had overseen
a broad effort to re-unite the Hawiye. He is said to be personally
tough and dogged, and, in the interview, he outlined an ambitious
vision for transforming Somalia from a sick state into one of the
leaders of the Horn of Africa, itself a region of instability.
</P>
<P>
   Salad's critics point to his long career in the Barre regime,
which he served for the better part of 20 years in a succession of
top posts, including minister of the interior. Saying he committed
no crimes, Salad contended that Somalis understand that his
generation is the last with actual experience running a government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the people of Somalia to judge,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wednesday, Somalis said they were fervently behind Salad. Many
paraded the streets with photocopies of a flattering portrait
pasted to signboards. Children waving branches chanted: ``Who is
the winner? Abdikassim!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very happy,'' said Okash Sugow Mohamed, 29, holding a
flower in front of a truck filling with people waiting to see Salad
at the stadium. ``Before our survival was very low. Today, I think
I become full.''
</P>
<P>
   Salad plans to stay in Somalia until Saturday, before leaving
for Egypt to meet with the Arab League, then to New York to visit
the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
