<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6597 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CORIOLANUS-THEATER-$A     08-30 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORIOLANUS-THEATER-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARRIOR WHOSE ONLY CHARM IS HIS LACK OF IT
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 (Editors: Also See SHAKESPEARE-FIENNES-THEATER)  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among Shakespeare's tragic heroes, Coriolanus stands apart. The
others seduce us. This one _ Rome's greatest warrior turned Rome's
fiercest scourge _ scorns even to try. When his city casts him out,
he joins forces with the enemy, sparing his compatriots not out of
clemency but out of deference to his gorgon mother.
</P>
<P>
   The play to which he lends his name, though praised by a
handful, is loved by few. Nor does his character find many
defenders. Yet as a comrade in arms, the man shines like a beacon:
To the courageous, a guardian angel; to the craven, a holy terror.
</P>
<P>
   Who forgives Coriolanus his righteousness, or his vicious
temper? In the field, against the enemy Volscians, he takes no end
of punishment, expecting no special credit (most certainly not
panegyrics) for his matchless deeds, and that is a sort of hubris.
But what does his tragic flaw amount to beside the self-lacerating
intellect of Brutus, who slaughters his beloved Caesar?
</P>
<P>
   Beside the ambition of Macbeth, who dispatches a sainted
monarch? Beside the jealousy of Othello, who murders a blameless
wife? Hamlet's indecision, Mark Antony's self-indulgence and King
Lear's vanity cause no end of calamity, to themselves and others.
Still, we suspend judgment, captivated by their gift for metaphor
or philosophical speculation. Coriolanus goes his way alone; his
soul has little music, maybe none.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Almeida Theater Company's production of
``Coriolanus,'' directed by Jonathan Kent, which begins
performances at the Brooklyn Academy of Music on Sept. 9, will
challenge entrenched opinion. The title role is entrusted to Ralph
Fiennes, the protagonist also of the Almeida's ``Richard II,''
which will alternate with ``Coriolanus.'' Not that Fiennes is an
actor to trade on easy charm. Yet deep within his tense, careworn
stage persona runs a streak of pathos that exercises a powerful
seduction of its own. In London, at the point in Act V where
Shakespeare's stage direction has Coriolanus holding his mother
``by the hand, silent,'' Fiennes grabbed her hand, kneeling and
sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's departures in ``Coriolanus'' from his standard
practice are radical _ so much so that studies of the play tend
reflexively to switch focus from figure to ground. The clashes
between patrician and plebeian at the center of the tragedy are
indeed in an epic class by themselves: An anatomy of the body
politic at its most disordered, conducted with an icily impartial
hand. At a historic production in Paris in the 1930s, riots broke
out between Fascists and Communists. Each side was convinced that
Shakespeare was affirming the justice of their own party line and
exposing the bad faith of their opponents. (Or was it the other way
around?)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Against the excitement of the crowd scenes and in the absence of
poetically arresting language, what becomes of those specifically
tragic stirrings of compassion for the hero, which Aristotle
ascribed to pity and terror (and Shakespeare to woe and wonder)?
The view of Frank Kermode in the Riverside Shakespeare epitomizes
received wisdom: ``We never feel that the author allows the hero to
come very close to him or to us, but in spite of his keeping
Coriolanus at a critical arm's length, Shakespeare can rarely have
more fully extended his powers than he does here.''
</P>
<P>
   At critical arm's length? Seen another way, not even in the
scarcely endurable ordeals of the outcast Lear does Shakespeare
probe a heart more feelingly. In fact, in certain respects, his
achievement in ``Coriolanus'' is more extraordinary than in
``Lear.'' Lear's existential trajectory teaches him (and us) what
it means to be a human being against the backdrop of indifferent,
unfeeling Nature. It is a lesson the outcast sovereign learns at a
few seconds to midnight, at a threshold of mortality (``fourscore
and upward''), from which the playwright, the actor and presumably
the vast majority of viewers feel safely detached. Any
identification with him (if identification is quite the word)
remains contemplative, theoretical.
</P>
<P>
   In Coriolanus, by contrast, we encounter a man of action in the
prime of life, a condition that most of us (wishfully or
accurately) equate with our own. Yet even at the pinnacle of
autonomy, he hovers at the edge of the abyss: A man yet still a
boy, a law unto himself yet, to his credit. of ``woman's
tenderness'' in the face of the wife and son he has tried in vain
to banish from his heart. Humbling, even humiliating knowledge,
frightening to witness. Kermode calls Coriolanus a ``beast-god,''
meaning a monster. Our brother, rather. In the entire tragic canon,
Shakespeare tells no sadder story, or one that cuts closer.
</P>
<P>
   For all the reviled hero's faults, much counts in his favor.
Presumption and malicious detraction rile him, but he acknowledges
good will, loses bets like a gentleman and praises his Volscian
nemesis without reserve. He invades an enemy city single-handed,
but leaves the room rather than hear his deeds praised. He knows no
greed or envy. Only under extreme provocation does he speak up in
his own defense. His affections run deep, as evidenced when he
dries his wife's tears coming home from the wars. As for his
refusal to coax or charm by diplomacy or fine language, this, too,
redounds to his credit. Like Cordelia, Lear's true-hearted youngest
daughter, rejected for plain speaking, he lacks ``That glib and
oily art/ To speak and purpose not,'' and finds an eloquence in
silence _ his most revealing moments are seldom his loudest. His
rare sallies into metaphor _ in exile he gives his address as ``th'
city of kites and crows'' _ are terse and often harrowingly to the
point.
</P>
<P>
   The embodiment of the forces that destroy Coriolanus from within
is Volumnia, his mother, unlike any other in Shakespeare. Romeo and
Juliet have mothers, for all the good it does them. Richard III has
one, for all the good it does her. Lady Macbeth seems to be one,
though no offspring are in evidence, and of the specters that haunt
her husband, childlessness torments him most. Of Shakespeare's
handful of mothers with grown sons to manage (notably Gertrude, in
``Hamlet,'' and the Countess of Rossillion, in ``All's Well That
Ends Well''), Volumnia alone shows the muscle for the job.
</P>
<P>
   To all Rome, her son is Coriolanus, a name fresh-earned in blood
by the walls of the enemy town of Corioles. To Volumnia, who
flutters out to meet him as the troops return, all the while
thanking the gods for the wounds and scars he bears, he is ``my boy
Martius.'' Tullus Aufidius, general of the Volscians, on whose
mercy Coriolanus casts himself when the Roman rabble drives him
out, calls him ``boy,'' too, with lethal consequences. ``When blows
have made me stay, I fled from words,'' the hero confesses early
on. And words, not swords, are the weapons that destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Volumnia, and in part for her son, her powers
do not work at a distance. The first of their two pitched battles
of will occurs in the wake of his reluctant campaign for the office
of consul, a political honor incompatible with his temperament or
his talents. Custom demands that a candidate stand forth publicly
in a ``gown of humility,'' showing passers-by his war wounds and
soliciting their votes, or ``voices.'' Coriolanus submits and wins
election, but his half-heartedness and sarcasm as he goes through
the distasteful motions give the Machiavellian tribunes of the
people all the ammunition they need to nullify the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I had children's voices?'' the outraged consul-elect
demands, characteristically counting on men to live up to their
word. Before long, the mob is baying for his blood. The only hope
for Coriolanus at this pass would be to make a calculated show of
contrition, a self-inflicted disgrace he consents to only after
Volumnia has played the most powerful card in her manipulative
deck: The threat of walking out.
</P>
<P>
   From the strategic point of view, she has only been making
sense. To her son, the appeal to expediency spells utter betrayal,
a trampling of the very values by which she has taught him to live
his life. He predicts that he will botch the charade (Shakespeare's
allusions to actors are seldom complimentary), and, sure enough, he
does. Once back in the public world of men, it takes the tribunes
the single word of ``traitor'' to goad Coriolanus to frenzy, with
his banishment the speedy result.
</P>
<P>
   When mother and son meet for the last time, he is leading the
Volscian army against Rome. Does this make him a traitor? Readers
have said so, but not the appalled patricians in the play, who see
his revenge as deserved retribution. Neither do the spineless
plebeians, who wring their ineffectual hands, or even the
unprincipled tribunes, whose wan hope is that the dreadful news
will prove false.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here Volumnia grasps the real monstrosity of his position.
Once again, though in a nobler cause, she goes the distance. Once
again, her boy capitulates at last, consenting to a peace that must
cost him his life. The flexible Aufidius, in whose rotten code of
honor Coriolanus has naively placed his faith, sells him out for
personal gain. As a last indignity, the butchered warrior is
subjected to his killer's cold epitaph:
</P>
<P>
   Though in this city he
</P>
<P>
   Hath widowed and unchilded many a one,
</P>
<P>
   Which to this hour bewail the injury,
</P>
<P>
   Yet he shall have a noble memory.
</P>
<P>
   What is it Mark Antony says over the corpse of Caesar? ``The
evil that men do lives after them,/ The good is oft interred with
their bones.'' So let it not be with Martius.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
