<HEADER>
A6599 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DIE-FILM-$ADV03-NYT &LR;      08-30 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIE-FILM-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING ON A TV NEAR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great things about having pay cable is the
opportunity it provides for discovering little films that were
denied theatrical release. Films like the awkwardly titled ``And
Then You Die,'' a hard-as-pig iron 1987 gangster drama that used to
pop up on HBO well past the shank of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For its first five minutes, ``Die,'' which charts the
treacherous skirmishes between warring Quebec mobs, works solely in
somber and gripping imagery, neatly sketching out the conflicts; it
was superbly directed by Francis Mankiewicz. It's an instance where
you can literally see the filmmaker running out of money and the
picture eventually compromised by budgetary shortfalls, though the
director's control is evident throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the films directed by John Dahl _ including ``Red
Rock West'' and ``The Last Seduction'' _ were first seen on pay
cable. Unreleased pictures made by major talents are going with
increasing frequency to the small screen. When ``Picking Up the
Pieces,'' a movie starring Woody Allen and directed by Alfonso
Arau, makes its debut on Cinemax, it's safe to say that the feature
film landscape has undergone a continental shift.
</P>
<P>
   A flimsy comedy with a core of magical realism, ``Picking Up the
Pieces'' went without distribution until it showed up earlier this
year on pay cable _ though the outlet's motivation was to score a
coup rather than to improve the level of its programming. Not all
films having their premieres on cable can be so quickly dismissed.
``Things You Can Tell Just by Looking at Her,'' which made a splash
on the film festival circuit this year, was swiftly acquired for
theatrical distribution at the Sundance Film Festival by MGM. It
has a noteworthy cast _ Cameron Diaz, Calista Flockhart, Glenn
Close and Amy Brenneman _ playing women who drift in and out of one
another's lives. Taking its shape from ``Short Cuts,'' Robert
Altman's collaboration with Raymond Carver, ``Things'' was directed
with a lighter-than-air touch by the newcomer Rodrigo Garcia. Yet
MGM decided that the film could never find an audience in theaters,
and it will slip into the world on Showtime in its first run, on a
date yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   The cast delivers a few inspiring performances; Amy Brenneman is
singular, and her work deserves a place on the big screen. The
movie is certainly as good as ``Autumn in New York,'' which MGM
foisted upon an unsuspecting public a few weeks ago. The problem is
that despite the record number of movie screens in the United
States, there are also a record number of independent films being
made. As you read about the notice some of them receive, but
realize they will never appear at a local theater, it's easy to
become dispirited.
</P>
<P>
   One such film _ which will get a berth in theaters in October
but is currently showing on Cinemax _ is ``Animal Factory,''
directed by Steve Buscemi and adapted from the Edward Bunker novel
of the same name. This fluky prison drama follows Ron (Edward
Furlong) and his assimilation into a large state prison, where he's
mentored (for lack of a better word) by the veteran inmate Earl
(Willem Dafoe, whose shaved head for the role makes his sharp
features look even more whittled). Despite his ropy build and
no-nonsense jaw line, Earl isn't the cliched kindly-but-tough
convict, nor is Ron the standard-issue fish needing to be schooled
in the ways of the prison yards. ``Animal Factory'' spares us the
baroque and picturesque tortures of something like ``Oz,'' the
gritty HBO prison series in which rape and assault appear so often,
they should be listed in the credits. ``Factory'' follows the
day-to-day dehumanization of the convicts and the tricks they
invent to get through a single day. Buscemi again reveals the fluky
timing and concern for the psychology of misfits that made ``Trees
Lounge,'' his 1996 directorial debut, such a pleasure; ``Animal
Factory'' actually plays like a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panic,'' directed by Henry Bromell, is going the way of films
that will never be seen in a theater, heading straight to Cinemax.
It's the story of a troubled hit man (William H. Macy) who is
trained to follow his murderous father (Donald Sutherland) into the
family business but who also tries to keep it from affecting the
lives of his young son and his psychiatrist (John Ritter).
</P>
<P>
   It's the relationship between Macy's conscience-stricken killer
and Sutherland's amoral father that gives ``Panic'' a prickly
dynamic. The Macy character seems rational, but his composure is
only skin deep, and his attempt at order is failing him. There's
the stink of moral rot coming off the character played by
Sutherland, who has lately become a master at playing brusque,
manipulative father figures; his turn as the coach in ``Without
Limits'' ranks among the best work of his career, and his
performance in ``Panic'' is on a similar level.
</P>
<P>
   Bromell's ability to tell a story is a bit more advanced than
his directing skill at this point, but he's smart enough to stay
out of the way of his narrative and not weigh it down with
unnecessary stylization. He's interested in his protagonist, a guy
who thinks of himself as decent until he's forced to recognize his
life through the eyes of his own child. Although the claustrophobia
of ``Panic'' lends itself nicely to television, it's a shame that
we may never get to see how Bromell's tightening intensity might
play in a theater. The dilemma offers both good news and bad:
audiences will finally get to catch these pictures, but not the way
the filmmakers intended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
