<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DRKOOP0831-COX     08-30 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRKOOP0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    drkoop.com Inc. cuts work force even further
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Just a week after taking over, the new
management at Austin's drkoop.com Inc. has pulled the plug on 42
employees, thinning the company's already skinny ranks by about a
third.
</P>
<P>
   The move _ which cuts drkoop.com's work force to where it was
before the company went public last year _ will further reduce
costs and allow it to concentrate on generating revenue, President
Edward Cespedes said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the remaining 79 employees will devote their time to
sales. Cespedes said the company would look to form partnerships
with hospitals and physicians' offices and sell advertising space
to pharmaceutical companies. Projects that weren't bringing in
money have been disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization that we inherited was not focused on any one
goal,'' he said. ``We want to refocus the company around sales.''
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say it will take more than new financing to
nurse drkoop.com back to health because the content-based site
relies too heavily on advertising sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obviously a good thing that they are trying to reduce
unnecessary costs and get rid of nonessential personnel, but that's
not going to change the tide. It's a good, smart, effective
managerial thing to do, but it's not central to whether or not the
company will be able to make it,'' said Claudine Singer, senior
health-care analyst with Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Cespedes and two other venture capitalists assumed management of
drkoop.com last week when investors committed a cash infusion to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The investors _ California-based Prime Ventures, Austin's Eco
Associates and three other venture firms _ raised their investment
to $27.5 million Monday. The new investors have named six directors
to the reconfigured eight-seat board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   While the decision to cut back staff was not made until after
the new investors took over, it was an inevitable move as they
struggle to rein in expenses, Cespedes said.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in March, drkoop.com employed 220 people, but began
losing many as its financial prospects dimmed in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   As it acknowledged that it had run through much of its cash, the
company laid off 30 people in May and 11 more in June, and most of
the top executives left by summer.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, the company had 103 full-time workers and 27
part-timers. Cespedes said the company would not have any more
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done everything we need to do to move forward,''
he said. ``We are now in a position where we have plenty of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But the newest layoff was the nail in the coffin of drkoop.com's
popular community programs. The site once featured scores of weekly
chat rooms centered around common health conditions and it employed
full-time staff as well as part-timers and volunteers as hosts.
Drkoop.com will discontinue the chats, though it might consider
reviving the section with chats created by another company,
Cespedes said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, ProLink Management of Spicewood filed a lawsuit
against drkoop.com Tuesday in Travis County Court, alleging that it
is still owed money from an agreement the two companies made last
year to sponsor a series of professional tennis tournaments. The
suit claims that drkoop.com owes ProLink $6.1 million under the
contract, which was extended until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   This report contains material from the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: apark(at)statesman.com or 912-5933.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
