<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLVED-ROBOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBOTS CREATED BY COMPUTER `BORN' IN BRANDEIS LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of them pulls itself along a tabletop like a cross between
an inchworm and a swimmer doing the breast stroke. One uses a
strained two-legged gait while dragging its body along the surface,
while another skitters sideways like a crab.
</P>
<P>
   These odd-looking blobs of white plastic at Brandeis University
are not capable of doing anything useful. But they could be the
first wave of a true revolution in the young but burgeoning field
of robotics.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike any robot ever built before, these creatures were not
designed or built by human beings. They ``evolved'' inside a
computer, and the computer then selected the most successful
designs after hundreds of generations, and directed their
manufacture through a kind of three-dimensional printing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the end of the process were humans required, to perform
a midwife's role in delivering these creatures into the world by
snapping motors into place on plastic arms.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is the first true demonstration of robots that
evolve and even reproduce sort of like living creatures. But don't
be alarmed, the researchers say: Humans will continue to run the
show for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long-awaited and necessary step towards the ultimate
dream of self-evolving machines,'' according to Rodney Brooks,
director of the Artificial Intelligence lab at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and one of the world's leading robotics
experts. He wrote a commentary in the current Nature accompanying
the paper describing the robots.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Pollack, the Brandeis computer scientist who carried out
this project with mechanical engineer Hod Lipson, said the goal of
the research is to move toward robots that are cheap, abundant, and
capable of doing a host of specialized functions _ anything from
clearing minefields to mowing your lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robotics, I think, has been on the wrong path for 50 years,''
Pollack said in an interview. He aims to set the whole field
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the robots he has produced so far aren't good for
anything in particular. The only thing they can do is move, and
they aren't even all that efficient at doing that. But, claims a
press release from Brandeis, ``The experimental machines now being
born in the Brandeis University DEMO Laboratory may well be to
robotics what Kitty Hawk was to aviation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the robots produced in this experiment are pretty
primitive, even compared to other robots. They consist of only four
elements, combined in different ways: cylinders, ball-and-socket
joints, motors, and control circuits. The basic nature of these
components is programmed into the computer, which then ``evolves''
new robots by combining any number of these building blocks in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The only measure of ``fitness'' used in the computer's
evolutionary program was the ability to move, measured as the
distance the robot was from a starting point after a given
interval. The program contained no guidance on how to produce this
motion, leaving that up to the trial-and-error process of
evolution. The computer was also programmed with the basic laws of
physics so that whatever the devices did on the screen would work
the same way in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the designs that seemed fittest were selected to be
automatically built by the rapid prototyping machine, which builds
them up from a quick-setting plastic, one layer at a time. Finally,
the motors and controller chips were snapped on by the researchers,
who then set the devices free on a tabletop world to see if they
behaved the way they had on screen.
</P>
<P>
   In virtually all previous robots, Pollack said, engineers built
the device first, and then software engineers figured out how to
program its actions. But that's not the way things work in the
world of biology: ``In nature, there never is a body without a
brain, flopping around on the ground waiting for a control
system,'' he said. Instead, the Brandeis team's approach is
``co-evolution, with incremental changes in the body and the
brain'' taking place together.
</P>
<P>
   Robots with the flexibility and intelligence to perform a whole
array of basic human tasks remain very far off, he said. ``The
field of robotics is still $100 billion shy, and centuries away,
from creating an all-purpose intelligent humanoid like Star Trek's
Commander Data,'' Pollack says.
</P>
<P>
   But if this work really succeeds, he said, ``we can do for
disposable robots what Bill Gates did for software releases: Make
them so affordable that everyone can own 100.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
