<HEADLINE>
BABY GETS LUNGS FOR TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rachel Sweet has gotten the lungs she was waiting for,
and the new lease on life they hopefully will bring.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-month-old with hazel hair and blue-grey eyes has been
struggling for weeks to stay alive at Children's Hospital while her
parents and doctors made a national plea for a donor set of lungs.
That call was answered sometime during the past two days, and
Wednesday night the hospital announced that Rachel was in critial
condition but had ``tolerated the surgery well.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Organ Bank declined to say where the lungs came
from, who donated them, or even when they arrived. The secrecy, it
said in a statement, is ``out of respect for the anonymity of the
donor family.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's family, however, has done everything it can to get out
the word about her illness and the fact that, without new lungs,
she would likely die soon. The infant had been in Children's
intensive care unit, with tubes pumping food into her stomach,
medicine into her arm and belly, and oxygen into her nostrils.
</P>
<P>
   Her condition is called alveolar dysplasia, which, together with
her pulmonary vascular disease, means that she has too few air sacs
to breath normally and that the ones she has do not work right.
Simply breathing took tremendous energy and put pressure on her
heart and other organs. It also impeded her physical and mental
development, although her doctor said that her prospects were good
if she got a lung transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's donation coincided with Tuesday's call by Pope John
Paul II for more people to donate their organs. But the pope's
plea, in a speech in Rome to 4,000 transplant specialists, is up
against imposing trends. Falling rates of violent and accidental
deaths, combined with rising numbers of people living long, healthy
lives, are shrinking the pool of suitable donors. In New England,
the list of those awaiting organs is 3,500 long, and nationwide
there are 71,000 on the list, with a new one added every 14
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If Rachel recovers the way they hope, Stacey and Michael Sweet
plan to take her back to their home in Barnstead, N.H. _ a home
that, because of her hospitalization, she has lived in for only one
of her six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
