<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6607 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MCQUARRIE-FILM-$ADV03     08-30 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCQUARRIE-FILM-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE MOVIE   THEY LET YOU MAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., Calif.)   By JAMIE MALANOWSKI   (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To hear Chris McQuarrie tell it, the origins of the
new film he wrote and directed, ``The Way of the Gun,'' lay in
disgruntlement, frustration and anger. We pick up the story about
four years ago, shortly after he was awarded the Oscar for his
screenplay ``The Usual Suspects.'' At that point, the project that
most enthralled McQuarrie, who appears to be one of those
formidably intelligent people who can produce a trove of well
thought out, cogently stated reasons in support of his opinions,
was to direct the life story of Alexander the Great.
</P>
<P>
   But the then 27-year-old McQuarrie, author of a screenplay that
was nonpareil in its genre, was finding no one who would let him
direct a movie about a 20-year-old who had conquered the world.
``It was probably a bad idea to pursue that as the first film,'' he
now grudgingly concedes. ``But I decided if I wanted to direct that
I should direct other films first. So I came up with ideas for some
smaller films. But literally every time I would go to a meeting,
the only interest anybody had in me making a film was if it was a
crime film. But I didn't want to be the crime guy. So I started
lowering my price, and then I started lowering my back end'' _
money to be earned through foreign distribution, cable television
or video sales _ ``and then I started lowering my standards, and
finally it got to the point when I was in a meeting and I said, `I
will take no salary, I'll take no back end, I'll eat craft service
and I will live in the jungle while I make this movie. You decide
the budget and the casting, as long as you let me make the film I
want to make.' They still said no.''
</P>
<P>
   After that meeting, a frustrated and fairly furious McQuarrie
went for coffee with the actor-writer-director Benicio del Toro and
the producer Ken Kokin, both of whom had worked on ``The Usual
Suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling completely miserable,'' McQuarrie recalled
recently during a visit to New York, ``and I said, `That's it, I'm
going to quit this whole business, I'm going to go write books.'
Benicio said: `It seems that they're willing to let you make a
crime film. If you want to say what you want to say, you have to
make the movie they want you to make. Why don't you make a crime
film?' So I conceded that he was right, and we started thinking
about a crime film.''
</P>
<P>
   But not happily. ``This movie was written from a place of real
anger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As del Toro explained later by telephone: ``Sometimes you get to
a point where you think everything is going to be easy, but then
there's another mountain to climb. He has so much talent. He just
had to use it before time passed him by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the Gun,'' which opens Friday, is the story of two
sociopaths, Parker and Longbaugh, played by Ryan Phillippe and del
Toro, who decide to kidnap a surrogate mother (Juliette Lewis) and
hold her and her unborn child for ransom. As it turns out, the
kidnapping becomes a bloody mess, and, what's worse, the man for
whom she is carrying the child is mob connected. Soon the screen is
populated by a number of very dangerous men, portrayed by Taye
Diggs, Nicky Katt and an understated James Caan, none of whom has a
motivation that can be described as unalloyed. The movie is tense
and twisty; it should now be harder for McQuarrie to avoid being
called the crime guy.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the movie was a marriage of del Toro's coffee shop
comment that he had never seen a really interesting kidnapping
movie, and a casual remark on the part of McQuarrie's wife. Heather
Neely McQuarrie, a film producer who also served as the costume
designer for ``The Way of the Gun,'' happened to mention an article
she had read about an executive with a much younger wife who hired
a surrogate mother so they could have a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were perfectly healthy,'' said McQuarrie, ``but she
didn't want to ruin her body. They hired bodyguards for the
surrogate mother. Well, as soon as I heard `bodyguards,' the movie
very easily unfolded. I wrote the first draft in about five days.''
Anger included.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from his personal difficulties, he was angry about the
film industry's insistence on sympathetic characters. (Many
executives found fault with Alexander's precipitous and
unattractive post-conquest, third-act decline.) ``I can't tell you
the number of times I've heard, `Well, you'll lose the audience if
that character does that,''' he said. ``It's maddening. It
completely takes away the ability to make a three-dimensional
character. They want films about crime, but they don't want
characters who are criminals. No one ever asked me to change the
fact that Person A killed Person B. They just wanted me to give
Person A a good reason, a reason why Person B deserved to die. And
I found that deplorable, that Hollywood's answer to toning down
violence was to work harder at making violence more acceptable, as
opposed to taking violence out.
</P>
<P>
   So when I sat down to write this film, I said fine, if I'm going
to write a crime film, I'm going to make a film about criminals.
Parker and Longbaugh are unapologetic, unqualified thugs who really
don't care who they're hurting or what they have to do to get their
way. When my agent read it, he said we're not even going to bother
taking it to the studios. They'd have wanted it rewritten. They'd
have wanted that scene _ that inevitable, awful scene _ in which
the characters explain why they are the way they are and end up
blaming somebody else so that you can find them acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Attentive readers will recognize Parker and Longbaugh as the
real surnames of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid. That's part of
McQuarrie's demythification: Butch and Sundance are pop culture
criminal names; Parker and Longbaugh are blotter names, docket
names.
</P>
<P>
   Phillipe said: ``What I remember about reading the screenplay is
that as soon as I finished, I started reading it again. So much was
conveyed, on so many levels, and you couldn't see things coming. I
knew it would be a lot of fun to say his words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris has a gift for storytelling,'' said del Toro. His
charismatic, not-too-talky performance in this film calls to mind
James Coburn's in ``The Magnificent Seven,'' only James Dean-ier.
``People could spend years writing and never write a line as good
as his.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie said that watching movies was ``about all I did'' as a
boy. ``A friend and I would take the newspaper every Friday and we
would plot the movies that were opening, and we would line up all
the times so that we could hit one after the other, right down to
the time it would take to travel from one theater to the next,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But his career in movies almost didn't happen. He was reared in
Princeton Junction, N.J., and although he liked to write, he was a
poor student and never aspired to college. Instead, he traveled a
bit, then took a temporary job, for his uncle's security agency.
</P>
<P>
   He was mostly a security guard, working, for example, in New
Jersey patrolling the construction site of the Freehold Raceway
Mall. After four years, he was about to join the New York Police
Department _ the broad-shouldered McQuarrie, who speaks in a low
rasp, would have been a formidable interrogator _ when he got a
call from a high school buddy, Bryan Singer, who was just out of
film school. Singer admired McQuarrie's writing and shared his
critical sensibility. Singer had money from investors to direct a
movie if only he could come up with a screenplay in 15 days. So
McQuarrie went to work, and three months later they were making a
thriller, ``Public Access'' (1992), about secrets in a small town.
Three years later they made ``The Usual Suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MCQUARRIE-FILM-$ADV03     08-30 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCQUARRIE-FILM-$ADV03-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: ``Usual Suspects.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McQuarrie brought fairly firm ideas to his first job directing.
His heroes are John Huston, John Sturges, John Ford and Sidney
Lumet _ ``all directors who stay out of the way.'' In a similar
way, he is firm about the shortcomings he perceives in his initial
effort. ``The films that inspired the visual style of `The Way of
the Gun' are `Bad Day at Black Rock,' `The Man Who Would Be King'
and `The Magnificent Seven,''' he says. ``In all of them the camera
remains as far back from the action as possible and just captures
the drama. And then when I got there I realized I didn't know
enough to create that drama. This film is a visual history of me
learning how to direct.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part was taking charge. ``There's two kinds of
people in the film business,'' he says. ``Those for whom it is much
easier to say `please,' and those for whom it is much easier to say
`no.' The people who say please cannot ever say no. I was a please
person. As a writer, you kind of have to be. You work to include
everybody's vision in your work. Whereas when you're a director,
you have to include everybody's work in your vision. I had to
become a person who says no. But there I was, on the set, trying to
include every idea, giving the actors every single opportunity to
do what they wanted. And they were having a great time, but the
movie was getting further and further away from where it needed to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally James Caan called me aside and said: `Let me tell you
something. Actors like to be directed. They need direction.' He
said: `This is your film. Quit messing around, and go tell those
people what to do.' And that's what I started to do. But it was
very difficult. I felt most like the novice.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, for one, disagrees. ``I never saw it,'' he says. ``I
say he looked like a director who was doing his 10th film.'' One
day it was determined del Toro's character needed to steal a car,
only there wasn't one with fake windows available. ``He just led us
out to the street and had me smash a real window,'' del Toro
recalls. ``He was commanding. It was thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   One person director McQuarrie had no trouble saying no to was
screenwriter McQuarrie. He happily tells about a scene in which
Parker in a long monologue explains to the surrogate mother how he
and his partner differ from her and other ``civilians.'' ``He tells
her that she has a lie she tells herself so that she can get out of
bed in the morning,'' McQuarrie explains, ``And it's a lie that
says there's only two ways that you die _ that it was your time, or
that you had it coming. But, he says, guys like Parker and
Longbaugh know that there's only one way you die, and that's that
you were in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go in, Ryan asks for a sandwich _ he wants to be eating
in the scene. He does the scene beautifully _ he's phenomenal. When
he finishes, I let the camera run. There was a long silence, and
then Juliette ad libs, `Are you going to eat the rest of that
sandwich?' And then he ends up giving her half the sandwich. And it
was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we got to the cutting room, I realized that was the
first time they'd really spoken to one another, and he wouldn't
have told her those things. So we cut the monologue and kept the
sandwich. And I was perfectly content. This was one of the places
where I was venting my anger. Once I was in the cutting room, I
could tell the difference between what was anger and what was
story.''
</P>
<P>
   This McQuarrie is a tough-minded fellow: reputations could be
built on what he throws away.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie is considerably less angry today. ``I've accepted that
when people hire you to write a screenplay, it's not your movie,
it's their movie,'' he says. He is currently working on a
screenplay for ``The Green Hornet.'' He and his wife have recently
settled in Seattle and are expecting their first child. ``I don't
know how I lived in Los Angeles for eight years,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people there are frightened, but they're never frightened
of the things that can actually kill them, the earthquakes and the
fires and the gangs. They're oblivious to that. What they're afraid
of is their status and people's impressions of them.'' He says he'd
like to direct again; in the end, he says, it was fun. And he's
still interested in Alexander the Great.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
