<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KIDNAP-TAXES-NYT &LR;      08-30 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRS LIMITS DEDUCTIONS FOR KIDNAPPED CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story, held yesterday, is now released for publication;
this is a slightly expanded version of the story.) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The taxpayer's question started out poignant, then turned
pragmatic: My child has been kidnapped. Can I still take a
deduction on my income tax return? The answer this week from an IRS
lawyer was matter of fact: only for the year the child was
abducted.
</P>
<P>
   The taxpayer asked an IRS customer service representative in
April about the exemption for the 1999 tax year. The taxpayer also
asked if the exemption could be claimed in future years if the
child's room was being maintained and money was spent on a search.
</P>
<P>
   In a reply that the agency released Monday, George Baker, an IRS
lawyer, said that in the year of the kidnapping, Congress allows
the tax break. But in subsequent years no exemption can be claimed,
he wrote, because the tax law generally requires a parent to
provide more than half the support for a child to qualify. The IRS
did not identify the questioner, saying tax matters were private.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's advisory opinion acknowledged that ``the issue is not
free from doubt''; the lawyer said he could not find a case that
addressed these issues directly. But he relied heavily on a 1980
U.S. Tax Court case in which Ebrahim Otmishi sought an exemption
for a child, Jeiran, who had been abducted by Otmishi's wife, Mina
_ or, alternatively, to deduct the costs of hunting for his child
as a theft loss. The court ruled against him.
</P>
<P>
   Several tax experts said yesterday that they agreed with the
lawyer's advisory opinion _ though not all were confident how long
it would stand. ``Now I expect we will see Republicans and
Democrats racing each other to show how much they care about
kidnapped children by fixing the law before the elections,'' said
Lee Sheppard, a tax lawyer known for her acerbic critiques of tax
policy in the journal Tax Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Many missing children, experts say, have been taken by a parent
denied custody in a divorce. A study by the National Center for
Juvenile Justice, a private research group in Pittsburgh, found
that 24 percent of abductions were by strangers and the rest by
relatives or friends.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a parent holding a child in such circumstances probably
would not qualify for a tax deduction _ and a kidnapper who was a
stranger certainly would not _ under a 1958 law in which Congress
denied dependent exemptions when ``the relationship between such
individual and the taxpayer is in violation of local law.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Barry Forman, a University of Oklahoma law professor
who specializes in family tax matters, said he was surprised at the
IRS position.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to an IRS regulation that lets the parents of a
newborn who remains hospitalized list the child as a dependent on
the theory that, but for the medical condition, the child would be
part of the household. By applying the same reasoning, the IRS
could let parents of abducted children claim the deduction, Forman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS legal memo is consistent with the agency's actions in
the case of 12-year-old Johnny Gosch, who was kidnapped by a
stranger in front of five witnesses in Des Moines in 1982. His
mother, Noreen Gosch, said the family's tax return was audited in
1986 and the exemption claimed for Johnny was denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRS agent was very cruel,'' Gosch said. ``She said, `Your
son chose to not live at home so you can't get an exemption for
him,' and we reminded her that he was taken from us. And she said
that was beside the point _ that if he wasn't living with us we
could not get an exemption for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosch and the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children
appealed to a variety of officials, but the auditor's decision
stood, she said. Johnny has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers claiming an exemption for a child must list the
child's Social Security number on their tax return. In 1999,
taxpayers could deduct $2,750 from their adjusted gross income for
each dependent.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has a system to check its records for the addresses of
parents suspected of kidnapping their own child and to release
information to law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Ransom paid to recover an abducted child is deductible, the IRS
ruled in 1972. It said such payments were treated as theft losses
due to extortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
