<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6612 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-ECUCATION-BOS &LR;      08-30 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ECUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI INTRODUCES CONTROVERSIAL TEACHER AID PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Saying Massachusetts is at a ``crossroads'' in its
seven-year school-reform effort, Gov. Paul Cellucci offered state
money Wednesday to boost the salaries of much-needed math, science
foreign language teachers and proposed a major expansion of
teacher-training programs outside traditional schools of education.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a Malden elementary school in what was billed as the
Commonwealth's first-ever ``State of Education'' speech, the
governor also promised that, despite alarmingly high MCAS failure
rates, he will not abandon the test as a graduation requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have already called for the suspension of the test or
easing of the standards,'' Cellucci said. `` But I will continue to
insist on high standards _ our children deserve nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's proposals, which he unveiled without price tags, were
warmly received by most of the 400 people invited to the event in
the Beebe School auditorium. But a dozen anti-MCAS protesters
picketed outside, and some in the audience were unimpressed by the
governor's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen E. Gorrie, who heads the Massachusetts Teachers
Association, said the governor should concentrate on raising the
salaries of all teachers, not just a select few. And he cast doubt
on the quality of many alternative teacher-training programs, such
as the intensive, seven-week Massachusetts Institute for New
Teachers that Cellucci wants to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very very hesitant to back programs that will allow
people in the classroom who are not properly trained,'' Gorrie
said. ``Just knowing your subject is not all there is to
teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci was joined on stage by Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift,
whom he designated as a sort of ``education czar'' _ although the
administration rejects that title.
</P>
<P>
   Swift will assume a leading education role at the beginning of a
critical school year: This year's 10th-graders will be denied a
high-school diploma if they don't pass MCAS by the end of the 12th
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Swift, who has been meeting for the past seveal months with
educators and others involved in reform efforts, will continue
those discussions and release a report this fall on how to improve
student performance.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks, Swift reiterated her call for volunteer tutors
to help every one of the 30,000 10th-graders expected to fail the
test in the spring of 2001. She didn't provide additional details
on how to find them, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``State government is a partner in this important endeavor, but
we cannot do it alone,'' she said. ``Today we are providing an
opportunity for everyone in this state to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's proposals are designed to counter a looming teacher
shortage caused in part by a graying teaching force and a red-hot
economy. Math, science and foreign-language teachers traditionally
are the toughest ones to find, and Cellucci's salary proposal is
designed to attract and keep them.
</P>
<P>
   Gorrie noted that many teacher contracts around the state
already allow districts to pay slightly higher salaries to those
teachers. But Michael Sentance, Cellucci's chief education adviser,
said the governor is proposing a far bolder approach _ and much
higher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about putting them higher on the same pay
scale _ we're talking about blowing it up'' Sentence said. ``Steve
thinks inside the box. We're not talking about inside the box.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said in his speech that any district that demonstrates
to the state that it will pay more to math, science and
foreign-language teachers could qualify for state money ``to offset
increased costs.'' But the governor's office couldn't provide
specific amounts, saying that would depend on how many districts
are interested and how much money ends up in the state budget for
the program.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Peyser, who chairs the State Board of Education, said
it makes sense to pay teachers based on ``market conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are too few math teachers, we need to pay math
teachers more,'' he said. ``There is a role for the state to play
in topping off teacher salaries, but it ought to be targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   But even some math teachers worry about what such a program
would do to teacher morale.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Moran, a math teacher at Methuen High School and the
state's reigning Teacher of the Year, said the proposal is logical
because many math teachers' skills would command much higher
salaries in the corporate world. But she said other teachers may
find the pay difference hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to give some of us more when we're all
underpaid,'' Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   In Malden, Cellucci also touted his alternative teacher-training
initiative as a way to deal with potential teacher shortages. Such
programs, he said, tend to attract professionals from other careers
who want to become teachers but don't want to spend years getting
the certification they need to be in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   He said the state's goal should be to hire one-tenth of all new
teachers from such programs by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Shorter alternatives to traditional education school programs
are becoming more popular. This past summer, the Commonwealth's
two-year old MINT program trained 150 new teachers in an intensive,
seven-week course. Sentance said that states such as Texas and New
Jersey already get between a quarter and one-third of their new
teachers from such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Moore Johnson, a professor at the Harvard Graduate School
of Education, said alternative methods of teacher certification
should be considered, given the threat of a shortage. But she
cautioned that such programs must be carefully constructed and
monitored to make sure the new teachers are adequately prepared.
</P>
<P>
   If not, she said, ``people will enter the classroom with less
understanding of the challanges of teaching, the complexities of
teaching and the practical day-to-day requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sandy Coleman of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
