<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-RIGHTS-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN ACTION REOPENS DISPUTE ON HUMAN RIGHTS MONITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A decision by Australia to limit its
cooperation with the United Nations on human rights reporting has
reopened a debate about whether international monitors are
sometimes harder on democracies than on closed societies.
</P>
<P>
   Some democracies, aware that information is more accessible and
independent advocacy groups are more influential in their
countries, are wary of the monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, a campaign has been building for months to curb
access to U.N. monitors since the release of reports that were
critical of the government's judicial treatment of Aborigines and
foreigners who sought asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians from Prime Minister John Howard's conservative
Liberal Party have been particularly angry over criticisms from the
U.N. Committee for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination that
relate to mandatory sentencing laws in Australia. The committee
found that they fell hardest on Aborigines, some of them children.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Australia said that it would demand that U.N.
monitors produce compelling reasons to visit Australia before
permissions for fact-finding trips would be granted.
</P>
<P>
   The government also said it would reject requests from the
United Nations to stay the deportation of unsuccessful asylum
seekers. Australia has become a magnet for illegal immigrants from
as far afield as Afghanistan and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Howard told Parliament on Wednesday that the decision to reduce
cooperation did not amount to ``a turning away by Australia from
the principles of the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it does represent a determination by this government to
ensure that matters affecting Australia are resolved by Australians
within Australia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. human rights activities are fragmented. There is a high
commissioner for human rights, Mary Robinson, a former president of
Ireland. That office is less than a decade old.
</P>
<P>
   An older group, the Human Rights Commission, is a body of
government representatives that meets annually to hear reports from
monitors assigned to specific countries or issues and may censure
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are treaty committees set up to monitor individual
covenants against torture, on the rights of the child, on the
elimination of discrimination against women, on the elimination of
racial discrimination and on civil and political rights. These are
expert panels whose candidates are nominated by governments and
elected by nations that have signed the relevant treaties or
covenants.
</P>
<P>
   Only countries that have signed the treaties are required to
submit reports for scrutiny, leaving some countries that are known
for abuses free of monitoring. Other nations that are signatories
submit perfunctory or late reports or ignore the requirement
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In open societies, where independent monitoring groups as well
as government agencies can provide voluminous information,
criticisms may be sharper and more detailed, human rights leaders
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Australia has been a strong supporter of these treaties and has
submitted regular reports. The Australian decision to restrict
future cooperation came as a shock to many rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Australians, who have done so much to build the
international human rights system and the treaty system, to say
this is a particularly sad moment,'' said Felice Gaer, director of
the Jacob Blaustein Institute for the Advancement of Human Right
and a member of the U.N. committee against torture.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 core international treaties that Secretary General
Kofi Annan has asked governments to sign or ratify during a summit
meeting of world leaders in new York next week, ``13 of them are
human rights treaties,'' Gaer said, adding that the timing of the
Australian step was unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of a message does this send to the rest of the world
about the importance of global norms, and the importance of living
up to them?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, the Sydney Morning Herald said in an editorial
that the government had ``delivered a diplomatic windfall to odious
regimes everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Australia's decision reflects opinions shared by some Americans
who oppose what they see as a growing tendency toward international
scrutiny. John Bolton, executive vice president of the American
Enterprise Institute in Washington and a former assistant secretary
of state for international organization affairs in the Bush
administration, said that his objections were constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Australia has done is a triumph for democracy,'' he said
in an interview. ``Within a constitutional system of representative
government, you're allowed to struggle for policy outcomes. In a
democracy, sometimes you win and sometimes you lose. What Australia
is objecting to is the idea that a losing side in a democratic
country can ask for a lifeline to a U.N. agency.
</P>
<P>
   The committee on racial discrimination is purporting to tell
Australia that its mandatory sentencing policies are discriminatory
against the Aboriginal population, Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are and maybe they aren't,'' he added. ``But in a
democratic society, that's a legitimate subject for debate, and it
gets resolved through the processes of representative government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In making its decision, Australia called for an overhaul of the
U.N.'s human rights committee system. Among the Australian demands
are ``adequate recognition of the primary role of democratically
elected governments and the subordinate role of nongovernmental
organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to parliament in Canberra on Wednesday, Howard
contended that Australia, which has signed all of the main human
rights treaties, was under greater scrutiny than the United States
and as much as Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
