<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6618 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-PSYCHOBEACH-REVI     08-30 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PSYCHOBEACH-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
The name, at least, is irresistible: ``Psycho Beach Party'' is the
kind of gimmick that the Z-grade producer in ``Ed Wood'' might have
pitched, brandishing a provocative title while lacking a script.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But in execution, this is no parodistic drop kick between the
goal posts of ``Psycho'' and ``Beach Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter is its prime target. But the trouble with sending up
such drive-in schlock is that the originals already are riddled
with inadvertent humor.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the barbs of ``Mystery Science Theater 3000,''
films such as 1964's ``Horror of Party Beach'' can be a cheesy
hoot, leaving ``Psycho Beach Party'' in a bit of a sand trap.
</P>
<P>
   While wallowing in quaint, retro ironies, the film ably emulates
the silly surf-and-sun antics of Frankie Avalon and Annette
Funicello, peppering the mix with plot-driving murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psycho Beach Party'' also punches up the equation by
sprinkling its surface innocence with bursts of profanity, flashes
of nudity, pointed sexual commentary and monotonous homo-eroticism.
</P>
<P>
   These jarring nuances work _ to a point. But more often the
movie is a mundane comic exercise, even while basking in the
tarnished nostalgic glow of cheaply patronizing teen exploitation
flicks.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of cheap, take ``Psycho Beach Party.'' Its cast has one
name star in Thomas Gibson of TV's ``Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' and
production values are meager, especially the muddy sound mix.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson plays an overaged surfer guru to a gang of empty-headed
beachcombers whom we first see at a drive-in. There, one girl is
murdered during a movie about a pizza waitress with three heads
(the film's funniest send-up), and soon surfers start washing up
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Chief suspect is Chicklet (Lauren Ambrose), a tomboy among them
who has ``morbidly psychotic episodes of schizophrenia.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery plays out more like a recent slasher flick than
horror yarns of yore. Yet plot points are beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, ``Psycho Beach Party'' is driven by a warped humor that
it rarely sustains.
</P>
<P>
   The absurdly grisly murders earn some guffaws, and the teens'
nutty naivete can be cute in a corny, offbeat way.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era of comic outrageousness, director Robert Lee King
and screenwriter Charles Busch have punched up the equation with
kinkiness, including a randy policewoman clearly played by an actor
in drag (Busch himself).
</P>
<P>
   Largely this comic carnality just doesn't fit. It's as
anachronistic as having '60s surfer chicks emulate Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Psycho Beach Party'' has its moments, especially a
galvanizing dance on the beach with music by legit surf band Los
Straitjackets.
</P>
<P>
   King also uses amusing, creaky flourishes such as rapid zooms
and inset thought balloons.
</P>
<P>
   How quaint _ and how fun. But finding hilarity in such silliness
remains a challenge when the source of the mocking is funny enough
by itself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Psycho Beach Party'' &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Starring: Thomas Gibson, Lauren Ambrose &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Now showing: at the Greenway 3 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Director: Robert Lee King &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Screenwriter: Charles Busch &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Not rated, but includes sexuality, nudity, profanity and violence &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Running time: 95 minutes &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Grade: C- &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
