<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6619 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BESTMAN-THEATER-ART-$     08-30 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTMAN-THEATER-ART-$ADV03-1,100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BARD OF AMERICAN POLITICS, STILL CAMPAIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore Vidal wrote ``The Best Man'' in 1959, a time when Joseph
McCarthy's legacy endured, when Adlai Stevenson and Richard Nixon
were among the nation's leading politicians, and when Vidal counted
as his friend a young senator from Massachusetts named John
Kennedy. The play, first produced on Broadway in March 1960, eight
months before Kennedy was elected president, drew on these
influences to become a tale of politics that may seem improbable
today: a stark struggle of two men of obvious complexity, set
during a national political convention where decisions of
consequence were actually made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' is returning to Broadway 10 presidential
campaigns since it first arrived to favorable reviews. Previews
begin on Sept. 5 at the Virginia Theater, where it opens on Sept.
17 with a cast that includes Charles Durning, Spalding Gray, Chris
Noth, Elizabeth Ashley, Christine Ebersole and Michael Learned,
under the direction of Ethan McSweeny.
</P>
<P>
   The play is dated, yet it is not, and in that, it is very much
like the 74-year-old Vidal himself. Politics have changed mightily
since 1959, and the play and its author are a reminder that much of
what once so invigorated the nation's presidential selection
process _ the suspense, the unvarnished characters, the sense that
something meaningful was at stake _ has seeped away.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal attended his first convention at the age of 14, yet he did
not even consider stopping by when the Democrats met in Los Angeles
to nominate Al Gore last month, even though he was 25 minutes away
by car, settled in at a rooftop suite with a private garden at the
Regent Beverly Wilshire Hotel. ``It's too dismal,'' Vidal said, the
morning after President Clinton gave his valedictory speech to the
assembled Democrats. ``I'm not interested in any of the
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Vidal has not, it seems, lost enthusiasm for what was
probably his best-received play, nor has he made any changes in the
original script to account for the intervening 40 years. Now
formally retitled ``Gore Vidal's The Best Man,'' to avoid confusion
with an unrelated movie called ``The Best Man'' that was released
last fall, the drama abounds with themes and lines that are at
times strikingly contemporary, notwithstanding the fact that they
were written before many of the current crop of politicians were
old enough to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some very good presidents who have slept around a
lot more than Bill Russell ever did, and in the White House, too,''
proclaims the frumpy national committeewoman Gamadge (played by
Ashley), as she comes to the defense of a candidate with an
exemplary public life and a marriage more complicated than that of
the couple now living in the White House. As Russell ( Gray) finds
himself drawn into the back alleys of political combat, he laments
that he entered public life to put an end to ``the business of
gossip instead of issues, personalities instead of policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two candidates, who are out to destroy each other,
there is a departing president (Durning), who makes a case for the
honorability of lying to the electorate, be it about his terminal
medical diagnosis or the fact that he does not believe in God. Most
fundamentally, though, Vidal presents a struggle between two types
of politicians who are as common today as they were then: the
ruthless, relentless yet effective Senator Joe Cantwell (Noth), and
the honorable, morally grounded yet maddeningly deliberate Bill
Russell.
</P>
<P>
   This was Nixon versus Stevenson in its time, the inspiration for
the competing politicians in the play, but there is no shortage of
present-day analogies. ``There are only so many types who are drawn
to politics,'' Vidal observed. And the questions he raises in
setting up the combat between his politicians are the same ones
that Bill Bradley's dispirited supporters were asking themselves in
New Hampshire as Al Gore cheerfully pummeled their candidate into
defeat: Who would make the better candidate for office? And who
would make the better president?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer and I never will,'' Vidal said last
month in Los Angeles, poking at a slab of seared salmon and
drinking iced coffee in the dining room of the Beverly Wilshire,
which was teeming with Democratic delegates who, to his constant
distraction, had taken to chanting ``Gore!'' as they marched
through the hotel corridors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dealing with game players,'' Vidal continued. ``These are
chess games. And I'm not going to analyze the chess player. I'm
going to analyze the game.'' (That said, Vidal has never attempted
to hide his empathy for Stevenson. So it is not surprising that
Russell comes across as more noble by the play's end.)
</P>
<P>
   The game, as Vidal would have it, involves the struggle between
Russell and Cantwell to win their party's presidential nomination,
played out in two hotel suites in Philadelphia in July 1960, as the
convention unfolds around them. Each man has dug up information
that could likely doom the other's candidacy. Russell is mortified
at his own behavior when, exhorted by his lieutenants and the
president, he confronts Cantwell with what he has discovered. ``I
never thought I could bring up something like this against any
man,'' Russell says. ``It revolts me.'' It falls to Cantwell to
buck up Russell. ``Oh, come on _ don't give it a second thought,''
he says. ``Look, I don't blame you. I'd certainly use it against
you if it was there.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the story line would be unimaginable today for
obvious reasons. `` `The Best Man' is based on the idea that
candidates have secrets,'' said Jeffrey Richards, one of the play's
producers and its press representative. ``Today, who has secrets on
the eve of the convention?''
</P>
<P>
   In its way, then, the play is a time capsule, a means to measure
how much the system has changed. Even the undercurrent of
homosexuality, which Vidal noted was ``scandalous'' in its time
(though certainly not a surprising theme for one of the nation's
first openly gay writers), seems almost quaint in these days of
Richard Hatch and television's ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Vidal did not alter the script, he would not
approach the subject the same way now. ``If I were to do a
political play today about who governs the United States, it would
not be set at a political convention,'' Vidal said. ``It would be
within a board room, as they argue about politicians, and audition
politicians, and figure out which one they're going to make
president.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his drama in light of the present period, he said:
``I don't see how you can begin to do a play that's constructed
like that _ which is really a dramatic contest between two
front-runners. And it can go either way. That doesn't happen
anymore. Primaries meant something then, but nobody knew in March
who the candidate was going to be _ which we knew in both parties
this year. It's predicted by how much money is spent in the primary
season and it's quickly wrapped up. So there's nothing to do at a
convention but pick a vice president. Generally undramatic, if
that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that ``The Best Man'' is being revived this
season. Richards said he had had it in mind for a play-reading
project that did not pan out, but still thought ``it would be great
to do in a year in which there was a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   When he subsequently contacted Vidal in Italy, Richards
recalled, ``His initial questions were: `Are you really serious
about this?' And, `Do you want me to update it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Richards said he put ``The Best Man'' in the category of
``classic popular entertainment''; ``I wouldn't update `The Front
Page' or `The Little Foxes.''' At the same time, though, there have
been few attempts by any writers over the last 40 years to make
politics the subject of a Broadway play ( Vidal tried once or twice
after ``The Best Man'' without much success), and it will be
intriguing to see if there is more interest in theatrical
treatments of politics than in the game itself. (The 1964 movie
version of ``The Best Man,'' for which Vidal wrote the screenplay,
starred Henry Fonda.)
</P>
<P>
   Vidal is not just another playwright, or historical novelist, or
essayist, or commentator, or whichever of the many resume entries
he might use to define himself. He has practiced what he is writing
about: he ran for Congress from New York in 1960, and for senator
from California in 1982, each time as a Democrat; he lost both
elections. And while in Los Angeles last month, he was a keynote
speaker at a forum sponsored by The Nation, an ideological retreat
for Democrats frustrated by the proceedings downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The speech he gave warned that the drive to increase the
country's military might was a threat to the economic viability of
the Republic at a time when the nation is anxious for peace and
suspicious of interventionism (much as Gore's grandfather was when
he served as a senator from Oklahoma).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite something,'' Gore said. ``Not only a standing
ovation, but they began to chant, `Go, Gore! Go, Gore! Go, Gore!'
They were running me for president!''
</P>
<P>
   Vidal is also unusual in that over the years he has kept some
notable company. He and Jacqueline Bouvier shared the same
stepfather, Hugh D. Auchincloss, at different times, and his
conversation is scattered with first-name references to former
presidents and first ladies, complete with anecdotes about, and
caricatures of, the people he has known.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't remind me of Truman at all,'' Vidal declared in a
husky falsetto, as he recounted what Eleanor Roosevelt told him
when she was asked her opinion of the president in ``The Best
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   As the playwright sat in on a rehearsal the other day in
Manhattan, wearing sunglasses and drinking a Diet Coke while the
actors competed over the thump of construction machinery outside,
he leaned over to offer a real-time footnote to his play. ``The
next line is one Jack Kennedy gave me,'' he said. He turned to the
makeshift ``stage,'' an assortment of couches, tables and empty
Absolut bottles, where one of Russell's supporters proceeded to
promise him that he was behind his candidacy ``100 percent.'' That
means, then and now, that ``you're finished,'' Vidal said tartly.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy attended a performance of ``The Best Man'' on
Broadway, with Charles Spalding, a longtime friend, at his side.
Vidal stood behind a curtain in the wings, observing the president
as the president observed his play. ``I had never actually watched
anybody who was watching a play,'' Vidal said. ``I could see their
eyes, so I could see who they were looking at. He was following it
very attentively. And there was a little giggle between him and
Spalding on the line about how to get girls in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And then he did his famous'' _ Vidal brought his fingers to
his mouth and tapped his teeth, evoking a dozen pictures of Kennedy
_ ``which meant he was thinking, he was really following it.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, another man who would be president, Ronald
Reagan, came close to playing Russell on Broadway. Vidal rejected
that casting suggestion from the producers, and the part went to
Melvyn Douglas. ``I'm responsible for Ronald Reagan,'' Vidal
whispered, as the rehearsal continued. ``I turned him down for the
part. They came to me and said, `What about Ronald Reagan?' I said,
`He is good, but I don't think he'd be credible as a presidential
candidate.' I have always thought that if I had cast him, Melvyn
Douglas would have become president. It's been on my conscience
ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Vidal said his days of palling around with presidents ended with
the Kennedys: ``I learned my lesson from the Kennedys, which is if
you want to be effective as a commentator on political matters
you've got to stay away from presidents. I was continually attacked
as a Kennedy apologist.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had met Clinton only briefly and found him charming,
``and I'm not easily charmed by presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is another matter. The two are distant cousins through
Vidal's mother, though Vidal, in the polite way one talks about
strayed relatives, leaves little doubt at his disappointment _ or
perhaps disinterest _ in this particular member of the famous
family.
</P>
<P>
   Would he vote for his cousin? Vidal, at this point speaking from
his villa in Italy by telephone, laughed heartily at the question.
``As they say in the House of Representatives, at the end of the
day, Gore is thicker than Nader,'' he said, presumably meaning that
his blood-tie to Gore counted more than his ideological attraction
to Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Vidal said he had never met Gore, and does not
think it possible to learn much about him, or George W. Bush, from
the way presidential campaigns are conducted. ``We'll never know
whether they're interesting or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of himself, Vidal said that at his age, he had reached
the ``springtime of my senility.'' As sharp and acerbic as ever, he
is also white-haired, magisterial in bearing and a bit slow in his
gait. ``I don't do e-mail,'' he declared. He did not seem fazed at
the rehearsal when, during a break, Michael Learned asked if he
would autograph a copy of his 1967 historical novel, ``Washington,
D.C.'' He is about to publish ``The Golden Age,'' the concluding
volume in his series on American history.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal follows developments in American politics by way of CNN
and The International Herald Tribune from his home in Ravello,
though he is indignant at the suggestion that he is something of a
recluse, a subject he had raised himself as the lunch in Beverly
Hills had come to a quiet end, without dessert. ``The illusion that
the press has carefully developed, because my views are not popular
with management, is that I must be depicted as an exile _ an
embittered expatriate. I am no such thing, and they know it. I've
been involved in every election, in one way or another, as a
commentator, sometimes as a candidate, for most of my life. And
this, after all, is my subject as a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
