<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-ALI-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      08-30 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ALI-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN FOR THE COUNT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Thurs., Aud. 31.) 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali was the Greatest; ``Ali: An American Hero'' is the
Gratingest. This turgid, useless biopic of boxing legend Muhammad
Ali was shot at the same time as a similar ABC teleflick, but was
delayed when it became clear that ABC's rush job would hit the
screen first (to overwhelming indifference, it must be noted).
Between the networks, no one scores even a TKO; the only loser,
alas, is Ali, who must contend with these lame, diminishing
portraits.
</P>
<P>
   David Ramsey stars as Ali, who looks not even remotely like the
champ; frequently, he sounds nothing like him, as well. Since Ali
boasts one of the most famous mugs in the history of the 20th
century, from the outset this is a dubious project: No one, for a
second, will believe they're witnessing the heroics _ or the
inspired antics _ of boxing's most compelling hero. This is a
Bizarro-World Ali, and therefore, one we feel free not to empathize
with (and it's not Ramsey's fault _ it's the grievous error of the
producers).
</P>
<P>
   So we grudgingly follow the connect-the-dots high points of
Ali's career trajectory _ with, it seems, a little more emphasis on
his conversion to Islam than most biographies would have devoted
(due mainly, it seems, to the fact that Joe Morton gives a notable
turn as Malcolm X). It's all built around, predictably, Ali's
battle with George Foreman in Zaire, the legendary ``Rumble in the
Jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   Said ``Rumble'' _ which was definitively depicted in Leon Gast's
``When We Were Kings'' and can't possibly be improved upon here
(and, of course, isn't) _ provides the rudimentary basis for the
stupid flashback sequences; when we return to Ali preparing for his
rope-a-dope trick in Kinshasa, he even witnesses his essence as a
child, nodding to him approvingly. This is all you need to know to
understand that this movie is a specious piece of nonsense; it is
distressing, nonetheless, to realize that becoming World Champion
still can't protect one from such crummy, cynical and assaultive
biopics.
</P>
<P>
   ---Mama mia! &QL; 
David Proval, who nearly capered away with the past season from
``The Sopranos'' as the murderous Richie _ and still found time to
play a rabbi (!) on an episode of ``The West Wing'' _ will appear
in a recurring role this season on the Emmy-nominated sitcom
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' as an Italian patriarch who definitely
does not approve of Robert (Brad Garrett) as a potential
son-in-law. Proval promises that this character is, in fact, not a
mobster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' celebrated its 100th episode Tuesday
night at Spago in Beverly Hills. Les Moonves, CBS CEO, called
``Raymond'' the most important series of his tenure _ which,
obviously, includes ``Survivor.'' The show survived an uninspired
first season _ buried on Friday nights _ to become CBS' top-rated
entertainment series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raymond's'' season opener will find Ray (Ray Romano) and his
family on vacation in Rome (the episode was shot on location),
where they encounter Proval's character. The 100th episode finds
Marie (Doris Roberts) inadvertently slamming her car through Ray's
front door, inspiring a testy round of family therapy in which Ray
and his long-suffering wife, Debra (Patricia Heaton), allow their
long-contained hostilities toward Ray's parents finally explode.
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
The show: ``Ali: An American Hero.'' &QL; 
What: TV biopic about the boxing great. &QL; 
The stars: David Ramsey, Joe Morton, Vondie Curtis-Hall, Clarence
Williams III. &QL; 
Where: Fox (Channel 11). &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
