<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLOGY0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford, United face their crises with apologies from the top
 &HT;    By Scott Leith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Corporate America is learning to do something that's
old hat to most folks.
</P>
<P>
   Say ``sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the subtext of TV commercials from Ford Motor Co.
concerning the Firestone tire fiasco and from United Airlines about
a summerlong spate of flight delays and cancellations. The ads
feature top executives vowing to set things right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the most effective way to deal with a crisis is full
disclosure, right upfront,'' said Jeff Springston, an associate
professor of advertising and marketing at the University of
Georgia. ``The public will forgive mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fessing up is a departure from years past, when bad news was
often hidden or ignored. Today that stance can be dangerous with a
marketplace that expects contrition.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers also want speed. Coca-Cola Co. and Coca-Cola
Enterprises were criticized last year for the way they handled a
costly product recall in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's former chief executive, M. Douglas Ivester, flew to
Europe to apologize in person. But the company still was seen as
slow to deal with the image crisis _ one of the factors that led to
Ivester's abrupt retirement a few months later and spurred ongoing
changes within the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company only has a very small window of time,'' said Leanne
Hand, senior vice president for public relations at WestWayne, an
Atlanta ad agency. ``It makes an indelible impression as to how
they treat their customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson set the standard for good crisis management
during the infamous Tylenol tamperings nearly 20 years ago. Tylenol
mounted an immediate recall, along with nationwide ads featuring
Johnson &AMP; Johnson's medical director asking for continued trust of
the brand.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the spectrum, Exxon was perceived as
arrogant after the Valdez oil spill in 1989. ``We've always held
Exxon up as sort of the `poster child' for not really stepping out
with a quick response,'' said Andy Bowen, vice president of
Fletcher Martin Ewing, a public relations firm in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news can heavily tarnish a brand. Remember ValuJet? A year
after the 1996 crash in the Florida Everglades, Atlanta-based
ValuJet was still struggling. Its recovery only began when it
merged with AirTran Airways of Orlando and adopted the smaller
carrier's name as part of an image makeover.
</P>
<P>
   United, whose service troubles snarled summer travel for
thousands of passengers, decided to air an apology featuring Jim
Goodwin, the chairman of parent UAL Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who's leading us through this,'' said United
spokesman Matthew Triaca. Goodwin was always the first choice for
the ad, which addresses United's severe service disruptions. ``For
us not to have him would immediately take credibility away.''
</P>
<P>
   Triaca declined to say how much United is spending on the ads,
which will continue through this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ford commercials, company President and CEO Jacques
Nasser offers an earnest message. He doesn't apologize for
Firestone's defective tires, although he pledges that Ford will
help fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Firestones are made by Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. of Nashville,
a subsidiary of Bridgestone Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Brown, a Ford spokeswoman, said the automaker was
inundated with calls after the Firestone recall began. Ford felt it
had to provide its own response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, of course, a Firestone tire that is the issue, but
Firestone has been a supplier to Ford for almost the whole 100
years we've been in business,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser's second ad appeared this week and will run for another
week. Firestone ran its own TV ads over the weekend, featuring an
executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Are Ford's ads working? That depends on who's watching. Bob
Garfield, a critic for Advertising Age magazine, thought Nasser was
a ``distraction'' in the first ad, wearing ``the world's ugliest
$4,000 Italian suit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore, his arms go up and down, to and fro, not like a
charismatic executive, but like an animatronic rodent at Chuck E.
Cheese,'' Garfield wrote. Nonetheless, Garfield credited the Nasser
spots with calling more attention to Ford's message.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said Ford and Firestone both reacted predictably. ``Your
first inclination in a situation like this is to become
defensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Sallot, an associate professor of public relations at UGA,
said the companies could have been better prepared. ``They should
have a crisis plan on the shelf,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout could be troubling for a venerable company such as
Firestone, which turns 100 this year. ``One bad incident, handled
incorrectly, can have lasting effects,'' Hand said.
</P>
<P>
   Springston, of UGA, said there's still a risk when apologies are
issued because they can be seen as empty unless promises of better
performance are kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``What speaks even louder is actual behavior,'' Springston said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
