<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney blasts Gore over military policy
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Republican vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney used
a sweep through Georgia on Wednesday to blast Democrat Al Gore for
``running down the military.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 25-minute speech repeatedly punctuated by applause from
veterans and GOP stalwarts, Cheney said the U.S. military is
``headed down the wrong road'' because of cutbacks by the
Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Mounting a successful Gulf War-type operation would be difficult
today, said Cheney, who was secretary of defense during the Bush
administration, during his address at a Buckhead hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``To point out that our military has been overextended, taken
for granted and neglected _ that is no criticism of the military,''
Cheney said. ``That is a criticism of a president and a vice
president and the record they have built together.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the running mate of GOP presidential nominee George W.
Bush, has repeated the military readiness theme in recent campaign
appearances. His stop in Georgia during a three-day Southern tour
also helped raise money for the GOP ticket. A GOP fund-raiser at
another Buckhead hotel generated at least $600,000, most of it for
use in the Georgia presidential contest. Over the last decade,
Cheney said, military commitments worldwide have escalated 300
percent while U.S. military forces were being cut by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the percentage of money spent by the U.S. on
defense is at a 60-year low, and only 65 percent of the Air Force's
combat units and 60 percent of the Army's helicopter fleets are up
to mission standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will prepare the military of the future,'' Cheney vowed.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Georgia immediately noted that Cheney oversaw
military cuts during the Bush administration _ a point Cheney
obliquely referred to in the speech as ``cutting what was no longer
needed and nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides to Gore, the Democratic presidential nominee,
have accused Cheney of focusing on a toothless defense argument to
deflect attention from Bush's lack of a specific plan to provide
access to health care coverage for millions of uninsured children
and prescription drug coverage for the elderly on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personal memory people have,'' said Georgia Democratic
Party chairman David Worley, ``is of the Bush administration
wanting to close military institutions across the state and
(then-Democratic U.S. Sen.) Sam Nunn kept them open.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of about 250 people in attendance _ including decorated
military veterans appearing in support of Cheney _ insisted the
military issue will ring true in the conservative South, where
military installations are bread-and-butter for many communities
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impressed, glad and happy because somebody is finally
saying what the truth is,'' said Jim Walsh, a 27-year Army veteran.
``If this just gets out past the spin- meisters, people will
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
