</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMOS-OPERA-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HIS STAGES, LIFE IS BUT A DREAM, A LAMOS SIGNATURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Lamos belongs to two worlds, in more ways than
one. First, he seemed headed for a career as a classical violinist,
a phase that lasted through four years at Northwestern University
on a music scholarship. Then he discovered the theater, where his
acting career lifted off in felicitous fashion, with an early
Broadway appearance as the heartthrob Christian de Neuvillette
opposite the Cyrano de Bergerac of Christopher Plummer and a
subsequent Hamlet at the Old Globe in San Diego. Next, Lamos
settled down as a director, first of straight plays, then also of
opera. At 54, he works steadily in both genres. The combination,
while not unique, is scarcely common. The track record, be it said,
is exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, his mind is on Donizetti's ``Roberto Devereux,''
which opens the New York City Opera season at the New York State
Theater on Sept. 12. Lauren Flanigan, his colleague on several
previous occasions, plays the starring role of Queen Elizabeth,
once played to iconic perfection on this stage by Beverly Sills.
Thanks to popular revivals (``Madama Butterfly,'' ``Tosca,'' ``The
Turn of the Screw'') and a transfer from Glimmerglass Opera (``Acis
and Galatea''), the season shapes up as an informal Mark Lamos
retrospective, with the director's signature on more than one in
three of the company's 14 productions.
</P>
<P>
   What is that signature?
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kellogg, long the artistic director at Glimmerglass and now
also at City Opera, who has been presenting Lamos' work since 1990,
puts it this way: ``On the whole, and certainly when Mark works for
us, there's a unifying clarity and freshness that I consider his
hallmark.''
</P>
<P>
   A vague answer, perhaps inevitably so. Unlike several brand-name
colleagues, Lamos has never settled down with a single designer or
circle of designers whose look might give his productions an
obvious stamp. Nor is he a slave to directorial theory. Sometimes
he mounts productions in period, sometimes he transposes. Above
all, he is a poet of the theater, if by poetry you mean not
embellishment and airy nothings but, as Lamos does, a property of
thought. His word for this is ``concentration,'' the arrangement of
all the elements of a production to point to one core truth.
</P>
<P>
   His dark, thick crop of hair brushed out of his face, dressed in
ivory ducks, a navy button-down shirt and the wire-rim glasses of
the inveterate bookworm, the director is unwinding at Calle Ocho, a
humming Pan-Latin eatery, just steps from the new Rose Center for
Earth and Space in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Might I look in on a rehearsal? Sorry, no visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Could we look at some drawings?
</P>
<P>
   I happen to know that the City Opera press department has
stuffed Lamos' backpack with color copies of what I hear are
eye-catching set designs by Andrew Lieberman and sumptuous,
period-inspired costumes by Judy Levin. They are not forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Please, could we talk about the show?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not,'' Lamos replies, smiling at his martini, not
ungraciously. ``I work off instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversation through dinner is by no means the ordeal this
opening may suggest. On any number of topics, Lamos swats the ball
back and forth with nimble, unguarded ease. His recent relocation
from Hartford to the Connecticut countryside, gardening, backstage
politics, his latest musical discoveries, his fondness for intimate
dinners, his horror of cocktail parties: all these yield delightful
volleys.
</P>
<P>
   Productions in progress are another story. ``We work in a dream
state,'' Lamos once told a roomful of directing interns, as good an
explanation as any of his reticence. On the subject of
``Devereux,'' he eventually relents a little: ``I'm feeling very
good about the production,'' he says. ``But I keep wondering. What
is it we're saying here? We're still conceiving to a certain
extent.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the auteur _ a director whose vision is the driving
creative force of a collaborative work _ belongs to film criticism,
but the phenomenon, if not the label, exists in the theater, too.
Robert Wilson definitely qualifies; Peter Sellars probably does;
Jonathan Miller may. Lamos definitely does not. One director he
does recall is Giorgio Strehler: similarly light in touch, catholic
in his tastes and inventive in making stage pictures that speak,
equally at home in straight plays and opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an interpreter,'' Lamos says. ``There's a school of
thought that says it's not good directing unless the director's
hand is unseen. That's not my view. I think that I'm present in a
production, but that the material remains in the realm the creator
intended. My attitude probably comes from being a musician. You
learn how to play a Bach partita or a Mendelssohn sonata or the
Copland Sonata, and you find a different voice for each but a voice
that is your own, because that's who you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same with acting. You use a different energy with
Shakespeare than you do with Shaw or with a new piece. You're
always releasing yourself into the piece and making it your own.
You're finding a voice somehow: a voice that is yours but works
with the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Directing simply extends the process. Ideally, what results is a
collaboration in which the sense of ownership extends to everyone
on the team. At the design stage, Lamos may set the compass for a
certain direction, but once the cast is assembled, the voyage
unfolds according to its own dynamic. ``Everything in rehearsal is
negotiation,'' Lamos says. ``If you have a tenor who is a stick and
you want a tenor who moves like a dancer, you're just going to be
unhappy. You have to find a way to make the show work with the cast
you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Free-associate through memories of Lamos productions past, and
what comes to mind? Pictures, mainly:
</P>
<P>
   --A cross-legged Oberon, king of the fairies in ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream'' (the play), hanging upside down over a quadrille of
wrangling lovers as they splash through a pond.
</P>
<P>
   --``Hedda Gabler'' played on a blood-red floor against
bone-white walls, ``a state of mind with furniture,'' as Lamos once
called it.
</P>
<P>
   --Helena, in ``All's Well That Ends Well,'' waltzing the
moribund king of France from his four-poster deathbed with
corkscrew columns.
</P>
<P>
   --Richard Thomas as Hamlet in some mad banana republic, with the
court grandstanding to ubiquitous hand-held news cameras, long
before such technology had degenerated into cliche.
</P>
<P>
   --Massenet's Werther expiring in a frozen tornado of his own
love letters.
</P>
<P>
   --Jerry Hadley's Gatsby, in the premiere of John Harbison's
opera, materializing from nowhere at the top of a staircase, for
one brief, shining moment the dreamboat and the enigma Fitzgerald
meant the character to be.
</P>
<P>
   --Wozzeck's shadow splayed like a crucifix against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   And toys. Toys in abundance. Rocking horses (``Peer Gynt,''
``All's Well That Ends Well''). Doll's houses, some big enough for
actors to take up residence in (``Tiny Alice,'' ``School for
Wives''). Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' Lamos answers. ``I enjoy the scale of toys
onstage, even giant ones, against the live performers. In `Antony
and Cleopatra,' the battle of Actium was staged with war toys _
tiny ships on a map of the sea that burst into flames. Then A. and
C. collapsed with shame and regret in the midst of the wreckage. I
sense a nostalgia inherent in toys. For children, they represent an
artificial adulthood. For adults, an irrecoverable past. They are
iconic, completely representational. Like theater itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6627 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LAMOS-OPERA-$ADV03-NY     08-30 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMOS-OPERA-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: theater itself.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   A string of epiphanies, ephemeral as epiphanies are bound to be.
Yet two of Lamos' productions shine in memory with a brightness
time has not touched.
</P>
<P>
   One is ``Il Re Pastore'' (``The Shepherd King''), at
Glimmerglass. Minor Mozart, this early piece was written to
instruct a young archduke in the virtue of magnanimity. Around the
buckram of moral preachment, Lamos fashioned a silken
``entertainment for royal children,'' set in a schoolroom furnished
with blackboard, alphabet blocks and a cradle. Onstage, pint-size
extras appeared in gold paper crowns, spellbound as the cardboard
characters of the plot came to life: mellifluous role models,
enacted by the court tutors, starry storybook princes twinkling
with benevolence that ennobled (and momentarily rejuvenated) even
jaded oldsters out front in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was ``The Rivals'' at the Hartford Stage, a
production fit to have crowned any drama festival on the planet.
Sheridan's featherweight plot involves two pairs of young lovers,
each pair perfectly matched but for the dizzy romantic caprices of
one of the ladies and the pathological jealousy of one of the
beaus. The characters and their meddlesome elders are easy prey for
slapstick, especially in the carnivals of artifice to which British
comedy of the 18th century is usually reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond the frippery, powdered wigs and innuendo, Lamos
discovered in Sheridan's sentimental entanglements a clear-eyed yet
mellow (sometimes melancholy) affection for human foibles we may
well call Mozartean. Malaprop herself, fount and origin of torrents
of pompous poppycock, showed within her Amazonian affectations the
disarming vulnerability of a fading belle. For an equally tactful
and generous vision of the human comedy, one would have to go back
to Ingmar Bergman's thoroughly atypical ``Smiles of a Summer
Night'' or to Goldoni's ``Arlecchino, Servant of Two Masters'' in
Strehler's well-traveled, much-revived production. (Someday, Lamos
must direct Verdi's ``Falstaff.'')
</P>
<P>
   As chance or mystic correspondence would have it, Sheridan's
comedy and Mozart's little pastorale date to 1775, the same charmed
year. That these most inspired of Lamos' productions both arise
from the literature of the enlightenment is no coincidence at all.
On the cumulative evidence of his work, the 18th-century ideals of
classical balance and harmony are his as well. (They were
Strehler's, too, as evidenced in his Mozart and Goldoni, whose
Arlecchino first stepped out in 1745.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Balance is where I naturally go,'' Lamos says. ``Sometimes to
the detriment of the play if the play isn't doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The caveat is perhaps unjust. More than a radical perspective,
an enlightened mind-set opens doors to worlds governed by laws
other than one's own. Here, too, may lie the key to Lamos' ease in
bridging the chasm between plays and operas. Attuned as he is to
their surface differences (and to the different working methods
those differences impose), Lamos perceives a musicality in action
and a structure in melody, which form their common ground.
</P>
<P>
   He has downed his decaf espresso. The night being balmy, we head
home on foot. Under the street lamp by his door, Lamos surrenders
the ``Devereux'' designs.
</P>
<P>
   What have we here?
</P>
<P>
   A marquee framed in light bulbs. Hard edges, strong verticals,
stark diagonals. A color scheme dominated by red and black. Looming
cutouts of Elizabeth in repeating formation, very sacramental.
Framed glamour shots of divas of yesteryear. A checkerboard floor
emblazoned, square by square with a portrait of the Virgin Queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about images of kingship,'' Lamos explains. Hmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using this,'' he warns, pointing out one striking
detail. ``And this area is different now.''
</P>
<P>
   Am I surprised?
</P>
<P>
   Experience has taught me that images in progress can look
stranger than what audiences see, usually more cluttered, mostly
less wondrous but sometimes more so. At a late rehearsal of Lamos'
original staging of ``The Turn of the Screw,'' the character of the
housekeeper came hulking onstage in a greatcoat lumpily studded
with dolls. Toys lost in action. Also on the casualty list: a tyke
in an angel suit, who walked Luciano Pavarotti onstage at the final
dress for the dream vision of Verdi's ``Lombardi,'' the occasion of
Lamos' Metropolitan Opera debut, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a mistake to lose him,'' I suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``So do I,'' says Lamos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the Met want you to get rid of him? Did Luciano?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No. It was my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   How often, I wonder, is Lamos happy with a production?
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy?'' he replies. ``I'm never happy. Or very rarely. The
fun in the work comes when I see an idea transformed by the
performers and the sets and the costumes and the lights into
something far beyond what I ever imagined it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Editing dreams is delicate work.
</P>
<P>
   Postscript, via e-mail, under the ironic, mock-Teutonic subject
line ``DEVEREUX Konzept'':
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean to be coy,'' Lamos writes from cyberspace. ``I
was intrigued by the cult of Elizabeth, the Tudor myth that her
reign continually worked to uphold: the Virgin Queen, Gloriana.
What we have in the design is a world of iconography. This is
Elizabeth's world, not only as she created it for herself but as
interpreters (Donizetti, Bette Davis, etc.) recreated it. And
ultimately she is trapped in advertisements for herself, the
advertisements that kept her myths alive and kept her ruling for as
long as she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intersection of queens and divas: that's here, too. Hence
the high-contrast photos of famous divas hanging in front of the
repeated portraits of the young Virgin Queen that jut out from the
wings as if spying on the other characters. We're not so much
concerned with making the opera look like history (as the
production by Tito Capobianco with Beverly Sills attempted to do).
We want to watch the major character being trapped in her own world
of self-deception.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see why I don't, as you point out, theorize. As Peter
Brook said, as soon as a theory in the performing arts makes itself
evident, another production comes along and that requires a whole
different set of theories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or something like that!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
