<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Undersized work force puts NASA at `critical juncture'
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MARK CARREAU
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   An aging, undersized work force that has shown signs of
job-related stress will be hard-pressed to fly NASA's shuttle
safely as the agency increases the flight rate to assemble the
international space station, congressional auditors warned
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on NASA's internal assessments, the U.S. General
Accounting Office identified 26 technical skill areas, ranging from
computer software work to mechanical engineering, that will require
increased staffing at the Johnson Space Center in Houston and other
spaceflight facilities in Florida, Alabama and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has reached a ``critical juncture,'' the GAO
said, because its shuttle program work force dropped from 3,000
federal workers in 1995 to 1,800 when NASA stopped the decline last
December.
</P>
<P>
   The drop was part of a wider effort by the Clinton
administration to reduce the federal work force to balance the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Space agency officials embraced the GAO report, because the
findings essentially echoed a much harsher assessment of shuttle
safety issues prepared by NASA itself in response to an electrical
short that accompanied the July 1999 launching of the shuttle
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   That incident prompted the Clinton administration to seek an
increase in shuttle spending and NASA to begin a sharp increase in
the number of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a very fair report,'' said Kirsten Williams, a
Washington-based spokeswoman for NASA's shuttle program. ``In a
balanced way it describes the challenges the shuttle program is
facing.''
</P>
<P>
   During the five-year period examined by the GAO, NASA's shuttle
launch rate dropped from eight in 1997 to just three in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the slowdown was because of Russian economic problems
that delayed the launch of the new station's habitat module by more
than two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-built Zvezda crew living and working quarters
finally joined two other orbiting components of the fledgling
outpost on July 25. That milestone broke the logjam of U.S. station
components waiting to be launched on the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Even with fewer missions, the GAO found areas where NASA's
declining workforce was stretched. Where it was the thinnest, the
auditors said, NASA noted signs of overwork and stress, including
forfeited leave, absences from training classes and calls for
stress-related assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties of NASA's declining work force were further
compounded by its worker demographics, the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency employs twice as many workers ages 60 or older
than those younger than 30, a trend that signals a further loss of
experienced personnel when their skills are needed most. The
auditors noted that it typically takes two years to train a new
hire and that the schooling often interferes with other job demands
when there is a worker shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the agency has been authorized to add 550 workers
by Oct. 1 at the Johnson, Kennedy, Marshall and Stennis space
centers to support a range of shuttle and station activities. The
shuttle program had 94 new hires by the end of July, said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, NASA's prime shuttle contractor, United Space
Alliance, has increased by 250 to a total of 3,850 the number of
technicians who prepare shuttle hardware for launch from Kennedy in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our work force is up. The training is in place. We are doing
the early preparations that will put us in an extremely good
posture to fly seven to eight flights a year,'' NASA shuttle
program manager Ron Dittemore said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that with the low flight rates of the past
few years, NASA will have to re-acclimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is there, and it will be a challenging effort for us
to put everything together,'' said Dittemore. ``There is a
confidence we can do it. It's not an overconfidence. We are being
very cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO's 20-page report was prepared for the U.S. Senate's
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee, which has NASA
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
