<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-BANKS-NYT &LR;      08-30 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACQUISITION HIGHLIGHTS SWISS FLARE FOR MANAGING EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Credit Suisse Group's planned acquisition of
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, following hard on the heels of the
deal for PaineWebber by the Swiss banking giant, UBS AG, is likely
to provide further illustration of Swiss banking's flair for
penetrating Wall Street and managing the cultural clashes that
expansion outside Europe often brings.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss early on sensed the need to expand beyond a domestic
market of seven million. And they seem, more than their European
neighbors, to have learned from missteps and become better able to
balance the need in financial businesses between autonomy and
control.
</P>
<P>
   This ability to adapt is increasingly crucial as European banks
break out of their traditional national markets. Many, seeking to
grow in size and gain expertise in banking skills less developed in
Continental Europe, are acquiring banks in Britain and the United
States. The pressure to do so has intensified as European capital
markets have unified, spurred by the creation of a single currency.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service businesses from corporate banking to personal
investment are increasingly shedding the tightly cosseted and
closely managed rules of European finance to take on more of the
freewheeling, creative quality common in Britain and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Deutsche Bank expanded its U.S. presence
by acquiring Bankers Trust for $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Zieschang, an analyst at Bank Julius Baer in Zurich,
said it was the Swiss who pioneered the penetration of the
Anglo-Saxon banking world. In 1995, the old Swiss Bank Corp., which
merged two years later with Union Bank of Switzerland to form UBS,
acquired SG Warburg, a British investment bank with a sizable Wall
Street presence. Swiss Bank also acquired two small but valuable
firms in Chicago: O'Connor Associates, a derivatives business, and
Brinson Asset Management, a money management firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Swiss were aware at an earlier stage of the critical
importance of growing internationally,'' Zieschang said.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse had moved even before then. In 1978, it
established a joint venture with the Bank of Boston Corp. called
Financiere Credit Suisse First Boston. That was very much a
learning experience, said Bryan Crossley, an analyst at ABN Amro in
London. In 1988, Credit Suisse First Boston was beleaguered by
duplication and friction, not least because of financial fallout
from the stock market crash the previous autumn, prompting Credit
Suisse in Zurich to take full control. In the process, it acquired
a global investment bank and a powerful calling card in New York,
London and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that business, it can be pretty ruthless,'' Crossley said.
``You can spill blood, but can make it a clean cut.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also the Swiss who moved earliest in consolidating the
European banking market, in 1997, when Union Bank and Swiss Bank
startled the financial world by announcing the merger to form UBS,
then the world's biggest bank by assets.
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Borer, a financial analyst at Bank Vontobel in Zurich,
says that what is driving the Swiss overseas is also the thirst for
size. ``They're very big and they want to be very, very big,''
Borer said. With PaineWebber, she said, UBS ``essentially bought
assets under management.'' With Donaldson, Lufkin, Credit Suisse is
getting size in investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern is familiar, she said, and the Swiss have plenty of
competition. In January, Citigroup announced it was acquiring the
investment banking business of Schroders of London for about $2.2
billion; several months later, Chase Manhattan agreed to buy Robert
Fleming Holdings, the British investment bank with substantial
operations in Asia, for $7.7 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts point to the considerable experience that Marcel
Ospel, the chairman of UBS, has had with American acquisitions.
Ospel played a role in Swiss Bank's acquisition of Warburg, a move
that some say threw the drive for British and American properties
into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Zieschang called him a ``front runner in opening to Anglo-Saxon
influence.'' Ospel and Lukas Muhlemann, chief executive of Credit
Suisse Group, are both 50, part of a younger generation in Swiss
banking and insurance. Like Ospel, Muhlemann, a former McKinsey
consultant and insurance executive, has also understood the value
of integration. Muhlemann, for instance, rotated Credit Suisse
First Boston's chief financial officer, Richard E. Thornburgh,
between Zurich and New York to deepen trans-Atlantic ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss hand in dealing with outsiders has not always proven
infallible, Borer said. For instance, efforts by Credit Suisse to
impose less lucrative European compensation schemes on Credit
Suisse First Boston's American bankers failed, she said, and Credit
Suisse was forced to backtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Vasco Moreno, who follows banking at the London
brokers Fox Pitt Kelton, ``the Swiss appear to be able to make it
stick more than other European institutions.'' In part, Moreno
said, that may be because the Swiss seem to be more culturally
aligned with the Anglo-Saxon way of doing business. The fact that
Swiss bankers, during the daily course of business in their own
country, have to deal with three different cultural groups and
three different languages may also be a reason they are more
adaptable.
</P>
<P>
   This does not, however, always mean they are welcome. Zieschang
noted that Josef Ackermann, a former Credit Suisse executive who
joined Deutsche Bank's management board in 1997, has been the focus
of friction and disputes that some attribute in part to his being
an outsider.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   AXA, the French financial services conglomerate that owns 72
percent of Donaldson, is shedding the unit because it ``was not
prepared to spend the capital to be a player in global investment
banking,'' said Crossley of ABN Amro.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expect AXA to use the proceeds to expand its asset
management business through acquisitions, notably in the United
States, following its big European competitors. Last year, Aegon NV
of the Netherlands paid almost $10 billion to acquire the
TransAmerica Corp. of San Francisco; earlier, the ING Group of the
Netherlands spent almost $15 billion buying various insurance
businesses from Aetna. In June, AXA Financial paid $3.5 billion
through an affiliate to buy the Wall Street broker Sanford C.
Bernstein Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Muhlemann of Credit Suisse has long been an advocate of
cross-fertilization of banking and insurance services. In 1997, the
year he took over as head of Credit Suisse, he bought the
Winterthur Insurance Co. Wednesday's cash-and-stock deal makes AXA
one of Credit Suisse's biggest shareholders, with a 10 percent
stake. It also stirred widespread speculation that Credit Suisse
might use the 5.5 percent share it holds in Swiss Life, another
insurer, as partial payment. Credit Suisse denied that this would
happen, but if it did, it would also leave AXA a major shareholder
in Swiss Life, weaving further links in Europe's financial services
industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
