<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-COMPUTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTING WITH THE OUTDOORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ News travels quickly through the Santa Monica
Mountains National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the park's self-taught computer specialist, Mike
Maki, envisioned it a year ago when he designed an Intranet
patterned after a similar system at Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation Area is among the
country's few national parks to have its own Intranet, an internal
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Intranet allows more than 100 employees in remote offices,
spread throughout the 153,000-acre region stretching from Santa
Monica to Thousand Oaks, to view a frequently-asked-questions page,
newsletters, input vehicle reports, post bulletins and communicate
via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation Area
lies in Maki's office in the Visitors Center in Thousand Oaks,
which is cluttered with books, CDs and three monitors. The park's
computers are linked to four servers in Maki's office, one for
mail, another for files and a third for the Intranet. The fourth is
a backup. The servers resemble nothing more than personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Maki, 40, had the system running in only one weekend, but it has
continually evolved with hundreds of hours of work. The Thousand
Oaks resident supervises the network of 100 computers, most in
outlying offices in Newbury Park, Calabasas, Agoura Hills and Los
Angeles. He is working on a project to convert to a higher-speed
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system is on the leading edge. He is just a great
resource,'' said Marilynn Sutton, Santa Monica Mountains National
Recreation Area Chief of Administration. ``He is able to
communicate to people with varying degrees of computer knowledge
and make some sense with everyone. He is very patient and friendly,
but most of all he adds the human touch to computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Computers have always been a hobby for Maki, a former volleyball
player at Cal State Northridge who rattles off terms like
bandwidth, packet size and window servers UNIX and LINUX as second
nature.
</P>
<P>
   But the West Hills native was not the typical techy nerd when he
joined the National Park Service in 1986, as he had visions of
becoming a consulting archeologist after graduating with a geology
degree. In fact, the position of computer specialist did not exist
within the Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Maki started as a seasonal interpretive ranger at Channel
Islands National Park, leading hikes before working as a
law-enforcement ranger over the next five years. He spent his time
operating a boat or living on one of the five islands in the park,
serving as a caretaker on an island. The ranger station at San
Miguel consisted of a converted cargo box with no other
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Maki transferred to the Santa Monica Mountains National
Recreation Area as a supervisory ranger for the Conejo District. In
1998, Maki was named as the park's computer specialist. The
position's conventional working hours have allowed Maki, a father
of two, to spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do miss the great outdoors of the park, but I truly enjoy
this extremely dynamic and fast-paced career,'' Maki said. ``I
don't miss working the nights, weekends or holidays. Supervising
computers is a lot easier than people.''
</P>
<P>
   Maki is on 24-hour call, but the typical crisis involves
troubleshooting, helping employees log on or accessing e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Troubleshooting takes up about half his time, with another 20
percent devoted to backing up files. The remainder is devoted to
keeping up with personal enrichment and technology through the
Internet and magazines. Maki recently completed certification in
managing routers through a course at Moorpark College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a steep learning curve,'' Maki said. ``Keeping up with
technology is half the battle. Just maintaining a network, you will
start to fall behind. You're always looking for creative ways to
increase speed. There are probably opportunities in the corporate
world, but it is nice to be part of an agency with a mission I
agree with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
