<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-CHENEY0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP camp in disarray on issues
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Appropriately enough for a period when his campaign
finds itself on the defensive, Republican vice presidential
candidate Dick Cheney came to town Wednesday to speak on the
nation's military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating one of the themes that seemed to be resounding so well
at the beginning of this month, when the Republicans roared their
approval of him in Philadelphia, Cheney charged that the current
administration is leading the military ``down the wrong road.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Atlanta speech, Gov. George W. Bush's running mate also
said Al Gore was taking unfair advantage of Pentagon officials when
the vice president claims ``all is well'' in the military.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta speech was part of a day of talking tax cuts and
military spending across a region where that message has a deep
resonance. But the fact that Cheney was in the South, pounding in
this particular message as August draws to a close, says something
about the shifting tides of the presidential campaign as it draws
close to Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The squishy summer polls were never very reliable anyway, so the
Republicans should not lament the tightening to what is currently a
neck-and-neck race. Most Americans were talking about this being a
close race before they actually began reflecting that opinion in
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   What should be of greater concern to the Bush camp is the
disarray in which it finds itself over issues such as prescription
drugs, where Gore is making headway at the moment with the general
proposition that his policy proposals have more depth.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republican National Committee put up an ad on
prescription drugs in Georgia and other states, the Gore campaign
arranged a conference call with former FDA Director David Kessler,
now dean of Yale University Medical School, to blast the ad as
``disingenuous'' and ``false and misleading'' for claiming to have
a plan Bush hasn't covered in his budget estimates.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the same attack in which Gore currently jabs at
Bush over their debate negotiations, saying Americans need ``an
intelligent, adult discussion.'' And until the Republicans can
steady themselves and come back with a counterpunch, the strategy
is having its effect.
</P>
<P>
   To return for a moment to the subject of military readiness,
here is the very last sentence of a Reuters dispatch about Bill
Clinton's visit to Colombia on Wednesday, which was marked by a
bomb scare and a pledge of $1.3 billion in U.S. aid for the war
against what is still not a very well understood assortment of
narco-terrorists and leftist guerillas:
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. officials are going to great lengths to try to refute any
notion that the aid package is an initial step in getting involved
in a Vietnam-like quagmire in Colombia.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to have that long a memory, or be a defense
analyst, to hear an ominous tone in that sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Quagmires do not have to be ``Vietnam-like'' to be quagmires.
Neither campaign has had much to say about Colombia, which for the
moment is still thought of within the framework of U.S. drug
policy, which both parties support.
</P>
<P>
   But if the military is in fact going down the wrong road, it
would probably lead to a jungle where, until the consequences
become evident, everybody thought we ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
