<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-FLYFISHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAIGHTEN UP AND FLY RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Bob Blackburn just wanted to cast his fly
fishing line better.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Pasadena resident found out - and it took him 1
years to learn - is that he needed to be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn recently became a certified Fly Fishing Federation fly
caster instructor, an honor only 800 anglers worldwide hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through their drill,'' he recalls, ``and they were
telling me I was not ready. I had to practice, practice, practice.
It was like remodeling the house. I had to tear that old house
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Casters must pass a written, oral and 2-hour performance test to
receive the certificate. The performance test must be made in front
of a member of the federation's board of governors or in front of
two certified instructors. Casters must perform control, accuracy
and distance casts and instructing ability. They must perform the
technique once and if it's not done perfectly that one time, they
fail. Tests are held only once a year, and the Southwest Council's
test is traditionally held during the Fred Hall Show in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we had a need for a program like this,''
certificate chair and board of governors member Floyd Franke said
from his Bozeman, Mont., office. ``We didn't want just anybody to
be teaching. The board felt that it is a major responsibility to
teach fly fishing instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The federation began offering the certificate in 1992 and Bruce
Richards of the federation board says about half the applicants
fail the test on their first try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want very high standards,'' Franke says. ``We have to be
very strict in our expectations because we want to make sure people
that want instruction will be prepared accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Among some of the casts that must be done in the performance
test are loop casts, line control, roll casts, accurate false casts
of 20, 30 and 45 feet, roll casts between 45 and 50 feet, double
haul casts of between 45 and 50 feet and a distance cast of a
minimum of 75 feet. Casters then must explain and demonstrate
casting narrow to loops, the cause and correction of tail loops,
changing casting distances, false casting and casting in head and
tail winds.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federation offers a Masters certification
program, which further enhances the certificate level, and involves
saltwater techniques, too.
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn, 68, failed in his first attempt at certification. He
began practicing at the Pasadena Casting Club's casting pond in
Lower Arroyo Park six days a week, two to three hours each day.
</P>
<P>
   The retired shopping center developer says he learned to fly
fish with his father 56 years ago, gave up fishing but then
returned to the sport in 1990 when he joined the Pasadena club.
Shortly after joining, he began helping teach casting techniques at
the club's Sunday afternoon casting sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the point where I was casting at a certain level, but
I was not going anywhere,'' he said. ``I wanted to cast at that
next level.''
</P>
<P>
   And he discovered he wasn't teaching at a higher level, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not quite completely understand the kinetics, and I was
unable to communicate effectively with students and explain casting
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a certificate is like a two-sided coin. On one side you
become a better teacher. On the other side, a better caster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pasadena Casting Club has three other certified instructors,
Bill Smith, Bill Heath and Steve Lim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to help people and I felt like I had (to get the
certificate) to do that,'' said Smith, who lives in La Canada. ``I
have to admit, it focuses your attention on working on your
casting.''
</P>
<P>
   Anglers do not need to take any tests to teach fly casting, but
when someone calls seeking lessons, Blackburn says it helps to say
that he has a certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be teaching faults,'' he said. ``We want to
be short and concise and we need to learn how to help students
overcome situations, like when they cast sidearm. The hardest is
teaching casters who already have faults. You have to break down
their muscle memory.''
</P>
<P>
   And perfect casting must include working with anglers with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the test, they asked me about teaching a woman who has
had a mastectomy. I hadn't thought about that. She can't cast
straight up because she has lost muscle. So, she has to start with
a sidearm delivery and then make a circle for the cast.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, Blackburn admits the process has made him a
better angler; not because he is catching more fish, but because he
can cast to a wider variety of spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can now cast to different spots I couldn't reach before,''
he says. ``That gives me a situation where I have the possibility
to catch more fish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
