<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Aug. 31. The New York Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY (Atlanta) _ Dick Cheney delivers a harsh assessment of
the condition of the armed forces under President Clinton, accusing
him of ``running down'' a military that has succeeded in recent
conflicts only because of the military build-up of past Republican
administrations. By Michael Cooper. (We plan to move the story by 9
p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CLINTON (Cartagena, Colombia) _ President Clinton makes
a one-day visit here to lend backing to Colombia's
counter-narcotics effort, insisting that the military aid the
United States is sending is limited to fighting drugs, not ending
the Colombian government's decades-long battle with rebel groups.
By Marc Lacey. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   Story runs under a 3-column photo; with map.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WORKERS (Tianjin, China) _ The Meite Packaging factory
here is nearly deserted now, its managers and machines all hastily
transferred over the last two days to an isolated development zone.
Although the closure had long been planned, the precipitous
departure was necessitated by an extraordinary event: Last week,
desperate Chinese workers fearing layoffs kept six foreign managers
from Meite's U.S. parent company hostage in the factory for 40
hours. The workers' frustrations that sparked this unusual incident
are extremely commonplace, leading to hundreds of worker protests
in the last 3 years. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-VEEPS (Undated) _ Joseph Lieberman and Dick Cheney are
waging starkly different campaigns as they strike out on their own
for the first time since each party's national convention. Cheney
has largely kept a low profile, staging small events, sticking to a
safe speech script, generally staying clear of reporters from
national news organizations. Lieberman has been a more active
campaigner, drawing far larger crowds and attracting _ indeed
courting _ more media coverage. By David Barstow. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to inside CAMPAIGN story about Bush and Gore today.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ROBOTS-REPRODUCE (Undated) _ For the first time, computer
scientists have created a robot that designs and builds other
robots, almost entirely without human help or expertise. In the
short run, this advance could lead to a new industry of inexpensive
robots customized for specific tasks. In the long run _ decades at
least _ robots may one day be truly regarded as ``artificial life''
_ able to reproduce and evolve, building improved versions of
themselves. By Kenneth Chang. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT19.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NY-PRIMARY (New York) _ It is a primary race that has spawned a
soap opera-like drama. The bitterness of a feud between two
Democrats in the 11th Congressional District in Brooklyn has not
only torn apart a longstanding relationship but has delivered some
of that anguish to the doorstep of other politicians and voters in
the borough. But it is also a race that has brought to the surface
simmering _ and often unspoken _ unease between black New Yorkers
whose roots are in the United States and those with Caribbean
heritage. By Jonathan P. Hicks. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA-POLITICS (Mogadishu, Somalia) _ Somalia finally has a
government, and its first president in nearly a decade arrived here
escorted by at least 120 pickup trucks carrying more than 1,000
militiamen armed with rifles, rocket launchers, even
double-barreled antiaircraft guns. And just to be on the safe side,
the president wore a bullet-proof vest. By Ian Fisher. (The story
has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT18,19,20.
</P>
