<HEADER>
A6640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINA-CARTOONISTS-NYT     08-30 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CARTOONISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIDER-MAN SPRINGS INTO CHINA WITH MORE COMICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Spider-Man isn't scaling the Great Wall just yet. But
Stan Lee, the legendary impresario of Marvel Comic superheroes, was
in Beijing this week as an honored guest at a ``friendship
banquet'' of leading Japanese and Chinese cartoonists and
animators.
</P>
<P>
   And he just happened to bring along the president and chief
executive officer of Stan Lee Media, a year-old Internet venture
that dreams of marketing Lee's latest characters and products to
1.3 billion Chinese residents.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he had been invited to Beijing by the Japan-Asia Comics
Exchange Society of Tokyo and by The People's Daily, which jointly
sponsored the banquet and an associated museum exhibition of
Japanese animation drawings and Chinese cartoons. Just why the gray
official newspaper of the Chinese Communist Party was playing host
was not clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most thrilling experiences of my life to
speak before that group,'' Lee said after the banquet. ``It's the
first time Japanese and Chinese artists have been gathered together
in this way, and if anything can bring countries together, it's
cartoons.)
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 77, and the famous characters he helped create in the
heyday of Marvel Comics, including Spider-Man, the Incredible Hulk
and the X-Men, are scarcely known in China. But this month Stan Lee
Media, which is based in Encino, Calif., and calls itself a
``multimedia production, marketing and licensing company,'' formed
a partnership with a leading Japanese producer of animation, the
Venture Soft Co. The venture, perhaps helping explain the
invitation, aims to market Lee's animated Web series and associated
products in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel-era die-hards may have a hard time digesting some of
Lee's latest creations. True, there is a Web serial called ``The
Seventh Portal,'' featuring superheroes and villains out to conquer
the universe. But his latest projects include an animated Web
series featuring the Backstreet Boys as rock stars by day and
supercrusaders by night with a promotional tie-in at Burger King,
and another series presenting the R&AMP;B singer Mary J. Blige as a
warrior linked to a line of hip-hop clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using the Internet to launch new branded character
franchises,'' is how Stan Lee Media's chief executive, Ken
Williams, described the company in an interview. Williams is a
former head of Sony's digital studios division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seventh Portal,'' Williams said, is likely to reappear as
a live feature film, a ride at Paramount theme parks and a
conventional Saturday morning animated series, and toys are being
licensed.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes. ``Well, I think inevitably there will be comic
books,'' he said after being prodded. ``But comics are a relatively
minor part of the revenue stream.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that he and Lee were aware of the barriers to
artistic production or sales in China. But the praise Lee heard at
the banquet, he said, ``was a validation of Stan's work and a
validation of the idea of entering China with American-style
animation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be back, and we'll be exploring ways we can work in
China,'' Williams said. ``We'll be moving resolutely but
judiciously.''
</P>
<P>
   As Disney and other Western entertainment groups have
discovered, gaining access to produce films or Web content in China
or even to market imported products faces stiff obstacles. For
example, this year's X-Men movie, loosely based on the old comic
book, has not been approved for commercial screening in China,
which strictly limits film imports, although pirated video compact
discs sell well. This may soften somewhat after China joins the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese children often read translations of Japanese or
Taiwanese cartoon books and favor some Japanese animated serials
that are allowed on Chinese television. The domestic products tend
to be bland.
</P>
<P>
   China's political leaders have often expressed concern about an
influx of foreign animated cartoons, said William Brent, president
of China Entertainment Network, a consulting concern in Shanghai.
``They've repeatedly called for animation by the Chinese for the
Chinese,'' Mr. Brent said.
</P>
<P>
   Animated shows and other children's fare are closely scrutinized
by government censors who worry about excess violence as well as
what they deem inappropriate cultural or political content.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Stan Lee group thinks they can come into China and make
superheroes along Western lines, they'll be disappointed,'' Brent
said. ``If they can find a way to develop home-grown superheroes
here, they'll have a better chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
