<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6643 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     08-30 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL HOUSE TOUR ALLAYS URGE TO PEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I have what has been described as a ``sconce
problem,'' which explains why I like to loiter outside strangers'
houses at dusk and peer through the windows at their lighting
fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   The specialist who diagnosed this malady (my husband), has also
formed some preliminary theories about a related condition he calls
``coveting your neighbors' furniture arrangements.'' He believes
that both are incurable. The only recommended treatment is to take
the dog along on these ``walks'' to establish a plausible excuse
for lurking in case the police show up.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Pottery Barn started a Web site this month.
The site's Home Tour invites shoppers to examine a layout that
shows the entire first floor of a real house (belonging to a family
in Piedmont, Calif.), then click on any room to start nosing
around, I mean, touring the premises. It is a kind of home remedy
for people like me who want not only to gaze through a stranger's
windows, but also to get inside to take a closer look at those
sconces flanking the fireplace in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the tour was to immerse a shopper in the
atmosphere of a real house, where it is possible to imagine oneself
reading a book while lolling in the Marseilles Leather Armchair
($1,649) or rolling out pie dough on the Hampstead Marble-Top Prep
Table ($699) in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this is much safer than my old method of snooping,
because it will not lead to a misdemeanor charge. But it also has
the potential to be far more dangerous for a longtime Pottery Barn
addict like myself, because Pottery Barn replaced the real-life
furniture (and sconces) with items that you can buy online.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as a longtime customer _ I once considered a 12-step
program to wean myself from compulsive purchases of the company's
cotton velvet drapery panels _ I was dubious about whether the
company's new online component would add anything to the
tried-and-true Pottery Barn shopping experience. After all, for
years I had been seeing products displayed in real-room settings in
the company's catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   My skepticism was prompted by a twinge of resentment that I have
been harboring toward Pottery Barn's parent company, Williams
Sonoma Inc. The company has been slow to start online shopping
sites, a delay that has made it hard to compare prices.
</P>
<P>
   I do not want to sound whiny, but do you know what it is like,
every time you stumble across a promising home-furnishing product
online, to have to get up from the computer, walk down to the
kitchen bookshelf, dig through catalogs to find the latest Pottery
Barn offering, then page through the thing looking for some item _
a magazine rack, a cabinet knob _ that you vaguely remembered
seeing?
</P>
<P>
   After causing me such pain, Pottery Barn thinks it can tardily
waltz online and offer me a search function and all will be
forgotten?
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to take our time to focus on developing a model that
would really work, to develop an online visual and shopping
experience that would satisfy our customers,'' said Shelley
Nandkeolyar, vice president of the eCommerce division at Williams
Sonoma Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Grudgingly, I admitted the delay may have made business sense.
Although many other online home-furnishing retailers are flailing _
Living.com went out of business earlier this month and
Furniture.com barely avoided the same fate earlier this summer with
a last-minute infusion of cash _ it is a good time for
Potterybarn.com. Unlike those Internet upstarts, Pottery Barn sells
a well-known brand, has plenty of inventory and has a reliable
record when it comes to distribution and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have purchased something from the company before and
know that it's a quality product, but more important, that it's a
quality shopping experience,'' said Barrett Ladd, a senior analyst
at Gomez.com, which publishes reviews of online retailers. ``The
important thing for them is to try to differentiate the Web site
from what they already have in their catalog. They have to add
something.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, I took a closer look at the site, which had a
clean design and simple, intuitive text and visual cues to aid
navigation. With the search function it was a cinch to find
information about any of the 3,000 products the company sells
online. Another important customer service convenience: you can
return any product you buy online to any of the 341 free-standing
Pottery Barn stores.
</P>
<P>
   Using Home Tour, I examined the house from the vantage of
someone who finally got inside a stranger's house. Although the
verisimilitude of the experience would have been enhanced if there
were a few pairs of children's shoes or some dog hair on the rug, I
was still having fun as I ran the cursor down the list of products
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   I clicked Mica Sconce to read the description: ``Shades made of
amber-toned mica, a thin material that creates warm ambient
light.'' At $89 each, I thought they might have been just what I
was looking for if I did not already own three pairs of garage-sale
sconces (including one set still packed away in a box).
</P>
<P>
   As I examined the Living Room more closely, I realized that the
thing that originally had captured my interest when I started the
Home Tour by peeping through the windows had been the beautiful
built-in bookcases that flanked the sconces. Now, I know the
architectural details in this house are not part of the Pottery
Barn merchandise list. Still, I printed out the image to store in
an already-bulging folder labeled ``Things to Ask the Carpenter to
Copy.''
</P>
<P>
   My specialist thinks that folder might be evidence of another
disease. But at least my sconce problem was in remission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6645 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TEXAS-MEDICAID-HNS &LR;      08-30 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MEDICAID-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN W. GONZALEZ
</P>
<P>
   and POLLY ROSS HUGHES
</P>
<P>
   c. Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In Houston, it took more than a year for a disabled
youth to replace the wheelchair he had outgrown. In Dallas, the
shortage of dentists serving the poor is so severe that only
patients with rotten teeth get prompt attention. In the Panhandle,
migrant workers often go unaware of their eligibility for free
health care.
</P>
<P>
   These were some of the Medicaid problems in Texas described by
Senior U.S. District Judge William Wayne Justice in his latest
bombshell ruling _ this time in a class action lawsuit over
indigent medical care. The judge concluded that more than 1 million
Texas children are poorly served by programs that are inadequately
funded and poorly managed.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling _ from the same judge who controlled Texas prisons
and mental health institutions for decades _ immediately set off a
rhetorical skirmish in the presidential campaign. Democratic Vice
President Al Gore assailed the performance of Republican Gov.
George W. Bush, who defended his efforts to extend health care to
needy families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good record signing kids up for Medicaid. We
intend to continue to do so,'' he said, adding, ``we're a
compassionate state.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice's scathing, 175-page ruling left Texas lawmakers
wondering what they might have to do to remedy Medicaid problems by
Oct. 13, as the judge demanded. It also sent state lawyers
scurrying to formulate a planned appeal due on Sept. 9. If a stay
were granted, remedial action could be postponed indefinitely
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed with the judge's ruling and believe it
does not represent a fair or accurate portrayal of Texas' efforts
to provide health care to children on Medicaid,'' said Bush
campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon where the state was in 1993, when the suit was
filed, and where we are today, we've made dramatic progress and
will improve upon that progress in the areas of outreach and
enrollment efforts,'' Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn was unavailable for comment, but
spokeswoman Andrea Horton said, ``We believe neither the law nor
the facts support Judge Justice's decision.'' And Bush spokeswoman
Karen Hughes called the ruling the product of a ``liberal activist
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice assailed the state's failure to provide medical and
dental checkups to many eligible adults and children and he
criticized the state's efforts to make services known to them.
Calling its data ``inflated and inaccurate,'' Justice said the
government exaggerated the number of people contacted and treated.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Justice said managed care was inhibiting access to
treatment by specialists and for mental health and pediatric
patients. Justice also cited logistical problems including poorly
publicized and operated transportation services, an inadequately
staffed toll-free help line and long delays in providing supplies
to patients.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the case of ``C.O.,'' a Harris County junior high
school student with cerebral palsy who outgrew his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took more than a year for C.O. to get a replacement
wheelchair. Unfortunately, C.O.'s troubles are not unusual,''
Justice said, noting that nearly half of the clients surveyed
reported problems obtaining special medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Justice also found a lack of medical services and outreach to
migrant families in the Lubbock area and he criticized as
inadequate the help offered to abused and neglected children
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of dentists has caused major problems in some areas,
Justice added. He said Dallas-area experts testified that a local
shortage was so critical that the only children getting treatment
through Medicaid were those with abscesses and rotten teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in 1993 on behalf of 1.5 million indigent
children entitled to health benefits through the Early Periodic
Screening, Diagnosis and Treatment program, also known as ``Texas
Health Steps.''
</P>
<P>
   A consent decree was approved in 1996 but plaintiffs returned to
court claiming the decree was ignored. Justice agreed, despite the
state's claims that programs were continually improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increased efforts have resulted in notable advancements in
all areas of the program's performance, from outreach to numbers of
eligibles served to staff resources allocated, making it one of the
most successful in the country,'' a brief filed by Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Further defending the state's efforts, Cornyn claimed:
</P>
<P>
   -- The medical checkup participation rate increased from 29
percent in 1993 to 66 percent currently;
</P>
<P>
   -- Program staff has grown from 10 in 1993, when the Medicaid
program was transferred to the Texas Department of Health, to
almost 600 workers now.
</P>
<P>
   -- The program made almost 5 million outreach contacts with
clients in 1999 _ about three times a year for each client.
</P>
<P>
   -- From 1993 to 1999, the Medicaid transportation program
expenditures increased from $19 million to $39 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- The dental program's expenditures have grown from $87 million
in 1993 to $140 million now.
</P>
<P>
   -- Some 87 percent of Medicaid recipients recognize the Texas
Health Steps name; and
</P>
<P>
   -- The participation rate for eligible teens rose from 37
percent in 1996 to 55 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Justice's ruling said there was ample proof that
the decree was violated.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiff's attorney Susan Zinn of San Antonio said she was
delighted by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's trying to say that the Texas Medicaid program is
not following federal law that Congress established in 1989. It's
more than 10 years later and they still haven't come through,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the remedies lie with the Legislature, whose next
regular session is in January. A special session appears
unnecessary at this time, state officials said, but questions about
future funding are already being posed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dental program is under funded. The case management
program is under funded,'' Zinn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature's decision in 1999 to establish a moratorium on
expansion of the managed care programs under Medicaid was
appropriate, Zinn added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Justice's order confirms that Texas has a long way to go
before more expansion of the managed care program would be
warranted, because there are so many problems,'' Zinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, money won't solve all the woes, a key lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of things we know we don't do enough of _
public schools, teachers' salaries, children's health insurance,
nursing home (reimbursement) rates,'' said Senate Finance Chairman
Bill Ratliff, R-Mt. Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I have of federal judges saying `you're not doing
enough' is one day they need to be in the shoes of the people
paying for it,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's Austin bureau chief Clay Robison contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
