<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT &LR;      08-30 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NAMES ROLL AS FATHER OF AUSTRALIAN PLAYER IS BOUNCED FROM U.S.
OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT33, NYT35 and NYT36 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Venus Williams is playing so well that she can afford
to pick on the little things. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my forehand down the line isn't where I want it to
be,'' the third-seeded Williams said after dismantling Kveta
Hrdlickova, 6-1, 6-1, in the second round Wednesday at the U.S.
Open in Flushing Meadows-Corona Park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-seeded Monica Seles, ninth-seeded Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario,
11th-seeded Sandrine Testud and 15th-seeded Jennifer Capriati faced
a similar lack of resistance on a day nearly upstaged by Damir
Dokic, the father of Jelena Dokic of Australia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Organizers banished the father from the tournament after an
official reported Dokic had verbally abused him in the players'
lounge and thrown his own grounds pass on the floor while ranting
about the price of salmon. The 43rd-ranked Jelena Dokic, a
Wimbledon semifinalist who won her first-round singles match
Tuesday and a doubles match Wednesday, was nearby. Damir Dokic was
thrown out of Wimbledon in July for disruptive behavior that
included smashing a journalist's cell phone, and was arrested at a
tournament in Birmingham, England, two years ago for lying down in
traffic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the Wimbledon champion, anchored the calm part of the
day, in which favorites marched through their opponents like
practice fodder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams dissected her performance because there was nothing
really to say about Hrdlickova, whose offense was limited to two
winners to Williams' 29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, there were no upsets on the men's side
either. Third-seeded Magnus Norman ripped 56 winners to sweep Paul
Goldstein, 7-5, 6-4, 6-4; sixth-seeded Marat Safin defeated Thierry
Guardiola, 7-5, 6-7 (5), 6-4, 6-4; 10th-seeded Cedric Pioline beat
Sargis Sargsian, 6-3, 6-3, 6-1, and 15th seeded Mark Philippoussis
was a 6-3, 6-2, 6-3 winner over Albert Portas.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seles committed 25 unforced errors, but she still tamed the
35th-ranked Anne Kremer, 6-3, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seles once owned this place. She won titles in 1991 and 1992
before she was stabbed in 1993 by a fan during a match in Germany.
Seles took two years off to heal, and has been a Top 10 occupant
for much of the time since her return in 1995. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new era of sinew and full-court aggression emerged during
Seles' comeback. But Seles sticks to her old game plan like a
security blanket, patrolling the baseline with limited range and
laser groundstrokes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her familiar style has made her a sentimental favorite. When
Seles began talking to herself after a lapse in concentration
against Kremer, a fan yelled, ``C'mon, Monica!'' Seles said the
encouragement snapped her out of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have that support behind you when you go out on
the court, when you struggle,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seles's miscues did not hurt her Wednesday. She hit 29 winners
to Kremer's 16. By the time Kremer figured out a way to stretch
Seles' two-handed strokes into one-handed lunges, it was too late.
After a long rally, Kremer netted a forehand to end the match after
just 1 hour 9 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the third round, Seles will face Chanda Rubin, a 2-6, 6-1,
6-1 winner over Barbara Schett. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Safin, who has won three tournaments in 2000, blamed his slow
start on a 10-day layoff since losing to Gustavo Kuerten in the
Indianapolis final. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even not playing your best tennis, you have to have this
attitude on the court where you try to make the game easier,''
Safin said. ``I don't have to make winners, just play my game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another men's match, Greg Rusedski, the Open runner-up in
1997, defeated Magnus Gustafsson, 6-1, 6-2, 6-4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the women, Testud took advantage of 30 unforced errors by
Iroda Tulyaganoa to win, 6-4, 6-3. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
