<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-ART     08-30 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-ART-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARY OF LINGERING VIOLENCE, CHECHEN REFUGEES ARE AFRAID TO RETURN
HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARABULAK, Russia _ An August thunderstorm had just shredded the
roof and walls of Raisa Gotsayeva's canvas tent, and she was airing
out the bedding and washing the floorboards when a visitor came
across her dirt threshold to inquire about conditions in the sea of
tents here on the border with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Set on the arid plain that sweeps up toward the Caucasus
Mountains, barely visible in the distance, this makeshift camp in
Ingushetia, which resembles an army bivouac, has taken the name
Sputnik.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to tell the authorities here that our tents are
leaking, they simply replied, `Why don't you go home?''' she said,
with a ring of indignation in her voice.
</P>
<P>
   She straightened her dress and motioned with more than a little
exasperation at the clutter of bunks, clothes and cooking utensils
that now defines her life, which she describes as ``sitting on
suitcases.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other place I would rather go than home,'' said
Gotsayeva, who fled Chechnya last October after Russian rockets
destroyed the central market in Grozny, the capital. She had been
selling clothes there when the rockets hit, killing 140 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go with great pleasure,'' she said. ``I would go
tomorrow, but my house is destroyed, there is no work there, and
every night there is shooting and they detain all the young men. If
you have a beard, they say you are a rebel. If you have a cut or a
scar, they say you are a rebel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would go home with pleasure. But we are afraid, and there
are no guarantees there for our security.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year of fighting, Russia's armed forces have declared
that the war against separatists in Chechnya is effectively over,
with only ``mopping up'' operations continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Some 155,000 people are still refugees, and the task of
returning them to their devastated land has confronted Moscow and
international aid groups with another problem: almost no one wants
to go home to a country where gunfire rules the night and where no
family feels safe after reports of rape, torture and abuse at the
hands of Russian military forces.
</P>
<P>
   Now another winter is coming, and hopes here are flagging. The
mammoth relief effort that has sustained the Chechen refugee
population is suffering from fatigue among donors. Bread
distribution here was cut off for six weeks this summer because the
Russian government failed to pay food vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations food relief coordinator for Russia, Bnim K.
Udas, said in an interview that his program did not have enough
food to get through September. A U.N. appeal for more food
assistance to Chechen refugees was sent out in June, he said. ``But
we have only received a response from the United States and
Canada,'' he added. ``No other countries made pledges so far,
including the European countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingushetia's top disaster coordinator, Valery Kuksa, told
reporters earlier in August that about 50,000 refugees were living
in tent camps and in abandoned train cars, but that this winter
there would be spaces in warm tents for only about 25,000 refugees.
He added that the ``official position'' of the Russian government
was that ``by Oct. 1, all Chechens should be in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   One government plan is to move the refugee camps just across the
border into Chechnya, removing them from what they view as the
protection of the Ingushetia government. In Chechnya, whether in
camps or back home, they would be policed by the Russian army and
the Moscow-appointed administration of Akhmad Kadyrov.
</P>
<P>
   But the refugees here insist that they will not return to their
republic until the shooting ends and the army stops inciting fear
among civilians with late-night knocks on the door, incessant
checkpoint searches, intimidation and extortion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The line between law enforcement and oppression in Chechnya is
difficult to distinguish even from the official communiques.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, for example, a statement issued from the office of
Sergei Yastrzhembsky, an aide to President Vladimir Putin, said 44
people had been arrested after ``search and raid operations'' in
the villages of Alkhankala and Alkhan-Yurt in the preceding 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested included Chechens with ``scars from wounds'' and
individuals who had secretly transported the bodies of rebels after
they had been killed in battle _ presumably to carry out the
tradition among the Muslim Chechens to bury them by sundown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kadyrov says come home, but how can we come home when the
Russians promise endless mopping-up operations?'' said Taharik
Vitaiyevo as she passed through a field of open latrines and
outhouses. ``We would approve of Kadyrov if he would do something
to end the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Every family at the Sputnik camp has a story. Many have sent
family members back to Grozny this summer to conduct reconnaissance
on whether it is safe to return. For most, the answer has been no.
</P>
<P>
   Zainab Ismailova, 41, arrived in Ingushetia on July 31 with her
three children. On her first attempt to get here last December, the
family narrowly escaped death when her refugee convoy was attacked
by Russian helicopters, she said. Now, she is determined not to
leave Ingushetia ``until I am sure that nothing will happen to my
family when I return'' home.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a cot among her new neighbors, Ismailova kept her
eyes on her 2-year-old son, Islam. ``I left Grozny because of this
child,'' she explained. ``During the whole war we stayed in the
city, living in the cellar, but my son cannot stand to hear
aviation noise anymore. He becomes paralyzed with fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Many children here suffer from nightmares and paralyzing fear.
One father said his daughter passes out when she hears a jet or
helicopter. It reminds her of the bombing. A woman fears that her
infant son has nerve damage, because his leg shakes when he sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   There is one tent where disturbed children are getting
psychological counseling. They draw pictures: Grozny in flames,
flowers coming out of cannons (titled ``The World as It Should
Be''), a screaming girl with body parts around her and a devastated
landscape called ``Bloody Sunday in the City of Shali.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These children have seen a great deal of evil in the last
year,'' said Khamila Khadisova, a Chechen schoolteacher working
with the children. ``Many drawings here show acts of revenge, but
this is very unwished for. We do everything we can to lighten their
pain and brighten their mood by dwelling on peace and friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not far from here, in the village of Gamuriyevo, 100 Chechen
refugees have moved into an abandoned house. All that was left by
the time Zarima Dzaitayev, 44, and her husband showed up was the
garage, which they share with 10 other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I returned to our home near Grozny recently,'' Dzaitayev said.
``It was an apartment building, and now two of the entrances have
collapsed and there is nothing left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to go home, even if we had to live in the
basement, but it is impossible because someone shoots at night, or
the soldiers come to you drunk and ask for money or vodka,'' she
said, adding, ``My daughter is 17 and I don't want to take her
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Dzaitayev and her husband, a construction engineer who
worked for the Chechen government and who has not been paid in
three years, will remain in the garage. They sleep on mats on the
concrete floor with their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last winter my mother died and we had to take her home to bury
her,'' Dzaitayev said, ``but at the checkpoints the Russians
suspected we were smuggling weapons, because my mother's body was
wrapped in a blanket, and so we had to unwrap her to show them and
then pay a bribe.''
</P>
<P>
   Dzaitayev began to cry, interrupting herself to say: ``Not every
Chechen is a bandit. Every nation has good and bad people in it,
but they call us a criminal nation, and it is not right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
