<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PARIS-SUBWAY-DERAIL-N     08-30 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-SUBWAY-DERAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
23 HURT IN PARIS SUBWAY DERAILMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: no byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A mysterious derailment injured 24 passengers in the
Paris subway Wednesday, but a catastrophe was narrowly averted
because the car that had tipped over skidded to a halt only 3 feet
from a train on the opposite track.
</P>
<P>
   Accidents in the Paris subway, which celebrated its 100th
birthday this year, are rare. Many of the trains, which run more
slowly and considerably more quietly than New York subways, have
side wheels that help stabilize them.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's derailment happened at 1:23 p.m. as the lead car of
a No. 12 train coming into the Notre Dame de Lorette station at
normal speed just ``keeled over on the opposite track,'' said Alain
Caire, controller general of security for the subway system. In his
31 years on the job,
</P>
<P>
   Caire said, ``I never saw a train keel over like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Passengers suffered cuts and bruises and one had a leg broken.
Firefighters quickly activated ``the Red Plan,'' designed for bombs
or terrorist incidents and nearly 200 firefighters in 20 trucks
converged on the scene and set up first aid stations on the subway
platform and in a nearby cafe. The neighborhood, where the
boulevards of central Paris begin the climb up to the narrow alleys
of bohemian Montmartre, was closed off for hours by dozens of
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials said it was possible something on the tracks had
knocked over the car and an investigation was ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The minor accident came on the heels of a major disaster for
French transport, the crash of a supersonic Concorde on takeoff
from a Paris airport, which killed 113. Preliminary results of an
investigation into that crash are due to be released Thursday.
Chief blame in that case is expected to focus on a piece of metal
left on the runway that burst a tire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
