<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DIAMONDS0831-COX     08-30 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAMONDS0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewelers try to avoid war-tainted diamonds
 &HT;    By Kirsten Searer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ African rebels have proved that a good diamond can buy
a lot of buried land mines, rusty machetes and dull axes.
</P>
<P>
   Now some diamond dealers say they can make sure that doesn't
happen anymore. For years, militants have funded their brutal
campaigns against governments in Sierra Leone and Angola with
black-market diamonds sold to consumers in wealthier countries.
Human rights organizations all the way up to the United Nations are
calling for a ban on the sale of those gems, which they call
``conflict diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easier said than done, say advocates and those in the
industry. Even the world's best experts cannot eyeball a diamond
and say whether it came from South Africa, Australia, Canada _ or
the killing fields of Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's LeeBrant Jewelers is one of the first in this area to
offer diamonds that are certified as conflict-free. But the price
for a clear conscience won't be cheap. Only LeeBrant's most
expensive diamonds are certified as coming from areas not at war.
Since June, the jeweler has carried up to a dozen _ each costing
$5,000 to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the stones you see advertised in print or on
radio,'' said John Reid, a certified gemologist at LeeBrant
Jewelers in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In a business where a diamond passes through many hands before
it sits on yours, some, including the Gemological Institute of
America, say it's almost impossible to accurately track the stones.
Several jewelers said the best they can do is to deal with trusted
diamond cutters, who vouch that their diamonds do not come from
Africa's more brutal areas.
</P>
<P>
   The diamond business is built on trust, said Dhanesh Bhindi,
owner of Bhindi Jewelers. That's why he takes the word of his
diamond dealers in Israel and New York who say their diamonds come
from Russia and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he said, dealers cannot truly guarantee where their
diamonds came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Chambliss, assistant manager of the Shane Co. in
Marietta, Ga., said, ``It is possible, because of who we do
business with. They have to present certification to us that they
do not deal with people in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   In that process, LeeBrant's supplier, Codiam Inc., guarantees
their Rand diamonds come from South Africa, said Codiam president
Leon Cohen. The company started selling the diamonds in June.
</P>
<P>
   Each diamond is photographed and blueprinted soon after it
leaves the mine, and a minuscule identification number is
laser-inscribed by the craftsman who cuts and polishes the stone.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen says his company does not charge more for the
documentation: ``We're not putting a price on morality.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he offers his jewelers in the United States, Southeast Asia,
the Middle East, South Africa and Europe diamonds as small as a
third-carat. In a few months, he will supply his certified diamonds
from a quarter-carat up. For almost a decade, insurgents in Sierra
Leone and Angola _ funded in large part by diamonds mined from
territory they control _ have amputated the limbs of civilians,
including small children, to terrorize the population, said Alex
Yearsley, an activist for Global Witness. The London-based human
rights group was one of the first to point out the connection
between diamonds and the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically became the main scare tactic to put the fear of
God in people,'' Yearsley said, ``and it certainly worked.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years, Global Witness has called for a global
tracking system for diamonds, with a certification process that
would document each diamond from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Yearsley had not heard of Codiam's tracking system, but he said
most diamond dealers are not sophisticated enough to really track
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a jewelry shop to put up a sign saying `conflict-free
diamonds' without offering confirmation _ I think it's a little
early for that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he supports Codiam's process of assigning a tracking number
to diamonds and photographing them as they are cut, polished and
transported.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has imposed an embargo on diamonds coming
from mines belonging to the Angolan rebel group UNITA but not on
diamonds coming from Democratic Republic of Congo or Sierra Leone.
The U.N.'s Children's Fund ranks Angola as the worst place to be a
child.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers, the world's most famous diamond diggers, decided a
little more than a year ago not to sell conflict diamonds. The
company has estimated that about 4 percent of the world's supply of
diamonds comes from conflict areas.
</P>
<P>
   Just three years ago, when the rebels were at their peak of
power, about 15 percent of the world's supply of diamonds were sold
to fund the wars in Africa, Yearsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
