<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      08-30 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG WAR CAN SUCCEED, CLINTON TELLS COLOMBIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia _ Trying to put a more humanitarian face on
a drug-fighting package that relies heavily on military spending,
President Clinton paid a day-long visit to this violence-torn
country Wednesday, saying Colombia can triumph over drug lords and
insurgents and attain peace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's whirlwind, 8-hour visit to this Caribbean port city,
which included meetings with widows of slain army officers and a
private discussion with President Andres Pastrana, was meant to
promote a $1.3 billion assistance package that over the next two
years will provide military training, 60 US-made helicopters, and
funds for new justice, agricultural and human rights initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing aside criticism that the package emphasizes military
over humanitarian strategies to help solve Colombia's problems,
Clinton said the assistance would help reduce the country's drug
supply and bring an end to a 40-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that the initiative would lead to a deeper US
involvement in Colombia's civil strife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject the idea that we must choose between supporting peace
and fighting drugs,'' Clinton said at a press conference with
Pastrana. ``We can do both, and indeed, to succeed, we must do
both.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit was largely symbolic for an aid package
that was approved by Congress earlier this summer. But Clinton's
presence in Colombia _ the first presidential visit since George
Bush's brief stop here in 1990 _ represented just how far relations
between the two countries have improved since Pastrana's
predecessor, Ernesto Samper, was denied a US visa for his alleged
ties to drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   A former journalist who was once kidnapped by the Medellin drug
cartel, Pastrana, 46, has pinned the success of his two-year-old
administration on reducing the country's illegal drug trade and on
a broad economic and social agenda known as Plan Colombia, which is
aimed primarily at ending the warfare with both leftist guerrillas
and right-wing paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, the civil strife has killed an estimated
35,000 people, displaced more than 1 million residents, and even
threatened to destablilize one of Latin America's longest-running
democracies. Meanwhile, drug production in the country has
skyrocketed over the past five years to roughly 550 tons annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times over the past decades, Colombians have felt alone
in bearing the burden of the international drug war,'' Pastrana
said in praising the new US commitment.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's first stops after arriving in Cartagena was to
the city's port, where he reviewed some of the Colombia's anti-drug
work. He then met with a group of women whose husbands were killed
in drug-related violence.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy security contingent of more than 5,000 officers _ made
up of both Colombian and US agents _ guarded this colonial city
during the president's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian National Police said they arrested two Marxist rebels
who were setting up a bomb in a working-class neighborhood near a
new courthouse where Clinton was scheduled to appear, Reuters
reported. Officials said hundreds of pamphlets signed by the
leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, known as the FARC,
were also found at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas, who have nearly 20,000 members and control large
portions of southern Colombia, have pledged that the aid package
will lead to more fighting across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, for now, seem to agree. Recent public opinion polls
show that more than half of Colombians fear an escalation of
violence as a consequence of the aid package, although most also
support the Pastrana administration's peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of residents lined the streets as the Clinton motorcade
wound its way around the narrow streets of this city of 2 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Ortiz, dressed in shorts and sandals, shrugged his
shoulders when asked about his hope for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can win this war,'' Ortiz, a 22-year-old
fish vendor, said. ``But we're still fighting it because no one
wants to give up. So more people are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Rojas, director of Paz Colombia, an umbrella group of 150
Colombian community and human rights organizations, said residents
would only put faith in the Pastrana plan if it advances
negotiations between the government and guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be validated if and when we move from rhetoric to acts
that lead to peace,'' Rojas said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was accompanied by several Cabinet members, including
Secretary of State Madeline K. Albright and Attorney General Janet
Reno, and by several members of Congress, including House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, Senator Joseph Biden and Representative William
Delahunt.
</P>
<P>
   With the aid package, Colombia, which supplies 90 percent of the
cocaine sold in the United States, now becomes one of the largest
recipients of US foreign aid. The two-year assistance package will
increase by 10 times the amount of aid allocated for agricultural
and human rights programs in Colombia to more than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the funds for 60 new US-made helicopters and for
military training, which make up the bulk of the US aid, that has
angered the plan's critics. Many observers note that Colombia's
military and police forces are severely understaffed and poorly
equipped to fight against rebels who are increasingly financed by
cocaine and heroin sales.
</P>
<P>
   However, the military's own poor record of human rights
violations, its unwillingness to prosecute high-ranking officials
and its alleged links to right-wing paramilitary groups have left
it open to criticism that more money will lead to more crimes
against civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CNN0831-COX     08-30 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reshuffling of management comeback plan for ratings slide
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner and Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN, fighting a ratings slide and preparing for the
merger of parent Time Warner and America Online, is creating a
comeback plan with reshuffled management.
</P>
<P>
   A reorganization unveiled Wednesday dilutes the role of Tom
Johnson, the chairman and chief executive of the CNN News Group,
and gives TV executives responsibilities for CNN Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives executives from Turner Broadcasting System, of
which CNN is a unit, more direct say in the Atlanta-based news
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who continues to report directly to TBS Chairman Terry
McGuirk, until now has overseen all of CNN's operations. Under the
changes, he will be responsible for the news product but loses his
president's title and cedes control of business operations. The
business responsibilities will be funneled up to Steve Heyer, TBS's
president and McGuirk's top lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about how to make CNN bigger and better,'' spokeswoman
Edna Johnson said. ``Johnson is going to be focused on the better.
Heyer is going to be focused on the bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The shakeup includes the departure, as expected, of Rick Kaplan,
president of the flagship network CNN-US.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, four company insiders emerge with enhanced roles.
Phil Kent, who headed Turner Broadcasting's sales, distribution and
business alliances outside the United States, will join the CNN
News Group as president _ formerly one of Johnson's titles _ and
chief operating officer. He will report to Johnson on editorial
matters and Heyer on operations.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Walton, who oversaw both CNN's TV sports network (CNN/SI)
and sports Web site (CNNSI.com), becomes president of a new
grouping of CNN operations in the United States, including TV
networks and Internet sites. Eason Jordan, who presided over CNN
International, takes the new title of chief news executive of the
CNN News Group. One of his lieutenants, Chris Cramer, becomes
president of a new group that includes all of CNN's international
operations, including both TV and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That it was done with insiders and not an outsider is telling
of how AOL is going to work for now: Give it a chance to see how
the local boys do,'' said Ed Turner, a former CNN vice president
who built the network during its formative years.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who turns 59 in September and joined CNN as president
in 1990, said he is ``enthusiastic'' about the new era at CNN.
``There is no better team in which to entrust the future of CNN,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk said he expects Johnson to remain chairman and CEO of
the news group ``for a very long time.'' Johnson was ``one of the
few non-negotiables'' when contemplating the changes, McGuirk said.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk said he and Johnson began reviewing CNN's management
structure over the summer in preparation for the planned merger
this fall of AOL and Time Warner. AOL has said it intends to build
on Time Warner's well known brands, including CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We determined that organizationally we have some improvements
to make,'' McGuirk said. The plan, he said, is to increase CNN's
``ability to integrate the analog business and the digital business
in a smooth way.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the reorganization should bring better intertwining
of CNN on TV and the Web. ``It is time to seize the moment because
this is the new era of the Internet and convergence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, whose power would have been reduced under the
reorganization, instead resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have offered me several opportunities about how I might
contribute in the future. But I believe it is best that I now move
on,'' Kaplan said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He had been president of CNN's flagship network for exactly
three years, having come from ABC News. Brought in to revitalize
the CNN network and improve ratings, Kaplan managed the former, in
the minds of some staffers, but not the latter. Despite spending
heavily on new prime-time shows such as ``The World Today'' and
``NewsStand,'' CNN's ratings are down more than 35 percent this
year compared to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's post will be filled on an interim basis by Sid
Bedingfield, formerly executive vice president of CNN-US and
Kaplan's right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's ratings have dropped in the past during slow news periods,
but the impact is greater now that the network faces more
competition from young cable news channels, including MSNBC, Fox
News Channel and CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Johnson attributes CNN's ratings drop to a shortage of big
news. But it has also been due to gains by competitors and younger
audiences less interested in traditional news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problems that they face are problems faced by all
news organizations,'' Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press, said earlier this year. Those
include, he said, a younger audience not interested in traditional
news, and increasing choices for people who care about news.
</P>
<P>
   One way CNN has sought a broader audience is by becoming one of
the first major news providers on the Internet. It is the number
two general news and information Web site in the nation, but it's
share of the market has eroded while that of the number one site,
MSNBC.com, has grown, according to Web measurement firm Media
Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Myers, chief economist for The Myers Report, a media
industry analyst, said CNN needs to study how rival MSNBC uses its
cable channel and Internet sites to reinforce one another.
</P>
<P>
   As for the management changes, Myers said, ``Kent is an
interesting move. He's very experienced in the international side,
the deal-making side. That sends a certain message in terms of
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking this as an opportunity to regroup,'' said Tom
Wolzien, an analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein who is a former
senior vice president of NBC. ``This is typical in the life of news
organization. When ratings have been down for a while, when things
are not working as well as they might like and a new owner is
taking over, it is time to do something differently.''
</P>
<P>
   But making big changes at CNN may not be cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering content even further is costly, said Michael Goodman,
senior analyst on media and entertainment issues for the Yankee
Group.
</P>
<P>
   One area CNN should concentrate on is producing more original
content on its Internet sites, said Michael Goodman, a media
analyst at the Yankee Group. The news group should offer different
enough fare that people rely on both mediums, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Goodman said, CNN needs top executives who
understand the business but are open to new ideas, ``because
clearly what they are doing now _ the status quo _ is not
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
