u f BC-EURO-BUYING-FRENZY-BO     08-30 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-BUYING-FRENZY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DLJ DEAL LATEST IN EUROPEAN BUYING FRENZY IN US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Donaldson-Credit)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The European financial establishment is on a buying binge, and
it's shopping almost exclusively for the made-in-America label _
even at top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Five prominent US financial firms have agreed this summer to be
bought by European companies. Three are investment managers
headquartered in Boston, including a formerly aggressive acquirer,
United Asset Management Corp. Two are big-name Wall Street firms.
The details of the deals are different, but they have this in
common: Offering prices too big to resist.
</P>
<P>
   European banks and insurance companies are paying premiums of 20
percent to more than 100 percent to get a foothold in the US
market. Their aim is, in part, to diversify their revenue streams
and to gain access to the hottest stock market on the globe for
five years running. They're also trying to address Europe's
changing investment appetite, as individuals and pension funds
follow the US lead into more aggressive stock investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are confronting a world to come in which asset
management, whether by individuals or pension funds, is going to be
an important competitive issue,'' observed Neil Epstein, an analyst
with Putnam Lovell Securities Inc. in New York. They're attracted
to the United States, he said, ``to get hold of capabilities and
insights of a more open financial structure.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, in some instances, is whether the Europeans are
spending wisely.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of United Asset Management, London-based Old Mutual
Plc _ South Africa's biggest insurance company _ is forking over
$2.2 billion, or a 22 percent premium, for a shrinking company.
</P>
<P>
   UAM, with $188 billion under management, made its name buying up
dozens of investment boutiques in the 1980s and early 1990s. The
sellers loved the model, it was often said, because UAM let them
operate independently. But the parent has seen tens of billions of
dollars pour out the door over the past three years, in part
because its affiliates were heavily involved in traditional pension
plans, where business is dwindling, instead of the booming 401(k)
realm. In addition, insiders now say, UAM failed to reinvest
adequately in its units.
</P>
<P>
   Norton Reamer, UAM's founder, did not want to sell the company,
say people familiar with the talks. Meetings held through the
summer of 1999 with Old Mutual, with the help of advisers at
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. yielded no agreements, according to UAM
filings with securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting in London in November, Old Mutual offered to buy a
small group of UAM's companies, with $15.5 billion under
management. The answer was still no. But the writing was on the
wall; later that month, Reamer's planned successor as CEO, Ed
Haldeman, said he would resign at year end.
</P>
<P>
   Reamer, then seeking a new chief executive, declined a
$20-a-share offer from Old Mutual in March. By April, he said he'd
take no less than $23 per share. In May, the new chief, James F.
Orr III, was aboard but the sale appeared to be falling apart, due
to numerous delays. But in a telephone negotiation, Orr secured the
sale price that stuck _ $25 a share, or $1.4 billion, the filing
says.
</P>
<P>
   He got the last couple of bucks at the eleventh hour, industry
sources say, thanks in part to an agreement a few days prior by
Boston's Nvest LP, which sold to Caisse des Depots et Consignations
Group of Paris for $2.2 billion. Shareholders got $40 per limited
partnership unit, or double the market price before the deal was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Why the big payout for a firm that had been growing at a snail's
pace?
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial services firms, no matter where they are in the
world, need the kind of steady, noncyclical revenues of asset
management firms,'' said Ben Phillips, London-based managing
director of Cerulli Associates, a Boston research firm. As banks
consolidate across Europe, he added, ``Asset management is the one
(business) they've all been screaming after, and the US is the
biggest market.''
</P>
<P>
   The firms that are selling out say they are gaining new markets.
It's difficult for US firms to sell their services in Europe, and
to attract new customers, without a local profile. The buyers aim
both to offer the US talent to foreign investors and to put new
muscle behind US sales efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips thinks the buyout of Pioneer Group, a 72-year-old
Boston mutual fund group, is even pricier than Nvest, for what
UniCredito Italiano Group is getting. Italy's number-two bank
offered $1.2 billion, or a 40 percent premium, for a $24 billion
company that failed to grow during the vast bull market of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pioneer is clearly above premium price,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale prices are even more astonishing, observers note, given
that the dollar is very strong. The euro has tumbled 23 percent vs.
the greenback since the European currency was introduced in January
1999. That makes anything Europeans buy here more expensive, said
Paul Podolsky, currency strategist at FleetBoston Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A heavy flow of European dollars leaving the continent to invest
in American companies is fueling the euro's decline, Podolsky said.
``There's a perception that the US has something special right now
that's worth paying for, at a time of rapid technical and economic
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Wall Street brokerage Paine Webber Group Inc. agreed
last month to be sold for $16 billion, in the biggest foreign
takeover of a US securities firm to date. The $73.50 that
shareholders reaped from Swiss banking giant UBS represented a 47
percent premium over the prior trading price.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, blue-chip investment banker Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette Inc. is being traded from French owners to the Swiss. Axa
SA, a French insurer, will fetch $13.4 billion, or a 36 percent
premium, in its sale of DLJ to Credit Suisse Group, which already
owns New York's Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The combination gives the Swiss firm a research powerhouse, a
contender in the online trading game, and a significant junk bond
operation.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely speculated that the buying frenzy is not over.
Investors are bidding up shares of the remaining independent
investment banks, including Lehman Brothers, Bear Stearns &AMP; Co.,
and J.P. Morgan. And there are dozens of asset managers that could
be targets for acquisitions, from Eaton Vance Corp. and Franklin
Templeton Investments to Invescap, parent of the AIM funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is the end of the line,'' said Epstein, the
analyst. He noted that this buying spree is merely the latest round
in a long-running trend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Boston's Scudder, Stevens &AMP; Clark Inc. was acquired by
Zurich Group, Switzerland's biggest insurer, for $1.7 billion.
Zurich had previously purchased Chicago's Kemper Investments.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the rare examples of major acquisitions in the other
direction, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in 1998 bought Mercury Asset
Management Group, the UK's biggest fund company, for $5.23 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
