<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SATCH IS WHERE IT'S AT
</HEADLINE>
  By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The old stadium is a relic of Jennifer Capriati's
vanished youth, the way former schools and teachers seem gigantic
from a distance of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know, I still see it as the real stadium sometimes,''
said Capriati, who does not seem to be the type who dwells on
apparitions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Louis Armstrong Stadium has gotten smaller. In the
recent renovation of the joint, they shaved off the top deck,
turning it into the absolute star of the National Tennis Center,
the place where people jam and maneuver and wheedle to get a good
seat. How New York is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``They still crowd in, and they're not quiet until, like, the
first few points are over from the changeover,'' said Capriati who,
in her relative dotage, would not have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium named for the great jazz musician rocked and swayed
for Capriati Wednesday, with men and women of a certain age
shouting, ``Good girl, Jen,'' and other parental sentiments as
Capriati whacked Henrieta Nagyova, 6-2, 6-2. The fans knew of her
troubles, an old story by now, and they were glad to see her show
vestigial glimpses of that right-handed forehand that once made her
a contenduh, as Marlon Brando put it.
</P>
<P>
   The Satch is an equal opportunity site. The fans love everybody
because they can get close enough to express that love. Whoever
plays there benefits from the impromptu joy of fans celebrating
something going out of style _ immediacy, intimacy, visibility.
</P>
<P>
   This certainly is not the case in the dreadfully conceived
Arthur Ashe Stadium, where nobody has yet performed the
Fountainhead thing and pushed the plunger, so they could start all
over. At the Art, there are corporate boxes and luxury boxes and
then tiers of seats stretching up to the Delta Shuttle. Television
hates the sight of the empty seats _ psychologically bad for
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's unfortunate,'' said Monica Seles, who beat Anne
Kremer, 6-3, 6-4, in the Art Wednesday. ``I understand, with the
whole boxes and corporations and so on and so on.'' Well, yes, the
corporate ennui does help pay Monica's prize money. But still.
</P>
<P>
   They could fix it by letting the ushers scalp the empty seats,
but that grand old Open tradition is apparently discouraged,
creating a vacuum. Where have all the people gone? To the Satch,
more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the main stadium; it was ridiculous,'' said a lady
in a sundress after Marat Safin outlasted Theirry Guardiola at the
Satch.
</P>
<P>
   With Capriati warming up, fans jammed the narrow hatchways and
deftly tried to cut the lines and fill in the 8,253 open seats
directly behind the 1,436 reserved seats in the lower boxes. ``It's
a cozy stadium,'' said Paul Bruehl of Locust Valley, Long Island
``In the big stadium it's like watching it on TV. I buy the
cheapest seat in the stadium, and then I move around for the first
week.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to remember how reviled the Satch was as the
main stadium. But now it has four handsome towers at the corners,
scoreboards at the north and south ends, precious little
advertising and a handsome, compact feel. And the fans flow in and
out like the tide, sometimes a riptide.
</P>
<P>
   Only one force is greater than the Satch, and that is the appeal
of the Williams Sisters, the hottest draw in the sport no matter
how much poor, fried John McEnroe blathers against women's tennis.
Wednesday, the sisters were supposed to play doubles in the Satch
in the late afternoon, but their match was rescheduled for the Art,
with its 23,219 seats.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look out! There went thousands of pilgrims racing across the
plaza, leaving behind a modest audience for two young Yanks,
Jan-Michael Gambill and Mardy Fish. Among the stalwarts was
Kathleen Bernard, originally from Montego Bay, Jamaica, and now a
tennis pro at the Roosevelt Island Racquet Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost Guga, I've lost Rafter, and now Jan-Michael is in
trouble,'' Bernard said, mourning the losses of Gustavo Kuerten and
Patrick Rafter on Tuesday. ``I can see the Williamses anytime, but
I've got to cheer for my man Jan-Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard was fair. She watched Fish whip forehands into the
corners, and she cheered, ``Go, Mr. Fish, you're really swimming
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses dispatched their opponents, and the hard-core
fans surged back to the Satch to watch Gambill defeat Fish in the
fifth set. As darkness fell, Martina Hingis and Pete Sampras were
on deck at the Art, which does perk up at night. Meanwhile,
Capriati was due back at the Satch for doubles, along with her
partner, one Anna Kournikova. At the Satch, the hits just keep on
coming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
