<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-COLLEGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
34 PERCENT OF COLLEGES POLLED BLOCK NAPSTER, SURVEY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ A survey of 50 US colleges and universities
found that 34 percent of campuses block access to Napster Inc.'s
Web site on school computers.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released Wednesday by the Gartner Group in Stamford,
Conn., found that none of the six Massachusetts schools queried,
however, prohibit Napster, the controversial software that lets
users swap music over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Napster, a program written by Shawn Fanning, a former
Northeastern University student, is distributed for free on the
Internet by Napster Inc., a San Mateo, Calif., company that is
currently under legal attack by the music industry for copyright
infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Babson College, Boston College, Boston University, Harvard
University, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and Wellesley
College were among the schools that did not explicitly ban Napster.
NU was contacted by Gartner researchers, but did not reply in time
for the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Many schools have objected to the use of Napster software
because the program ties up too many computers for what is regarded
as a nonacademic use. However, many schools are also wary of the
legal consequences of allowing the use of Napster on school
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the music industry wins its case against Napster, it's
possible they will go after individual users and the institutions
that give these users Internet access, including colleges and
universities,'' said P.J. McNealy, senior analyst with the Gartner
Group. ``Legal liability is the monster lurking at the end of the
hallway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
