A6680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ENRON0831-COX     08-30 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENRON0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Enron officials attribute success to Internet ventures
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Enron Corp. President and Chief Operating
Officer Jeff Skilling said he is pleased that the Houston company
is often cited as a good example of an Old Economy enterprise that
successfully joined the Internet Age.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the company morphed from a natural-gas
pipeline company dependent on fixed and buried assets and limited
suppliers to the leading trader of energy in North America.
EnronOnline, a division that Skilling helped launch, handles gas
and electricity contracts with an estimated value of $1 billion a
day as it uses the Internet to buy and sell deregulated energy
wholesale. That business accounted for most of Enron's $289 million
in profit in the second quarter and has made the 47-year-old
Skilling heir apparent to Enron Chief Executive Kenneth Lay.
</P>
<P>
   But Enron officials note that the Internet didn't make Enron
successful. Enron's commodities-trading business, which was
launched nearly 10 years ago, exploited the Internet to create new
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like turning on the after-burners,'' Skilling told
an audience of about 100 people at the Austin Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   When deregulation made energy a commodity in 1989, Enron spent
took nine months to negotiate one transaction, Skilling said. Now,
EnronOnline handles 40 transactions a week, which take only
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the Internet is a tool and not the solution to
e-commerce is part of the message at InteractiveTexas, a three-day
conference sponsored by Enron, Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard
Co. and others.
</P>
<P>
   Skilling, who was the keynote speaker at a panel Wednesday, said
Enron derives 80 percent of its profit from businesses it has
launched in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He said start-ups that expect to exploit the Internet by
focusing only on providing services like information exchanges,
which Internet users are used to getting free, will not survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few free-standing (business-to-business) sites will be a
revenue generator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
