<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BUSINESS NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ALTAVISTA EXECUTIVE RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista said that its U.K. managing director Andy Mitchell had
resigned. The news follows the company's botched plans to provide
flat-fee Internet access service to British customers. AltaVista
trumped competitors by being first to announce that it would
provide cut-rate Internet access for a single low-cost payment, but
then failed to deliver the service. Unlike the free and fixed-rate
services in the United States, those in Britain charge by the
minute. AltaVista had planned to take advantage of new rules aimed
at loosening British Telecommunications PLC's grip on the local
phone market. ``The mistakes in our planned Internet access
service, which we do acknowledge, probably made Andy's departure
inevitable,'' said Pierre Paperon, president of AltaVista Europe.
Stephanie Himoff, who has replaced Mitchell in the role of acting
managing director, said she will focus on the company's core
business of providing Internet search engines.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CHIEF EXECUTIVE AT PHILIPS
</P>
<P>
   Royal Philips Electronics said Gerard Kleisterlee, a 25-year
veteran of the Amsterdam-based consumer electronics company, will
replace Cor Boonstra as chief executive when he steps down April
30. During Boonstra's four years at the helm, he streamlined the
company and shored-up profits by selling lagging divisions. His
successor, Kleisterlee, has held numerous positions within Philips,
including running the company's components business in Asia. The
departure of the 62-year-old Boonstra, coincides with the
resignation of Adri Baan, 57, who will step down from his post as
president and chief executive of Philips Consumer Electronics March
29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWEDISH VENTURE FUND
</P>
<P>
   Three Swedish companies, Ericsson, Investor AB and AB
Industrivarden, along with Merrill Lynch, said they would form a
$300 million venture capital fund to invest in mobile Internet
start-up firms. The fund will be called Ericsson Venture Partners
and will focus on all aspects of mobile Internet technology,
including network infrastructure, services and applications. Each
partner is committing $75 million to the fund, which is expected to
be operational by October. In June Ericsson, the Stockholm-based
telecommunications company, said it would launch an incubator and
venture-capital company called INN to develop new technologies
beyond its core telecommunications-equipment business.
Industrivarden is one of Sweden's largest holding companies with a
stock portfolio worth about $8 billion. Investor, whose largest
shareholder is the Wallenberg family of Sweden, manages about $20
billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   VOLKSWAGEN TALKS BREAK DOWN
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of wage talks between union leaders and
management at Volkswagen's plant in Puebla, Mexico, have broken
down despite the government arbitrator announcing late Tuesday
night that Volkswagen had raised its offer to 20 percent. Union
leaders representing 12,600 workers at the only plant in the world
that still produces the VW Bug and its popular successor, the New
Beetle, are holding out for a 21 percent rise. But a union
spokesman said that the two sides could reach agreement when talks
reconvene Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE SWITCHED OFF
</P>
<P>
   Solidaridad 1, a Mexican telecommunications satellite that broke
down over the weekend, was switched off after the operating
company's repeated efforts to restart the central processor failed.
The $250 million satellite, built by General Motors Corp.'s Hughes
Space &AMP; Communications Co., failed Sunday morning and prompted
Mexico's only satellite operating company, Satmex, to shift service
for more than 100 domestic and international clients to its other
three satellites and other orbiters owned by other companies.
Solidaridad 1 was operating at half its capacity on a back up
computer after the principal central processor broke down last
year.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL FUND CONSOLIDATION
</P>
<P>
   In a further consolidation of Canadian mutual fund managers, AGF
Management has agreed to buy Global Strategy Holdings for $438
million (Canadian), or $295 million (U.S.). Global and AGF (for
American Growth Fund) are both based in Toronto. With Global's 6
billion Canadian dollars in 22 funds, the combined company will
manage $35 billion (Canadian) dollars worth of assets ($23.6
billion U.S.) in 102 mutual funds, moving it close to front-ranked
Investors Group and the Trimark-AIM combination. Over the past five
years, several smaller Canadian fund companies have been bought by
larger competitors as sales have slowed, and managers have had to
trim costs to compete with lower fees charged by foreign
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI EXECUTIVE RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   The head of South Korea's largest brokerage house, Hyundai
Securities, resigned, bowing to pressure from the government and
creditor banks that had accused him of hindering restructuring
efforts at its parent company, Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest
conglomerate. The executive, Lee Ik-chi, 56, has been a close aide
to the Chung family that founded Hyundai Group. Creditor banks
blamed Lee, and other executives loyal to the Chung family, of
playing a major role in leading to the financial trouble at the
conglomerate. His resignation will be accepted at a board meeting
scheduled for next Monday, Hyundai Securities said.
</P>
</TEXT>
