<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRC-TENNIS-CYCLOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR U.S. OPEN TENNIS, A SERVICE LINE UMPIRE THAT NEVER BLINKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tennis fans who dislike the temper tantrums thrown by
some top players over line umpires' calls can thank Bill Carlton
that there aren't more of them.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton, an inventor from Malta, developed a system called the
Cyclops by Carlton, a service line monitor that uses infrared beams
to determine whether a serve is in or out.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclops, which was developed about two decades ago and has
been refined continually since then, is now used in many major
tournaments, including Wimbledon and the U.S. Open, which is taking
place this week and next at the National Tennis Center in Flushing
Meadows-Corona Park. Line umpires say the system helps relieve some
of the pressure when calling serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an umpire, I loved it,'' said Jay Snyder, tournament
director at the U.S. Tennis Association. ``Probably the most
argued-over call in tennis is the serve because it's so
split-second. But the players don't argue with the Cyclops. They've
come to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no published accuracy statistics, Snyder said
that Cyclops' calls were accurate more than 99 percent of the time,
barring extreme temperature changes that can affect the court
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Other umpires appreciate the system's objectivity in situations
where they could be accused of favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machine doesn't care whether you're from Spain or from Los
Angeles,'' said Brian Early, a referee with the U.S. Tennis
Association. ``It just calls the balls the way it is, and that's
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the U.S. Open gets under way each year at the National
Tennis Center, Bill Carlton's daughter, Sarah Gauci Carlton,
arrives from Malta to set up Cyclops systems on center court and on
three others where marquee matches are played. Carlton stays
through the tournament to maintain the systems and make
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   The tennis association, which started using Cyclops for the Open
in 1981, rents the systems from the Carltons. Cyclops is also used
at Wimbledon and the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclops system consists of two boxes bolted to the court
surface on the sidelines, in line with the back of the service box.
One of the Cyclops boxes transmits five infrared beams across the
court to the other box, which is the receiver and is connected to a
smaller control box held by the service line umpire. There is an
identical setup on the other side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   The boxes are positioned so one infrared beam runs along the
good side of the service box line, and the other four run on the
fault side, up to 18 inches from the line. When a ball hits on the
line (or just inside the line) it momentarily breaks the first beam
and turns off the others. If the serve is long, it breaks one of
the four other beams.
</P>
<P>
   The control box signals with a green light when the serve breaks
the first beam. It it breaks any of the others without breaking the
first beam, it signals with a red light and a loud beep. A serve
well beyond or in front of the beams is considered easy enough for
the umpire to judge by eye.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclops can be used only at the service line because, unlike
the baselines or sidelines, there are no feet or rackets present to
break the infrared beams. The system must be inactivated (the
umpire pushes a button on the control box) immediately after a good
serve so the ball, racket or feet do not trip the beams again,
triggering more beeps.
</P>
<P>
   Another system, called Tennis Electronic Lines, was installed to
monitor baseline activity at the U.S. Open in the early 1990s,
Snyder said, but it was unsuccessful. The system used metal sensors
under the court lines and a tennis ball with metallic fibers to
determine the ball's location. The system was expensive, and it was
frequently set off by players who had metal eyelets in their tennis
shoes or metallic fibers in their rackets.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Cyclops system has been redesigned to be
less sensitive to insects attracted by the lights that are used for
night games, Snyder said. And the whistle that was initially used
to indicate a fault has been replaced by a lower-pitched beep,
partly because it can be heard better in large stadiums and partly
because some spectators would occasionally mimic the whistle sound
when they thought that a ball was out.
</P>
<P>
   As precise as it is, the Cyclops system is used to complement,
not replace, people. The line umpire has the final call and can
shut down the system if there are questions about its accuracy.
That rarely happens.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each match of the Open, Carlton speaks to the
service-line umpire about how well the system worked. ``There are a
few linesmen who are more particular than others, but very few who
don't like it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
