<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEMP-UNION-NYT &LR;      08-30 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMP-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR BOARD MAKES UNION MEMBERSHIP EASIER FOR TEMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years it was nearly impossible for temporary
workers to join unions, but the National Labor Relations Board
issued a ruling on Wednesday that opened the door for many temps to
join unions at their workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based labor board, in a 3-1 decision that took
effect immediately, authorized temporary workers at a business to
join the same union as the company's permanent workers without
first obtaining permission from the employment agency that assigned
the temps to the business.
</P>
<P>
   In its previous rulings, the board stated that temporary workers
sent by an employment agency to a company could vote to join a
union at the company only if the employment agency agreed.
Temporary help agencies rarely gave the workers they sent to a
company the go-ahead to join a union at the company.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the AFL-CIO hailed the ruling, saying it would
help improve wages, benefits and working conditions for many of the
1.2 million people employed by temporary agencies _ one of the
fastest growing segments of the work force.
</P>
<P>
   But many business groups criticized the ruling, insisting that
it would raise production costs for many employers and might force
companies to pay their temporary workers more than they had agreed
to in their contract with temporary staffing agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The labor board ruled that in many cases temporary workers are
in effect the employees of the user company and not of the agency
and that, because of their similar circumstances, they should be
treated as part of the same bargaining unit as the user company's
permanent employees.
</P>
<P>
   The labor board wrote, ``A growing number of employees who are
part of what is commonly described as the `contingent work force'
are being effectively denied representational rights guaranteed
them under the National Labor Relations Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the decision, labor unions might simply petition the labor
board to rule that several dozen temporary employees at a unionized
work site should be added to the union bargaining unit, even
without a vote by the temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the union movement is straining to add workers,
the decision was important for labor because the number of people
working for temporary help agencies soared more than sixfold from
1982 to 1998, while jobs over all grew by 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, the AFL-CIO's president, said the ruling ``is an
important step in addressing the rights of contingent work force
employees, who have too often been relegated to second-class status
and rights, if any.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Craver, a labor relations expert at George Washington
University, said, ``For unionized firms that have been bringing in
temporary workers to save money, that benefit may be lost because
all of a sudden those temp workers may have to be in the same
bargaining unit as the permanent workers. As a result, there will
be less incentive to use outside workers.''
</P>
<P>
   David Miller, a lawyer for one of the companies that lost the
case, the Jeffboat Division of the American Commercial Marine
Service Co., said, ``This could be a devastating decision. It means
that these employees could be covered by the wages and benefits in
a union contract when neither the user company or the temp agency
had considered that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
