<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     08-30 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV17-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 17, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: I am having trouble clearing a clog from my bathtub drain.
Water runs out so slowly that it can take up to an hour for the tub
to empty completely.
 &HT;    I pulled out the pop-up drain in the bottom of the tub and
cleaned out all the matted hair and soap, then used a plunger on
the drain opening. This helped only slightly.
 &HT;    Short of using a strong chemical drain cleaner (which I have
been advised to avoid) is there something else you can suggest?
 &HT;    A: You can use a drum-type cable auger (or ``snake'') to clear
tub clogs that are further down in the drain line.
 &HT;    Remove the pop-up drain first, then unscrew and remove the
overflow plate (at the top of the tub). The linkage that connects
this plate to the drain stopper will come out with it.
 &HT;    Next, feed about three feet of the auger cable down through the
overflow tube pushing it in with steady pressure while turning the
crank on the handle.
 &HT;    After pushing through the trap (you will feel resistance
decrease sharply) pull the cable out and run lots of hot water down
the drain.
 &HT;    Then replace the pop-up drain and the overflow plate.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My plastic laminate kitchen counters are now dull looking,
not bright like they were originally.
 &HT;    Is there anything you can suggest to restore their luster?
 &HT;    A: There are products on the market that are supposed to restore
the gloss to worn Formica and similar plastic surfaces, but as a
rule these only work well on walls, cabinets and other vertical
surfaces.
 &HT;    They can be used on counter tops, but will not last very long
and will wash off easily.
 &HT;    The only other option would be to cover the old laminate with a
new layer of plastic laminate.
 &HT;    Or maybe try something like a clear polyurethane coating over
the old surface _ though I am not sure if the counter would then be
safe for cutting foods on.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q:. We have a retaining wall behind our house that is made of
railroad ties piled on top of each other.
 &HT;    The ties had been treated with creosote and this creosote is
constantly seeping out of the exposed wood. The odor is very strong
and annoying.
 &HT;    Is there any way we can treat this exposed wood to seal in this
odor?
 &HT;    A: This problem is not easy to solve. Scraping off as much of
the creosote as you can will help.
 &HT;    Then wash with a solvent such as paint thinner or kerosene. This
will dissolve the creosote on the surface so it can be washed off.
 &HT;    Even more effective would be to use a pressure washer or steam
cleaner, although this may only help for awhile because some of the
creosote may continue to ooze out later on.
 &HT;    Longer lasting results will be secured if you paint over the
creosote with two coats of a stain-killing sealer such as BIN or
Kilz after the wood has been cleaned. These dry white, but the
creosote would probably cause them to turn a brownish color as it
``burns through'' the finish.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My wood chairs had a heavy wax buildup which I finally
cleaned off several years ago.
 &HT;    However, the finish on the chairs is now sticky again _ when
people sit on a chair they tend to stick to it.
 &HT;    What would you suggest to clean off this sticky film of wax or
soil?
 &HT;    A: For removing wax and polish I have found that mineral spirits
(paint thinner) works well.
 &HT;    Dry cleaning fluid also works well in most cases, and is safer
to use because it is not flammable, but make sure there is plenty
of ventilation in the room when you use any of these.
 &HT;    Wet a rag with the solvent and rub on vigorously over one
section at time. Change rags as they get dirty.
 &HT;    Then rub with a dry cloth to remove the softened wax.
 &HT;    Repeat if necessary.
 &HT;    If the surface is dull apply a cream type furniture polish _ but
apply this sparingly and not too often.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``CLEANING A BATHTUB DRAIN'' goes with
this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Cable-type drain auger is pushed into tub's drain
opening to clean out clog inside pipe or trap under tub.
 &HT;     
