A6708 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-INTL-SOC0831-COX     08-30 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTL-SOC0831-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Qualifying draw aids Euro washouts
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The new European order that was created after this
summer's Euro 2000 tournament might not remain for long.
</P>
<P>
   UEFA's ``blind draw'' ensured that a few of the
poorer-performing clubs stand a decent chance of reaching the 2002
World Cup. European qualifying starts on Saturday, and some of the
blander sides _ England, Germany, Norway, Belgium and Denmark _
face very weak opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two of the best teams of the summer _ stylish Euro
semifinalists Holland and Portugal _ are lumped together in Group
2, although they should have no trouble prevailing when qualifying
concludes a year from now. The nine group winners and the top
second-place team advance directly to play in Japan and South
Korea. The remaining eight runners-up will play off for the
remaining four positions.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling battle this weekend could be Saturday's
friendly in Paris between reigning champion France and England,
which doesn't start qualifying until next month. The match will be
the last for retiring French captain Didier Deschamps, but England
is taking a similar side to the one that disappointed during the
Euro. The major addition is striker Andy Cole of Manchester United,
who could inherit the role of the retired Alan Shearer.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend also will mark the competitive debuts for new
coaches with four of the biggest teams in Europe: Giovanni
Trappatoni of Italy, Louis van Gaal of Holland, Rudi Voller of
Germany and Antonio Oliveira of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   In Group 1, Yugoslavia is the clear favorite. The Republic of
Ireland has a brutal draw in Group 2, playing at Holland and
Portugal to start. Bulgaria, the Czech Republic and Denmark should
compete in Group 3.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has never qualified for the World Cup, but has a good
chance in a Group 4 draw with only Sweden to worry about. Norway
and the Ukraine are the best of the lot in Group 5, with Croatia,
Scotland and Belgium enjoying the same status in Group 6.
</P>
<P>
   Spain should have no trouble winning Group 7, and Group 8 honors
should go to Italy and Romania. England and Germany didn't make it
out of the same Euro foursome, but Group 9 probably will be theirs,
because Finland, Greece and Albania haven't come close to reaching
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In CONCACAF, the United States on Sunday plays host to
Guatemala, which never has won on American soil. The contest at RFK
Stadium could propel the Yanks into the next round. Erratic Mexico
plays host to Panama, and Trinidad and Tobago could clinch a berth
against Canada.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA, UEFA MEET
</P>
<P>
   In a rare show of unity, officials from FIFA and UEFA are
meeting in Zurich today to hash out alternatives to European
Commission threats to tear down the present system of transfer fees
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The international and European federations allege that the EC's
proposal to grant freedom of movement to in-contract players would
cause ``chaos'' in the sport at a time of record signings and
increasing dominance by wealthy teams. ``The gap between rich clubs
and the others would worsen,'' FIFA boss Sepp Blatter told Le Monde
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   EC spokesman Christophe Forax said the Brussels body is not
proposing to do away with a compensation plan but only is forcing
soccer entities to operate under the same European Union laws as
all other employers in
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS LEAGUE Defending champion Real Madrid has earned a
relatively easy break for first-round group play in the Champions
League, which kicks off Sept. 12. Real will meet Bayer Leverkusen,
Sporting Lisbon and Spartak Moscow. Manchester United also has a
favorable draw with Dynamo Kiev, Dutch champions PSV Eindhoven and
Belgian power Anderlecht. Italian champion Lazio should advance out
of a group that includes Arsenal, Sparta Prague and Shakhtar
Donetsk of the Ukraine. The toughest cluster is Group H, with
Barcelona, AC Milan, Leeds and Turkish runner-up Besiktas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
