<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-TOO-CLEAN-HOUSES-ART-     08-30 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-CLEAN-HOUSES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, THERE'S SUCH A THING AS TOO CLEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN LELAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been a banner season for slobs. As the nation spent the
summer watching those telegenic survivors turn desert-island filth
into high ratings, researchers in the United States and in England
told a different kind of dirty story: a little squalor may be good
for the health. Common household germs and dust, it seems, play a
vital role in the development of immune systems. In housekeeping
terms, this is the equivalent of discovering that chocolate bonbons
cure varicose veins.
</P>
<P>
   All of this may come as a surprise to those who watched Cheryl
Mendelson's manual, ``Home Comforts: The Art and Science of Keeping
House'' (Scribner, $35), rise up best-seller lists last year.
Riding a drift in the national mood, Mendelson raised a crisply
ironed flag for a holy mission against disorder. Even the neatest
of us, she proposed, lives but one step removed from ``the
oppression of dirt, with its associations of death, discomfort,
shame and danger.'' Wielded with due rigor, the Electrolux becomes
not just a modern convenience but a weapon in a moral crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a handful of studies indicate that this crusade may have
gone too far. Though the evidence is still preliminary, researchers
believe our progress in domestic hygiene may be at least partly
responsible for increased rates of asthma, eczema, hay fever and
allergies, and that it may open the avenue for the emergence of new
germs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are changing the bacteria that we've adapted to over
millions of years,'' said Dr. Stuart Levy, director of the Center
for Adaptation Genetics and Drug Resistance at Tufts University
School of Medicine. The results of this tinkering, he said, are
ominous.
</P>
<P>
   Even a clean room _ that holy grail of parenting _ is overrated,
said Robert Billingham, a professor of human development and family
studies at Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have bought into the idea that if I don't teach my kid
to be clean and organized, I'm not a good parent,'' said
Billingham, who admitted to not being terribly neat. ``But there
isn't any research that shows messy children are any less healthy
or successful or happy than orderly ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Arizona reported last week in
The New England Journal of Medicine that children who were exposed
early to common household germs and infections were less likely to
develop asthma and wheezing by the time they turned 6. Forget about
protecting kids from germs: Those who had older siblings or
attended day care before the age of 6 months _ both prime sources
of filth and infection _ were healthier than the ones who did not.
</P>
<P>
   The results offered the latest round of support for what has
been called the ``hygiene hypothesis,'' a growing contention that
we don't have enough dirt and germs in our lives. In the 1980s,
researchers sought to explain why asthma and allergies were growing
at striking rates in some parts of the world, including the United
States, while pottering along in others. The most obvious
explanation was that pollutants in industrial societies were making
people sick.
</P>
<P>
   Then a string of studies found an unexpected pattern: more
highly polluted cities in places like the former East Germany and
industrial China actually had lower rates of asthma than their
cleaner counterparts in West Germany or Hong Kong. The explanation,
clearly, lay elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're finding is that childhood exposure to infections
and certain environmental toxins seems to have a protective
effect,'' said Dr. Andrew Liu, a pediatric asthma specialist at the
National Jewish Medical and Research Center in Denver. In dirtier
cities, the children grew up around high levels of toxins, and
their immune systems developed the right defensive responses; in
cleaner cities, those growing up in meticulously tidy homes were
less likely to develop defenses against the toxins _ and by
extension, more likely to develop asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Liu and a team of researchers in Denver found that early
exposure to ordinary house dust appears to reduce young children's
chances of developing asthma. The researchers surmised that the
children developed an immune response to common bacterial
components called endotoxins, which are found in dust and around
many animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immune system learns much like our brain learns,'' Liu
said. ``There's a tremendous amount of learning in the early years.
It's also possible that there's a critical period for learning an
immune response, and that you may have difficulty catching up
later.'' He cautioned, however, that if someone already has asthma,
dust will only make it worse.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers further speculate that, with too few germs or
allergens to attack, the immune system turns on the body's own
cells. But the studies of this autoimmune response have been mixed,
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more risky than the overzealous broom are the armies of
antibacterial products waiting to invade the kitchen, Levy of Tufts
said. A recent survey conducted for the Infectious Diseases Society
of America found that nearly half of all soaps on the market now
contain antibacterial agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does Windex need an antibacterial in it?'' he asked. ``It
already has alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, Levy said, these products are ineffective. But even if
one did work when first applied, as its level of concentration
dropped, bacteria could produce strains that resist it. Earlier
this summer, in response to this threat, the American Medical
Association suggested government regulation for antibacterial
products. Regular soap and water, Levy said, are the best defense
against germs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The war against mess, like other passions of the home, has long
had a social and moral dimension. In America, after all, ``the
great unwashed'' bear a deep social stigma. At the turn of the last
century, keeping a clean home was a ritual not just of hygiene, but
of assimilation, said Suellen Hoy, a historian and the author of
``Chasing Dirt: The American Pursuit of Cleanliness'' (Oxford,
1995). ``It was how you showed you were eager to be an American,''
Hoy said.
</P>
<P>
   Though early pioneers had to establish basic levels of hygiene
to survive, cleanliness quickly evolved into a mark of status and
social mobility _ not next to godliness, as the Methodist leader
John Wesley preached, but next to worldly success. Poor families in
the South swept their dirt floors; immigrants in New York scrubbed
tenement stoops to hospital levels of cleanliness.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Martha Stewart arrived on the scene, tidy rooms and
spotless floors became landmarks in the American mythology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were cleaning up and moving up,'' Hoy said. ``For a
country that has a hard time coming together on anything, we
certainly do on cleanliness.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a tradition that never dies. This year, Ace Hardware ran
a contest soliciting photographs of America's messiest room. They
are portraits of the abyss, the quagmire from which civilization
nonetheless continues to arise.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The current attack on germs also continues a history, said Nancy
Tomes, a professor of history at the State University of New York
at Stony Brook and the author of ``The Gospel of Germs: Men, Women
and the Microbe in American Life'' (Harvard, 1998). The last germ
panic, as she calls it, took shape in the 1900s. Then, as now, the
anxieties about germs rose during a period of increased immigration
and travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden in the early 20th century, people far away
from you were making your clothes,'' she said. ``The movement to
regulate sweatshops arose from a fear of germs from all these
immigrant workers. With the railroads and subways, people started
to travel among people they didn't know, and whose cleanliness
habits were unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   The current germ mania, she said, began with the outbreak of
AIDS, but has grown beyond the limits of reason. ``I understand the
anxieties about emerging viruses,'' she said. ``But there's nothing
in the science of public health to back up those fears.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the end, the struggle for a clean home is a quest not just
for hygiene, but for control. If we cannot control the decline of
civilization in global politics or at the multiplex, at least we
can oppress the dirt in the foyer. In this battle, the control
freaks may have pushed their advantage too far, opening the door
for new levels of chaos and squalor. Sloth may appear lazy, but it
never stays down that long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
