<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-BORN, JAMAICAN-BORN: PRIMARY HITS ETHNIC NERVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn.)   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a primary race that has spawned a soap
opera-like drama. The bitterness of a feud between two Democrats in
the 11th Congressional District in Brooklyn has not only torn apart
a longstanding friendship but has also delivered some of that
anguish to the doorsteps of other politicians and voters in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a race that has brought to the surface simmering
_ and often unspoken _ tension between black New Yorkers whose
roots are in the U.S. and those with Caribbean heritage. In her
campaign for Congress, Una Clarke, the Jamaican-born city
councilwoman, has not only heralded her Caribbean roots in the
campaign, but has also accused her old friend and mentor, U.S. Rep.
Major Owens, of being anti-immigrant. Owens, who was born in
Memphis, has accused Clarke of trying to turn black Brooklynites
against one another by using ethnic chauvinism to get votes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, theirs has not just been a political contest. It
has represented a springboard for many to consider anew the
relationship between two groups of black New Yorkers who often have
their own share of prejudices against one another. At the same
time, it has focused attention on the political impact of New
York's growing Caribbean population.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been some degree of tension between
African-Americans and Caribbean-Americans over the years,'' said
Don Quinn Kelley, a professor of history at Medgar Evers College in
Brooklyn. ``Color is the thing the two have in common. But there
are misconceptions, and some degree of mistrust.'' And a race like
the one between Owens and Clarke, he said, ``causes people to focus
on them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that mistrust may come from a natural succession that
has become part of the fabric of New York: The latest immigrant
group encroaching on the territory of earlier groups. In this case,
the wariness has been complicated by the fact that many U.S.-born
blacks in New York City have not had the same economic success that
earlier groups of immigrants had.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans have not translated their gains in the
public sector in the way that the Jews or the Italians did,'' said
Philip Kasinitz, a professor of sociology at the City University
Graduate Center and author of the book ``Caribbean New York.''
``So, when they face the same issues of ethnic succession, in this
case by Caribbeans, it seems that there is more to lose. And that
contributes to the tension.''
</P>
<P>
   To Clarke, a 64-year-old legislator known for her sharp tongue
and her championing of immigrant rights, Owens, also 64, is a tired
congressman who has grown ineffective and disconnected. ``It's not
about friendship,'' she said. ``Too much has been made of
friendship. It's about leadership and effectiveness. I don't think
he has kept up with the needs of the changing community.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens sees Clarke's challenge through a different lens. It is,
he insists, spurred purely by her desire to cling to public office
in the face of a term-limit law that prohibits her from running for
re-election to the New York City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Owens says that by appealing to voters based on her Jamaican
background, Clarke has crossed the line between ethnic pride and
demagoguery. In a recent debate on New York 1, the New York City
cable news network, he likened those tactics to Hitler's.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said the congressman accused her of something she has
never done. ``I appeal to everyone in every community,'' she said.
Clarke added that it was the congressman who was trying to place a
wedge between citizens born here and those born overseas. The
debate turned into a shouting match, with Clarke declaring
repeatedly, ``Major Owens, you're a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   The population of the 11th Congressional District is about 55
percent black, with more than two-thirds of those being Caribbean
blacks. The district is also about 25 percent white, which includes
a significant population of Orthodox Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the elected officials in central Brooklyn have endorsed
Owens, saying that his seniority in Congress would place him in a
position to be chairman of a committee or subcommittee, should the
Democrats regain control of the House. Moreover, while many
officials complain that the congressman's record has been
unremarkable, they say he has nonetheless been effective and has
roots deep in the community.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman has taken great pains to portray Clarke as an
ally of the Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, which is not
considered a plus in this heavily Democratic district. He charges
that Clarke has not been outspoken about incidents where police
brutality was alleged, pointing out that he was arrested during
civil disobedience activities while she had not been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dare say that I will get far more Caribbean votes than she
will,'' Owens said. ``And I will get more Jewish votes, too. I
haven't just started forging relationships in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clarke suggests that she expects Caribbean and Jewish voters
to respond favorably to her view on Owens' stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   She denies his contention that she is motivated by term limits;
rather, she calls it a sincere desire to improve the quality of
representation in the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you ask people in the district to name a couple of things
that the incumbent has done that demand his remaining, they are
hard pressed,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
