<HEADER>
A6720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BANKS-TAKEOVERS-NYT &LR;      08-30 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-TAKEOVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT SUISSE-DLJ DEAL MAY SIGNAL WAVE OF FUTURE ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, David H. Komansky, the chief executive of
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., has been predicting that the financial world
one day will be dominated by a handful of global giants. That
forecast has become accepted wisdom on Wall Street but figuring out
who the eventual rulers will be _ and how many of them will be
based in the United States _ is not getting much easier.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that several Wall Street firms, including J.P.
Morgan and Lehman Brothers Holdings, are too small to be among them
unless they buy or are bought by other banks or brokerage firms.
The proposed sale of mid-sized investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette to Credit Suisse Group is the clearest sign yet that
securities firms need to be diverse, both geographically and in
their lines of business, to serve the biggest corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Even Merrill Lynch, with the biggest network of stockbrokers in
the world, is not assured a seat at the head table if its
competitors continue to grow at a faster pace. Merrill is no bigger
than any of the other companies generally considered to rank among
the world's top five investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock-market valuation of about $56 billion makes it the
equal of the Goldman Sachs Group and Credit Suisse and considerably
smaller than Citigroup and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. By that
measure, Merrill is only about 10 percent bigger than the discount
brokerage firm Charles Schwab Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the management of Merrill Lynch or Goldman
Sachs woke up this morning and said, `Gee, this is great,''' said
Michael Holland, president of the money-management firm Holland &AMP;
Co., referring to Credit Suisse's proposed $12.8 billion purchase
of Donaldson, which was officially announced Wednesday. ``It is
clearly a more competitive creature.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe L. Roby, Donaldson's chief executive who will be chairman of
First Boston's executive committee for three years after the
merger, said his management team decided to sell now because
``there's significant change afoot in our industry.'' Alluding to
consolidation that he expects to continue, he said, ``We were
concerned about activities around us which could have an impact on
our competitive position.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome P. Kenney, a Merrill executive vice president who
formulates corporate strategy, acknowledged that the combination of
Donaldson and Credit Suisse's Credit Suisse First Boston investment
bank, appears competitive with Merrill on paper. ``One firm is
elevated and could be ranked higher than we are in a few
categories,'' he said. ``This will be a tougher challenge for us
but one we think we're ready for.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney said Merrill's executives had long anticipated the
consolidation in financial services now taking place. They expected
Donaldson to be snapped up by a competitor and believe similar
acquisitions were inevitable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within three years, we expect there to be no major mid-size
independent securities firms in this country,'' he said. ``We'll
end up with 6 to 10 top-tier global players.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Merrill, Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were
an unchallenged triumvirate known as ``MGM'' on Wall Street. But
several changes have shaken up the ranks of investment banks:
Morgan Stanley merged with the Dean Witter brokerage firm and grew
much larger, Salomon Brothers merged with the Smith Barney
brokerage firm and then became part of the Citigroup financial
conglomerate, and Goldman Sachs went public and raised capital to
finance its growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Credit Suisse became a contender by building up
its technology banking practice in Silicon Valley, just in time to
cash in on the bonanza of Internet stock offerings. Another Swiss
bank, UBS AG, has acquired two investment banks in the last five
years and is in the process of buying PaineWebber Group, the
fourth-largest brokerage firm in the United States, for about $12
billion.
</P>
<P>
   A third big European bank, Deutsche Bank of Germany, acquired a
presence on Wall Street by buying Bankers Trust and its Alex. Brown
brokerage unit, based in Baltimore. And Chase Manhattan Corp.,
which owns the nation's third-biggest bank, has been buying up
investment banks with the hope of becoming competitive in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those banks has the resources to buy one or more of the
remaining independent firms on Wall Street. The imbalance of supply
to the potential demand has driven up the prices of shares of those
firms, including Lehman Brothers, J.P. Morgan and Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   The pending purchase of Donaldson has set a floor under the
prices those firms would fetch, analysts said. Credit Suisse has
agreed to pay about three times Donaldson's book value, or the
value of its assets minus liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said other firms would sell for a higher multiple
of their book value, either because they have more stable revenue
and earnings than Donaldson or because a merger involving them
would not involve as much cost-cutting and as many layoffs as are
expected in the Donaldson deal.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Donaldson and First Boston said they expected to
eliminate about 2,500 jobs in merging the two firms, or about 9
percent of the combined work force of 26,000. Richard Thornburgh,
First Boston's chief financial officer, said that number was low
compared with some bank mergers.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said they expected more. ``There will be a lot
of carnage here, tons,'' said Steven Eisman, an analyst at CIBC
Oppenheimer. In addition to layoffs, he said, ``I see a lot of
people coming in here and picking off employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Judah Kraushaar, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, said he thought
J.P. Morgan was the truly attractive target on Wall Street because
it had a strong money-management business that produces steady
fees. He estimates that J.P. Morgan could be acquired for $180 to
$240 a share, compared with its current price of $151.06.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second-tier firms share a lot of the challenges that DLJ
confronted,'' he said. ``After this, they will have a deep-seated
need to reassess a go-it-alone strategy. That's not to say that
some of the bigger companies might not react too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraushaar said that Chase ``had an interest in DLJ'' and seemed
``eager and willing to look at anything that might come on the
block.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
