<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CNN-FUTURE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-30 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-FUTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN IS SEEKING A NEW STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients and a
graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1997, CNN, the 24-hour cable news channel, found itself at
somewhat of a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   Its blanket coverage of the Persian Gulf war had already
established it as the news outlet to turn to in times of crisis.
But it was not the one to watch for general news when times were
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   With the country well into a prolonged period of prosperity, and
new cable news outlets being started by Fox and General Electric's
NBC _ creating the threat of competition where there had been none
before _ CNN's executives were looking for something to make it the
news outlet of record all of the time.
</P>
<P>
   So they hired Richard N. Kaplan, an ABC News producer widely
regarded as gifted, in the hope that as the president of their
United States operation, he would bring to CNN what the broadcast
networks already had: highly produced news programming so
compelling that millions of people would tune in regularly whether
there was big news or not. Think ``Nightline'' and ``Prime Time
Live'' on ABC, a unit of the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   But in the three years that have passed, CNN's audience has
shrunk to its lowest levels in at least a decade. Advertising
revenues, while still increasingly significant thanks to a robust
market, are not meeting expectations, executives there said.
</P>
<P>
   Dual announcements Wednesday that Kaplan was resigning from CNN
and that its entire executive structure was being revamped were
accompanied by admissions that the strategy did not work and a
sense in some quarters that the network had become too slick and
sophisticated for its own good. The situation seems to be of
pressing concern as CNN finds itself in an increasingly competitive
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that CNN News group make major changes, which
will better equip us to strengthen ourselves,'' said Tom Johnson,
the CNN chairman, ``and to become even more competitive in the
Internet world.''
</P>
<P>
   The question remains: where, exactly, does CNN go from here?
</P>
<P>
   Can it ever regain its status as a must-see network at a time
when its franchise has been chipped away at relentlessly _ among
conservatives and political junkies, by the News Corp.'s Fox News
Network, among the young, by MSNBC, and among the financial news
junkies now being served by the fast-rising CNBC?
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's resignation also raises the question of what CNN will
look like inside its prospective, new corporate parent, America
Online, which is acquiring Time Warner, of which CNN is a
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   These are questions that have been consuming much of the CNN
executives' time. In recent weeks, at meetings at the Four Seasons
Hotel in Atlanta and other venues, they have been in various,
sometimes tense discussions trying to analyze the network's
failings and trying to figure out what can be done to draw viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fallout from Wednesday's news, executives at CNN's
Atlanta's headquarters were sending somewhat mixed signals as to
what needed to be done to turn things around at the network.
</P>
<P>
   There was wide agreement that the expensive and highly produced
programming that Kaplan made his trademark at the network would not
be in such abundance, that the network would go for somewhat of a
rougher, newsier feel like the one that helped put it on the map in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kaplan had tried to bring a higher level of sophistication
to the network, one top-level manager said executives would like to
also produce a greater number of stories with broader audience
appeal, though he did not offer specifics. There was also an
acknowledgment that the network needs more news stars, large
personalities who will stand out above the din, help CNN
distinguish itself and draw viewers _ echoing a refrain from before
Kaplan's arrival there.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with numerous CNN executives Wednesday, there
was a sense that the network had been slowfooted in adapting to the
new environment, after being, for so long, the only major cable
news provider.
</P>
<P>
   They said they believe this led to one of their greater
failings: not realizing that with all the new competition, CNN
needed to be more heavily promoted in other media.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan _ whose fate was sealed Tuesday, when he was presented
with a new CNN flow chart that did not include him _ said the lack
of promotion was a key factor in the failure of his magazine-style
programs, and, ultimately, in his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Boasting a large presence both literally and physically _ he is
6 feet 4 inches tall with a booming voice _ Kaplan arrived at CNN
with a reputation as an imposing figure in the broadcasting
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   He brought in some of his former stars from ABC, like Willow Bay
and Jeff Greenfield, as well as some producers. Some old guard CNN
executives who were at the network from its start in 1980 and still
saw themselves as television news renegades, took to calling Kaplan
and his new hires ``the ABC mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   They predicted that his signature news magazine program,
``NewsStand,'' would not work on cable, where viewers tend to flip
between channels and do not necessarily have patience for longer,
in-depth stories. It has still not taken off with viewers. The
program stumbled when its first episode, alleging that the United
States military used nerve gas during the Vietnam War, had to be
retracted.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from his office in Atlanta Wednesday,
Kaplan said he thought ``NewsStand,'' like all of CNN's
programming, would have done better in the ratings if it had been
better advertised to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our problem is that, in an age when people are
promoting the hell out of everything they do, for CNN to still do
absolutely no promotion is wrong, and is debilitating, and I think
they know that,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the network is now planning to make a major
promotional push in order to raise audience awareness about its
programs. ``I wish it was something that happened when I was
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected that the merger between CNN's parent and AOL
would further help promote the network.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL's appearance on the scene is said by top CNN executives
to be among the largest factors in Kaplan's forced resignation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
