<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RIVERA-NYC-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERALDO CONSIDERS A RUN FOR MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (eds: also moved in `p' category)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geraldo Rivera wants to run for mayor of New York
City and he does not mind if that makes people laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the first reaction to be, `Geraldo as mayor, ha
ha,''' Rivera said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rivera, the longtime television journalist who is anchor of
a talk show on CNBC, said on Wednesday that he was completely
serious about an independent campaign for mayor, after a petition
drive to get his name on the ballot, a campaign that he said would
be ``totally self-financed'' _ even if it costs $5 million to $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is ``just an exploration'' now, Rivera said. He
said he was considering commissioning a poll to determine his
chances. As for qualifications, Rivera cited his long career
covering issues of relevance to the city, his background as a
lawyer, and, as he put it: ``My whole gene pool is New York. I'm
Puerto Rican and Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's proposed candidacy harks back to a long New York
tradition of media figures' seeking to run for City Hall, reaching
at least as far back as the newspaper publisher William Randolph
Hearst in 1905 and including efforts by William F. Buckley Jr., the
conservative writer and talk show host, in 1965 and the novelist
Norman Mailer in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they all lost.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera would prefer a different comparison. ``I think Jesse
Ventura comes much closer to what I want to do: a truly independent
campaign from a political outsider with a serious agenda.'' He said
he would not enter the primaries or try to win the nomination of
any political party.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Rivera, who had lived in New Jersey
but has moved back to Manhattan, said he was convinced the city
needed ``a way to come back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera acknowledged that his often made-for-tabloid personal
history, which has included multiple romantic liaisons and public
fistfights, could pose problems. But he said he had sought
redemption the last several years in serious journalism for CNBC
and NBC News. ``I think I've succeeded,'' he said. ``I defy anyone
to debate me on any issue of consequence to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   One question left unanswered: Would it be Mayor Rivera or Mayor
Geraldo? Rivera said, ``Like Elvis and Lassie and Oprah, I have
one-name recognition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
