A6731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     08-30 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SISTERS DOGGED BY FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Venus and Serena are running. They are sprinting
across the crimson paving stones of the plaza at the National
Tennis Center Wednesday afternoon, and everybody is trying to catch
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus, Serena,'' people are shouting. ``Hey, there they are.
Hey, sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   The mighty Sisters Sledgehammer have to be careful that they
don't trample their pet dogs _ tiny, leashed terriers that seem to
be running for their lives. Jack Russell Williams, Serena's
bauble-on-legs, is white with beige splotches. Pete Williams,
Venus's butterscotch Yorkshire, reminds me of one of Martina
Navratilova's midget curs that her coach with the bygone Boston
Lobsters, Roy Emerson, described as ``a rat with a hair stylist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus, Serena.''
</P>
<P>
   People are following, waving pens for autographs, and just plain
waving. Or cameras, trying to get the Misses Williams _ Serena in
purple slacks and top, Venus in navy shorts and T _ in their camera
sights. This has become a parade to make the Pied Piper of Hamelin
jealous.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of flutes, the sisters mesmerize with rackets. The
procession is a movable metaphor for tennis and the US Open: The
crowd _ their rivals _ pursues like puppies but cannot overtake.
The way these sisters accelerate, who could do anything but end up
coughing, swallowing their dust? To catch a Williams you'd have to
be a Williams _ in the title bout. Either Serena keeps her title,
or Venus takes it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to play Serena in the final,'' Venus says. She has
just flattened Kveta Hrdlickova, 6-1, 6-1, in a 48-minute
second-rounder. The sisters are perched on opposite sides of the
draw, third-seeded Venus in 1997 champ Martina Hingis's precinct,
fifth-seeded Serena in 1998 champ Lindsay Davenport's. ``That would
be my pick, Serena and me. We've played each other in practice
almost every day for years. But we'd like this better, playing for
a lot of people. We feel badly when there's no one there to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks are watching the giggling, grinning sisters' gigantic
strides now as they pass a throng, maybe a couple of thousand,
waiting for Anna Kournikova at a scheduled autograph session.
Kournikova, the most luminous Russian since Catherine the Great,
may win more male hearts, but she's merely a sideshow here. The
sisters are the Grand Exposition, the kids who win on court, too.
</P>
<P>
   As they keep moving along the plaza toward Louis Armstrong
Stadium to browse the gallery containing the International Tennis
Hall of Fame's championship exhibit, word spreads of another
brouhaha and defeat of Dokic. That would be the erratic Damir
Dokic, president of the sport's Bad Dads Club, father/coach of
gifted 17-year-old Aussie Jelena Dokic, who ranks No. 43.
</P>
<P>
   Papa Dokic, a relative newcomer to the scene but already a
persona non grata internationally, got into yet another jam,
screaming at employees of the players' dining room over the price
(adjudged too big, $13.50) of a piece of salmon (adjudged too
small). Unable to calm him, security called a police officer, who
threw him off the grounds from which he's been banned. Nothing new.
Another fine kettle of fish, leaving his daughter weeping. He was
pitched from the Birmingham (England) tourney last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, burly, bearded Daddy D. has assaulted a TV cameraman
at the Australian Open, and a TV reporter at Wimbledon. Dokic
watchers wonder why he was so uncharacteristically docile at the
French Open. An outburst there, coupled with Wednesday's
performance, could have given him a Grand Slam of boorishness.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters' papa, Richard Williams, has had his moments on
camera, too. But such as his victory dance on a TV booth after
Venus won Wimbledon are hardly in Dokic's ill-tempered league.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the gallery, the sisters pause at one of numerous
huge banners, a photographic juxtaposition of Ellen Hansell, the
original US champion, victor in 1887, and Serena, the last champion
of the 20th century. A pair of 17-year-olds. The show, entitled
``The Lady is a Champ,'' features 35 Americans who have won US
women's singles titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty long dress on her,'' Serena is amazed at the shoetop,
fully-sleeved gown enshrouding Hansell. ``Pretty hard to run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No ankles unveiled in those days,'' says Mark Young of the
Hall of Fame. ``And they wore whalebone corsets.'' The sisters
wince.
</P>
<P>
   Peering into a display case, they are intrigued by the spiked
shoes of Helen Jacobs, the victor of 1932, '33, '34, and '35.
``They must have used them when the tournament was on grass,''
Venus surmises correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Althea Gibson, who hurdled the tennis color bar in 1950 and won
the title in 1957 and '58, grabs their attention.
</P>
<P>
   A man standing nearby says, ``Althea was the hardest-serving
champ until you, Serena.''
</P>
<P>
   But the item that really gasses them is the red gingham dress
that Tracy Austin (winner in 1979 and '81) wore in her 1977 debut
as a 90-pound, 14-year-old quarterfinalist. It's a pinafore made by
her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine me trying to get into that,'' laughs Serena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't even be a T-shirt for you,'' responds Venus.
``But, remember? Mom made my outfit for my first pro tournament in
'94.''
</P>
<P>
   They're off on the run again, and the dogs look intimidated.
``Gotta get back to the locker room and change for doubles,'' says
Serena. That will be a 45-minute gig over Kristy Boogert and Miriam
Oremans, 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was it like?'' the vanquished Netherlanders are asked.
``The stadium was nice,'' says Boogert. ``But the Williams are too
big, too strong, too good.''
</P>
<P>
   And running too fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-NAPSTER-PRANKS-AR     08-30 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NAPSTER-PRANKS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SIDES IN THE NAPSTER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When John Fix III closes Cornell's True Value
hardware store in Eastchester, N.Y., every night at 6, he turns out
the lights but leaves the computers running. During the day they
perform inventory checks or crunch numbers, but at night, the
store's 12 personal computers are connected to Napster, the music
file-sharing service.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other Napster users, Fix doesn't have a long list of
favorite songs he hopes to have downloaded by the time he returns
in the morning. Instead, he is using his battalion of PCs to work
toward a different goal: he wants to riddle the Napster universe
with thousands of unusable song files, thereby making Napster less
reliable _ and less attractive _ to its many fans.
</P>
<P>
   Fix and his brother, Michael, operate a Web site that explains
how to ``lay'' what they call cuckoo's eggs, or bad song files,
onto the hard drives of Napster users. The brothers' Web site is
just one of many homespun initiatives to come out of the disputes
generated by Napster and other sites, like Gnutella and Scour, that
let users trade MP3 music files.
</P>
<P>
   In September, a three-judge panel is expected to hear arguments
on whether to permit an injunction against Napster to go into
effect. The injunction would stop Napster users from trading
copyrighted music. But many people have not been content to wait
and have gone online to express their own opinions on the issue _
and even take action to promote their points of view.
</P>
<P>
   Napster and its kin can be viewed as sharing or stealing, as an
innocent means of file sharing or an insidious way to infringe on
copyright. There are plenty of sites on both sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians are behind many of the anti-Napster sites. Earlier
this summer, the Fix brothers were gleefully downloading live Bruce
Springsteen tracks from Napster and reveling in the fact that all
of it was free. But Michael Fix, whose wife, Stephanie, is a singer
and songwriter, started thinking about the unfairness of taking the
work of other people without their permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all thrilled by it,'' he said, ``and then all of a
sudden repulsed by it because of Stephanie. We wish there was a
fair system for artists to share their work online. It's not so
much about compensation for us, but it is about permission. It
should be up to the artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Working after hours at the hardware store, the Fix brothers
released their first batch of cuckoo's eggs in mid-June,
transferring songs by Stephanie Fix to Napster and renaming them as
songs by popular artists. Napster users who searched for Bruce
Springsteen's ``American Skin,'' for example, and downloaded the
version offered by the Fix brothers would instead hear a song by
Stephanie.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fixes had to change their strategy when they realized
that their message was being misunderstood. ``People sent e-mails
accusing us of promoting Stephanie's work, not protesting
Napster,'' Michael Fix said. The second batch of song files
consisted of correctly named song files, but 30 or so seconds into
each song, the brothers inserted an audio clip of the cartoon
character Charlie Brown saying, ``Congratulations,'' followed by a
clip of Yosemite Sam saying, ``Looks like you goofed up
somewhere,'' followed by the sound of a chirping cuckoo that
continued for the rest of the track.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuckoo's Egg Project has received an onslaught of angry
e-mail messages at the site (www.hand-2-mouth.com/cuckooegg), and
hundreds of messages about it have been sent to Slashdot, the
technology site. John Fix said messages were also sent to the
Napster site from people who have downloaded Cuckoo's Egg Project
song files. He estimates that the 91 cuckoo's eggs he and his
brother have created are downloaded 300 to 400 times a day. He said
he was banking on the idea that many people made their song files
available to others without listening to them first.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the folks who disagree write a profane e-mail and move
on, or try to write an intelligent response,'' Michael Fix said,
``but a lot of people have contacted us to say they think we're
doing a great job. The discussion makes us happy and makes it worth
all the work.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One cuckoo's egg went to Tim Poirier, of Bath, Maine, when he
recently downloaded what he thought was a Backstreet Boys remix for
his daughter. When he played the song using a Winamp MP3 player, he
heard a string of cuckoos and saw the Cuckoo's Egg Project Web site
address in the tag window. He went to the site to find out what had
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was annoyed at first,'' Poirier said, ``but then I went to
check it out and read what he had to say. He has a very good case
that people like his wife aren't ever going to make any money
through Napster.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He also went to Stephanie Fix's site and listened to a couple of
her songs. The experience made him re-evaluate his use of Napster.
``I have no problem downloading a song for my kids that they're
going to listen to once instead of buying the CD for $15,'' he
said. ``But I'd buy Stephanie's CD instead of downloading it
because it's something I'd listen to again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another site, Stopnapster.com (www.stopnapster.com), started by
The Tabloids, a rock band in Oakland, Calif., explains and
encourages the use of ``Napster bombs'' (mislabeled song files) and
cuckoo's eggs (it calls them Trojan horses). It also presents the
legal arguments against sharing copyrighted material, as well as
the dangers file sharing presents for users' computers. (Michael
Robinson, lead singer of The Tabloids, says file sharing is like
``unsafe sex.'') Robinson says sites like Napster hurt recording
artists who release albums on independent labels because it is more
difficult for them to recover the costs of lost album sales.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If record companies hired anti-Napster staffs to create and
disperse bad song files, the site says, Napster and other
file-sharing sites would soon ``go the way of the Hula-Hoop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster has started this Orwellian logic where things aren't
really what they seem,'' Robinson said. ``Stealing is called
`sharing' or `sampling,' but in our minds, it's stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he had started the site because he believed that
people were overlooking the fact that Napster is a business. ``This
is not two college kids e-mailing songs to each other,'' he said,
``but a corporation making money off of published music.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Robinson, Stopnapster's administrative manager, said the
site got about 4,000 visitors a day and a steady influx of e-mail.
The site has received 132 e-mail messages from people who are
anti-Napster, 173 e-mail notes from people who are still on the
fence, and 278 e-mail messages from people who support Napster _
some of whom Robinson calls howlers because of the obscenities they
use in their protests.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Travis Hill, a software designer in Provo, Utah, has been
working on a different way to squelch Napster users. His Media
Enforcer software (www.mediaenforcer.net), which he released in
May, allows an individual to search Napster and Gnutella servers
and compile lists of the screen names of people who are offering to
share specific artists or song titles. A new version of the
software, which will soon be released, will also reveal the music
sharer's IP address, which can be traced to that person's Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, an amateur musician, said he had designed the program to
help artists track people distributing their music without
permission. He thinks that music-sharing sites are a deterrent for
aspiring artists, he said. ``If you eliminate intellectual property
royalties,'' he said, ``there won't be a reason for musicians to
create any work. The music industry really should put together a
better digital distribution plan. But for now, people need to
respect copyrights and intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the trail back to the Napster user ends with the ISP,
Hill said, his software will allow artists, their managers or their
record labels to get in contact with the ISP with a request to
forward a ``cease and desist'' notice from the artist to the
computer that was used to share music files. The privacy policies
of most ISPs require a court order before they will contact one of
their clients or forward a message to a client, but Hill said he
believed that an artist whose music was being shared without
permission would have grounds to get such an order. Hill said the
Media Enforcer software would work on other MP3 sites so would be
effective even if Napster was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If an artist or a label really wants to stop someone from
making their music available,'' Hill said, ``they're going to need
a sizable group of people working just to track the usage patterns
of Napster users on the Internet. It's really the only productive
way to go about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of the music-sharing debate _ the contention that
MP3 sites like Napster and Gnutella benefit musicians and that file
sharing over the Internet should be unregulated _ are also
represented online. Matt Miszewski, a band manager in Milwaukee,
for example, began Napster Freedom (Napsterfreedom.com) in August
in an effort to show anti-Napster bands that consumers were buying
their albums as a result of listening to them through files shared
online.
</P>
<P>
   The site's Tracker section features a list of recording artists
who have spoken out against Napster, and it invites visitors to say
how much they have spent on records by each artist. That
information (which the site does not verify) is sent to each
artist's management.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release, Miszewski wrote that Napster Freedom was a
powerful way to garner support for ``downloadable music and its
martyr, Napster.'' The site also features a pro-Napster petition
and encourages the purchase of CD's from pro-Napster artists by
listing some of them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Miszewski's argument for supporting Napster _ that it helps
support little-known bands _ has been widely debated. ``We utilize
Napster and other MP3 sites to market products that aren't getting
air time elsewhere,'' he said. ``Shutting down the site will be an
unfortunate side effect for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people believe that because Napster is a search engine that
lets people look up specific songs and artists, there is little
opportunity for people to encounter new artists through
serendipity. (Miszewski argues that Napster and similar sites
promote new artists through chat rooms and other programs.) Other
music sites, like ThrottleBox (Throttlebox.com) and Freelisten.com
(freelisten.com), have been created to help promote the work of
lesser-known recording artists via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ThrottleBox, based in Johnson City, N.Y., promotes the work of
new and lesser-known artists by making audio and video files, liner
notes and other marketing material available. It also protects the
artists' work by putting them into a file format that is difficult
to copy (users must download ThrottleBox Player software to listen
to the music files).
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what we believe to be the single-largest collection of
sanctioned downloadable content for free,'' said Drew Saur,
ThrottleBox's chief technology officer. The site, he said, is based
on the idea that exposure drives record sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that after I find something I like, I buy it,'' he
said. ``Now it's time for the record labels to step up to the plate
and start doing this sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Adario Strange, formerly editor in chief of The Source, a
hip-hop magazine, started Freelisten.com this month to highlight
new artists with both free music files and other promotional
material. Instead of providing an unending array of free music
files, Strange said, Freelisten will focus on a few artists and
offer exclusives from better-known artists to attract listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to accrue value and cool points with the fans,''
Strange said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fans can tip their favorite artists online through Fairtunes,
which was started this month by two students at the University of
Waterloo in Ontario (fairtunes.com). The site lets the fan enter in
a dollar amount, indicate the recipient and submit a credit card
number. The founders of Fairtunes, Matt Goyer and John Cormie, then
send checks to the artist's management. ( Goyer said postage fees
came out of their tuition money.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the site because we were downloading songs from our
favorite artists but it seemed inefficient to go to the record
store and buy a CD as a way of compensating them,'' Goyer said.
``We thought, `We can get songs over the Web, so why can't we pay
artists over the Web?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fairtunes has raised nearly $1,400 in American and Canadian
dollars. It recently sent a check to U2 for $80, and a check for
$30 to a lesser-known Canadian band called The Noisies, Goyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Goyer and Cormie also hope to work with other MP3 sites to add
tip buttons next to downloading bars so people downloading music
can choose to pay the artists through the Web site.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It's even conceivable that Fairtunes or other programs like it
could become a vehicle for not only voluntary tipping, but enforced
payment. Last week, NapsterFreedom made an agreement with Fairtunes
to include a voluntary tipping button on a new Napster-like
file-sharing program being developed by Topical Networks, the
company that created NapsterFreedom.
</P>
<P>
   Miszewski, of NapsterFreedom, said that the new file-sharing
program would be based on voluntary payments but that Topical
Networks would work with record companies if a court decision
mandated payment for MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't flip the switch until a court decision mandates
payment,'' Miszewski said, ``but we're ready for it if it
happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
