<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-PRAYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Jewish group says prayer efforts show insensitivity
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By KEVIN MORAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE _ Efforts promoting Christian prayer in the stands at
Santa Fe's public school football stadium are insensitive to
religious minorities, Jewish Anti-Defamation League officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort undermines the Supreme Court's efforts to protect
the religious liberties of all students,'' league spokeswoman Dena
Marks of Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ministerial Alliance of Santa Fe and Hitchcock announced
Tuesday that area Christian pastors would be urging their
congregants and others to begin reciting the Lord's Prayer after
the national anthem is played before Friday's season-opening game
between the Santa Fe Indians and the Hitchcock Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the Santa Fe
Independent School District could not allow student-led prayer over
the public address systems at football games.
</P>
<P>
   Besides pastors of about 30 area churches, a Temple-based group
called No Pray, No Play has been urging Christians across the state
to descend on Santa Fe's new high school stadium Friday to join in
the what is being called a ``spontaneous'' prayer effort.
</P>
<P>
   No one person is expected to lead the prayer and the organizers
have said they will not use a public address system. Organizers
predicted that as many as 10,000 people, in addition to the nearly
5,000 the stadium holds, will be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The No Pray, No Play group is urging people to park as close to
the stadium as possible. ``We will pack in around the stadium,''
the group said on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Defamation League leaders maintain that No Pray, No Play
and other stadium prayer organizers' claims of sensitivity to
non-Christians have a hollow ring. Christian organizers had
suggested that anyone who didn't want to hear the prayer could come
late to the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the group's efforts were to pass constitutional
muster, its highly publicized efforts to engage in religious
worship are likely to cause members of minority faiths to feel
coerced and vulnerable at a place where everyone should feel
welcome,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Yovan, pastor of Santa Fe's Maranatha Christian Center,
said those who want to pray at the game have no intention of
hurting anyone's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Vietnam veteran and Vietnam veterans fought for the
minorities,'' Yovan said. ``And we don't want to step on anyone's
religious rights whether they're in the majority or the minority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're in the minority or the majority, I think we
ought to be allowed to worship God or to pray anywhere we want to,
in school, out of school, in church or out of church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No Pray, No Play director Kody Shed was unavailable for comment
Wednesday on whether he had secured a site for a proposed prayer
rally after the prayer recitation.
</P>
<P>
   But on the group's Web site Wednesday, Shed told visitors that
``a main stage will be set up near the stadium (off government
property) for a post-game celebration to include live music. Local
pastors will be given the opportunity to lead the army of prayer
warriors in intercession for the town, our state and our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe Police Chief Barry Cook said his department had not
been notified Wednesday of the time or location of any gathering
aside from the one at which people are expected to pray before
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of traditionally Christian prayer at public school
football stadiums in Santa Fe and other Texas cities have argued
that such prayer violates the principle of separation of church and
state. They also maintain that non-Christians in tax-supported,
publicly owned stadiums should not be subjected to Christian
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of Friday's planned prayer in the stands said they do
not intend to offend anyone but they are not willing to forgo the
decades-old tradition of praying at public school football games.
</P>
<P>
   If members of non-Christian religions are offended by the
stadium prayer, Yovan said he would respond: ``We apologize that we
made you uncomfortable, but we also have rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We love people _ whether Mormons or Jews or gentiles or
Buddhists,'' Yovan said. ``I have nothing bad to say about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want them to do at this point is to allow me to pray the
prayers I want to pray, if it's in private or in public.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
