u f BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      08-30 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MP3.COM STRATEGY REJECTED AT COPYRIGHT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge on Wednesday rejected the argument of
an online music start-up that Universal Music Group is improperly
pursuing a copyright infringement claim against the company as a
means of driving a potential competitor out of business.
</P>
<P>
   During testimony by Edgar M. Bronfman Jr., the chief of
Universal's parent, the Seagram Co., Judge Jed S. Rakoff of federal
district court in Manhattan, ruled as irrelevant MP3.com's
contention that Universal would not settle the suit because of its
own online strategy.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the trial is whether MP3.com willfully disregarded
copyright law when it created an online database that included
about 5,000 of the Universal recordings. Rakoff ruled in April that
MP3.com had violated copyrights held by the five major record
labels with the creation of a service called My.MP3.com. All of the
companies except Universal have since reach settlements with
MP3.com that allow their music to be used in the service for an
undisclosed sum. The other companies are Sony Music, Time Warner,
the EMI Group and Bertelsmann A.G.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge finds that MP3.com willfully violated the law, he
could set damages as high as $150,000 per compact disc. If he finds
that the violation was not willful, damages could be as low as
$200.
</P>
<P>
   My.MP3.com allows users to store music centrally on MP3.com's
computers and get access to it through devices like portable music
players or a personal computer. Rather than requiring users to load
their own music into an online locker, which can be a
time-consuming process, My.MP3.com allowed them to simply insert a
CD into the CD-ROM drive of a computer. Once MP3.com's software
verified that the person had possession of a CD, the company gave
the user access to the music stored on its own computers.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com in May suspended the My.MP3.com service, which it said
had roughly 500,000 participants and about 80,000 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, MP3.com called Bronfman as a hostile witness and
tried to use his testimony to suggest that Universal had an
anticompetitive motive for refusing settlement. Michael Carlinsky,
one of MP3.com's lawyers, asked Bronfman about remarks he had made
comparing MP3.com with Jimmy and Doug's Farmclub, a Web site for
unsigned artists that Universal introduced last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did MP3.com's market valuation bother you?'' Carlinsky asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it excited me,'' Bronfman replied.
</P>
<P>
   Carlinsky also asked Bronfman about a speech in which he
described the My.MP3.com service along with two other Web music
sites, Napster and Gnutella, as ``exemplars of theft, of piracy, of
the illegal and willful appropriation of someone else's property.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think there was a willful disregard for the law?''
Carlinksy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're asking me, do I think someone accidentally purchased
80,000 CDs,'' Bronfman replied.
</P>
<P>
   But after about an hour of back-and-forth, Rakoff dismissed
Bronfman, calling the question of motive irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is obliged to settle a lawsuit,'' the judge said,
adding that he would not allow ``a misuse of a court proceeding for
the airing of hard feelings that understandably exist between the
defendant and the remaining plaintiffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
