<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP EXECUTIVE LEAVING MORGAN STANLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter F. Karches, a top executive of Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and one of its biggest individual shareholders,
has resigned as head of its businesses that cater to institutional
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley said that John J. Mack, the president and chief
operating officer, would take on Karches' responsibilities. Stephan
F. Newhouse, who has been deputy to Karches, will remain in that
position, reporting to Mack, said Ray O'Rourke, a spokesman for the
firm.
</P>
<P>
   All of Morgan Stanley's investment banking and stock and bond
sales and trading operations report to Mack, the firm's No. 2
executive under Philip J. Purcell, the chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Karches, 48, a horse-racing enthusiast who owns thoroughbreds,
is leaving to ``focus my attention on some other goals and
priorities,'' he said in a statement. He had been taking a less
active role in daily operations, people at the firm said.
</P>
<P>
   He has also kept a low public profile after a regulator found
that the industry's rules on political campaign finance were
violated when Karches made a $1,000 contribution to the Senate
campaign of William F. Weld, then the governor of Massachusetts.
Morgan Stanley was subsequently barred from the municipal finance
business in Massachusetts for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Karches, who was not available for comment, has accumulated a
large stake in the firm since he joined it 24 years ago after
graduating from Columbia Business School. He was the first person
hired directly out of business school by the Morgan Stanley bond
sales and trading business, O'Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the firm's latest proxy statement, filed in
January, Karches owned about 4.5 million shares of the firm's
stock. That stake would be worth about $475 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
