<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-TOURISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    EDS: See tilde note in parentheses in last graf
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PORT RESIDENTS HOPE VISIT REVIVES TOURISM
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JOHN R. OTIS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia _ Although President Clinton pledged to
support Colombia's fight against drug traffickers, Marxist rebels
and right-wing paramilitaries, residents of this Caribbean port
city seemed far more concerned about tourists Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they were counting on the hoopla surrounding Clinton's
nine-hour visit to attract thousands of newcomers to Cartagena,
Colombia's most popular tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for the city's image. All over the world,
people will see Cartagena and realize that it is a secure city,''
said Carlos Angulo, a real estate agent who has lived here all his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Due to a long-running civil war, drug-related violence, and the
highest kidnapping rate in the world, Colombia's tourist industry
is suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Just 841,000 international tourists ventured to Colombia last
year, down from 1.4 million in 1995. Even communist Cuba, which is
officially off-limits to most U.S. visitors, has a more robust
tourist trade.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department has warned tourists against traveling
to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a greater risk of being kidnapped in Colombia than in
any other country in the world. ... Acts of violence against
foreigners have occurred in all regions of Colombia, both urban and
rural,'' a State Department travel advisory says.
</P>
<P>
   But civic leaders here point out that Cartagena is one of the
safest destinations in the Caribbean and is more secure than many
U.S. cities. They are lobbying Washington to exclude Colombia from
the travel advisory, which carries great weight in the tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to reactivate tourism, the State Department must
modify its travel warning regarding Cartagena,'' said an editorial
Wednesday in the daily El Universal.
</P>
<P>
   A walled Spanish colonial port, Cartagena is packed with
fortresses, mansions, churches, monasteries, and plazas. It has
served as the setting for novels, paintings, and movies and is a
favorite spot for honeymooners.
</P>
<P>
   Nobel-prize-winning novelist Gabriel Garcia Marquez has a house
here while Cartagena also serves as a vacation retreat for
Colombia's presidents.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, President Bush visited Cartagena for an anti-drug
summit, while President Kennedy stopped here in the early 1960s to
promote his ``Alliance for Progress,'' a massive social program for
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for Clinton's visit, city hall workers embarked a
series of small-scale social programs. They paved streets, fixed
pot holes, painted buildings and walls and removed homeless people
from the historic city center.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from a community justice center in a poor
Cartagena neighborhood toured by Clinton, workers tore down the
shanty of 85-year-old Antonia Sarmiento because it was deemed an
eyesore. They are now building her a new cinderblock house.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that the urban renewal has gone overboard and said
the American president ought to have seen Cartagena, warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they trying to get rid of everything that is ugly?''
said Sonia Penalosa (TILDE OVER N in Penalosa) an unemployed
Cartagena resident. ``They should show (Clinton) the poor parts.
There is so much poverty here in Colombia.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
