<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT &LR;      08-30 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A NAME AND A DATE FOR SONY'S NEW PDA
</P>
<P>
   After almost a year of dribbling out bits and bytes of
information about a collaboration with Palm Inc., Sony announced
this week that its sleek, new personal digital assistant would go
on sale next month. And the device, which will have
lithium-rechargeable batteries and a gray-scale display (color is
in the works), finally has a name: CLIE (pronounced KLEE-ay).
Advance orders can be placed at www.sony.com/clie. CLIE is an
acronym, for communication, link, information and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Palm operating system licensed from Palm Inc., the
CLIE features applications commonly found on Palms, like electronic
address books, calendars, to-do lists and easy synchronization with
personal computers and laptops.
</P>
<P>
   But the CLIE's designers say they have tweaked the Palm system
to add functions. For instance, the device can store and play back
short video clips and can place names with pictures of faces in its
address book.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the CLIE's distinctive features are made possible
because of Memory Sticks, Sony's solid-state removable storage
medium. A stick may be inserted into a slot on top of the slender
(five-eighths of an inch) device. The device comes with 8 megabytes
of internal memory, more than most Palms, and an 8-megabyte Memory
Stick. Additional Memory Sticks for the CLIE come in 16, 32 and 64
megabytes, with a 128-megabyte version scheduled for release, Sony
executives said. Functions that may soon be added to the CLIE
through special Memory Stick expansion modules include a camera, a
Global Positioning System tracker and a voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the CLIE handheld,'' said Russell Paik, vice president
for handheld marketing at Sony Electronics, ``Sony is continuing to
pioneer the integration of entertainment with clever, functional
and elegant electronics devices.''
</P>
<P>
   MICE FOR THE TOUCHY-FEELY AND FOR THE SHORT OF SPACE
</P>
<P>
   Consumers make lots of choices about the computer itself _ how
fast, how much storage, how much RAM _ but a mouse is taken for
granted as just part of the package. You have to have a really good
reason to change the default mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Two new optical mice from the manufacturers Logitech and Targus,
trying to stand out from the crowd. Optical mice replace the rubber
roller ball with light sensors that bounce off any surface and
pinpoint the position of the mouse. Since there are no moving
parts, it doesn't get clogged with dust or get pitted like the
roller ball mice.
</P>
<P>
   Logitech has added force feedback to its new iFeel mouse. Force
feedback is an old concept to computer gamers, but this is a newer
addition to a mouse for the general public. For example, in a
flight simulation game, when you bank left, a signal is sent to the
joystick activating a motor that simulates the effect of resistance
to executing the turn that you'd feel in a real plane. Just about
everybody uses the technology called TouchSense developed by
Immersion Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With the iFeel mouse, the same principle is applied when the
mouse moves over menu items in any Windows program or hyperlinks on
a Web site. Logitech also used Immersion technology. Depending on
which of Immersion's options you use, you get a different sensation
when you move the mouse over different objects on the screen. It
could be a vibration or even a tone. Once the software for the
iFeel mouse is loaded, all Windows programs and all Web sites will
provide feedback.
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, is why does anyone need a mouse that
shakes, rattles and rolls? Bruce Schena, vice president and chief
technology officer of Immersion, said: ``It's the missing element
in how we interact with our computers. We have the visual and
auditory component and now we're adding the tactile.'' There are
two versions of the Logitech iFeel mouse, the MouseMan ($59) and
the Mouse ($39).
</P>
<P>
   Targus, on the other hand, is aiming its new optical mouse at
mobile professionals and those with cramped computing space. Anyone
who has tried to use a laptop on a plane knows that there is barely
room for the computer on the tray, let alone an external mouse.
Targus' Mini-Mouse ($49.99) is half the size of the standard mouse.
The USB mouse comes with a converter that allows older laptops
without a USB port to use the mouse (although the computer must run
Windows 98 or higher).
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM RAISES THE SPECTER OF VIRUSES ATTACKING PDA'S
</P>
<P>
   The first malicious program to attack a Palm organizer appeared
on the Internet this week, causing no permanent damage but leading
security experts to warn that more harmful incursions are probably
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The program, known as Liberty Crack, is a not a virus because it
does not automatically replicate. For that reason, most experts
believe that it is already nearly extinct.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said David Perry, public education director for Trend
Micro, a security company, the program represents a milestone.
``This is the first time in history that someone has written a
piece of malicious software to affect a Palm Pilot.'' The program
was a Trojan horse, designed to trick users into thinking it was a
piece of code that would override the copyright restrictions on
Liberty, a program that lets people play Gameboy games on the Palm.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the program was designed to delete any software that
had been previously downloaded to the Palm, like maps, games and
city guides. Programs that came loaded with the Palm, like the
address book, were not supposed to be affected.
</P>
<P>
   The first warnings about the Trojan horse came from the author
himself, Aaron Ardiri, a software programmer in Sweden who develops
applications for the Palm.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail interview, Ardiri said he had never intended the
program for distribution. He wrote it as a piece of code that would
help clean out the Palm when it was reset. He named it ``test'' and
passed it on to a couple of friends via Internet Relay Chat. Only
later, he said, did he find out that it had been renamed as a crack
program for Liberty, a program that he himself created. ``I have
tried to do anything and everything to prevent its spread and
`infection,''' Ardiri wrote. He also told Internet security
companies about the program.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has reported being victimized by the Trojan
horse, Perry said. ``I consider the case closed,'' he said. But it
may not be long, he added, before similar programs are unleashed as
replicating programs, wreaking much more havoc on personal digital
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opens the door for more development of PDA-malicious
software,'' he said, ``particularly viruses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
