<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA JUDGE RULES MICROSOFT CASE CAN GO ON
</P>
<P>
   A California Superior Court judge in San Francisco has allowed
the first class-action suit to proceed against Microsoft Corp.
based on allegations that the software company used its monopoly to
harm California consumers. Many similar suits have been filed
across the country since Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S.
District Court in Washington ruled that the company had violated
federal antitrust laws. In the California case, Superior Court
Judge Stuart R. Pollak said an unspecified number of California
consumers could be represented in one trial to determine whether
they were forced to pay unreasonably high prices for Microsoft
Windows, Word and other products. Microsoft said it was reviewing
the ruling. No trial date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   DRKOOP.COM CUTS STAFF BY A THIRD
</P>
<P>
   Drkoop.com, the struggling health information Web site, plans to
cut its work force by 33 percent, bringing the number of employees
down to 80. The cuts are being implemented by the group of
investors who last week provided the company with a much needed
$27.5 million cash infusion. Drkoop.com laid off 35 percent of its
staff in May. ``Drkoop's tremendous sales and marketing expenses,
coupled with the lack of success they've had in getting a
significant revenue stream from advertisers has led them to this
point,'' said Rachel Terrace, a health analyst with Jupiter
Communications. ``When the investors took over, they said they
wanted to start running drkoop like a business, and their first
order of business, to lay off employees, is not surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE RETAILERS CUTTING SOME COSTS
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a shift from costly television ads to less expensive
online advertising and marketing, per-customer acquisition costs
for online retailers declined to $40 in the second quarter of this
year, from a high of $71 in the fourth quarter of 1999, a new
survey says. The a survey of 66 North American online retailers,
conducted by Boston Consulting Group and Shop.org, a trade
association for Internet retailers, also found, however, that
acquisition costs were higher in the second quarter than the $35
per customer found in the third quarter of 1999, when the survey
was first conducted. Conversion rates _ the proportion of online
customer visits that turn into actual orders, as well as the rate
of repeat customers, improved slightly, according to the study.
``These key economic factors are all marginally up, but in
aggregate they'll have a significant impact for online retailers as
they try to achieve profitability,'' said James Vogtle, the
director of e-commerce research at Boston Consulting.
</P>
</TEXT>
