<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-BROADCOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL SUES BROADCOM, CLAIMING PATENT INFRINGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel filed a lawsuit on Wednesday accusing the
Broadcom Corp. of ``a carefully crafted plan'' to build its
business in cable and high-speed networking products by violating
Intel patents.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Delaware, stems
from an earlier Intel case alleging that Broadcom misappropriated
trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly every aspect of Broadcom's business _ cable products,
high-speed networking products, even semiconductor package
configurations _ violates one or more Intel patents,'' the new
complaint alleges. ``Broadcom focused on acquiring Intel technology
by inducing Intel employees to disclose trade secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcom shares dropped by 5 percent on Wednesday, closing at
$238.44, down $13.50, in Nasdaq trading. Intel shares closed at
$73.50, down 56 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Mulloy, an Intel spokesman, said, ``Typically we would
prefer to find some sort of amicable solution, but it is clear that
Broadcom does not have any respect for Intel's intellectual
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blanning, a spokesman for Broadcom, said the company had
heard of the suit only through press inquiries. ``We haven't had a
chance to review it,'' Blanning said. ``Intel made no effort to
contact us or resolve any issues they might have with us. We're
confident in the soundness of our business practices and will
defend ourselves vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to the complaint, Intel made many attempts to
contact Broadcom and secure the return of its trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Intel sued Broadcom in a California state court on March 8 in
the trade secrets case, and on March 10 that court entered a
temporary restraining order prohibiting Broadcom from ``disclosing,
using or acquiring'' Intel's trade secrets. Nine days later, the
court issued a preliminary injunction against Broadcom.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 25 order, the California court said there was probable
cause to believe that only days after the temporary restraining
order was issued, Broadcom's highest management had misappropriated
Intel trade secrets under the pretense of employment interviews.
The court said that ``Broadcom's approach to protecting Intel's
trade secrets was extremely cavalier,'' adding that it found
excuses offered in testimony by Broadcom's chief executive, Henry
T. Nicholas 3rd, ``unpersuasive and not credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcom, based in Irvine, Calif., is subject to a
court-appointed, independent monitor to ensure that it complies
with the court's order not to misappropriate Intel's trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said the patents involved covered a range of technologies,
including networking products, motion picture decoding used in
Broadcom cable products, and packages that Broadcom uses to sell
its chips. Intel, based in Santa Clara, Calif., seeks monetary
damages to compensate for Broadcom's past infringement and requests
the court to block sales of future infringing products.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bulk of Intel's charges, Mark Edelstone, an analyst
with Morgan Stanley, said that Broadcom had substantial
intellectual property of its own, and would inevitably countersue,
probably ultimately resulting in a cross-licensing agreement
between the two companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SARATOGA-MIGRANTS-     08-30 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SARATOGA-MIGRANTS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HORSES ARE SUPREME, MIGRANT WORKERS ARE THE LONG SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Chile)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ God may have given people dominion over
the animals, but such Biblical injunctions mean little for the
sleek, toned thoroughbreds that are stabled around the Saratoga
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Here horses are supreme. They are waited upon and cared for by
hundreds of grooms, hot walkers, exercise riders, veterinarians,
night watchmen, assistant trainers, trainers, jockeys and owners.
They fetch tens of thousands to millions of dollars at auctions,
and the race to the wire not only breaks or makes fortunes, but
imparts worth and identity to the lowest of stable hands. All of
life, it seems, is viewed through a totemic relationship to a
horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was given an autographed picture by the exercise rider who
handled Secretariat,'' said the Rev. Jim Watson, 51, the Southern
Baptist minister who serves as the race track chaplain in the
summer at Saratoga and each fall at Belmont, ``and this was 20
years after Secretariat won the Triple Crown. But in this world, he
is somebody because he once rode Secretariat.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two enclaves at the racetrack for horse enthusiasts.
In the world the public sees, the animals are unleashed at 40 miles
an hour in a thundering fury by diminutive jockeys dressed in
colorful silk jackets and polished black boots. Presiding over this
world are owners who often invest millions of dollars to finance
their passion and rarely turn a profit. It is the Saratoga of show,
glitter, excitement and sumptuous excess.
</P>
<P>
   The underside of the sport is the backstretch, where 1,200
migrant workers, who tend the stables and the mounts, live crowded
into dirty, spartan rooms and usually work seven days a week for a
couple of hundred dollars. The backstretch was dominated a few
decades ago by African-Americans from the South, but it now belongs
mostly to Puerto Ricans and Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   Those in this world rise as early as 4 a.m. They dart around the
highly strung 1,000-pound animals, cleaning out the stalls, filling
water buckets, pouring out feed, washing down the animals and
walking them to cool down after their daily 20 minutes of exercise.
Most work seven days a week. Few receive overtime. Nearly all have
been kicked, crushed or knocked over by the horses, with many
spending weeks recovering from broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we go outside the gates we are made to feel we do
not belong,'' said Maria Roma, 49, who has worked most of her life
as a groom, ``especially in Saratoga. You should see how they look
at us, like dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would not give up this life. I like the movement, the
excitement and the people. I was not made to sit at home in a
house. I don't like to be tied down.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, a portly preacher who speaks English and Spanish in a
slow Arkansas drawl, says he is called to minister in the
backstretch. He often rises early in the morning to drink coffee
along the rail of the practice track, chat and watch the exercise
riders, bent low or riding high in the stirrups, as they work the
horses.
</P>
<P>
   He broke horses in Hot Springs, Ark., as a young man, and has a
scar running from his left armpit to his hip where he was tossed
into a barbed wire fence. He has spent most of his life at tracks,
hanging around Oakland Park in Arkansas as a boy, and has worked
for 14 years as a chaplain at Belmont, Aqueduct and Saratoga, hired
by Race Track Chaplains of America.
</P>
<P>
   While he loves the animals and says he adores the misfits and
oddballs that make up the racing scene, he also sees it as
destructive to many who toil in its lower rungs. His weekly service
and daily devotionals with the jockeys rarely attract more than a
dozen congregants. But he slogs on, hoping to relieve what he says
is widespread fatalism and despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not like the emphasis that makes an animal more important
than a human being,'' he said. ``It affects the way the people on
the backstretch think of themselves. It is not so much that they
are told they are not important, but that they are constantly told
how important is the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a tremendous impact on self-esteem. If a horse limps
out of a stall, everyone gets excited and upset. If a groom limps,
no one cares as long as he can make it around the shed row.''
</P>
<P>
   The migrant workers move from track to track. They may spend the
summer in Saratoga, the fall at Belmont or Aqueduct and the winter
in Florida. Most have few possessions, little job security and no
roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life at the track teaches you to live day by day,'' Watson
said one morning, as half a dozen horses were pounding down the
dirt strip. ``You learn not to count on tomorrow. I would say that
95 percent of those in the backstretch do not know when they will
leave Saratoga for New York. If they are lucky the trainer will
tell them the night before, if they are not they will learn about
it the morning of departure. And many do not even know if they will
go from here to Belmont or Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the top horse in the country and he can take one
misstep out there and suddenly after all that work you have
nothing,'' he said. ``The problem with living like this is that it
makes people fatalistic. They believe they do not have control.
They merely react to what happens. There is a very fine line
between learning to live day by day and giving up on life and
letting things happen. And this fatalism shows itself in alcohol
abuse and drug use.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dusk one evening this week, after the races had ended and
the horses been put into their stalls for the night, Hispanic
laborers, some of whom admitted they were in the country illegally,
crowded around a pavilion where two women cooked rice, beans,
tortillas and hunks of beef. The women dished out the food on thin
aluminum plates and stuffed crumbled $5 bills from the workers into
their aprons. Those eating the food clutched bottles of Budweiser
with soiled fingers.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of children and wives back home and the struggles to
wire enough of their earnings to support them. They spat out the
names of jockeys, who can earn hundreds of thousands of dollars a
year, but bring them only a box of donuts the morning after winning
huge purses. They cursed trainers who they said pushed them too
hard.
</P>
<P>
   When they talked of their ambitions, all stayed within the
narrow hierarchy of the track. They said they dreamed of moving
from hot walker to groom to exercise rider to trainer, as if this
was the only progress in life worth contemplating. All said they
loved horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father spent 11 years as a groom here,'' said Carlos
Sepulvera, 21, a groom from Chile, his long hair cascading out of a
baseball cap. ``Now he is an assistant trainer in Chile. I am
waiting to go back and train my own horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Sepulvera, who works seven days a week and sleeps on
the floor of a room with four other men, survives on $200 a week
and waits.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A hush fell over the stable workers as Watson began his weekly
open-air service. The minister laid out Bibles, adorned with
pictures of jockeys riding their mounts in the winner's circle, on
folding chairs. The covers of the books said, ``A Guidebook for
Running the Race of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight people, including Pat Day, 46, who earned over a million
dollars this year, making him the leading jockey in the country,
sat in the chairs for the service. Day, with other jockeys, had
also attended a devotional service with Watson shortly before the
day's race.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The clang of a bicycle bell announced the arrival of Eduardo
Fontanel, 52, who is known as El Gato, the cat, because of the
meowing sounds he makes while he speaks. He had collected dozens of
empty beer bottles and strapped them in plastic bags to his
ornately decorated bike, which he said he bought for $20 three
years ago and took with him from track to track. He wore beads in
the form of a Puerto Rican flag around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make $50 a day returning these bottles,'' he said, taking a
swig from a beer bottle he had placed in a wire holder on his
handlebars. ``Every day I have a huge new crop.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to pray, the worshippers bent their heads.
They talked of the sick, the injured and the departed, and then the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``God grant us safety,'' said Bill Rutherford, 39, a night
watchman, ``and protect the horses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``There is no protection for us,'' said Tatiana Martinez, 16, a
hot walker, who sat a few feet away. ``No woman walks around the
backstretch in the dark, not with all the people who get crazy
every night from drink.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
