<SLUG> BC-NIXON-DRUG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO NIXON AIDES DENY HE MEDICATED HIMSELF IN THE WHITE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs lede to shorten and clarify description of Dilantin;
Subs 7th graf, Dreyfus said ..., to add 7 grafs bgng, Dilantin,
introduced ..., of background on the drug, expert comment; pickup
penultimate graf, Taylor produced ...) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two aides to President Richard M. Nixon said
Wednesday that they doubted he ever took the drug Dilantin, an
anti-seizure medication, despite a new book that says he did.
</P>
<P>
   The aides, John H. Taylor, the director of the Nixon Library in
Yorba Linda, Calif., who knew Nixon from the mid-1980s until the
former president's death in 1994, and Steve Bull, who was Nixon's
personal aide from mid-1969 until late 1974, said they were
skeptical of assertions in the book that Nixon medicated himself
with Dilantin given to him by Jack Dreyfus, the founder of the
Dreyfus Fund and an avid promoter of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus said last week that an account in the book, ``The
Arrogance of Power: The Secret World of Richard Nixon,'' that he
gave Dilantin to Nixon in 1968 was correct. Dreyfus said he gave
Nixon a bottle of 1,000 capsules of 100 milligrams each ``when his
mood wasn't too good,'' and later gave him another bottle of 1,000
capsules.
</P>
<P>
   The book written by Anthony Summers and published by Viking
paints an unfavorable portrait of Nixon politically and personally.
Its assertion that he freely medicated himself while coping with
the burdens of the White House is one of several contentions that
have been disputed by Nixon's relatives and associates. Taylor and
Bull volunteered their views in reaction to reports about the book.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the Richard Nixon he knew ``went to traditional
doctors when he was sick and always did what they said.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Dilantin, Bull, who is now director of government
relations for the U.S. Olympic Committee, said, ``I never saw any
evidence that he used any medication of that kind. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus has advocated the drug as being effective in dealing
with anxiety, anger, depression and other troubling conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Dilantin, introduced in the 1930s, is routinely prescribed by
neurologists to prevent seizures caused by epilepsy or other
conditions, but is rarely used to treat mental disorders. However,
other, newer anti-seizure drugs _ including Tegritol and Depakote _
are used in the treatment of depression and some other psychiatric
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frederick Jacobsen, a psychopharmacologist at George
Washington University, said Dilantin was not widely used because it
had not proved very effective as a treatment for mental disorders,
and had more side effects than newer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Common side effects of Dilantin, which is chemically related to
barbiturates but does not share their addictive properties, can
include sedation, mental confusion or fuzziness, physical
unsteadiness and slurred speech. According to the Physician's Desk
Reference, such side effects occur primarily when patients take too
much Dilantin. But Jacobsen said confusion can also occur ``with
doses within the therapeutic range.''
</P>
<P>
   With long-term use Dilantin can also cause an overgrowth of the
gums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the majority of psychiatrists do not find much benefit
for Dilantin,'' Jacobsen said. ``It's not in the standard
repertoire of the general psychopharmacologist.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen said that to describe Dilantin as a ``mind-altering
drug'' was not entirely accurate. ``It would be more accurate to
characterize it as a `brain-altering drug,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Self-medicating with Dilantin, as the book contends Nixon did,
would not be a good idea, Jacobsen added. ``Self-medication in
general is not a good idea, and certainly one runs the risk of
toxicity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor produced a summary of White House records from April 1969
through mid-1973 recalling numerous attempts by Dreyfus to gain
government backing for Dilantin through Nixon. The records state
that Nixon met with Dreyfus now and then socially, but they portray
the president as reluctant to get into lengthy discussions about
Dilantin.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Nixon might have accepted Dilantin from Dreyfus so
as not to hurt his feelings, but that if he did he threw it out
rather than taking it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
