<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-TIRES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EXPANDS SCOPE OF INQUIRY ON DEFECTIVE FIRESTONE TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs to recast throughout, updates background, details and
quotes.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal regulators trying to determine how much the
Ford Motor Co. knew about defective tires used on its Explorers
expanded their investigation Wednesday by demanding that the
company provide detailed information on any tire problems in 16
countries outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure was made public by regulators in a letter sent on
Tuesday to Ford from officials at the National Highway
Transportation Safety Administration. Both the agency and the
automaker have come under increasing political pressure,
particularly as it has become clear that for nearly two years Ford
received complaints from overseas about possible problems with
Firestone tires on its Explorers but did not recall them until this
month. U.S. regulators say that they have received more than 750
complaints about the tires involving at least 62 deaths. Almost all
of the deaths occurred in sport utility vehicles, mostly Explorers,
that rolled over.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was a clear attempt by the regulators to determine
who knew what, and when. Ford executives have said that they
investigated complaints in Venezuela and in Saudi Arabia about tire
problems and challenged the conclusions of Bridgestone/Firestone
Inc., the American unit of Bridgestone of Japan, that the tires
were not defective. But Ford executives have also said that they
did not understand the true magnitude of the problems until earlier
this month after discussions with Firestone and that they then
acted quickly to begin the process of replacing 6.5 million tires.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say they have limited ability to monitor
recalls and defects of cars sold abroad, although some critics like
Joan Claybrook, a former top official at the National Highway
Transportation Safety Administration, say the agency has the
authority under a 1966 law to monitor recalls and defects abroad
but refuses to exercise it.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is exploring whether to expand the authority of the
regulators and impose new rules on automakers to report problems
discovered outside the United States. This week, Ford and Firestone
described a series of disagreements about the tires after
complaints in 1998 in Venezuela and last year in Saudi Arabia. Ford
had concluded the tires were defective, while Firestone insisted
they were not.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a government agency in Venezuela is expected to
issue a report criticizing both Ford and Firestone for the way that
they handled tire problems there. Ford had recalled vehicles with
the tires in Venezuela in May and had earlier replaced tires on 160
Explorers in Thailand in March and April.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies and American regulators are expected to face
intensive questioning next week when congressional hearings begin
over the tire recall. The companies are obliged to report defects
in the United States to regulators, but regulators have said the
companies do not face reporting obligations in many circumstances
when the problems are noticed in cars abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers have certain legal obligations to report defect
problems and NHTSA has some obligations to Congress,'' said Ken
Johnson, a spokesman for Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who heads one of
the House committees investigating the tire recall. ``Someone
dropped the ball, and we're trying to find out who. But we're
really trying to figure out some broader issues. Did Firestone
break the law or is the law broken? We're going to have to take a
hard look at the law to make sure it's strong enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Those scheduled to testify next week at the proceedings before
two House committees include Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater, other transportation regulators, executives from the two
companies and safety experts. Congressional aides say they may also
take testimony from owners of Explorers involved in traffic
accidents that they think were caused by defective tires.
</P>
<P>
   There were further negotiations Wednesday between lawmakers and
Ford over the possible appearance at the hearings of Jacques A.
Nasser, the chief executive of Ford, who has refused to testify.
The company announced Wednesday that it would send Helen
Petrauskas, vice president for environmental and safety
engineering, and Tom Baughman, an engineering director, to testify.
By contrast, Bridgestone/Firestone agreed to send Masatoshi Ono,
its chief executive, to the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the Commerce Committee said Wednesday that it
would postpone the beginning of its hearings by a week until
mid-September. Congressional aides said the hearings were delayed
to give the committee's chairman, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., more
time to recuperate from recent surgery for skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials said that the Senate hearing could be
broader than the House proceeding and that it might also examine a
court decision on Tuesday that said Ford had knowingly installed
defective ignition mechanisms in nearly 2 million vehicles produced
from 1983 to 1995. Ford has disputed those findings.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Highway Transportation Safety
Administration declined to comment about the judge's decision
Wednesday. Nearly two years ago, the agency concluded that Ford had
not been forthcoming about ignition problems but decided to take no
action against the company. In a letter sent at the time to Ford
and a plaintiff's lawyer who had raised complaints that the company
was deceptive, the transportation agency's chief counsel decided
not to penalize Ford because the company's failure to be
forthcoming had occurred in the 1980s and the potential penalties
would amount only to a maximum of $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of both Ford and Bridgestone have slumped since the
tire recall was announced. Shares of Ford have fallen 12 percent,
to $26, while the American depository receipts of Bridgestone have
fallen 22 percent, to $144.50. In Japan, shares of Bridgestone have
declined 34.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
