<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY IN TEXAS CASE IS OVERTURNED
</HEADLINE>
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A federal judge has overturned the death sentence of a
Texas man convicted of killing a 16-year-old boy, citing the
``dismal'' performance of the convicted man's lawyer during his
trial as well as the prosecution's failure to disclose to jurors
that an important witness was a paid informer.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Folsom of U.S. District Court in Texarkana, Texas,
ruling on a motion filed four years ago, left intact the conviction
of Delma Banks Jr. for the April 1980 murder of Richard Wayne
Whitehead. Prosecutors say Banks shot Whitehead in Nash, Texas, and
then stole his car to drive to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But Folsom ordered the state either to reduce Banks' sentence or
to order a new sentencing trial within 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling endorsed the findings of a federal magistrate,
Caroline Malone, who in May cited the poor job done by Banks'
lawyer and the prosecution's failure to disclose that one of its
witnesses, Robert Farr, was a paid informant.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom's ruling was issued on Aug. 18 but was first reported on
Wednesday in The Texarkana Gazette. He cited the magistrate's
finding of ``a reasonable probability that but for the errors and
omissions of trial counsel at the punishment phase, combined with
the state's failure to disclose Farr as a paid informant, the
outcome of Banks' punishment phase would have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   The magistrate also stated that ``the state's failure to
disclose Farr's informant status, coupled with trial counsel's
dismal performance during the punishment phase, undermined the
reliability of the jury's verdict regarding punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifton L. Holmes, a Longview, Texas., defense lawyer who is one
of Banks' appellate lawyers, said Banks' trial lawyer did ``very
little preparation in terms of preparing for the punishment trial
and introducing those kinds of things that all courts recognize as
mitigating factors, such as the condition of his upbringing and the
like.''
</P>
<P>
   If Banks were to be retried to determine whether he is to be
executed by lethal injection, he would stand a good chance of
receiving only prison time, Holmes said. He contended that evidence
collected since the trial casts doubt on the conviction, and he
said that Banks has not been a dangerous or violent inmate in his
20 years on death row, making it difficult for prosecutors to argue
that he is a danger to society.
</P>
<P>
   If Banks is not sentenced to death, he could be eligible for
parole, based on the time he has already spent in prison, the Bowie
County district attorney, Bobby Lockhart, told the Texarkana
Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, who did not return a telephone call seeking comment,
told the newspaper that ``we feel like he'd be eligible for parole
right now.'' He said his office plans to appeal Folsom's ruling to
the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, and that he would leave the
decision of whether to retry Banks to Whitehead's family and to one
of his assistant prosecutors. ``I can't imagine any reason why we
wouldn't retry it,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The competency of lawyers who represents indigent defendants in
capital cases in Texas has become a political issue this year.
George W. Bush, the governor of Texas and the Republican
presidential nominee, is a strong supporter of the fairness of the
state's death penalty system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet critics have attacked the system, arguing that many
defendants receive inadequate counsel, including at least three
widely publicized cases of lawyers who have slept through parts of
the proceedings. The state appeals court has reversed only eight
death penalty cases in the last five years, while affirming the
convictions and death sentences in 256 cases, according to court
statistics. This is the lowest reversal rate in capital cases in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, which ranks behind Texas with the nation's
third-highest death row population, has a 50 percent reversal rate.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom's ruling was on a writ of habeas corpus, a motion that
seeks court review of an imprisonment. Such petitions are common in
death-penalty cases, but they are not granted very often. However,
Maurie Levin, a lawyer at the Texas Defender Service, in Austin,
which represents indigent death-row inmates, said federal judges in
Texas have granted some form of habeas relief in at least two other
death penalty cases just this year.
</P>
<P>
   The habeas rulings, Levin said, ``underscore and exemplify the
errors in the system and the need for the kind of advocacy'' during
the appeals process that revealed errors at trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
