<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-GOVS-NYT     08-30 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GOVS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS HOPE TO BEGIN RETAKING GOVERNORSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in Mississippi's history, state lawmakers
were called on early this year to choose the next governor. No
candidate had reached the 50 percent plus one required to win the
popular vote, and so the election went to the House of
Representatives, where the outcome was far more certain.
Overwhelmingly Democratic, the House made Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove
the winner over his Republican opponent, Mike Parker, a former
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   It is upon such thin reeds that Democrats are building their
hopes of making even a dent this fall in the Republican Party's
30-18 advantage in governorships. (Maine has an independent as
governor, Angus King, and Minnesota has Jesse Ventura, now with the
Minnesota Independence Party.)
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 states are holding elections for governor in November.
By all accounts most of the races are too close to call, but the
biggest swing that either party realistically envisions is two or
three seats. The real test of the parties' struggle for the
nation's statehouses is not likely to come until the off-year
elections of 2002, with governors' races in 36 states.
</P>
<P>
   It was the elections in those states in 1994 that dug the hole
from which the Democrats are now trying to emerge. Two years into
President Clinton's first term, a restless electorate not only
delivered control of both houses of Congress to Republicans for the
first time in 40 years but also turned the Democrats' 30-18
advantage in governorships into a 30-19 lead for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and again in 1998, the Republicans extended their
advantage by one, to give them 32 governors, a 50-year high for the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Republicans holding slimmer margins in Congress and
Vice President Al Gore edging ahead of Gov. George W. Bush in some
national polls, Democrats say the time is right for them to reclaim
some of the executive offices they have lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were making book, I'd say we will pick up one to three
seats this year and will very likely pick up two,'' said Gov. Paul
Patton of Kentucky, chairman of the Democratic Governors'
Association. ``Then I'd expect to pick up another one next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are defending governorships this fall in Delaware,
Indiana, Missouri, New Hampshire, North Carolina, Vermont and
Washington. Republicans are defending in Montana, North Dakota,
Utah and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, only New Jersey and Virginia will have races for
governor, and in both the office is now held by Republicans barred
from seeking re-election. Democrats view their chances as
especially strong in New Jersey, where James McGreevey, who barely
lost to Gov. Christie Whitman in 1997, has time to generate money
and support while Republicans fight over which of three candidates
will oppose him.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials brush off any projections of significant
Democratic gains, contending that more Republicans are elected as
governor these days because voters prefer them. Republicans also
say they are encouraged because the four Democratic governors who
this year are seeking another term _ Frank O'Bannon in Indiana,
Jeanne Shaheen in New Hampshire, Howard Dean in Vermont and Gary
Locke in Washington _ are all facing Republican opposition that is
stronger than first expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to just say we're better than them,'' said Clinton
Key, executive director of the Republican Governors' Association.
``Our guys get it. We have a group of truly talented people who
know how to get elected and get things accomplished. Our
attractiveness is as high as it's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   With only a relative handful of elections this year, it is
difficult to discern an overriding theme. Issues like education and
taxes have dominated the political discourse among most candidates,
but the particular needs and nature of each of the states tend to
keep them from being meaningfully linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gubernatorial candidates are going to be evaluated on their
own merits more so than how some candidate performs in a
neighboring state,'' said Thomas Carsey, associate professor of
political science at Florida State University and author of a new
book, ``Campaign Dynamics: The Race for Governor.''
</P>
<P>
   One variable, particularly in the close races, is the effect of
the presidential election. A strong Democratic turnout for Gore in
West Virginia, where Rep. Bob Wise, a nine-term Democrat, is
challenging Gov. Cecil Underwood, could help Wise in one of the six
races for governor rated a tossup by The Cook Political Report. The
other tossup states, where presidential fortunes could play a role,
are Delaware, Missouri, Montana, North Carolina and North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a strong showing in Indiana by O'Bannon, who
is leading his Republican challenger, Rep. David McIntosh, in
recent polls, could help Gore win a state that has voted for only
two Democratic presidential nominees in 100 years, Franklin D.
Roosevelt and Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
