<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORE RETAINS MOMENTUM IN POLLS
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is still enjoying a post-convention
bounce in presidential preference polls. Gore has taken a 15-point
lead over Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in Maryland, an 8-point lead
in Florida, a 5-point lead in Illinois and has closed to within 4
points in New Hampshire. In Maryland, according to a
Gonzales-Arscott poll of 649 registered voters taken Wednesday
through Sunday, Gore leads 51 percent to 36 percent, while in
Florida, according to a Rasmussen Research poll of 439 voters
conducted Saturday and Sunday, he leads 48 percent to 40 percent.
In Illinois, a Mason-Dixon poll of 629 voters taken Thursday
through Sunday showed Gore ahead of Bush 46 percent to 41 percent,
while in a New Hampshire poll, covering 540 registered voters and
conducted Thursday through Saturday, Bush retained a lead of 48
percent to 44 percent. The margin of sampling error for the new
Florida poll was plus or minus 5 percentage points. In the three
other polls it was plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   NADER WINS UNION BACKING
</P>
<P>
   The news is good and bad this week for Ralph Nader, the Green
Party's presidential candidate. On Wednesday in Erie, Pa., Nader
won the endorsement of the 35,000-member United Electrical, Radio
and Machine Workers of America, after telling the union's
convention that while the Democratic Party might be labor's
traditional political partner in presidential races, it always
promised more than it delivered. He promised to deliver. The union
seldom endorses presidential candidates. But there was bad
political news for Nader on Tuesday in South Dakota, where he had
missed the June 20 filing deadline for getting on the fall ballot
and had been trying to persuade a judge that he should be listed
anyway. The judge turned him down. Also, in Wyoming on Tuesday,
state election officials said that Nader would not be on the fall
ballot there because he fell short of the 3,584 signatures needed
to qualify. One reason he fell short was that a volunteer walked
off with a petition containing 650 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY FEUD UNRESOLVED
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Lynchburg, Va., ruled Wednesday that he did
not have jurisdiction to decide the bitter feud over who is the
Reform Party's presidential nominee. Allies of one candidate, Pat
Buchanan, sought an order barring a competing faction from
operating under the party's name. But Judge Norman K. Moon of U.S.
District Court, who has heard other Reform Party disputes, said he
lacked jurisdiction in this instance because the power struggle did
not raise any constitutional issue. At the party's convention in
Long Beach, Calif., earlier this month, delegates opposed to
Buchanan declared his nomination illegal and walked out, asserting
that he had packed the convention with hard-right followers who
were not qualified delegates. The rump group then held its own
convention across the street and nominated John Hagelin, a
physicist from Iowa. Both sides are seeking $12.6 million in
Federal Election Commission money and competing to get sole billing
on state ballots. Buchanan officials said they would next try a
state court.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON STATE'S BATTLE OF THE ADS
</P>
<P>
   With just three weeks to go before the Democratic primary in
Washington state, Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn has unveiled
her television advertising campaign for the U.S. Senate nomination.
Senn accuses her better-financed opponent, former Rep. Maria
Cantwell, of dodging debates and ``hiding in a TV'' via her own
commercials. Cantwell, who became a millionaire several times over
as an Internet executive after being turned out of office in the
1994 Republican takeover of Congress, has been showing
advertisements throughout the summer, pointing out her business
experience and other credentials and all but ignoring Senn. Some
polls have shown Cantwell well in front, but Senn says those polls
demonstrated only name recognition, not popular support. The winner
of the Sept. 19 primary will face the Republican incumbent, Sen.
Slade Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LIEBERMAN, HEBREW-STYLE
</P>
<P>
   It was bound to happen. On Tuesday, at a late night rally in
downtown Portland, Ore., Vice President Al Gore and his running
mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman (did we mention that he's Jewish?),
were greeted by supporters waving placards that spelled out
Gore-Lieberman in Hebrew letters. It should be noted, however, that
the signs said ``Gore-Lieberman 2000,'' not Gore-Lieberman 5761,
the date of the coming election in the Hebrew calendar.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Toledo, Ohio, and Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   DICK CHENEY _ Fort Lauderdale and West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE and JOSEPH LIEBERMAN _ Seattle
</P>
<P>
   RALPH NADER _ New York
</P>
</TEXT>
