<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: AMERICAN'S PLEA SCHEDULED
</P>
<P>
   A day after Edmond Pope's wife and his congressman made a public
appeal for better medical treatment for the former naval
intelligence officer awaiting trial in Moscow on espionage charges,
a Moscow court scheduled a hearing to reconsider Pope's plea for
conditional release. The Moscow City Court, responding swiftly to a
new petition, announced it will hear an appeal on Sept. 11 from
Pope's lawyer, Pavel Astakhov, whose earlier filings were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA: TRIBUNAL WITNESS SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   A Croatian witness in war crimes trials who testified nearly two
years ago was slain in a bomb blast near his home in Zagreb in what
was seen as a warning to others who might testify to the
International Criminal Tribunal on the Former Yugoslavia about
possible Croatian war crimes in Bosnia. Tribunal officials said
Milan Levar was given government protection in April 1998, after he
testified for the third and last time, and that they had had no
contact with him since.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: HUME GIVES UP A SEAT
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, the leader of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party and a principal architect of the Ulster peace pact,
said he was giving up his seat in the new Northern Ireland
Assembly, explaining that ``for health reasons, I have decided it
is necessary to cut my workload.'' Hume, 63, will keep his party
post and his seats in the British Parliament and the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TRIMBLE SPEAKS OUT
</P>
<P>
   The British province's most powerful Protestant politician, the
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, condemned warring Protestant
paramilitary groups whose turf war led to the firebombing of more
than 25 homes in two towns and has resulted in the deaths of three
men and the shooting of an 11-year-old girl in the past 10 days.
Police say the violence is a struggle for control of the drug
trade.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: STRIKE HITS TOURISTS
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of vacationing British tourists were stranded at ferry
terminals on both sides of the English Channel as French fishermen
blockaded piers to protest rising fuel prices. Also on the rise
were neighborly irritations. One Englishman stuck in Calais, David
Langford, 28, of King's Lynn, Norfolk, said, ``I've just traveled
from Thailand and I have come through 11 countries, and it is
always France that causes the trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: COST OF WAR
</P>
<P>
   The new minister of finance disclosed to Parliament that the
country's two-year-long involvement in Congo's civil war has cost
about $200 million, nearly three times more than previously
disclosed. Even as its own economy has crumbled over the last two
years, straining to pay for fuel and electricity imports, Zimbabwe
has had thousands of troops stationed in Congo battling rebels
backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: PLEA ON RACISM
</P>
<P>
   Opening a national conference on racism, President Thabo Mbeki
urged black and white South Africans to fight the scourge that
continues to afflict the nation six years after the end of
apartheid. Mbeki acknowledged that some whites may consider the
discussion of racism painful and divisive. But he said the struggle
will fail unless people work together.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: ELECTION REPORT
</P>
<P>
   In its final report on Mozambique's elections, the Carter Center
found that the credibility of the vote was marred by technical
problems and a lack of transparency in the final count. But the
Center officials, who observed the elections on Dec. 3, 4 and 5,
said the problems did not affect the result. President Joaquim
Chissano was re-elected and his party retained control.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   WEST TIMOR: U.N. RESUMES AID The United Nations has resumed aid
to East Timor refugees in camps in West Timor after Indonesia
arrested two suspects in the beating of three aid workers on Aug.
23. Authorities in West Timor, which shares an island with East
Timor and is moving to independence under U.N. administration, also
opened an inquiry into violence against aid workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
