<SLUG> BC-E-TAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    GOVERNOR TO DECIDE FATE OF CALIFORNIA E-TAX BILL
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Retailers with a brick-and-mortar presence in the
state will be required to pay sales tax on their Web site sales to
Californians if Gov. Gray Davis signs a just-approved e-commerce
bill into law.
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of the E-Commerce Sales Tax Fairness Bill, which
was approved by the Senate late Tuesday, is uncertain at best.
Davis has not decided whether to sign it but is generally opposed
to Internet taxation, said spokesman Roger Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   He has until Sept. 30 to sign or veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Internet sales taxation is a national issue, and the U.S.
Supreme Court has ruled remote Internet businesses can't be taxed
by a state if they have no physical presence there.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers who have facilities in California voluntarily pay
sales tax on their Web site sales, even if their dot.com
subsidiaries are located in another state.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including a couple of large bookstore chains, don't
collect the tax, said Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco,
who cosponsored the bill with Assemblywoman Dion Aroner,
D-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate floor analysis estimates the state is losing $14.4
million annually in these uncollected sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Migden said the bill's purpose was to clarify California sales
tax law. She argued that if a store is located in California, it
must collect sales tax and forming an Internet-based subsidiary
that sells essentially the same products doesn't relieve the store
of its obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have said the bill is unconstitutional and imposes a
new tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet sales tax issue has parallels in any retail
segment, but independent booksellers pushed for the California
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The mega-booksellers who have stores in California but don't
collect sales taxes on online sales to Californians put
independents at a competitive disadvantage, and they take needed
tax revenue away from the communities they do business in, said Hut
Landon, owner of Landon Books in Mill Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just saying enforce the law across the board,'' Landon
said.
</P>
<P>
   The independent booksellers don't know what the governor will
do, but they hope he will support local businesses and communities,
Landon said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the issue, said Jeffrey Solsby, spokesman for U.S.
Rep. James Rogan, R-Pasadena. The state Legislature is more
interested in collecting new taxes to fund its spending than
protecting small businesses that are the lifeblood of the country,
Solsby said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan is an ardent supporter of the Internet tax moratorium,
Solsby said. The Internet Tax Freedom Act Internet businesses,
including the giant online bookseller Amazon.com, gives a pass on
new or discriminatory taxes until October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Solsby predicted the technology and e-commerce lobbyists would
put pressure on Davis to veto the bill and might force another
split with the statehouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
