<SLUG> BC-THQ-GAMER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAME COMPANY PAYS FOR PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. _ When Jim Boone was growing up, he and his
fellow video game addicts figured you gotta be some kind of genius
to have created titles like Space Invaders and Tempest.
</P>
<P>
   Never did they think they could crack that world.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old thinks upon this as he puts the finishing
touches on Summoner, a swords and sorcery game being launched with
Sony's PlayStation 2 on Oct. 26. He is senior producer at THQ, the
video game company that has brought you titles like WWF
Wrestlemania 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Boone took a few community college courses _ he meant to become
a firefighter _ but he was schooled by Atari, ColecoVision and
IntelliVision. Now he looks back and laughs at his serendipitous
rise. His parents look back and laugh too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, You play so many video games. It's never going to
help you out getting a job,'' said Boone, a senior producer.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem like a case of arrested development if the job
didn't pay so well. Management salaries range anywhere from $75,000
to $150,000 in the industry and designers make royalties in the
same manner as recording artists.
</P>
<P>
   That and the incredibly high stakes of the business are the
reminders that there's a job behind the fun. Video games are an
industry in which companies rise and fall daily based on things
like market share and share price.
</P>
<P>
   The journey to Boone's office through the development section of
THQ headquarters is like a trip through a sci-fi convention. The
cubicles, draped in all manner of toys and video game controllers,
resemble vendor booths and they're all populated by
twenty-somethings wearing baggy cargo pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as this starts feeling like a job, people will
leave,'' said Boone's boss, Vice President of Product Development
Michael Rubinelli.
</P>
<P>
   So Rubinelli wasn't too surprised to walk down the hall at 12:30
a.m. Wednesday and find Boone still hard at work reviewing
Summoner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no shoes on, his feet up on the desk,'' said Rubinelli.
</P>
<P>
   And that was OK even at a company Boone said is considered
somewhat conservative by video game industry standards. Employees
(begin italics) must (end italics) wear long pants.
</P>
<P>
   The culture is why Boone doesn't mind the late hours and why
stress doesn't register. Play and work are one to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we're still making video games,'' he said. ``We're
not making defense systems or something like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-E-TAX-LADN     08-30 0505
