<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-VEEP-1STLD-W     08-30 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-VEEP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING MATES ARE A CONTRAST IN STYLE AS THEY CAMPAIGN SOLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Adds 5 grafs at end with color from K.C. event.) 
 (See also CHENEY) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT24, 25, 32 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday in a steamy union hall in Chicago, some 1,300 rowdy
Democrats roared the now-ritualistic chant ``Go, Joe, go!'' as
Mayor Richard M. Daley and the other big wheels of the Chicago
Democratic machine escorted Sen. Joseph Lieberman to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Handing his rumpled jacket to an aide, Lieberman began a folksy
stump speech that was interrupted by applause, laughter and more
chanting. When he stepped off the stage to shake hands, people
surged forward. Men clapped him on the back. Women leaned in with
kisses and whispered words of encouragement in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, 400 miles away in Kansas City, Mo., fewer than
75 people waited for Dick Cheney, the Republican nominee for vice
president, to speak at the headquarters of Fellowship of Christian
Athletes. Most of those in the audience were employees of the
organization. They sat in polite silence. There were no campaign
signs. Cheney and his wife, Lynne, entered the hall unannounced;
for a painful minute, there was no response until a few people up
front realized they ought to clap.
</P>
<P>
   A few introductory speakers talked about the importance of faith
and abstinence, and Mike Sweeney, first baseman for the Kansas City
Royals, gave Cheney a jersey. Another moment of awkward silence
followed before Cheney began a brief, low-key speech about teaching
children the importance of character. ``It's about what you do when
nobody is looking.'' Then he sat back down to brief, low-key
applause.
</P>
<P>
   With Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
entering a crucial phase of their race for the White House, their
running mates are waging starkly different campaigns as they strike
out on their own for the first time since each party's national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who has confronted questions about his health, his
voting record in Congress and his multimillion-dollar retirement
package from a major oil services corporation, has largely kept a
low profile, staging small events, sticking to a familiar speech
script and generally staying clear of reporters from national news
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has been more active, drawing far larger crowds and
attracting _ indeed courting _ more media coverage. On Monday in
Chicago, his motorcade included two vans filled with reporters,
most from national news organizations, who are flying with him on
his campaign airplane. Cheney's campaign has no accommodations for
a traveling press corps at this time. National reporters follow his
campaign by taking commercial flights and taxicabs to his events.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Cheney finally took questions from the national
press corps on the last day of a three-day trip through California
and Oregon, he found only three journalists facing him. ``Why do I
need a press secretary if I've only got three?'' he said jokingly
to his press secretary, Dirk Vande Beek.
</P>
<P>
   After his event on Tuesday, Cheney paused briefly to take
questions from reporters. When one tried to ask a follow-up
question, Cheney cut her off, saying, ``You had your question.''
</P>
<P>
   After four questions, Vande Beek ended the interview. Trying for
a fifth question, a reporter asked Cheney how he planned to
celebrate his 36th wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Cheney said, ``is a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   He did answer one question about the differences between his
campaign style and Lieberman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of in keeping with my quiet, low-key demeanor,''
Cheney said. ``I come from the West. A man of few words. Grew up in
the House of Representatives where we are limited to five minutes
in our speeches. Joe's from Connecticut. He comes from the Senate,
where they make a lot longer speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   But he firmly rejected what has become conventional political
wisdom among even some Republicans _ that while Lieberman is
helping Gore, Cheney is not yet doing the same for Bush, whose
standing in the polls has sagged since his selection of Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to respond favorably to my being on the ticket,''
Cheney said, adding, ``I don't want to take personal credit or
blame for what happens in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Cheney's taste for the low profile sometimes fails to
grab headlines or move polls, Lieberman's high-profile appearances
have risks of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman demonstrated this on Sunday in Detroit, when his
assertion that religion is the basis of morality drew a strong
rebuke from the Anti-Defamation League, atheists and groups that
advocate a strict separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier high-profile appearance before the black caucus of
the Democratic National Committee served to highlight Lieberman's
past differences with black leaders about affirmative action and
school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's restrained style, meanwhile, reinforces what many
consider to be his strongest contribution to Bush: his reputation
as a senior statesman with the depth of experience to offset Bush's
relative lack of exposure to military issues, foreign affairs and
the ways of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's understatement has also added a quiet potency to his
criticisms of Gore and President Clinton, not to mention his calls
for a restoration of honor in the Oval Office, a line that drew
roars of approval from party stalwarts at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Only Wednesday, in a campaign event in Atlanta, Cheney drew on
his experience as secretary of defense in the Bush administration
to accuse Clinton and Gore of presiding over a military that is
``overused and under-resourced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1990,'' he said, ``America has pursued a strategy that
would allow us to fight two wars simultaneously, and win both
decisively, with the lowest possible risk to our troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet just last fall, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
testified that the risk involved in two wars has increased, and
would now be `moderate' risk in the first, and `high' risk in the
second. And how would that risk be measured? Ultimately, it's
measured in the lives of our troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has also chosen to adopt an understated tone when
laying into Bush and Cheney. He usually sets up his sharpest
criticisms by first declaring that both men are ``decent and
honorable.'' And after he delivers a zinger, he tends to soften the
blow by smiling and raising his eyebrows, as if to ask, ``Wasn't
that a good one?''
</P>
<P>
   But on the stump, Lieberman differs most from Cheney in his
eagerness to place his life story at the center of his political
message. He never fails to remind audiences that he is the son of a
bakery truck driver, that his wife's parents escaped the death
camps in Germany, and the communists in Czechoslovakia, that he was
the first person in his family to graduate from college, that he
went to Mississippi in 1963 to fight for voting rights for black
people.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly every stop he speaks of his religion, and about how
his status as the first Jew on a presidential ticket means that
``doors of opportunity'' have opened for all who have faced
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is not nearly so effusive. After he addressed a chapter
of the Future Farmers of America at Crater High School in Medford,
Ore., a student asked him what most politicians would consider the
easiest of softballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question for you is, who are you?'' the boy asked. ``What
do you like to do on the weekends? What are your hobbies, and where
do you like to travel?''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney might have used the moment to tell some dramatic stories
about perhaps his greatest professional triumph, victory in the
Gulf War as President George Bush's secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he gave a bare-bones recitation of his resume _ schools
attended, jobs held, place of birth, number of children and
grandchildren, the latter ``a very important part of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies? ``You can usually find me if I have some time off with
either a fly rod or a shotgun in my hand.'' And that was about it.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Cheney, Juleanna Glover Weiss, said Wednesday
that Cheney would soon play a more visible role on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said reporters would be able to fly with Cheney sometime
next week, when he expects to inherit the Boeing 727 that Bush has
been using for his campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretary Cheney looks forward to many long and fruitful
conversations with the national reporters in the back of the
plane,'' she said. ``He's one of those guys that the more you see,
the more you like.''
</P>
<P>
   But the larger question is whether Cheney will prove capable of
forging a critical bond with his audiences over the next months.
Can he, through force of personality or the power of his oratory,
do what the best politicians do: turn a 10-minute stump speech into
a moment of magic that translates into votes won?
</P>
<P>
   At the Kansas City event, before a crowd that was mostly
receptive to his message, Cheney failed that test.
</P>
<P>
   While his wife, Lynne, approached the front row to shake a few
hands after his speech, Cheney lingered behind the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody tell us what to do,'' an elderly woman said a few
rows back, uncertain if it was all right to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Just then the woman noticed a man pushing his way out the back
of the hall. ``There's a leader,'' she said to her friends. ``We'll
follow him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
