u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT     08-30 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING FOR HOWARD IS LATEST TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week after the collapse of a four-way trade that would have
sent Patrick Ewing to Seattle, the Knicks have renewed efforts to
trade the future Hall of Fame center.
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to be more evidence of a nearly irreconcilable
chasm between Ewing and New York, the Knicks have discussed sending
Ewing to the Washington Wizards for Juwan Howard, two Eastern
Conference officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No deal is imminent, but according to NBAofficials, Washington
would jump at making the move. If the Wizards received Ewing, who
has one year and $14 million remaining on his contract, they could
potentially be $10 million beneath the salary cap next summer and
vie for a top-flight free agent such as Michael Finley, Dikembe
Mutombo or Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Why the Knicks would make such a trade is less clear. Howard is
coming off the worst season of his six-year career. On a team that
underachieved from start to finish, Howard averaged 14.9 points and
5.7 rebounds and, on several occasions, was booed lustily by his
home fans. If Howard, a 6-foot-9-inch forward who is not
particularly powerful or graceful, could return to the form that
saw him average 19.3 points and 7.9 rebounds over his first five
seasons, he could be productive.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and the Wizards have spoken about a deal for Ewing
several times over the past year, including two weeks ago before
the Knicks put together the foiled four-team, 13-player trade that
would have sent Ewing to the Seattle SuperSonics. During those
discussions, the Wizards' president, Michael Jordan, rebuffed a
Knicks offer that included Larry Johnson and Chris Dudley because
he felt the Knicks were trying to dump multiple big-money,
long-term contracts onto his team. After the trade collapsed, the
Knicks rekindled talks on a more realistic and less ambitious
scale.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks would still have only Marcus Camby and Chris
Dudley at the center position. And they would be an even weaker
rebounding team than they were last season, when they finished 24th
overall in rebounding and dead last on the offensive end. Giving up
Ewing for Howard certainly would not make the Knicks a threat to
the new-look Miami Heat, which acquired Brian Grant from Portland
Wednesday in a three-team deal that sent Shawn Kemp from Cleveland
to Portland and Chris Gatling, Clarence Weatherspoon and Gary Grant
from Miami to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that a Ewing-for-Howard trade would
lead to a second move, in which the Knicks would send Camby and
Allan Houston to the Atlanta Hawks for the All-Star center, Dikembe
Mutombo. But an official with the Hawks said Wednesday that no such
deal has been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Knicks General Manager Scott Layden nor Coach Jeff Van
Gundy could be reached for comment, but Layden said last week that
the Knicks, working in concert with Ewing and his agent, David
Falk, would continue to explore trade opportunities that benefited
both the team and the player.
</P>
<P>
   But few deals that would meet that criteria seem to be possible.
The Phoenix Suns, whom Ewing would approve a trade to, are not
willing to dismantle their promising young nucleus for the
38-year-old Ewing, and few other teams are willing to give up top
talent to take on his salary.
</P>
<P>
   While a deal with Washington might be the Knicks only realistic
chance for a trade, even it does not fit the description given by
Layden. If Ewing is sincere in his quest for a championship, he
will not want to spend a season in Washington, where the Wizards
have no chance of winning the East. And it is doubtful that the
Wizards would re-sign Ewing for two more years after next season.
</P>
<P>
   The talks between the Knicks and the Wizards seems to be a clear
indication of the enormous disgust that Ewing has developed for the
Knicks and New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to Ewing say he was deeply hurt by the negative
response of the news media and the fans to his being traded last
week, and even before his public censure, his acceptance of a trade
to Seattle, where neither a contract extension nor a finals
appearance was likely, pointed to his simply wanting to leave New
York.
</P>
<P>
   While playing in Washington will not pit Ewing, who lives in
nearby Potomac, Md., during the off season, against Indiana or
Miami in the second round of the playoffs, it would allow him to
close out his career in the city of his collegiate glory
(Georgetown) alongside a close friend (Jordan).
</P>
<P>
   These talks may be a sign that Ewing has told the Knicks to
trade him or else, that he no longer wants to be the third
offensive wheel on a team he once ruled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
