<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS NEWS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whirlpool Lowers Forecast, Reflecting Industry Anxiety
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool, the nation's largest maker of home appliances, warned
that its profit would be sharply lower than expected in the second
half of the year, partly because of Circuit City's decision to stop
selling major appliances at its retail outlets. Whirlpool also
blamed an industrywide slowdown and fierce price competition that
is cutting into profit margins. Much of the downturn in the home
appliance market is attributed to slumping retail sales and a
weakening housing market.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Widens Probe of Defective Firestone Tires &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators trying to determine how much Ford Motor Co.
knew about defective tires used on its Explorers expanded their
investigation Wednesday by demanding that the company provide
detailed information on any tire problems in 16 countries outside
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Says Sales in August To Decline a Surprising 14 Percent
</P>
<P>
   The Gap stunned investors by announcing after the stock market
closed that sales in stores open at least a year, a key industry
measurement, would decline 14 percent in August, well below what
most analysts expected. The Gap's announcement is more remarkable
because it comes after a series of highly atypical stumbles. The
company had a rare earnings disappointment in the first quarter,
and then announced a more pronounced earnings shortfall in the
second quarter and predicted that earnings would be lower than
analysts expected for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico Ordered to Pay Damages
</P>
<P>
   An international tribunal that worked to arbitrate a
cross-border dispute between an American company, Metalclad, and
the Mexican government ordered Mexico to pay nearly $17 million in
damages. Citing investor protection provisions of the North
American Free Trade Agreement, the tribunal found that the
government's actions amounted to an expropriation because they
prevented Metalclad from enjoying the full use of the hazardous
waste treatment and disposal site it constructed. Shares of
Metalclad rose 6 cents, to $4.31.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Chips Drop on Profit Concerns
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks dropped on concern about profits at
manufacturing companies. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped
112.09 points, or 1 percent, to 11,103.01, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index lost 7.25 points, to 1,502.59. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 21.64 points, to 4,103.81.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Sues Broadcom in Patent Case
</P>
<P>
   Intel filed a lawsuit accusing Broadcom of ``a carefully crafted
plan'' to build its business in cable and high-speed networking
products by violating Intel patents.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rejects MP3.com Argument
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge rejected an argument by MP3.com that the
Universal Music Group is improperly pursuing a copyright
infringement claim against the company as a means of driving a
potential rival out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt Exchange Standing Pat
</P>
<P>
   Werner Seifert, the head of the Frankfurt stock market, refused
to sweeten the terms of a proposed merger with the London Stock
Exchange, dismissing a rival bid of $1.2 billion by OM Gruppen of
Sweden as ``ridiculous and derisory.'' The unexpected, and hostile,
bid has at least temporarily blocked the planned merger with
Deutsche Boerse.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and BellSouth Deal Approved
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications and BellSouth won Justice Department approval
to create the nation's second-largest mobile-phone company after
agreeing to sell overlapping properties in 16 markets with 20
million people.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Indicators Fell 0.1 Percent in July
</P>
<P>
   The index of leading economic indicators fell 0.1 percent in
July, the third consecutive monthly drop, an industry group said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
