<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, AUG. 31 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PERU-U.S.-BERENSON-NYT (moved Monday, August 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 28
about a decision by a Peruvian military court to revoke a life
sentence and grant a new treason trial to Lori Berenson, a New
Yorker,included an erroneous detail in an account of an appearance
by Ms. Berenson before journalists at a detention center in 1996.
She did not raise a fist to the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The article also included an outdated statement by one of her
lawyers, Thomas Nooter. While he said four years ago that Ms.
Berenson had had a romantic relationship with a member of the Tupac
Amaru rebel group, Mr. Nooter now says that he knows from speaking
to her since then that she did not.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated what Mr. Nooter had said about a
rebel who testified against Ms. Berenson. He said that the rebel
might have incriminated her in exchange for a lighter sentence, not
in exchange for a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MARKET-NYT (moved Monday, August 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 28
about the daily performance of the stock market misstated the
record high for the Dow Jones industrial average. It was 11,722.98
points in January, not 11,287.08 in April.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT (moved Tuesday, August 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 29
about GetMusic, an Internet site owned by Bertelsmann and Seagram,
misstated the site's plans for music sales. It is considering
finding another company to handle sales of compact discs in the
United States, but it has not made a final decision to do so, and
it still intends to sell music through computer downloads. It is
not getting out of selling music. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
