<P>
   (NYT51) UNDATED -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT --
Hammering nails is such an elementary task that it would seem that
no explanation is needed. Yet professional carpenters and shop
instructors say that many do-it-yourselfers don't know how to drive
nails efficiently. The most common mistake is in holding the hammer
too close to the head. (Ed Lipinski/New York Times Illustration)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT50) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- NY-GIDONE-MEMORIAL -- The
family of a mentally disturbed Hasidic man who was fatally shot by
the police last year while wielding a hammer on a street in central
Brooklyn has filed a wrongful-death lawsuit charging that the
officers involved in the killing acted with excessive force. A
group of Hasidic girls and boys watch as a makeshift memorial to
Gidone Bush was placed on the sidewalk where Bush was killed in a
volley of 12 shots fired by police officers on Aug. 30, 1999.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT49) KARABULAK, Russia -- Aug. 30, 2000 --
CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-2 -- With winter coming the mammoth relief effort
that has sustained the Chechen refugee population is suffering from
fatigue among donors. Bread distribution in Ingushetia, near the
town of Karabulak, was cut off for six weeks this summer because
the Russian government failed to pay food vendors. Chechen women at
a makeshift refugee that has taken on the name Sputnik wait to have
their buckets filled with soup. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT48) INGUSHETIA, Russia -- Aug. 30, 2000 --
CHECHNYA-REFUGEES-1 -- After a year of fighting, Russia's armed
forces have declared that the war against separatists in Chechnya
is effectively over. Still, some 155,000 people are still refugees
and do not want to go home to a country where gunfire rules the
night and where no family feels safe. Thousands have settled in a
makeshift Chechen refugee camp in Ingushetia, near the town of
Karabulak, that has taken on the name Sputnik. A Chechen boy at the
camp on the border of Chechnya used a makeshift gymnastics bar for
a workout. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT47) ATLANTA -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- CHENEY-2 -- Republican vice
presidential candidate Dick Cheney, who served as secretary of
defense during the 1991 Gulf War, blamed President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, Wednesday for cutting military spending too
deeply during their eight years in the White House. Cheney speaking
at the Southern Center for International Studies in Atlanta said
the cuts combined with an unclear and growing number of overseas
deployments were stretching the armed services to the limit. (Ben
Gray/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT46) ATLANTA -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- CHENEY-1 -- Republican vice
presidential candidate Dick Cheney speaking at the Southern Center
for International Studies during a campaign stop in Atlanta, lashed
out at the Clinton administration Wednesday for adopting policies
he said had reduced the morale of the U.S. military and diminished
its ability to respond to foreign conflicts. ``Our military today
is overused and under-resourced,'' Cheney told a crowd of about 300
Republicans, including several war veterans. (Ben Gray/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) NEW YORK -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN. SEPT. 3 --
SONGWRITERS-THEATER -- There are many ways a songwriter today can
be unfashionable. Choosing to write for the American musical
theater is merely one of the surer routes. Take Michael John
LaChiusa who writes songs in the classic Broadway manner as
descended from the American popular songbook. LaChiusa's music
flouts tradition with incendiary rebelliousness, both lyrically and
melodically. The cast of Michael John LaChiusa's iconoclastic
musical ``The Wild Party,'' at the Joseph Papp Public Theater.
(Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
