Internet has enabled expatriates to be more connected to home than
ever before. Kate Juliff of Australia, an information technology
manager who has lived in New York for seven years, started
Australians Abroad in 1996 with Richard Rankin, in order to ``raise
issues of relevance to expatriates, as well as provide stories of
interest, resources and a cybermeeting place for Australians living
overseas.'' The site now has 600 regular users with 1,000 drop-ins
a day from 50 countries. (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) EASTCHESTER, N.Y. -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- CIR-NAPSTER-PRANKS
-- Not all music lovers love Napster. In fact, some are so opposed
to it, they practice something between a prank and sabotage, making
music files that look like popular songs, until you download them.
Then it's something else entirely. John Fix III and his brother
Michael in a hardware store where they work on fake Napster files.
(Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- CIR-LONG-DISTANCE-LOVE
-- Keeping a long-distance relationship alive via computer is
possible. But the RSI is brutal. Prentice Welch and Erika Lam,
expecting their first child in October, kept their relationship
alive via the Internet when Lam was in Costa Rica and Welch worked
in Beijing. (Thor Swift/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOMBAY, India -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- SLUG -- Amitabah
Bachan, right, host of India's popular game show ``Kaun Banega
Crorepati,'' quizzes a contestant. Since early July, India, a
nation where the average person would need 2,325 years of income to
become a millionaire, has been obsessed with the show, translated
as ``Who Will Become a Ten-Millionaire,'' created in Britain and
now exported to 31 countries including the United States, Japan,
Israel, Finland and Argentina. The prize money is in rupees.
(Santosh Verma, Agence France Press for The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOMBAY, India -- Aug. 30, 2000 -- INDIA-QUIZ-SHOW-1 -- A
family in a Bombay slum watches ``Kaun Banega Crorepati,'' on
Monday. Since early July, India, a nation where the average person
