<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TV-LESS-MOSCOW-INDEPE     08-30 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LESS-MOSCOW-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV-JUNKIE MUSCOVITES FACE LIFE WITHOUT THEIR `NARCOTIC'  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 800-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Muscovites were thrown back to the pre-electronic age
Tuesday after the devastating fire at the Ostankino television
tower, which knocked most of their TV channels off the air.
</P>
<P>
   The body of a third victim, trapped in an elevator which
plummeted during the blaze, was identified, but all but close
relatives of the dead were more concerned about how they would cope
with the loss of news and entertainment programs to which they had
become addicted.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were exploring ways of resuming normal service
as soon as possible. One idea was to use the spire of Moscow State
University, one of the seven famous ``wedding cake'' skyscrapers
built under Stalin, for broadcasting. Another was to attach
transmitters to dirigibles.
</P>
<P>
   Independent NTV had already found a partial solution by
transferring its programs to the TNT channel, which did not rely on
Ostankino, and it offered to make room for the pro-Kremlin channels
there as well. But the offer was sniffily rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Watching NTV on TNT was only an option for a small number of
Moscow's 10 million inhabitants, however, as reception was
impossible in the built-up inner city.
</P>
<P>
   It was ironic that the Russian provinces, often seen as
languishing in the Stone Age compared with go-ahead Moscow, were
receiving television broadcasts while most viewers in the capital
could see nothing on their screens but snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we haven't even had a coup,'' quipped my friend, Vitaly.
His 17-year-old son, Kirill, was in a black depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is terrible,'' he said. ``I don't know how I'm going to
live from now on.'' ``Well, you could see it as a chance to catch
up on all that history you still have not read,'' said Vitaly.
``I'm not going to do that,'' snorted the teenager. ``You'll have
to get me the Internet now.''
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Russia, along with Iceland, had the highest
literacy rates and the most avid readers in the world. The
Icelanders read because of the dark winters. The Russians read
because Soviet television, with its endless reports of Brezhnev
speeches and bumper grain harvests, was unwatchable.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners in Moscow were regularly shamed to discover that
Russians had read far more Shakespeare, Dickens, Balzac or Goethe
than they had.
</P>
<P>
   In post-Communist times, however, Russians have been glued to
the box _ and not only the younger generation. For the poor, unable
to afford outings to restaurants or theatres, and the housebound
elderly, the game shows and imported soap operas have been a
godsend and a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just me,'' said Kirill. ``My granddad can't fall
asleep without the television and grandma takes `Sunset Beach' so
seriously that she thinks all the characters are real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists warned that the loss of television could spark a
rise in mental illness and the newspaper Moskovsky Komsomolets
predicted a crime wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of such an irresistible narcotic as television
will certainly cause a rise in the sort of senseless crimes usually
carried out when there is nothing else to do,'' it said. ``Boredom
sets in. So you rob a bystander, knife the neighbor or bash in the
windows of a nearby shop.''
</P>
<P>
   The only trouble is that viewers will not be able to see any of
this on the true crime programs that were even more popular than
the soaps.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation Tuesday, Muscovites were queuing at kiosks to buy
videos, many of them bootlegged versions of the most violent and
banal Western-made films.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're snapping up everything from kick-boxing movies to
cartoons,'' said one kiosk owner. ``I haven't seen anything like
this since Western videos first became available after the end of
Communism.''
</P>
<P>
   If the video traders were cashing in, then the losers after the
fire were the well-paid media workers and advertising executives
linked to television.
</P>
<P>
   They were facing the same kind of cuts and layoffs as the middle
class in general suffered after the great financial crash of August
1998. That ultimately proved healthy for the Russian economy.
Likewise, the Ostankino fire may force a modernization of
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   This week, those with access to the Internet counted themselves
lucky. The joke site, www.anecdote.ru, which stopped laughing out
of respect for the Kursk submariners who drowned in the Arctic
earlier this month, was back with its usual pitch of black humor
and nothing was sacred any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authorities are still investigating the cause of the
Ostankino fire,'' went one joke. ``They do not rule out the
possibility of a collision with a foreign submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   Or another: ``The fire is still raging at Ostankino. All hopes
are pinned now on the arrival of the Norwegian divers.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
