<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-FLOPS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY FLOPS AS A RUNNING MATE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This 675-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``p'' political
news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Republican presidential nominee, George W.
Bush, named Richard Cheney to be his running mate four weeks ago,
there were quips from Bush-critics that the ticket was the wrong
way around.
</P>
<P>
   Was not Cheney, a former White House chief of staff and
respected defense secretary during the Gulf War, better equipped to
be president than the one-and-a-half-term governor of Texas, George
Bush?
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, with opinion polls showing Bush and his Democratic
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, running neck and neck into the
crucial Labor Day weekend, that same Cheney is looking increasingly
like a liability for the Bush ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A series of missteps has called into question Cheney's political
acumen and last Sunday, as the two nominees took a rare weekend off
from campaigning, the Republican candidate for vice president found
himself in the hot seat of the television talk shows, trying to
limit the damage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the thorniest problems concerns a possible conflict of
interest relating to the position he has just relinquished as chief
executive of the Texas oil equipment company, Halliburton.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was he awarded a multimillion-dollar retirement package
_ which he says is standard for the industry, even though he broke
the terms of his contract by leaving early _ but he continues to
hold share options which cannot be exercised for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Cheney has refused to countenance giving up the options,
nor did he do so Sunday, saying only that he had advisers working
on ways that the appearance of any conflict of interest could be
avoided.
</P>
<P>
   So long as the share option problem persists, Cheney draws
attention to his (and Bush's) ties with what Gore derides as ``big
oil,'' and perpetuates a view that there is one law for the rich
and another for ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   The government experience Cheney was supposed to bring to the
Republican ticket is also turning out to be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush attacked the state of the country's armed forces,
blaming the Clinton-Gore administration for underfunding the
military, the one-time defense secretary was not on hand to back
him up. (He was actually honing his blunted campaign skills,
reading ``The Hungry Caterpillar'' to elementary school children.)
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats delighted in pointing out, it was Cheney who had
decreed the biggest cuts in military spending _ holding out the
prospect of a 25 percent cut as the post-Cold War ``peace
dividend'' _ during the administration of Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   Responding for the first time Sunday, Cheney quoted figures to
show certain branches of the military slashed by almost half in
recent years, but he had no answer to the central charge.
</P>
<P>
   Before his television appearances last weekend, Cheney's
contributions to the Bush campaign had been alternately invisible
and clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he even suggested that a Bush administration might
reverse some of Clinton's orders designating new national parks: a
proposal that only reinforced the Democrats' portrayal of the
Republican candidate as anti-environment and pro-big business.
</P>
<P>
   And when he appeared on television Sunday _ at 6 a.m. local time
from his vacation home in Wyoming _ he flouted the weekend
political dress code, appearing overly formal in dark suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has it that a running mate has no impact on
the success or otherwise of a presidential ticket _ an argument
apparently borne out by the Bush-Quayle victory in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   This year, both candidates chose running mates who could
compensate for deficiencies in their own character or records. Of
the two, however, MrGore's choice of Joseph Lieberman seems so far
the more successful.
</P>
<P>
   Warm, relaxed and politically sharp, Lieberman has shown himself
an accomplished solo performer as well as a supportive team player.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, in contrast, seems cool and aloof, hardly part of a
joint ticket at all, and his experience of high office is proving
to be as much burden as boon.
</P>
<P>
   A running mate may not save or sink the ticket, but a bad choice
cannot but reflect poorly on the candidate's judgment. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 675-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
