<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BUSH-HNS &LR;      08-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush off course in campaign strategy, fending off accusations
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    and JULIE MASON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERIE, Pa. _ Fighting to regain momentum against Democratic foe
Al Gore, George W. Bush on Wednesday accused the Clinton-Gore
administration of failing to provide leadership on health care and
tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential nominee had planned this week to
showcase his educational achievements as Texas governor and promote
education initiatives. And he reviewed his educational priorities
in speeches here and in New Hampshire, but he also has been forced
to address distractions.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bush watched a double-digit lead over Gore evaporate in
voter polls. Then he found himself embroiled in a controversy over
health care and presidential debates. And finally, he faced even
more bad news on Wednesday _ a federal court finding that his home
state has been deficient in providing health care to low-income
children on Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   He denied suggestions that he had been forced into a defensive
posture. ``I feel like I'm making good progress getting my message
out. I feel very comfortable about it,'' he said. But he also went
on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talk in this campaign, but it's time to get
leadership in Washington who will get something done,'' Bush said
at an airport rally on arriving in Erie, a key center in a
battleground state.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the country, Vice President Gore and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., campaigned together
in Oregon, continued to push their health care proposals and
accused Bush of being unwilling to guarantee the sanctity of future
Medicare funding.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the Republicans want to use the federal budget surplus
on a tax cut mostly benefiting the wealthy. ``Their theory is
that's going to be good for the country, and they say it's your
money,'' Gore said. ``Well, it is your money, but it's your
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is proposing removing Medicare from the federal budget so
that future surpluses can't be used to cover other expenses. By
doing so, Gore estimates that $400 million over the next 10 years
could go to strengthening Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic contenders have criticized Bush for failing to
commit to similar protective measures, and for declining so far to
outline specifics of his own health care plan. Bush has said he
will detail his proposals on health care next week.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Wednesday morning on CNN, where he fielded questions
posed over the Internet, Bush reiterated his charge that the
Clinton administration squandered its chances to reform Medicare
and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration has had seven years to get something
done.'' Bush has said he favors a bipartisan congressional proposal
to give Medicaid beneficiaries the option of selecting from a range
of private health plans that would include drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In a town hall meeting at Portland State University in Oregon,
Gore said he is against that plan because it would raise premiums
for coverage, force seniors into health maintenance organizations
against their will, and raise the eligibility age for Medicare from
65 years to 67 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman in the past has supported raising the eligibility for
Medicare. Since accepting the slot as vice presidential running
mate, Lieberman has said he is deferring to Gore on such policy
positions.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated Gore's contention that Republican tax cuts could
benefit wealthier Americans at the expense of the lower and middle
classes. ``There's nothing wrong with being rich. In America
everybody dreams of being rich,'' he said. ``But the fact is that
if we've got this kind of surplus, we shouldn't give it most to
those who need it least, and least to those who need it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought to claim the tax issue himself Wednesday, citing
what he said were broken promises after President Clinton and Gore
were elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of 1992 all over again. Remember the
(Democratic) promises to give the middle class tax relief?'' he
asked the audience in Erie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon election the middle class didn't get tax relief. They got
a tax increase,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Bush was referring to a federal tax increase
enacted in 1993, the first year of the Clinton-Gore administration.
He said that package raised the gasoline tax, increased the tax on
Social Security benefits and raised the top income tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
