<HEADER>
A6807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT     08-30 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STOP ASTROS AND KEEP SHARE OF FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no fussing so far as Rick Reed is concerned.
He stands on the mound, he receives a sign, he winds up and he
usually throws a pitch that is close to the strike zone. Then Reed
retreats to the pitcher's rubber and repeats the same routine,
eager to keep the game moving and to keep the tempo flowing. Why
waste time?
</P>
<P>
   Reed moved at his swift and efficient pace Wednesday night,
retiring batter after batter against the baffled Houston Astros.
Reed's fastball almost never reaches 90 mph, but he locates all of
his pitches so precisely that the fastball looks more imposing.
That helped make the Astros look helpless.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros did not get a hit off Reed until the fifth inning and
they did not score off him through seven innings as the Mets
tip-toed to a 1-0 victory at Shea Stadium. Chris Holt gave up the
game's only run, in the first inning, when he unleashed a two-out
wild pitch that enabled Benny Agbayani to cruise home. It was a
frustrating way to lose for the Astros, epitomizing their dreary
season.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, it was another tidy performance by Reed, who won a
second straight start by allowing three singles, and another day
spent tied for first place in the National League East with the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and the Braves, who beat the Cincinnati Reds, 5-2,
Wednesday night, have shared first in the National League East for
the last three days. It is the latest into a season that the Mets
have been in first since they were alone at the top on Sept. 3,
1990.
</P>
<P>
   The fans at Shea Stadium picked up on Reed's no-hit bid in the
fifth and clapped rhythmically when he jumped ahead of Mitch
Meluskey with an 0-2 count. Meluskey hit a grounder toward the
second base hole, but Edgardo Alfonzo took a few steps to his left,
scooped the ball up and flipped to Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen outs without a hit, 14 more to go. Reed did not change
his rapid pace on a warm night. He picked up the resin bag a few
times to reduce the perspiration on his fingers, but he continued
working quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers, who was four for 15 against Reed in his career,
worked the count to 3-2. Reed had three strikeouts at that point
and all three had been on fastballs. Would Spiers be expecting a
fastball with a full count? Perhaps Reed thought so. He tossed a
changeup that stayed high and Spiers flicked it into left field for
a single.
</P>
<P>
   With the chance for a no-hitter eliminated, the fans gave Reed a
polite ovation. All Reed did was go back to work. He retired Tim
Bogar on a twisting liner to right field and got Holt to wave at a
curveball for strike three. The Astros finally had their first hit,
but they still looked anemic.
</P>
<P>
   Reed allowed a one-out single to Julio Lugo in the sixth, but
erased him by getting Jeff Bagwell to rap into a
third-to-second-to-first double play. Robin Ventura's throw to
second was below Alfonzo's waist, but he neatly caught the ball and
whipped it on to first. Lance Berkman singled in the seventh, but
Reed anchored him to first by retiring the next three Astros.
</P>
<P>
   For a pitcher with control as precise as Reed, having a plate
umpire like Mark Hirschbeck was like receiving an early birthday
present. Hirschbeck was calling inside strikes so Reed kept trying
to swipe another inch to see how much of the plate he could get.
Reed twice fired called third strikes by the former Met Roger
Cedeno, who jumped back from the plate in animated fashion each
time.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani, who only looks like a leadoff hitter when someone
stares at his .404 on-base percentage instead of his
5-foot-10-inch, 225-pound body, did what leadoff hitters should do
when he walked in the first. Darryl Hamilton, who probably would
have rested a sore left shoulder if Derek Bell (bruised left knee
and strained left groin) were available, followed with a nifty bunt
single along the third-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Holt induced Alfonzo to slap into a double play. But Holt's
breaking pitches, which are the reason he is second in the league
in securing double plays, were the reason the Mets scored. Holt
bounced a pitch to Mike Piazza that slithered under Meluskey's
glove and enabled Agbayani to chug 90 feet with what became the
only run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reed did the rest, routinely, with help from Turk Wendell in the
eighth and Armando Benitez in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
