<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLAS-COMIC-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEIGHT LIFTED FOR DC COMICS: CHARLES ATLAS SUIT IS REJECTED
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charles Atlas might have been one of America's most
famous musclemen, ably taking on bullies who kicked sand in his
face at the beach. But this week, a federal judge treated his
company like a 97-pound weakling and threw it out of court.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which markets a bodybuilding course popularized in
part through generations of comic book advertisements, had gone to
court claiming that a character in a short-lived DC comic was taken
from Atlas' famous campaign ``The Insult That Made a Man out of
Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement told the brief story of Mac, the 97-pound
weakling, and a bully who kicks sand in his face. Mac, humiliated
by the sand kicking, takes the Charles Atlas course, becomes a
hulking giant and returns to thrash the bully. In the final panel,
the words ``Hero of the Beach'' hover over Mac's head, while his
girlfriend looks on.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, DC Comics published a book featuring a character called
Flex Mentallo. The comic book featured a vignette titled
``Musclebound _ The Secret Origin of Flex Mentallo.'' Like Mac,
Flex started out as a weakling, was humiliated by a bully and
gained super strength through exercise. But after beating the
bully, Flex turns on his girlfriend and beats her, proclaiming, ``I
don't need a tramp like you anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Atlas Ltd. claimed the Flex Mentallo character owed its
origin to the Mac advertising campaign, and that DC's portrayal had
damaged the good will gained by the original advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Naomi Reice Buchwald, of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan, rejected Atlas' argument. She granted DC's motion for a
summary judgment and dismissed the case on Tuesday. Buchwald ruled
that Charles Atlas had failed to raise the issue within the
six-year statute of limitations required by such cases, and she
also found that the DC comic was a parody of the Charles Atlas
advertisements, and therefore not subject to a lawsuit for
trademark infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Laserson, vice president and general counsel for DC
Comics, welcomed the decision, saying the episode was meant as a
parody. ``We meant no harm to the Charles Atlas company, nor do I
think we caused any harm,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyer for Charles Atlas said DC Comics should not have
copied the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our position, whether or not he had turned around and
beat up his own girlfriend after he became an Atlas man, it would
have been an infringement,'' said Seth Akabas, a lawyer whose firm
represented Charles Atlas Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The company survives the bodybuilder Charles Atlas, who died in
1972. He was often featured in the advertisements in his bathing
suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
