<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA BANS U.N. HUMAN-RIGHTS INSPECTORS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for upcoming Olympics, Sydney)   (This 375-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KATHY MARKS  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SYDNEY _ With only a fortnight to go until the Sydney Olympic
Games, the Australian government has taken the controversial step
of banning visits by United Nations human-rights inspectors in the
wake of recent criticism of the country's treatment of its
Aboriginal people and of asylum-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister, Alexander Downer, said Tuesday that U.N.
committees would not be allowed to visit Australia or be supplied
with any information unless there was a compelling reason to do so.
He said that Australia's future involvement with the committees was
dependent on them being reformed.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the move could hardly be more provocative, ahead
of the Olympic Games, which Aboriginal activists have threatened to
use as a platform to highlight their second-class status.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the U.N. Human-Rights Committee criticized the
Australian government for its stance on Aboriginal land rights and
for mandatory sentencing laws which it said resulted in
disproportionate numbers of Aborigines being sent to jail.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney-general, Daryl Williams, accused the U.N. of
concentrating on relatively minor issues in democratic countries
like Australia while ignoring serious human-rights abuses
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``If we are comparing (Australia's record) with
arbitrary arrests and executions and having your arms chopped off,
the problems in Australia pale into insignificance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition Labor party criticized the government's
response, as did Amnesty International, which said that Australia
appeared to want to be accountable only to itself. ``This is an
irresponsible overreaction to recent poor report cards,'' said Kate
Gilmore, Amnesty's Australian director.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's 400,000 Aborigines are the country's most
disadvantaged group, with much higher infant mortality and much
lower life expectancy than the rest of the population of 19
million.
</P>
<P>
   Last May the U.N. committee on the elimination of racial
discrimination published a report criticizing the federal
government for its failure to override mandatory sentencing laws
that are in effect in Western Australia and the Northern Territory.
</P>
<P>
   The laws require that repeat offenders be jailed even for
trivial crimes and, according to human-rights campaigners, target
the kind of offenses committed by Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. committees have also criticized Australia's policy of
holding illegal immigrants in detention camps while their refugee
applications are determined. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 375-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
