<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GAP-SALES-NYT &LR;      08-30 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAP-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAP PROJECTS DECLINE OF 14 PERCENT IN ITS AUGUST SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gap Inc. stunned investors Wednesday evening by announcing after
the stock market closed that sales in stores open at least a year,
a well-watched industry measurement, would decline 14 percent in
August. The numbers were not only well below what most analysts
expected, they seemed to truly surprise the normally efficient
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results were clearly a disappointment and feel well below
our own expectations,'' said Heidi Kunz, executive vice president
and chief financial officer, in a recorded message for investors on
monthly sales. While August hardly rivals December for retailers,
it is nonetheless an important month because of back-to-school
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at each of Gap's brands were lower than they were last
year in stores open at least a year. Gap's lower-priced chain, Old
Navy, which after blazing growth last year had a sharp downturn
early this summer, a sales decline of more than 20 percent. Sales
at the namesake The Gap stores were down, the company said, ``in
the mid-single digits.'' And even Banana Republic, previously a
growth stalwart for the company, had similar declines in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Gap's miss on sales is more remarkable because it comes after a
series of highly atypical stumbles. The company had a rare earnings
disappointment in the first quarter, and then announced a more
pronounced earnings shortfall in the second quarter and predicted
that earnings would be lower than analysts expected for the entire
year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sent shares of Gap plunging 12 percent, to $22.50, in
after-hours trading after the company announced its August sales.
The shares are down more than 50 percent from a February high of
$53 and are trading at their lowest point since October 1998. And
the news could get worse.
</P>
<P>
   The company acknowledged that because of a ``highly
promotional'' environment, with sales earlier and more widespread,
gross margins were lower this August than last year, and said the
trend could further hurt earnings. ``We continue to see risk and
challenge in the third and fourth quarters,'' Kunz said in the
telephone message.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Barbara Miller, an analyst with Goldman,
Sachs, thought Gap's earnings a share would be $1.58. Earlier this
month, she lowered her forecast to $1.28. Wednesday night she would
not say if she planned to lower her estimates again, but did say,
``This certainly gives me pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Gap said that some problems emerged with all its brands. First,
back-to-school sales, which the company said had built consistently
through the month previously, failed to expand in August. The
company also blamed the cutback in spending by consumers for retail
items.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company cited its decision to rely less on
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gap brand's decision to shift its marketing mix away from TV
in favor of in-store marketing and promotion efforts did not
succeed as well as we had hoped,'' said Millard S. Drexler, the
company's president and chief executive, in a press release. The
Gap said it would change course and support its brands with lots of
television advertising in the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers have had a disappointing year. After six interest
rate increases by the Federal Reserve, consumer spending on retail
is declining. After the second quarter, many of the biggest
retailers said they were expecting a consumer slowdown in the third
and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some retailers managed to do well with teen-agers heading
back to school. Analysts are expecting American Eagle Outfitters, a
fast-growing Gap rivals, to report a sales gain of 9 percent
Friday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Analysts worried that there might be something more amiss with
Gap. ``There are no teen-agers going naked back to school,'' said
Richard Jaffe, a retailing analyst at PaineWebber. ``There have to
be other issues impacting Gap. It is a cause for concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WORKFORCE-DEATH-NY     08-30 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WORKFORCE-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKFARE CRITICS CITE THE CASE OF A WOMAN WHO DIED ON THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  By THOMAS J. LUECK  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A woman's death at her job in the city's workfare
program earlier this month prompted bitter criticism of the mayor
Wednesday by opponents of the program, who said the woman had been
afraid to take time off to visit her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Laura Morales, 34, a mother of three, died Aug. 11
while working as a kitchen aide at a Brooklyn homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, a group of about 100 people protested the
rigors of workfare outside the offices of Jason Turner, the
commissioner of the Human Resources Administration, who is in
charge of the workfare program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the type of work that caused this death, but the
atmosphere in which she worked,'' said Stephen DiBrienza, the
chairman of the City Council General Welfare Committee and an
impassioned critic of workfare, who attended the protest.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said Morales ``lived in fear and died in
fear, and it is Jason Turner who is responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   According to an account Wednesday in the Queens edition of
Newsday, friends and relatives of Morales' said she had been
experiencing severe headaches, but had refused to take time off for
fear of losing her welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the woman's death has not been disclosed by the
city's medical examiner. But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, responding to
the protest at a news conference, said that evidence indicated she
had died of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In defending the workfare program, the mayor also said that
Morales would not have been prevented from seeing a doctor because
of her assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragically, unfortunately, people do die at work,'' the mayor
said. He appeared at City Hall with Turner and several workfare
administrators and praised their ``aggressive efforts to move
thousands of people from welfare to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2256EDT &QL; 
