<HEADER>
A6815 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CZECH-CHERNOBYL?-INDE     08-30 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-CHERNOBYL?-INDEPENDENT-600&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY FEARS OVER `UNSAFE' CZECH NUCLEAR POWER PLANT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Note Sept. 5 and 10 - grafs 2 and 4)   (This 600-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: THIS ARTICLE CAN STAND ALONE IN 600 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT IS
975.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JUSTIN HUGGLER  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TEMELIN, CZECH REPUBLIC _ The people who live near Temelin, in
the rolling hills of south Bohemia, have been issued with two small
tablets each. They have been told to keep them in a safe place _
and to take them if anything goes wrong at the Soviet-designed
nuclear power plant that is about to be activated a few miles from
their homes, a plant Germany said this week it was not convinced is
safe.
</P>
<P>
   You can see the four massive cooling towers that rise over
Temelin for miles around. The nuclear power plant, Russian-designed
and partly modernized by a subsidiary of British Nuclear Fuels Ltd.
(BNFL), is due to be activated some time around Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the German government announced that its nuclear
watchdog, the GRS, is not convinced Temelin is safe, and demanded
urgent meetings with the Czech authorities before the first reactor
is activated. The Germans say Temelin could affect the Czech's
Republic's application for membership of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech authorities have agreed to meet their German
counterparts on Sept 5. But that meeting will have no effect on the
decision to activate Temelin, they insist.
</P>
<P>
   Austria, whose border is only 30 miles away, has been furiously
lobbying against Temelin for months. Greenpeace claims there are
serious safety shortcomings at Temelin _ claims which are
strenuously denied by the Czech nuclear safety authority.
</P>
<P>
   Work started at Temelin under the old communist authorities, in
1983, and has been going on ever since. Last year, the Czech
authorities decided to finish and activate the reactor. The Czech
Republic is not short of electricity, but Temelin is expected to
provide lucrative energy exports.
</P>
<P>
   In the villages around Temelin, opinion is divided. ``They
should have switched it on months ago,'' says Frantisek Petrasek.
``We should be making money from it. The Germans should mind their
own business. They're just trying to ruin our economy. We've
already sold most of the country to the West as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody agrees. ``Of course I'm scared,'' says Gerhard
Draschko, an Austrian visiting Hluboka castle with his two young
children. ``I'm scared for the children.'' Draschko lives just
across the border, 30 miles from Temelin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans say it's not safe and I think they're right,''
says Jana Rosa, a Czech who owns a cafe near the castle. ``What can
we do?'' asks her husband, Vladimir. ``Nobody asked us about it. It
was decided in communist times, when they made the decisions and
just told us, `Shut up.' Nothing's changed, they still don't ask
us.''
</P>
<P>
   A national referendum on Temelin was proposed, but it never
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they've spent so much of our taxes on it, we have to
switch it on so we can get the money back,'' says Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Czech people don't realize we have a democracy now,'' says
Horst Lampert, an anti-nuclear campaigner who lives a few miles
from Temelin. ``They think we have to accept what the politicians
decide, like in the old days. They don't realize we can object, so
they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Lampert, who once won a keg of beer from his local landlord when
he bet he could power the local school with solar energy, organizes
vacations in the Czech Republic for the child victims of the
Chernobyl disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the children of Chernobyl,'' says Lampert. ``They've
got no hair, they know there is no cure for them and that they're
dying,'' says Lampert. ``I have three children and two
grandchildren. I'm worried.'' &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 600, OR CONTINUE TO 975) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Temelin's two reactors are Russian VVER-1000s _ generally
regarded as the safest of the Russian designs, and completely
different from the reactor that went wrong at Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the plant _ the instrumentation and control _ are being
replaced with American designs by the U.S. firm Westinghouse, a
subsidiary of BNFL.
</P>
<P>
   The GRS, Germany's nuclear watchdog, in a report for the German
government, has identified three areas of concern at Temelin, all
of them concerned with emergency safety mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious appears to be the fear that safety valves which
allow steam out of the reactor cannot cope if water comes out
instead _ a very rare but potentially dangerous occurrence which
was first identified in America's Three Mile Island disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech nuclear licensing authority, the SUJB, is confident it
has already resolved the Germans' other two worries. One is a fear
cooling pipes may break; the SUJB says that is prevented by an
American design the Germans are not familiar with. The other is
that emergency batteries do not have enough capacity; the Czechs
say it has already been increased.
</P>
<P>
   But the German Environment Ministry says it is concerned with
Temelin in general. The plant is surrounded with unsubstantiated
allegations of safety lapses and incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace claims there are cracks in the reactor vessel larger
than the safety limit, but offers no documentary evidence. The SUJB
says the cracks are well within the safety limit.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace says repair welding to cooling pipes wasn't tested.
The SUJB says it was, and was proved safe.
</P>
<P>
   A Czech engineer who worked on the project says pipes weren't
properly cleaned, which could allow dirt to get into the reactor.
The SUJB says they were thoroughly cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   There are claims nuclear fuel was moved without precautions and
radioactivity escaped. The SUJB denies this. There is no conclusive
evidence for any of these allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The SUJB's own annual reports, though, are damning of safety
procedures at Temelin _ particularly of those of Skoda, the Czech
contractor responsible for most for the hardware. But Dana Drabova,
chairman of the SUJB, says those concerns do not affect the safety
of the finished reactor, which is being thoroughly tested. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 975-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
