<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LIEBERMAN-RELIGI     08-30 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LIEBERMAN-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LIEBERMAN'S RELIGIOUS WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 31:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman's nomination as the Democratic
vice-presidential candidate was widely hailed as a breakthrough for
tolerance. Now, in a remarkable campaign development, Lieberman is
being criticized by some Jewish leaders and others fearful that his
declarations of faith as a devout Jew, and his calls for more
religion in public life, are an affront to Americans who are less
religious or whose faith comes from a different tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, leaders of the Christian right are defending
Lieberman while asserting that some of their own leaders who seek a
bigger role for religion and religious institutions should be
absolved of similar charges of intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has long and eloquently argued that a general decline
in moral values, especially in popular culture, must be reversed by
a reaffirmation of religion. However, in comments last Sunday he
seemed to cross the boundaries of tolerance when he declared that
``George Washington warned us never to indulge the supposition
`that morality can be maintained without religion.''' As the
Anti-Defamation League pointed out, this sort of talk is offensive
to many highly ethical citizens who are not religious. On Tuesday
Lieberman explained that he did not mean to suggest that
irreligious people could not be moral. But whenever religious
matters are addressed, Lieberman should firmly and unequivocally
reiterate his support for the separation of church and state, a
bedrock principle of the U.S. Constitution and political system.
</P>
<P>
   No one should want Lieberman to refrain from speaking from his
heart about his faith. Voters are entitled to know _ indeed they
need to know _ what inspires and informs the thinking of anyone
running for office. Lieberman has also performed a great service by
reiterating that deep religious faith is not a monopoly of
conservatives. As he notes, religious ``awakenings'' led to such
liberal milestones as the Bill of Rights in the 18th century, the
abolition of slavery and various progressive social reforms in the
19th century, and the civil rights revolution of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Today Lieberman is calling for a fourth ``awakening'' of
religion as an antidote to violence, promiscuity and the
degradation of family values. These positions, not to mention his
condemnation of President Clinton's sexual misconduct in 1998,
appeal to many voters and were clearly a major reason Vice
President Al Gore selected him as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that spiritual guidance can help in combating
immorality is irrefutable. The danger lies in political appeals
that are so zealous that they unsettle Americans with different
religious views, making them feel like second-class citizens, or
lead to policies coercive toward non-believers.
</P>
<P>
   As Lieberman has pointed out, throughout U.S. history tolerance
for American pluralism and diversity has done far more to enhance
religion than to undermine it. That is why it is good for the
national dialogue to see someone of deep religious faith argue in
favor of abortion rights, against school prayer and against
discrimination of homosexuals, as Lieberman has.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has also condemned the movie industry for its disdain
of moral values, deplored the proliferation of pornographic and
violent material on the Internet and _ like Gore and Gov. George W.
Bush _ called for greater government funding for ``faith-based''
organizations that deliver services to the poor and the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   In instituting these policies, there should never be any
compromise with the Constitution's ban on government establishment
of religion. Exhorting Hollywood to make different movies cannot
veer into government censorship, and government funding of
``faith-based'' organizations should never be used to support
religious proselytizing by these groups.
</P>
<P>
   What should also never happen is for either side to frame the
debate over these questions as a kind of litmus test of one's
religious conviction, which is something many advocates of school
prayer and other issues have done. It is fine to call for more
religion in American public life.
</P>
<P>
   But supporting the constitutionally based separation of religion
from public policy or favoring limits on the role of government in
promoting religious values should not be denigrated as immoral or
anti-religion. In the end, tolerance and understanding of the
boundaries between church and state are what have allowed religion
to flourish in the United States as it has in few other countries
in history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
