<HEADER>
A6818 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-LAZIO-AD-BOX-NYT &LR;      08-30 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZIO-AD-BOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: LAZIO MAKES TRUST THE ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a new 30-second commercial, called ``Believe,'' that the
Lazio campaign began broadcasting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: The Murphy Pintak Gautier Hudome Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: A single shot: Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
champion of legislation to overhaul campaign finance laws, sitting
in a chair, calmly talking straight into the camera, and showing a
bit of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``You know, when Mrs. Clinton said she wouldn't take
huge special interest soft money contributions if her opponent
wouldn't, I believed her. But since then, she's taken in millions
in soft money and used it for attack ads distorting Rick Lazio's
record. Rick Lazio has said he'll agree to a soft money ban, but
Mrs. Clinton just refuses. So it's pretty clear there's only one
Senate candidate who really wants campaign finance reform. Rick
Lazio _ he's the candidate you can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: It is less than accurate to say, as McCain does in the
ad, that Clinton refuses to agree to a ban on soft-money
contributions, the largely unregulated contributions that are
supposed to be used mainly for party building. Clinton called for
such a ban before Lazio even entered the race. However, she
attached conditions on her proposal that Lazio's aides have
dismissed as untenable: that he make certain that a dozen or so
independent committees that are financing television campaigns
attacking Clinton halt their efforts as well. The result is a
deadlock unlikely to break.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: Although the ostensible subject of the advertisement
is campaign finance reform, it really is about Clinton's
credibility, and thus, the crucial sentence in this advertisement
is the last one. It is a theme that Lazio used in another ad
earlier this week, and will be a recurrent one throughout the
campaign. McCain was a popular figure, nationally, during his run
for the presidency this year, although he did lose the presidential
primary in New York to George W. Bush. In theory, at least, he
appeals to independent voters who may not have made up their minds
in this race. However, it is unclear whether he carries the sway
today that he did when he was a candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
