<HEADER>
A6961 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-QADDAFI-INTRIGUE-FISK     08-30 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QADDAFI-INTRIGUE-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEACEMAKER' QADDAFI'S CURIOUS DEALINGS ACROSS AFRICA, ASIA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London. Middle East Correspondent Robert Fisk was
recently named ``Amnesty International Print Journalist of the
Year.'')  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Muammar Qaddafi must sometimes find it difficult to
remember which ``liberation'' movement he has supported and which
he has ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Sierre Leone's Foday Sankoh _ famous for his
group's leg, ear, hand and lip amputations _ trained in Libya
alongside Charles Taylor, Liberia's gangland boss-made president.
In May, Qaddafi sent a delegation to Sierre Leone to work for the
release of U.N. staff taken hostage by rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh's appalling Revolutionary United Front has been supported
by Liberia and by Burkina Faso whose president, Blaise Compaore _
whose close ties with Qaddafi have been in evidence for years _ has
been accused of channelling weapons to the RUF.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Compaore have both been charged by an international
investigation of exchanging guns _ some of them from Qaddafi's
Libya _ for diamonds that end up in the trading houses of Antwerp,
Tel Aviv and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Libyan weapons, including shoulder-fired SAM-7 missiles, are
said to be legally purchased from Libya by Burkina Faso and then
sent on to Liberia, often through the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   When he turned up at an African summit in Cairo in December of
last year, Qaddafi was hard at work trying to convince the
presidents of Sudan, Eritrea, Uganda and Congo to drop their
differences and support Sudanese president Omar Bashir's new state
of emergency in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   In Qaddafi's presence, Bashir and President Yoweri Museveni
signed an agreement to establish diplomatic relations between their
two countries.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of this year, Bashir was urging Qaddafi and
President Moubarak of Libya to persuade John Garang's Sudan
People's Liberation Army to make peace with Khartoum, while Qaddafi
all the time blamed the United States for encouraging the southern
Sudanese rebels to delay an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   His successes in Africa may not always be obvious, but his
delight in publicity has never been in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, for example, Qaddafi travelled to a Togo summit in a
massive convoy that made its ponderous way across Niger, Burkina
Faso and Ghana. The wagon train took a week to reach its
destination.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly arrives at North African conferences escorted by
long-haired maidens with automatic rifles, his special protection
squad who run alongside his air-conditioned limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Qaddafi's support for the African National Congress during the
apartheid years was a singularly shrewd policy, earning him the
friendship of former South African President Nelson Mandela and a
special visit to Tripoli this month by South African minister
Ronnie Kasrils, to receive the two South African hostages of the
Philippines' Abu Sayyaf rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Kasrils spent several years in Libya as an exile during the
apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   At an Organization of African Unity conference in Algiers a year
ago, Qaddafi was supposed to end the Ethiopean-Eritrean border war
and send a peacekeeping force to the Congo. He set up his green
tent on the lawns of the Sheraton Hotel in Algiers but refused to
stay inside the building because it was ``a symbol of American
imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   In May this year, Qaddafi was hosting Chadian President Idriss
Deby in Tripoli and President Alfa Omar Konare of Mali. He wanted
greater economic cooperation between the Sahel and Saharan nations
of Libya, Sudan, Mali, Chad, Burkina Faso, Eritrea. Niger and the
Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no time to waste over backward ideologies like
border, tribal and ethnic disputes,'' he admonished the Cairo
summit last December. ``We don't want future generations to inherit
ethnic and tribal conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``peacemaker of Africa'' naturally earns tributes in his own
newspapers. Indeed, a columnist in Al-Zhaf al-Akhdar _ whose views
exactly parallel those of the great leader _ recently rhapsodized
about Qaddafi's supposed good looks.
</P>
<P>
   His teeth, the writer announced, were ``naturally immune to
stain'' for when he released ``a full-blown smile, the naturally
white teeth discharge a radiation pregnant with sweet joy and real
happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Which just shows what peacemaking can do for you. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
