r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ROOKIES-T     08-30 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ROOKIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' ROOKIE TRIO OF CORNERBACKS BURNED BY SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Kareem Larrimore practiced at left cornerback
with the Dallas Cowboys' first-team Wednesday, and practiced well.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore's performance was exemplary, especially because
Phillippi Sparks was on the same practice field for the first time
since the Cowboys lured the retired veteran out of his living room
and away from his children for $2 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kareem had a real good practice,'' Cowboys defensive
coordinator Mike Zimmer said at Valley Ranch. ``I would've been
disappointed if he hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, who did not mope or press at practice, has emerged as
the most game-ready member of a trio of rookie cornerbacks drafted
by the Cowboys in April. They arrived in this order: Dwayne
Goodrich (second round), Larrimore (fourth) and Mario Edwards
(sixth).
</P>
<P>
   While their roles still have not been defined just days from the
regular-season opener against Philadelphia, Larrimore has dealt
with the extra pressure of seeing his three-week hold on a starting
job turn into a game-day decision. Either he or Sparks could start
at left cornerback on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to lose that spot. I have to flat out do some
stupid things to lose it,'' Larrimore said, adding, ``I'm not
worried. I'm taking it as a business decision. It's all about
winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   The position Larrimore finds himself in is the latest in a
series of setbacks that have affected the rookie cornerbacks this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich, under the gun early for falling behind the others,
hasn't played since the preseason game in Tokyo on Aug. 5 because
of a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the most frustrated I've ever been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards hasn't played since the Oakland preseason game Aug. 13
because of a strained left hamstring, although he returned to
practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is hard enough anyway,'' Edwards said. ``If it was
easy, you'd have people lining up from here to MacArthur Boulevard
wanting to give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   All three rookie cornerbacks became friends at the Senior Bowl
in January, and they've remained friends despite competing for
playing time. Their lockers are within 12 feet of each other.
Larrimore is more of a loner, but they do socialize off the field.
</P>
<P>
   The three are here because of how the Cowboys reacted in April
to the pending loss of Deion Sanders in June.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders wanted an $8 million signing bonus, which he got with
Washington, while Goodrich ($1 million signing bonus/$250,000
first-year salary), Larrimore ($280,000/$193,000) and Edwards
($60,000/$193,000) will cost the Cowboys less than $2 million
combined this season.
</P>
<P>
   They represent the future. But once Kevin Smith left the team,
presumably to retire, the thinking in training camp was that if one
of the three rookies could start this season it would be a steal.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Larrimore was burned on several big plays in a
preseason game in Denver, Goodrich and Edwards were sidelined, and
Sparks was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my ability,'' Larrimore said. ``I'm confident _ not too
much cocky _ but I also take things slow. I really feel that I was
born to play this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Darren Woodson, the Cowboys' five-time Pro Bowl strong safety,
said rookie cornerbacks are put in a tough position: They must be
humble because they are rookies, but cocky because they are
cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a rookie cornerback doesn't have any confidence in his
ability, he's not going to make it in this league. That's just
being honest,'' Woodson said. ``You're going to get beat. It's how
you react after you get beat that matters. You've got to have a
really short memory.''
</P>
<P>
   And blinders.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, who has resumed play in nickel packages against slot
receivers, was being watched closely again Wednesday as Sparks
worked with both the first and second team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked rusty, but good,'' Zimmer said of Sparks, who
participated in his first team drills since preparing for the New
York Giants' season-ending game at Texas Stadium in December.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, for his part, recalls how he felt invisible when he
moved into Sanders' old locker at Valley Ranch three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knew who I was,'' Larrimore said. ``Now everyone wants
to know what I can do.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
