<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTISM IN HEAT TOUGH ON SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Summer vacation officially ended Wednesday for
newly signed Dallas Cowboys cornerback Phillippi Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, who vomited several times on the sidelines, admitted
struggling through his first workout in 103-degree temperatures.
But he said, ``I'll get there, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Sparks will get there in time to make a
contribution in the season opener against the Philadelphia Eagles
on Sunday. Sparks, a former New York Giants cornerback who came out
of retirement to sign with the Cowboys on Tuesday, has not had a
serious workout since last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo said he'll be able to better assess
Sparks' readiness after he has gone through a few more practices.
Campo said he expected Sparks' conditioning to be rusty because he
missed training camp.
</P>
<P>
   However, Campo said there's no question that the nine-year
veteran will play against the Eagles. It's just a matter of how
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We limited his reps in practice to make sure we're not pushing
him too hard,'' Campo said. ``From not participating, we don't want
him to end up pulling something. But he's a veteran. He sees
things. He's going to be fine. We will do some extra things with
him to make sure he is mentally ready to go.'' HOPING TO PUT HEAT
ON EAGLES
</P>
<P>
   With the high temperature expected to be in or near triple
digits Sunday, the Cowboys are counting on the Eagles to experience
a little of what Phillippi Sparks was feeling Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo, who had the Cowboys running sprints after practice
Wednesday, said the heat should be an advantage for the Cowboys
against a team that's not used to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to concentrate and focus in the heat, especially in
the fourth quarter,'' Campo said. ``I talked to our team about that
during team drills and after practice.'' PRACTICE SQUAD UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   After adding rookie tight end James Whalen to the practice squad
Tuesday, the Cowboys worked out former Pittsburgh Steelers
quarterback Anthony Wright on Wednesday in an attempt to close out
their practice-squad numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys vice president Stephen Jones said they were just waiting
for Wright to pass a physical before signing him. Wright, a
two-year veteran who played in college at South Carolina, would be
the second quarterback on the practice squad, along with Clint
Stoerner. Jones said the Cowboys had no problem having two
quarterbacks on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Whalen was picked in the fifth round of the 2000 draft by the
Tampa Bay Buccaneers, who released him Sunday. A former Kentucky
standout, Whalen is considered an ideal H-back prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Already signed to the practice squad are receiver Damon Hodge
and running back Troy Hambrick. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerback Mario Edwards (hamstring) is back at practice.
However, his availability for Sunday's game won't be assessed until
later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornerbacks Charlie Williams (knee) and Dwayne Goodrich
(hamstring) have been ruled out of the Eagles game.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys handed out 1999 team awards at Tuesday's kickoff
luncheon. Emmitt Smith was named offensive player of the year.
Dexter Coakley was named defensive player of the year. Former
Cowboys receiver Ernie Mills won the Ed Block Memorial Courage
Award. The Legends award was renamed the Tom Landry Legend's award.
The late Cowboys coach was honored as the 2000 recipient. His
widow, Alicia Landry, accepted the award. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
