<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE PISTONS WILL GET LAST LAUGH ON LAETTNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the story is true, and the truth is somewhat blurred, then a
twist of irony has been wrapped around prominent jock kingdom necks
of late.
</P>
<P>
   Follow along:
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, Don Nelson was hired to coach the New York
Knicks, where he immediately fell out of favor with the star
player, one Patrick Ewing, and with all fans and media of the most
important franchise in the NBA. And if you don't believe me on that
last point, just ask the league office, or better yet, watch how
the referees call any playoff game involving the beloved Knickies.
</P>
<P>
   But I wander aimlessly. As I was saying, Nelson decided his new
club in New York could never win a championship with Ewing as the
focal point of the offense. He wanted to spread the shots, and the
floor. The rebellion, however, was harsh and swift.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing turned on Nelson. He recruited other players in the
revolt. The fans joined in. The media ganged up. All that got
Nelson fired, pronto. Big Nellie didn't last the season in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But fast-forward the shot clock some four years, which brings us
to this week. The Dallas Mavericks made a trade with the Detroit
Pistons, and a very questionable trade it was. Known trouble
arrived in the 6-foot-11 quirky package labeled Christian Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, however, hooted loudly over the Mavericks' good fortune,
as did owner Mark Cuban. They are promoting Laettner as a welcome
addition, which is normal in these cases. Nelson and Cuban worked
for weeks to make the deal happen.
</P>
<P>
   For Big Nellie, there was also additional glee that the
Mavericks (or so the local story goes) personally wrecked a
four-team trade last week that had made national headlines. That
one involved the Knicks dealing Ewing to Seattle for Vin Baker,
with the Lakers getting Laettner and Detroit ending up with various
iguanas.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, however, was the centerpiece of the transaction, mainly
because the Knicks wanted to dump him. And when that trade died, a
mighty roar of displeasure came from all precincts in New York,
particularly fans and media. They wanted this guy gone. Why? Too
selfish to assume a lesser role, that's why. And the Knicks
couldn't win a championship with Ewing as the focal point, that's
why.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, hold it a second. Isn't that what Nelson said four years
ago? And was barbecued for offering that theory on Patrick?
</P>
<P>
   The reason Ewing remains in New York, so says Nelson, is because
he and Cuban convinced the Pistons to pull out of the deal because
the Mavericks had a better package of players to offer for Laettner
than Detroit would be receiving in the four-way rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   This is indeed sweet irony. And some nice revenge for Nelson. He
gave back to New York exactly what Gotham had once told him it
dearly wanted. Except ...
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons now claim they pulled out of the earlier deal on
their own, not due to advice from any voices down Dallas way. And
that the Mavericks' deal was the one they planned on making all
along.
</P>
<P>
   Last laughs are fun, and Nelson is having one at the moment. But
give it a season and will the Pistons be chuckling over unloading
Laettner on the Mavs?
</P>
<P>
   This just in from a Detroit sports page columnist Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the Pistons struggled, the more Laettner looked to
satisfy his own self-interests. He'd sulk if he didn't get enough
shots and was one of the first in the locker room to tune out Alvin
Gentry, contributing to the coach's ouster late last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter whom the Pistons acquired for Laettner.
What's most important is he's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner has left similar impressions in two other NBA stops.
Not a very likable guy to start with, his talent level isn't good
enough to overcome a cobra personality.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt, however, Nelson pushed Cuban hard to land
Laettner, and the owner was more than willing to come up with yet
another $3 million, in cash, to grease Detroit palms. Cuban always
seems to have an extra $3 million in his hip pocket anytime the
Mavericks are trade-ready, which is all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But as Cuban, Nelson and a nice foundation of young talent have
caused a total U-turn in public perception for a franchise that
went unloved locally for a decade, Laettner represents a threat to
a budding success story.
</P>
<P>
   The team unity was strong last season. Even with Worm Rodman in
town for a while, that unity didn't crumble. But Laettner could
wreck all that in a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's true about this guy being big
trouble,'' Nelson said Wednesday by phone from Hawaii. ``Yes, he's
had his moments in the league. Yes, he's a little different. But I
think I know him well enough, that all that can be handled. I
certainly don't anticipate problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Basketball-wise, Laettner is a big man who plays a Nellie kind
of game. You can spread the floor with him, and dictate matchups.
He gives a contrast at center with Shawn Bradley, but then again,
who doesn't? One other factor which can be viewed as favorable _
Laettner is in the last year of his contract. If the Mavs don't
re-sign him, they get the salary cap bump. But a player in the last
year of his contract is also normally on his best behavior while
attempting to play at his best.
</P>
<P>
   Last laughs and great irony aside, Laettner will have to be
monitored closely, both on the floor and in the area known as
goodwill toward teammates. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
