<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WILLIAMS HANDLES EVERYTHING _ INCLUDING McENROE 
(REPLACES earlier version)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was long after she impressively tucked away her
21st match in a row, but Venus Williams was still on her game,
still delivering returns with the speed of a quick wit.
</P>
<P>
   This is how you handle a heckler; and this is how she put away
John McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the comments McEnroe made in this week's issue of The
New Yorker _ where he declared that the dominant Williams sisters
could be beaten by a male college player or any man on the senior
tour (like him) _ made their way to Venus Williams. Instead of
taking offense to remarks that belittle her achievements, she took
the challenge with a good rip at humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could fit him in my schedule right now,''
Williams said when asked about a battle-of-the-sexes match with
McEnroe. ``I don't think it's fair to put a 20-year-old against a
40-something person. So, I'll let that pass.''
</P>
<P>
   She was in too good a mood to let anyone spoil it. She had just
unnerved Kveta Hrdlickova with the might of her lumberjack strokes,
and exited the court with a 48-minute, 6-1, 6-1 exclamation mark to
her current roll.
</P>
<P>
   Williams could not help but finding the light side of Day 3 at
the U.S. Open. After leaving the interview room, she stopped and
posed for a picture, gave the lens a bright crescent-moon smile,
and all but skipped toward the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, there was a feel-good atmosphere to the day. In the
same hallway, Jennifer Capriati was spotted embracing her
boyfriend, Xavier Malisse, and wishing him good luck just before
she went off to win her second-round match in Louis Armstrong
Stadium and he departed for Court 10, where he took his first-round
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when we play at the same time,'' Malisse said. ``I
want to see her, and she wants to be at my match. She finished
first. So, I liked seeing her come in. It was good to look and see
her there.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a limit to the positive vibes. Outside the
players' cafeteria, Jelena Dokic was seen crying. It was her father
again. As a reminder of the sports dysfunctional dark side, Damir
Dokic was making a scene for the second Grand Slam in a row. At
Wimbledon, he went on a tirade as he made his way through the
pristine grounds, ending his out-of-control behavior by smashing
the cell phone of a reporter before security led him away.
</P>
<P>
   It was uncertain what triggered that outburst. This time, it was
the price of salmon. Apparently outraged at the cost of the lunch
in the players' cafeteria, Dokic went off on a shouting binge until
security officers hustled him away. His daughter was the teary-eyed
witness to it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I feel sorry for her,'' a fellow Aussie, Mark
Philippoussis, said. ``She should be enjoying herself. When I
played mixed doubles with her at Hopman Cup, she didn't look like a
happy 16-year-old girl. She's not. She's not smiling out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The vision of Jelena Dokic provided a dose of reality to an
otherwise lighthearted day. Although the wild-card entrant Mardy
Fish, a personable 18-year-old from Vero Beach, Fla., could not
fight off the popular Jan-Michael Gambill in the fifth set, his
growing cult following was pleased with his effort. In the stands,
the Fish Heads, as his fans are known, were cheering.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning I tried to get the crowd on my side because I
knew I would need them if it went long,'' said Fish, who could hear
the crowd chanting his name. ``It helped a lot. I had my mom, my
sister and my dad here.''
</P>
<P>
   There is such a thing as a normal player's family. But there are
certain parents who stand out. Damir Dokic is one of them. And the
father of Venus and Serena Williams, Richard, is another. But even
though the eccentric Richard Williams has been an attention-grabber
at times _ making outrageous statements and waving signs in the
friends box _ his daughters don't show any side effects from his
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams was proof of that Wednesday. She didn't need
anyone to defend her against McEnroe's opinions; she had her own
thoughts as to whether McEnroe or a male college player could beat
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're playing a college player, they just aren't as
smart,'' Williams said. ``They don't understand what it is to be at
30-all, 40-all in a big situation. They don't understand these
things. So therefore. ... Well, I've played a lot of guys that were
stronger than me, and I was smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is not important. I have a career, and it's very
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   She had a point. Williams is on the kind of streak many,
including McEnroe, might envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martina Navratilova went a year and she lost only one match,''
Williams said when asked if a Tiger Woods-type roll was possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Monica Seles was out in the early '90s, she had all types
of winning streaks. And Steffi won four Grand Slams in one year,
plus the Olympics,'' she said, referring to Steffi Graf.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Williams will stick to those goals, and leave the
struggling men's tour on its own. ``I'm a lady,'' Williams said.
``I don't want to play with the men's tour. The ladies' tour is
where it's good to be at right now. I want to be right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Good comeback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
