<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXI-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF-DUTY OFFICERS BALK AT DRIVING TAXIS
</HEADLINE>
 By ELISSA GOOTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an effort to build the ranks of taxi drivers, the
city's Taxi and Limousine Commission is considering a proposal to
encourage police officers to moonlight behind the wheels of yellow
cabs, but the plan is being greeted coldly by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, officers would be able to waive an 80-hour
training course and a drug test that taxi drivers must take.
Officials with the commission, which is scheduled to discuss the
plan on Sept. 28, say the taxi industry proposed it as a way to
deal with a driver shortage. The officials said police officers
were an obvious choice, because they had completed driver training
courses and were randomly tested for drug use.
</P>
<P>
   But though many officers do hold down second jobs, many note
that they already spend their days dealing with the public and
patrolling the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't appeal to me,'' said Rick Lee, the community
affairs officer in Lower Manhattan. ``I think there should be other
ways we should be compensated. We should maybe make a little better
salary.'' He called the plan insulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of saying, `Well, it might be all you're good
for,''' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The taxi owners realize officers may not be interested, but they
thought it was worth a try, said Diane McGrath-McKechnie, the
chairwoman of the commission. ``The economy is very, very strong
right now, and they're having more difficulty than usual in
recruiting drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   She estimated that at any given time, 8 to 10 percent of the
city's more than 12,000 medallions were unused, primarily because
of the driver shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage is so acute, said the spokeswoman for the
Metropolitan Taxicab Board of Trade, Maureen Connelly, that some
fleet operators are willing to lease taxis for shorter periods than
the standard 12-hour shift.
</P>
<P>
   But officers say they were all too familiar with the woes and
perils of cabby life, and do not want to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People drunk, people not paying, people making a mess in the
back of the cab,'' said Officer Thomas Reilly, 29. ``I've seen a
lot of cabdrivers. I see a lot of the problems they have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000830.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-30 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-MAKEOVE     08-30 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-MAKEOVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELLIE LOVES MAVERICKS' MAKEOVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ This time of year in North Texas the heat has become so
stifling that even the most ardent sun-worshipper would probably
want to rush to the ocean to catch a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Not Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is vacationing in his off-season home in majestic Maui,
Hawaii. While the scenery there is magnificent, to Nelson nothing
is as inspiring as the roster the Mavericks have pieced together
during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Maui, but I can hardly wait for training camp to
start,'' said Nelson, the Mavericks' coach and general manager.
``It's been quite a summer from the draft until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the crown jewel of his red-hot summer was Tuesday,
when the Mavericks acquired former All-Star Christian Laettner and
Terry Mills from the Detroit Pistons for Cedric Ceballos, Eric
Murdock, John Wallace and $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner and Mills will both be backups for center Shawn
Bradley, and they both can play power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Those acquisitions, along with the acquisitions of rookies
Courtney Alexander, Etan Thomas, Donnell Harvey and Eduardo Najera,
and veterans Howard Eisley, Bill Curley and Dana Barros, has Nelson
wishing the Oct. 3 opening of training camp could be pushed up a
month.
</P>
<P>
   From their roster of a season ago, the Mavericks traded away
Erick Strickland, Sean Rooks, Robert Pack, Bruno Sundov and
Ceballos, and decided not to re-sign Damon Jones. But Nelson isn't
fretting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really like the players we got,'' Nelson said. ``The
players we lost, we feel we can work around their departure, so
we're as excited as heck.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also is exciting about going into his first full season
with Mark Cuban as the Mavericks' owner. Cuban obtained official
control of the Mavericks from Ross Perot Jr. late last season, and
has pledged to turn the team's fortunes around .
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said money would be no object. As an example, the NBA
allows a team to toss in a maximum of $3 million to complete a
deal, if such a transaction is needed. NBA owners normally don't
toss in $3 million to complete deals, but Cuban didn't bat an eye
while using this strategy three times over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole career I coached and was a general manager for
conservative guys, and I'm used to that,'' Nelson said. ``I'm used
to pinching pennies, but that has changed and it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a kid in a candy store. I'm like a hobo on a ham
sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban pulled a surprise in May when he signed Nelson to an
11-year, $22 million deal. Nelson will be the Mavericks' coach and
general manager for the next three seasons, work solely as the GM
from 2003-'06, and be a team consultant from 2006-'11.
</P>
<P>
   It's a deal that stunned even Nelson, who had planned to retire
after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban's bold style has rejuvenated the 60-year-old Nelson and
allowed him to consummate deals without money being a shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark has done a fantastic job,'' Nelson said. ``He has put his
money where his mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cuban, shaping the Mavericks into what appears to be their
most competitive team since the 1989-'90 season has been as much
fun as the $1.5 billion he collected from helping build
Broadcast.com into an Internet phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this team and what we can do,'' Cuban said. ``This will
be my first (training) camp, so naturally I'm excited to see how
all the pieces play out and see what I can do to make the
environment better for winning.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Nelson is concerned, Cuban has gone above and beyond
what he could ask any owner to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done what he said he was going to do,'' Nelson said.
``And we were able to make a lot more deals because of that
philosophy.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
