u p BC-NY-DEM-AD-BOX-NYT     08-30 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEM-AD-BOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: DEMOCRATS CONJURE SPECTER OF GINGRICH 
</HEADLINE>
  By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a new 30-second commercial, called ``Stand,'' which the
New York State Democratic Party began broadcasting Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: David Axelrod.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The advertisement takes a ``man on the street''
approach, a departure from the previous commercials for the Senate
campaign. It opens with a close-up of a woman as the off-camera
narrator asks, ``Excuse me, did you know that for four years Rick
Lazio was deputy whip to Newt Gingrich in Congress?'' The woman
looks stunned and says she did not know. The announcer goes on to
make a series of statements about Lazio's record, as phrases like
``$270 billion in Medicare cuts'' scroll across the screen. The
camera cuts quickly from one wholesome-looking person to another,
each of them looking surprised and saying things like, ``Oh, my
goodness,'' as they hear about Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: ``Excuse me, did you know that for four years, Rick
Lazio was deputy whip to Newt Gingrich in Congress?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This does surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that he helped write and pass the Gingrich budget, with
two hundred and seventy billion in Medicare cuts?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that rather disappointing, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was more pro-health care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that Lazio followed Gingrich's lead and voted for the
largest education cuts in history?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my goodness, I didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell Lazio to stop playing both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knew?''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: The narrator sounds as if he is revealing deep, dark
secrets about Lazio: his votes to reduce Medicare spending and to
make the largest national education spending cut in history. But
the Clinton campaign has attacked Lazio on Medicare and education
spending in its commercials before, based on the same two votes.
Lazio voted to cut the rate of growth in Medicare spending, not the
Medicare budget, as his campaign reiterated Wednesday. The cut in
education spending, the Lazio campaign insisted, was smaller than
one proposed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: The Democrats seem to think that reminding voters of
Lazio's link to Newt Gingrich may be an effective move, although
the Clinton campaign tried and abandoned that tactic weeks ago.
What is most notable about the commercial is the absence of
slickness and the use of ordinary people reacting to Lazio's
record. The ad is financed with so-called soft money _ unregulated
contributions that legally cannot be spent to promote individual
candidates. Employing a loophole now widely used by both major
parties, the Democrats use a script that attacks Lazio but never
explicitly refers to the Senate race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
