<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DEFENSE-CLEANUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY AND PENTAGON SIGN CLEANUP AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Department of Defense officials and New Jersey environmental
regulators have signed an accord in which the Pentagon agreed to
finance the cleanup of 550 contaminated sites on former military
bases around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The signing came two years after the two parties agreed in
principle to such a plan and after surveys to identify the sites on
29 former and current Army, Navy and Air Force bases, said Robert
C. Shinn Jr., commissioner of the state's Department of
Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gives state officials a role in setting priorities
for which sites are cleaned up as Defense Department funds become
available. Shinn said the total cost of the cleanup, for which
there is no firm timetable, is expected to be $350 million.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey became only the second state to enter into such an
arrangement with the military, which began shrinking its forces and
facilities after the Cold War ended. Pennsylvania signed a similar
agreement in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thrust of this agreement is to have a joint priority
list and really focus on cleanup,'' Shinn said. ``They are saying
that they are responsible for the costs of the cleanups, and they
want to get budget allocations for projects that they can actually
complete without problems at the state level.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherri W. Goodman, deputy under secretary of defense for
environmental security, said that New Jersey and any other states
that sign agreements will ``benefit from having a known plan for
addressing future assessments and cleanups.''
</P>
<P>
   The key cleanup sites, Shinn said, include a missile silo at
McGuire Air Force Base where a 1960 fire caused plutonium
contamination. Since then, the site has been sealed in reinforced
concrete. Another site is a Fort Dix bombing range, on the fringes
of the Pinelands in the center of the state, where there is a risk
of dummy bombs leaching lead into ground water.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental effort will also allow the state and federal
governments to experiment with cleanup technologies, as they
already have at one Fort Dix site near Pemberton Township. There,
Shinn said, the Army is financing a soil washing program to remove
lead from a target range and planting mustard plants to absorb any
lead residue that remains.
</P>
<P>
   But Shinn observed that the most important feature of the
agreement _ aside from experimental technologies and federal
financing _ was that it would speed up the effort to clean up sites
before extensive environmental damage and threats to health and
safety occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-30-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
